<SLUG> BC-HILLARY17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    First lady is Democrats' as N.Y.
 &HT;    By Jill Vejnoska
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Albany, N.Y. _ It's official.
</P>
<P>
   It was just before 9:30 p.m. Tuesday when first lady Hillary
Rodham Clinton formally accepted the nomination of New York's state
Democratic party as its candidate for the U.S. Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Bathed in frequent applause by President Clinton and 11,500
othersat the party's annual convention, Mrs. Clinton completed a
journey that had begun nearly 11 months ago. She eventually reached
into all 62 counties in New York and took the role of presidential
spouse into vast, unexplored territory.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the chance of a lifetime,'' Mrs. Clinton said near the
end of a 40-minute speech that touched on such grand themes as the
need to unite all Americans across class and race lines, as well as
more specific concerns, such as affordable health care and
broadband access for all of New York. ``The test we will be judged
on is whether we, as a party and a people, are up to meeting this
challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   Left unspoken was the name of New York City Mayor Rudolph W.
Giuliani, who had been presumed to be her Republican opponent until
a prostate cancer diagnosis and marital woes cropped up about three
weeks ago. Giuliani hasn't yet decided whether to pursue the
nomination at his party's convention May 30 _ but the first lady
indicated she didn't care who she runs against.
</P>
<P>
   ``Make no mistake _ this election is not about me or any
Republican opponent,'' she said, pausing slightly for emphasis.
``It's about the people of New York and our common mission.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton may be breaking ground as the first first lady to
run for national elective office, but she still got the traditional
red, white and blue balloon drop at the close of the event in the
Pepsi Arena in this capital city about 150 miles north of
Manhattan. Indeed, the evening had all the trappings of a standard
political convention, from the Dixieland band and bunting outside
the arena to the colorful signs and frequently purplish prose
inside.
</P>
<P>
   But much about it also felt unprecedented, starting with the
candidate herself and the singleminded determination of nearly
everyone present to unite in support of her candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   While Mrs. Clinton's nomination was never in doubt _ a party
official who jokingly, yet traditionally, asked for the names of
other nominees was practically booed out of the arena _ some drama
did hang over the event.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the candidate didn't know if her husband would be
here. On Tuesday, President Clinton made it clear how far he's
willing to go to help his wife win a Senate seat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not yet registered to vote in New York,'' the president
said during a Rose Garden ceremony, ``but I intend to register to
vote for her in the fall.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night, the huge crowd stood twice to applaud the
president, who sat to his wife's right on the stage with Democatic
Sens. Daniel Patrick Moynihan, who is retiring, and Charles
Schumer, who nominated her. One prolonged round of applause was
prompted by the first lady's own tribute to her frequently
embattled husband.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am delighted the president is here this evening and I am so
grateful for his support,'' Mrs. Clinton said as Schumer and
Moynihan leapt to their feet, practically pulling the president up
with them. ``I would not be standing here tonight if it were not
for Bill and all he has done for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Giuliani, who met privately with doctors earlier in the
day to discuss his cancer treatment, was not mentioned Tuesday
night, he made his presence felt. Minutes before the kilt-clad,
bagpipe-blaring Albany Police Fife and Drum Corps presented the
colors at 5:30 p.m., Giuliani's campaign e-mailed reporters a
statement accusing Mrs. Clinton of trying to ``reinvent'' herself.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is still only one candidate in this race with the record
of success and follow-through that has improved the lives of New
York families,'' the statement continued. ``When New Yorkers think
about their futures, about lower taxes, new and better jobs, health
and education reform, safer neighborhoods and a better quality of
life, they think about Rudy Giuliani.''
</P>
<P>
   But for the delegates here, this day was all about Mrs. Clinton
and a singular moment in time.
</P>
<P>
   Said Lori Garel, 12, who missed a day of school in the Bronx to
ride a bus here with her mother, Pat: ``I'm excited because the
first lady is running for Senate and maybe president some day. And
it's about time.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
