<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKEES-WHITESOX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRUSTRATION AND LOSSES MOUNT FOR THE YANKEES  
 BY BUSTER OLNEY  
</HEADLINE>
  c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Jorge Posada retreated to the runway leading from the
Yankees' dugout, trying to hide from prying eyes, and he smashed
his bat in a rage, hammering it against a wall once, twice, a third
time.
</P>
<P>
   The frustration is mounting for the Yankees, who cannot get hits
these days, cannot score runs, cannot win. They lost their fifth
straight game Tuesday night, by 4-0 to the Chicago White Sox, while
managing just three hits against Cal Eldred and two relievers at
Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees have scored three runs or fewer in four of the last
five games. Orlando Hernandez (4-3) allowed two runs in eight
innings, but for the second straight start the Yankees could not
score for him.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees are not merely in an offensive funk, some temporary
condition, like an annoying runny nose. They have played nearly a
quarter of their season and rank next to last in the American
League in scoring, and this is a full-blown epidemic of scoreless
innings.
</P>
<P>
   They found no cure in the early innings against Chicago's Cal
Eldred, who began the game with a 2-2 record and a 5.36 earned run
average. It's getting somewhat monotonous, Paul O'Neill said the
other day, to constantly say that the opposing pitcher threw a good
game. It's about time the Yankees started hitting, O'Neill added.
But Eldred did have good stuff Tuesday night, a fastball that ran
and sunk and sailed.
</P>
<P>
   The White Sox were trying to be patient against Hernandez,
taking his first pitch repeatedly, and they could not score in the
first four innings, either. But with one out in the fifth,
Hernandez threw a fastball on the outer half of the plate to the
burly Carlos Lee, and Lee launched a high fly, the ball soaring and
carrying into the seats in left field, above where the Yankees'
Shane Spencer stood and watched.
</P>
<P>
   Just one run. To a team that cannot get hits, to the Yankees, it
must have seemed like 20 runs.
</P>
<P>
   Spencer lined a single leading off the fifth for the Yankees'
first hit and the 31,143 fans roared enthusiastically, with
anticipation of the rally they have come to expect. Then Spencer
was quickly erased when Scott Brosius grounded into a double play.
</P>
<P>
   But Eldred bounced a fastball off the left shoulder of Clay
Bellinger, and with Bellinger running on the pitch to the next
batter, Chuck Knoblauch lined a single into center field, Bellinger
taking third. Ricky Ledee came to bat, under growing pressure to
produce runs, and he coaxed a walk from Eldred, loading the bases
for O'Neill.
</P>
<P>
   Eldred challenged O'Neill with high fastballs, O'Neill fouling
off three in a row. With the count 1-2, Eldred whipped another
fastball, O'Neill swung, the ball climbing away from his bat and
toward left field. Fans roared, but O'Neill knew: He ambled toward
first base, knowing it was not enough, knowing Lee would settle
under the ball easily and make the catch well in front of the
warning track.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees' frustration continued in the next inning. After
Tino Martinez singled, Posada swung at one pitch wildly, as if
desperate to hit a two-run homer, and fouled the ball back. He
eventually struck out, then snapped in the dugout.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Konerko smashed a triple opening the seventh, and Chris
Singleton _ one of those former Yankees whose name haunts club
officials _ drove a double down the left-field line, scoring
Konerko. The White Sox led, 2-0. He added a hit-and-run single in
the ninth inning to set up Chicago's two-run rally against Mariano
Rivera. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
