<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEACHES-REPORT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
URBAN RUNOFF THREATENS HEALTH OF REGION'S SHORES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HARRISON SHEPPARD 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; LOS ANGELES _ Southern California's legendary beaches -
inspiration of Beach Boys tunes and ``Baywatch'' backdrops - are
confronted with major problems from water pollution to
overdevelopment, according to a study of the nation's coasts.
</P>
<P>
   The study - compiled by the Surfrider Foundation, an Orange
County-based advocacy group - was based on some 50 factors, ranging
from water quality to public access to weather. The ``State of the
Beaches'' report included a top-10 list of the nation's best
beaches, with two from Southern California - Newport Beach and
Santa Barbara's East Beach - making the cut.
</P>
<P>
   The group didn't even rate Los Angeles County's beaches, which
have been repeatedly criticized for serious pollution problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Urban runoff is the single biggest threat to California's
receiving waters,'' said Surfrider Executive Director Chris Evans.
``In the short term it shuts beaches down. We don't really know in
the larger scheme everything it does to marine life, but it's bad
for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Runoff contains anything that washes down storm drains, from
pesticides to dog waste to hazardous chemicals. The drains,
intended to carry rainwater, often empty close to the shoreline.
</P>
<P>
   In Los Angeles County, the beaches that seem to be chronically
polluted over the years include Malibu's Surfrider Beach, Will
Rogers State Beach and Santa Monica's beach near its pier, said
Marc Gold, executive director of Heal the Bay.
</P>
<P>
   The pier, he said, is especially unhealthy because pigeons tend
to congregate there, while fishermen and others tend to toss food
waste off the pier.
</P>
<P>
   A storm-water diversion project is going to be built near the
pier within two to three years that will capture dry weather runoff
and pump it into the sewer system for treatment, rather than
sending it untreated straight to the beach.
</P>
<P>
   But in general, Gold says he has seen little improvement in the
area's beaches over the past few years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have not done a very good job of reducing our polluted
runoff problems,'' he said. ``That's obviously the largest water
quality problem not only in L.A. County, but Southern California
and the nation. It's something that's not being adequately
addressed.''
</P>
<P>
   The report notes that California has some of the most stringent
policies on water quality monitoring, thanks to a new state law
passed two years ago. Unfortunately, the group said, that means the
beach closure rates are higher here than most other states.
</P>
<P>
   ``California's better than a lot of states at public water
quality posting,'' Evans said. ``That may explain why we have a lot
of hot results for dirty beaches. The water is definitely tested
more in California than anywhere else.''
</P>
<P>
   Because many states have loose standards for testing and poor
public notification, it is difficult to measure how they stack up
in terms of water quality.
</P>
<P>
   Surfers feel the brunt of ill effects since they spend the most
time in the water, often in the same locations day after day.
</P>
<P>
   Malibu surfer Jeff Duclos has gotten what he calls the ``hat
trick'' of beach-related illnesses over the years - ear infections,
sinus infections and rashes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sort of a dubious badge of honor,'' said Duclos, who
co-chairs Surfrider's Malibu branch.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stories of surfers who surf Malibu are consistent - ear
infections, sinus infections, rashes, fevers. There's a whole
litany of things you can get. It seems quite clear that it's not
coincidental and it clearly has to do with the degraded condition
of the water.''
</P>
<P>
   County health officials say every individual has to make an
effort to help Southern California's beaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``People should just be more aware of what they're dumping on
the ground,'' said Richard Kebabjian, chief of the county health
department's recreational health program. ``They should pick up
after dog droppings. They should pick up after horse manure from
stables - anything that will run out to the environment or make its
way into a flood control channel.''
</P>
<P>
   Another problem is overdevelopment of structures along
California's beaches, Evans said. But it is difficult to know the
extent of the problem because of a lack of available information.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now in California, nobody knows the answer to this
question: What percentage of the California coast is armored with
hard structures like seawalls, jetties and groins?'' Evans said.
``How can the Coastal Commission issue the next permit if they
don't know what's the cumulative effect of everything that's
there.''
</P>
<P>
   So far this year, there have been four beach closures in Los
Angeles County, the same as for all of 1999, Kebabjian said. Beach
closures generally result from an extraordinary event, such as a
broken sewer line. Postings about water quality go up when bacteria
counts pass certain levels. There are typically one or two postings
every day somewhere in the county, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ventura County has had two beach closings so far this year,
according to a county official.
</P>
<P>
   California, with its 1,100 miles of shoreline and tougher
testing standards, usually leads the nation in beach closures,
according to the Natural Resources Defense Council. In 1998, the
state had 3,273 closings and advisories out of 7,236 nationwide,
according to Ann Notthoff, the group's California advocacy
director.
</P>
<P>
   L.A. County had 147 closings and advisories that year, while
Ventura County had 237. San Diego County, by contrast, had 877,
while Orange County had 498. Figures for 1999 have not been
compiled yet.
</P>
<P>
   The Surfrider Foundation's report was mostly funded by Mazda of
North America, which provided $100,000.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
