<HEADLINE>
RATES HEAD HIGHER, BUT CONSUMERS AREN'T DETERRED _ YET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PAUL WENSKE  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ In an effort to dampen consumer spending and
cool an overheated economy, the Federal Reserve on Tuesday raised
interest rates by half a point, pushing a key rate to its highest
level in nine years.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed raised its target for the federal funds rate, the
interest that banks charge each other, from 6 percent to 6.5
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Commercial banks immediately reacted by announcing they were
raising their prime lending rates by half a point, which will
affect millions of dollars in consumer and business loans.
</P>
<P>
   Commerce Bank and Bank of America bumped their rates from 9
percent to 9.5 percent effective today. Firstar raised its rate the
same way, but the increase was effective Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   But if the hot Kansas City housing market is any indication, the
rate increase may not have the effect Fed Chairman Alan Greenspan
envisioned. Some consumers remain unfazed by interest-rate
increases.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff and Mary Hunzinger of Lee's Summit, for example, locked in
a home loan on Tuesday at 9 percent, just as banks were bumping up
interest rates. And he still thought he got a good deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The important thing was getting the house we wanted in the
price range we wanted,'' Jeff Hunzinger said. He doesn't think
consumers are going to be overly influenced by a bump in rates.
``We're in fairly prosperous times right now. Most people are
living well.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether we will continue to live well is, of course, at the crux
of the central bank's actions. Fed policy-makers worry that
consumer demand for homes, cars and other goods and services
spurred by the boom economy is too much for the available supply of
labor and produced goods.
</P>
<P>
   Ignoring this predicament, the Fed warned, ``could foster
inflationary imbalances that would undermine the economy's
outstanding performance.'' This was the sixth time the Fed has
increased the funds rate since last June, but it was the single
biggest increase in five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Greenspan is saying, `Hold it folks, you are too optimistic,'
'' said Sheryl Garrett, a Kansas City-area certified financial
planner. ``Our companies aren't going to continue having so much
productivity. Technology can't solve all our problems. We still
need human beings to do the work. And we're running out of human
beings.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, though, any encroaching doomsday scenario might seem
theoretical at best to many consumers, especially in Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   The Hunzingers reflect a strong housing market in which home
values have surged, despite rates rising about 2 percentage points
in less than 18 months.
</P>
<P>
   In Johnson County alone, more than 2,666 homes were sold through
April. While that's down from 3,065 homes sold during the same
period last year, it's still as peppy as the boom years of 1996 and
1997, when interest rates were closer to 7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the only thing holding back more record home sales is
the lack of enough finished new homes to sell, said Jerry Meyer, a
veteran senior salesman for Century 21 Heartland and number
cruncher for the Johnson County (Kan.) Board of Realtors.
</P>
<P>
   The overall economy grew at a fast 5.4 percent annual rate
during the first three months of this year. And a lot of the reason
was consumer spending, which accounts for two-thirds of economic
activity and grew at rates that haven't been seen in 17 years.
</P>
<P>
   Unemployment in the nation is at a 30-year low of 3.9 percent.
In parts of metro Kansas City, it's less than 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday the government reported that consumer prices, which had
risen earlier because of higher gas prices, remained unchanged in
April. But officials said the Fed remains worried that rapid
economic growth will spawn inflationary wage increases because of a
lack of workers.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed hopes ...MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
