<SLUG> BC-RATES-CONSUMERS-2NDTAKE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RATES HEAD HIGHER, BUT CONSUMERS AREN'T DETERRED _ YET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PAUL WENSKE  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ ...a lack of workers.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed hopes that incremental rate increases will slow spending
and economic growth without bringing growth to a screeching halt or
into the unwanted abyss of a recession. It's a tricky balancing
act, one some economists view skeptically.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not convinced that we need to increase the cost to
business and consumers of taking out loans,'' said Peter Eaton,
director of the University of Missouri-Kansas City Center for
Economic Information. ``I'm not convinced we have to increase the
cost of production, because that means having to lay people off,
and that's where consumers get hurt directly.''
</P>
<P>
   But Garrett believes the Fed move was necessary. ``Greenspan is
trying to reduce consumerism to make it less attractive for us to
go into debt,'' she said. ``It's like food. You need a certain
amount of food to survive. But if you overeat you will become
unhealthy.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, convincing consumers is another thing. After all, they've
been encouraged to spend for a decade to spur the economy. And now
they're being told to slow down.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is this debate _ are we tilting at windmills or not?''
said Dennis McKee, president of County Economic Research Institute,
the economic research institute in Johnson County. ``Consumer
confidence here and across the nation is high. It's historically
high. So people do feel good about their economic prospects. And so
they are willing to spend money.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we'll reach a point when the cost of credit is too
expensive, and that will slow us down. The cost of money to
business will be too much and their production will slow down. And
they'll add the cost to consumer goods.''
</P>
<P>
   If that is the reality, the Fed's bold rate increase might be a
time for consumers to sit up and take notice.
</P>
<P>
   James Nutter Jr., executive vice president of James B. Nutter &AMP;
Co., a major Kansas City mortgage company, said it is key to watch
what the Fed does next.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the economy seeming in some areas to be picking up speed
in the last few months, there's a good chance he will continue to
raise rates,'' Nutter said. That means that consumers who still
want to spend must be savvy.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, Nutter, whose company gave the Hunzingers their
loan Tuesday, said that as interest rates rise, a fixed-rate
mortgage might offer more value. ``What I'd tell anyone is that if
they are thinking of buying a house, buy now.''
</P>
<P>
   While mortgage rates will register the greatest impact from the
rate increase, auto loans, credit cards and home equity loans will
also be affected to varying degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Jon Stewart, president and CEO of Metcalf Bank, said that so
far, rising interest rates ``haven't appeared to slow down the
consumer.'' But he said that consumers should begin planning their
borrowing more soberly and base it on what they can afford.
</P>
<P>
   Car loan rates are expected to rise moderately, and so will some
lower-cost credit-card rates, though many Americans are already
conditioned to paying the higher credit-card rates.
</P>
<P>
   Home equity loans are expected to jump, making them less
attractive as vehicles to consolidate debt. Borrowing on the equity
of your home to invest in the stock market, an act of faith to
begin with, will turn into a reckless gamble, experts say.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone who is carrying debt is going to pay for it, if they
don't have a fixed rate,'' said Jeff Sheets, a spokesman for the
Consumer Credit Counseling Service of Greater Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   Savers, notably, stand to benefit from rising rates for
certificates of deposit.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed actions will have the most perilous effect on those
consumers who continue to borrow heavily beyond their means.
``Right now is the time to accelerate paying off your debt as much
as you can,'' Sheets said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people who will be hurt most are the people carrying the
most debt and who can't afford it.''
</P>
<P>
   Late Tuesday, the Hunzingers were waiting optimistically, with
their new loan, to see if their offer on their new house was
accepted.
</P>
<P>
   What the Fed does or doesn't do, Jeff Hunzinger said, ``is not
going to affect us one way or another.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
