<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORLD-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   NORTHERN IRELAND: GOVERNMENT DELAY
</P>
<P>
   Britain dropped hopes of restoring the suspended power-sharing
government in Belfast on Monday after leaders of the Ulster
Unionists objected to proposals for restricting the flying of the
Union Jack from government buildings and for changing the Royal
Ulster Constabulary's name. Northern Ireland Secretary Peter
Mandelson agreed to hold up on starting the government until after
the Protestant party votes on Saturday on whether to accept
disarmament moves by the Irish Republican Army. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY: PRESIDENT SWORN IN
</P>
<P>
   Ahmet Necdet Sezer, a former top judge, was sworn in as the new
president and said in a brief speech after his inauguration that
Turkey ``cannot remain closed within itself'' and should
concentrate on ``securing the rule of law and democracy.'' Sezer,
58, replaced Suleyman Demirel, a veteran politician who had sought
unsuccessfully to amend the Constitution so he could seek a second
term.
</P>
<P>
   BELARUS: VOTE CHANGES PROPOSED
</P>
<P>
   The country's autocratic leader, Alexander Lukashenko, has
agreed to negotiate changes in restrictive election laws next month
with pro-democracy forces, an aide said. But some in the
opposition, believing the move a feint, are demanding rights
reforms and international supervision of any talks first.
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE: INTERNET COLLEGE
</P>
<P>
   France will set up a college dedicated to the Internet and
provide more money for technology research, Prime Minister Lionel
Jospin announced. The school, near Marseille, will offer a
university education to gifted students and to people seeking
retraining in the growing Internet market. Jospin said France would
make more cash available to researchers.
</P>
<P>
   MIDDLE EAST
</P>
<P>
   PALESTINIANS: `MOST WANTED' SEIZED
</P>
<P>
   Officials of the militant Hamas group have confirmed that the
Palestinian Authority recently arrested Mohammed Deif, who has long
headed Israel's most wanted list for terror attacks. He was seized
and went quietly when Palestinian agents stormed a Gaza City house.
Palestinian officials have refused to confirm the arrest publicly
because, one official said, ``The people are giving us enough grief
about refugees and prisoners.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LEBANON: DUBLIN INCREASING TROOPS
</P>
<P>
   Ireland is the first country to agree to bolster its troops
serving in the United Nations forces in southern Lebanon before
Israel's withdrawal, Israeli radio said. Denmark, Norway and Sweden
have also been asked to send in more troops.
</P>
<P>
   IRAN: ANOTHER PAPER CLOSED
</P>
<P>
   The hard-line judiciary shut down another pro-reform newspaper,
Ham-Mihan, accusing it of ``advocating lies and suspicion.'' The
paper is published by the former mayor of Tehran, Gholamhossein
Karbaschi. A total of 18 papers and journals have been closed since
the press crackdown began last month.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   SRI LANKA: CLASHES RESUME
</P>
<P>
   After a brief lull, intense fighting resumed as artillery and
mortar fire by the Tamil Tiger guerrillas forced government troops
to shift their defense lines at Tanankillappu, just east of Jaffna
city.
</P>
<P>
   INDIA: FOOD PROTESTS
</P>
<P>
   Sonia Gandhi, India's main opposition leader, led a march
through New Delhi, protesting the government's decision to reduce
subsidies on food and cooking fuel. She threatened that her
Congress Party would continue street agitation until the cuts were
reversed.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   CANADA: RARE VICTORY
</P>
<P>
   The Conservative Party won a rare victory, narrowly holding on
to a parliamentary seat in a Newfoundland by-election. The victory,
in a district dominated by conservatives since Newfoundland joined
Canada in 1949, came after the party had lost leaders, strategists,
donors and legislators, largely to a new right-wing party, the
Canadian Alliance. The Conservatives, who formed Canada's first
government in 1867, are reduced to 18 members of Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   COLOMBIA: PEACE TALKS CANCELED
</P>
<P>
   Accusing the country's largest guerrilla group of responsibility
for the death of a woman who was blown to pieces in an extortion
attempt, President Andres Pastrana has ordered the cancellation of
peace talks the rebels convened for this month. Pastrana said the
Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia, who denied any involvement,
must show ``a change of attitude'' if peace talks begun last year
are to succeed.
</P>
<P>
   VENEZUELA: COALITION SPLIT
</P>
<P>
   With a general election little more than two weeks away, one of
the three parties in the coalition led by President Hugo Chavez has
pulled out. The left-wing Fatherland for All movement said it was
worried about the militarization of Chavez's government. The
decision has raised questions about the future of Energy Minister
Ali Rodriguez, a founder of the party and president of OPEC.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-17-00 0028EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
