   &UR; For WEDNESDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Wednesday, May 17.
</P>
<P>
   filed The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern
Time. To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for
reruns on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on
UPI DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   U.S.-CHINA-REACT (Brooklyn Park, Minn.) _ The American flag
flies over Wal-Mart in this Minneapolis suburb. The parking lot is
packed with Ford SUV's and Chrysler mini-vans. Even the stucco
facade is a patriotic melange of red, white and blue. Yet the
appeal of America's most successful retail chain, with its ``We
Sell for Less'' slogan emblazoned over the front door, stems in
part from the enormous low-cost production capacity of a far-away
nation that many people in this country view as a moral outcast and
potential military rival: China. From $16.95 Looney Tunes Tweetie
Birds to $5.94 Rawlings NCAA Final Four basketballs, Wal-Marts are
two-square-acre valentines to the idea that America should trade
with Communist China _ or, as President Clinton put it when
visiting a nearby farm late last week, ``reaching out a hand, not
shaking a clenched fist.'' But even as they fill their carts,
shoppers have their doubts. By Joseph Kahn.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Locator map has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-WORKERS (Beijing) _ Up to 2,000 unpaid workers and
retirees have besieged their factory and government offices in a
northeastern city, Liaoyang, a city of 1.8 million in the Rust Belt
province of Liaoning. The protest is the latest example of growing
labor unrest as China's once-dominant state industries collapse. By
Erik Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE-CONSTITUTION (Paris) _ Since the French Revolution,
France has remodeled its constitution four times. Now it looks as
if the Fifth Republic, 52 years old, may soon be refashioned too. A
proposal to cut the president's term of office to five years from
seven is gaining support from political leaders on both the right
and the left. It is an idea that has been put forward many times
before but has died in one political tangle or another. But this
time it looks as if political interests may increase its chances.
By Suzanne Daley.
</P>
<P>
   PERU-POLITICS (Sicuani, Peru) _ The Belgian-born wife of
President Fujimori's challenger in the presidential runoff speaks
Spanish and an Indian language with a French accent, but it is
proving to be a big campaign asset. By Clifford Krauss.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   QUADRIPLEGIC-GRAD (Cambridge, Mass.) _ Struck by a car on her
first day of seventh grade and given little hope of survival,
Brooke Ellison, a quadriplegic from Long Island, is graduating from
Harvard early next month, having navigated the campus for four
years in a wheelchair she steers with an electronic touchpad near
her tongue. Selected by her classmates to give a senior day
address, Ms. Ellison is sure to pay tribute to her mother, who has
been with her in every class since eighth grade. Mrs. Ellison moved
into her daughter's dormitory room freshman year and the two have
been within earshot of each other for every moment since. By
Jacques Steinberg.
</P>
<P>
   ALLEN-SEATTLE (Seattle) _ All the ways in which one man (that
would be Paul Allen) is having a major impact on the landscape of a
big American city, Seattle. Allen, the co-founder of Microsoft and
the 3rd/4th/5th richest guy in the world (we're still figuring this
out) is the money behind the ``experience music project,'' a new
wildly colorful and curvy Frank Gehry museum going up next to the
Space Needle; the blowing up of the Kingdome and its replacement
with a new outdoor football stadium; a huge development of
apartments expected to go up along Seattle's Lake Union; a new
superduper headquarters that is anchoring redevelopment of a
quarter of downtown; a bunch of buildings on the University of
Washington campus. By Sam Howe Verhovek.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-ANTARCTIC-DEATH (Undated) _ The death of the scientist at
South Pole shows it is still a dangerous place. By James Glanz.
</P>
<P>
   FORESTS-ENVIRON _ The environmental groups are galvanized and
the logging industry is scrambling to figure out how to fight the
fight over the 43 million acres of forests that President Clinton
has set aside to be free of roads. It's a tale of advertising,
grass-roots organizing and other advocacy on what both sides see as
their top environmental priority for the year. By Douglas Jehl.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CAMPAIGN _ (Moved in ``p'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   GORE-ADVISERS (Washington) _ Vice President Al Gore has
assembled a large team of foreign policy advisers whose members
could form the national security nucleus of a Gore administration.
The current role of the advisory group is somewhat nebulous,
however, since Gore has never relied on outsiders for advice on
foreign policy and the new panel has not yet contributed much of
substance to his campaign. The vice president has great faith in
his own national security experience and instincts. He has an
intimate, 20-year relationship with his national security alter
ego, Leon Fuerth, through whom all foreign policy information
flows. The vice president has participated in every major national
security debate over the past decade and has access to intelligence
and foreign policy expertise throughout the government. By John M.
Broder.
</P>
<P>
   SOCSEC-CANDIDATES (Undated) _ Al Gore and George W. Bush take
the debate over social security to younger audiences. Gore will try
to convince voters that the stock market is a risky place for this
critical part of their retirement, while Bush will argue that this
is just the way to make sure that the system is still solvent when
they retire. By James Dao and Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   GORE-INVEST (Undated) _ Al Gore is not only an opponent of
investing Social Security money in the stock market, he is also a
non-player in the markets with none of his own money invested in
stocks. By Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-WEBSITES (Undated) _ The proliferation of grass-roots
web sites that promote and disparage the presidential candidates.
By Leslie Wayne.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON _ (Moved in ``w'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   PHONE-TAX _ A century ago, Congress imposed a temporary tax on a
relatively new technology considered a luxury item: telephone
calls. The need was urgent: paying for the Spanish-American War.
The House Ways and Means Committee is now hearing arguments to
abolish the tax, which costs a typical family $50 a year. House
approval is considered a sure thing. By Irvin Molotsky.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CONRESS _ Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, the presumptive
Republican presidential nominee, has told Senate Republicans that
he opposes legislation they back to set a deadline for withdrawing
American ground troops from Kosovo, fearing that it would tie his
hands if he is elected president. By Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-FEDERALISM _ A news analysis on the Court's set of
rulings limiting Congress's power and supporting the sovereignity
of states. By Linda Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-DETECTIVES (San Francisco) _ Within hours after a
destructive computer program began circulating this month, borne by
an e-mail marked ``I Love You,'' a handful of high-tech detectives
around the globe leaped into action. Scrutinizing clues left in the
computer code, and pursuing evidence accumulated in hidden corners
of cyberspace, the detectives homed in on several suspects in the
Philippines. But the detectives are unlikely to testify at trial,
or receive official commendation. That is because they are not
police officers, but ordinary citizens. They are among a growing
number of Net habitues turned cybersleuths whose work has become
vital to the pursuit of Internet criminals. These amateur
detectives are taking part in what the authorities say is
unprecedented cooperation between law enforcement and citizens. But
the police say the cooperation also is a mixed blessing. By Matt
Richtel.
</P>
<P>
   FED-MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ Alan Greenspan, the chairman of the
Federal Reserve Board, still believes that his medicine _ higher
interest rates _ will slow the economy. But it appears that the
medicine is much weaker than he had thought it was a year ago, and
that much higher doses will be needed to have the desired effect.
By Floyd Norris.
</P>
