<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAMPAIGN NEWS AND NOTES FROM AROUND THE NATION 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BATTLE OVER BATTLE FLAG
</P>
<P>
   If South Carolina lawmakers hoped that the NAACP would drop its
economic boycott now that they have agreed to move the Confederate
battle flag from the Statehouse dome, they had not counted on the
group's tenacity. Kweisi Mfume, the national president of the
group, said Tuesday that the NAACP might even consider expanding
the boycott beyond tourism, because the state plans to move the
banner to a flagpole in front of the State Capitol, near a monument
to Confederate soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   Although the group's original boycott resolution demanded that
the flag be moved out of a position of sovereignty, Mfume argued
that the flag was no less prominent in front of the building than
it was on top. The state Senate and House are expected to iron out
minor differences on a bill to move the flag in the next few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   DECISION IN KENNEDY CASE
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles city attorney declined Tuesday to file
misdemeanor battery charges against Rep. Patrick J. Kennedy,
D-R.I., over a confrontation with a security guard at Los Angeles
International Airport in March. The prosecutor's office summoned
Kennedy, 32, and the guard, Della Patton, 58, to a hearing last
week to review a videotape of the incident. Kennedy had earlier
acknowledged acting rudely and apologized, but he denied hurting
Patton.
</P>
<P>
   George L. Mallory Jr., a lawyer for Patton, who has complained
of shoulder pain and has not worked since the incident, said he
expected to approach Kennedy about a settlement and would sue if
those talks failed.
</P>
<P>
   GUBERNATORIAL EARLY BIRD
</P>
<P>
   It's a year early, but the 2001 gubernatorial race in Virginia
is already taking shape, with one self-made millionaire announcing
this week that he is stepping aside for another in the Democratic
competition. A former congressman, L.F. Payne Jr., a
Charlottesville developer who lost as the Democratic Party's
candidate for lieutenant governor in 1997, took himself out of the
running and endorsed Mark R. Warner, who heads a venture capital
firm in Alexandria. Payne said Warner had ``the right experience,
the right ideas and the right values'' to win the governorship.
</P>
<P>
   Payne's base is in rural conservative Democratic politics and he
showed his popularity in managing to finish ahead of the rest of
his ticket in the Democrats' bid to take the Statehouse in 1997.
But he conceded that Warner, whose base is in the northern suburbs,
had a dominant edge in organization and fund-raising among
high-tech corporate donors. In the meantime, Payne may take on an
organizational role in Warner's campaign. The Republican nomination
for governor next year is expected to be contested by Lt. Gov. John
H. Hager, who defeated Payne in 1997, and Attorney General Mark L.
Earley.
</P>
<P>
   `LIVE TAX FREE OR DIE'
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Jeanne Shaheen of New Hampshire announced Tuesday that she
would seek a third two-year term. But she did not say whether she
would renew her pledge to veto an income tax, which is seen by some
state leaders, albeit reluctantly, as the best way for the state to
respond to a court order to reform school financing.
</P>
<P>
   Year in and year out, taxes are the hottest political issue in
New Hampshire, a state that, along with Alaska, has no personal
income tax or general sales tax (its official motto is ``Live Free
Or Die'') and whose residents take great pride in roughing up
politicians who do not pledge to oppose new levies. Shaheen, a
Democrat, took ``the pledge'` in her 1996 and 1998 campaigns but
she has thus far avoided discussing what she might do in the 2000
campaign _ though she did agree to a temporary tax, at one point,
as the state initially tried to respond to the court
school-financing order.
</P>
<P>
   In this year's Democratic primary, she will face state Sen. Mark
Fernald, who supports a state income tax to solve the school
problem. On the Republican side, four candidates are competing for
the nomination, with mixed views on the tax question. There is also
an independent candidate.
</P>
<P>
   PAYBACK TIME
</P>
<P>
   Call it political payback _ the kind with potential to undermine
party unity in one of this year's major presidential and
congressional battlegrounds: Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter circulated last week during the state's Republican
convention, Gov. John Engler and the state Republican Party
chairman, Rusty Hills, agreed to elect supporters of John McCain as
delegates to the Republican National Convention this summer in
Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   After all, McCain won the Michigan primary in February,
upsetting Engler's candidate, George W. Bush. But by the time the
convention votes were in, McCain's primary victory had effectively
been overturned. Most of the 58 delegates selected for the national
convention were Bush backers. In protest, McCain, just days after a
peace parley with Bush, has canceled a trip to the state this
Friday that was to have benefited Sen. Spencer Abraham of Auburn
Hills and and a Republican House hopeful, Mike Rogers of Brighton,
both caught in tight contests that very well could be crucial in
determining control of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Hills said he and Engler signed the letter in good faith but
they had little control over the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   WEDNESDAY'S SCHEDULES
</P>
<P>
   GEORGE W. BUSH _ Everett, Wash.
</P>
<P>
   AL GORE _ New York; Orlando, Fla.; Nashville
</P>
