<HEADER>
A7224 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-FLAKE-AZR &LR;      05-17 0671
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLAKE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RIVALS ASKING FLAKE TO RETURN CONSULTING FEE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 BY KRIS MAYES  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
(PHOENIX) - Two of Jeff Flake's Republican opponents in the 1st
Congressional District called on him Tuesday, May 16, to return the
$72,000-a-year consulting fee he is receiving from an Arizona
non-profit group.
</P>
<P>
   And one of the opponents, Tom Liddy of Chandler, suggested that
Flake's failure to act could jeopardize the GOP's credibility in
the race, which has attracted national attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a Republican, Jeff Flake ought to understand that he has
put our party in a bad situation, and he ought to put it right,''
Liddy said. ``It should either go back to Ira Fulton or to poor
kids, but it should not be in the pocket of a guy who is running
for Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   Money for Flake's fee was made available by a donation to the
Arizona School Choice Trust from Flake's campaign finance chairman,
Phoenix area developer Ira Fulton, an arrangement that should now
be reversed, according to two of Flake's opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Also Tuesday, May 16, Democrats followed through on their
promise to file a complaint with the Federal Election Commission
asking for an investigation into whether the consulting fee
represents an excessive campaign contribution.
</P>
<P>
   In their complaint to the FEC, Democrats allege that Flake has
inadequately accounted for the hours he says he has worked for the
non-profit group:
</P>
<P>
   ``We have reason to believe . . . that no records exist
reflecting the amount of pledged time that Mr. Flake has spent
`consulting' with or for the School Choice Trust.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Patterson, chairman of the board of the trust, told The
Arizona Republic last week that Flake has not been required to keep
regular hours at the organization or file regular paperwork there
because he is a contract worker.
</P>
<P>
   However, according to several board members interviewed by The
Republic, Flake has regularly attended board meetings to report on
his progress.
</P>
<P>
   Another GOP opponent, Susan Bitter Smith, agreed with Liddy that
Flake should return his fee, noting that last year, the School
Choice Trust had more applicants than it had dollars to provide
scholarships. She said repayment of the fee ``would be a good first
step.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom-line victims of all of this are the kids that
didn't get funded,'' said Bitter Smith, who is also a former member
of the trust's board of directors. ``Returning it would be a start,
but I don't know if it fixes all the other problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Flake, who did not return calls for comment, has defended the
consulting fee and its source, saying that Fulton never intended to
make a political contribution when he agreed to donate $50,000 to
the trust.
</P>
<P>
   Flake has also said that his services as a fund-raiser for the
School Choice Trust are well worth the money.
</P>
<P>
   In return for the consulting fee, Flake is helping the School
Choice Trust establish an employee payroll deduction program with
large Valley corporations that could help bring in thousands of new
donations to the group. Those duties, Flake has said, require him
to put in about 30 hours a week, mostly at night.
</P>
<P>
   Liddy also blasted the Democrats for disingenuously attempting
to make hay of the matter and suggested that Flake return the money
over time if he is unable to make a one-time payment.
</P>
<P>
   ``He should just pledge and commit to do it over a course of
time,'' Liddy said. ``We all have to be reasonable about that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats also called for Flake to repay his fee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think, at a minimum, that is a good course of action,'' said
Cortland Coleman, executive director of the Arizona Democratic
Party. ``However, that will not deter our action in filing with the
FEC, the U.S. attorney or the IRS.''
</P>
<P>
   The party intends to file separate complaints with the Internal
Revenue Service and the U.S. Attorney's Office later this week. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Reach the reporter at Kris.Mayes(at)ArizonaRepublic.com or (602)
444-8285. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-17-00 0050EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
