<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FED-REACT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONSUMERS ALREADY FEELING HIGHER INTEREST RATES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS SIEROTY AND GREG WILCOX 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; LOS ANGELES _ The Federal Reserve Board's half a percentage
point increase in interest rates Tuesday likely means consumers
will pay more for home loans, car loans and credit cards.
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, they already are.
</P>
<P>
   Financial analysts say the Federal Reserve's Open Market
Committee action is an effort to slow the economy and keep
inflation in check. Many expect another rate hike in June after the
group's next meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers shopping for a new home in the past several weeks got
a preview of the Fed's action because mortgage rates moved up in
anticipation of Tuesday's increase.
</P>
<P>
   For example, last week interest rates for a 30-year fixed
mortgage in California averaged 8.81 percent, up from 8.28 percent
at the end of April, according to a survey by HSH Associates, which
publishes mortgage rate information.
</P>
<P>
   Interest rates have now risen 1.75 percent in less than a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is quite a traumatic increase, and a lot of it is already
incorporated in (mortgage) rates, and it is lowering sales,'' said
G.U. Krueger, deputy chief economist for the California Association
of Realtors, based in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Fresh evidence surfaced this week that rising rates are having
the desired effect of reeling in the economy.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday the Southland Regional Association of Realtors
reported that sales of single-family homes in the San Fernando
Valley fell 9.1 percent in April on an annual basis.
</P>
<P>
   The Realtors cited rising interest rates as one culprit - the
first time in years rates have chilled the market.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's making it harder to buy a home. The cost of housing
becomes more expensive,'' Krueger said about rising rates.
</P>
<P>
   When home-buying slows, so can purchases of such big-ticket
items like washers, dryers and refrigerators.
</P>
<P>
   And with prices also rising, sales could slow even further, some
predict. Others disagree.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Carney, head of the Real Estate Research Council at
California State Polytechnic University, Pomona, doubts that the
Fed's action will have any effect on the residential housing
market.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe it will have no dampening effect on consumer
confidence. It's at a very high level,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Local Fed watchers - Carney among them - say Federal Reserve
Chairman Alan Greenspan and company aren't finished increasing
rates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless there are dramatic changes in the economy, you will see
the Federal Reserve raise interest rates by another half-point at
their next meeting,'' said Jack Kyser, chief economist for the Los
Angeles Economic Development Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Following another increase, Kyser expects the Federal Reserve to
take a break to see whether the rate hikes have had the desired
effect of slowing the economy enough to control inflation without
causing a recession.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Weiss, senior vice president and chief investment
officer with City National Investments, a division of City National
Bank, said: ``This one wasn't a shock to us, but this is not the
end of the interest rate hike cycle.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the central bank increased the federal funds rate to
6.5 percent from 6 percent. The federal funds rate is what banks
charge each other on overnight loans.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed also raised the discount rate, the interest it charges
to make direct loans to banks, from 5.5 percent to 6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed's half-point increase in the funds rate was followed by
an announcement by Bank of America, Bank One and City National Bank
that they were boosting their prime lending rate by a similar
half-point from 9 percent to 9.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The prime rate is the key measuring stick for millions of loans,
including mortgages, car loans and credit card balances.
</P>
<P>
   ``The good news is ... to the extent the Federal Reserve is able
to tame inflation, that will keep long-term interest rates
steady,'' said Weiss.
</P>
<P>
   So what should consumers expect?
</P>
<P>
   ``People aren't going to wake up tomorrow and find their rates a
half-point higher,'' James E. Glassman, a managing director at
Chase Securities, said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's progressively growing more expensive'' to borrow for
millions of consumers whose aggregate personal savings rate, as a
proportion of disposable income, has dwindled to virtually nothing,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   In general, the highest borrowing rates - typically on credit
cards for those with subpar incomes or repayment histories - will
be hit relatively lightly because they reflect more the lenders'
cost of administration and write-offs of uncollectible accounts
than the cost of money.
</P>
<P>
   But there will be some direct effects.
</P>
<P>
   Citibank, for example, ties its credit card rates to the prime
rate, which it raised a half-point Tuesday to 9.5 percent, in
lockstep with the Fed, as has become the pattern in recent years.
The bank's policy is to review these rates on the last business day
of the month, meaning its card rates will rise for July payments on
purchases made in June, said Susan Weeks, a spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the sixth increase in interest rates within 12 months,
analysts say California's robust economy should continue to expand,
albeit at a slightly slower pace.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the end of the year, we are going to see the local economy
move at a slower pace, which isn't bad,'' said Kyser.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Ackerman, president and chief executive officer of the
Economic Alliance of the San Fernando Valley, said he fears higher
interest rates will dampen enthusiasm for developing commercial and
residential real estate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, we need all the new units we can build because
demand for housing is outpacing supply,'' said Ackerman.
</P>
<P>
   Weiss notes that because Los Angeles County's economy is
dominated by aerospace, technology and entertainment, it is
somewhat insulated from direct shocks linked to interest rate
hikes.
</P>
<P>
   Weiss compared the latest rate hike to a dose of medicine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes it doesn't taste good while you're taking it, but
there is a good chance it will benefit your long-term health,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times contributed to this story.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
