<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CAMPAIGN-REFORM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: IMITATIONS OF `WEST WING' 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial of Wednesday, May 17:
</P>
<P>
   In this season's final episode of ``West Wing,'' President
Josiah Bartlet (played by Martin Sheen) will deal tonight with a
downed pilot in Iraq, a balky space shuttle and a battle with
Congress over campaign finance reform. As it happens, the last of
these issues is unfolding in the real Washington this week, in
almost the same way. But while Bartlet is bravely trying to reshape
the Federal Election Commission and ban soft money, President
Clinton (played by himself) and the real Democrats are battling
only half-heartedly for reform.
</P>
<P>
   In the real Washington, the fight is over the drive by Trent
Lott, the Senate majority leader, to place Bradley Smith, a
notorious opponent of campaign finance laws, on the Federal
Election Commission, where he would be responsible for enforcing
those laws. Lott is offering the Democrats all kinds of incentives
to go along. On television, the Senate majority leader (Lott's
counterpart) is trying to block a Democratic effort to make the
commission stronger by appointing reformers. He, too, is offering a
deal _ let the commission remain weak with its existing members in
return for action on a pet Bartlet proposal.
</P>
<P>
   We have a hunch that Bartlet will rebuff the Republican
deal-makers and carry through on reform. Clinton and Tom Daschle,
the Senate minority leader, should stand as firm. They might be
pleased to note that, in TV land, Bartlet's approval ratings have
risen with his seizure of the reform banner, just as Sen. John
McCain's did in real life this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``West Wing'' producers are betting that viewers are rooting for
a campaign finance cleanup. Washington will never want to compete
with most goings-on in the show. This one is worth a try. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-17-00 0102EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
