r s BC-BBO-LeBRETON-COLUMN-T     05-17 0841
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-LeBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CUTE HOUSTON STADIUM PLAYS UGLY ON PITCHERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LeBRETON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Houston, we have a problem. But there's nothing you
can do about it now.
</P>
<P>
   The ribbon is cut. The $248 million is spent. And Jose Lima's
earned-run average is already higher than the cab fare from the
airport.
</P>
<P>
   At first glance, Enron Field is ... uh ... cute. It is a
matchbox of washed stone and eye candy, squeezed purposefully into
a corner nook of downtown Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that nobody lives in downtown Houston. The new home
of the Astros, like so many of the knee-jerk,
must-have-a-skyscraper-view ballparks of these times, was built on
the premise that if you squeeze it in, they will come.
</P>
<P>
   And they have. Despite Lima and despite the home team's
disappointing record, the Astros have performed in front of sellout
and near-sellout crowds all season.
</P>
<P>
   This is not your father's Astrodome. This is not even a distant
cousin.
</P>
<P>
   Compared to the inert, beer-stained Astrodome, home of baseball
in Houston for 35 seasons, Enron Field is a Disneyland. It has a
playful hill butting the wall in straightaway center field. It even
has a toy train.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, the train. Enron Field adjoins the city's historic Union
Station. The locomotive that chugs along the makeshift track atop
the left-field seats blows steam and whistles like the real deal
whenever an Astro hits a home run. It's not really a train, in
other words, but it plays one on TV.
</P>
<P>
   Visiting managers have labeled it a shrill nuisance, yet it's no
more annoying than those infernal bell chimes at Yankee Stadium.
The real tragedy of the Enron Field choo-choo is that it detracts
from the home-run-cued cartoon on the adjoining scoreboard _ the
snorting steer and the galloping cowboys from the Astrodome's
original ``scoreboard spectacular.''
</P>
<P>
   Too much of a good thing, however, soon gets boring, and Astros
fans sound as if they don't know what to make of their new
playhouse on the corner of Crawford and Texas streets.
</P>
<P>
   Through their first 19 games there, the Astros are 6-13 and a
total of 69 home runs have been hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love this place,'' outfielder Henry Rodriguez said, echoing
the sentiments of many players.
</P>
<P>
   The problem, alas, is that Henry plays for the Chicago Cubs.
Astros pitchers are singing a song that is quite different.
</P>
<P>
   In ye olden days, cities built ballparks to match the
surrounding landscapes. Topography was relative. Thus, the
venerable Fenway Park boasts its famous left-field wall. The Polo
Grounds was more or less the shape of a shoe box.
</P>
<P>
   When Baltimore's Camden Yards opened in 1992 to rave reviews and
nightly sellouts, baseball's ears perked. Not every new stadium, it
discovered, needs to be built like the grand opera house.
</P>
<P>
   Camden Yards' charm is its lack of spaciousness. Cal Ripken
seems so close you could almost touch him.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, nobody polled the pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   The home run sells, the lords of baseball decided. Enron Field's
left-field foul pole is a very intentional 315 feet from home
plate. Against the Astros Sunday night, Cincinnati's
left-handed-hitting Eddie Taubensee, trying to poke an outside
pitch the other way, nearly poked a 315-feet, 6-inch home run over
the left-field wall. It was foul by a foot.
</P>
<P>
   Right field at Enron is only 326 feet, and the inviting alley in
right-center is 373 but buttressed by a mere seven-foot wall.
</P>
<P>
   In San Francisco, right field at the new Pacific Bell Park
measures 307 feet. I'll bet the right-field line at your nearby
high school field is farther.
</P>
<P>
   The point is, unlike the old parks, these are not accidents of
geometry. Astros owner Drayton McLane obviously wanted his team's
new home to play this way.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a beautiful place,'' said Lima, whose first seven
starts produced 16 home runs and a 9.53 ERA. ``But it's worse than
Coors Field on pitchers. You can see the hitters smiling as they're
walking up to the plate.''
</P>
<P>
   Alarming stat of the month: The home run per-game ratio at Enron
Field (3.63) is higher than at the mile-high home of the Colorado
Rockies. Enron Field is Coors Lite.
</P>
<P>
   Quaint and cozy are admirable features for a ballpark to have.
But hitters today are bigger, stronger and fueled by all sorts of
natural (and unnatural) herbs and spices. They can't fit in places
like Enron Field and Pac Bell Park anymore.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't make the new home of the Astros a bad place. But it
totally changes the baseball landscape in Houston, where the heroes
have always seemed to be pitchers _ Nolan Ryan, Mike Scott, Don
Sutton, J.R. Richard, Larry Dierker.
</P>
<P>
   On April 10 in the fourth game at Enron Field, the Cardinals and
Astros combined for eight home runs. In 35 years at the dead-air
Astrodome, the most ever hit was six.
</P>
<P>
   Astros fans, judging by the talk shows, are mortified. But it's
too late _ the train has left the station, in more ways than one.
</P>
<P>
   I think the new place is, uh, cute.
</P>
<P>
   Too cute?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-17-00 0107EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
