<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-MINING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: A PROMISING ACCORD IN MONTANA 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Wednesday, May 17:
</P>
<P>
   In the past, the mining industry in Montana has made few
environmental concessions to anyone. But in a surprising and
salutary development, the Stillwater Mining Co., which operates two
platinum mines in the Beartooth Mountains at the edge of the
Absaroka-Beartooth Wilderness, has signed a good-neighbor agreement
with a coalition of local environmental and citizens' groups
operating under the umbrella of the Northern Plains Resource
Council.
</P>
<P>
   This striking agreement holds the East Boulder and Stillwater
mines to a higher set of environmental standards than those
required by state and federal authorities. It institutes oversight
committees with members drawn from mine management and citizens'
groups. The company will place thousands of acres under
conservation easements, and it will finance audits of its own
environmental performance. Most important, it has agreed to an open
exchange of information with the council and will invest in what
the council calls ``groundbreaking new water treatment and waste
reduction technologies.''
</P>
<P>
   It is possible to attribute the fact of this agreement to the
profitability of these mines, which has given Stillwater Mining
greater latitude to negotiate. But this agreement could not have
come about without enlightened leadership at the company or the
dedication of negotiators for local citizens and environmentalists.
The result makes genuine environmental protection consistent with
continued productivity. With luck, this may become a model for
similar agreements elsewhere. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-17-00 0108EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000517.0023 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 01:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7248 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBC-BAYLOR-SHOPPACH-H     05-17 1020
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBC-BAYLOR-SHOPPACH-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TERRY BLOUNT  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
WACO _ A couple of weeks ago against Kansas, Baylor catcher Kelly
Shoppach made two aggressive tags while blocking the plate to keep
runs from scoring.
<TEXT>
<P>
   He glared at one Kansas baserunner who got face-to-face with
him, then spiked the ball on the plate and ran back to the dugout.
</P>
<P>
   When the game ended, the first person on the field to greet
Shoppach was Baylor football coach Kevin Steele.
</P>
<P>
   ``OK, I'm giving you the option,'' Steele said. ``Fullback or
linebacker, whichever you prefer. It's all yours. Just put on the
pads, and we're good to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Shoppach, who rushed for more than 1,000 yards in each of his
last two football seasons at Brewer High School in Fort Worth, just
chuckled and said thanks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I go to every Baylor football game, and it wasn't out of the
question that I might play,'' Shoppach said. ``Growing up in Texas,
that's all you ever want. But when it came down to it, I thought I
had a better future in baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   It appears he was right because Shoppach and his teammates did
something this season no living Baylor alumnus has done _ win an
outright conference baseball championship. The last time that
happened was 1923.
</P>
<P>
   The fourth-ranked Bears (42-14, 23-7 Big 12) enter the Big 12
tournament in Oklahoma City as the top seed after clinching the
league title last weekend with a three-game sweep at Kansas State.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were loose and relaxed, and we knew what we had to do,''
Shoppach said. ``We went there to win the title and play like the
best team in the Big 12.''
</P>
<P>
   Baylor, which learned Monday it will host an NCAA regional for
the second consecutive year, will play Texas A&AMP;M in a first-round
game tonight at the Bricktown Ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   Shoppach and the Bears hope to add the tournament championship
to their regular-season title, but the big goal is a trip to the
College World Series. Baylor fell one game short of reaching that
plateau last season, losing to Oklahoma State in a Super Regional
at Waco.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of us remember how that felt,'' Shoppach said. ``We don't
want to feel that way again.''
</P>
<P>
   As the team's cleanup hitter, Shoppach has been a big part of
Baylor's success this season. He is hitting .311 with nine homers
and 39 RBIs. It has been a pleasant surprise to coach Steve Smith,
who wasn't so sure about Shoppach's future after his freshman year
last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kelly had some soul-searching to do, and he did it,'' Smith
said. ``He needed to change his attitude, and he needed to change
his life. And physically, he needed to get in shape.''
</P>
<P>
   The 5-10 Shoppach, a stocky and muscular guy, put on some pounds
while sitting the bench as a freshman, tipping the scales at 250
pounds near the end of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kelly came down here, and he let himself go,'' Smith said.
``He became pessimistic and real negative in his thinking. He came
in thinking he was not going to start and lost his competitive
nature. He didn't realize that I was open about it. I was waiting
for him to step forward.''
</P>
<P>
   But that didn't happen, so Smith felt it was time to have a
serious chat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every year at the end of the season, I meet individually with
each of the players,'' Smith said. ``It's usually a very pleasant
exchange.
</P>
<P>
   ``But this was not a dialogue. This was about a 10-minute
monologue. Bless his heart. He came in with a smile on his face
about leaving for the summer, but when he left, he was very stoic.
I don't think he said one word the entire time he was in my
office.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith told Shoppach he wanted him to return in shape, but he
also wanted him to return with the attitude he saw in Shoppach when
he was one of the best high school athletes in the state. He had
scholarship offers in football from Texas, Baylor, Oklahoma and
Mississippi.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was so impressed with him in high school,'' Smith said. ``He
was the leading rusher, leading receiver. He kicked off, he punted,
and he returned punts.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is so physically strong. It was funny watching him play
baseball in the summers. The kids in the stands would be talking
about him. I heard them whispering, `Shoppach.' It was like he was
a folk hero. He was this larger-than-life guy in high school.''
</P>
<P>
   But that wasn't the person Smith saw last year at Baylor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was almost like he was a depressed and melancholy guy,''
Smith said. ``My level of confidence in Kelly was not very high. I
was uncomfortable with the situation, and I told him what I thought
he needed to do to change it.''
</P>
<P>
   Shoppach took Smith's advice to heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach Smith was very honest, and it was good for me,''
Shoppach said. ``He was right. I came in here not sure what my role
would be. You're not the leader that you were in high school, and I
didn't take that transition well at all. I knew I had to change and
be the best I could be for my teammates.''
</P>
<P>
   When Shoppach arrived for his sophomore year last fall, one
change was obvious.
</P>
<P>
   ``I left for Liberal, Kan., where I played ball last summer, at
245 pounds,'' Shoppach said. ``I came back at 195 pounds. I started
running, and the weight just came off. Right now I'm at 215, which
is the ideal weight for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith admits he has been surprised at Shoppach's transformation,
physically and mentally.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope and pray my own kids will respond to me the way he
did,'' Smith said. ``What he is now, in terms of makeup, is what I
expected him to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Shoppach came back for his sophomore year knowing he would have
to beat out senior Bryan Loeb for the starting catcher's job. Loeb,
who was drafted by the New York Mets, elected to stay in school.
</P>
<P>
   Shoppach's renewed dedication earned him the job. He has started
41 of 56 games behind the plate, making only two errors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kelly is as good defensively as anyone I've ever been
around,'' Smith said. ``He can go a long way in the game of
baseball on that alone. And he will get better as a hitter with
time. He has the one thing you can't teach, and that's physical
strength.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
