<HEADER>
A7249 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBC-HOUSTON-NANCE-HNS     05-17 0766
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBC-HOUSTON-NANCE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NEAL FARMER  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ University of Houston lefthander Shane Nance
has a way of taking over a game. He already has set a school record
with 30 career wins, and as the 2000 season draws to a close, his
fastball has been clocked at 93 mph _ the hardest he has ever
thrown the baseball.
<TEXT>
<P>
   But there is another area in which Nance has made an unexpected
contribution for the Cougars.
</P>
<P>
   Nance is batting leadoff and has shown a propensity for power.
He was just what the Cougars needed when they suffered through a
midseason slump _ mostly at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is one thing that has kick-started us out of our
doldrums, I think it was when he went into the leadoff spot,'' UH
coach Rayner Noble said. ``He contributed for us, and that was big,
especially when combined with what he has been doing on the
mound.''
</P>
<P>
   Houston, 39-14 and ranked No. 6 by Baseball America, plays at 3
p.m. today in the first round of the Conference USA tournament. The
top-seeded Cougars will face No. 8-seeded Louisville.
</P>
<P>
   The winner of the tournament receives the league's automatic bid
to an NCAA regional, although UH already is in the playoff field by
virtue of being named a host of one of the 16 first-round
tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   Nance had a chance to bypass his senior season at Houston when
he was selected by the Los Angeles Dodgers in the 24th round of
last year's draft. He met with Noble after the draft, wanting to
discuss UH's future and what could be accomplished in the 2000
season. With 10 seniors returning, all involved thought it could be
a special year. The discussion turned to Nance's being able to play
the outfield and serve as a designated hitter, which intrigued him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Originally, batting was not what we were going to talk
about,'' Nance said. ``The conversation just went that way. I told
them that we were going to have a good team this year, and if I
could help the team by playing in the outfield and swinging the
bat, then I could do that. I said that if I was going back for my
senior year, I wanted to play as much as I could. I wasn't worried
about getting hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   So on opening day this year Nance was batting second in the
lineup, alternating between DH and left field. He found his stroke
Feb. 22 with a two-homer game against Rice that included a grand
slam. He continued batting second until he was injured March 10 at
Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   Nance and center fielder Jason Pekar slammed into each other in
the outfield while chasing a bloop hit, and Nance missed four weeks
at the plate and six weeks on the mound with a shoulder injury. He
returned as a pinch hitter April 8 against South Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Nance continue to swing the bat well and was moved to leadoff
April 18 against Baylor in a game he also started on the mound.
Houston scored 10 runs in the first inning and cruised to an 11-2
win.
</P>
<P>
   Nance has been the Cougars' catalyst on offense, just as he has
been Mr. Dependable as a starting pitcher. He has a 7-1 record in
10 starts and a team-leading ERA of 2.33. In 65 innings, he has
given up 17 earned runs (23 total), allowed 58 hits and struck out
55 while walking 19.
</P>
<P>
   As a hitter, he is batting .361 in 97 at-bats and has reached
base in 48 percent of his plate appearances. He has scored 25 runs
while knocking in 21.
</P>
<P>
   Brandon Caraway, who hit leadoff for the Cougars when the season
began, was in a slump when he was replaced by Nance. Now they both
are hitting well, with Nance batting leadoff and Caraway ninth
against righthanders and Caraway hitting leadoff with Nance last
against lefties.
</P>
<P>
   Noble compares Nance with former college stars Jason Jennings of
Baylor and Brooks Kieschnick of Texas as players who made
differences for their teams with the bat as well as their arms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shane is fiery and really creates things,'' Noble said. ``When
Shane came in as a freshman, at that point he probably was a better
outfielder than a pitcher, although he was pretty good at both.
When I saw how valuable he was going to be on the mound, I didn't
let him hit much or play in the field much. I know it has been a
passion of Shane's to play in the field.''
</P>
<P>
   Nance admits as much, but he also knew his route to the pros was
via the mound.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe playing outfield and batting brought back a little bit
more of a fire or a sense of urgency for me, since this is my last
year here,'' he said. ``I think I am just as focused as I always
have been. But I think it brought back a hunger.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
