<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 01:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7250 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKC-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-     05-17 0769
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
FranBlinebury
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
THE bottom is still down there somewhere, below the chair-throwing,
the vase-tossing, the boss-abusing, the player-choking and the
authority-flaunting, to name just a few benchmarks.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Knight's fall is not finished, and the gentle thud from the
soft landing provided by Indiana's farcical university president
Myles Brand was both an echo and an omen.
</P>
<P>
   There will be more where that came from. You can count on it,
which is what Brand seems to be doing. And the bump, bump, bump to
wherever this finally comes to rest is going to sound like a body
going down an empty well.
</P>
<P>
   Do the letters IU stand for ``invertebrate uncles'' or ``idiotic
utterances''? For to implement a zero-tolerance policy on Knight at
this point is the equivalent of reading Willie Sutton the
bank-robbery laws after all the money is gone.
</P>
<P>
   After 29 years of head-butting, son-kicking, verbal tirades,
childishness and unadulterated cruelty to so many, what constitutes
an act that would embarrass the university and thereby prompt
Knight's dismissal?
</P>
<P>
   An altercation with a Puerto Rican policeman during an
international competition? Been there.
</P>
<P>
   Lifting an LSU fan off his feet and dumping him into a trash can
at the Final Four? Done that.
</P>
<P>
   Grabbing one of his players by the throat? Unleashing a
profanity-filled blast at a 64-year-old female secretary and
heaving a vase against a wall behind her head? Knocking the sports
information director to the floor? Motivating his team at halftime
of a game with the shockingly disgusting _ even for him _ action of
waving used toilet paper in their faces?
</P>
<P>
   It is all part of a laundry list of antisocial,
I-don't-have-to-answer-to-anyone behavior that has defined Knight
far more than his basketball genius for the better part of three
decades.
</P>
<P>
   His defenders will claim it is all old news that is being used
in a dose of new-millennium political correctness to tarnish an
icon.
</P>
<P>
   And to an extent, they will be correct. It is old news, and
that's why Brand and the Indiana board of trustees should have
embarrassed faces that are redder than one of Knight's sweaters
because they have never lifted a finger to act in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Knight has won a lot of basketball games and three national
championships that kept the wolves at bay for so long. He has also
struggled to find success in the first round of the NCAA Tournament
in recent seasons _ unheralded Pepperdine dropped the ax this year
_ and that has brought critics who were previously willing to
tolerate his antics out of the woodwork.
</P>
<P>
   But it should not _ and it is not _ about simply winning and
losing as long as the stated mission of a well-respected university
is to instill values in, as well as educate, young minds. How does
it serve the university in any way to have Knight ranting, raving,
scowling, sneering and cursing in front of an IU banner at all who
ever questioned his methods or his madness?
</P>
<P>
   Bullies. Motivating by fear. So big in their own minds. So small
is their recognition of the respect they are never given outside
their range of direct influence.
</P>
<P>
   Knight would long ago have been fired at any Fortune 500 company
or from any small business in the private sector. But in
Hoosierland, his intimidation of the powers that be in the
university administration allowed Knight to feel invincible and
only fueled more unacceptable acts for which he was never held
accountable. Compared to Coach Bob, eels are Velcro.
</P>
<P>
   What Brand would have us believe is that he is coming down hard
on Knight with the zero-tolerance mandate, when what he is really
doing is taking the easy, spineless way out. In a state where the
coaching legend is still a political force, not to mention one of
the school's biggest fund-raisers, Brand does not want Knight's
blood on his hands. So he will wait for another body to be thrown
on the pile.
</P>
<P>
   Brand wants Knight to pull his own switch, and he knows it will
eventually happen. Bobby-baiting will become an unofficial sport
around the Big Ten. Will it be a goading fan at a road game who
causes the next explosion? Will a notoriety-hungry reporter
challenge Knight in front of the TV cameras and set him off? Or
will it be a Charlie Bauman, the Clemson football player who was
punched out by another self-destructive dictator/coach, Woody
Hayes, a generation ago?
</P>
<P>
   The bottom is still down there somewhere, waiting to happen.
</P>
<P>
   The blame will be Bob Knight's. The shame will be Indiana's.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
