<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 01:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7251 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s BC-BKC-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI &LR;      05-17 0922
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FELLOW HOTHEAD PINIELLA THINKS KNIGHT CAN CHILL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Now that Bobby Knight has promised not to add to his
considerable lead in the ``America's Funniest Tantrums'' video
archive _ the entirety has been broadcast on multiple channels this
week _ there is a chance for the runner-up to cut into the lead.
</P>
<P>
   But as far as Lou Piniella is concerned, no thanks.
</P>
<P>
   Portland Trail Blazers forward Rasheed Wallace, rising fast, is
welcome to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hardest thing a person has to control is his temper _
fought it all my life,'' Piniella said before Tuesday night's game.
``My temper is not planned; it just comes out. Bobby's had a
similar situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's wound a little different. It's just a question of
how you control yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   That, of course, has become the new national wager _ the date
when Knight loses whatever control he alleged himself to have.
</P>
<P>
   For all the deserved blistering that Indiana University honchoes
are taking for belatedly dealing with the longest-running pout in
non-diapered history, there was some shrewdness involved in the
sanctions of their basketball coach this week. What they lacked in
guts, they made up for in strategy.
</P>
<P>
   The trustees put Knight in a box so tight that he is virtually
doomed to fail. But by giving him a final chance, the onus for his
departure has shifted onto Knight.
</P>
<P>
   If he had been fired outright, the president and trustees would
have been held accountable for the basketball team's subsequent
mess. And given Knight's contentiousness, he probably would have
figured a way to sue.
</P>
<P>
   Almost certainly and most importantly, a firing would have
allowed Knight to hold himself as a martyr, felled by the
pointy-headed campus liberals who never wore a jock yet benefited
from the glory he brought the university.
</P>
<P>
   The legions of mouth-breathing Hoosiers fanatics who accorded
Knight unfettered loyalty would have stormed the red castle armed
with torches and pitchforks.
</P>
<P>
   The strategy's only vulnerability is if Knight develops a career
first: Civility.
</P>
<P>
   Piniella is among a teensy minority who thinks he can pull it
off.
</P>
<P>
   ``I gotta believe he'll do it,'' said Piniella. ``You have to
resolve to yourself that you have to change. You're the only one
who can do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he would have resigned. I read it as true
contrition, and you're going to see a change.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners manager became acquainted with Knight when Piniella
was running the Cincinnati Reds from 1990-92. A big baseball fan,
Knight made several trips to Riverfront Stadium, where the two were
friendly enough that Piniella had a standing offer to be Knight's
guest for any Hoosiers home game.
</P>
<P>
   Piniella described Knight the way almost everyone does who is
not in a chokehold or covered in his spittle: Friendly, bright,
well-read and passionate.
</P>
<P>
   But despite Piniella's own considerable history as a
player-throttling, cap-stomping, base-throwing desperado, he no
longer subscribes to Knight's apparent tactics of anger and
intimidation as a tool.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not anymore,'' said Piniella. ``When I played, yes. But I've
calmed down a lot. Early in my managing career, I was more
confrontational. Now, I'm not. I don't want confrontations. I don't
want problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``The game has changed at the high school, college and
professional level in how you relate to the players. If I meet with
a player, it's on an individual basis in the privacy of my office.
That's it.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to get players to play relaxed while installing a
winning attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though Piniella has entertained Mariners fans for years
with his near-smackdowns with umpires, he was much more fiery in
his earlier tenures with the Yankees and Reds.
</P>
<P>
   Most memorable was his post-game clubhouse brawl with Rob Dibble
after the Reds reliever called him a liar. That videotape gets
almost as much play as Knight's chair-hurling episode.
</P>
<P>
   But the fight marked a turning point.
</P>
<P>
   ``That started it,'' he said. ``It was embarrassing for me as a
manager. I said to myself, `You either start calming yourself down
or get yourself out of the business.'''
</P>
<P>
   Piniella credits his wife, Anita, for pulling his foot off the
accelerator.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing she suggested, which I've done for quite awhile now,
is if I'm upset about something, I don't address it right away,''
he said. ``Go home, sleep on it, think some more, have lunch over
it. It works very well.''
</P>
<P>
   After so many years in sports, the 56-year-old Piniella also has
learned something about self-control that has apparently escaped
Knight, 59.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least at the professional level, I think the most important
thing is that you can't want it more than your players want it,''
he said. ``Look, if your team is going out there and playing hard
for you and not beating itself with bonehead plays, that means your
level of play is consistent with the talent on hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't expect more, just because you want it more. You've
got to find that equilibrium. If you don't, it just puts more
pressure on your team.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a fine line.''
</P>
<P>
   The line is apparently so fine it has escaped Knight for most of
his life. Unless, of course, he never cared to search.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, that is, and will be, the difference in the tantrum
archive between No. 1 and No. 2.
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Art Thiel can be reached at 206-448-8135
</P>
<P>
   or artthiel &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
