u i BC-DOMINICAN-ELECTIONS-1     05-17 1198
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOMINICAN-ELECTIONS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN BOOM TIMES, THE HAVE-NOTS INFLUENCE THE DOMINICAN VOTE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Subs grafs 2, 4, 5 and 6 for updating with preliminary vote
figures) 
 By DAVID GONZALEZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTO DOMINGO, Dominican Republic _ Dominicans turned out in
large numbers Tuesday to elect a president _ either one who would
build on the current government's policy of economic liberalization
or one who wants to reconsider some of the changes to help the
millions of poor and rural residents who say the boom years have
overlooked them.
</P>
<P>
   While this Caribbean nation has enjoyed four years of robust and
unprecedented growth, dissatisfaction among the poor has been great
enough to drive the candidacy of Hipolito Mejia, of the
left-leaning Dominican Revolutionary Party. Mejia, an agronomist
and businessman who was a cabinet official in the 1970s, has
campaigned on a platform of increased social spending, assistance
to farmers and a reassessment of the current government's
privatization policies. Preliminary results based on 27.7 percent
of the polling places were giving him 49 percent of the vote early
Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   But the same sentiment has also propelled the unlikely candidacy
of former President Joaquin Balaguer, who is seeking his eighth
term in office. Balaguer, an autocrat who was close to the dictator
Rafael Trujillo, is 93 years old and blind. In his infrequent and
brief stump speeches, he has had to be helped to the podium by
aides.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, his Social Christian Reformist Party was garnering
26.7 percent of the vote. He has promised price controls and more
public housing and public works.
</P>
<P>
   The third main candidate, Danilo Medina, of the governing
centrist Dominican Liberation Party, known as the PLD, has vowed to
continue his party's economic policy but with an eye toward having
the benefits flow down to the neediest sectors of society.
Wednesday morning, he had 23.6 percent of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   If no candidate wins a majority, a runoff is scheduled for June
30. While some polling places experienced delays, the vote
proceeded without disruptions or conflict.
</P>
<P>
   The current president, Leonel Fernandez, a lawyer who was
educated in the United States, has been praised by international
groups for having enacted a series of economic changes that have
stimulated a growth rate of approximately 8 percent and have
attracted considerable investment here over the last four years.
</P>
<P>
   Fernandez, who is prohibited by law from a second consecutive
term, also focused on improving transportation and roads.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been a fairly progressive government by Dominican
standards,'' said one diplomat here. ``It has done more than most
governments in recent Dominican history.''
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of Medina, who was a top aide to Fernandez, said the
recent economic growth _ which last year made the Dominican
Republic's economy the fastest growing in Latin America _ should
continue under their party's supervision. They said that the
country's stable currency and finances would improve the country's
ability to invest in schools and health services.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want to work, you can work,'' said Idelfonso Cora, as
he waited to vote for Medina. ``I support Danilo because of the
growth under the PLD has been the best.''
</P>
<P>
   But the governing party's economic changes and capital projects
have not played as well among some poor and rural voters, who feel
the initiatives have done little to improve their circumstances.
There are continuing complaints about high food prices and a lack
of jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``People still have to get on boats and go to Puerto Rico
because there is not enough opportunity here,'' said Samuel
Collado, a security guard who was waiting to vote for Mejia. ``We
want a government that will help the poor, not just the rich.''
</P>
<P>
   He and others have especially been rankled by the government's
privatization of state run sugar and electrical production
industries. In the town of Guerra, about 15 miles outside of Santo
Domingo, voters said the privatization of the sugar company had a
devastating effect on their town, which used to thrive on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sugar cane?'' said Maria Altagracia Lebron. ``Don't even talk
about that. We used to live from that, but not anymore. There is no
cane or anything, because the government privatized it. And who
does that favor? The millionaires who have the money.''
</P>
<P>
   While Mejia said he would review the privatization policies, he
may have no choice but to continue, said one diplomat, because he
is also enough of a businessman to know that it was ultimately the
only choice the country had.
</P>
<P>
   In some respects, both he and Medina tout similar promises of
helping those who have been left out.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is about personality,'' said one diplomat. ``There is
also a more direct connection between the parties and the people.
The concept that one candidate might do good for the whole nation
is alien. It's what can you do for me?''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the master of that retail political strategy has been
Balaguer, who has honed it over decades, dispensing jobs, food and
favors _ as he does at Christmas, when crowds line up outside his
home to receive baskets of goodies. That generosity, combined with
his autocratic style, has always had its appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people who support him got things _ a job, a school or a
building,'' said one diplomat. ``I also think there is some sort of
nostalgia for the caudillo, the strong leader. They feel they want
a society where they do not have much chaos. If you see someone who
gives you order, you react to that.''
</P>
<P>
   The campaign season was relatively free of violence and was seen
by many as among the most tranquil in years. Nonetheless, there
were disquieting incidents of violence and angry accusations.
</P>
<P>
   In late April, two supporters of the governing party were shot
and killed by. Mejia's bodyguards during a campaign swing in the
town of Moca. Although the bodyguards said the two were suspected
of planning to attack Mejia, the police dismissed that motive.
Several suspects were arrested.
</P>
<P>
   Recalling the violence that wracked this nation during
Balaguer's rule, the family of a journalist who was killed by a
death squad linked to the military in 1975 tried to block
Balaguer's candidacy, accusing him of complicity. The Central
Electoral Council declined to pursue the case, saying there was not
enough evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Balaguer's supporters, in turn, accused the governing party of
plotting to assassinate Balaguer, saying that his age and frail
physical condition made him vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   Balaguer could still be in a position to exercise influence
should his party come in second. It is expected that Mejia could
face a challenge from a united front forged between his two
opponents. At the same time, Mejia's supporters say their
candidate's strength among the poor and rural voters has not been
reflected in the polls, and observers said that his party's
organizing capacity gave him a strong advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a good candidate,'' said Alfonso Bolque Brito, a street
vendor. ``He is the only one who can put food in the mouths of
those who are unhappy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
