<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 01:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7265 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-NETWORTH-PENDER-SFCHR     05-17 1223
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETWORTH-PENDER-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 BANK SALES REPS CAN PEEK INTO YOUR ACCOUNTS TO PITCH PRODUCTS  &HT;     By KATHLEEN PENDER 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ My friend Kay called last week with a story that
is becoming all-too-common now that the walls separating banks,
brokerage firms and insurance companies have collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   A few months ago, she was waiting in line at Wells Fargo's
Stonestown Galleria branch in San Francisco when a well-dressed,
elderly man hobbled in on the arm of his health care attendant and
settled himself into a seat at one of the desks on the sales floor.
</P>
<P>
   After making small talk with the Wells Fargo rep on the other
side of the desk, he asked, ``Can you tell me why you called me
down here regarding my account?''
</P>
<P>
   Because the man was hard of hearing, the rep talked loud enough
for everyone in the bank to hear.
</P>
<P>
   The rep said the man had $100,000 in his checking account, and
he wasn't earning any interest on it. The rep said he could be
earning money in another type of account. Then he scribbled down
some numbers on a piece of paper and showed it to the customer.
</P>
<P>
   The man said something like, ``I'm 84 years old. I've worked all
my life. I'm not interested in making any more money.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the rep continued asking the man questions about
his income, his mortgage and other personal information.
</P>
<P>
   Kay forgot about the incident until the week before last, when
she came home one night and found a cryptic message on her
answering machine. Someone at ``Wells Fargo'' wanted to talk about
``her account.''
</P>
<P>
   She had recently sold some mutual funds and had temporarily
parked $85,000 in her checking account. ``The money was in there
three or four days when I got the call,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Had she not remembered the episode at the bank, Kay says she
would have panicked, thinking that someone had gotten her ATM card
and cleaned out her checking account.
</P>
<P>
   When she returned the call the next day, she got a recording
from a woman with Wells Fargo's investment arm. Kay left her own
message, saying, ``If there is a problem with my checking account,
call me. If there's nothing wrong, don't call me.''
</P>
<P>
   Kay feels her privacy, and the man's, were invaded. ``If I get a
call from Merrill Lynch, I know they're there to sell me stuff. But
I feel old-fashioned about my bank.''
</P>
<P>
   She wonders: Can banks legally pry into your checking account to
sell you other products?
</P>
<P>
   The answer, Kay, is yes.
</P>
<P>
   What Wells is doing is known as affiliate sharing _ or using
customer information from one division (such as banking) to sell
products (such as mutual funds or insurance) from other divisions.
</P>
<P>
   Under new regulations that were just approved last week,
financial institutions can share customer information with their
affiliates, as long as they tell customers once a year they're
doing so.
</P>
<P>
   Since its merger with Norwest, Wells has become a leader in this
business of cross-selling.
</P>
<P>
   In its 1998 annual report, CEO Dick Kovacevich said that the
average Wells customer has only 3.2 Wells products. ``We want to
get to eight,'' he wrote. ``We expect to sell at least one more
product to every customer every year.''
</P>
<P>
   You can expect to see a lot more cross-selling now that banks,
insurance companies and securities firms are free to merge. They
gained that right under the Gramm-Leach-Bliley Act, passed last
year.
</P>
<P>
   As part of that act, consumer and privacy advocates wanted
strong protections on customer information.
</P>
<P>
   What they got were the watered-down regulations that were
finally issued last week, but still won't go into effect for eight
more months.
</P>
<P>
   You can read the 176-page directive at  &LR; www.bog.frb.fed.us &LR; 
 &LR; /BoardDocs/Meetings/2000 &LR;   &LR; /20000510/OpenMemos.htm. &LR;  Click on
``Proposed New Regulation P.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the new regs, financial institutions can share information
with their affiliates _ and with nonaffiliated third-party
companies _ as long as they notify customers when they open an
account and annually thereafter.
</P>
<P>
   Financial institutions must allow customers who don't want their
information sold to third parties to ``opt out.'' But they do not
have to let customers ``opt out'' of affiliate-sharing
arrangements.
</P>
<P>
   And there's another loophole: ``If there's a joint marketing
agreement between the bank and a third party, the customer doesn't
have to be provided with an opt-out,'' says Frank Torres,
legislative counsel with Consumers Union in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer groups failed in their attempts to get an ``opt-in''
policy that would have required financial institutions to get
permission from customers  &LR; before  &LR; sharing their financial secrets.
</P>
<P>
   So now, ``the burden is on you,'' says Ken McEldowney, executive
director of Consumer Action in San Francisco. ``I find this very
ironic. Banks say they want to share information to let you know
all about these wonderful services. But they don't have enough
faith in their products'' to rely on consumers opting in.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer advocates agree that Wells wasn't breaking any laws
when it peeked into customers' bank balances to try to sell them
other products.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell Chaney, a bank-stock analyst with Sutro &AMP; Co., even
thinks Wells may have been doing the older guy a favor _ depending
on what the rep was trying to sell him.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he has 100,000 in his checking account and he doesn't use
$100,000, then they are doing a service saying, ``Mr. Jones, you
don't need $100,000 in your checking account. We could sweep it
into a money market account and get 4 or 5 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Wells Fargo rep probably violated the older man's
privacy when he announced his bank balance for all to hear. And
consumer advocates think that sales reps should identify themselves
more clearly when they're making cold calls.
</P>
<P>
   ``We clearly abide by the law,'' says Craig Litsey, senior
counsel with Wells. ``There's a requirement that we identify the
caller and the business they're with. We may say Wells Fargo Bank
or Wells Fargo Securities. More often than not, it's (just) Wells
Fargo.''
</P>
<P>
   If a sales rep did shout out a customer's bank balance, ``it's
unfortunate and not typical of how we operate,'' Litsey says.
</P>
<P>
   Wells Fargo's privacy policy is posted on its Web site at
 &LR; www.wellsfargo.com/privacy &LR; . For more info, click on ``Use of
Information Provisions.''
</P>
<P>
   Now That's Rich
</P>
<P>
   Worth magazine came out with its annual survey of the nation's
250 richest towns this week. Bay Area 'burbs occupied four of the
Top 10 spots, but didn't rank No. 1 or 2. The richest communities
were Jupiter Island, Fla., where the median home price is $1.9
million, and Aspen, Colo., with a median home price of $1.75
million.
</P>
<P>
   Atherton, home of the $1.7 million house, ranked third. Others
in the Top 10 were Belvedere ($1.46 million), Hillsborough ($1.38
million) and Los Altos Hills ($1.33 million).
</P>
<P>
   The median home price for all 250 richest towns was $555,841 _
which  &LR; might &LR;  buy you a condo in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Free Trades
</P>
<P>
   Online broker Web Street Securities ( &LR; www.webstreet.com &LR; ) will
offer all customers unlimited commission-trades all day on Tuesday,
May 30. The offer applies to all market and limit orders, as long
as they're placed on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Kathleen Pender at  &LR; kpender(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
