<SLUG> BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 NOT MUCH HERE STAYS UNDER WRAPS  &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Oops, that Egyptian priestess mummy at the de
Young Museum wasn't a priestess after all, but a young man.
</P>
<P>
   That mummy ain't no mommy, but what's the surprise? As Japantown
Gerry points out, ``This  &UR; is  &LR; San Francisco.''
</P>
<P>
   Home of the cross-dressing mummy.
</P>
<P>
   World's first case of a person being outed by a CAT-scan.
</P>
<P>
   The mummy is so well-preserved that scientists suspect he may be
a patient of Dr. Seth Matarasso, San Francisco high-society's
plastic surgeon. Seth's motto (or it should be): ``Where the elite
meet to discreetly delete their crow's-feet.''
</P>
<P>
   The CAT-scan of the mummy also showed that the man's skull and
other bones had been fractured. Which leads scientists to theorize
that the mummy may have been an ancient San Francisco pedestrian.
</P>
<P>
   One theory is that he was trampled by a ferocious Munisaur.
</P>
<P>
   IN THE MOVIE ``The Mummy,'' scientists burn tania leaves to
bring the Egyptian mummy back to life. Alvin Guthertz wonders if
the de Young Museum folks gave that a try. Why rely on CAT-scan
clues when you can get the story from the mummy's mouth?
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, by law, tania smoke can be inhaled only for
medicinal purposes, and the mummy has no prescription.
</P>
<P>
   LET'S HEAR IT for Clint Reilly.
</P>
<P>
   To me, the guy was starting to look like a bulldog whose only
mission in life was to take a bite out of Willie's trousers.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the mayor was for, citizen Clint was against _ the
49ers' stadium-mall, Willie for re-election, the sale of The
Chronicle to the Hearsts and the Examiner to the Fangs.
</P>
<P>
   But as someone close to Reilly recently told me, ``Some people
only see Clint's anger. They don't realize that this guy is angry
for the right reasons. He doesn't like what he sees happening
behind the scenes.''
</P>
<P>
   It could be that Reilly, as his foes contended at the trial, is
miffed at being shut out of a sweet real-estate deal when his bid
for the Examiner was nixed.
</P>
<P>
   But Reilly's lawsuit and trial have given us an eye-opening
education into newspapers and politics and business in this cozy
little city.
</P>
<P>
   A LEAN NEWSPAPER, that's what would-be publisher Ted Fang
promises if he is allowed to ``buy'' the Examiner.
</P>
<P>
   But wouldn't a lean newspaper be a violation of the city's new
anti-fat-discrimination law? Would it deprive the portly &AMP; stout of
a voice?
</P>
<P>
   Incidentally, there is an angle Reilly and his attorney, Joseph
Alioto, missed. If the Fangs are saying to the Hearsts, ``Give us
$66 million and we'll take that newspaper off your hands,'' isn't
that a violation of the city's ban on aggressive panhandling?
</P>
<P>
   MAYOR BROWN, according to court testimony, called the Examiner
``a civic treasure.'' He has also said that the Ex isn't fit to be
used as toilet paper.
</P>
<P>
   Those sentiments seem somewhat conflicting. But the
contradiction helps explain how the same newspaper that doggedly
uncovers startling corruption in a mayor's administration can also
glowingly and unequivocally endorse that mayor for re-election.
</P>
<P>
   Only in S.F.: a cross-dressing newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   FRIENDLY SKIES, with an edge: United Airlines briefed travel
agents with the following memo (boldface mine):
</P>
<P>
   ``United is currently experiencing some flight cancellations due
to weather conditions and crew shortages. United and its pilots are
not in a labor dispute and pilots continue to fly their assigned
flights  &UR; (thank God!)  &LR; in a professional way  &UR; (whew, &LR; 
 &UR; no silly pranks!).  &LR; To manage the situation, United is fine-tuning
its schedule of 2,400 flights and canceling a small number of
flights up to a week in advance, then notifying customers so they
can make alternate plans.''
</P>
<P>
   Says travel agent Janice Hough: ``So all those cancellations are
not labor-related, they are simply `fine-tuning.' And by the way,
`up to a week in advance' includes less than an hour in advance.''
</P>
<P>
   BOBBY KNIGHT, say what you will about the guy, it was darn
decent of him to give Indiana University another chance.
</P>
<P>
   THE MAYOR'S quickness saved him a spill Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Bicycling to work with a group of folks, Willie sailed through
the intersection of Bush and Polk. Two of the riders farther back
in the pack weren't so lucky, they got Bushwacked, mowed down by a
motorcyclist who ignored a traffic cop's stop sign.
</P>
<P>
   Only in San Francisco: Ambulance to Work Day.
</P>
</TEXT>
