<SLUG> BC-CYBER-ECONOMY-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 U.S. ECONOMY SPINS AROUND HIGH TECH  &HT;     By DAVID LAZARUS 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Just as some might be tempted to start taking
the tech revolution for granted, along comes the American
Electronics Association with a report showing that, yup, high-tech
firms continue to pour cash and jobs into the U.S. economy.
</P>
<P>
   California, naturally, still leads the way in just about every
growth category _ except for highest wages paid. New Jersey, of all
places, has slipped past the Golden State with an average tech wage
of $68,700, compared with California's $66,900.
</P>
<P>
   William Archey, the association's president, conceded that
annual reports detailing the rise and rise of the U.S. tech
industry are probably becoming old hat.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we started issuing this report a few years ago, people
were like, `Wow!' '' he said. ``I told my staff that, sooner or
later, this wouldn't be a big deal. Perhaps that time is now.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps. Or not.
</P>
<P>
   ``Technology is still carrying the ball,'' said Gary
Schlossberg, an economist at Wells Capital Management in San
Francisco. ``This is clearly a tech-led expansion.''
</P>
<P>
   As such, he said it's hard to overstate the impact that
industries like semiconductors and communications equipment are
having on U.S. economic growth.
</P>
<P>
   Tech manufacturing and services accounted for 6.5 percent of
U.S. gross domestic product in 1998, compared with 5.6 percent in
1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``This may not be news to San Francisco,'' Archey said, ``but it
is news to about 45 other states.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the more noteworthy developments in the association's
latest report, titled ``Cyberstates 4.0,'' is that, for the first
time, all 50 states posted gains in high-tech jobs between 1997 and
1998.
</P>
<P>
   California, Texas, Virginia, Colorado and Georgia led the way in
creation of jobs.
</P>
<P>
   In California alone, a record 835,000 people were employed in
some facet of the tech industry as of 1998. Only education and
health care produced more jobs statewide.
</P>
<P>
   Fun fact: Seventy of every 1,000 workers in California's private
sector are employed by tech firms.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado has the highest density of tech workers (84 per 1,000),
followed by New Hampshire (83 per 1,000) and Massachusetts (79 per
1,000).
</P>
<P>
   California leads the way in high-tech exports ($53 billion),
venture capital ($17 billion) and total R&AMP;D expenditures ($42
billion).
</P>
<P>
   At $42 billion in R&AMP;D, the state accounts for a fifth of all
research and development spending nationwide, or nearly as much as
the next four states _ Michigan, New York, New Jersey and
Massachusetts _ combined.
</P>
<P>
   While California is tops in creation of high-tech jobs _ up 30
percent since 1993 _ tiny Delaware is setting the pace in
tech-export growth, climbing 134 percent from 1997 to 1999.
</P>
<P>
   California's tech exports grew just 4 percent in the same
period, but nevertheless account for almost a third of America's
total $181 billion in technology shipped abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Looking ahead, the association is projecting that total U.S.
tech employment will jump 45 percent from 5 million last year to
7.1 million by 2008.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are we cheerleading?'' Archey said. ``Damn right. I don't
apologize for it.''
</P>
<P>
   The association is the country's biggest tech industry group,
representing some 3,000 companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the end of the beginning, that's where we are,'' Archey
said. ``Technology has become part of the fabric of the community,
but it's still very new.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail David Lazarus at  &LR; davidlaz(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
