<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BARTER-ONLINE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 USE OF ONLINE BARTERING SHOWS GROWTH  &HT;     By CAROLYN SAID 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Finally, an Internet trend Fred Flintstone could
grok.
</P>
<P>
   Barter, which has been around since a hunter first traded a
woolly mammoth tusk for a flint ax, has moved online in a big way.
Its primary adherents are small businesses that benefit by getting
goods and services without having to lay out cash.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're starting out, cash flow is everything,'' said
Catherine Fischer, co-owner of the Parkway Theater, an Oakland,
Calif., movie house that serves up pizza, pasta and beer to its
audiences. ``By bartering, you can get goods and services you need
to get your business going without tying up your cash.''
</P>
<P>
   During the past two years, she estimates that she has bartered
for $10,000 to $15,000 of services _ plumbing repairs, bulk
mailing, pest control, even a $2,000 security system.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like having a credit card that you don't have to pay back
in cash,'' she said. ``You do pay it back, but it's by people using
your business as opposed to your sending in money.'' Fischer uses a
site called BarterTrust after starting with a service that was
acquired by BarterTrust.
</P>
<P>
   Plenty of other Web sites have sprung up recently to help small
businesses barter online, including BigVine, LassoBucks,
BarterItOnline and uBarter.
</P>
<P>
   They list a diverse range of professional services _ accounting,
consulting, legal, photography, training _ and some nuts and bolts
like car repair, office cleaning and printing. Travel and
entertainment items, such as restaurant meals, catering services,
airline tickets, hotel rooms and meeting rooms are also big, as is
advertising space. Products available for barter include fax
machines, credenzas and laptops.
</P>
<P>
   Even though most cultures adopted cash-based economies millennia
ago, barter never really went away. About $16 billion worth of
goods and services were bartered in 1999. Much of that happened
through small regional exchanges and informal community networking.
</P>
<P>
   What Internet barter sites bring to the party are a broader
reach, unconstrained by geography, and critical mass _ plus the
ability to add services such as escrow and financing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Scale matters, and the Internet provides scale,'' said Mike
Edelhart, chief executive of Internet Barter Inc., which runs
BarterTrust.
</P>
<P>
   But that means a barter system is only as good as the number of
listings it provides.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more people using a barter system, the more effective it
is,'' said Arthur Lazere, publisher and editor of arts-review Web
site culturevulture.net.
</P>
<P>
   Lazere, who uses BigVine, said he likes it as a way to generate
more resources for his small business. He offers ad space on his
Web site and has used his barter credit for Internet marketing
services. ``I'm a frugal person, so this appeals to me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Although he has been pleased with BigVine's customer service, so
far he has been able to use the system only for icing-on-the-cake
items. He would like it to add basic office supplies like printer
cartridges so he could rely on it to reduce some of his set
expenses.
</P>
<P>
   Online barter is rarely a straight tit-for-tat exchange. If a
dry cleaner needs someone to install Windows 2000, he might not
want to wait for a computer professional with rumpled clothes to
come along.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, each barter system uses its own in-house currency, a
kind of Monopoly money that works only within that system. Often,
users can prime the pump by putting an initial amount on a credit
card or a system's in-house credit.
</P>
<P>
   Barter clients post their wares at fair-market value _ the same
rates they would charge cash customers. When someone takes them up
on the offer, they get that dollar amount of credit on the system,
which they can redeem whenever they want.
</P>
<P>
   The barter exchange takes a cash cut of the transaction _
anywhere from 4 to 10 percent, split between the two parties.
</P>
<P>
   For tax purposes, barter accounting is straightforward. There's
even a line on tax forms for barter income. Businesses report
barter gains as if they had received that amount in cash, deducting
the commission as an expense.
</P>
<P>
   Besides conserving cash, online barter has another plus for
small businesses: It exposes them to a new world of potential
customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like BarterTrust is acting as an advertising or
promotional agent for us,'' said Larry Bearg, vice president of
Planet Organics, a San Francisco company that delivers organic
produce to Bay Area households.
</P>
<P>
   That's because his firm is listed on the site and comes up in
any searches its clients do for food-related products. BarterTrust
also is letting him enclose a brochure about Planet Organics in its
next mailing to customers _ at no charge. ``Those are customers I
wouldn't reach otherwise,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bearg estimates that he has done about $8,000 to $10,000 worth
of barter during the past five months. In exchange for produce
deliveries, he has received locksmith services, had signs painted
on Planet Organics' five vans, done photocopying, and placed ads in
the Bay Guardian and East Bay Monthly.
</P>
<P>
   Two Bay Area companies, Internet Barter Inc. of San Francisco
</P>
<P>
   and BigVine.com of Redwood Shores, Calif., are leaders in the
charge to online barter. Both have amassed large war chests (of
cash, not bartered services) and both have impressive blue-chip
backing.
</P>
<P>
   BigVine, which launched its site in late January, has $60
million in venture backing from American Express, the Starwood
Hotels chain, Kleiner Perkins Caufield &AMP; Byers and Kohlberg Kravis
Roberts &AMP; Co., among others.
</P>
<P>
   Its agreement with American Express lets it market directly to
the 2 million firms that hold small-business AmEx cards or that
accept the card.
</P>
<P>
   ``What eBay did for auctions, we're trying to do for barter,''
said BigVine chief executive Bippy Siegal.
</P>
<P>
   The company practices what it preaches. BigVine has bartered for
its water machine, food it provides to employees and construction
in its building, Siegal said.
</P>
<P>
   Internet Barter has $70 million in backing from investors
including General Motors and GE Capital Corp. The private company,
started last April, has grown rapidly by acquiring smaller regional
exchanges, including ones in Mexico and Canada, and putting them
online. In 1999 it facilitated $120 million worth of transactions;
its revenues totaled $10 million. The company is undergoing an
audit to determine its net profit or loss for 1999, and said it
expects to turn a profit in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Although 90 percent of BarterTrust users are small businesses,
several big corporations, such as Panasonic, TWA and Maytag, also
list their wares on the site, to the tune of about $1 million in
inventory each, Edelhart said. ``Big companies want one more way to
reach out to small businesses. No company ever has all the
distribution channels it needs,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Edelhart is in talks with both GM and GE about offering their
goods on the service. ``It's quite conceivable that a year from now
you could barter for a GM truck,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Sprenger's experience with barter goes back to his
childhood. His father owned Calistoga Mineral Waters in the 1970s.
``I remember him doing a lot of bartering for boxes and bottles,
all kinds of stuff,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   So it was a no-brainer for the Santa Rosa, Calif., golf pro to
try out BigVine. He's particularly happy that some people who
signed up for barter lessons turned into cash customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a free way to advertise to a broader market,'' Sprenger
said.
</P>
<P>
   When he needs plumbing or car repairs, he plans to look first on
the site. ``The whole idea of bartering is pretty great,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Carolyn Said at  &LR; csaid(AT)sfgate.com. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
