<SLUG> BC-HP-EARNINGS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 HP'S 2ND-QUARTER EARNINGS RISE A VIGOROUS 17%  &HT;     By HENRY NORR 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The evidence is mounting that Chief Executive
Officer Carly Fiorina's campaign to re-energize Hewlett-Packard is
paying off.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the Palo Alto, Calif., computing giant posted
results for its second fiscal quarter that far exceeded analysts'
estimates. The impressive report was the company's third straight,
following a year of uneven results.
</P>
<P>
   Excluding one-time charges and gains, earnings per share from
continuing operations in the quarter totaled 87 cents, compared
with 73 cents for the same period last year. The consensus estimate
among analysts surveyed by First Call/Thomson Financial was 82
cents.
</P>
<P>
   Including one-time items, such as an early retirement program
and costs associated with spinning off HP's former
test-and-measurement business into the soon to be independent
Agilent Technologies, earnings per share was 79 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Net earnings from continuing operations, again excluding
one-time items, were $899 million, up 17 percent from $766 million
in last year's second quarter. Net revenue from continuing
operations for the quarter, which ended April 30, was $12 billion,
up 15 percent from $10.5 billion a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Excluding the effect of currency fluctuations, revenue growth
was 17 percent. In the second quarter of last year, it was only 4
percent.
</P>
<P>
   The ``continuing operations'' qualification excludes results
from Agilent. The spin-off of that company will be completed June
2, when HP investors will receive the 84.1 percent of Agilent
shares the parent company still owns.
</P>
<P>
   HP's growth was especially strong in its computing systems
business, which includes everything from high-end servers to
low-cost consumer PCs. Overall, revenues in that category were up
19 percent, compared with no growth in the same quarter a year ago.
Home PC revenues were up 85 percent, on an increase in unit
shipments of 105 percent, according to the company.
</P>
<P>
   In the notebook PC arena, where HP in the past has lagged behind
its competitors, revenues and unit shipments were up 180 percent
and 248 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Revenues from Unix servers _ a segment Fiorina identified as a
major problem area for HP last fall, shortly after she took over
the company in July _ were up 26 percent over last year.
</P>
<P>
   In a conference call with analysts, she emphasized that the
company's restructured and reinvigorated server sales force _
``unlike some competitors'' _ is not signing unprofitable deals or
trading hardware for future service revenues.
</P>
<P>
   HP also reported solid growth in its printing and imaging
business, which includes printers, scanners and supplies. Personal
printers and scanners, plus supplies, showed the largest increases.
In the office arena, company officials said, demand for color
printers is growing strongly, but there is a continuing shift away
from personal monochrome laser printers.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, Agilent reported net income of $166 million (36
cents a share) compared with $157 million (41 cents) in the same
quarter last year. Excluding a gain of 4 cents per share on
investments, Agilent said, earnings were 32 cents a share, matching
the First Call consensus.
</P>
<P>
   Revenue for the quarter was up 24 percent, to $2.49 billion.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Henry Norr at  &LR; hnorr(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
