<SLUG> BC-GAS-PRICES-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 LOWER PRICES FOR GAS NOT EXPECTED TO LAST  &HT;     By VERNE KOPYTOFF 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Gas prices in the Bay Area have dropped 8 cents
a gallon over the past four weeks, reaching their lowest level in
more than two months, according to a survey released Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   However, the California Automobile Association survey also said
that consumer savings will only be temporary because prices are
expected to rise again during the summer driving season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the biggest drop that we've seen in quite a while,'' said
Paul Moreno, a spokesman for the automobile association. ``But
unfortunately, it's not going to last.''
</P>
<P>
   The average price for a gallon of self-serve unleaded gas in the
Bay Area now stands at $1.78, down from $1.86 last month. In San
Francisco, the price of a gallon of self-serve unleaded gas is
$1.86, down from $1.92.
</P>
<P>
   Moreno said that gas prices declined because of an increase in
crude oil production by OPEC countries and healthy gas production
by California refineries.
</P>
<P>
   However, he said that crude oil prices have been on the rise
recently, which should make gas more expensive as drivers take to
the road in what is expected to be a busy summer vacation season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It should be a matter of one or two weeks before gas costs
more,'' Moreno said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the current decline in gas costs, prices are still a lot
more expensive than in January, when a gallon of self-serve
unleaded gas averaged $1.46 in the Bay Area.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Verne Kopytoff at  &LR; verne(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-17-00 0136EDT &QL; 
