<HEADLINE>
PRISON SYSTEM FOR YOUTH BLASTED BY WITNESSES
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By GREG LUCAS 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  SACRAMENTO _ A former California Youth Authority ward, a former
department employee and Davis administration officials told a
Senate committee Tuesday that the troubled agency is failing its
mission to rehabilitate youthful offenders.
<P>
   Witnesses recounted a litany of horrors from assaults, rapes and
drug use among wards to sexual and physical abuse of wards by
guards.
</P>
<P>
   ``You prepare yourself for what I consider battle. You have to
fight. You must survive. I did so,'' Armando Lopez, who served
seven years in the CYA for second-degree murder, told the Senate
Public Safety Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's hearing was the first comprehensive look lawmakers
have taken of the 7,300-ward prison system for young offenders in
the wake of recent accounts of inmate abuse, biomedical experiments
on wards and the resignation of the agency's director last December
after only 10 months on the job.
</P>
<P>
   Some witnesses cited deep budget cuts in the early 1990s for
sharply increasing the ratio of counselors and parole officers to
wards, reducing treatment of mentally ill wards and increasing
stress-repated workers compensation costs.
</P>
<P>
   Steve White, the Davis administration inspector general for
prisons and the CYA, said lack of money was part of the problem, as
was an ``implosion of spirit'' in the agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``We learned the system is totally out of whack,'' said Sen.
John Vasconcellos, chair of the committee.
</P>
<P>
   Lopez, who now works at a Southern California CYA parole office,
painted a harrowing picture of incarceration where 90 percent of
violence occurs without knowledge of guards, where gang members are
pitted against each other, where ``hovering'' over a youth
authority official can lead to months of incarceration with just
one hour a day outside of a cell.
</P>
<P>
   Although Lopez, 23, praised some of the programs designed to
help wards return to society, he said some of the staff ``did not
have the skills'' and, often with the threat of rival gang members
in the same class, ``you're not thinking about studying.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked by Sen, Richard Polanco, D-Los Angeles, if drugs are
prevalent, Lopez said:
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely. Every type of drug you can think of is in there.
Methamphetamines. Marijuana. Everything is accessible.''
</P>
<P>
   Then Polanco asked about the incidence of male rapes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I witnessed two rapes and another I heard of,'' Lopez said.
``I only seen one person defend himself from an attempted attack.''
</P>
<P>
   Marcus Midyett, an Oakland police officer, whose son is a CYA
ward, echoed some of Lopez's testimony.
</P>
<P>
   His son, Sean, entered the CYA at 17 for an assault with a
deadly weapon. Since then, Midyett said, his son's sentence has
been lengthened by 18 months for testing positive for cocaine,
tattooing himself, not working and fighting a member of a rival
gang.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sean feels safer in lockdown and that's sad,'' Midyett said.
``If what is described is rehabilitation, what is punishment?''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Presley, Davis' cabinet secretary for youth and adult
prisons, acknowledged there have been problems at the authority,
but said the Davis administration was taking steps to correct them.
</P>
<P>
   He said biomedical research on wards had been ended. He also
said he began a series of audits by the Board of Corrections of
several CYA facilities to assess their operation and treatment of
wards.
</P>
<P>
   Vasconcellos praised the new director of the agency, Jerry
Harper, former undersheriff for Los Angeles County, for a
willingness to focus more energy on the department's goal of
rehabilitation.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Gray Davis appointed Harper to the job in March, nearly
four months after Davis' first choice for CYA head resigned amid
revelations of ward abuse by guards.
</P>
<P>
   Vasconcellos said he and Polanco were working on a plan to pour
more money into the department to add counselors, improve medical
care and increase employee training.
</P>
</TEXT>
