<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GROW-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 GROW A BUSINESS: CHAMBER CELEBRATES 150TH YEAR  &HT;     By PETER SINTON 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Wednesday night, the San Francisco Chamber of
Commerce hosts its 150th anniversary gala at the Festival Pavilion
at Fort Mason. For the $200 price tag, guests will be treated to
the city's culinary treats and a specially written ``From Gold Rush
to Cyberspace!'' performance by Steve Silver's Beach Blanket
Babylon.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco Mayor Willie Brown and Gov. Gray Davis' wife,
Sharon, are scheduled to attend and should like this twist on
``California Dreaming'' by the Mamas and the Papas: ``All the
mayors are Brown and the governor's Gray.'' (The other Brown is
Oakland Mayor Jerry Brown.)
</P>
<P>
   Also likely to draw laughs are these revised lyrics for Peggy
Lee's ``Fever'': ``The worldwide Web is taking over, cyber cafes
everywhere. Yahoo taxis all around me, I like a man who's wealthy
and square. Got dot-com fever.''
</P>
<P>
   The chamber was formed by 19 San Franciscans in May 1850 to
arbitrate business disputes. Its first case in 1851 had little to
do with local issues. It involved four jugs of linseed oil broken
on a voyage from London. Now the chamber has 2,200 members and more
than 250 programs and events. The organization focuses on such
public policy issues as the business climate, affordable housing,
public education, transportation and parking.
</P>
<P>
   Silicon Valley Fun Raiser
</P>
<P>
   An even more select, invitation-only party and charity auction
will be held this Friday evening at the Atherton, Calif., home of
Ron Conway, founder of Angel Investors, which has invested more
than $160 million in more than 100 local startups since the
mid-1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Warren Buffett will give a brief pep talk on the virtues of
financing worthwhile causes. Then Conway hopes to raise $1 million
or more for local charities by auctioning off such things as a golf
game with Tiger Woods, tennis match with Pete Sampras and Arnold
Schwarzenegger's Humvee. Dana Carvey will act as emcee.
</P>
<P>
   IPO Pullback
</P>
<P>
   There are signs everywhere that the IPO frenzy is fading. Just
look at this week's anemic IPO calendar of local activity.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Case, CEO of Chase H&AMP;Q, also sees a major change in how new
stocks are priced since the Nasdaq minicrash last month. He notes
that in the first quarter, only 2 percent of companies that went
public sold their shares below the pricing range that they filed
with the Securities and Exchange Commission. By contrast, over the
past 30 days, three-quarters of companies priced their stock below
their planned range.
</P>
<P>
   ``IPO pricing tends to adjust near instantaneously to market
conditions,'' Case says. Nevertheless, he adds that the market
correction was ``much needed and healthy'' and predicts IPO
activity this summer will be ``robust'' even if it doesn't set new
records. What is likely is that more startups will turn to debt
financing or find a wealthy merger partner.
</P>
<P>
   That's what Hambrecht &AMP; Quist did last year. The San Francisco
investment bank was acquired by New York's Chase Manhattan Corp.,
whose top executives held their annual meeting in San Francisco on
Tuesday to present their case to West Coast digerati. A handful of
execs flew in on Chase's Gulfstream, including Chase CEO Bill
Harrison and Jimmy Lee, the head of global investment banking whom
Michael Douglas styled his slick Gordon Gecko character on in the
movie ``Wall Street.``
</P>
<P>
   Startupfailures.com
</P>
<P>
   If you are getting nauseated by all the VC success stories and
tales of dot-com millionaires, you might want to visit a new Web
site called Startupfailures.com. It was launched this month by Nick
Hall, who previously started two companies that failed and worked
for a third.
</P>
<P>
   Hall dubs the site ``the place for bouncing back'' and offers
discussion boards, ``Ask a coach'' services, failure feedback, job
listings and other resources for those who have hit a ditch.
</P>
<P>
   He offers soothing statistics such as only 6 of every 1,000
business plans win venture funding and 60 percent of companies that
do receive financing go bankrupt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our purpose,'' states Hall, ``is to take the stigma out of
failing and help entrepreneurs recover quickly from the failure and
get back in action.''
</P>
<P>
   In little more than a week, Hall's site has attracted about
40,000 visitors, and he is talking with potential sponsors.
However, he is unsure if or how Startupfailures.com might move from
philanthropic community service to profitable enterprise.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, Hall has an angel investor. His wife, a sales
manager for Playtex Products, helps support his ventures. In
addition to Startupfailures.com, Hall is president of the Silicon
Valley Association of Software Engineers, currently a nonpaying
position. He is also author of ``The Future Scrapbook: Having the
Design of Your Life.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Peter Sinton at  &LR; entrepreneurs(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
