<SLUG> BC-B2BPORTALS-SMALLBIZ-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 THE BEST WEB PORTALS FOR ENTREPRENEURS  &HT;     By PETER SINTON 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Small business portals say they can help
entrepreneurs set up a Web site with ease, save money ordering
goods and services online, and simplify their management chores.
But as many small businesses have discovered, it's often not as
easy as it sounds.
</P>
<P>
   The advice is often simplistic. One-size-fits-all services have
their limits. Most portals refer customers only to ``preferred''
partners with whom they have a self-serving business relationship.
And many sites charge fees and don't necessarily save users time or
money.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, numerous Web sites are worthwhile. In its May 1
issue, Fortune Magazine ( &LR; www.fortune.com &LR; ) provides an A to Z list
of winning features of some of the best portals for small
businesses. Here is a brief summary:
</P>
<P>
   -- ABC Business _ Originally Go.com's small-business portal and
now part of ABCNews.com, this site offers a useful weekly ``Small
Business Builder'' column and some personal financial calculator
tools.
</P>
<P>
   -- AllBusiness.com _ It offers plenty of details on running a
business, including more than 300 ready-to-download forms, from
licensing agreements to venture capital term sheets. It also
provides answers to frequently asked questions and concise but
basic how-to guides as well as services from more than 40 partners.
</P>
<P>
   -- BCentral.com _ Microsoft's small-business portal lets users
submit their Web sites to search engines, check how many visitors
they receive on them and create customer mailing lists. It also
offers a free banner-ad exchange program and a variety of paid
services.
</P>
<P>
   -- Business Owner's Toolkit _ The site's SOHO (small office/home
office) guidebook offers how-to information on marketing, taxes,
incorporation, financing and employees that is of special interest
to fledgling small-business owners. It offers some business forms
but only scant advice on moving your business online.
( &LR; www.toolkit.cch.com &LR; )
</P>
<P>
   -- DigitalWork.com _ Various Web sites license its services,
which focus on offline business needs such as press releases,
direct-mail campaigns and recruiting. It offers a list of preferred
providers, but usually only one per category.
</P>
<P>
   -- Freeworks.com _ Although there's little content, it is a
novel and free way to process expense reports, travel requests and
purchase orders throughout a company.
</P>
<P>
   -- Inc.com _ Affiliated with Inc. magazine, the site has good
material but it's not always easy to find it. There are useful free
tools for finding health insurance and calculating your company's
fiscal health. In addition, there are fee services for tasks such
as processing payroll.
</P>
<P>
   -- Office.com _ It covers more industries from architecture to
solid-waste collection than other sites and offers specific news as
well as general advice. Business services are available from
preferred vendors and Winstar, its parent company.
</P>
<P>
   -- Onvia.com _ This site's useful request-for-quote service
covers dozens of categories, including health insurance, business
loans, Web design and even tax-law advice. Instead of providing a
link to a preferred vendor, it passes requests to a network of
providers who then submit quotes. Downside: Users must fill out a
new form for each service, and without reviews or user feedback,
it's not easy to gauge the quality of a vendor.
</P>
<P>
   -- Quicken.com _ It provides good general business information
and easy access to credit-card rates, tax information and forms,
payroll and other services. Although it provides links to other
sites, it has few business tools to run an online business.
</P>
<P>
   -- Smalloffice.com _ This site is not easy to navigate but
offers plenty of advice on how to start and run an online business,
such as building customer support into your Web site and tools to
help find a local Web designer or HR firm. Users can post questions
to online advisers.
</P>
<P>
   -- SmartAge.com _ Site offers tools, some free, to help run a
site, such as checking your server's performance and tracking your
popularity on search sites. Some tools and templates are basic.
</P>
<P>
   -- SmartOnline.com _ Site offers a few interactive features for
businesses that are just getting off the ground, such as the $15
Smart Incorporator quiz to help a user choose the best way to
organize and generate the required paperwork. Some of the 1,800
legal forms and 500 business letters are free.
</P>
<P>
   -- Workz.com _ Site offers most everything one needs to know
about running an online business, from creating banner ads to
accepting credit cards to comparing vendors. For example, it
compares prices for site-submission services and dozens of merchant
account providers. Workz also offers free tools such as checking a
site for dead links and other problems.
</P>
<P>
   -- Yahoo.com _ Although the site touts Yahoo's own Web services,
a user will find useful resources when searching for a topic like
e-commerce, finance and human resources.
</P>
<P>
   -- ZDNet.com _ The site of Ziff-Davis, publisher of PC
publications, offers sophisticated tutorials on e-commerce, Web
design, intellectual property and other issues.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
