<SLUG> BC-LYCOS-MERGER-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 WEB PORTAL LYCOS WILL BE BOUGHT FOR $12.5 BILLION  &HT;     By VERNE KOPYTOFF 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Terra Networks, the Internet arm of Spanish
telecommunications firm Telefonica, said Tuesday that it will buy
Lycos, the Web portal, in a $12.5 billion deal aimed at creating a
global technology giant to rival America Online.
</P>
<P>
   The new company, called Terra Lycos, will have its hand in the
Internet, wireless communications and television. It will also be
an international force, with operations in 37 countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``This shows that the Internet is going global,'' said Rob
Enderle, a technology industry analyst with Giga Information Group,
a market research company. ``Clearly, a lot of the growth on the
Internet is going to be international, and this will put the new
company in a good position for that.''
</P>
<P>
   Terra Lycos, to be based in Madrid, will be the world's
third-largest Internet company in terms of revenue after America
Online and Yahoo. The combined companies expect to take in $500
million this year.
</P>
<P>
   Terra Networks, with 2 million Internet subscribers, has Web
sites throughout the Spanish- and Portuguese-speaking world. Lycos,
of Waltham, Mass., has the fourth most-popular Web property in the
United States and a strong field of Internet sites in Asia, Latin
America and Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Whit Andrews, an analyst with the Gartner Group, a market
research company, said that the deal links Terra Networks to a
wealth of online commerce and content for its Web sites. He added
that buying Lycos gives Terra Networks a portal for its wireless
Internet devices.
</P>
<P>
   But Andrews questioned whether Terra Networks had to buy Lycos.
He said that Terra may have been able to partner with Lycos for
much less.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not clear to me that the two companies need to own each
other to have their promise fulfilled,'' Andrews said. ``The notion
that a company with the breadth and depth of experience of Lycos
will mainly serve to create a front end for Terra is absurd.''
</P>
<P>
   The merger comes a year and a half after Lycos considered being
acquired by USA Networks, the cable television firm led by Barry
Diller. That deal fell through because of shareholder skepticism.
</P>
<P>
   The Terra-Lycos merger also follows a series of other big
acquisitions in the Internet industry. In January, America Online
announced a deal to buy media giant Time Warner, while Disney
bought Web portal Infoseek in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Juan Villalonga, the Terra Networks and Telefonica chairman who
will lead Terra Lycos, said that the deal gives his company a big
advantage over its competitors because of its geographic reach and
access to broadband, wireless and satellite technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``From today, AOL has a competitor,'' Villalonga declared.
</P>
<P>
   Also announced Tuesday was a marketing agreement between Terra
Lycos and Bertelsmann, the German media conglomerate. Bertelsmann,
already a partner with Lycos Europe, will pay $1 billion for a
five-year deal to offer its books, films and music on the Terra
Lycos Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   The deal between Lycos and Terra Networks must still pass
regulatory hurdles and be approved by shareholders. The companies
said that the agreement will probably be finalized this summer.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement calls for Terra Networks to pay $97.55 in its own
stock for each Lycos share. That is nearly double the price of
Lycos stock on May 10.
</P>
<P>
   Lycos will continue to be operated out of its headquarters in
Massachusetts. No layoffs are expected. Bob Davis, Lycos president
and chief executive, will be chief executive of Terra Lycos.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Verne Kopytoff at  &LR; verne(AT)sfgate.com. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
