<SLUG> BC-QUACKENBUSH-HOLOCAUST-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 HOLOCAUST CLAIMS LAW SITTING UNENFORCED, ASSEMBLYMAN SAYS  &HT;     By LYNDA GLEDHILL 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO _ The author of California's law requiring insurers
to settle the claims of Holocaust victims is accusing Insurance
Commissioner Chuck Quackenbush of not enforcing it.
</P>
<P>
   Assemblyman Wally Knox, D-Los Angeles, has asked Attorney
General Bill Lockyer to investigate why no insurance companies have
had their licenses revoked as allowed by a law Knox authored.
</P>
<P>
   Quackenbush has been under fire for pushing earthquake insurers
to contribute to a nonprofit foundation he established in lieu of
their paying large fines. Two legislative inquiries are proceeding,
and Lockyer has gone to court to stop the foundation from spending
any more money.
</P>
<P>
   Knox said revocations should have been started May 7, but he has
had no word from Quackenbush's office as to why no action has been
taken.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have absolutely no confidence that further reasons wouldn't
be found for further delays,'' Knox said. ``It was time to involve
the chief law enforcement officer of the state.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for Lockyer said his office has received Knox's
request and is reviewing the matter.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of Knox's bill, all insurance companies that
conduct business in the state were required to produce a list of
Holocaust-era policies. The goal was to allow survivors or their
beneficiaries to determine if they are owed money. Knox said any
company that did not provide the information should have had their
license to do business in the state revoked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Companies that fail to fully and timely disclose their claims
can have their licenses lifted,'' he said. ``The thing the
insurance company is supposed to do is pay claims to people. The
failure to pay claims is a reason to deny doing business.''
</P>
<P>
   But several insurance companies have filed lawsuits challenging
the constitutionality of the laws. Quackenbush's office said a
delay in regulatory action against the companies was part of the
response to the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We filed very aggressive opposition _ a 133-page brief and 800
pages of evidence _ to the lawsuits,'' Quackenbush said in a
prepared  &LR; statement. He said his office decided to ``defer
initiating regulatory action until after the court ruled.''
</P>
<P>
   ``To permit adequate opportunity to take discovery and prepare
that extensive opposition to the insurance companies' motions, we
agreed in court-filed documents to defer initiating regulatory
action until after the court ruled.''
</P>
<P>
   But Knox said the court should have been the one to stop any
action mandated by the law.
</P>
<P>
   ``The act does not authorize that kind of deal,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Quackenbush has been under fire for allowing insurance companies
to duck up to $3 million in fines by contributing to a nonprofit
foundation.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation was supposed to pay for earthquake research and
consumer aid, but Quackenbush acknowledged at an Assembly hearing
last week that no money has yet  &LR; gone to earthquake victims as yet.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, money has been paid to some of Quackenbush's political
operatives; a $500,000 contribution was given to the Greater
Sacramento Urban League; $12,000 went to the National Latino Peace
Officers Association; and $200,000 benefited the 100 Black Men
program.
</P>
<P>
   Quackenbush also wanted to create a foundation with $4.2 million
that three Dutch insurance firms gave that is intended for poor
Holocaust survivors. Knox has requested Lockyer to determine
whether the Dutch firms donated this money in lieu of fines, as
they did with the Northridge foundation.
</P>
<P>
   In his statement, Quackenbush said none of the money has been
spent, and that the foundation idea has been scrapped because of
the problems with the earthquake foundation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will present to the Legislature next week a proposal to set
up an appropriate vehicle to implement the distribution of these
monies to California survivors,'' he said.  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
