 CALPERS HEALTH INSURANCE COSTS MAY RISE  &HT;     By CAROL EMERT 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The 1 million members of the California Public
Employees Retirement System are likely to see significant increases
in their health insurance premiums and drug co-payments next year.
</P>
<P>
   CalPERS' health benefits committee yesterday approved a hotly
debated compromise plan that would raise premiums an average of 7.3
percent in 2001 and double co-payments to $10 from $5 in certain
cases. The CalPERS board will vote on the plan Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   If co-payments are left unchanged, premiums would have to
increase 9.2 percent to offset rising health care costs, said
CalPERS spokeswoman Pat Macht.
</P>
<P>
   CalPERS is the nation's largest public pension fund and
represents current and retired state and local government
employees.
</P>
<P>
   Unions representing state workers want the state to absorb the
looming increases, using the current budget surplus.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday's plan modified another co-payment increase
recommended by the health benefits committee staff in April.
</P>
<P>
   Under the new plan, co-payments made for doctor's office visits
would remain $5. Increases will be used to encourage members to buy
generic drugs and to order drugs through the mail.
</P>
<P>
   A $10 co-payment would be charged when brand-name drugs are used
to treat short-term illnesses in cases where cheaper generics are
available.
</P>
<P>
   The $10 rate would also be charged for refills of
``maintenance'' drugs for long-term conditions when the drugs are
bought at a pharmacy. Pharmacies typically fill a maximum of 30
days' worth of medicine. When ordering prescriptions through the
mail, CalPERS members would be assessed a $10 co-pay for a 90-day
supply.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Carol Emert at  &LR; cemert(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
