<SLUG> BC-FED-RATES-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 STOCKS CLIMB DESPITE ATTEMPT TO COOL ECONOMY  &HT;     By DAVID LAZARUS 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Trying yet again to pour cold water on the
red-hot U.S. economy, the Federal Reserve raised short-term
interest rates to a nine-year high Tuesday and signaled loud and
clear that further increases may be in the works.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Wall Street shrugged off the widely expected Fed
action as investors unleashed money they had kept aside while
waiting for the central bank's decision.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones Industrial Average climbed 126.79 points to close
at 10,934.57, while the tech-heavy Nasdaq composite index rose
109.92 points to 3,717.57. The broader Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 Index
gained 13.68 points to 1,466.04.
</P>
<P>
   The market's resilience reflects the persistent ``irrational
exuberance'' that Fed chief Alan Greenspan has been trying to curb
for years as well as attempts by Fed officials in recent weeks to
soften the blow of an aggressive rate increase.
</P>
<P>
   The central bank's target for the influential federal funds rate
_ the level that it expects banks to charge one another for
overnight loans _ was lifted half a point to 6.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed also raised the discount rate for its direct loans to
financial institutions to 6 percent. These are the highest such
levels since 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Steepest Increase in 5 Years
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's increases were the first time in five years that the
Fed boosted its benchmark rates by more than a quarter of a point
and the sixth time in 11 months that Greenspan and company have
moved to reduce inflation risk by trying to put the brakes on
economic growth.
</P>
<P>
   The economy has expanded by more than 5 percent in each of the
last three quarters _ the first time this has happened in 17 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past, a half-percentage-point increase would have
caused the market to plunge,'' said Allan Roness, research director
at JW Genesis Securities in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``But people saw this coming,'' he said. ``And where else are
you going to put your money _ in your shoe?''
</P>
<P>
   Investors Not Intimidated
</P>
<P>
   Bill Meehan, chief market analyst at Cantor Fitzgerald in New
York, said Wall Street's ho-hum response to the rate increase
suggests that investors are growing bolder in the face of continued
monetary tightening from the Fed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Fed is more afraid of the market than the market is of the
Fed,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Meehan said investors' take-it-on-the-chin
attitude now may serve to embolden the Fed to raise rates even
higher.
</P>
<P>
   ``This action indicates that the Fed can be much more aggressive
without panicking the market,'' he observed.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed clearly suggested that more interest rate increases are
on the horizon. It said in a statement that economic risks ``remain
weighted toward conditions that may generate heightened inflation
pressures.''
</P>
<P>
   The Fed also noted it is concerned that the ``disparity in the
growth of demand and potential supply will continue, which could
foster inflationary imbalances that would undermine the economy's
outstanding performance.''
</P>
<P>
   A June Raise Possible
</P>
<P>
   The next meeting of the Fed's policy-making committee is set for
June 28. Analysts say a quarter-point increase is possible then or
shortly thereafter if the economy keeps blazing ahead.
</P>
<P>
   While rate increases are generally bad for the stock market
because they raise the cost of corporate borrowing and cut into
profits, traders received Tuesday's action more with relief than as
a sign of impending catastrophe.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have been waiting for this since the first quarter,''
said Arthur Hogan, chief market analyst at Jefferies &AMP; Co. in
Boston. ``There's been a whole lot of cash waiting to get back in
the market.''
</P>
<P>
   Investors may be unfazed by higher rates, but the impact of the
Fed's move certainly will be felt by consumers forced to pay more
for car loans, mortgages and home equity loans.
</P>
<P>
   Bank of America Corp., Wells Fargo &AMP; Co. and other lenders
immediately responded to the Fed's action by raising their prime
lending rates half a point to 9.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Credit Card Peril
</P>
<P>
   Cantor Fitzgerald's Meehan said the ones who really will feel
the pinch will be consumers who have run up enormous piles of debt
on their credit cards. ``These people will get hurt,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, however, this is precisely the effect intended by
the Fed. By slowing consumer spending, or even making it downright
painful, the central bank intends to drive a stake through the
heart of inflation.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Labor Department reported Tuesday that the April
consumer price index was unchanged from a month before, but rose
0.2 percent when food and energy were excluded.
</P>
<P>
   While this is less than the 0.4 percent increase posted in
March, the overall consumer price index is expected to increase by
4.3 percent for the entire year _ the largest gain in a decade.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Schlossberg, an economist at Wells Capital Management in
San Francisco, predicted that ``there are still several more
tightenings in the pipeline'' and that the Fed could act again as
early as next month.
</P>
<P>
   Delayed Impact
</P>
<P>
   But Jefferies' Hogan said Greenspan may sit back and watch
awhile before making another move. He pointed out that it can take
weeks or months before the full economic impact of a rate increase
becomes visible.
</P>
<P>
   ``Moving forward, we're going to have a nice summer rally in the
stock market,'' Hogan said. ``Earnings have been good and inflation
remains low.''
</P>
<P>
   Bolstering this view is the fact that retail sales fell last
month for the first time in a year and a half.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, the Commerce Department said Tuesday that
construction starts on new houses and apartments jumped 2.8 percent
last month _ even though the average interest rate for a 30-year
fixed-rate mortgage has topped 8 percent, compared with about 7
percent a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, unemployment hit a three-decade low of 3.9 percent
last month, raising the possibility that increased labor costs for
employers will be passed along to consumers in the form of higher
prices.
</P>
<P>
   Volatility Predicted
</P>
<P>
   With further interest rate increases looming, JW Genesis' Roness
said investors can expect share prices to become even more
volatile. ``You're going to have to pick stocks more carefully,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   But other analysts noted that Wall Street has lost ground since
the beginning of the year. They believe this could help deter the
Fed from pushing rates much higher.
</P>
<P>
   Since January 1, the Dow has dropped about 5 percent and the
Nasdaq nearly 9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the platform that we start trading higher from,''
Jefferies' Hogan said.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail David Lazarus at  &LR; davidlaz(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
