<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOMS'-NEW-WEAPON-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOMS' ANTI-GUN MARCH MAY TRIGGER POLITICAL CHANGE  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (NOTE: NRA Convention, FRIDAY, MAY 19, N.C.)   (This 750-word ``separate-buy'' article is from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By MARY DEJEVSKY  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Politicians of both main parties were confronting
the possibility of a signal change in the American political
landscape Monday, after the massive turnout at Sunday's ``Million
Mom March'' in favor of tougher gun laws.
</P>
<P>
   Even the fiercest opponents of the gun control cause conceded
that the predominantly suburban crowd on Washington's National Mall
probably exceeded half a million, while the amazed and delighted
organizers claimed a crowd approaching 750,000.
</P>
<P>
   Parallel demonstrations by gun advocates, not just in
Washington, but across the United States attracted far fewer
people.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to the success of Sunday's march, Wayne LaPierre of
the hugely influential National Rifle Association (NRA) came out
with a fighting call to arms.
</P>
<P>
   Gun registration and licensing, he said _ referring to the
measures demanded by the marchers _ would be tantamount to ``a
controlled burn of the Second Amendment... and setting fire to
freedom should never be the answer.''
</P>
<P>
   The NRA, which has 3.5 million members across the U.S., and
which makes large contributions to the campaign funds of many
Republican congressmen, is expected to make a fuller response
during its national convention which opens in North Carolina on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Donna Dees-Thomases, the public relations executive turned
housewife behind the Million Mom March brainchild, urged the
marchers to continue their involvement with the gun control
movement by supporting existing lobby groups and forming, or
joining, new Million Mom March action committees to lobby
state-level and national legislators.
</P>
<P>
   Connie Morella, a Maryland Republican congresswoman sympathetic
to gun control, reiterated the importance of political follow-up if
the movement was to become a political force.
</P>
<P>
   ``They cannot rely on yesterday's (Sunday's) event alone to make
their point,'' he said. They will need to lobby in Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   Rather more pithily, the New York Times said in an editorial:
``The hands that rock the nation's cradles have the potential to
rock its political institutions _ but only if they keep rocking
hard.''
</P>
<P>
   A point repeatedly emphasized by speakers at Sunday's rally was
the potential voting power of the suburban women who felt strongly
enough about gun violence to travel many hundreds of miles to make
their voices heard.
</P>
<P>
   This overwhelmingly white, middle-class constituency includes
many of the ``soccer moms'' who were seen by analysts as key to the
election of Bill Clinton. With their votes again in contention in
the coming presidential election, no presidential candidate can
afford to take their loyalty for granted.
</P>
<P>
   The voting strength of the ``moms'' goes some way towards
explaining why the Republican Governor of Texas, George W. Bush,
announced on the eve of the march that the state would offer free
child-proofing trigger locks to anyone who wanted them.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who is no friend of the gun control movement, said that he
would also subsidize a similar measure nationwide, should he become
president.
</P>
<P>
   The voting capacity of suburban women was also a point heavily
stressed by the well-briefed speakers on Sunday, who called on
mothers to cast or withhold their vote on the single issue of gun
control.
</P>
<P>
   This opened the prospect of gun control being used by the
political left and center much as the conservative right has used
abortion as the single issue determining which candidate they will
support.
</P>
<P>
   Capitalizing on the public support for gun control as shown in
Sunday's march, President Clinton Monday renewed his call for
Congress to pass the gun control legislation that has been stalled
since its defeat in the House last year.
</P>
<P>
   One notable absentee, both Monday and from the march itself,
however, was Vice President Al Gore, whose much-publicized casting
vote had ensured passage of the legislation through the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   One explanation for his low profile on the issue could be a poll
last week that suggested he was unexpectedly losing support among
male voters, who by and large support gun ownership.
</P>
<P>
   By a coincidence of timing, Monday also saw the release of the
official police report on one of the major catalysts for the
weekend march _ the April 1999 shootings at Columbine High School
in Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   While adding little new to what has already been leaked into the
public domain, the report confirms that police failed to act on
information that the two teenage gunmen planned some violent act at
the school, and criticizes the delay in ordering the emergency SWAT
team _ the elite rapid-reaction police unit _ into the school. &QL; 
