 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By KIM SENGUPTA  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ To all intents and purposes, Brigadier David
Richards is now the military overlord of Sierra Leone, albeit
possibly a reluctant one.
</P>
<P>
   With the Sierra Leone Army in a state of disarray, forces loyal
to the government an exotic circus, and the United Nations
peacekeepers ill-equipped and demoralized, the Brigadier with his
British task force is the man who matters.
</P>
<P>
   The Sierra Leone president, Ahmad Tejan Kabbah, has sought a
daily meeting with Brigadier Richards and British officers are said
to be directing operations against the rebels.
</P>
<P>
   The head of the U.N. peacekeeping force, the Indian General
Vijay Jetley, desperately needs the logistical help Richards can
provide. Also invaluable has been the intelligence provided by SAS
units operating away from Freetown, behind rebel lines.
</P>
<P>
   Brigadier Richards has been a soldier for 29 years, and has
served in Northern Ireland, the Far East and the Rhine Army. He
came to the attention of the senior hierarchy in East Timor where
his diplomatic as well as military skills were noted.
</P>
<P>
   Colleagues describe Richards, married with two daughters aged 14
and 16, as affable but also someone who does not suffer fools
gladly.
</P>
<P>
   He is said to have a talent for improvisation but also has a
streak of independence which could put him ``off message'' to the
line back at headquarters. This was when ministers were lining up
in London to say the role of the force was purely to extricate
civilians. Brigadier Richards in Freetown said the mandate of the
British forces could be liberally interpreted.
</P>
<P>
   He was not, say colleagues, particularly phased by the fuss. A
colleague said : ``He is a keen student of military history and has
a broad vision. He has already shown he is in top of the situation
out there.'' &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this brief profile from THE INDEPENDENT newspaper in
London, it must be purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's
sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at
732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is weyded(at)nytimes.com. If
unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at
816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
