Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into the ``e''
entertainment news, ``a'' domestic/general news and ``k''
commentary news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By CHERRY NORTON  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ The rest of the world may be giving up smoking, but
Hollywood
</P>
<P>
   d indep??? indep54k cwhite 628 05-09 16:35 xxxxx rk
BC-JUDGE-ON-WHEELS-INDEPENDENT indep54a cwhite 629 05-09 16:34
xxxxx ra BC-JUDGE-ON-WHEELS-INDEPENDENT indep53f cwhite 627 05-09
16:34 xxxxx rf BC-ARTICHOKE-ENERGY-INDEPENDEN indep53a cwhite 628
05-09 16:33 xxxxx ra BC-ARTICHOKE-ENERGY-INDEPENDEN indep52k cwhite
843 05-09 16:32 xxxxx rk BC-BUSHMEN-SIERRALEONE-INDEPEN indep52a
cwhite 843 05-09 16:32 xxxxx ra BC-BUSHMEN-SIERRALEONE-INDEPEN
indep51k cwhite 706 05-09 16:31 xxxxx rk
BC-PRIMER-SIERRALEONE-INDEPEND indep51a cwhite 707 05-09 16:30
xxxxx ra BC-PRIMER-SIERRALEONE-INDEPEND indep45k cwhite 990 05-08
17:22 xxxxx rk BC-CELLPHONE-BACKLASH-RESEND-I indep45a cwhite 990
05-08 17:21 xxxxx ra BC-CELLPHONE-BACKLASH-RESEND-I indep50k cwhite
1048 05-08 17:15 xxxxx rk BC-HOMER-SLUGFEST-BASEBALL-IND indep50s
cwhite 1048 05-08 17:14 xxxxx rs BC-HOMER-SLUGFEST-BASEBALL-IND
indep50a cwhite 1049 05-08 17:13 xxxxx ra
BC-HOMER-SLUGFEST-BASEBALL-IND indep49k cwhite 1146 05-08 17:12
xxxxx rk BC-ISRAEL-US-WARMONGERS-EXCLUS indep49a cwhite 1147 05-08
17:11 xxxxx ra BC-ISRAEL-US-WARMONGERS-EXCLUS indep48k cwhite 621
05-08 17:10 xxxxx rk BC-CORPSE-SPAREPARTS-INDEPENDE indep48a cwhite
622 05-08 17:10 xxxxx ra BC-CORPSE-SPAREPARTS-INDEPENDE indep47l
cwhite 488 05-08 17:09 xxxxx rl BC-POKEMON-CELLPHONES-INDEPEND
indep47a cwhite 489 05-08 17:09 xxxxx ra
BC-POKEMON-CELLPHONES-INDEPEND indep46k cwhite 820 05-08 17:08
xxxxx rk BC-WHO-IS-SANKOH?-INDEPENDENT- indep46a cwhite 820 05-08
17:07 xxxxx ra BC-WHO-IS-SANKOH?-INDEPENDENT- More? just can't kick
the habit.
</P>
<P>
   According to the most comprehensive research ever done on
tobacco on screen, leading characters are lighting up in more than
nine out of 10 films, while a fifth of movies aimed at children
feature smoking.
</P>
<P>
   The findings are the result of work by a team of American
researchers at Dartmouth Medical School in New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   They looked at the 250 highest-grossing U.S. films over 10 years
and discovered that in 95 percent of them the characters are
continuing to smoke. In the worst cases, the stars are seen puffing
away for a third of the films' duration.
</P>
<P>
   ``JFK,'' Oliver Stone's Oscar-winner starring Kevin Costner,
came out as the worst offender of the 1990s and was branded the
smokiest film. It was closely followed by ``Dick Tracy'' and
``Bugsy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Cocktail'' and ``Pulp Fiction'' featured smoking on screen for
almost a third of their entire length, while ``Schindler's List,''
``Forrest Gump,'' ``Titanic,'' and ``Get Shorty'' also featured
tobacco prominently.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers analyzed the top 25 box-office hits from each
year from 1988 to 1997. They counted the number of times a major or
minor character smoked a cigarette or cigar and recorded how long
smoking was shown on screen.
</P>
<P>
   A total of 3,346 occurrences of tobacco use or imagery were
identified in the 250 films. One-fifth of these involved use by
ancillary characters, and almost a third involved background
tobacco imagery. In more than half of the movies analyzed, the
major character smoked.
</P>
<P>
   Although Hollywood has now formally renounced fees for placing
tobacco brands prominently in view, it still uses cigarettes as a
cinematic shorthand denoting ruggedness in men, or vampishness in
female characters.
</P>
<P>
   Tobacco use by major characters was also associated with other
high-risk behavior and was portrayed differently for men and women.
Among female characters who smoked on screen, smoking was
associated with sexual affairs, illegal activities and reckless
driving.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, smoking was used by male characters to show violent
behavior and dangerous acts.
</P>
<P>
   The interaction between tobacco use, gender and the portrayal of
specific behavior suggests that tobacco may be used to characterize
``tough'' men and ``bad'' women, the researchers said.
</P>
<P>
   James Sargent, professor of pediatrics at Dartmouth Medical
School, said: ``Adolescents respond to role models and persons of
star status by emulating them. By allowing stars to depict smoking
behavior on screen, the movie industry may be contributing to the
current epidemic of adolescent tobacco use.''
</P>
<P>
   Doctors and anti-smoking campaigners have jumped on the
findings, condemning the widespread smoking as irresponsible. The
high level of smoking on screen runs counter to the realities of
smoking in western society, where adult smoking is generally in
decline, they said.
</P>
<P>
   In Britain, the number of smokers has fallen to 27 percent of
the adult population, although the latest figures show that smoking
among teenage girls is rising.
</P>
<P>
   Sargent, who presented the research Sunday at the annual meeting
of the Pediatric Academic Societies in Boston, said that although
the film industry had said in 1990 it would not to take money from
tobacco companies to show their products on screen, the prevalence
of smoking in movies was still very high.
</P>
<P>
   ``Children viewing movies will frequently be exposed to tobacco
use as normative and even glamorized behaviors. Parents cannot rely
on movie ratings to screen movies for tobacco use,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Co-author Dr. Madeline Dalton said: ``We are especially
concerned about tobacco use by popular stars because we believe
this is likely to have the greatest impact on adolescent
behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   Amanda Sandford of Ash, the anti-smoking group, said: ``Smoking
tends to be portrayed in a glamorous way which makes it more
attractive to people. If films portrayed the reality of smoking
they would have people choking, wheezing and dying of lung
cancer.'' &QL; 
