<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-E-BOOKS-ONLINE-RESEND-WORTH-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEPHEN KING'S ONLINE BOOK MARKS DAWN OF DIGITAL PUBLISHING  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (RESENDING from May 10)   (This 500-word ``separate-buy'' story is from the May 2000 issue of
``WORTH'' magazine. To publish this article, it must be purchased
from the New York Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail
address is weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert,
please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been double-filed _ into the ``a''
domestic/general/technology news and ``f'' financial news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By DAVE CALIFANO  
 c.2000 Worth Magazine  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   Until now, electronic books were an idea whose time might have
never come. But thanks to Stephen King, publishing houses and
electronics manufacturers are taking a second look at a market they
have long been content to ignore.
</P>
<P>
   Prompting the reassessment is the March publication of King's
66-page novella, ``Riding the Bullet,'' which was initially
available only on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Offered for free by both Amazon.com and, briefly,
barnesandnoble.com, and for a mere $2.50 on other sites, King's
story flew off servers as fast as Web surfers could log on to them.
</P>
<P>
   In the first two days the book was available, more than a
half-million copies were downloaded. (In the print world, King's
books typically sell about 75,000 hardcover copies on the first day
of sale, which is a huge amount.)
</P>
<P>
   The online furor proved that ``content is what people want and
will read,'' says Tom Morrow, a spokesman for SoftBook Press, a
unit of Gemstar International, which owns the technology behind the
SoftBook electronic books. ``The medium isn't that important.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, not quite. It's important that the medium be affordable
and easy to use. Today's electronic book-reader technology isn't.
But that's changing.
</P>
<P>
   For now, Gemstar has a virtual monopoly on E-readers. The
SoftBank costs $600 by itself, or one can purchase it for $299,
plus a commitment to buy $20 worth of E-books a month for 24
months. The lower-end Rocket eBook retails for $199.
</P>
<P>
   An E-reader isn't needed to download ``Riding the Bullet'' _
it's readable on an ordinary personal computer _ but SoftBook sales
did increase around the time of the novella's release.
</P>
<P>
   Gemstar is convinced that there's a viable market for a
popularly priced electronic reader. To bring down costs, the
company has allied itself with Thomson Multimedia, the French
electronics manufacturer.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of the deal, Thomson will license Gemstar's
technology and produce an electronic reader under the RCA brand.
Thomson declines to give a price range, but it plans to have an
``affordable'' product on the market this year.
</P>
<P>
   Price alone won't persuade consumers to buy an E-reader. A good
selection of choices is also important, and tradition-bound book
publishers have been slow to digitize their wares, says John
Corcoran, an analyst with CIBC Worldmarkets in New York.
</P>
<P>
   But by 2004, International Data Corp. predicts there will be 4
million users of electronic books. That's incentive enough for
publishers to start digitizing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most major publishers realize that electronic publishing is an
important market,'' says SoftBook's Morrow, ``and they're making
more content available.'' Much of the first wave will be
educational and business titles.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, the economics of E-books may be irresistible. ``If
the Web is about nothing else,'' says Corcoran, ``it's about
reducing the cost of distributing content to something close to
zero.''
</P>
<P>
   Since distribution, not paper or printing, is a publisher's
biggest cost, Stephen King may soon have some company on the
electronic bookshelf. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITOR'S NOTE: Dave Califano is a staff writer at ``Worth.'') &LR;  &QL;   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _______ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (To publish this 500-word ``WORTH'' magazine article, it must
be purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's sales
representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at
732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is weyded(at)nytimes.com. If
unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at
816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL;
