<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 02:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7296 &Cx1f; tab-z
r f BC-SWEDEN-STOCKMARKET-RE     05-17 0833
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWEDEN-STOCKMARKET-RESEND-WORTH-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SWEDES' SMELL OF SUCCESS  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Business Editors...RESENDING from May 10)   (This 625-word ``separate-buy'' financial story is from the May
2000 issue of ``WORTH'' magazine. To publish this article, it must
be purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's sales
representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at
732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is weyded(at)nytimes.com. If
unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at
816-822-1444.)  
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been double-filed _ into the ``a''
general news and ``f'' financial news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By TODD G. BUCHHOLZ  
 c.2000 Worth Magazine  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   Sweden is beautiful. The land is beautiful. The people are
beautiful. The economy is beautiful. And yes, the stock market is
beautiful.
</P>
<P>
   So far this year, Sweden is winning the race among major
countries for the strongest stock market. Its Stockholm (``OMX'')
index was up some 20 percent, as of mid-March, and has soared 74
percent since last October.
</P>
<P>
   Those are the kind of outsized gains investors have come to
expect from blazing tech stocks. It's no wonder: Sweden is among
the most tech-savvy countries in the world. If you visit Stockholm,
you'll hear more cell phones beeping on a street corner than most
any other place in the world. And fully one-third of Swedes are
plugged into the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   While Sweden's infamous welfare state still stands, its
government was forced to cut spending in the mid-1990s to combat a
12 percent budget deficit and is actually now running a surplus.
</P>
<P>
   Sweden's 28 percent corporate tax rate is far below the European
Union average of 40 percent. Even labor policies are less rigid
than in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Though it's difficult for firms to fire full-time workers, the
market for temporary workers is fairly fluid. No surprise, then,
that a company like Poolia, which provides temporary help, is
thriving. Its stock price has climbed 61 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
   In March, when many high-tech stocks around the world
experienced a major fall as investors shifted assets back into
old-economy industries, Swedish tech companies escaped with less
damage than most.
</P>
<P>
   ProAct IT, which provides data storage, is up 123 percent this
year, and Digital Vision, which specializes in digital processing
for movies and television, has jumped 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Even Ericsson, locked in a tough battle with telecom giants
Nokia and Motorola, has climbed 50 percent in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The Swedish economy is galloping along at a healthy 3.5 to 4
percent clip, much like it did in 1999. Most impressive is that
economic growth hasn't kicked up inflation, which remains below 2
percent.
</P>
<P>
   And the central bank, led by trusted bureaucrat Urban
Baeckstroem, has been slowly raising interest rates, following the
successful example of U.S. Federal Reserve Board Chairman Alan
Greenspan, just to make sure that inflation doesn't re-ignite.
</P>
<P>
   The market's faith in Baeckstroem shows up in the solid trading
of the Swedish krona, which has gained over 6 percent in the past
year against the flabby Euro currency. And Swedish ten-year-bond
rates, at 5.38 percent, were nearly a full percentage point below
U.S. rates in mid-March.
</P>
<P>
   For a country of only 8.5 million people, Sweden is also an
export powerhouse, racking up a current-account surplus of $4.5
billion in 1999. By selling so much to the rest of the world,
Sweden helps keep the krona strong.
</P>
<P>
   Any worries? The government looks a little shaky. The ruling
Social Democrat Party (SDP) holds only a minority of the seats in
the Riksdag, Sweden's parliament, and it depends on the leftist
Green Party and Left Party to maintain power.
</P>
<P>
   That alliance could crumble before the next election, which
isn't scheduled until September 2002. Prime Minister Goran Persson
would like Sweden to join the European Monetary Union, but that
would have to be approved in a general referendum, which would
likely be held in 2000 at the earliest.
</P>
<P>
   Businesses would welcome the currency stability and reduced
transaction costs that come with EMU membership. Labor unions,
however, would like to see unemployment, currently at 5 percent,
drop a percentage point beforehand.
</P>
<P>
   As for the voters, many are undecided, but a plurality feel
that, for now, Sweden's currency and economy are doing fine without
Europe. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITOR'S NOTE: Todd G. Buchholz is the author of ``Market Shock''
and Chairman of Victoria Capital Partners, LP.) &LR;  &QL;   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _______ &QC;
</P>
