<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000517.0064 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 02:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7300 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-ASTROS-BREWERS-HN     05-17 0767
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-BREWERS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH DUARTE  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
MILWAUKEE _ Win or lose, nothing seems to come easy for the Astros.
<TEXT>
<P>
   What began Tuesday night finally concluded in the wee hours this
morning as the Brewers ended a 16-inning tug of war with a 6-5
victory at County Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   A sparse crowd of 9,239 was on hand when the game began, and
only a handful of fans remained as the Astros and Brewers completed
the 5-hour, 39-minute game. Astros manager Larry Dierker was
ejected in the 13th inning for arguing balls and strikes.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros are 1-3 in extra-inning games this season. They have
lost seven of their last 11 games.
</P>
<P>
   Marquis Grissom led off the Milwaukee 16th with an infield
single off Chris Holt (1-6) and advanced to third on a single to
right field by Lyle Mouton. With one out, Henry Blanco drove in the
winning run with a fly ball to right field that was dropped by
Roger Cedeno. Blanco was credited with a sacrifice fly.
</P>
<P>
   Horacio Estrada (2-0) earned the victory.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Caminiti accounted for a career-high five hits for the
Astros. Moises Alou drove in three runs, which included his fifth
homer of the season in the second inning.
</P>
<P>
   After holding a three-run lead only to blow it, the Astros
rallied to tie the game at 5 in the eighth inning. Jeff Bagwell and
Caminiti hit consecutive singles to lead off the inning, and Alou
followed with an RBI single to left field.
</P>
<P>
   From there, both teams engaged in an inning-by-inning exercise
in frustration. The Astros used every position player on the roster
and every member of the bullpen, although Jay Powell did not pitch
but was used only as a pinch hitter for fellow reliever Jose
Cabrera.
</P>
<P>
   The Brewers stranded 19 runners in the game; the Astros left 11
on base.
</P>
<P>
   The Brewers had a chance to push across the potential winning
run in the eighth inning off Mike Maddux, loading the bases on a
pair of singles and a walk. Doug Henry retired Mark Loretta on a
weak pop-up to second base to leave the bases full.
</P>
<P>
   Milwaukee threatened in the 12th inning only to be denied again.
This time Billy Wagner worked out of a jam with runners at second
and third base by coaxing Grissom into an inning-ending pop-up to
first base.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros had a runner at third base in the top of the 13th but
came away empty-handed when Juan Acevedo struck out the side.
</P>
<P>
   In the bottom of the 13th, catcher Tony Eusebio made a
game-extending catch when he took a throw from second baseman Craig
Biggio and held on to the ball in a collision at home plate with
Ron Belliard.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Hernandez led off the Brewers' 14th inning with a single to
right field off Cabrera, who then hit Mouton with a pitch. But
Cabrera struck out Blanco, Luis Lopez grounded into a fielder's
choice, and Belliard flied out to center field to strand two
runners in scoring position.
</P>
<P>
   Astros righthander Shane Reynolds allowed five runs and five
hits in six innings. He had five strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros jumped on Brewers righthander Jason Bere for three
runs in the second inning, all courtesy of home runs. After a
leadoff double by Caminiti, Alou hit his fifth homer of the season,
a two-run shot to left-center field. Later in the inning, Tim
Bogar, making only his second start in the past eight games, hit a
solo shot to left to give the Astros a 3-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The lead didn't last long. Mouton hit a solo homer off Reynolds
in the bottom of the second. The Brewers added two more runs in the
third as Reynolds walked two batters in the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Belliard walked with one out and scored from first after Cedeno
slipped along the grass in front of the warning track on a double
by Mark Loretta. After a walk to Jeromy Burnitz and a flyout by
Kevin Barker, Grissom hit a two-out RBI single to right field to
tie the game at 3.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros regained the lead in the fourth with a walk to
Richard Hidalgo and an RBI double by Mitch Meluskey.
</P>
<P>
   Milwaukee, which dropped three of four games to the Astros at
County Stadium in late April, regained the lead in the fourth
inning. Mouton singled to center field to lead off the inning, and
Blanco sent a 2-2 pitch from Reynolds into the half-empty bleachers
in left field.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros stranded a pair of runners in the third and fifth
innings. With runners at first and second in the fifth, Alou
drilled a deep drive off Bere that was caught by Grissom against
the center-field wall. And in the seventh, representing the
potential tying run, Cedeno was thrown out attempting to steal
second base.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
