<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERSIDE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHOENIX HAS FIRST-HALF PHIASCO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LEE BARNATHAN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ On what turned out to be their final night of the
1999-2000 season, Phoenix wondered what if.
</P>
<P>
   What if Tom Gugliotta had been healthy for the playoffs?
</P>
<P>
   That was a valid question before Tuesday's Game 5. Afterward,
there were more what ifs.
</P>
<P>
   What if the Suns had decided to show up? What if they had
responded to Ron Harper's winning prediction?
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate to say it was one of those nights,'' Luc Longley said,
``but when you try to explain it, we can't think of anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps some low moments are best left unexplained, except to
say the Suns couldn't shoot in the one game they needed to most.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix scored an NBA record-low nine points in the second
period and a franchise-low 23 points in the first half. That's a
far cry from 71 in Game 4 Sunday. The 65 total points also is a
franchise low.
</P>
<P>
   No Phoenix starter scored in double figures. Only Todd Day (10)
did.
</P>
<P>
   The Suns shot 11.8 percent in the second period and 29 percent
(23 of 80) for the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got the looks,'' said Anfernee Hardaway, whose eight points
tied him for top-starter-scoring honors. ``We didn't capitalize on
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Jason Kidd called Gugliotta, with an average of nearly eight
rebounds a game, Phoenix's best rebounder, best post player, a good
perimeter shooter and ``that's six more fouls we'd have. Gugs is
missed tremendously.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, as the Suns knew, they had to play with the personnel
they had (San Antonio had to make do without Tim Duncan, and the
Suns took advantage). The key was to duplicate Sunday's Game 4
success (a 117-98 victory) at Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a simple game,'' Rodney Rogers said. ``We make it
tough.''
</P>
<P>
   And to make it tough on the Lakers, the Suns had to come out and
establish a high energy level and stay competitive.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'll come out hard, and whatever team makes their
impression felt at the end of the first quarter will be in
control,'' Kidd said before the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We play the first to get to the second,'' Rogers said, ``then
we play the second to get to the second half.''
</P>
<P>
   Except the second half was rendered meaningless by virtue of
L.A.'s 49-23 halftime lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``We lost confidence in the second quarter and started playing
too fast,'' Phoenix coach Scott Skiles said. ``They got a big lead
and we thought we had to get it all back at once.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't all bad. Phoenix held the Lakers to 36-percent
shooting. Shaquille O'Neal and Kobe Bryant were a combined 13 of
35.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you told me, we'd hold Shaq to 7 of 19 and Kobe to 6 of 16,
I'd have felt pretty good,'' Skiles said.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Suns set futility records and made Harper's
prediction come true.
</P>
<P>
   There was a bright spot for Phoenix, however: Harper said his
Bulls teams would have beaten Phoenix by 200 points. The Suns lost
by only 22 and now can spend the entire summer wondering what if.
</P>
<P>
   ``You hate to have your worst game of the season be your last
game,''Skiles said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
