<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 03:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7303 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBN-DODGERS-CUBS-LADN     05-17 0789
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-CUBS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS WRANGLE WITH WRIGLEY FANS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO -- Mayhem and madness broke out with one out in the
bottom of the ninth inning at Wrigley Field when several fans and
members of the Los Angeles Dodgers bullpen became engaged in an
altercation that spilled into the stands.
</P>
<P>
   The melee lasted nine minutes and was triggered when catcher
Chad Kreuter was allegedly punched in the head and had his hat
taken from him in a game the Dodgers beat the Chicago Cubs 6-5
Tuesday on Todd Hundley's three-run homer in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody hauled off and hit one of my guys in the back of the
head and went after his hat,'' Dodgers manager Davey Johnson said.
``When they run down and whack one of your guys on the field and
run and take off, other guys saw it and went after him.''
</P>
<P>
   Kreuter was sitting in the Dodgers bullpen, situated down the
right-field line and against the stands. A fan allegedly came down
and hit Kreuter and took his hat. Kreuter went into the stands in
an attempt to retrieve it, several players said. Several more
players and bullpen coach Rick Dempsey then went into the stands to
try to help Kreuter before the rest of the Dodgers noticed.
</P>
<P>
   Once aware of the trouble, the Dodgers players on the field and
in the dugout raced to the bullpen to try to restore order to a
chaotic scene. Fans were punching and pulling at Dodgers players in
the stands while teammates were standing at the edge of the bullpen
and stands trying to pull people back onto the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was chaos down there,'' said Hundley, a Chicago native.
``It just got out of hand. There were so many fans involved, it was
out of control. Some of the guys were so deep in the stands, I was
just watching to make sure no one got hurt. Security had it calmed
down and then a fan threw another sucker punch and it got out of
hand again.''
</P>
<P>
   Kreuter declined to talk about the situation, instead saying he
wanted to focus on Hundley's home run and Jeff Shaw's save.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just know that when players go into the stands, you're
taking a big risk,'' Cubs manager Don Baylor said. ``The next thing
you know, you have their general manager standing next to me on the
field. He shouldn't be there, either. You can't go into the stands,
no matter what they throw.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers said when order was being restored, numerous fans
continued to throw beer and push and shove. Johnson said so much
beer was being thrown that it was burning his eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Dempsey, who along with Kreuter, went to identify a fan in the
Wrigley Field holding area, said he grabbed the arm of a fan who
was about to punch Kreuter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then, I fell back and was pinned against the seats,'' Dempsey
said. ``I couldn't get up. We were trying to get the players back
on the field.''
</P>
<P>
   Several fans in the area said a few of the Dodgers players were
as many as eight rows deep in the stands. Several of the Dodgers,
including left fielder Gary Sheffield, were trying to pull the
players from the stands to safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``I turned around and I saw a bunch of stuff by the bullpen and
I ran over there as soon as fast as I could,'' Sheffield said. ``I
was trying to get everyone back on the field. My first instinct is
to go and pull them out of the stands. I was just trying to protect
your players.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was shocked more than anything. I've never seen it in my
12-year career. Not in highlights or anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Security had numerous people in custody. A Chicago police
department spokesman said three fans were cited for disorderly
conduct and fined $100.
</P>
<P>
   Malone said he didn't anticipate any action being taken against
any of the Dodgers, either by Major League Baseball or Chicago
police, but it's likely the commissioner's office will investigate
the situation. Malone said the Dodgers wouldn't take any
disciplinary action against the players. He added no players were
injured except for a few bumps and bruises were suffered.
</P>
<P>
   ``It kept going on and no security was showing up,'' Dodgers
general manager Kevin Malone said. ``They were late. It was
self-protection. It could have been worse and it was scary.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Rathje, director of stadium operations who's been with the
Cubs for 18 years, said he remembered one other incident in which
players went into the stands but declined further comment.
</P>
<P>
   Malone said he was told by Wrigley Field personnel that more
security would be added to the bullpen area for the final two games
of the series.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very disappointed in my hometown fans,,'' Hundley said.
``It's not the Chicago I know. Not at a professional baseball game.
That's disgusting.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
