<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-ORIOLES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE BAD PITCH COSTS ANGELS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Ken Hill is hurt. Ramon Ortiz is in the
minors. Scott Schoeneweis, Jason Dickson and Jarrod Washburn are
going through growing pains typical of young pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   Meet Kent Bottenfield, Angels ace.
</P>
<P>
   Bottenfield pitched into the eighth inning and kept the Anaheim
Angels in the game, but it wasn't good enough as the Baltimore
Orioles ended a seven- game losing streak with a 4-3 victory
Tuesday night before 15,881 at Edison Field.
</P>
<P>
   The loss dropped the Angels into last place in the AL West, even
though they are only two games under .500 (19-21) and 2 games
behind first-place Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Conine's sacrifice fly in the eighth inning off Angels
reliever Mark Petkovsek scored Delino DeShields to snap a 3-3 tie.
Angels left fielder Darin Erstad robbed Conine of a three-run homer
on the play, but one run was plenty.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Erickson (1-1) pitched seven innings to get the win, and
Mike Timlin earned the save. It didn't seem to matter to the Angels
hitters that Erickson was making only third start of the season
after having arthroscopic surgery to remove bone chips from his
elbow March 3, or that he was 0-1 with a 12.46 ERA going into the
game.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout his career, Erickson has pitched better against the
Angels than any other team, improving to 16-4 with Tuesday's win.
Erickson gave up three runs and nine hits in a season-high seven
innings.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Bottenfield has pitched into the seventh inning or
longer in five consecutive starts during which time his ERA is
2.83. In fact, the four runs Bottenfield allowed Tuesday marked
only the second time he has yielded more than three runs in a game
in his nine starts this season.
</P>
<P>
   Throw out his one bad start - nine runs in 3 innings against
Toronto on April 20 - and Bottenfield's ERA is 2.68 (16 earned runs
in 53 innings).
</P>
<P>
   The reason Bottenfield has only three wins has to do with run
support. In his nine starts, the Angels are averaging 4.3 runs per
game. With all other starters, the Angels average 5.6 runs per
game. The 1.3-run difference would have made a difference Tuesday,
but Bottenfield won't blame the offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``They gave me a two-run lead, that's all I could ask for,'' he
said. ``Sure, it's frustrating, but the thing I have to do is
control the game better. I've got to make a better pitch to him,
more like I did two innings later when he grounded out.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Him'' in this case is Mike Bordick, whose two-run homer in the
sixth tied the game at 3.
</P>
<P>
   ``A pitcher can't control when a team scores runs for you,''
Angels manager Mike Scioscia said. ``The fact he's pitched deep
into games so often is really what it's all about. The wins will
come.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that he is leading the starting staff, Bottenfield says he
is doing what he can to help the younger pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talk on the bench, about what I might do in certain
situations,'' Bottenfield said. ''That's my job. I need to do a
better job of leading by example. I've got to do better out there
or they won't trust what I say sitting on the bench.''
</P>
<P>
   Albert Belle's leadoff homer in the second inning gave the
Orioles a 1-0 lead, but it didn't last long.
</P>
<P>
   Erstad led off the Angels' third with a walk, stole second and
went to third on a sacrifice bunt by Adam Kennedy, who was safe at
first on Erickson's error. Mo Vaughn followed with a sacrifice fly
to left to tie the game at 1.
</P>
<P>
   In the fourth inning, singles from Bengie Molina, Benji Gil,
Erstad and Vaughn resulted in two runs and a 3-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Bottenfield was cruising. He needed only four pitches
to retire the side in the fifth, but things didn't go quite so
smoothly in the sixth. Brady Anderson led off with a single and
scored on Bordick's two-run homer, tying the game at 3.
</P>
<P>
   Bottenfield left with two on and one out in the eighth and the
game tied at 3, but Conine hit the first pitch thrown by Petkovsek
to left-center, where Erstad made a leaping catch at the fence.
DeShields tagged from third to score the game-winner.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
