<HEADLINE>
NEXT UP: BEST-IN-WEST CONTEST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE DILBECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Here it comes, just as advertised. Just as
predicted since before the season started. The Big Showdown is now
at hand, high noon in the NBA West.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Lakers and Trail Blazers, deemed the league's
best since Phil Jackson showed up in L.A. and Scottie Pippen in
Portland, now officially get to determine who's best in the West,
if not all the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   Both teams completed their Western Conference anticipated
semifinal victories Tuesday night - the Lakers with a convincing
87-65 win over the Suns - to set up their Western Conference Final.
</P>
<P>
   Starting on Saturday at Staples Center, answers to seven months
worth of questions will finally arrive.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is kind of fitting,'' said Lakers forward Glen Rice.
``That's how it should be. We have the two best teams on the West
Coast. What better way to have the final battle?
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew it was going to come down to these two teams, and now
that it's here, it's going to be a lot of fun.''
</P>
<P>
   The teams split the four games played in the regular season,
each winning once on the other's court. But it was the Lakers'
90-87 victory in Portland on Feb. 29 that set the tone for the rest
of the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers went onto finish with the best record in the NBA,
earn the homecourt advantage and became nearly everyone's popular
pick in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Then the Lakers were forced to a decisive fifth game by
Sacramento in the first round and embarrassed in a Game 4 loss at
Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   The Blazers were rolling through the playoffs, until losing a
close Game 4 at Utah. Plenty started jumping off the Lakers'
bandwagon and carrying Portland's colors.
</P>
<P>
   Not that anyone is claiming how they got here matters much.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't mean anything,'' Rice said. ``What's going to mean
something is when the time comes at tipoff, to see who's playing at
their top then.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Forget everything you've seen,'' said Lakers forward Robert
Horry. ``Just wait and see what happens the next couple of games.''
</P>
<P>
   The Blazers are considered to have a major bench advantage.
Theirs is one of the best and deepest in the league. The Lakers'
bench is usually strong at home but inconsistent on the road.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers, of course, have a one-two of Shaquille O'Neal and
Kobe Bryant that no team can match.
</P>
<P>
   ``Portland has big bodies to throw in there at Shaq,'' said Suns
coach Scott Skiles. ``A very deep team. You could say on paper,
Portland has more weapons.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I'd never bet against Shaq and Kobe. I think the way to
build a championship team is to have two or three great players,
four or five good players, and four or five role players. And
that's how the Lakers are built.''
</P>
<P>
   Some might figure the Lakers will have to play better than they
did against Phoenix to defeat Portland in their best-of-seven
series, but not Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' Jackson said. ``Did you see Portland play? They played
two games that weren't so pretty themselves. But that's what
happens when you're slugging it out in the playoffs and playing the
same team over and over again. Pretty soon it becomes a real
struggle.
</P>
<P>
   ``This series has been predicted all year long and it's here.
This is the one that everyone has been talking about almost from
day one in the Western Conference. It's fitting it should be like
this.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-17-00 0315EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000517.0069 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 03:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7306 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-LAKERS-SUNS-LADN     05-17 0826
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-SUNS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS ELIMINATE SUNS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Here they come again, the stubborn survivors of
both small tremors and big-time temblors, the guys who keep
slipping and tripping, offering pratfalls at inopportune times but
always regaining balance just in time.
</P>
<P>
   Here come the Los Angeles Lakers, dancing elegantly back into
championship form, all prior bumbling nothwithstanding.
</P>
<P>
   Just two days after plummeting to their worst loss of the
postseason, the Lakers rose once more Tuesday night and put
everything right with an 87-65 rout of the Phoenix Suns at Staples
Center.
</P>
<P>
   Series clinched. Bid to Western Conference finals received. Date
with Portland Trail Blazers awaiting. (The series opens Saturday
afternoon at Staples Center.)
</P>
<P>
   And with it all, a message to the Lakers faithful, or anyone
else shaken by that 117-98 setback two days prior.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a statement to the city of Los Angeles, just to
relax,'' Kobe Bryant said with a laugh. ``If you lose one game,
it's not Armageddon.''
</P>
<P>
   In dismantling Phoenix to finish off the series, 4 to 1, the
Lakers erased every poor image cast in Game 4. They went back to
winning with defense, holding the Suns to an all-time low for a
Laker playoff opponent and to five points fewer than Phoenix scored
in the first half alone on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``How's !ital!that!off! for killer instinct?'' Bryant said.
</P>
<P>
   That trait had been called into question after the Lakers failed
to complete the sweep, but no more.
</P>
<P>
   They contested every shot from the outset, challenged every
drive into the lane. Active, aggressive, intolerant of any sort of
Phoenix offensive. The Suns scored just nine points in the second
quarter, tied an NBA playoff low with 23 points at halftime and
managed just 17 in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix went more than 11 minutes without a field goal from the
second to third quarters.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were aggressive ... it's real defeating when you smother a
team like that,'' coach Phil Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   And yet even he seemed a little stunned by the two-day
turnaround. The Suns' shooting plummeted to 28.8 percent after a
50-plus effort in Game 4. Only reserve Todd Day (10 points) scored
in double figures for Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   ``This game's a mystery to me,'' said Jackson, `` that the Suns
can get 71 points in Sunday's ballgame in a half and can't score 70
in a game. It's just the difference in a day sometimes, the way a
team approaches a basketball game, what happens out there, the luck
of the bounce sometimes, this is one of those nights.''
</P>
<P>
   Steady defense allowed the Lakers to rest easy on offense.
Bryant led the way with a mere 17 points, and Shaquille O'Neal
needed just 15 points 20 below his series average
</P>
<P>
   to get the victory. Glen Rice added 14 points, and the role
players did the rest.
</P>
<P>
   It was a strange way to end a series characterized by offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very ironic,'' Jackson said. ``Is it a full moon tonight?
It is, isn't it?''
</P>
<P>
   A sore right knee and shin, bruised from Sunday's collision with
Suns guard Penny Hardaway, limited O'Neal's offense, and he played
just 33 minutes, sitting the entire fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a little off tonight,'' O'Neal said. ``However, my
teammates stepped up for me, and that's what being a good team is
all about ... I had to convert my game into the Big Token again. I
just had to rebound, block shots and do everything else.''
</P>
<P>
   He finished with 21 rebounds 13 in the first half and three
blocks, plus untold numbers of misdirected shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he was real dominant in the game,'' Jackson said.
``I thought he changed shots, I thought his presence down there was
effective.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal's own final shot was sent to the media.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew we were going to do that (win). You guys probably
didn't think we were going to do that. You probably thought it was
going to be like the Sacramento series. We didn't want to have two
efforts like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Rather than enjoy their Sunday rout, the Suns spent two days
simmering over Ron Harper's postgame comment that the Lakers would
``beat the (bleep)'' out of the Suns in Game 5. But come game time,
the Suns showed more ire than fire, falling behind 21-14 after one
quarter, then scoring nine points in the second to trail 49-23 at
halftime. The game was never close.
</P>
<P>
   So maybe the Lakers found that missing mean streak Harper was
talking about. And maybe Harper, who correctly predicted a victory
just as he did before Game 5 against Sacramento
</P>
<P>
   is some kind of prophet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I ain't a prophet, I just felt that way,'' Harper said. ``I
just felt my team is a good team. I knew we were playing at home, I
knew we were going to be good at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came out and I told the guys, `Let's go out and beat the
(bleep) out of them. Point blank. Lets go out and do the job we
have to do.' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-17-00 0317EDT &QL; 
