<SLUG> BC-BKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUIETLY, LAKERS LET ACTIONS SPEAK LOUDLY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Accountability is a keyword in Phil Jackson's
world. So the two days between Games 4 and 5 of the Western
Conference semifinals figured to be a regular Phil-ibuster for the
Los Angeles Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   Lord knows their somnolent performance Sunday against Phoenix
begged more questions than are on a week's worth of Regis Philbin
cue cards. In no particular order: How could a team with a
first-team All-Defensive player (Kobe Bryant) and the runner-up in
the Defensive Player of the Year voting (Shaquille O'Neal) give up
71 points in the first 24 minutes?
</P>
<P>
   How could a team in a position to make a sweeping statement lose
by 19?
</P>
<P>
   And what possessed Rick Fox to earn a fourth-quarter ejection?
</P>
<P>
   Alas, when it came to answering for their poor performance, the
Lakers came down with a collective case of laryngitis. Their
silence was unprecedented, like a quiet interlude during an NBA
game.
</P>
<P>
   We're talking about guys who usually are as gregarious as the
gals from ``The View.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal fills notebooks the way he does the low post. Bryant's
sound bytes are as smooth as his shooting stroke. Fox is a
part-time actor who doesn't need a script to be articulate. John
Salley breathes, therefore he talks.
</P>
<P>
   Derek Fisher attacks questions the way he does loose balls; he
holds nothing back. Ron Harper is in everybody's ear like wax.
</P>
<P>
   Just when we were wondering whether maybe the Lakers' collars
weren't getting a tad tight, thus restricting the flow of air to
their larynxes, they came out Tuesday and returned the thrashing,
dispatching the Suns 87-65 to close out the best-of-seven series.
</P>
<P>
   Guess they decided to let their play do their talking. A superb
strategy, that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes you can talk a little too much,'' Fox said, ``and
not put the right actions behind it.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox put his best foot forward, falling into step behind O'Neal
(who had 13 of his 21 rebounds in the first half) and Kobe Bryant
(13 first-half points on his way to 17). The frustrated reserve
forward, who came into the game averaging a paltry two points and
11 minutes for the series, played 10 minutes in the first half and
was 2 of 3 from behind the three-point arc.
</P>
<P>
   In a related development, the Lakers led 49-23 after 24 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The 48-point turnaround in the Suns' fortunes in the first
halves of Games 4 and 5 was easy to break down if not believe: In
Game 4, they converted 58.3 percent of their shots and coughed up
the ball only four times.
</P>
<P>
   In the first 24 minutes Tuesday, the Suns shot 21.6 percent from
the field and committed 11 turnovers, which begat eight Lakers
points. Starting point guard Jason Kidd and sixth man Rodney Rogers
each had as many turnovers (three) as the entire Laker team.
</P>
<P>
   If Phoenix looked like an entirely different team than the one
that had embarrassed the Lakers on Sunday, well, Fox's
metamorphosis was nearly as remarkable, considering he had two
three-point baskets to show for the four previous games.
</P>
<P>
   Amazing, isn't it, how powerful a motivator shame can be.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was an embarrassment factor,'' Fox said, in the silence
before the imperfect storm that wiped out the Suns (the Lakers did,
after all, shoot 36.3 percent). ``You don't want to talk about how
unprofessionally you conducted yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox was speaking for himself and of Sunday's lackadaisical
Lakers, in general.
</P>
<P>
   It was good the Lakers saved their breath, unleashing all their
energy on the poor Suns. The finish line is now very near.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers are four victories from the NBA title.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, we know whichever team advances will have Miami or New York
or Philadelphia or Indiana standing between it and a champagne
shower.
</P>
<P>
   But it says here the Finals will be a mere formality for
whichever team emerges from the West. The 2000 NBA Finals will be
like the 1980 Winter Olympics when the U.S. hockey team defeated
the Soviet Union in the semifinals and then iced the gold medal
with a win over Finland.
</P>
<P>
   But that's us talking, not the Lakers, who Tuesday were content
to let their total eclipse of the Suns be their brashest statement.
The only prediction we could pry out of anybody was this, from
Harper:
</P>
<P>
   ``Whoever emerges,'' in the Western Conference final, he said,
``will know they have earned it.''
</P>
<P>
   The way the Lakers played Tuesday, they gave themselves a
chance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
