<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 03:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7309 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LA     05-17 0724
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HORRY NOT GREEN WITH ENVY AS A SUB
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ One is a hammer, the other scissors. One is a
record-setting iron man, the other frequently held together with
gauze and tape. One is a starter who plays as little as a quarter
of the game, the other a sub who gets the meaningful minutes.
</P>
<P>
   They're an odd couple, A.C. Green and Robert Horry. ``Two
totally different players,'' Horry says.
</P>
<P>
   Though their power-forward partnership isn't as noisy as the
superstar combination of Shaquille O'Neal and Kobe Bryant, it says
as much about why the Los Angeles Lakers have advanced to the NBA
Western Conference final for only the second time since Magic
Johnson's 1991 retirement announcement.
</P>
<P>
   Those who ask why Horry is never in the starting lineup were
handed more reasons to wonder Tuesday night at Staples Center when
he made a series of big plays to send the Lakers on their way to an
87-65 victory over the Phoenix Suns and a 4-1 series victory.
</P>
<P>
   But to those inhabiting the world of coach Phil Jackson, it
makes perfect sense that Green started all 82 games in the regular
season and has started all 10 in the playoffs, and will continue to
start until the Lakers win the championship or are knocked out.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson was asked Monday - not for the first time this season -
whether he'd considered starting Horry, the more productive of his
power forwards. No, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm stubborn that way,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   That tongue-in-cheek answer doesn't give the coach credit,
though.
</P>
<P>
   In recent seasons, under Del Harris and Kurt Rambis, the Lakers
were models of instability, with a more jumbled lineup than a
Double-A baseball club. Eight different Lakers appeared in the
starting lineup in 1997, O'Neal's first season with the team. Seven
players started in 1998 on the way to a Western Conference final
sweep by the Utah Jazz.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, amid the comings and goings of Dennis Rodman, Glen
Rice and Eddie Jones, 10 Lakers took turns in the lineup. That
doesn't count occasional lineup changes forced by injuries and
suspensions.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson has restored stability to the court. Six Lakers have
started in 1999-2000, and Derek Fisher wouldn't have made it if
Bryant hadn't opened the season on the injured list.
</P>
<P>
   Another coach might have switched Horry and Green at some point.
Maybe in January, when Horry played more than Green in six straight
games, or in February and March, when Horry got more minutes in 12
in a row.
</P>
<P>
   But that would have made it a battle, inflamed an issue, raised
doubts. So Jackson sticks with his lineup.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives everybody a comfort zone to work from,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   From his comfort zone, on the bench to begin game 5, Horry
replaced Green with 2:18 to play in the first quarter and the
Lakers ahead by three. He immediately grabbed an offensive rebound
that led to two Rice free throws. He drew a foul chasing a loose
ball and made a free throw.
</P>
<P>
   And in one sequence early in the second quarter, Horry sank a
3-pointer, stole a pass and went in for a breakaway dunk, putting
the Lakers up by 12 on their way to 26 up at halftime.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Green, playing in his 1,120th consecutive NBA game,
went scoreless in 10 first-half minutes, giving him three points in
a span of 3 games.
</P>
<P>
   How does a 6-foot-9 man with a green bear on his head fade from
view? Green turned invisible in the Phoenix series, seeing his
minutes, points and rebounding decline night by night, and doing
too little to stop the Suns' Clifford Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   Horry doesn't mind picking up more than his share of the load.
Coming off the bench ``is fine with me,'' he said. ``A.C. does a
great job. He's more physical and I'm more of a slasher. It gives
(opponents) two totally different players to look at.''
</P>
<P>
   More important, it gives the Lakers one familiar lineup and one
well-practiced set of roles to look at. That's symbolic.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson has a gift for not overreacting. He doesn't overreact
when Green is outplayed by Horry. He doesn't overreact when the
Lakers are embarrassed by the Suns, as they were Sunday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   He sends out the same lineup and watches it restore order. Green
starting, Horry off the bench, everything in its place.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-17-00 0320EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
