<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MERCKER GRATEFUL FOR SUPPORT OF FANS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Pitcher Kent Mercker, undergoing evaluation
and tests at UC Irvine Medical Center after suffering a cerebral
hemorrhage Thursday, issued a statement Tuesday:
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife Julie and I would like to express our deepest
gratitude for all the supportive responses we've received in the
past week. The thoughts, messages and prayers have meant a great
deal to our family. We also want to say thanks to the staff at UCI
Medical Center, my teammates and the Angels organization for being
there every step of the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been a frustrating and confusing period of time in
trying to secure all the answers. I feel pretty good now, but
believe me I intend to continue following my doctor's instructions.
I look forward to seeing all of you soon, either in the clubhouse
or on the mound. Again, words can't convey our appreciation.''
</P>
<P>
   Mercker, who was transferred from intensive care to a private
room Monday, was visited Tuesday by Troy Percival and Darin Erstad.
</P>
<P>
   Luuloa called up: The Angels called up shortstop Keith Luuloa
from Triple-A Edmonton Tuesday, optioning Trent Durrington to
Edmonton. The Angels were in need of a backup shortstop with Gary
DiSarcina on the disabled list and Benji Gil moving to the starting
spot.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels also moved shortstop Justin Baughman from Double-A
Erie to Edmonton, as they try to brace themselves for what seems
inevitable losing DiSarcina for a significant amount of time.
</P>
<P>
   Results from Monday's angiogram performed on the right shoulder
of DiSarcina were negative, meaning no aneurysm was found. He was
examined Tuesday by the Chicago Bears team physician, who will go
over the results with Angels team physician Dr. Lewis Yocum today.
</P>
<P>
   DiSarcina has grown frustrated by the lack of a diagnosis but
knows that he isn't capable of playing in his current state. ``I've
been poked, prodded, zapped, zipped and nuclear-tested,'' DiSarcina
said last week. ``They can run all the tests they want, but when I
walk out of the doctor's office, I still have a sore shoulder.''
</P>
<P>
   How long for Hill?: Pitcher Ken Hill is out with a torn muscle
in his rib cage and there is no timetable for his return.
</P>
<P>
   ``They haven't told me anything because they don't know,'' Hill
said. ``They can't say three months because I could be back in two
weeks. And they can't say two weeks because it might be three
months.''
</P>
<P>
   Hill says the pain has lessened, but there are times it is bad.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I sneeze, that's the biggest thing now,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Hill is guaranteed $6 million for 2001 if he makes 33 starts or
pitches at least 190 innings. Those seem out of reach, but Hill
says it doesn't concern him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have plenty of money,'' said Hill, who is making $5.6
million this season. ``It's about showing these guys I can pitch.
I'm tired of being hurt. I've been playing for 12 years, I have
nothing to prove to anybody. But I've been banged up. I want to
give these guys something.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Levine: Because of off-days, the Angels don't need a fifth
starter until May 27, and not again after that until June 6. Among
those being considered is Al Levine, who has been a lifesaver out
of the bullpen so far.
</P>
<P>
   Levine has been big when the starter has been knocked out of the
game early. He threw 3 hitless innings Sunday after Jason Dickson
lasted only 1 innings, allowing the Angels to rally from a 4-0
deficit to win 7-6. His 3.03 ERA is the lowest on the staff and of
his 11 inherited baserunners, only one has scored.
</P>
<P>
   ``The role Al provides is vital to a championship-caliber
pitching staff,'' manager Mike Scioscia said. ``He's not scared off
by any situation. He has the confidence to execute his pitches and
he understands his game plan as it relates to the hitters and the
situation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
