<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FACTOR IN FOX FOULS: LOSING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Yes, Rick Fox was frustrated and irritable when he
got himself ejected from the fourth quarter of Sunday's Los Angeles
Lakers disaster in Phoenix. But no, he said, it wasn't about
playing time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I was frustrated because we were losing so bad,'' Fox
said Tuesday, addressing the incident for the first time. ``I mean,
here we were 3-0 in a series and it didn't seem like we came to
play, really. I've seen this before with us, and it's not anything
we should be proud of. It's fight - how much fight do you have in
you? How much pride do you have in you to actually do whatever it
takes to win?
</P>
<P>
   ``And obviously at that point, it was way beyond control, with
three minutes to go. You always want to be in the game. If you want
to say I'm upset because I'm not in the game, I'd like to play 40
minutes. That hasn't been the case all year. Wanting to be out
there was definitely something on my mind, and then once I got out
there, wanting it to be more than just being out there running up
and down the court for the last three minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   So instead of standing there, Fox wrapped up Clifford Robinson
twice, each time drawing a technical foul from referee Joey
Crawford, and thus an automatic ejection. But Fox disagreed with
Crawford's decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The fouls) were given intentionally, but that doesn't warrant
being kicked out of the game,'' he said. ``I didn't try to disrupt
or instigate anything. You just sit and watch Cliff Robinson and
Jason Kidd and the rest of those guys for 48 minutes run through
you, and it gets kind of tiresome watching. There comes a point
where you have to do something about it. If they're going to just
score as easy as they've been scoring all day, I'd rather let them
feel it a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Defensive: Coach Phil Jackson was pleased to see both Shaquille
O'Neal and Kobe Bryant garner votes in the Defensive Player of the
Year balloting, released Tuesday. O'Neal (21 votes) finished a
distant second to Miami's Alonzo Mourning (62), and Bryant got four
votes to tie Seattle's Gary Payton for fifth place.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great,'' Jackson said of O'Neal's second-place finish.
``I think it registers ... his improvement this year as basketball
player, a complete basketball player.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson seemed to disagree with Mourning as the top vote-getter.
``Alonzo blocks shots, I guess that's what counts. (Atlanta's
Dikembe) Mutombo blocks a lot of shots, he used to be the guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Of Bryant receiving as many votes as Payton - regarded as the
best backcourt defender in the league - Jackson said, ``That
surprised me a little bit. This is a very active player whose
disruptive ability is quite noticeable on the floor, and his
attention has grown so much this year, his focus and concentration
are much better.''
</P>
<P>
   Bryant previously was named to the All-Defensive first team.
O'Neal made the second team.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
