<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 10:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7444 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-YOUNG-COLUMN18-COX     05-17 0627
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: The almighty 'mute'
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ The National Organization for Women is urging
letters and calls to ABC to squelch any temptation it might have of
putting the spore monster of radio, Rush Limbaugh, on ``Monday
Night Football.''
</P>
<P>
   Limbaugh is hot for the TV job. ABC is silent, maybe because
this trial balloon has proved so leaden.
</P>
<P>
   I'm solidly on NOW's side in this taste test. But I can deal
with Rush in this and any manifestation.
</P>
<P>
   Let's say, worst case, Rush gets the job. Do I do a write-in?
No, I do a mute-on. One jab of my remote and Rush becomes a
pointless mime. TV sound off, I then turn the radio dial to the
nearest CBS Radio affiliate for the play-by-play to go with ABC's
pictures. Ta-ta, Rush.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the job of zeroing out three hours of self-inflated
blowhard isn't what the mute was invented for. For that, a walk
from recliner to the TV is a trip well-invested.
</P>
<P>
   We know the essential mission of the mute: to zero-out incessant
sales pitches.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of sales pitches, the remote control looms as a major
force in the 2000 elections.
</P>
<P>
   We may have seen the mute at work in the New Hampshire
Republican primary. George W. Bush spent millions to program his
way into TV viewers' hearts as (a) the real conservative; (b) the
real reformer; or (c) Colin Powell.
</P>
<P>
   New Hampshire voters, including cross-over Democrats, and
independents, chose (d) John McCain.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts wondered how someone like Bush, with so much money to
spend on focus-group-crafted TV commercials, could fail to click
with broad-based voters/viewers.
</P>
<P>
   The culprit was their clickers.
</P>
<P>
   The remote. Can it render political commercials moot? All that
well-crafted imagery? All those French horns and violins? All that
enlightening, life-changing information jammed into 30 seconds? All
those nasty attacks? All for naught? Nice thought.
</P>
<P>
   A mute is a wonderful thing. A mute is a powerful thing. And,
though once a novelty, the mute has become a pervasive thing.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Remote Central, a clearinghouse on remote
controls of all kinds, confirmed that remotes and mutes are a
novelty no more. Virtually all new TVs have them. Bad news for
candidates. Good news for democracy.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe campaign commercials can help a candidate, but they look
more and more like a dubious investment.
</P>
<P>
   In New Hampshire, McCain profited from getting in front of lots
and lots of real audiences. Bush quickly figured he had better do
the same.
</P>
<P>
   In the months ahead we will see candidates try to manipulate
opinion with TV spots and attack ads, but the result of it all _
the lion's share of all that campaign money for which so many
favors are pledged _ will be barely neglible. Credit the mute.
</P>
<P>
   As the campaign winds down, what will sway the undecided won't
be stuff pasteurized by a TV guru. What will count will be
presidential debates, issues coverage in print and on the air _ you
know, what voters choose to supplement what they know.
</P>
<P>
   The mute is a button of choice. The mute is democracy in action.
It is how discriminating viewers screen out ways to program their
behavior.
</P>
<P>
   So, candidates: Stick to issues. Debate freely and often. Choose
real audiences over studios.
</P>
<P>
   If you expect to get your message out to America by wedging it
between ``Friends'' and ``Frazier,'' we have bad news for you.
</P>
<P>
   As for Limbaugh's chances for a Monday Night Football slot, one
could say that ``remote'' is a most apt characterization.
</P>
<P>
   John Young is opinion page editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald. He
can be reached at jyoung(at)wacotrib.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
