<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 10:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7445 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-JEFFERSON-COLUMN18-CO     05-17 0692
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JEFFERSON-COLUMN18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Hate is an equal-opportunity killer
 &HT;    By Stebbins Jefferson
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's an ages-old lottery going on. Don't despair that you
haven't bought a ticket. You already have one. You were born with
it.
</P>
<P>
   Admittedly, your chances of winning the big jackpot are
astronomical. Be assured, however, that there will be winners. The
lottery that I refer to is the chance that someone consumed by
intense hatred of your kind could target you for violence _ for no
reason other than your racial or ethnic identity.
</P>
<P>
   That's what happened April 28 in Mount Lebanon, Pa., an upscale
suburb of Pittsburgh. Around noon, Richard Baumhammers, the son of
Latvian immigrants, went next-door and shot a 63-year-old Jewish
woman, Anita Gordon, who had been a lifelong neighbor and close
friend of his parents'. He then went to her nearby synagogue, shot
out the front windows and painted red swastikas on the building.
</P>
<P>
   With that act, the 34-year-old immigration attorney began a
shooting spree that spanned two counties. Within about two hours,
he had killed five people and critically wounded one.
</P>
<P>
   At a grocery, two Indian immigrants, 31 and 24, were shot, one
fatally. Next, Baumhammers gunned down two Asian men who worked at
a restaurant. About a half-hour later, he killed a 22-year-old
black man at a karate school.
</P>
<P>
   With the exception of Ms. Gordon, Baumhammers didn't know his
victims. He seems to have chosen targets based on their ethnic
minority identities. Witnesses to the slaughter in the restaurant
say the gunman took aim, fired and calmly walked away.
</P>
<P>
   In court Tuesday for his arraignment, he smiled and remained
tranquil. Dr. Christine Martone, the court-ordered psychiatrist who
had spent 83 minutes with him over two days, diagnosed him as a
paranoid schizophrenic who is unfit to stand trial. ``Auditory
delusions,'' she said, cause him to hear voices. Common Pleas Court
Judge Lawrence O'Toole withheld his ruling on motions to
institutionalize Baumhammers until he receives the results of
another psychological evaluation.
</P>
<P>
   Baumhammers has a history of mental illness. At one point, he
had been prescribed psychotropic drugs. In this regard, he has a
lot in common with fellow Allegheny County resident Ronald Taylor,
39, a black man who in March went on a shooting spree during which
he killed three white men and wounded two others. If we still need
proof that hatred is an equal-opportunity killer, these gunmen
provide it.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor also has since been diagnosed as schizophrenic with a
history of mental illness. In other words, these men _ one white,
one black _ are ``sick.''
</P>
<P>
   To salve our consciences, I fear we all too conveniently apply
this term to crimes motivated by race hatred. Or, when a single
victim is involved, we dismiss such crimes as an inevitable
byproduct of the times we live in, in which violence is
commonplace, predictable and inevitable. But killing sprees with
multiple, random victims violate our tenuous hold on a sense of
public safety.
</P>
<P>
   When hatred of ``the other'' is so virulent as to become the
singular focus of the sick mind, we should ask ourselves what
perverted logic built the ticking hate-bomb. Is it possible that
the ingredients were tiny expressions of hate, each in itself
relatively harmless? Was it an ethnic slur delivered in jest? A
negative stereotype casually dismissing others' humanity? Or _ most
potent of all _ daily consideration of color above all other human
attributes in all matters and decisions?
</P>
<P>
   Consciously or subconsciously, we all buy into these acts from
time to time. We continue to claim sanity because we stop short of
physically assaulting each other. We understand that in American
society, polite ethnic and racial hatred is standard civil
protocol, tacitly encouraged and usually tolerated.
</P>
<P>
   That's why we say Baumhammers and Taylor are sick. They didn't
have enough sense to know this lottery has rules.
</P>
<P>
   Stebbins Jefferson is a columnist for The Palm Beach Post.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
