<P>
   DEM-CONVENTION (Sacramento, Calif.) _ As activists around the
country secure lawyers and plan for massive demonstrations at the
Democratic National Convention, California Gov. Gray Davis is
asking the Legislature for $4.1 million so police can pay overtime
and buy equipment in preparation for potential riots, vandalism or
terrorism. By ROBERT SALLADAY.
</P>
<P>
   ARCHBISHOP-GAYS (San Francisco) _ San Francisco's Catholic
Archbishop William Levada says he was misquoted in the May 11
edition of the popular Roman newspaper Il Messaggero. Levada
allegedly criticized plans for a gay march in Rome in July because
it coincides with the Catholic Church's millennial Jubilee
celebration. By CAROL NESS.
</P>
<P>
   JUDGE-ROADBLOCK (El Paso, Texas) _ It's the classic American
success story: The Mexico-born son of immigrant parents graduates
from Harvard, forges a successful legal career and makes this Texas
border city proud when the president nominates him to the 5th U.S.
Circuit Court of Appeals. There, the story of Enrique Moreno hits a
roadblock. Two Republican senators are thwarting the nomination on
the grounds that Moreno lacks the experience for such a high bench.
By PEGGY FIKAC.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   B2B-STOCKS (San Francisco) _ Uneasy lies the head that wears the
Internet crown. Mere months after the business-to-business, or B2B,
e-commerce sector was anointed as the latest successor to the
cyberspace throne, analysts and investors alike are stepping back
and taking a more tempered view of it. By ALAN T. SARACEVIC.
</P>
<P>
   B2B-EXEC (San Francisco) _ The siren song of B2B Internet
business is wafting through even the biggest, most established
corporations, luring top-drawer talent away from blue-chip firms.
Case in point: Mei-ling Cheng, the former chief information officer
at Hewlett-Packard Co., has jumped to Net newcomer WineExchange.com
to become its chief technology officer. By DAVID ARMSTRONG.
</P>
<P>
   SBC-DSL (San Francisco) _ A national arbitration board has
slapped at $27.2 million judgment against SBC Communications,
parent company of Pacific Bell, for not delivering equipment and
space to DSL provider Covad Communications Group in a timely manner
_ a violation of the Telecommunications Act of 1996. By VANESSA
HUA.
</P>
<P>
   AUTO-OFF-ROAD (White Sulphur Springs, W.Va.) _ Nestled in the
Allegheny range of the Appalachians, the Land Rover Driving School
offers visitors a chance to learn the basics of off-road driving on
trails carved out of hardwood forests among some of the most scenic
mountain vistas on the North American continent. By G. CHAMBERS
WILLIAMS III.
</P>
<P>
   SF-C-OF-C (San Francisco) _ On April 10, 1850, the Alta
California newspaper ran a brief item regarding the founding
fathers of San Francisco business. According to the paper's report,
a gathering of local businessmen met ``in the fine room in Ward's
Court . . . to take into consideration the propriety of
establishing a Board of Trade.'' Thus was born the San Francisco
Chamber of Commerce 150 years ago. By ALAN T. SARACEVIC.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SUMMER-MOVIES (Undated) _ The calendar tells us it isn't summer
yet. For that, we have to wait until June 21. But Hollywood has
different ideas about the tilt of Earth and the passage of time,
and for its purposes, the hot season has already arrived _ with
``Gladiator,'' ``Mission: Impossible 2,'' and more. We look at
upcoming movies. By AMY BIANCOLLI.
</P>
<P>
   TV-COLUMN (Undated) _ In a move that should surprise no one
following the desperate and lucky adventures of ABC, the network
announced that it will spray ``Who Wants To Be a Millionaire''
around the schedule on four nights instead of three, thus using the
most powerful weapon in its arsenal to get ratings. By TIM GOODMAN.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD (``d'' category)
</P>
<P>
   WINE-COLUMN (Houston) _ Maybe you do like a glass of wine with
dinner, but you really don't care so much about where it comes from
as you do how much it costs and will it go with tonight's meatloaf.
Today's list includes widely available wines that may not set the
world on fire but that are consistently well-made. And not
expensive, either. By MICHAEL LONSFORD.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPFIRE-STEW (San Antonio) _ Using leftovers from around the
campfire, here is a recipe for a venison stew that can served over
boiled potatoes or noodles. By RALPH WININGHAM.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   OLY-SAILING (San Antonio) _ San Antonio's ``Bullet Lasagna''
sailing star recently left his heart on San Francisco Bay. In a
grueling eight-day, 16-race regatta, Mattia D'Errico confronted
choppy seas, tricky currents and the best of America's one-man,
small-craft skippers. In the end, he finished 18th out of 32 in the
Laser class of the U.S. Olympic Trials for sailing, falling short
of his Olympic dream for the second time. By JERRY BRIGGS.
