<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 11:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7469 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-MA-ECONOMY-ART-2TAKES     05-17 1109
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-ECONOMY-ART-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OVERHEATING CAUSES JITTERS IN BAY STATE 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS  
 (ART ADV.: A photo and a graphic are being sent to NYTNS clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchases by calling
888-346-9867 or 888-603-1036.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ As in the 1980s boom, signs of economic excess are
spreading across Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   The job market is stretched as tight as piano wire. Office rents
in prime locations in Cambridge have leapfrogged over Manhattan
rents. Housing prices, even in Central Massachusetts, have risen
beyond the grasp of middle-class families.
</P>
<P>
   And all eyes are on the teetering stock market, which has begun
to hit star companies like CMGI Inc., the Andover-based dot-com
giant that announced more layoffs last week.
</P>
<P>
   Some economists are worrying aloud that these might be
harbingers of unsustainable growth in Massachusetts, growth that
would dramatically reverse itself if the stock market were to
plummet or the high-flying technology industry were to crash to
earth. Is the state economy again ``overheated'' and at risk of
collapsing as it did in the late 1980s, when minicomputers, real
estate, and defense folded like a three-cheese souffle?
</P>
<P>
   This time the excesses are being driven by different industries
than in the 1980s, but the comeuppance, warns David Birch, a
business economist in Cambridge, could be the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``When this falls apart, we're going to be right back where we
were in 1990 and 1991,'' he said last week. ``We're destined to be
wiped out again.''
</P>
<P>
   Economists around the state are hunkered in front of their
computers, poring over charts and statistics. The question everyone
_ corporate executives, state government officials, union leaders,
workers, consumers _ most want answered is whether the
platinum-lined economy of Massachusetts' boom contains a big gray
cloud.
</P>
<P>
   But even the Cassandras, with their pessimistic prophesies,
cannot ignore how much has changed since the crash of the late
1980s, when a few giant companies _ Digital Equipment Corp., Data
General Corp., and Wang Laboratories Inc. _ had accounted for much
of the economic activity of the state. Their technology became
outmoded, and Massachusetts at its depths sustained 100,000 layoffs
in a single month, January 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Eliot Winer, the state government's chief economist who has
tracked Massachusetts for 30 years, is among those who argue that
the rebuilding that occurred during the 1990s, as the nation
experienced an unprecedented expansion, has made the state's
economy far more resilient and immune to collapse than it once was.
</P>
<P>
   ``The difference nowadays, compared to when we had a strong
economy in the 1980s, is the diversity. We're not as dependent on
any one sector,'' Winer said. ``If we had problems in the stock
market and the financial sector, it wouldn't have that dramatic an
effect.''
</P>
<P>
   The evidence is pervasive. The state's technology industry,
which once revolved around minicomputers, is now a rainbow of small
firms, writing software, transporting data over the Internet, and
developing drugs.
</P>
<P>
   While much has been made of tiny dot-com firms with Fortune
500-level stock prices but no profits, most of the state's
technology firms are profitable and are adapting quickly to
breathtaking change brought by the Internet and other technological
breakthroughs. Cisco Systems Inc., Sun Microsystems and Amgen Inc.
are based in California, and all are establishing beachheads in
Massachusetts that employ thousands. Taunton-based Kopin Corp.,
which makes components used in cell phones, announced last week
that it would open a new plant and double its payroll, to 500, by
year-end.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see a world of difference between today's economy and that
of the 1980s,'' said Sara Johnson, economist for Standard &AMP; Poor's
DRI, a consulting firm. ``Today, we have an economy that's driven
by small innovative companies.''
</P>
<P>
   Growth of the mutual fund and brokerage industries, which now
employ 63,600 in Massachusetts, has been a powerful force
propelling the economy during the great bull market of the 1990s.
But the services industry since 1984 has added 407,300 jobs and
employs more than 1 million in the state _ one-third of all
workers. Boston has always been a hub for ``knowledge-based''
firms, ranging from law, advertising, and accounting firms to
medical, engineering, and architectural firms. But business
services also include corner dry cleaners and copy shops. Services,
economists said, tend to be less sensitive to economic cycles than
manufacturing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The basic underpinnings of the economy,'' said Karl Case, an
economics professor at Wellesley College, ``are more diversified
and are healthier than they were in '89.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A textile mill straddling the Assabet River in Maynard is a
microcosm of Massachusetts' economy. Some of the tenants are
dot-com companies.
</P>
<P>
   The mill was once headquarters for Digital, which moved out amid
a 1998 acquisition by Compaq Computer Corp. The sprawling mill was
purchased 2 1/2 years ago by developers who quickly leased most of
its 1 million square feet of office space to some 80 tenants.
</P>
<P>
   One is Peanutpress.com. Founders Jeff Strobel and Mark Reichelt
devised encryption software so publishers could sell rights to
download books or newspapers into Palm Pilots. In four months,
Peanutpress.com has hired eight employees and moved into one of the
tiny brick-and-beam offices lining the mill's maze-like walkways.
Regardless of where the Nasdaq tech-stock index may be headed,
Strobel said he believes the potential audience of Palm Pilot
readers is enormous. ``If we can get somebody to try one of our
books, customers get hooked really quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   The mill's tenants include a flute maker, Verne Q. Powell Flutes
Inc., consultants such as Wilson Group, which helps clients develop
compensation programs for employees, and Payright Payroll Services
Inc., which handles payrolls for small companies.
</P>
<P>
   Philip O'Brien started Payright in 1989, just as the state
economy went into a slump. His timing was bad, but he persisted. He
now has eight employees serving 450 clients, from Dunkin' Donuts
franchises to the American Textile Museum. He has attracted dot-com
clients in the mill and set up a Web site to serve them,
Payrightpayroll .com.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you asked me six months ago, I would have said this won't
happen for a few years,'' said O'Brien, 51, who has begun to wear
the khaki pants that are the uniform in the dot-com world. ``Things
are happening that quick here.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
