<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 11:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7470 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-AUTHOR-KOZOL-2TAKES-A     05-17 1436
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTHOR-KOZOL-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 JONATHAN KOZOL HAS MADE EDUCATION REFORM HIS LIFE'S WORK 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-ART-BOS  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK FEENEY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ ``It's been a quiet life,'' Jonathan Kozol says,
sitting on a bench in the South End, a block away from the site of
what was once the Storefront Learning Center, an alternative ``free
school'' he helped found and run three decades ago.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, ``quiet'' is a relative term.
</P>
<P>
   It's been a quiet life for the Kozol who lives alone in a small
18th-century house in Byfield, 30 miles north of Boston, with his
golden retriever, Sweetie Pie.
</P>
<P>
   Kozol, who has been known to spend up to 14 hours a day writing,
jokes that, ``My research assistant, if she hasn't heard from me
for a few days, will sometimes call the post office to ask them to
make sure I'm still alive.''
</P>
<P>
   It's also been quiet for the Kozol who, over the past seven
years, has visited Mott Haven, the poorest part of the poorest
section of New York, the South Bronx, more than 200 times. He has
written a pair of books about the neighborhood and its children,
``Amazing Grace'' (1995) and the just-published ``Ordinary
Resurrections.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of the children look on him as an auxiliary father,''
says Mother Martha Overall, who as pastor of St. Ann's Episcopal
Church figures prominently in ``Ordinary Resurrections.''
</P>
<P>
   It's been anything but quiet for the Kozol who for almost 40
years has worked tirelessly as an education reformer and advocate
for the disadvantaged. Such books as ``Illiterate America'' (1985),
``Rachel and Her Children'' (1988), about homelessness, ``Savage
Inequalities'' (1991), about school funding, and the two books
about Mott Haven have maintained his reputation as one of America's
foremost social critics.
</P>
<P>
   ``You cannot read him without feeling a call to action,'' says
Robert R. Spillane, superintendent of Boston schools from 1981-1985
and now a regional officer with the US Department of State's Office
of Overseas Schools.
</P>
<P>
   Kozol's best-known work, ``Death at an Early Age'' (1967), an
account of his year teaching fourth grade at a public school in
Dorchester, won a National Book Award and stirred more controversy
in this city than perhaps any title published since Boston stopped
banning books.
</P>
<P>
   ``Uncompromising,'' not ``quiet,'' would be a better word to
describe such a life. Paul Parks, former state secretary of
education and a founder of the Metropolitan Council for Educational
Opportunity, knows that Kozol well. ``Jonathan has never been a
politician _ not even close!'' Parks says with a laugh. ``We knew
that, and we wouldn't let him negotiate. He wasn't going to yield
any point.''
</P>
<P>
   That unwillingness to yield has won Kozol both admirers and
detractors, but not many victories. ``Where do you put an idealist
who doesn't have practical ideas?'' asks Douglas J. Besharov,
director of the American Enterprise Institute's Social and
Individual Responsibility Project.
</P>
<P>
   ``If more people were like Jonathan Kozol, it would be a better
world. But are his ideas about what causes poverty and disadvantage
correct? . . . The weight of authority is against him. . . . I
don't think he has a large voice in liberal-left policymaking.''
</P>
<P>
   Kozol, 63, remains undimmed in his idealism. Energetic and
medium-sized, he hunches his shoulders and leans forward when he
walks. It's the posture of a man on a mission.
</P>
<P>
   He has a sad, slightly hang-dog face _ but one capable of
breaking into a surprisingly impish smile. There's something almost
boyish about Kozol: the way he combines enthusiasm and openness,
his delight in small details of everyday life. Ordering coffee, he
sees a display of glazed doughnuts. They look so good, he asks for
two. Or there's the way his face lights up as he walks through the
South End, pointing out landmarks from the 20 years he spent living
in the neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   Kozol gives his complete attention to whatever he's saying. The
subject can be charter schools (about which he has misgivings) or
an all-night drugstore on Columbus Avenue, Braddock Pharmacy (for
which he has nothing but praise); Kozol gets equally caught up in
each. When it's pointed out that he's neglected to drink any of his
coffee, he shakes his head and grins. ``Oh, I do that all the
time.'' He never does get around to the doughnuts.
</P>
<P>
   Kozol grew up in just outside of Boston, in Newton. His parents
are in their 90s. Dr. Harry L. Kozol, a founder of the field of
forensic psychiatry (he testified as a government witness in the
Patty Hearst trial), suffers from Alzheimer's disease. Ruth Kozol
devotes her time to rooting for the Red Sox (as Kozol points out,
she can actually remember when they last won the World Series) and
looking out for her son. ``She's still trying to match me up,'' he
laughs. ``She has some lovely nurses taking care of her, and every
so often she'll say to me, `It's not too late!' '' Kozol, who was
married for five years during the 1970s, is childless.
</P>
<P>
   He graduated from the Noble and Greenough School and then
flourished at Harvard. An English major, he studied with the poet
Archibald MacLeish, the novelist John Hawkes, and the literary
critics Harry Levin and Richard Poirier. (Kozol had equally starry
friends: Joseph Lelyveld, now executive editor of The New York
Times, was a freshman roommate; a future US senator, Jay
Rockefeller, lived across the hall.) He graduated summa cum laude
in 1958 and won a Rhodes Scholarship.
</P>
<P>
   Kozol stayed less than a year at Oxford. ``I'd had such an
intense education at Nobles and Harvard I found the atmosphere at
Oxford immature, less serious. I went to Paris. I've never
regretted that.''
</P>
<P>
   Literature, not activism, first attracted Kozol. He had already
published a novel, ``The Fume of Poppies'' (1958), about an
undergraduate romance _ he later dismissed it as ``my toy novel'' _
and in Paris the expatriate novelist James Jones adopted him. Kozol
became friends with William Styron and James Baldwin and one
evening literally bumped into Richard Wright in a Left Bank
bookstore.
</P>
<P>
   In 1963, he abandoned the novel he'd been writing about his
grandparents, Jewish immigrants from Russia, and returned to
Cambridge. Uncertain about his future, Kozol spent the next 18
months at loose ends. One day, during the Freedom Summer of 1964,
he saw a Congress of Racial Equality flier in Harvard Square.
Kozol, who was so apolitical he'd never heard of CORE, took the
subway to Roxbury to volunteer. ``That was the hardest thing I ever
did in my life,'' he says. Within a week, he'd led a successful
rent strike.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly thereafter, the former Rhodes Scholar was a ``permanent
substitute'' in the Boston public schools earning the princely sum
of $3,600 a year. He was assigned to the predominantly black
Christopher Gibson School. Kozol's ``classroom'' was the school
auditorium, which his class had to share with three others. The
cellar smelled of urine. One day a large window fell, nearly
hitting several children. Students were sometimes beaten with a
rattan.
</P>
<P>
   Ten days before the end of the school year, Kozol _ who by all
accounts had proven himself a gifted and dedicated teacher _ was
fired for ``curriculum deviation'': He'd read his class a Langston
Hughes poem. Outraged parents picketed and held sit-ins to protest
his dismissal.
</P>
<P>
   That was nothing compared to what happened when ``Death at an
Early Age'' was published two years later. Released at the height
of the Kevin White-Louise Day Hicks mayoral race, it sold a
thousand copies a day in the city and was serialized in the Globe.
The book ``really caused some aggravation in Boston,'' Spillane
says with a dry chuckle. ``It was a bombshell, definitely,'' adds
Parks. A city that prided itself on Horace Mann and the Boston
Latin School suddenly found its school system portrayed as racist,
decrepit, and incompetent. The fury ``Death at an Early Age''
inspired was some small foretaste of the response that would greet
court-ordered desegregation seven years later.
</P>
<P>
   Kozol had found his calling. The teacher who wasn't good enough
for the Boston public schools was hired as a consultant by the US
Office of Education. He also helped develop an alternative school
in Roxbury and spent two years teaching fifth grade in Newton. By
then, he'd moved to the South End. ``Making the reverse commute,''
he notes, ``I felt like a METCO kid myself!''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
