<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 11:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7471 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u d BC-FOOD-CORDON-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAKE     05-17 1036
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-CORDON-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 LONGON: ... what I did.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Possibilities in a food career were practically nonexistent for
a woman when I attended the Cordon Bleu. No one understood why I
was going. My sharp-tongued college roommate told a mutual friend
that I was moving to Europe to train as a maid.
</P>
<P>
   I had never heard of the school before I met English-born Anne
Willan (see related story), who had gone there. She was food editor
of the Washington Star newspaper, and I was a dictationist in the
newsroom. When Anne left the Star to freelance, she took me with
her.
</P>
<P>
   She had a contract to Americanize The Cordon Bleu Cookery
Course, a popular British cooking partwork (a slim magazine sold
weekly on newsstands _ this one had 100,000 readers). It became
``The Grand Diplome Cooking Course.'' I learned cooking, writing,
and food styling. For what, I wasn't sure.
</P>
<P>
   When the ``Grand Diplome'' project was nearing an end, Anne
said, ``If you want to write about cookery, you'll have to become a
cook. No one will ever ask a sportswriter whether he can play his
sport, but someday someone will ask you whether you can cook.'' She
called London and insisted that my name move to the top of their
waiting list. She also told me that as a bonus for three years'
work, she and her husband, Mark Cherniavsky, an economist at the
World Bank, were paying the tuition for cooking school and giving
me enough extra cash to cover the airfare and initial expenses. I
was stunned by their generosity.
</P>
<P>
   On the first day, we received soft nylon caps to go with our
white smocks and blue oilcloth aprons (you couldn't wipe your hands
on them). We were paired up and shown the kitchens. A community
refrigerator sat at one end of the room, and one sink served many
students. It cured me forever of the American habit of chopping
near the sink.
</P>
<P>
   That first lunch was pretty silly. I was sure that this
cooking-school thing was a big mistake. We made ``jacket potatoes''
(read: baked).
</P>
<P>
   It got better quickly. We cooked lunch and ate at the little
stations. We dipped our fingers into the whipped cream bowl and all
gained weight together. The girls taught each other the Sabrina
egg. They managed to convince me that all the leftover food _ main
courses, breads, and desserts _ were delivered to the neighboring
convent, where the nuns combined everything (even the sweets) in
one pot and reheated it for the poor.
</P>
<P>
   Director Gray says all the food did go to the convent until
English health and hygiene laws prevented them from doing that. I
don't have the courage to ask her about the desserts being mixed
with the meat. The convent benefited from the school's renovation,
however. Even though the nuns would no longer receive leftover
lunch from the girls, they were given the school's freezer packed
with food.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Aspics and lard crusts
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   We cooked mainly from the ``Penguin Cordon Bleu Cookery,'' by
the school's co-principals Rosemary Hume and Muriel Downes. I
stayed longer than I had planned, moving from the ``certificate''
course to the advanced class. Years later, I learned that Lydia
Shire, who owns Biba and Pignoli, had done the certificate course a
few years earlier (she took the name Biba from an avant-garde
London store of the time whose clothes she loved).
</P>
<P>
   Shire remembers making English steamed puddings and wondering
when she would ever make them again. ``Now steamed puddings are
very fashionable,'' she says. ``I loved my time there. I thought it
was great.'' Returning a few years ago, she thought the place
seemed cold.
</P>
<P>
   Besides puddings and other English specialties, we learned
classic French cooking and Indian dishes. So deep-dish meat pies
topped with lard crusts were on the curriculum, as well as homemade
curry powder. Then we did things like kedgeree, crazy but charming
British corruptions of Indian food. We made sautes, aspics, pates,
all the important sauces like hollandaise and demi-glace, puff
pastry, and ice cream. We boned our own fish, poultry, and meat.
</P>
<P>
   The advanced course was hard, but we worked together in a large
kitchen down the street from the school. There was a beautiful old
Aga, the coal-fed Swedish cooker. Victoria Proctor, a no-nonsense
woman who had lived through the war and reminded us about it,
taught the course. During lean times, she said, her family ate
pastry made with the solidified fat from the surface of chicken
broth. She had a thing about waste. She would run her fingers
through our scrap bowl and reprimand anyone who trimmed her
vegetables more than necessary.
</P>
<P>
   One day, I heard my name cracking through the air of the large
kitchen. ``Miss Julian!'' she screeched.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, ma'am!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything is wrong,'' she hissed. ``Your custard is wrong. I
don't like the way you're holding the spoon. That's not the way to
hold the pan. And it's the wrong pan!
</P>
<P>
   ``And one more thing, Miss Julian.'' By this time Mrs. Proctor's
very pronounced nose was leaning precariously close to my skunk
eyes. ``Never address anyone in England as `ma'am,' '' she said.
``Unless you're talking to the queen.''
</P>
<P>
   I made it to the end. Mrs. Proctor even managed a compliment
before she sent me off.
</P>
<P>
   Paris was next, again at Anne Willan's encouragement.
Surprisingly, I didn't like the classes at the Cordon Bleu there as
much as I had in London. Except for a fabulous pastry chef, the
others didn't seem to love teaching.
</P>
<P>
   By the time I returned home to America, I had been away a year.
I had adopted the Paris uniform: navy skirt and navy cardigan. My
hair was in a topknot, and I was thin. No more skunk eyes.
</P>
<P>
   One day while I was visiting friends, the college roommate who
never had a nice thing to say stopped by. ``Are you Sabrina yet?''
she asked. I pulled out a bowl, took an egg in my right hand,
tapped it against the edge of the bowl, then used the thumb and
ring finger of the same hand to open the bottom of the shell.
</P>
<P>
   The egg tumbled into the bowl. And I could hear the girls in
London giggling.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Le Cordon Bleu London is located at 114 Marylebone Lane, London W1M
6HH, England. Telephone 011-44-20-7935-3503. Fax
011-44-20-7935-7621. E-mail london(at)cordonbleu.net.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
