<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONJOBS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIVING KIDS A SAFE PLACE ONLINE AMONG NEW WORK BENEFITS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE E. LEWIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With so many kids hooked on computers, some employers are
looking to offer a new benefit to employees whose children are
connected to the Net: secure Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   Seventy-five percent of all parents with children in grades K
through 8 have computers, and 62 percent are linked to the
Internet, according to a recent Newsweek/Kaplan Poll.
</P>
<P>
   Two companies, national daycare chain Bright Horizons of
Cambridge, Mass. and Bell Atlantic Corp., are exploring ways to
ease employees' concerns about their children's online exploration.
</P>
<P>
   For several weeks, Bright Horizons has been reviewing a product
called KOLA, or Kids on Line America. Developed by a California
start-up with the same name, the KOLA Web site offers programming
and live, monitored chat rooms.
</P>
<P>
   Employers offering the service must register the names,
addresses, and telephone numbers of employees who join through the
company. Once they are enrolled, employees are given access to
``closed'' chat rooms available only to other employees at a
particular firm, school, or daycare center. Programs and chats for
children and teens are scheduled weekly and are monitored regularly
by the service.
</P>
<P>
   Bell Atlantic is expected to launch a test of the same service
in June, according Fred Jenkins, director of human resource
communications and work/life strategies. Employees will be offered
KOLA free of charge, on a first-come, first-served basis. In all,
800 employees in New England, New York, and the mid-Atlantic states
will test the service next month.
</P>
<P>
   ``The plan is to offer it to employees for two months before
deciding whether the service will actually benefit our employees,''
said Jenkins.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which employs 130,000 in 13 states and the District
of Columbia, decided to try the program on an experimental basis
after its human resource managers received calls from workers
worried about their children's safety.
</P>
<P>
   How does the service work? Companies can either purchase it for
employees or pay a portion of the costs. If a company won't pay, a
group of employees can sign up directly through KOLA and pay the
monthly fee.
</P>
<P>
   Bright Horizons, a limited investor, says it plans to offer the
benefit to employees at its centers and to its corporate clients in
June for $3.95 per month per employee, excluding Internet access.
In September, families with children enrolled at Bright Horizons'
centers will be offered the same service for the same fee. The
total cost of the service, plus Internet access: $19.99 per month.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the dangers of having children involved in chat is that
you really do not know who they're speaking to,'' said David Lissy,
chief development officer at Bright Horizons. ``But knowing that
the company that offers the service has also prequalified the
parents or members gave us some confidence, because participants
can find out who's in the chat room with their kids. And parents
can make some editorial decisions about the kind of access they
want their children to have.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, there is no fool-proof way of guaranteeing something
bad won't happen while your kids are logged on. Hiring a service to
provide closed chat sites and monitoring is one approach, but it
can't replace parental guidelines or rules. Blocks or screens such
as Cyber Patrol and Net Nanny can also help by steering kids away
from inappropriate information and adult-only sites.
</P>
<P>
   While it's still too early to tell whether large numbers of
employees will take advantage of Internet monitoring services,
statistics from a May 2000 survey by Hewitt Associates, the
international benefits consulting firm, show that companies have
significantly increased their use of other soft benefits in an
ongoing push to retain _ and attract _ top staff.
</P>
<P>
   When Illinois-based Hewitt Associates surveyed 1,020 US firms,
it found 74 percent now offer flexible work schedules, up from 66
percent in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   The most widely used benefit? Child care assistance. Of the
firms polled, 90 percent provide some type of assistance to workers
with young children, ranging from dependent care spending accounts
(88 percent) to help employees pay for daycare with pre-tax
dollars, onsite daycare, or child-care slots at nearby community
centers.
</P>
<P>
   The fastest growing service? Elder care. In all, 47 percent of
employers now provide the benefit, up from 24 percent in 1994.
Approximately 32 percent offer dependent spending accounts, 40
percent have contracted with research and referral firms, 17
percent provide long-term care insurance, and 4 percent provide
individual counseling to workers struggling with the emotional
strain of caring for a sick or frail parent.
</P>
<P>
   And demand for elder care is expected to rise, according to The
Conference Board, a New York research group, which reports that the
need for such benefits will outstrip the demand for child care by
2003.
</P>
<P>
   In all, 25 percent of US workers were caring for an ailing or
frail parent four years ago, says the Families and Work Institute.
Next year, 42 percent of an estimted 9 million employees will be
engaged in some form of elder care, ranging from essential tasks
such as meals and personal care to assisting aging parents with
bills or driving them to medical appointments.
</P>
<P>
   Now that the first wave of baby boomers is over 50, the number
of workers requiring elder care benefits will grow to one in three
adults over the next two decades and the majority of the caregivers
will be women.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Only 30 percent of the graduate students enrolled at US business
schools are women, says Catalyst, the New York women's research
group. By contrast, 44 percent of the students at medical and law
schools are now women.
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to shed more light on why fewer women are seeking MBAs,
Catalyst polled some 850 female graduates from a dozen of the
nation's top business schools. The poll had a margin of error of
2.4. Among the results: 56 percent of the participants said women
were more apt to shy away from business school because of a lack of
female faculty role models; 47 percent mentioned that women are
still struggling to fully balance work-life demands; 45 percent
said women have less confidence in their math skills; and 42
percent said working women interested in pursuing business degrees
are less likely to receive encouragement from employers.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Diane E. Lewis can be reached at 617-929-2069, by e-mail at
work(at)globe.com, or at The Boston Globe, Box 2378, Boston, MA
02107-2378.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
