<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 11:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7473 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-AUTHOR-KOZOL-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAK     05-17 1068
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTHOR-KOZOL-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 BOSTON: ... kid myself!''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   These were heady times for Kozol. Young, articulate, and
increasingly radical, he was now something of a '60s icon. He
helped run the Storefront Learning Center for three years, an
experience that inspired a how-to guide for educational reformers,
``Free Schools'' (1972). His writing became more polemical, as
evinced by his next two books, ``The Night Is Dark and I Am Far
From Home'' (1975), an indictment of American society and
schooling, and ``Children of the Revolution'' (1978), a paean to
literacy programs in Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Times were changing, though _ and so was the South End. ``I'd
look out the window,'' he says, ``and see a Volkswagen van pull up
and someone who looked alarmingly like me moving in.'' He sold his
house in the mid-'80s and moved to Essex County. First he lived in
Newburyport (``I liked living in a town where William Lloyd
Garrison started out''), then Byfield.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hardest time for me was the Reagan years,'' he says. ``My
dad said to me, in a moment of stentorian disapproval, `You think
you're an intellectual guerrilla commandante, but your soldiers in
blue jeans have gone back to business school.' Around that time I
was offered a position teaching religion and ethics at Exeter, and
some of my books were going out of print. A little later on, in the
late '80s, I found that the public policy debate was no longer
between the left and the right but between the center and the
right. I felt marginalized and was scared.''
</P>
<P>
   He shakes his head.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what firmed up my will not to go to Exeter. One
day I just said to myself, `I don't want to spend the rest of my
life telling rich kids what it was like to work with poor kids when
I was young and brave.' So I said no to that and went to New York .
. . and started to write `Rachel and Her Children.' ''
</P>
<P>
   That book marked a turning point for Kozol. He started to focus
more on people and less on positions. For him, the political has
always been the personal; but in all his recent books, and
``Ordinary Resurrections'' above all, it's the personal that
predominates.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not a day in the South Bronx that I don't at some
point get angry at the terrible injustice that wastes so much of
the promise of these marvelous kids,'' Kozol says. And the
injustice is terrible: Mott Haven has 75 percent unemployment; the
highest rate of maternal AIDS in the United States; and almost
total segregation in its public schools (the student population is
99.8 percent minority). The facts are so appalling, they speak for
themselves _ and free Kozol to concentrate on Pineapple, Elio,
Otto, and the other children whose story ``Ordinary Resurrections''
is.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted this book to be a very gentle book,'' Kozol explains.
``I got sick of angry polemic. I don't like the literary furies
that rip people's guts apart in New York City. So I tried to subdue
my voice. I thought it would be unworthy of the children's
sweetness if I wrote in a strident tone.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always liked gentle rebels,'' he explains, citing as
examples St. Francis of Assisi; Dorothy Day, of the Catholic Worker
movement; the Trappist monk Thomas Merton; and Cesar Chavez, the
farmworker organizer, with whom Kozol worked briefly in the early
'70s.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like rebels who don't lose their sense of humor, who still
take delight in the small details of life, who don't get so caught
up in their own rhetoric they forget about things like licorice
sticks and Crayola crayons. Some of my political friends might
wonder why I'm so interested in those details. But life is not made
up of abstract concepts. . . . The political and spiritual heroes
that I find most invigorating and refreshing are those like Merton
who had a genuinely transcendent vision of a just society but also
took delight in squirrels outside the window.''
</P>
<P>
   All the heroes Kozol names were either clerics or religiously
devout. Again and again, in his conversation as well as in
``Ordinary Resurrections,'' references to the sacred appear. Mother
Overall, the Mott Haven pastor, likens him to the Old Testament
prophet Nathan and, noting Kozol's ``gentle, Biblical way,'' points
out that ``Most people here think he's a member of the clergy.''
</P>
<P>
   Kozol remains resolutely secular, but there is a certain logic
at work here. He has followed a path of almost-clerical vocation
and austerity _ and, his critics would add, unworldliness.
Spirituality is the highest form of idealism, after all; and past a
certain point, the political becomes as much a matter of faith as
principle.
</P>
<P>
   The French poet Charles Peguy said, ``Everything begins in
mysticism and ends in politics.'' Has Kozol reversed that
formulation? It's a question taken seriously by this ``recovering
agnostic,'' as a nun friend likes to call him.
</P>
<P>
   ``The children have drawn me back to the religious feelings I
had as a child,'' he says. ``One of my friends in Manhattan once
said something like, `It's nice the way you play along with them
when they're talking about religion.' It doesn't seem that way to
me at all. When the children talk about things unseen, I want to
see them. I find their playfulness contagious. I find the intricate
details of their theology so beautiful that I want to believe it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I could believe in God with the literal certitude most
of these children have. I wish I could believe in the resurrection
_ any resurrection _ as deeply as they do. I wish I could believe
in immortality; with my parents nearing the end of their journey, I
very much want to believe. But I don't believe in all those things
the way the children do.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the children go up to kneel at the altar railing at St.
Ann's on Sunday morning to take communion, I'm often the only one
left in the church sitting at a pew. My Judaism is terribly
important to me, so I will never take communion. But some Sundays,
if I haven't had breakfast, when the priest holds up the wafer and
says `the bread of heaven,' it sounds pretty good! Then there's
this little boy who teases me, he whispers, `Try it, you'll like
it.'
</P>
<P>
   ``So that's one kind of communion I'll never have. But the
openness, the trustingness of the children, the sweetness of their
affection, that's the bread and wine for me. That's the only kind
this 63-year-old Jewish man is going to know. That's my version of
communion.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
