<DOCNO> NYT20000517.0085 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 11:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7474 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-MA-ECONOMY-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAKE-     05-17 1015
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-ECONOMY-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 BOSTON: ... quick here.''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As services have grown in importance, manufacturing has
contracted by 234,300 jobs since its heyday in 1984, when the
economy grew a sizzling 9.8 percent. For the average worker,
factory jobs are prized for their good pay and health benefits.
But, as Massachusetts workers learned in the late 1980s and Indiana
steelworkers learned in the 1970s, if technology or business
conditions no longer favor a major employer, heavy layoffs can
precipitate a regional downturn.
</P>
<P>
   As Digital was letting workers go, less visible forces began
reshaping the state's manufacturing industry in important ways.
What remains of manufacturing is smaller but less subject to
dramatic swings, economists point out, because once dominant
computer-hardware makers have been supplanted by a variety of
companies with growing markets for their products.
</P>
<P>
   The nation's economic expansion of the past decade has enabled
companies such as Hopkinton-based EMC Corp. to sell more
computer-storage systems, the Lucent Technologies Inc. plant in
North Andover to sell more telecommunications equipment,
Cambridge-based Genzyme Corp. to sell or research more drugs, and
Bedford-based Hologic Inc. to make more medical diagnostics
equipment.
</P>
<P>
   There is a shift going on, and the question is, ``Are the
industries we're shifting to more or less vulnerable?'' said Ed
Moscovitch, a consultant with Cape Ann Economics in Gloucester. ``I
think the answer is less.''
</P>
<P>
   By expanding into more world markets, manufacturers such as
Nypro Inc. have protected themselves against swings in domestic
sales, economists said. In Central Massachusetts, Nypro uses
refined processes to make small plastic parts. On a walk through
the spotless plant in Clinton with Brian Jones, president of North
American operations, row upon row of injection-molding machines
could be seen spitting out aqua razor holders for Gillette, black
computer keypads for Dell, green printer cartridges for
Hewlett-Packard Co., champagne-colored cell phone cases for
Ericcson, and dozens more products. Plastics, Jones said, ``is one
of the vital industries in Massachusetts, which people in Boston
don't really know about.''
</P>
<P>
   Nypro's sales are soaring 30 percent a year as worldwide demand
for plastics has grown. Jones joined Nypro in 1987, when it had 320
employees in Clinton. Today there are 1,100. Globally, the company
employs 6,000, with plants opening in China, Mexico, the Dominican
Republic, and Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1988, exports of Massachusetts-made goods have almost
doubled, to $18.2 billion last year, according to the University of
Massachusetts at Amherst. After financial turmoil in Asia cut state
exports sharply in 1998, new buyers from Mexico and Latin America
are restoring trade nearly to levels prior to Asia's collapse.
</P>
<P>
   Goods being exported are changing, said Andre Mayer of the
Alliance for the Commonwealth, a business organization: In 1987,
computer equipment was the state's leading export. Last year, the
top exports were electronic and electrical equipment used in
telecommunications, computer data storage, stereos, and computer
modems.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are more diversified in terms of the products we export and
in terms of the markets we're exporting to,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Despite major restructuring of Massachusetts' economy, it can
never be immune.
</P>
<P>
   Even the most optimistic economists acknowledge that the state _
like the nation _ is exhibiting signs of unsustainable growth,
because of a tight job market that is pushing up wages. An economy
cannot really grow ``too fast'' when that growth translates to job
creation and better pay. But, unusually fast growth results in
unhealthy imbalances that lead to a hard landing rather than a soft
downturn.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to puncture US consumer confidence and curtail
inflation, Federal Reserve chairman Alan Greenspan has boosted
interest rates five times since last summer. Another increase is
expected at the Fed's meeting Tuesday as the economy charges ahead
unabated.
</P>
<P>
   During the boom of the past nine years, Massachusetts has not
seen the galloping growth of the miracle years. The question for
economists is whether the state has a solid foundation to withstand
a sudden shock.
</P>
<P>
   Pointing to boom-bust theories, pessimists such as Birch,
president of Cognetics Inc., an economics consulting firm, argue
that Massachusetts is more at risk of collapse than the country as
a whole because of its too-heavy reliance on the securities
business _ Fidelity Investments, for example, is approaching $1
trillion in managed assets _ and a proliferation of dot-coms funded
by stock-market gains.
</P>
<P>
   Start-up activity reached a frenzy in 1999 as the Nasadaq
climbed 86 percent and 36 companies in Massachusetts went public.
Employment by the software and technology services is 156,600, or
two-thirds bigger than it was in the mid-1980s, according to RFA
Dismal Sciences, a West Chester, Pa., research firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``What do you think is driving all the job growth and business
spending and advertising and the money flowing into retail and the
homes being bought?'' asked RFA's chief economist, Mark Zandi.
``Initial public offerings and exercise of stock options and
venture capital money coming in.''
</P>
<P>
   But Case, of Wellesley College, sees a key difference between
the current boom and the 1980s boom: Although real estate prices
have risen sharply recently, there has not been the speculation
that occurred statewide in the 1980s when there was an ``overhang''
in excess commercial space and ``everything that breathed'' had
been converted to condominiums.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, bad loans brought Boston's banks to their knees,
deepening Massachusetts' slump, which was its worst recession since
the Depression.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Case said, he can detect some ``speculative euphoria in
markets like Cambridge and the western suburbs.'' But he added that
he is ``pretty convinced'' there is not a speculative bubble in the
Massachusetts real estate market _ not yet, anyway.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
