<DOCNO> NYT20000517.0087 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 11:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7476 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-LYCOS-DAVIS-BOS &LR;      05-17 0659
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LYCOS-DAVIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER FAILED DEAL, DAVIS PERSEVERED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT BERNARD NELSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A career salesman, Lycos chief executive Bob Davis is still
dogged by the one that got away.
</P>
<P>
   In the highest profile moment of his high-profile career, Davis
couldn't persuade shareholders last year to go along with a merger
between new-fangled Lycos and old-school USA Networks. Instead, he
took a heap of abuse when Wall Street turned its back on his vision
of the Internet's future.
</P>
<P>
   Shares in Lycos lost a third of their value in the week after
the deal was announced last February. Before the merger was
scrapped two months later, at least 18 shareholder lawsuits were
filed and Davis was pilloried both online and in the financial
press.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bob was assailed from every corner when that deal was
announced,'' said Pat Marshall, president of GTE New Media
Services, a Lycos business partner. ``He knew through it all that
he was right and the critics were wrong, but he still agonized over
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Now the Boston-born dealmaker is finding the reaction more to
his liking after unveiling the Lycos merger with Terra Networks SA.
This time, Wall Street is cheering.
</P>
<P>
   After word leaked out about the impending merger, Lycos shares
jumped more than 34 percent over the first two days of trading this
week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bob Davis is a great CEO,'' said Andrea Williams Rice, an
analyst at Deutsche Bank Alex Brown. ``He's got a bit of a street
fighter mentality in him, which serves him particularly well during
tough times.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis comes by his resolve naturally, if not his role as an
e-commerce visionary.
</P>
<P>
   He was raised in Boston's Dorchester section, the son of a
lawyer and a homemaker. One parent passed away while Davis attended
Boston College High School, and the other while he was at
Northeastern University.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he graduated summa cum laude from Northeastern
University, and went on to earn an MBA from Babson College.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bob grew up in a very difficult environment, and it taught him
how to survive and win and grow and compete,'' said Dan Nova, a
Lycos board member and former Davis colleague at Wang Labratories.
``Looking back, I think it shaped him in some positive ways.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis was attracted to high-tech companies from his early days
at Northeastern, when he spent three months as an intern at an IBM
sales office in Waltham, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   When IBM refused to hire him as a salesman after he graduated in
1979, Davis took a sales job at General Electric. Before long, he
landed a job at Wang, where he hawked computers for the next 11
years.
</P>
<P>
   In 1984, he outmaneuvered his former bosses at IBM to get Wang's
first contract with the Stop &AMP; Shop supermarket chain. When Wang
executives tried to back out of the deal, Davis went back and
convinced them it was the right move.
</P>
<P>
   ``He tends to fight the hardest when the odds are against him,''
Nova said.
</P>
<P>
   Davis, who became Lycos's first employee in 1995, appears to
have the odds with him in the latest deal. Though it still has to
clear regulatory and shareholder hurdles, the announcement met with
generally positive reaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``People on both sides of the Atlantic want this deal to
happen,'' said Bear Stearns analyst Jeffrey Fieler. ``The numbers
are better than a year ago (for Lycos shareholders), and the timing
is indubitably better.''
</P>
<P>
   The proposed merger between Lycos and USA Networks came at a
time when Internet stocks were soaring, and investors couldn't
imagine why Davis would want to weigh down the high-tech venture
with an old-line media company.
</P>
<P>
   The mood had changed by this January, though, when America
Online and Time Warner combined forces.
</P>
<P>
   ``Davis saw the value in that kind of link-up before the rest of
Wall Street,'' said Rice, of Deutsche Bank Alex Brown. ``Sometimes
when you're a leader, you end up with a few arrows in your back.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
