<HEADLINE>
BACK TO THE CORDON BLEU 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHERYL JULIAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ The first time I was here it was 1972, a bleak,
drizzly, chilly winter. I was on my way to cooking school. Like any
23-year-old, I wasn't thinking about the curriculum or what I would
learn. What was on my mind was how I looked. I'd been studying
British fashion magazines. The photographs from the airport
send-off show a long black skirt and high brown suede lace-up
boots, curly hair pretty much standing straight up, and huge
circles of white makeup around my eyes. In short, rather than a
Carnaby Street hopeful, I looked like a young woman trying to
imitate a skunk.
</P>
<P>
   There were other girls at the Cordon Bleu School of Cookery who
worked as hard on their look, but mostly what I remember about them
was how much they laughed. The girls were fun, robust, giddy
(picture Fergie before Weight Watchers), well educated, and biding
their time between secondary school and university or marriage.
When I learned British accents, I realized theirs were mostly upper
crust. There were hardly any outsiders, only a couple of other
Americans and a few Australians and South Africans.
</P>
<P>
   It was a warm place, even with a stern all-female staff who were
addressed _ and in turn addressed us _ as ``Miss.'' The directors,
or principals, were two formidable women who had been honored by
the queen. Aspects of the Cordon Bleu gave it the air of a serious
finishing school. A brilliant film director couldn't have come up
with it.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not sure why I was expecting to find those girls when I
recently returned to the Cordon Bleu. Not only were they gone, but
so were the jolly English voices. In fact, except for the staff's,
there were hardly any British accents. Certainly, the passage of 30
years has brought all kinds of changes to the food industry.
Celebrity chefs are making small fortunes on restaurant empires,
and as the industry grows, there isn't enough talent to go around.
</P>
<P>
   So the serious young men and women who populate the school
today, some who paid $27,000 for the nine-month grand diplome
degree, are virtually guaranteed jobs when they return home _ to
more than 50 countries across Europe, Asia, and North America.
</P>
<P>
   The Cordon Bleu School of Cookery changed hands in 1990, when it
was purchased by Andre Cointreau, of the Cointreau and Remy Martin
families, and renamed Le Cordon Bleu. Six years earlier, Cointreau
had bought Le Cordon Bleu de Paris, at a moment when it had so
deteriorated it hardly resembled the place where Julia Child had
learned to cook.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after the purchase, the London school underwent a massive
renovation, in which the dozens of tiny cooking stations and
partitions _ essentially miniature home kitchens _ were replaced
with big, airy rooms filled with shiny stainless equipment. The
students call the teacher ``chef,'' follow a classic French
curriculum, and learn complicated sugar work.
</P>
<P>
   Cointreau's wife, Hedwige Cointreau de Bouteville, owns Pierre
Deux, the expensive Provencal home furnishings company. ``A lovely
link for us,'' says Lesley Gray, who was principal at the time of
the sale and stayed on with the new regime. She had been a teacher
when I was there. She seems old-school (even though we are about
the same age, she is so proper that I have to keep myself from
calling her ``Miss Gray''). But she talks new-school.
</P>
<P>
   Under Cointreau, Le Cordon Bleu is ruthlessly entrepreneurial.
The staid 67-year-old institution whose girls catered the
coronation lunch for Queen Elizabeth II _ and invented ``Coronation
Chicken,'' made with curried mayonnaise _ now capitalizes on its
name. Le Cordon Bleu participates in advertising endorsements and
commercial promotions. It seems to churn out cookbooks. Besides
Paris and London, other schools are located in Ottawa, Tokyo, and
Sydney. There are also partnerships at some American culinary
schools in California, Oregon, Pennsylvania, Arizona, and
Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   ``Culinary institutes are expensive to run,'' says Gray, by way
of explaining the publishing ventures and ``co-branding,'' the word
she uses for the school's collaboration with food and equipment
companies. ``At the end of the day, you want to run a business.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Tokyo Cordon Bleu, there is a ``Sabrina'' course, named
for the popular 1954 movie in which Audrey Hepburn comes home from
cooking school in Paris having learned to crack open an egg with
one hand. Five Sabrina books published by the Cordon Bleu (in
Japanese) sell briskly.
</P>
<P>
   The London school used to require an interview, though
exceptions were made for the few foreigners. Now all the students
are foreigners. ``Today it's all done by letter,'' says Gray.
</P>
<P>
   Students come from everywhere. A dozen foreign languages are
spoken into cell phones on the front curb. Students have to cram
their conversations in before class, since a sign inside reads:
``Attention Everybody. Please note that before entering this
demonstration room, all mobile telephones must be switched off.''
</P>
<P>
   The phones were a problem, Gray tells me. Even after the sign
went up, someone's phone rang one day during a cooking
demonstration. The ringing was coming from the front of the class.
</P>
<P>
   It was the chef's. He was the only person who hadn't seen the
notice.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth R. and Philip
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Gary Poole-Gleed, a hip 36-year-old Londoner who worked for
several years for the Roux brothers, famous French-born English
restaurateurs, is typical of today's Cordon Bleu chefs. He's a good
teacher, at ease with all sorts of techniques, including pastry and
elaborate garnishes. On the day of my visit, he makes warm oysters
with a sherry cream glaze, sea bass fillets with crispy potato
scales and an orange butter sauce, and tartlets filled with red
currants, praline, and meringue. The students take copious notes
because they are about to go into the kitchens and repeat the menu.
</P>
<P>
   The room is decorated with huge cutout photos of beautifully
garnished dinner plates. We can watch Poole-Gleed on one of two
television monitors or simply look up into a 7-foot overhead mirror
that reflects the cooktops beneath it. When he finishes cooking, an
office assistant swoops in and takes the food to a corner, where a
photography table is already set up. She snaps a picture of each
plate before giving it back to the students to sample.
</P>
<P>
   On a wall in the conference room on the top floor of the Cordon
Bleu hangs founder Rosemary Hume's Member of the British Empire
citation, signed ``Elizabeth R.'' and ``Philip.'' Gray and I have
stopped here to look at the school's many books. I'm interested in
what the school used to be like, but she keeps emphasizing that
it's important to look ahead.
</P>
<P>
   She talks about the awards her chefs receive, how they come from
all the top restaurants and hotels, including the Dorchester and
Claridge's. Keeping abreast of trends is one of her concerns.
``You've got to be aware of what's going on in the food world,''
she tells me.
</P>
<P>
   When I ask how she likes Morro, the young, packed restaurant I'd
been to the night before, she doesn't know it. Gray seems to keep
track of certain distinguished dining rooms and prides herself on
sending students there. ``They're desperate to find good staff,''
she says. A student who went to Claridge's did so well that the
chef asked Gray, ``Can you get me 20 more like that?''
</P>
<P>
   She can, she says, but few students have working visas, and
restaurants aren't willing to process papers for them. Gray has
just learned about a job opening at Kensington Palace, one of the
royal households, and she wonders if she has anyone to offer it to.
</P>
<P>
   Because the London curriculum is tied to the other Cordon Bleu
schools, students can take courses at any of the locations. So they
can begin, say, in London, and then head for Paris.
</P>
<P>
   Which is what I did.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
