<HEADLINE>
BOSTON, SOUTH AFRICA FIGURE IN IRISH ROAD TO PEACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELFAST _ Three months ago, after the British government pulled
the plug on the power-sharing local government in Northern Ireland,
the mood in Belfast was gloomy.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting thousands of miles away in Johannesburg, Sathyandranath
``Mac'' Maharaj did not share that gloom. Maharaj had been in
Belfast in the days leading up to the suspension of the elected
assembly, trying to persuade Irish republicans and pro-British
unionists to compromise. But they couldn't, and the most hopeful
attempt yet to transform Northern Ireland into a peaceful,
democratic society was put in cold storage.
</P>
<P>
   While almost everyone wondered whether the peace process could
survive the political inertia and personal recrimination that
followed, Maharaj sat across from Cyril Ramaphosa, his old friend
and comrade in the African National Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``This,'' he told Ramaphosa, ``is soluble.''
</P>
<P>
   The South Africans have always had more faith in Northern
Ireland's politicians than the politicians had in themselves, and
for nearly a decade South Africans have been trying to help bring
about peace. Just Monday, Ramaphosa arrived in Belfast after
agreeing to serve as one of the two inspectors who will certify the
Irish Republican Army's weapons are ``beyond use.''
</P>
<P>
   The link between the two countries traces to a 1992 conference
at the University of Massachusetts at Boston, which for the first
time brought together the leading politicians of both nations. That
conference, along with later gatherings in Boston, Belfast, and
South Africa were organized by Padraig O'Malley, the Dublin-born
senior fellow at the John W. McCormack Institute of Public Affairs
at UMass.
</P>
<P>
   O'Malley spent much of the 1970s and 1980s immersed in the
Troubles of his native land. His books, ``Uncivil Wars'' and
``Biting at the Grave,'' a study of the 1981 Irish republican
hunger strike, are highly regarded examinations of the conflict in
Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   But in the 1990s, he turned his attention to South Africa.
Nelson Mandela had been released from prison, F.W. de Klerk's
National Party was ready to deal, and the apartheid system was
about to collapse. As O'Malley saw it, if the South Africans could
bring apartheid to an end and install the black majority in a
relatively peaceful transfer of power, they could teach the Irish
and British something.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, I asked them if they would help. It took me a
while. I nagged them. But once the South Africans agreed to help,
there was no stopping them. They put enormous time and energy into
Northern Ireland,'' said O'Malley, who is in Belfast this week to
reassure all sides that Ramaphosa and Martti Ahtisaari, the former
president of Finland, will be impartial inspectors of IRA weapons
dumps.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, after a brief stop in London to consult with Prime
Minister Tony Blair, Ramaphosa and Ahtisaari came to Belfast and
began meeting privately with the various parties.
</P>
<P>
   The ANC had considerable credibility with the IRA and Sinn Fein,
the IRA's political wing. A mural of Mandela had for years
decorated a wall across from the Falls Road office of Sinn Fein in
West Belfast. The IRA often compared its ``armed struggle'' to that
of the ANC's.
</P>
<P>
   The white Afrikaners, meanwhile, seemed to have empathy with
Protestant unionists who want to maintain the union with Britain,
sharing a siege mentality and the sense that the whole world was
biased in favor of their opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Roelf Meyer, the National Party's chief negotiator who
negotiated the end of apartheid with Ramaphosa, said those views
gave way over time. He said he and Ramaphosa, who traveled to
Belfast together and then hosted the Northern Ireland politicians
in South Africa in 1997, were able to impart their experiences to
both sides.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are people,'' said Meyer. ``There is little
difference.''
</P>
<P>
   For years, many people in Northern Ireland, especially the
unionists, had rejected the notion that outsiders had anything to
teach them about resolving their differences. When the South
Africans heard such talk, they nodded and smiled knowingly.
</P>
<P>
   ``The South Africans kept telling the Irish, `You're not that
special.' I think it is a message they all needed to hear. If the
South Africans can get beyond their history, why can't they?''
O'Malley said.
</P>
<P>
   Eleven days ago, the IRA made a stunning offer aimed at pushing
along the stalled peace process. In exchange for restoring the
power-sharing government and full implementation of the Good Friday
Agreement, including reform of the Royal Ulster Constabulary and
scaling back British forces, the IRA said it would allow
international arms inspectors to verify that its arms dumps were
secure.
</P>
<P>
   The IRA said it intended to ``initiate a process that will
completely and verifiably put IRA arms beyond use.''
</P>
<P>
   Longtime observers were stunned by the IRA's language, which was
far more conciliatory and flexible than in the past.
</P>
<P>
   There is little doubt that statement would not have been issued
if not for the influence of Maharaj and Ramaphosa, and if Ramaphosa
had not been chosen by the British and Irish governments as one of
the arms inspectors.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last few years, both Ramaphosa and Maharaj have met
with senior IRA leaders, including Brian Keenan, the Belfast IRA
commander who is considered the most influential of the
seven-member Army Council that rules the IRA. As former
revolutionaries, the South Africans command respect in the IRA.
They speak the same revolutionary jargon and harbor the same
distrust of the establishment.
</P>
<P>
   But in South Africa, Ramaphosa and Maharaj have become part of
the establishment. If the two men wielded power by holding guns
during the apartheid era, today they do so by holding seats on
various company boards of directors. Maharaj, a one-time communist,
is now a bank director. When Nelson Mandela decided that Thabo
Mbeki would succeed him as president, he told Ramaphosa to go out
and be a role model in the private sector for young blacks.
Ramaphosa did just that. He is now a rich man.
</P>
<P>
   And in Maharaj, the IRA leaders could talk to someone who once
shared their ambivalence about shutting down a paramilitary
organization and entrusting its goals to democratic politics.
</P>
<P>
   Maharaj served time with Mandela in the Robben Island prison,
and the two are extremely close. But even after Mandela began
negotiations with de Klerk, Maharaj continued to mount attacks
against the South African security forces. After Mandela convinced
Maharaj that continuing the violence only postponed reconciliation
with whites, Maharaj put down his weapons and became transporation
minister in Mandela's Cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   Ramaphosa and Maharaj urged IRAleaders to be more generous with
its language. But the South Africans accepted the IRA leadership's
insistence that, given the risk of provoking a split in the IRA,
they could not make even a token gesture of turning in weapons.
</P>
<P>
   The IRA's May 6 statement, crafted under the tutelage of the
ANC, was as close as IRA leaders feel they can come to saying the
war is over. And they must have taken some comfort knowing the ANC
was standing in the wings, nodding approvingly.
</P>
<P>
   While the ANC men feel more of a connection with the
republicans, it is also true that the South Africans respect the
Ulster Unionists, particularly their leader, David Trimble.
</P>
<P>
   More than one ANC leader has compared Trimble to de Klerk. And
as Mandela's prickly relationship with de Klerk proved, you don't
have to like someone to respect him and do business.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago in South Africa, Mandela gave separate lectures
to the visitors from Northern Ireland because unionists refused to
sit in the same room as the republicans. He laid into the
unionists, telling them you don't make peace with your friends but
with your enemies. But he gave no comfort to the republicans,
telling them the IRA had to restore its cease-fire immediately, and
that it could not retain a private army if democracy was to take
root.
</P>
<P>
   If the Ulster Unionist Council votes Saturday to accept the IRA
offer, it would seem that Mandela's words have finally been heeded.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
