<HEADLINE>
BEING TOO CONSERVATIVE CAN BE DANGEROUS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. My wife and I both work part time but do not rely on the
income for financial planning purposes. Our main goal is to have
enough money to live comfortably, travel a bit, and, most
important, to be able to pay for assisted living as we age. Our
annual expenses, including the various insurance payments, were
$80,000 last year, some of which represented discretionary spending
such as furniture, vacations, eating out, and so forth. We
recognize that we have become conservative. Assuming that as time
goes on our only income will be from my pension and investments,
what should we be doing differently?
</P>
<P>
   A.E., Boston &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. When it comes to the matter of growing conservative as we age
_ most people do. But I like to think that some of it is a function
of our growing smarter.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the combination of having only a little more than 14
percent of your assets in stocks, retiring quite early, and having
a pension that ends at the time of your death, whether or not your
wife remains alive, is a dangerous one. Just to give you an idea
what I am talking about, if inflation runs at an average 3.5
percent for 30 years, it will cost $224,543 to support the life
style that $80,000 buys today.
</P>
<P>
   Here's my suggestion. My calculation is that you have been using
roughly half of the yield from your various investments to augment
your pension income. What I would do is invest the remaining yield
from your various investments either in stock funds or at the
minimum in balanced funds, which hold both stocks and fixed income
investments. I would put all of your yield except what you are
using to meet your expenses in Vanguard Index Value, making the
deposits on a monthly basis so that the investment will basically
be a dollar-cost-averaging program.
</P>
<P>
   If you are leery of this program and unwilling to take the risk
of the all-stock fund, I suggest that you at least follow the same
suggestion using a proven balanced fund, such as Vanguard Balanced
Index fund or Fidelity Puritan fund.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Until now I have not had any savings, but now I can put away
$300 a week. I need to save for retirement but am financially
ignorant and don't know where to begin. I'm wondering if I should
have $5,000 in a savings account, put $2,000 a year in an IRA, and
put the rest in mutual funds? Should the IRA be a Roth or not?
Should I put any money in CDs? I plan on educating myself in this,
but I need to know how to get started.
</P>
<P>
   C.B., Waltham, Mass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Let's start with the $5,000, which you apparently have
decided to keep in liquid savings as protection against
emergencies. That's a solid plan, but I would not leave it in bank
savings. Current savings bank rates are very low, typically around
2.5 percent, whereas you can command about twice as much interest
if you move it to a mutual fund company's money market fund. This
will not significantly reduce the liquidity, since with such
accounts you can obtain check-writing privileges that allow you
immediate access to the money. Since I'm going to suggest the
Vanguard fund family for other investments, I would take a look at
Vanguard's Prime Money Market fund for this.
</P>
<P>
   I agree that establishing an IRA would be the next move. As you
probably already know, the difference between a Roth IRA and a
traditional IRA is that the contributions to a Roth are made with
after-tax money, and when withdrawals are taken, all of the
withdrawals are tax-free _ including any investment gains you have
realized. With a traditional IRA, you get a tax deduction for the
$2,000 per year maximum contribution, but will owe taxes on the
full amount of withdrawals when they are taken. I am guessing that
since you are now able to save at a rate of $15,600 a year that you
are in a fairly high tax bracket. I am also guessing that since
your total accumulation in the fund portfolio is likely to be
$543,124 at age 65, that you will be in a lower tax bracket in
retirement. Therefore, the traditional IRA would be more
advantageous to you _ and particularly so if the up-front tax break
would allow you to save more.
</P>
<P>
   As for an investment for the IRA, I would begin with the
Vanguard Index 500 fund, which simply seeks to duplicate the
results of the Standard and Poor's 500 Index. I would continue
investing there _ opening a taxable account as soon as you have
maxed out on the allowed contributions to your IRA _ until the
account reaches $10,000. At that point, I would look to gain access
to three other market segments, through the Vanguard Mid-Cap Index,
Vanguard Small-Cap Index and the Vanguard Health Care. I suggest
you eventually seek a portfolio balance that shows 50 percent in
Index 500 and 16.66 percent each in the other three funds. I'd
continue in that vein until about five years before your
anticipated retirement, then gradually reduce the risk level with
more conservative investments.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, invest in an excellent paperback book, ``How To Buy
Stocks'' by Louis Engel and Brendan Boyd.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Kenneth Hooker can be reached at The Boston Globe, P.O. Box 2378,
Boston, MA 02107-2378.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
