<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-YOUTH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO VIEWS OF PEACE, PROSPECTS DIVIDE A GENERATION IN MIDEAST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALIZA MARCUS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BETHLEHEM _ Three nights a week, a disc jockey, Johnny Serani,
strips down to a tight black T-shirt and makes the floor at this
tiny dance bar come alive. He's into hip-hop and rap, and so is the
crowd, a mix of spiked heels and sneakers, tight halter tops and
button-down shirts.
</P>
<P>
   It's like any night in any bar where the crowd wants to dance
and where the lights are low, except this is a Palestinian bar and
there's an Israeli watchtower up the street, with soldiers in green
fatigues lounging against barricades.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian youth come here to have a good time, and to forget
daily frustrations. Besides, there's the matter of an Israeli
checkpoint that stops them from trying the nightlife 15 minutes
away, in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   This is a generation that hasn't known war but that hasn't
really known peace, either, and it feels stuck in uncertainty and
the vagaries of the frequently stalled peace process.
</P>
<P>
   ``The peace process is a joke; everyone knows it because you
can't have real peace while Israel still controls our land, our
economy. I feel like I live in a big prison,'' said Serani, 20,
during a break outside Memories bar in Bethlehem, an Israeli flag
fluttering just at the bend in the road.
</P>
<P>
   A friend of his, with black sunglasses pushed up over black
spiked hair, nodded. ``I just hope the peace process moves quickly
so we can get our own state and have a better life,'' said Khalid
Bahnan, a 24-year-old factory worker.
</P>
<P>
   A few minutes' drive away in Jerusalem, past the Israeli
checkpoint that keeps out Palestinians who do not have the
hard-to-get permit to enter Israel, there's a bar with the same
type of pounding music and sweaty couples smoking cigarettes while
they dance.
</P>
<P>
   But inside the bar named Underground, an Israeli soldier is
dancing on a table, M-16 in hand. And that's not the only
difference: Here, there's little sense of the frustration young
Palestinians feel about the stop-and-go peace talks.
</P>
<P>
   Talks now underway for a final peace agreement may be moving
slowly, but it does not make a big difference to what sort of jobs
young Israelis can find or how they will live their lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think something will come out of the peace talks, I am sure,
but no one will get exactly what they want. We will all have to
compromise and it won't happen tomorrow,'' said Noam Zuckerman, a
26-year-old who has his own high-tech company.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, the whole process does not really affect my life so
I'm not following it 100 percent,'' he added with an apologetic
shrug.
</P>
<P>
   Two peoples, many views, and a stagnating peace process; this,
for the members of this region's young generation, is all that's
known. They grew up after the intifadah, or Palestinian uprising of
the late 1980s, when Israeli soldiers and Palestinians clashed
violently every day.
</P>
<P>
   They barely remember what life was like when Israel occupied the
whole of the West Bank and Gaza, and they might not even recall the
first handshake between Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat and the
late Prime Minister Yitzhak Rabin, assassinated two years later by
an Israeli Jew opposed to the peace accords.
</P>
<P>
   For many in this generation of Israelis, the conflict with the
Palestinians often seems so muted and far away that it is hard for
them to understand why a few months, or even years, of delay in a
final settlement should concern their Palestinian counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   They hardly ever come into contact with residents of the West
Bank and Gaza, who usually do not get permission to enter Israel
unless they are among the tens of thousands of workers who enter
each day as truck drivers, street sweepers, construction workers,
and manual laborers.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli soldiers stationed in the West Bank or Gaza may
occasionally face rock-throwing demonstrators, but violence has
ebbed now that the Palestinian Authority has jurisdiction over 40
percent of the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   For Palestinians as well, daily life is more stable, but their
dreams of an independent state are dimming.
</P>
<P>
   The nation that Arafat had promised by last year is delayed
because of breakdowns in peace talks. Negotiations that resumed
last week to work out a frameworkfor a final agreement by Sept. 13
have been plagued by disagreements over issues such as how much
land the Palestinians will control and what to do about Jewish
settlements there.
</P>
<P>
   Economic opportunities for Palestinians are limited, and
Arafat's promises of development have been stymied by corruption in
his self-rule administration and Israeli restrictions on goods and
people entering and exiting the self-rule areas.
</P>
<P>
   Israel still occupies most of the West Bank, parts of Gaza and
East Jerusalem, all of which Palestinians want for an independent
state. Jewish settlements on occupied land are still confiscating
land that Palestinians say is theirs, and are building more housing
units.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian youth, brought up amid a peace process and taught
that this would soon free them from Israeli occupation and
domination, are waiting impatiently. For many of them, each day
that goes by without a final peace deal is another day of
uncertainty about the future.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
