<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 11:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7486 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-LYCOS-TELEFONICA-BOS &LR;      05-17 0766
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LYCOS-TELEFONICA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TELEFONICA CHIEF REACHES ACROSS NEW NATIONS, TECHNOLOGIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON ZITNER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ To folks in its home state of Massachusetts, Lycos
Inc. is one of the jewels of the Internet industry, a symbol of the
state's claim on the electronic frontier.
</P>
<P>
   But to Madrid-based Telefonica, the Lycos buyout is one more
move on a global gameboard, another step toward turning a stodgy,
government-run telephone company into a worldwide master of many
media.
</P>
<P>
   Telefonica is hardly a household name in the United States, but
the Spanish company has made waves in Europe and South America both
for its aggressive acquisition spree and the swashbuckling behavior
of its chairman, Juan Villalonga, a former member of the elite
Trilateral Commission known for rewarding himself richly and dating
a one-time Miss Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   While the newly privatized phone giants of Germany and France
have focused on their home markets, Villalonga has pushed his far
smaller company to look beyond Spain to conquer new technologies
and new markets.
</P>
<P>
   He has made Telefonica a major provider of communications
services in Chile, Argentina, Peru and other nations. Most of its
markets have two characteristics in common: a government that has
opened state-run industries to new competition, and a Spanish- or
Portuguese-speaking culture that is familiar to Telefonica
managers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've pursued a very aggressive strategy of expanding not
only across different regions but across services _ fixed line
(local phone service), wireless, Internet. In some countries, they
have cable TV operations,'' said Jamila Xible, who follows the
Brazilian communications market for the Yankee Group, a Boston
consulting firm.
</P>
<P>
   Lycos is not Telefonica's first Internet acquisition. The
Internet service provider it bought in Brazil has become that
country's second largest as well as a major Internet portal, Xible
said. Telefonica even reached into television production recently,
buying a Dutch maker of ``reality-based'' TV shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``Paradoxically, the fact that the Spanish economy is not as
strong as Germany's or France's created a need to go international
faster than some companies from those other countries did,'' said
Robert Norcross of Mercer Management Consulting in Washington.
``Telefonica has been more successful than a lot of the larger,
potentially more advanced companies in creating an international
presence for itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Villalonga, a childhood friend of the Spanish prime minister,
was picked by the government in 1996 to run Telefonica as it was
privatized. He initially won raves. The company's share price has
soared, and Telefonica was listed at 193d on last year's Fortune
Global 500 list of the world's largest companies, ahead of American
Express, Coca-Cola and MCI-Worldcom.
</P>
<P>
   But Villalonga, a former McKinsey &AMP; Co. consultant, also has
stepped on some toes as he brought American-style capitalism to
Spain. He was criticized strongly for offering multimillion-dollar
stock options to himself and other Telefonica managers, a rarity in
Spain. An attempted merger with a bank sparked complaints that too
much business power would be held in too few hands.
</P>
<P>
   Telefonica also created an outcry when it tried to hire the
European Union's outgoing telecommunications commissioner. The move
might have helped Telefonica expand in Europe, but rival companies
protested that the revolving door from government had spun too
quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Villalonga, who seldom gives interviews, was reported last year
to have left his wife and to have begun dating Mexican beauty queen
Adriana Abascal. He now spends much of his time in Miami. For
several years, he was a member of the Trilateral Commission, the
325-member, high-level foreign policy group that is a favorite
focus of conspiracy theorists. A spokesman for the commission said
he left the group last year.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say that Villalonga is sure to continue trying to buy
his way into the top ranks of telecommunications and content
companies, using the hefty cash flow that most incumbent phone
giants enjoy. The Lycos acquisition should be seen in this light,
they say.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is about the next deal,'' said Norcross. ``It's not that
this one is the be all and end all, but how does it make Telefonica
look for the next deal with Worldcom or AT&AMP;T or Deutsche Telekom? .
. . The idea is that if you get a good first deal, it makes you
more attractive for the second deal, and even more attractive for
the third.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
