<HEADLINE>
&HT;      
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Every other week, The Chronicle features ``Learning
to Cook'' by Marion Cunningham, a cooking teacher and cookbook
author best known for her revisions of the Fannie Farmer cookbooks.
This column is intended for novices in the kitchen. &HT;     
 LEARNING TO COOK: Add a Spark With Blue Cheese Crumble  By Marion Cunningham  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR; Every home cook worth his or her salt has a couple
of favorite concoctions, either in the refrigerator or cupboard,
waiting to be used in case of unexpected guests, or just to improve
a rather spartan lunch or supper.
<P>
   In days gone by, relishes, pickles and olives added sparkle to
dull fare. The Pennsylvania Dutch, for example, were masterful at
filling their tables with what was called ``sweets and sours.''
</P>
<P>
   The following recipe, Blue Cheese Crumble, is a good example of
a modern sweet-and-sour. It has won recipe contests, and is most
popular served as an hors d'oeuvre with crackers or Melba toasts.
</P>
<P>
   The recipe can play different roles, however, depending on your
need. It's delicious spooned onto grilled or pan-fried steaks or
hamburgers. The nuggets of blue cheese gradually soften and melt
over the sizzling-hot meat. There's something about beef and blue
cheese . . . they really do go together.
</P>
<P>
   Blue Cheese Crumble also is brilliant as a topping for salads.
Given the ingredients _ onions, garlic, olive oil, vinegar and
lemon juice _ no wonder it's a natural with lettuce.
</P>
<P>
   Or, try serving it with sliced Granny Smith apples and your
favorite crackers as the fruit-and-cheese course to enhance a meal.
The tiny bit of garlic won't hurt the apple one bit.
</P>
<P>
   This is a perfect example of home cooking at its best. This
simple recipe can turn a so-so dish into a favorite family meal.
One word of warning, however, be sure to try just a little sample
of Blue Cheese Crumble on whatever dish you wish to improve to see
if it blends well.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
BLUE CHEESE CRUMBLE
</P>
<P>
   This is from Sharon Kramis, a great Seattle cook.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   8 ounces blue cheese, crumbled
</P>
<P>
   2 garlic cloves
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup chopped red onion, or chopped green onions (also called
scallions)
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons red wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon fresh lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup parsley leaves
</P>
<P>
   1/2 to 1 teaspoon ground pepper (start by adding 1/2 teaspoon
and taste to see if this is enough for you)
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Preparing the cheese, garlic and onion:  &LR; If you buy a solid
block of blue cheese instead of the crumbled style, it is very easy
to crumble. Use the large holes on a box grater; the bits of cheese
should come out about the size of corn kernels.
</P>
<P>
   Remove the papery skin from the garlic cloves and slice each
clove in half lengthwise, then slice each half lengthwise into
little strips. Hold the strips together and cut into small pieces
crosswise. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Remove the papery outer skin from a red onion. Cut the onion
into little pieces in the same way you cut up the garlic cloves.
Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Finishing the blue cheese crumble: &LR;  Sprinkle the crumbled
cheese in an even layer into a shallow 8- or 9-inch dish. Mix
together the garlic and olive oil and sprinkle over the cheese. Put
the vinegar and lemon juice into a small bowl and stir to mix. Stir
in the red onion, parsley and pepper; spread all over the cheese.
</P>
<P>
   Cover and refrigerate for at least 1 hour before using.
</P>
<P>
   This keeps well for at least 1 week, stored in a covered jar in
the refrigerator.
</P>
<P>
   Yields a generous 21/2 cups.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER TABLESPOON: &LR;   &LR; 40 calories, &LR;   &LR; 1 g protein, 0 carbohydrate,
3 &LR;   &LR; g fat (1 g saturated), 4 mg cholesterol, 79 mg sodium, 0
fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-17-00 1255EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
