<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 12:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7534 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r d BC-POTPOURRI-SFCHRON &LR;      05-17 0682
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POTPOURRI-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Each week, wine editor Gerald Boyd discusses a
variety of wine topics. 
 
 WINE POTPOURRI: England, Australia Can Teach the U.S. Some Wine 
 Sense   By Gerald D. Boyd  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  In the late 1960s, when my interest in wine was
beginning to develop, I became a collector before taking up
writing. Later, writing became a way for me to share my passion for
wine with others.
<TEXT>
<P>
   My goal then and now was to educate and inform readers about
wine, not to sell wine. It's an iffy position because some people
dismiss wine writers as merely publicists for the wine industry.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, I bristle when I read edicts from political hacks
who worry more about politics than any purported health threat
posed by consuming alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   In the last month, U.S. Surgeon General David Satcher threw up
another wall against efforts to convince Americans that an
occasional drink will not lead to ill health and ruin. Satcher
worries that the new labels on wine bottles proposed by the wine
industry, which urge consumers to learn more about the health
effects of wine, will instead encourage ``irresponsible drinking.''
And he adds weight to his argument by citing statistics about
alcohol abuse.
</P>
<P>
   Alcohol abuse is a serious problem and should not be taken
lightly. But anybody who wants to get blitzed doesn't do it with
wine. This is especially true for underage drinkers. Few of the
teens who believe that drunkenness is cool are forking out $15 to
$35 for a bottle of wine.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1970s, when the interest in wine exploded, industry
prognosticators predicted that annual per capita wine consumption
would hit 10 gallons by 1990 or, at the latest, by 2000. But
American wine drinkers never broke the three-gallon-per-year mark.
And if politicians continue to inflict their personal agendas on
everyone else, interested consumers will never be able to reap the
benefits of a fully-supported industry.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Why Not in California? &LR;
</P>
<P>
   While I'm grousing, two other items about public and government
support of wine came to my attention. A recent travel story about
what to see in London mentioned the new Vinopolis, an
``edutainment'' site on the banks of Thames devoted to the world's
wine regions, including Napa and Sonoma. Vinopolis offers lectures
about wine, and visitors can also taste and purchase wine.
Congratulations to the forward-thinking Londoners who came up with
the idea, an admirable achievement especially since England, unlike
California, doesn't have a large commercial wine industry to
promote. Also, it would seem that the Vinopolis organizers didn't
have to worry about neo-prohibitionists fretting that such a public
display of wine as a beverage to be enjoyed in moderation with food
would somehow undermine all that is good about English society.
</P>
<P>
   The other item, from Australia, heralds the opening of The
National Wine Centre in Adelaide's Botanic Gardens. Visitors can
sample wines from more than 50 Australian growing areas, visit a
wine tourism information center and purchase wine. The centre is
funded jointly by the state and national government and the
Australian wine industry.
</P>
<P>
   The joint venture between government and private industry to
promote wine can demonstrate to an unwilling California wine
industry, too busy flogging their own brands, that it's beneficial
to join together, with or without government help, to promote the
idea of enjoying wine in moderation.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Looking into the Future &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Monterey County vintners have had their ups and downs over the
years, but grape growers and winemakers are very excited over the
future of the county's Syrah and Pinot Noir. Paraiso Springs, for
one, has made major changes on its 400-acre Santa Lucia Highlands
estate, removing Gewurztraminer and Pinot Blanc and planting more
Syrah and Pinot Noir. When finished the estate vineyard will
comprise 65 acres of Chardonnay, 75 acres of Pinot Noir, 20 acres
of Syrah and a little Riesling and Souzao, a Portuguese variety
used for Port.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-17-00 1256EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000517.0102 </DOCNO>
