A7538 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r d BC-SECRET-SALAD-SFCHRON &LR;      05-17 0731
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SECRET-SALAD-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Each week, The Chronicle offers readers the recipe
for an outstanding dish at a Bay Area restaurant, plus the chef's
secrets for making it a success. Tips and recipe follow in optional
trim. 
 
 SECRETS OF SUCCESS: Montage's Sprightly Salad   By Michael Bauer  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  Pairing fruit and savory ingredients is a
difficult challenge and, frankly, not many chefs are good at it.
Without the proper balance, the flavors clash and the dish becomes
one-dimensional.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fortunately Jennifer Cox, chef of Montage in the Sony Metreon,
has the gift. There are several examples on her seasonal menu, but
my favorite is a salad of juicy strawberries and peppery
watercress. The pairing is accented by toasted almonds and creamy
 &LR; fromage blanc &LR; , a mild soft white cheese with a slightly tangy
edge.
</P>
<P>
   Montage looks kind of like a 1990s supper club. There's not a
straight wall in the entire restaurant. Three rows of booths
separated by 5-foot-high partitions appear to stair-step up, thanks
to the soffit ceiling. The artwork on the curved walls consists of
gold-framed video screens that project moving abstract images, as
well as artwork on loan from the Museum of Modern Art, located
close to the Metreon.
</P>
<P>
   The huge shopping complex with a host of restaurants, video
games, virtual bowling and high-tech shop, such as Microsoft's
first retail store, is Sony's answer to our digital society.
Fortunately, this cool countenance doesn't translate to Cox's food.
You could grab a vitamin shake or pop a pill, but Cox has a
refreshing, soulful California style that is soothing after a
grueling day of virtual games.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Montage, 101 Fourth St. (at Mission, in Sony Metreon), San &LR; 
 &LR; Francisco; (415) 369-6111. Lunch, dinner daily. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
SECRETS OF SUCCESS
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Pairing fruit and greens. &LR;  The combination of watercress and
strawberries sets up a refreshing, startling contrast.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Balsamic reduction. &LR;  The dressing, made from reduced balsamic
vinegar, has a natural affinity for strawberries and creates a
bridge that brings the flavors together.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; STRAWBERRY WATERCRESS SALAD
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound watercress, trimmed
</P>
<P>
   1 pint strawberries, stemmed and cut into 1/4-inch slices
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup (about) Balsamic Vinaigrette (recipe follows)
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 cup fromage blanc (see note)
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup sliced almonds, toasted
</P>
<P>
   Balsamic Syrup (see recipe)
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Put the watercress and strawberries in separate bowls. Drizzle
Balsamic Vinaigrette over each and toss to coat. Season with salt,
pepper and more vinaigrette, if desired.
</P>
<P>
   Divide the watercress among 6 salad plates. Top with the
strawberries. Generously dot the salad with the cheese. Sprinkle on
the almonds. Drizzle on a small amount of the Balsamic Syrup.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Note: &LR;  Fromage blanc is a soft fresh white cheese available at
cheese stores and many upscale markets.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 280 calories, &LR;   &LR; 4 g protein, 7 g carbohydrate,
24 &LR;   &LR; g fat (7 g saturated), 17 mg cholesterol, 396 mg sodium, 3 g &LR; 
 &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
BALSAMIC VINAIGRETTE
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons Balsamic Syrup (see recipe)
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup good quality balsamic vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon Dijon mustard
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons kosher salt
</P>
<P>
   2/3 cup + 11/2 teaspoons mild olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Whisk together the Balsamic Syrup, vinegar, mustard and salt.
Gradually whisk in the oil until the mixture is emulsified.
</P>
<P>
   Whisk to blend before using.
</P>
<P>
   Yields about 1 cup.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER TABLESPOON: &LR;   &LR; 100 calories, &LR;   &LR; 0 protein, 0 carbohydrate, 9
g &LR;   &LR; fat (1 g saturated), 0 cholesterol, 269 mg sodium, 0 fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
BALSAMIC SYRUP
</P>
<P>
   Store any extra syrup in the refrigerator. Use on grilled
vegetables.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   1 cup good quality balsamic vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup finely minced shallots
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Combine the vinegar and shallots in a nonreactive saucepan over
low heat. Gently simmer until the liquid is reduced to about 1/3
cup, increasing the heat slightly at the end, but watching
carefully to avoid scorching. This should take about 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Strain the syrup, pressing on the shallots to extract as much
liquid as possible.
</P>
<P>
   Yields about 1/3 cup.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER TABLESPOON: &LR;   &LR; 83 calories, &LR;   &LR; 0 protein, 0 carbohydrate, 0 &LR; 
 &LR; fat (0 saturated), 0 cholesterol, 0 sodium, 0 fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-17-00 1256EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
