</P>
<P>
   By Stephanie Strom. (An early version of this story will move by
3 p.m. EDT.)
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-BANK (Tokyo) _ The Japanese government is expected to
announce as early as Thursday that an investment group run by
Wilbur L. Ross, one of America's leading bankruptcy specialists,
has been chosen to acquire Kofuku Bank, a regional bank in Osaka
that failed last year. By Stephanie Strom.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `e' news category or as indicated)
</P>
<P>
   FILMS-CANNES (Cannes) _ Though one could lose several nights'
sleep just trying to see all of the films in competition at this
year's Cannes Film Festival, there are great movie finds outside of
the main event. By Elvis Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   POPE-BIRTHDAY (Rome) _ On May 18th the pope turns 80, a
milestone that also falls in a Holy Year of the Roman Catholic
Church, and the Vatican has prepared a day-long religious and
musical extravaganza. Among the chief conspirators in the
celebration is Gilbert Levine, a Jewish, Brooklyn-born conductor,
who is so comfortable inside the Vatican he refers to audiences
with the pope as ``going upstairs.'' By Alessandra Stanley. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DESIGNER-CAMERAS (Undated) _ The toy-like I-zone and its
instant-camera siblings, the larger Popshot and Joycam, mark a
radical departure for Polaroid, whose success in the 1960s and 70s
was based on technological innovation. Now its innovations are
coming from design, according to David Laituri, Polaroid's manager
of design strategy, who offered a peek at Polaroid's future. By
Phil Patton.
</P>
