<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUMMER-MOVIES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     AS SUMMER BECKONS, SO DOES HOLLYWOOD 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By AMY BIANCOLLI  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Summer, in case the long, cold winter left forgetfulness in its
wake, means two things. One is barbecuing. The other is movies.
</P>
<P>
   The calendar tells us it isn't summer yet, of course. For that,
we have to wait until June 21, a disheartening four weeks off. But
Hollywood has different ideas about the tilt of Earth and the
passage of time, and for its purposes (not to mention ours), the
hot season has already arrived.
</P>
<P>
   It came with ``Gladiator.'' It comes again with ``Mission:
Impossible 2,'' due for release May 24. It comes with every
mega-mondo tub of popcorn doused with extra butter _ or whatever
that stuff is _ and it comes with the seasonal opening of drive-in
theaters. It comes with _ dare we say it _ hope.
</P>
<P>
   It's with hope that the summer movies below are listed. As ever,
this isn't a complete list; it isn't a projection of box-office
potential; it isn't a prediction of who or what's going to win
which Oscar next March. It is, however, a sample of just a few
movies that this lone critic is looking forward to seeing in the
months ahead.
</P>
<P>
   (Please note the following list does not include ``The
Patriot,'' Mel Gibson's rah-rah Revolutionary War epic, due for
release June 30. This omission is neither accidental nor meant to
slight Monsieur Gibson, whose output, be it good or bad, always
merits critical and box-office attention. Mel is fine. War movies
are fine. Less fine: Roland Emmerich and Dean Devlin, the
directing-producing duo that brought ``Independence Day'' and
``Godzilla'' unto the masses.)
</P>
<P>
   _ M:I-2 (MISSION: IMPOSSIBLE 2, May 24). Cool trailer. Cool
sunglasses. Cool rock-climbing stunt. Cool director (John Woo).
Cool Cruise. Cool Rhames. Cool Hopkins. Cool music. (Bum. Bum.
BUH-DUH. Bum. Bum. BUH-DUH.) And anyway, it's gotta be better than
the first one, right?
</P>
<P>
   _ CHICKEN RUN (June 23). From Nick Park, the Oscar-winning
animator who blessed the world with the Wallace and Gromit shorts
(``The Wrong Trousers,'' ``A Close Shave''), comes his claymation
debut feature _ about hens on a Yorkshire farm who revolt against
Mr. and Mrs. Tweedy, their murderous farmers. Mel Gibson provides
the voice of a cocky rooster. And you wondered why we didn't
include ``The Patriot.''
</P>
<P>
   _ THE PERFECT STORM (June 30). Three reasons to see this movie:
(1.) It's based on Sebastian Junger's devastatingly good nonfiction
account of the wreck of the fishing boat Andrea Gail. (2.) It's
directed by Wolfgang Petersen (``Das Boot''), who knows a thing or
two about seaborne vessels. And (3.) The trailer. Check out that
wave, mon.
</P>
<P>
   _ THE HOLLOW MAN (July 28). Call it morbid curiosity, but the
prospect of seeing James Whale's (and H.G. Wells') classic
``Invisible Man'' remade by yeccch-merchant Paul Verhoeven
(``Showgirls,'' ``Starship Troopers'') gives some of us goosebumps.
And that's not necessarily a bad thing. Certainly Kevin Bacon isn't
a bad thing, though it remains to be seen whether his take on the
mad scientist is as sympathetically human, or as enduring, as
Claude Rains'.
</P>
<P>
   _ THE LEGEND OF BAGGER VANCE (Aug. 4). Notwithstanding Robert
Redford's penchant for hiring ethereal blond actors who look like
cryogenically preserved mini-Bobs, there's every reason to be
hopeful about this mystical golf drama. Matt Damon (who got cast
after Redford decided he was too old) plays a World War I hero who
tackles a golf tournament; the ever-genial Will Smith plays his
wise and eerie caddy. Who knows how it'll do at the box office, and
who cares? We're intrigued.
</P>
<P>
   _ CECIL B. DEMENTED (Aug. 11). Bad-taste virtuoso John Waters
makes ... an action movie? So says he; are you convinced? Melanie
Griffith and Stephen Dorff join Waters regulars Ricki Lake and
Patricia Hearst in some kind of sick-boy variation on a Hollywood
blockbuster. Dorff plays the titular independent filmmaker who
kidnaps Griffith in the name of art. Plus, great title _ a spoof on
Waters' nickname, bestowed upon him by some crank of a critic.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Amy Biancolli is the film critic for the Albany Times Union,
P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212. Her electronic mail address is
abiancolli(at)timesunion.com, or call 518-454-5738.)
</P>
</TEXT>
