<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 13:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7562 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-TV-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      05-17 1302
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     ABC BANKS ON `MILLIONAIRE' 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (EDs: Note optional trim.)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By TIM GOODMAN  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a move that should surprise no one following the desperate
and lucky adventures of ABC, the network has announced that it will
spray ``Who Wants To Be a Millionaire'' around the schedule on four
nights instead of three, thus using the most powerful weapon in its
arsenal to get ratings.
</P>
<P>
   The Regis Philbin-hosted game show was the major story of the
1999-2000 television season as ABC pointed it at _ and destroyed _
virtually everything in its path.
</P>
<P>
   The show's success masked poor performances elsewhere on the
schedule and this latest move by ABC, which will add only four new
series next fall, proves it intends to ride its workhorse until the
fad wears thin, if it ever does.
</P>
<P>
   ABC is canceling ``Sports Night,'' the acclaimed half-hour
comedy (which is expected to get picked up by HBO), and dismantling
its youth-themed ``TGIF'' line-up on Fridays. In addition, ABC will
follow the lead of NBC and fill fewer slots with newsmagazines,
taking an hour back from the schedule. The popularity of
newsmagazines has waned because of overexposure and the impact of
game shows and other reality programming.
</P>
<P>
   ABC presented its fall schedule Tuesday at the so-called
``up-fronts'' in New York, where networks showcase new shows to
advertisers who then allot ad money based on how well (or not) they
believe the shows will perform. ABC will finish this season as the
No. 1 ranked network, thanks almost exclusively to ``Who Wants To
Be a Millionaire.''
</P>
<P>
   The ratings champ customarily gains an increase in advertising
revenue with the win and ABC's decision to stick with Regis and the
``Millionaire'' sensation didn't raise any eyebrows.
</P>
<P>
   In other moves, ABC will make Fridays a kind of guy-themed
comedy night instead of its long-running and once-successful
attempt to attract teens and families. ``Norm'' will move to
Fridays from Wednesdays.
</P>
<P>
   Also, continuing last season's slot-sharing, ABC will air ``Once
and Again'' in the Tuesday night ``NYPD Blue'' time, then shift
that burgeoning hit to Mondays when ``Monday Night Football'' ends.
``NYPD Blue'' will then be launched in its familiar position, but
not until January. After complaining about the time-sharing last
year, ``NYPD Blue'' series creator Steven Bochco took to the idea
primarily because ABC devoted a lot of advertising to the series
and it didn't have to air many reruns. It was a blunder that turned
golden when both shows got solid numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Of the new fiction series ABC will bring out in the fall, three
of them have serious star-power behind them. Geena Davis, Gabriel
Byrne and Andre Braugher will each appear in shows made for them.
Three of the new shows are comedies and ABC will bring out an
additional three sitcoms as midseason replacements, continuing what
appears to be a network trend back to comedies after two seasons
dominated by hour-long dramas.
</P>
<P>
   The three midseason comedies are:
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The Joan Cusack Show,'' starring the comic actress as a
confused romantic on the verge of getting married. The series is
produced by James L. Brooks (``The Simpsons,'' ``Jerry Maguire,''
``As Good as It Gets'') and has a fine pedigree.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Leary,'' the working title of a new show geared around comic
Denis Leary, who plays _ surprise _ a bitter, acerbic and
semi-crazed New York cop who thinks the world has gone mad,
prompting him to rant about it a lot and believe he's the only sane
one left. Nobody else agrees.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``My Wife and Kids,'' starring Damon Wayans (``In Living
Color'') as a father who thought he had a normal, ``Leave It To
Beaver'' type family, but finds that his stay-at-home wife (Tisha
Campbell-Martin) has become a day trading pro and his kids are
either rebelling or making fun of him. A family comedy that, on
paper, seems about as predictable as it sounds.
</P>
<P>
   While ABC has some big names on its roster, TV has proven
regularly that stars don't necessarily translate into instant hits.
The network is gambling strongly, then, that the country still has
millions of viewers who want to be a millionaire.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here's a rundown of ABC's shows, night by night:
</P>
<P>
   MONDAY: ``Monday Night Football'' and ``20/20'' (the programs
will be swapped depending on the time zone.)
</P>
<P>
   TUESDAY: ``Who Wants To Be a Millionaire'' begins its onslaught
here, followed by ``Dharma &AMP; Greg,'' then the new series ``Geena.''
That series stars Davis as a power woman in New York who meets the
man of her dreams (Peter Horton from ``thirtysomething'') who just
happens to have two kids. Trying to balance kids while keeping her
independence and love of the city and her friends is the gist of
this modern day take on motherhood and having a career. Mimi Rogers
also stars. Why the show is called ``Geena'' and her character is
called ``Teddie'' is something we can't figure. ``Once and
Again''/``NYPD Blue'' fill out the rest of the night.
</P>
<P>
   WEDNESDAY: ``Who Wants To Be a Millionaire'' opens the night,
followed by ``Drew Carey'' and the revamped ``Spin City,'' which
finds Charlie Sheen joining the cast. Then, ABC's new drama is
``Gideon's Crossing'' starring Braugher, last seen on network
television as the riveting Detective Pembleton on ``Homicide: Life
on the Street.'' In this new drama, Braugher plays Ben Gideon, an
icon of a doctor and teacher who is both compassionate and
demanding. Ruben Blades co-stars. It sounds like a perfect
larger-than-life vehicle for Braugher, but the question will be
whether viewers will take to another hospital drama.
</P>
<P>
   THURSDAY: Whether ABC is throwing in the towel against NBC's
revamped ``must-see'' line-up on Thursday remains to be seen. But
the network is putting on back-to-back episodes of ``Whose Line Is
It Anyway?'' _ a decent performer, but not worth a double-dose _
before rolling out another ``Who Wants To Be a Millionaire.'' ABC's
newsmagazine, ``Primetime Thursday,'' finishes the night.
</P>
<P>
   FRIDAY: This is ABC's biggest shake-up as it tries to target
guys staying home with a little comedy. The endlessly bad ``Two
Guys and a Girl'' kicks off the night, followed by the new sitcom,
``People Who Fear People.'' The series stars David Krumholtz (``The
Ice Storm'' ``The Santa Clause'') and Brad Raider (nobody you know)
as two buddies who fear the world is out to get them. Their friend
(Paget Brewster) just happens to be a therapist and she spends her
time telling them not to be so paranoid. But they believe that a
new next door neighbor (Jon Cryer) is a spy keeping track of them.
In fact, he is. ``Norm'' follows on this new night. The Norm
MacDonald show had been on the bubble, but survived. It's followed
by ``Madigan Men,'' a sitcom starring Irish actor Byrne (``The
Usual Suspects'') as a recently divorced architect in New York who
is clueless about the dating world and hasn't figured out that
women adore him. Hmmm. He gets tips from his 16-year-old son, who
is juggling girlfriends, and his recently widowed and very
opinionated father, who moves in with them. This series comes from
Cindy Chupak, who was a writer on ``Sex and the City.'' The night
is closed out by ``20/20.''
</P>
<P>
   SATURDAY: ABC keeps its ``Big Picture Show'' theme, airing
theatrical films.
</P>
<P>
   SUNDAY: This is a potential blockbuster night for ABC as ``The
Wonderful World of Disney'' leads into ``Who Wants To Be a
Millionaire'' (which scores well with families) and ends with ``The
Practice.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Tim Goodman is the television critic for the San Francisco
Examiner, P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic
mail address is goodman(at)examiner.com).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
