<DOCNO> NYT20000517.0106 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 13:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7582 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r d BC-WINE-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      05-17 1002
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     AFFORDABLE WINES THAT STILL PLEASE THE PALATE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MICHAEL LONSFORD  
 &HT;     c.2000 Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   I met a fellow who said something nice about the wine column,
then followed up with, ``But I sure wish you wouldn't write about
such obscure wines. They can be hard to find.''
</P>
<P>
   And he had a point _ up to a point. I didn't bother to go into a
long spiel about how interesting wine is to me, how I love to
discover little-known but flavorful wines, that I'm not one to
settle for drinking the same wine, day after boring day.
</P>
<P>
   One of the best things about wine is its diversity: of flavors,
of origins, of quality. But a lot of people who also like wine
aren't interested in all those aspects; all they want is a
good-tasting glass of wine with their meal that doesn't cost an arm
and a leg.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe you do like a glass of wine with dinner, but you really
don't care so much about where it comes from as you do how much it
costs and will it go with tonight's meatloaf.
</P>
<P>
   As much as I dislike ``shopping lists'' of wines, there comes a
time when they can be useful. So here's one of available wines that
may not set the world on fire but that are consistently well-made.
And not expensive, either. All of them may not constitute what
Shakespeare called ``a world-without-end bargain,'' but they're in
just about every wine-lover's financial reach. Almost all of the
wines today will be less than $15 a bottle; sometimes a lot less.
</P>
<P>
   And while vintages matter a great deal with First Growth
Bordeaux and grand cru white burgundies, they're less important
with these wines.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the main thing to consider with these wines is to get
the latest vintage.
</P>
<P>
   _ Sparkling wines
</P>
<P>
   Imported: Rotari from Italy; Cristalino, Segura Viudas, Paul
Cheneau and Aria from Spain; Willm Cremant d'Alsace and Bouvet from
France.
</P>
<P>
   Domestic: Domaine Chandon, Domaine Ste. Michele, Gloria Ferrer,
Gruet, CapRock.
</P>
<P>
   _ White zinfandel
</P>
<P>
   Buehler (pretty dry, may be hard to find but worth the search),
Beringer (fruity and off-dry, but not as sweet as many others.
</P>
<P>
   _ Rose
</P>
<P>
   Imported: Chivite's Gran Feudo and Marques de Caceres from
Spain, Domaine Tempier, Chateau Mourgues du Gres and Chateau
d'Aqueria Tavel Rose from France, Regaleali Rosato from Italy.
</P>
<P>
   Domestic: Pedroncelli Zinfandel Rose, Joseph Phelps Grenache
Rose.
</P>
<P>
   _ Chardonnay
</P>
<P>
   Imported: Louis Latour Ardeche, Fortant de France and Reserve
St. Martin from France; Antinori Castello della Sala from Italy;
Bulletin Place and Preece from Australia; KWV Cathedral Cellars
from South Africa; Caliterra, Casa Lapostolle, Errazuriz, Catena,
Santa Ema and Montes from South America; Brancott and Omaka Springs
from New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
   Domestic (in no particular order): Clos du Bois, Bandiera,
Belvedere, De Loach, Adler Fels, Dry Creek Vineyards, Markham,
Gundlach-Bundschu, Gloria Ferrer, Ravenswood, Rabbit Ridge, William
Hill, Gallo of Sonoma, Anapamu, Zabaco, Chateau Woltner, CapRock,
Benziger, DeLorimier, Edna Valley, Freemark Abbey, Chateau St.
Jean, Geyser Peak, Sebastiani Sonoma Cask, Rodney Strong, Toad
Hollow, Wente, Messina Hof, Meridian, Schuetz Oles, Escondido
Valley, Llano Estacado, Simi, Hess Select, Raymond, Hogue and J.
Lohr.
</P>
<P>
   _ Sauvignon Blanc:
</P>
<P>
   Imported: Chateau de Sancerre, Michel Redde Pouilly Fume and
Chateau Bonnet Blanc from France; Grove Mill, Nautilus, Villa
Maria, Sacred Hill and Kim Crawford from New Zealand; Taltarni from
Australia; Casa Lapotolle from Chile; Neil Ellis from South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Domestic: Canyon Road, Huntington, Barnwood, Geyser Peak,
Murphy-Goode, Concannon, Callaway, Buena Vista, Kendall-Jackson,
Markham, Kenwood, Parducci, Quivira, St. Supery.
</P>
<P>
   _ Other whites
</P>
<P>
   Imported: Domaine Saint Peyre Picpoul de Pinet, 1995 Muscadet
``Clos des Rosiers Vieilles Vignes (old vines),'' A. Mann Pinot
Auxerrois, Trimbach Pinot Blanc, Trimbach Riesling, Hugel Riesling,
Schleret Pinot Blanc, Jaja de Jau Blanc, Domaine de Triennes
Viognier, Macon La Roche from the Chateau de la Greffiere, Abbaye
de Valmagne Blanc from France; Villa Frattina, Stella and Bollini
Pinot Grigio from Italy; Montecillo Cumbrero Blanco and Torres
Grand Via Sol from Spain.
</P>
<P>
   Domestic: DeLorimier Spectrum, Adler Fels Gewurztraminer, Geyser
Peak Gewurztraminer, Husch Chenin Blanc, Chappellet Chenin Blanc,
Fall Creek Chenin Blanc, Messina Hof Riesling, Wild Horse Pinot
Blanc, Murphy-Goode Pinot Blanc, R.H. Phillips Viognier, Jekel
Riesling, Chateau Ste. Michele Riesling.
</P>
<P>
   _ Cabernet Sauvignon
</P>
<P>
   Imported: Jaja de Jau Rouge, Chateau Haut Fabregues, Chateau
Tour de Grenet Lussac from France; Backsberg Cabernet, Cathedral
Cellars Cabernet from South Africa; Casa Lapostolle Cabernet, Santa
Ema Cabernet, Montes Cabernet from Chile; Wynn's Cabernet from
Australia.
</P>
<P>
   Domestic: Bandiera, Chateau Souverain, Mondavi Coastal, Seven
Peaks, Gallo-Sonoma, J. Lohr, Hess Select, Charles Krug, Beaulieu
Napa.
</P>
<P>
   _ Other reds
</P>
<P>
   Imported: Santa Joana Bairrada from Portugal, Tommasi and Zenato
Valpolicella, Badia a Coltibuono Cetamura Chianti, Nozzole Chianti
Classico and Vetrice Chianti Rufina from Italy, Rosemount Shiraz
from Australia, Alamos Ridge Malbec from Argentina, Montes Merlot
and Caliterra Merlot from Chile; Guigal, Delas, Jaboulet and
Moillard Cotes du Rhone and Domaine de Valmoissine Pinot Noir
(Louis Latour) from France.
</P>
<P>
   Domestic: Laurel Glen ``Reds,'' Quivira Zinfandel, Quivira Dry
Creek Cuvee, Ramsay Pinot Noir, Seghesio Zinfandel, Sebastiani
Barbera, Fall Creek Passionelle, Ravenswood ``Vintners Blend''
Zinfandel, Beringer ``Founder's Estate'' Pinot Noir, Bogle Petite
Sirah, Montevia Zinfandel, Cambria Syrah, Cline Cotes d'Oakley,
Rosenblum Vintners Cuvee Zinfandel, Pedroncelli Zinfandel, Echelon
Pinot Noir, Meridian Pinot Noir, Meridian Merlot.
</P>
<P>
   These are just a handful of wines out there from which to
choose, but they all represent good value _ and consistency.
</P>
</TEXT>
