<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 13:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7584 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r d BC-CAMPFIRE-STEW-HNS &LR;      05-17 0272
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPFIRE-STEW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     VENISON STEW FOR THE CAMPFIRE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By RALPH WININGHAM  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Leftovers normally aren't a problem around the hunting or
fishing camps I have been fortunate enough to visit.
</P>
<P>
   However, there are times when a little bit of this and a little
bit of that seems to be overlooked by the ravenous horde after they
have laid waste to an evening meal.
</P>
<P>
   On one of these occasions, I managed to salvage some of my
homemade barbecue sauce and a little bit of cheese, which I used in
the following dish.
</P>
<P>
   This is a good way to prepare your stew meat and is tasty served
over boiled potatoes or noodles.
</P>
<P>
   Store-bought barbecue sauce can be substituted if you don't want
to go to the trouble of making your own.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   BETTER BARBECUED VENISON
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds venison stew meat
</P>
<P>
   seasoned flour
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons bacon grease
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cup chopped onion
</P>
<P>
   2 cloves garlic, minced
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon each red and black pepper
</P>
<P>
   salt, to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 cup beef broth
</P>
<P>
   1 cup water
</P>
<P>
   1 cup barbecue sauce
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup shredded cheddar cheese
</P>
<P>
   1 cup fresh mushrooms, sliced
</P>
<P>
   Cut the stew meat into 1-inch cubes. Place in plastic bag with
seasoned flour and shake well to coat. Heat bacon grease in a deep
cast-iron skillet over medium heat. Brown floured meat on all
sides, then add onion and garlic. Continue browning until onion is
transparent. Add remaining ingredients, except for the mushrooms,
stir well and reduce heat to simmer for about one hour. Add
mushrooms and simmer for another 15 minutes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
