<HEADLINE>
REBEL LEADER CAPTURED IN SIERRA LEONE 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed.) 
 By CHRISTOPHER S. WREN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ The rebel leader Foday Sankoh, who vanished
nine days ago during a violent confrontation outside his Freetown
home, was captured Wednesday by pro-government soldiers who
stripped him of his clothes before locking him up.
</P>
<P>
   Word of his capture triggered spontaneous celebrations in the
streets of Freetown, where residents have lived in fear of an
assault on the capital by the Revolutionary United Front, Sankoh's
insurgent fighters. The rebels have gained notoriety for committing
atrocities like mutilating and dismembering civilians.
</P>
<P>
   The Sierra Leone government, whose forces have been battling the
rebels since a peace accord achieved last July broke down this
month, asked the British troops deployed in the capital to protect
British nationals to transport Sankoh to safety after a mob
gathered outside the police barracks where he was being held. A
British helicopter flew Sankoh to Lungi Airport, which is held by
British paratroopers, where he was transferred to safer police
custody.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has been taken to a secure location,'' a spokesman for the
British force, Lt. Cmdr. Tony Cramp, told news agencies. ``He is in
the custody of the Sierra Leone police. He's been taken to that
place in a British helicopter.''
</P>
<P>
   Cramp was quoted as saying that the rebel leader's captors had
taken away his clothes to humiliate him.
</P>
<P>
   Sankoh disappeared on May 8 after his bodyguards shot into a
crowd of several thousand people who were protesting in front of
his Freetown residence, killing several demonstrators. There had
been speculation that he was dead, had escaped to a rebel-held area
or was being held by the government.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear what will happen next to Sankoh, who still holds
ministerial rank in the coalition government that was cobbled
together as part of the peace agreement. Authorities in Freetown
have accused him of plotting another coup but have not formally
charged him with any crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's now a matter for the Sierra Leone government and the U.N.
to decide what should happen,'' Cramp said.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the United Nations mission in Sierra Leone,
David Wimhurst, said the United Nations had played no part in
capturing Sankoh. ``The U.N. is in no way involved in this
apprehension,'' Wimhurst said at a news conference in Freetown.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. officials are expected to urge Sankoh to facilitate the
release of an estimated 347 peacekeeping troops and military
observers who have been detained by rebel fighters since the
beginning of the month.
</P>
<P>
   Another 157 detained U.N. peacekeepers were released after the
intervention of Liberia's president, Charles Taylor, who has been
close to Sankoh.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Britain's foreign secretary, Robin Cook, welcomed Sankoh's
arrest, saying that it has deprived the rebellion in Sierra Leone
of its leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope that we may be able to stabilize Sierra Leone and
reverse rebel advances,'' Cook told reporters during a visit to
Moscow. ``To do that, we need to have a strong and effective U.N.
mission on the ground.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday at 12:45 a.m., 25 British paratroopers clashed for the
first time with rebels, killing at least three attackers in a
firefight that lasted 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Britain has maintained that its troops have been sent to
evacuate British nationals and will not assume a combat role, but
they are permitted to shoot back if attacked.
</P>
<P>
   Other fighting was reported between the rebels and Sierra
Leone's army and pro-government militia at Port Loko, about 40
miles northeast of the airport.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
