<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTO-OFF-ROAD-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     MOUNTAIN COURSE OFFERS FOUR-WHEELING LESSONS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By G. CHAMBERS WILLIAMS III  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WHITE SULPHUR SPRINGS, W.Va. _ Where the pavement ends, the fun
begins.
</P>
<P>
   That's the creed of most four-wheel-drive enthusiasts, who think
nothing of driving on the highway for hours or even days just to
get to a great spot where they can leave the hard surface behind
and venture into paradise: an off-road trail that embodies the
concept of ``the road less traveled.''
</P>
<P>
   Southwestern off-roaders know some of the best places to go: the
San Juan Mountains around Ouray, Colo.; the Arches National Park
near Moab, Utah; the Rubicon Trail across Northern California's
Sierra Nevada range; and the Anza-Borrego Desert State Park near
San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   But not all of the best four-wheeling is found in the West. The
professionals who operate the Land Rover Driving School at the
Greenbrier resort here are sold on the off-road trails of the
Appalachian Mountains, particularly those on the resort's own 6,500
acres in Greenbrier County, in the southeast corner of the Mountain
State.
</P>
<P>
   Nestled in the Allegheny range of the Appalachians, along
Interstate 64 about 75 minutes from Roanoke, Va., the Land Rover
Driving School offers visitors a chance to learn the basics of
off-road driving on trails carved out of hardwood forests among
some of the most scenic mountain vistas on the North American
continent.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, I'm a bit prejudiced in favor of these storied mountains.
I grew up about 100 miles from here, in Charleston, W.Va., and
spent much of my free time on weekends and summer vacations
exploring the mountain trails of the Southern Appalachians in
Greenbrier and surrounding counties.
</P>
<P>
   Here, miles of unpaved fire roads and logging trails go up and
down while simultaneously making sharp turns, and it's not unusual
to top a steep hill _ with no view ahead but the sky or the tops of
trees _ and then have to make a quick turn to drop down the next
hill to cross a swift-running mountain stream.
</P>
<P>
   There is a stark contrast between the Western mountains, such as
those around Ouray and Telluride, Colo., and those of the
Appalachian chain, which stretches from northern New England to
northeastern Alabama. The Eastern mountains are green, the Western
brown. And when the foliage is at its peak, the Eastern mountains
are hard to see through.
</P>
<P>
   Nowhere is this contrast more noticeable than the mountains
around the Greenbrier, where Land Rover North America, the
distributor of the British-built Land Rover and Range Rover
sport-utility vehicles, last year set up its second permanent
off-road driving school. (The first, at The Equinox in Manchester,
Vt., has been open since 1997.)
</P>
<P>
   For an hour, a few hours or even a day or two, people who want
to learn how to drive their four-wheel-drive vehicles off road can
take lessons from one of Land Rover's professional drivers and
explore some of the most scenic trails around.
</P>
<P>
   Instruction is offered in either a Land Rover Discovery II or a
Range Rover, and both are capable of negotiating just about
anything the rugged Appalachians have to offer. The cost is $150
for the first hour, then $100 per hour after that, which includes
the vehicle and the instructor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's absolutely fun and some of the most gorgeous scenery I've
ever encountered,'' Ken Sutton, an insurance agent from Clinton,
N.C., said as he drove one of the Greenbrier's trails last week
during his first off-road lesson, in a Range Rover.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was staying at the Greenbrier for a business conference and
saw the signs about the driving school,'' he said. ``I got all
excited and went to check it out. I own a four-wheel-drive pickup,
but I've never done any off-roading like this, and I would have
been afraid to do it on my own. Until you have someone like these
instructors show you how to do this, you just don't realize how
capable these vehicles can be.''
</P>
<P>
   Only about 40 percent of the people who take lessons at the
school are Land Rover or Range Rover owners, said Bob Burns,
manager of off-road programs for Land Rover North America or, as he
likes to put it, ``Land Rover's vice president of mud.''
</P>
<P>
   The rest are people who may or may not own an off-road-capable
vehicle, but who want the experience of driving on some truly
challenging and beautiful terrain, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our main role here is to educate people on the proper use of
four-wheel drive,'' Burns said. ``Most Range Rovers aren't usually
taken off road, except by some wealthy ranchers in Texas who
occasionally use theirs to haul hay.''
</P>
<P>
   With the prices of Range Rovers beginning in the upper $50,000s
and Land Rovers starting in the low $30,000s, owners often are
reluctant to take them off road for fear of damaging them. But
that's true of most of today's family sport-utilities, whose prices
average in the low- to mid-$30,000s.
</P>
<P>
   ``We teach people how to drive them off road safely, without
damaging them, so they can truly enjoy what their vehicles are
capable of,'' Burns said. ``This is not the high-speed,
wheels-in-the-air experience like some of the TV ads; if we hit 5
mph, that's the land speed record for the day.''
</P>
<P>
   Sane and sensible off-road exploring is much different from the
jump-and-splash driving that teen-age boys enjoy with mud puddles
and their four-wheel-drive pickups. This experience is for seeing
new and different terrain that isn't accessible by the average car;
and slow-and-easy is the theme of the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``We say that you should drive as slow as you possibly can, but
as fast as you need to,'' said instructor Fred Monsees, a veteran
of the annual Land Rover Camel Trophy worldwide off-road driving
championship competition. ``The gentler you are with your right
foot, the better your off-road experience will be.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Leaving the driving school's headquarters at the Greenbrier's
Hunt Club, the vehicles head down a dirt road and then across
Howard's Creek to reach the off-road trails that wind through the
mountains.
</P>
<P>
   Rule No. 1: ``When we say `Stop,' we mean stop,'' Monsees says.
``Not in a few seconds, but now. Right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Crossing Howard's Creek is the first cool move in the day's
drive. It's more than a foot deep and about 300 feet wide, with a
rocky bottom. Before starting across, the vehicle is shifted into
four-wheel-drive low range, where it will remain for most of the
day.
</P>
<P>
   ``These vehicles have a maximum wading depth of 20 inches, so
we're fine here,'' Monsees says as the Range Rover starts into the
water. The driver is a bit tentative, however, so Monsees urges him
along. ``You've got to keep up a bit of momentum in the water so
you don't bog down,'' he says. ``You need to be going fast enough
to generate a bow wave.''
</P>
<P>
   The vehicle comes out of the water and up a bank, then makes a
sharp right turn down a steep, muddy hill. Before descending, the
vehicle's automatic transmission is put into low gear, which,
combined with the low-range mode of the Range Rover's two-speed
transfer case, allows engine braking to hold the speed to about 5
mph without having to use the foot brakes.
</P>
<P>
   Slowly the vehicle moves through the creekbed at the bottom of
the hill, with the driver using gentle left-foot braking before
dropping into the streambed to prevent the rear of the vehicle from
bottoming out. Then, he shifts into third gear for the climb up the
next hill, with enough momentum _ but not too much _ to negotiate a
bit of mud on the slope.
</P>
<P>
   ``You need to go slow enough to figure out what you need to do
as you come to each challenge, whether it is a steep hill, sharp
curve or stream crossing,'' Monsees says. ``Before you make that
move, there are four steps to work through: identify the problem,
predict the vehicle's reaction, decide on the best course and
execute the move.''
</P>
<P>
   It's as simple as that, but you don't go charging into anything
without due consideration first, he explains.
</P>
<P>
   There's lots of time for stopping to enjoy the landscape and
even the wildlife.
</P>
<P>
   We crane our necks when a passenger in the rear yells, ``Look at
that huge snake!''
</P>
<P>
   Instructor Jim Swett yells, ``Stop,'' and the driver complies.
Right now.
</P>
<P>
   Swett, a Connecticut native, jumps out and turns to me, a
born-and-bred West Virginian, and asks, ``What kind of snake is it?
It is poisonous?''
</P>
<P>
   ``No, it's not dangerous,'' I say. ``It's just a blacksnake. Its
bite will hurt a little, but it's not poisonous and it won't kill
you.''
</P>
<P>
   That's enough for Swett, who takes a long stick and holds down
the snake's head, then reaches behind the head and picks it up. Six
feet of sinewy snake body wind around his arm, and the snake's
yellow eyes look with contempt at its tormentor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels like a constrictor,'' he says, looking again for
reassurance that he is going to be OK.
</P>
<P>
   The group of vehicles following has stopped, and the people from
them have gathered around for a look. Then, with a huge laugh,
Swett drops the snake on the hood of a Range Rover surrounded by
the gawkers. It dives for the ground, the people scatter, and it
slithers into the woods.
</P>
<P>
   Back at the Hunt Club later, the day's ``student'' drivers get
to exchange stories and pat each other on the back for their
successful off-road maneuvers. Some made the climb up some of the
muddy hills on the first try, others took four or five attempts.
Some didn't make it at all, and they get some good-natured ribbing.
</P>
<P>
   Sutton, the insurance agent from North Carolina, sums up his
experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really enjoyed it,'' he said. ``I'd recommend it to anyone.
And I will be back.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Contact G. Chambers Williams III by telephone at 210-250-3236
or by e-mail chambers(at)express-news.net)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
