<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 13:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7648 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r p BC-HILLARY-CLINTON-HNS &LR;      05-17 1120
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HILLARY-CLINTON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     DEMOCRATS BACK FIRST LADY IN HISTORIC NOMINATION 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By LARA JAKES  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ New York Democrats nominated Hillary Rodham
Clinton as their U.S. Senate candidate in a historic convention
filled with presidential pomp, speeches from a star-studded cast of
politicians and a few glancing blows at a GOP opponent who may not
even wind up in the race.
</P>
<P>
   The only first lady ever to run for office overshadowed even the
president as she gained the unanimous backing of the delegates amid
the cheers of a heady crowd that packed the Pepsi Arena Tuesday
night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Make no mistake _ this election is not about me or any
Republican opponent,'' Clinton said during her 38-minute acceptance
speech. ``It's about the people of New York and our common
mission.''
</P>
<P>
   Boasting of a party for once unified behind one candidate,
officials assiduously avoided any mention of New York Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani or the personal woes that threaten to sideline him from
the race. But the first lady drew a subtle comparison between
herself and Giuliani in an uncharacteristically public display of
devotion to her spouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am delighted that the president is here,'' said candidate
Clinton, looking to the side of the stage at her husband, who had
abruptly decided Tuesday morning to accompany his wife at her
political coronation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am so grateful for his support,'' she added. ``I would not
be standing here tonight were it not for Bill and were it not for
all he has done for me.''
</P>
<P>
   The president sat silently behind his wife throughout the
speech, then joined her at the podium for the tumultuous ovation
from the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   While the Clintons' relationship has been under public scrutiny
for years, it was Giuliani's marriage that became the focus of the
Senate race this week after he revealed a relationship with another
woman and announced he was separating from his wife of 16 years. In
the aftermath of his recent prostate cancer diagnosis, Giuliani was
still deliberating whether he will compete in a race that had
rivaled this year's presidential contest in terms of national
interest.
</P>
<P>
   While Democrats were careful to not directly lash out at
Giuliani, they opted instead to criticize all things Republican.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton defined the party's mission as improving schools,
providing affordable health care, strengthening families, creating
more jobs and a slew of other themes she has sounded from the stump
since she first began campaigning 10 months ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``As I said before, it's not about candidates. It's about
children; it's about families; it's about our future,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The biennial convention drew 11,500 supporters and other party
faithful _ 10 times the number of attendees at the last Democratic
convention in 1998. Despite threatened challenges from two
virtually unknown hopefuls, Clinton was unanimously selected as the
party's official designee by the 352 delegates on the convention
floor. Hers was the only name offered for consideration.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The night, however, grew long on hundreds of convention-goers
who grew impatient with the litany of speeches by virtually every
top Democratic official in New York. By 8 p.m. _ a full 90 minutes
before Clinton took the stage _ the rowdy crowd began chanting ``We
want Hillary.''
</P>
<P>
   That was a relief to convention organizers who initially feared
the president's appearance would overshadow the spotlight of the
first sitting first lady to run for elected office. But pandemonium
reigned in the arena when both Clintons took the stage to the
strains of ``The Natural.'' They exited to a balloon and confetti
drop and ``Chariots of Fire.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's very effective to have so many people here,''
said delegate Betty Momrow, secretary of Albany County's Democratic
Committee. ``It shows there's support for her, I hope. I know I've
been getting so many calls from people wanting to volunteer and
help out. ... Daniel Patrick (Moynihan) has been a wonderful
senator; he's done a wonderful job. And I think she can continue to
do it.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, the retiring Moynihan delivered a relatively
sedate yet classy farewell after 24 years in the Senate. Moynihan's
wife, Liz, as she has been throughout his tenure, was at his side
in saying goodbye.
</P>
<P>
   When they first began, he reminisced, it was ``Liz running the
campaign; me doing as told,'' he quipped. ``For now, we say
goodbye. We thank our party for a great run.''
</P>
<P>
   The soon-to-be senior senator from New York, Charles Schumer,
took a different tack in his speech nominating Clinton. In a
melodramatic deadpan toward the end of his speech, Schumer asked
for a moment of silence.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know what that sound you just heard is?'' he asked. ``It's
the sound of Republican headquarters on election eve when Hillary
Clinton is elected United States senator from New York.''
</P>
<P>
   Schumer also took a veiled swipe at the unapologetically
confrontational mayor in his speech, describing New York as a
``melting pot'' in need of culturally sensitive leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``For this, the most complicated and diverse place on Earth to
really work, people need and want to get along,'' the senator said.
``It is all to easy to pit one group against another, to find a
scapegoat for the problems in New York City, but divisiveness won't
solve a single problem.''
</P>
<P>
   State Republicans are scheduled to hold their nominating
convention May 30 in Buffalo, but even top party leaders remain in
the dark over who will get the official GOP nod. If Giuliani drops
out of the running, Rep. Rick Lazio, a more conservative Republican
from Long Island, will be his likely replacement. He would start a
six-month countdown to Election Day with a relatively meager $3.5
million in his campaign treasury. Clinton has amassed $12 million.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Giuliani's camp received a small but much-needed morale
boost Tuesday in the form of a Quinnipiac College poll indicating
that relatively few voters would hold Giuliani's personal life
against him at the ballot box. The survey showed Clinton and
Giuliani still locked in a statistical dead heat _ unchanged from
their standings before the mayor's series of bombshell personal
revelations.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, Clinton led Giuliani in the poll 44 percent to 43
percent, within the poll's margin of error.
</P>
<P>
   ``After a year of campaigning, it remains clear that what New
Yorkers truly care about are performance and record,'' said
Giuliani spokeswoman Juleanna Glover Weiss. ``When New Yorkers
think about their futures ... they think about Rudy Giuliani.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
