<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 13:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7656 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-SBC-DSL-HNS &LR;      05-17 0401
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SBC-DSL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     SBC FINED $27 MILLION OVER INTERNET ACCESS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By VANESSA HUA  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A national arbitration board has slapped at
$27.2 million judgment against SBC Communications, the parent
company of Pacific Bell, for not delivering equipment and space to
DSL provider Covad Communications Group in a timely manner, a
violation of the Telecommunications Act of 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Santa Clara-based Covad, which provides high speed Internet
access through digital subscriber lines, or DSL, alleged that San
Antonio-based SBC Communications delayed delivering space and
equipment needed to provide service from 1997 to 1999, giving SBC
an unfair advantage in the race to offer lucrative DSL services.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of March, SBC had a total of 301,000 DSL customers
for its popular, heavily promoted service, up from 169,000 last
year.
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, Covad had about 100,000 customers at the end of
April. A large percentage of the customers for both companies are
in California.
</P>
<P>
   The penalty, issued by the American Arbitration Association on
Monday, covers Covad's lost revenue due to the delays, Covad
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Under federal law, SBC is required to offer space in central
offices for Covad equipment within four months, but instead took
six months or longer. SBC's operable loops, required to be made
available in 10 days or less, instead took 15 days or more.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were unnecessarily hampered,'' said Covad's Dhruv Khanna,
executive vice president and general counsel. ``Instead of blanket
coverage, we had Swiss cheese coverage that was not easy to market
or sell.''
</P>
<P>
   The decision comes as SBC plans to make a bid to enter the
long-distance market in California later this year. The
telecommunications company must first demonstrate to federal
regulators that it has opened its local markets to competition.
That includes giving access to competitors such as Covad on utility
poles, cables, equipment and other network elements.
</P>
<P>
   SBC plans to appeal the decision, asserting that it had already
resolved the delivery issues through the terms of its
interconnection agreement with Covad. ``They're trying to use the
Telecom Act to compensate their inability to meet their revenue
forecasts,'' said Pacific Bell spokesman John Britton. ``There's no
legal basis.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-17-00 1355EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
