<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000517.0114 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 14:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7668 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-NOLAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      05-17 0696
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOLAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAN FRANCISCO'S NEWSPAPER FIASCO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARTIN F. NOLAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO -- In 1885, while he was flunking out of Harvard,
William Randolph Hearst wrote to his father about a newspaper the
elder Hearst had bought in 1880.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have begun to have a strange fondness for our little
paper,'' Will wrote, ``a tenderness like unto that which a mother
feels for a puny or deformed offspring, and I should hate to see it
die now after it had battled so long and so nobly for existence; in
fact, to tell the truth, I am possessed of the weakness which at
some time or other in their lives pervades most men; I am convinced
that I could run a newspaper successfully.''
</P>
<P>
   On March 4, 1887, George Hearst, who made millions in the Gold
Rush, took the oath of office as US senator. On the same day, his
son became proprietor of the San Francisco Examiner, which he
christened ``The Monarch of the Dailies.'' He quickly boosted its
circulation tenfold with the splashy, free-spending Hearst formula.
Politics and journalism helped build the Hearst monarchy, but in a
San Francisco court these days, the Hearst legend is once again
puny and deformed, a sad court jester.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1965, the Examiner has been kept alive by a joint
operating agreement with the San Francisco Chronicle. A JOA exempts
partners from antitrust laws. The Ex, publishing in the afternoon,
has lost so many readers that the morning Chron now outsells its
rival, 4-1. Profits are divided 50-50. The Chron's owners decided
to sell last year, and the winning bid was Hearst's at $660
million. Whether the paper would be the Chron-Ex or the Ex-Chron,
Hearst would be in charge.
</P>
<P>
   But a former mayoral candidate, Clint Reilly, sued to prevent
Hearst from buying the Chron and ditching the Ex. The testimony
thus far is not memorable for antitrust precedent, but for one
simple concept, ``horse-trading.''
</P>
<P>
   That's what you were doing when you had lunch last August with
Mayor Willie Brown, right? Reilly's lawyer asked the Hearst honcho
for the monarchical merger, Timothy White, that question. The
Examiner publisher answered ``yes,'' confirming the suspicions of
readers and the fears of reporters and editors that credibility is
for sale.
</P>
<P>
   The next day White said he was ``tired and confused'' on the
stand. He was also fired, or ``suspended indefinitely.'' A shower
of assurances from Hearstlings about integrity and code-of-ethics
blather has not washed away a single cubit of the contempt of
readers nor the grief of writers on both newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The San Francisco Examiner is dying, and it can't even die
with dignity,'' Rob Morse, its lead columnist, wrote in Sunday's
Examiner. ``We're a failing newspaper,'' he added. ``We're even
failing at going out of business.'' In the Chron, Ken Garcia wrote:
``The real tragedy in this play is that it was set into motion
because a majority of the family owners of my newspaper, rife with
jealousy and greed, decided to unload it after 135 years of arduous
editorial battles rather than wait a few more and finally win the
war.''
</P>
<P>
   The JOA is scheduled to expire in 2005.
</P>
<P>
   In The New Yorker 40 years ago this week, A. J. Liebling defined
a central truth: ``Freedom of the press is guaranteed only to those
who own one.'' Liebling, like Hearst, is dead, and today's press
criticism is instant and conspiratorial. ``Did Tim White Act
Alone?'' asks a Lee Harvey Oswald-evoking headline in one Web site,
which alleges that the Ex went easy on the mayor after the famous
lunch at the North Beach Restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   The Hearst Corp. enjoys a good reputation among people in the
news business, many of whom hope and expect that any hint of
dissent in the judge's ruling will make it pause. ``If the judge
sneezes, Hearst should spend its $660 million elsewhere,'' one
said.
</P>
<P>
   In the May 5 New York Times, a Hearst ad quotes the founder:
``We must be alarmingly enterprising, and we must be startlingly
original.'' Today's San Francisco fiasco is probably not what he
had in mind.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Martin F. Nolan's column appears regularly in the Globe.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
