<HEADLINE>
CRUISE CAN'T `SHUT' UP; BRAVING THE `STORM' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW GILBERT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Eyes Wide Shut'' didn't succeed at the box office, and most
movie critics were bored by it. But Stanley Kubrick's final film
has done remarkably well at the box-of-sour-grapes-office, as
Kubrick fans and supporters continue to blame the movie's failure
on viewer preconceptions about Kubrick, and hype that led audiences
to expect more sex. And so the Vanity Fair cover interview with Tom
Cruise opens the ``Shut'' case once again, with Cruise continuing
to analyze what happened and why even those who know Kubrick's work
``missed it.'' The article is timed to promote Cruise's forthcoming
``Mission: Impossible 2,'' but it seems to spend more time looing
into ``Eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   Cruise also reflects in depth on his career arc, recalling the
defining moment when he learned that, despite a critical drubbing,
``Cocktail'' had made a killing at the box office during its
opening weekend. The interview is conducted by Cameron Crowe, the
writer-director who worked with Cruise on ``Jerry Maguire,'' and
Cruise seems less defensive and controlled than he generally is
with the press. But still, he is one doggedly sincere fellow, and
it appears to be hard for anyone to get him to say anything much
racier than ``it is a privilege for me to be able to do something
that I love to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Vanity Fair also picks over the bones of the beats, Jack Kerouac
to be specific. Around the time of the publication of ``On the
Road'' in the late 1950s, Kerouac had an on-again-off-again affair
with a younger writer named Joyce Glassman, now Joyce Johnson.
Allen Ginsberg fixed them up, and Kerouac was smitten, despite the
fact that he wasn't inclined to like blondes. The piece, an excerpt
from a forthcoming book, features Johnson's correspondence with
Kerouac (they spent more time apart than together), and the letters
are interwoven with her narrative chronology of their story. They
were ``together'' for a year and 10 months, during which time
Johnson fell in love with the fast-typing writer, despite his
unwillingness to commit. His letters are all about dodging
rendezvous with her (``I'm a confirmed bachelor &AMP; hermit''), trying
to write in the midst of compulsive travel and beat hype, and
railing against those barriers to creativity such as ``liverish
pale fag editors.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, here's the latest product from Beat Generation
Inc.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It was fun to see George Clooney return to ``ER'' last week,
even if that night's ads spoiled the surprise. (Alas, surprise is a
june bug in the hurricane of today's maniacal hype machine.) But
Clooney's movie-star magnitude increases with each picture he
makes, not including, of course, ``Batman &AMP; Robin.'' He doesn't
project the kind of product control and box office macho of Cruise;
just an un-Nautilized manliness and a game approach to acting in
semirisky ventures.
</P>
<P>
   His next movie is an adaptation of Sebastian Junger's ``The
Perfect Storm,'' in which he reunites with his ``Three Kings''
costar, Mark Wahlberg, for the tragic story of Gloucester's Andrea
Gail. Premiere for June talks to Clooney and Wahlberg, who are
described as sharing more of a mutual admiration society than a
friendship. ``These men seem to admire each other so much that they
can't quite relax in each other's presence,'' writes Trish Deitch
Rohrer.
</P>
<P>
   The article goes into the time the production spent in
Gloucester, where bonds were reportedly made between the filmmakers
and the locals. ``I was just imagining producers on cell phones,''
Junger says, ``striding around the Crow's Nest.'' But the ``West
Coast attitude'' never reared its head. The actors mixed with the
families of the people they portray, and the townspeople and
families participated in the memorial-service scene, which sounds
like it was a catharsis of sorts. ``I'm telling you,'' one producer
says, ``the whole town, they were weeping.''
</P>
<P>
   It also sounds like the movie doesn't tack on the kind of
feelgood ending usually associated with adventure hits. Now that's
a bit of a surprise.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``This may be her only moment, so she is working like there's no
tomorrow.'' That's the gist of Chris Mundy's look at Britney
Spears, who appears on the cover of Rolling Stone for May 24. He
portrays her as being bored as an ordinary teen, but feeling a
little guilty for having left home and family behind. She doesn't
like being viewed as a sexual object, despite her revealing
costuming; she thinks Justin from 'N Sync is ``the cutest boy in
the world'' and admits to kissing him; and she is hoping to be a
movie star. She also tells Mundy, ``I wish stories were more about
my music, instead of the personal questions.'' Somehow I think she
would get a lot less press if that particular dream came true.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
