<HEADLINE>
WOMEN GRADUATES GET THE WRONG IDEA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EILEEN MCNAMARA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just once, for a change of pace, wouldn't it be something to
hear a commencement speaker caution an audience of bright young men
against expecting to ``have it all'' in life?
</P>
<P>
   It's that season again and, across the land, college graduates
are being urged to follow their dreams, to aim high, to reach for
the stars. Well, not all college graduates. It is only at elite
women's colleges that graduates are told to choose their path
carefully, to beware the compromises ahead, to avoid the minefield
of motherhood lest their careers be derailed.
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago, it was Joyce Purnick, an editor at The New York
Times, telling Barnard College graduates it was impossible to be
both a mother and a high-achieving journalist. She must never have
bumped into Anna Quindlen _ Barnard '74, Pulitizer Prize winner,
mother of three _ in the ladies room.
</P>
<P>
   Now comes modern artist Judy Chicago to warn Smith College
graduates of the ``pernicious lie'' that they can be mothers and
accomplished professionals of any sort. ``I looked to history and
discovered that those women who had achieved at the level at which
I had set my sights had been childless and those that were not had
suffered constant guilt at not being able to meet the demands of
both their work and their children,'' she told the Class of 2000,
on Mother's Day no less.
</P>
<P>
   Some choice: childlessness or professional mediocrity.
</P>
<P>
   Both Purnick and Chicago are women of no small achievement.
Purnick is the first woman to run the metropolitan section of the
Times. Chicago is a feminist icon for ``The Dinner Party,'' her
1979 tribute to historically significant but unheralded women. By
choice or happenstance, neither woman had children. Chicago once
told an interviewer that she ``felt fortunate that my own
biological needs were entirely drowned out by an overpowering
creative drive.'' It is wonderful that, at 60, she has lived the
life she wanted. But isn't it a tad presumptuous to tell young
women that her path is the only path to success? Why shouldn't
Smith grads demand, instead, a workplace and a culture that gives
them the same shot at parenthood and accomplishment as their
brothers?
</P>
<P>
   None of this is to deny the obvious. In a world of inadequate
child care and inflexible work schedules, of course it is more
difficult for women than men to juggle baby and briefcase. Of
course there is guilt. But struggle and guilt are the price of
admission to the human condition. If you don't have kids to feel
guilty about, chances are you have a mother.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, trade-offs are required to balance children and a
career, but they aren't nearly as Draconian as Chicago would have
Smith women believe. Have children and a career; just don't count
on clean floors or folded laundry. Have children and a career; just
don't expect to sleep in on Saturdays. Have children and a career;
just don't expect to recognize any title on any bestseller list.
</P>
<P>
   Your life won't be all work and school plays, though. You'll
entertain, but forget ``Cooking with Julia''; you'll discover
Gourmet-to-Go. You'll learn that dim lighting does more than set
the mood for a dinner party; it hides the peanut butter stains on
the upholstered chairs. You'll even find time for a hobby, but
forget that neat, perennial border Martha Stewart is hawking;
you'll want to cultivate the messy cottage garden look. In a pinch,
when confronted by an irate neighbor, you'll pass off your
overgrown lawn as a natural meadow.
</P>
<P>
   The last thing graduates of women's colleges need to be told at
their commencements is to work harder. Greater numbers of them
already pursue studies in mathematics and the natural sciences.
More of them already go on to earn advanced degrees and higher
levels of achievement in the professions, government, business, and
the arts than do their co-ed counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would hate for you to discover that choices must be made
after you had already made those whose consequences will shape your
life for years to come,'' Chicago said on Sunday in Northampton,
warning of the dangers lurking in the Pampers aisle. ``I believe
that it is important to be clear about your goals and to be willing
to shape your life in a way that makes them possible to achieve.''
</P>
<P>
   You know what's even more important, ladies? To realize that no
one can totally shape her life. How boring if we could. Don't set
out on your path looking down for minefields. Look up, follow your
dreams, aim high, and reach for the stars, instead.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Eileen McNamara's e-mail address is mcnamara(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
