<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TALL TALES AND SHORT STORIES: Check the facts before you smirk
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LUFKIN, Texas _ Yesterday, there at the post office, I was going
through my mail, separating the bills from the junk mail, throwing
away the junk mail and wishing I could throw away the bills ...
</P>
<P>
   I came to a letter from the National Organization for Women.
Without thinking twice, I tossed it into the waste basket. Then I
stopped, and I thought twice.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, I guess I thought three times. That's how many stories
came to mind.
</P>
<P>
   Story No. 1: I was a young man attending Sunday school. The
controversial issue of abortion was much in the news. I asked my
Sunday school teacher what the Bible had to say about abortion.
</P>
<P>
   According to Old Testament law, my Sunday school teacher said,
if a pregnant woman is injured by someone in a fight and the injury
results in her miscarriage, then the person who injured her is
guilty of murder.
</P>
<P>
   That settled it for me. If you're going to believe in the Bible,
best you believe what it says. No telling how many people I told
that to.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't until some time later that I happened to come across
the scripture for myself and found out differently.
</P>
<P>
   According to Old Testament law, if a pregnant woman is injured
by someone in a fight, and the injury results in her miscarriage,
then the person who injured her is subject to a fine. Only if the
woman dies is he guilty of murder. (Exodus 2l: 22-23.)
</P>
<P>
   No telling how many people I had told wrong. I felt like a fool.
</P>
<P>
   Story No. 2: I was a cub reporter. The controversial issue of a
federally funded regional council of governments was much in the
news, part of JFK's New Frontier programs to ensure good housing
standards.
</P>
<P>
   My little hometown of Lufkin, its leadership fearing creeping
socialism, refused to join. The regulations, I was told, were
preposterous.
</P>
<P>
   ``For instance,'' an elected official said, ``it would be
mandatory that all houses have screen doors. Some of Lufkin's
finest homes don't have screen doors. It would be ridiculous.''
</P>
<P>
   I didn't think to ask to see it in writing. But I told no
telling how many people how ridiculous it would be.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't until some time later that I happened to ask a
proponent of the council of governments how he could justify
requiring screen doors on all houses.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the regulations actually say,'' he told me, ``is that all
houses are required to have a screen door where the door is used
for ventilation.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he showed it to me in writing. I felt like a fool.
</P>
<P>
   Story No. 3: I was a young editor. The controversial Equal
Rights Amendment, supported by the National Organization for Women,
was much in the news.
</P>
<P>
   It was common knowledge, widely repeated, that such an amendment
could result in uni-sex restrooms. I had used that argument myself,
no telling how many times.
</P>
<P>
   A friend of mine, a woman reporter who worked on a big-city
newspaper, was trying to convince me the ERA would advance women's
rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is that what you women really want?'' I said, smirking.
``Uni-sex restrooms?''
</P>
<P>
   ``We already have uni-sex restrooms,'' she said. ``It's what all
of us have in our homes. It's not a problem, because there's a lock
on the door.''
</P>
<P>
   I had never taken the time to think it through. Boy, did I feel
like a fool.
</P>
<P>
   That was a long time ago and the ERA was never ratified by
enough states to become law.
</P>
<P>
   But yesterday, there at the post office, I fished the letter
from the National Organization for Women out of the waste basket,
opened it and read it. It was asking for contributions to advance
women's rights. I wrote a check and mailed it back. I felt better.
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin (Texas)
Daily News, is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. E-mail address is
jmurray(AT)txucom.net; mailing address, P.O. Box 151108, Lufkin,
Texas, 75915; website, http://www.coxnews.com/newsservice.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
