<HEADLINE>
AUTHORS DETAIL THE RANGE OF VISIONS OF HEAVEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL PAULSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Heaven, it seems, is a place, and a state of mind. It is ancient
and it is eternal. It is bliss and it is peace.
</P>
<P>
   To the ancient Icelanders, heaven was an extraordinary land of
ice bridges and flaming mountains.
</P>
<P>
   To the ancient Greeks, it was Mount Olympus, home to a whole
family of gods.
</P>
<P>
   A Jewish mystic described the exact measurements of God, with
his heart of 70 names and his neck measuring 130,000,000 parasangs.
</P>
<P>
   And Dante envisioned the classical heaven, with angels gathered
around a divine throne, singing the praises of God.
</P>
<P>
   Over time, humanity has conjured up endless visions of life
after death, and now a husband-and-wife team of religion scholars
at Smith College has compiled an anthology of writings about heaven
that span the spectrum of time and genre.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are comic ways, satiric ways, approaches that find
heaven to be beautiful or amusing, people finding heaven to be
solemn or serious or a garden of delights,'' said Philip Zaleski,
who edited ``The Book of Heaven'' ($30, Oxford University Press),
with his wife Carol. ``Colorful material existed in equal measure
in literary fiction and in religious writings meant to be taken
literally. Both approaches produced wildly imaginative and colorful
heavenly creations.''
</P>
<P>
   Modern theologians sometimes shy away from literal images of
heaven, preferring to think of heaven as simply a state of being in
God's presence. And Sigmund Freud famously denounced heaven as a
``compensatory fantasy,'' saying that the human ego could not
accept the notion of its own death.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the Middle Ages people were not so much worried about
whether there was an afterlife, but how they would fare at
judgment, and they needed to be assured that their sins were
forgiven,'' Carol Zaleski said. ``Today people are worried that
there may be nothing at all after death. The interest in heaven is
not just an interest in a nice afterlife, but in having one at
all.''
</P>
<P>
   The Zaleskis had both been thinking about heaven for years
before embarking on this project at the suggestion of an editor.
Philip Zaleski says his Catholic childhood left him with a strong
notion of heaven as a place where saints and dead relatives live
on; Carol Zaleski said her academic research on near-death
experiences left her wondering about concepts of the afterlife.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our first idea was that heaven is a place where good people go
when they die, but it's actually a lot more than that,'' Carol
Zaleski said. ``In some cultures, especially ancient, it's the
place where the gods live, and there may be three heavens, or seven
heavens, associated with the planetary spheres.''
</P>
<P>
   Some early cultures merged the physical heavens _ the sky and
the stars and the weather systems _ with the spiritual heavens.
Astrology, Carol Zaleski said, most clearly reflects the concept
that life on earth can be understood in terms of changes in the
physical heavens.
</P>
<P>
   The book features poetry and prose, songs and spells, literature
and liturgy. It offers satire by Mark Twain, imagining Captain
Stormfield in heaven, struggling with his wings, and by Julian
Barnes, imagining heaven as a place where there is endless
breakfast and golf and sex but, ultimately, it's boring.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Carol Zaleski said, some of her students seem to envision
heaven as something like Disney's Magic Kingdom, while others fear
that it is akin to an endless church service.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever heaven is, as the place that is the reward of the
blessed, it's got to be the best place you can imagine, and people
who write about it use their imagination to its fullest extent to
depict something that would meet our deepest longings,'' Carol
Zaleski said.
</P>
<P>
   Inevitably, as they promote the book, the Zaleskis find
themselves asked if they will compile a second anthology, ``The
Book of Hell.'' Each says no.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't want to live with all that torment material,''
Carol Zaleski said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Holiday of the week
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Thursday is Buddha Day, a holiday called Vesak or Visakha Puja
day, which is the most important celebration in the Buddhist year.
</P>
<P>
   The holiday, sometimes celebrated on alternate dates by some
Buddhists, marks the birth, enlightenment and death of Siddhartha
Gautama of southern Nepal, who came to be known as the Buddha.
</P>
<P>
   Gautama, whose life is generally dated to the sixth century BC,
was the son of a royal family who achieved enlightenment _
realizing his ability to overcome suffering _ and then taught for
45 years.
</P>
<P>
   The holiday is generally celebrated at temples, where religious
texts are chanted, and in the home, where pictures of the Buddha's
life are hung and candles are lit, according to Christopher Queen,
an expert on Buddhism at Harvard Divinity School.
</P>
<P>
   The most distinctive ritual of the day, Queen said, is the
pouring of water of the head of a statue of the baby Buddha. Some
celebrants also release caged birds and perform charitable acts,
such as distributing cash to the underprivileged or visiting
orphanages.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Michael Paulson covers religious topics for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
