<HEADLINE>
&HT;     EXECUTIVE GOES FROM COMPUTERS TO WINE ON THE WEB 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DAVID ARMSTRONG  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The siren song of business-to-business (B2B)
Internet commerce is wafting through even the biggest, most
established corporations, luring top-drawer talent away from
blue-chip companies.
</P>
<P>
   One case in point: Mei-ling Cheng, the former chief information
officer at Hewlett-Packard Co., has jumped to Net newcomer
WineExchange.com to become its chief technology officer.
</P>
<P>
   Founded just last year and set to launch at www.wineexchange.com
in late June, WineExchange.com is an on-line broker and source of
information for growers, suppliers, retailers and wineries.
</P>
<P>
   Cheng said she believes her new employer will be well-positioned
to compete in the small but growing on-line wine trade.
</P>
<P>
   Competitors for WineExchange.com include winebuyer.com and
eVine. Moreover, consumer sites such as Wine.com target general
wine drinkers in search of that perfect $10 bottle of California
Chardonnay.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet is ready to grow more pervasively,'' Cheng said
in a telephone interview. ``I felt if I was able to get outside a
singular company and do more with more companies, it would be a
great challenge. What excites me is changing how things are done.''
</P>
<P>
   For the U.S. wine trade, 90 percent of which is centered in
California, Cheng said the Internet can prove especially useful.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole supply chain process can be more and more
streamlined on line,'' she said. ``And the Internet can drive the
availability of information itself, making it more timely and more
widely available.''
</P>
<P>
   Allowing that wine is a relationship-based business, Cheng said
she does not think the Internet ``will ever replace
person-to-person business. We're people, you know.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, she said, she has found the wine business open to new
ideas from the new world of technology to the old world of vines
and grapes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The wine producers have been very receptive. I think I had
that fear: What is the acceptance going to be like?''
</P>
<P>
   So far, the fear has been unfounded.
</P>
<P>
   Cheng is not the first executive to decamp from pure high-tech
companies and move into the world of wine.
</P>
<P>
   Lew Platt, the former Hewlett-Packard chief executive, also has
made the move, recently leaving Silicon Valley for Sonoma County
where he is chief executive of Kendall-Jackson wines.
</P>
<P>
   Cheng herself worked for Hewlett-Packard for 25 years, rising to
vice president in the company's LaserJet Imaging Systems and
Computer Products business.
</P>
<P>
   While at the Palo Alto company, Cheng managed the re-engineering
of the corporation's supply chain for order fulfillment. Prior to
that, the Stanford graduate was worldwide administrative systems
manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have wine in my blood,'' she said, ``but I think the
wine business is the next vertical business for the Internet.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
