<SLUG> BC-BEAM-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THERE'S FAMOUS, AND THEN THERE'S WHATEVER I AM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX BEAM  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A comedy writer named Bruce Vilanch is staging what sounds like
a very amusing one-man show in New York. It is called ``Almost
Famous.'' Granted, no one has ever heard of him, but he is almost
famous. He has written for ``The Brady Bunch Variety Hour'' and
concocted shticks for the Oscar broadcast. He also appears on
``Hollywood Squares.'' ``Squares'' is to fame as that patch of sky
over Providence is to Logan Airport. You're holding; you're almost
there.
</P>
<P>
   Demifame is a subject of no small interest to me. I have been
there. ``60 Minutes'' taped an interview with me (defending Boston
University president John Silber) and then never ran it. (Of
course.) I often appear on talk shows in late summer, when the real
opinionators are on vacation. You've never heard me, because you're
on vacation, too.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, I write columns for the Boston Globe, but that yields a
mediated form of notoriety. Inevitably, a ``fan'' approaches me at
a party and fulsomely praises ``that piece you wrote on (insert
pressing societal concern here.)'' A few quick questions reveal
that the actual author of the column was Ellen Goodman. I feel like
Ernest Hemingway, who supposedly woke up on a Moscow park bench
after a bracing drunk, and woozily begged a policeman for special
treatment. ``I am a famous American writer,'' Hemingway pleaded.
``Ah, John Steinbeck!'' the cop exclaimed.
</P>
<P>
   But I'm not half as semifamous as the singer-songwriter
Christine Lavin, whose work I adore. ``You've heard of me. Maybe,''
Lavin wrote in a hilarious Washington Post article called ``Who is
That Woman?'' ``I might be that actress who worked at Mel's Diner.
Or the screenwriter whom Mark Fuhrman used the N-word with.'' It's
true that her name is easily confused. I once bought a ticket to a
Patty Larkin concert, thinking she was Christine Lavin. Larkin has
her allure, but she's no Christine Lavin.
</P>
<P>
   Lavin's first brush with semifame came in 1981, when she sang
her song ``Prince Charles'' on the ``Today'' show. Presciently, she
urged Charles not to marry Diana:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(poetry style) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Oh, yes, I know she's pretty
</P>
<P>
   Yes, I know she's rich
</P>
<P>
   But I read in the National Enquirer
</P>
<P>
   Lady Diana is a . . .
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(end poetry style) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Lavin has recorded 13 solo albums, performed everywhere, and
authored perhaps the funniest song ever written, ``Sensitive New
Age Guys.'' (Check out the verse that rhymes ``premenstrual
syndrome'' with ``Seattle Kingdome.'' For that matter, check out
the cabaret version, sung entirely in German, at
christinelavin.com.) At a private benefit concert a few years ago,
the man who hired her suggested she should cut a record. At that
time, she had done six.
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks ago, I received a unexpected fan letter from Lavin,
who lives in Manhattan. (She didn't like ``American Beauty,''
either.) I paraded around the paper's ``arts'' section, boasting
that I had received a fan letter from Christine Lavin. No one had
any idea who I was talking about. Sic transit Gloria Estefan.
</P>
<P>
   My favorite five-seconds-of-fame story concerns my wife. Eight
hundred years ago, she and I were correspondents in Moscow. At a
glittering embassy reception, we bumped into the musicians Chick
Corea and Gary Burton, who, even then, were genuinely famous. I
introduced myself, and they nodded politely. My wife gave her name
and Burton effused:
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you (itals)the(unitals) Kirsten Lundberg?''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, she was. At the time, National Public Radio couldn't
afford foreign bureaus and used United Press International
reporters like my wife to file dispatches from faraway lands.
Burton was an avid listener. So for him, my wife was as famous as
Sylvia what's-her-name, who reports out of Rome. The one with the
trilly voice; I'll remember her name in a second.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Alex Beam's e-dress is beam(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
