<SLUG> BC-STRESSED-JURIES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEQUESTERED JURIES BECOMING A THING OF THE PAST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RALPH RANALLI  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   After a day of testimony, Massachusetts jurors, even those in
the highest-profile cases such as the Reggie Lewis medical
malpractice case or the 1998 murder trial of British au pair Louise
Woodward, do something that 15 years ago would have been
unthinkable.
</P>
<P>
   They go home.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly because of cost and partly in consideration of the
emotional well-being of jurors, judges routinely send them home
each evening on nothing more than a pledge to avoid television,
radio, and newspaper coverage of their case.
</P>
<P>
   It's a far cry from the days when jurors in major cases were
locked away in hotel rooms under the watchful eye of court officers
who controlled every aspect of their lives, from censoring their
news diet to eavesdropping on their telephone conversations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sequestering a jury, is, except for the brutality, like
imprisoning them in a medium-security prison,'' said Middlesex
Superior Court Judge Hiller Zobel, who presided over the Woodward
case. ``They wake up when they are told. They eat when they are
told. They go to sleep when they are told. Their freedom is
restricted. One does not sequester a jury lightly.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Zobel did order the Woodward jurors sequestered during
deliberations, even that limited practice is becoming increasingly
rare, specialists say.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, the wide-open approach comes at a time when jurors
face a confluence of influences, from Court TV to nonstop legal
commentary on 24-hour cable channels, making it far more likely
that deliberations could be infected. And some wonder whether it's
wise to put jurors on the honor system, given the widely held
belief among veteran prosecutors and defense attorneys that jurors
routinely peek at television news and the newspaper when they go
home _ and then fib about it the next day when judges ask whether
they did.
</P>
<P>
   ``Inevitably, with any rule, there are people who are going to
bend or break it,'' said Andrew Good, one of Woodward's lawyers who
failed to persuade Zobel to sequester the jury for the length of
the case. ``Of course, there are a million faults in the system and
that's just one.''
</P>
<P>
   Many believe that the near-total shift away from sequestering
juries represents one of the biggest changes in the Massachusetts
trial system in the last 20 years. Yet the manner in which it was
adopted may be even more remarkable.
</P>
<P>
   In an area of law where change is either glacial or imposed by
higher courts, state judges say the move away from locking up
juries was relatively quick and spontaneous.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like the Legislature passed a statute or the SJC
decided a case,'' said state Jury Commissioner Frank Davis. ``It
was more of a groundswell in the court where judges decided that
the hardship it imposed didn't seem necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   Just ask Jasper Bing, who served as foreman during the 1981
trial of notorious art thief Myles J. Connor in the murder of a
Boston police officer. He recalls his Dorchester neighbors watching
as a uniformed court officer in a cruiser with its lights flashing
escorted him home so he could pack a toothbrush and some clothes
for what turned out to be 28 days of sequestration.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were in their yards saying, `Ooh, what did Bing do?' ''
recalled the 56-year-old Green Line trolley driver.
</P>
<P>
   He and his fellow jurors weren't allowed to go home for
Thanksgiving. Instead, their families were invited to join them for
a turkey-and-trimmings dinner in their East Boston hotel _ as a
uniformed court officer stood at each table to make sure no one
talked about the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a downer, but there wasn't really much we could do
about it,'' Bing said.
</P>
<P>
   Group bowling trips and touch-football games behind the hotel
weren't enough to keep the group from going a bit stir-crazy at the
end, Bing said, and there were times he stepped in to head off
flare-ups between some of his frazzled fellow jurors.
</P>
<P>
   Such stresses are a key reason that the practice has been
largely abandoned here and elsewhere, according to G. Thomas
Munsterman, director of the Center for Jury Studies at the National
Center for State Courts in Arlington, Va.
</P>
<P>
   A recent study by the center found that ``sequestration for the
length of trial'' was rated as the number-two source of juror
stress, trumped only by ``deciding whether to give the death
penalty.''
</P>
<P>
   Sequestering costs _ room and board for 12 people, plus
court-officer salaries _ were also a major issue, even during the
state's first sequestering of a jury _ the group of men who in 1770
decided the fate of Captain Thomas Preston, the British commander
involved in the Boston Massacre.
</P>
<P>
   Records still exist showing that ``punch, bisquit and cheese''
were served to the Preston jurors for breakfast. Pipes and tobacco
were offered after dinner, which also featured ``punch.''
</P>
<P>
   Good meals were always considered part of the bargain for
jurors' services, but the filet mignons and twin lobsters added up.
Expenses for a single sequestered jury in a murder case _ hotel
rooms, meals, and overtime for court officers _ often ran as high
as $50,000 or more. By contrast, last year the state spent just
$337,000 on all jury-related expenses.
</P>
<P>
   One turning point away from automatic sequestration was the
decision by federal judge David Nelson not to lock up the jury for
the duration of the racketeering case against Boston Mafia
underboss Gennaro Angiulo in 1986. The trial went relatively
smoothly, to the surprise of some.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once Angiulo was tried, it was almost as if we said, `Why are
we wasting all of this money?' '' said Superior Court Judge Robert
A. Barton, who once sequestered a jury on which his boss, the late
chief justice for the Superior Court, Thomas Morse, was serving.
</P>
<P>
   Barton said he believes the new honor system is better.
</P>
<P>
   Barton said trial attorneys who are in court all the time
probably have a more jaded view of jurors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really do believe that the great majority of jurors are
conscientious about their duties,'' Barton said. ``To most of them,
this is the only time they will sit on a significant case. I really
do believe that they rise to the occasion.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
