<HEADER>
A7705 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-RAC-PREAKNESS-BOS &LR;      05-17 0752
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-PREAKNESS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PREAKNESS HERD IS THINNED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON INDRISANO  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ Actions speak louder than words, and Fusaichi
Pegasus was so impressive winning the Kentucky Derby that most of
the trainers who ran a horse in that race will shut up rather than
show up at Pimlico for Saturday's Preakness, the second leg of the
Triple Crown.
</P>
<P>
   The Derby field numbered 19; the Preakness field will number no
more than eight. Trainer Todd Pletcher confirmed Tuesday that
Impeachment, who closed for third in the Derby without threatening
the winner, would try the Preakness after working a half-mile in
:48 at Belmont Park. That brings to four the number of Derby
contestants who will give Fusaichi Pegasus another go. The others
are Captain Steve (eighth in the Derby), High Yield (15th), and
Hal's Hope (16th).
</P>
<P>
   The newcomers to the Triple Crown trail are Red Bullet, who ran
second to Fusaichi Pegasus in the Wood Memorial at Aqueduct April
15; Snuck In, second in the Arkansas Derby on the same date; and
Hugh Hefner, a California-bred who ran second in the Snow Chief for
state-breds at Hollywood Park April 30.
</P>
<P>
   Captain Steve is trained by Bob Baffert, and High Yield is
trained by D. Wayne Lukas. Both men are in the Preakness because
they believe it is impossible to hold a classic race without
benefit of their participation. Hal's Hope is trained by
88-year-old Harold Rose, and he is running because Rose is enjoying
the banquet circuit.
</P>
<P>
   However, Impeachment is legitimate, though Pimlico does not suit
his late-closing style with its tight turns. Impeachment came from
dead last in the Derby to grab the show in a fine effort, but he
was more than 5 lengths behind Fusaichi Pegasus, who never even
knew Impeachment was in the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``He went great, then galloped out (5 furlongs) in 1:00 1/5,''
said Pletcher, who started four horses in the Derby (More Than
Ready, fourth; Trippi, 11th; and Graeme Hall, who was eased) but is
down to one hope. ``Craig Perret will ride him, and he'll van down
Thursday. His style won't be any different for the Preakness. You
couldn't change it if you wanted to.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Fusaichi Pegasus is due to arrive at Pimlico
Wednesday after zipping 5 furlongs at Churchill Downs in :59
Monday. He will be on the same plane from Louisville that is
bringing Captain Steve and Snuck In. High Yield, Red Bullet, and
Hal's Hope are on the grounds, and Hugh Hefner is expected
Wednesday, following an overnight flight from California.
</P>
<P>
   ``His work (Monday) was a little faster than I wanted, but he's
bright and clear,'' said Neil Drysdale, who trains Fusaichi
Pegasus. ``He went well within himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Fusaichi Pegasus, who can be high-strung but was a perfect
gentleman in the Derby, is scheduled to arrive around noon, and he
will be stabled on the backstretch rather than in the special
stakes barn Pimlico features behind the grandstand. Drysdale fears
a media circus if the big bay is kept out front.
</P>
<P>
   Whether Fusaichi Pegasus will be tested Saturday is what remains
to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not here trying to beat one horse,'' said Lukas, who
never gives up. ``We're here because we want to win. We don't pick
out horses to beat in some kind of obsession.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Snuck In makes strides
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Snuck In breezed a half in :48 at Churchill Tuesday. ``He went
very well, and we're all set,'' said trainer Steve Asmussen. ``He
was a little flat when he ran in the Arkansas Derby, but he's been
training much better. I think he's moved forward consistently since
then. He'll have to improve for this race.'' . . . Captain Steve
really sizzled Monday at Churchill, going 5 furlongs in :58 1/5.
``The horse is doing excellent,'' said Baffert. ``He came out of
the work in great shape.'' . . . High Yield worked at Pimlico
Monday, covering 5 panels in :59. ``It was exactly what we wanted
for him,'' said Lukas. ``He couldn't be doing any better as far as
we can tell.'' . . . Hugh Hefner, who is trained by Martin Jones,
has been ridden by Corey Nakatani in his last three starts, but
Victor Espinoza will ride him in the Preakness . . . Wheelaway,
fifth in the Derby, was the last of those who made the Rose Run to
be declared out of the Preakness. Trainer John Kimmel made the
announcement Monday. ``After conferring with the owners,'' he said,
``it was decided to skip the Preakness, and get the horse ready for
the Belmont Stakes (June 10).''
</P>
</TEXT>
