<HEADLINE>
APPLE PICKING THROUGH AN ORCHARD OF JUICY EVENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Picked up pieces from the land of Rudy, Rocket, and
Latrell . . .
</P>
<P>
   --Darn. All this time I was hoping that the Red Sox winning the
World Series was going to be the Third Secret of Fatima.
</P>
<P>
   --Double Secret Probation. That's what Bob Knight got. Indiana
University President Myles Brand, a/k/a Dean Wormer, embarrasses
his school and his state.
</P>
<P>
   --If I'm doing the math correctly, Pedro Martinez will make his
return to the Yankee Stadium mound on Sunday night, May 28, on
ESPN. It'll be Pedro's first New York appearance since his
17-strikeout epic last Sept. 10. His opponent should be Orlando
Hernandez. Have you noticed that the Red Sox make both of their
trips to Yankee Stadium between next Friday and June 14? That's
right. They don't go back to New York after mid-June . . . until
the ALCS.
</P>
<P>
   --Jose Canseco has launched his own financial services firm.
Calling Jose to protect your investments sounds about as smart as
assigning Mark Chmura to chaperone your high school prom. Jose must
have learned it all from Jack Clark. Let's have a name-the-company
contest for Jose. How about ``Yahoo on Yahoo''?
</P>
<P>
   --Twenty-two points, 16 assists, 10 rebounds, great hair. Kidd
Jason had a pretty good game against the Lakers Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   --With the Yankees trailing, 2-0, in the ninth in Detroit
Sunday, Paul O'Neill tried to bunt his way on. That's as bad as it
gets for the New Yorkers. When the Yankees went 0 for 3 at Comerica
Park, it was noted that they went 0 for 6 at Fenway in the
inaugural year (1912) of our little bandbox.
</P>
<P>
   --It'll be the Avalanche over the Devils in the Stanley Cup
Finals. Ray gets his name on the Cup.
</P>
<P>
   --Enough of the ``way-back'' jokes. John Wasdin quietly has
lowered his ERA to 3.38.
</P>
<P>
   --Next time some wiseguy figures out how much Pedro is getting
paid per pitch, per inning, per strikeout, per win, etc., remember
that Courteney Cox Arquette and Friends are each getting $750,000
per half-hour episode for the next two seasons. Makes Jeff Frye
sound like a bargain.
</P>
<P>
   --Buffy The Vampire Slayer (Sarah Michelle Gellar) was courtside
for Game 4 in New York. Why can't the Celtics get fans like that?
</P>
<P>
   --Wonder if Larry Bird will tell his Pacers what it was like to
be on the other side when the Celtics came back from a 3-1 deficit
to beat the 76ers in the 1981 Eastern Conference Finals?
</P>
<P>
   --Brand just hired Steve Howe, Darryl Strawberry, and Dennis
Rodman as faculty members. Brand said they're all getting a second
chance and no misbehavior will be tolerated. Zero tolerance.
</P>
<P>
   --Into their fourth generation of car racing, bad luck caught up
with the Petty family. It's like when on-the-job death visits the
Wallendas. Nothing changes. Risk-taking is a livelihood and a way
of life for these folks.
</P>
<P>
   --Two guys who always will love Knight: Red Auerbach and Bill
Parcells.
</P>
<P>
   --The buzz in the Apple is that Michael Jordan is going to hire
former Cambridge Rindge &AMP; Latin and Boston University coach Mike
Jarvis to guide the Washington Wizards.
</P>
<P>
   --Lookalikes _ Scribes on the beat have noticed that Pete
Schourek and Cosmo Kramer look a lot alike.
</P>
<P>
   --Wonder if choking a math student gets you fired if you are a
professor at Indiana University?
</P>
<P>
   --Anthony Carter says Charlie Ward scored his 9 straight Game 4
points during garbage time and the Heated rivalry gets better. Who
remembers that the Knick-Heat wars really got going when P.J. Brown
flipped Ward back in 1997?
</P>
<P>
   --Hockey players Travis Roy and John Gilpatrick graduate from
their respective universities, BU and Suffolk, Sunday. Both young
men are the personification of courage and perseverance. Roy was
paralyzed 11 seconds into his first shift at BU. Gilpatrick was
similarly injured just a few weeks later while playing for Suffolk.
</P>
<P>
   --How's Knight going to stay well-behaved? Everyone can bait him
now, without fear. I will beg the boss to let me go to Indiana and
open a press conference with, ``Excuse me, Bob, why are you such a
bully and what's with the sweater?''
</P>
<P>
   --George Steinbrenner says he's noticed the Yankees are
struggling and he's unhappy with some players and they know who
they are. Can't wait to see how the Boss reacts if the Sox stuff
the Pinstripes in the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   --Prayers go out to Kent Mercker, who's been hospitalized in
California with bleeding in his brain. Not too long ago, he was a
vital part of the Red Sox. The 32-year-old pitched the wild-card
cliching game for Boston in Chicago last year, and also started
three postseason games, including the first and last games of the
ALCS against the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   --Coming soon to a store near you: the Red Sox Monopoly Game.
Wonder if the Yawkey Trust is represented near Park Place and
Boardwalk?
</P>
<P>
   --Myles Brand is George McFly. Bobby Knight is Biff.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dan Shaughnessy is a Globe columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
