<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR THURSDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Thursday, May 18:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SIERRA-LEONE (Freetown) _ Sierra Leone's rebel leader Foday
Sankoh, who vanished nine days ago during a violent confrontation
outside his Freetown house, was captured Wednesday by
pro-government soldiers. By Norimitsu Onishi.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-TRADE-CLINTON (New London, Conn.) _ President Clinton on
Wednesday will address graduates of the Coast Guard Academy on new
threats to national security, including cyberterrorism, and on the
China trade bill. By Neil A. Lewsi.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-TRADE (Washington) _ The House Ways and Means Committee
and the Senate Finance Committee are to vote on, and presumably
pass by large margins, the China trade bill. These are first
Congressional votes on the measure, and backers hope they will
provide momentum going into the House floor vote next week. By Eric
Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-TRADE-LOBBY (Washington) _ Lobbyists for high-tech
industries are working furiously to support the China trade bill.
By Lizette Alvarez. High tech industries are lobbying furiously for
the trade vote.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-LEBANON (Jerusalem) _ Israel remains committed to
withdrawing from Lebanon by July 7. By Joel Greenberg.
</P>
<P>
   YUGOSLAVIA-MEDIA (Belgrade) _ In a dramatic challenge to the
democratic opposition, the Serbian government on Wednesday seized
ownership and control of the main opposition television station,
Belgrade's Studio B, which it accused of advocating an uprising
against the authorities. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-U.S. (Washington) _ The U.S. Senate is scheduled to vote
Wednesday on a bill that would end funds for U.S. troops in Kosovo
by July 2001. By Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-POLITICS (Tokyo) _ Finance Minister Kiichi Miyazawa on
Tuesday denied charges that he had bribed a politician for his
silence when Miyazawa was prime minister. By Stephanie Strom.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   MILITARY-DRAFT (Washington) _ Selective Service says that in
some states only 70 percent of young men register. By Irvin
Molotsky.
</P>
<P>
   GUNS-CONGRESS (Washington) _ The Senate takes up important but
symbolic gun control measure. By Lizette Alvarez.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (``p'' code)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-TRADE (Seattle) _ George W. Bush stumps in favor of
granting China normal trade status with an enthusiastic speech that
puts him closer on the issue to the Clinton administration than the
vice president. By Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   GORE-SOCSEC (Orlando, Fla.) _ Al Gore talks to seniors about the
evils of Bush's social security plan. By James Dao.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-BRIEFS (Undated) _ News and notes from the hustings.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   ALA-CHURCH-BOMBING (Birmingham, Ala.) _ Two of four suspects in
the 1963 Birmingham church bombing are indicted by state
authorities after a lenghty investigation with federal officials.
The case is the most prominent of a number of unresolved, racially
motivated killings of blacks from the civil rights era that are now
under scrutinty. Thomas Blanton Jr., a onetime member of the Ku
Klux Klan, surrendered Wednesday and Bobby Frank Cherry was as
expected to turn himself in. By Kevin Sack.
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT6.
</P>
<P>
   DOMESTIC-VIOLENCE (Undated) _ Confirming a long-standing trend
in crime and society, a new Justice Department report shows a
continuing, steep drop in killings attributed to domestic violence,
particularly among blacks. Among blacks, the biggest drop is for
men killed by women, which has actually gone down about 71 percent
since the 1970s. (The number for women and men used to be about
even.) But there is one disturbing trend to emerge from the
department's annual report _ the numbers for white women have gone
up slightly. The face of domestice violence in America is now
largely a problem of attacks on white women, a major shift that
sociologists and law enforcement officials are just starting to
grapple with. By Fox Butterfield.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-SCHOOLS (Los Angeles) _ On the 46th anniversary of the
landmark Brown vs. Board of Education decision, a coalition of
civil rights groups on Wednesday filed a class action lawsuit
alleging that the disparities in California's public schools are so
great bewteen rich and poor districts as to violate the state
constitution's guarantee of a free and equal public education for
all, and demanding that the state guarantee that all schools have
the ``bare necessities'' of textbooks, teachers, classrooms,
toilets and so on. Lawyers for the plaintiffs described the suit as
the first of its kind in the nation, and say they hope it will open
a new front in a two-decade effort that began with attempts to
equalize school financing, then moved on to address adequacy of
conditions. By Todd S. Purdum.
</P>
<P>
   LOS-ALAMOS-FIRE (Los Alamos, N.M.) _ The Parks Service's plan
for a controlled burn at Los Alamos, filed last month, warned
officials, ``You have not lost one in a long time and are starting
to feel a little smug.'' Officials rated the consequences of
failure as ``moderate.'' By Douglas Jehl.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-DIET-HYPERTENSION (Undated) _ A controlled study shows that
lowering sodium intake along with a high calcium diet known as DASH
is effective in combatting hypertension. By Denise Grady. (1000
words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-DIOXIN-CANCER (Undated) _ In the draft of a report to be
released in June, the EPA lists dioxin as a ``human carcinogen.''
By Gina Kolata. (800 words)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   DO-IT-YOURSELF-FUND (Undated) _ Most mutual funds are not worth
owning, says Steven Wallman, a former federal securities regulator,
because they cost too much, repeatedly fail to beat the market and
frequently produce big tax bills. He contends that he has found a
better and, in many cases, cheaper way for investors to create
their own, customized baskets of stocks, which he calls folios. For
a fee of $295 a year, his company, Folio, will let investors buy
three of these do-it-yourself mutual funds and fill each one with
as much money as they choose spread among as many as 50 stocks. For
no additional charge, they can make changes in their holdings as
often as twice a day through what Wallman hopes will become an
efficient, internal trading system. Whether the world will beat a
path to Wallman's portal is far from certain. He is not the first
to try to tap into investors' growing discomfort with the
limitations of traditional mutual funds, a restlessness that has
spawned several variations on the theme. By Patrick McGeehan.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST (Washington) _ The government will defend
its proposed breakup of Microsoft, filing a counterresponse by the
end of the day. The next step is a hearing on May 24 at which both
sides are to present arguments on the remedy question. By Joel
Brinkley.
</P>
<P>
   MATTEL-APPOINT (Undated) _ Mattel names Robert A. Eckert, 45,
former president of Kraft Foods, to succeed Jill Barad as chief
executive. Barad was ousted in February after a turbulent three
years as chief executive. By Constance L. Hays.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The daily marketplace column.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ A day after the Federal Reserve decision to
raise interest rates a half point, stocks were lower. At 11:10
a.m., the Dow Jones industrial average was down 1.36 percent, the
S&AMP;P 500 was down 1.41 percent and the Nasdaq composite index was
down 2.44 percent. Treasury prices are lower. European stock
markets were also lower. London is down 1.59 percent and Frankfurt
were down 2.11 percent. The Nikkei closed down 0.84 while the Hang
Seng index ended down 2.19 percent. By Robert D. Hershey Jr.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPBELL-OUTLOOK (Undated) _ Campbell Soup warns that profit
this fiscal year will fall as much as 7 percent short of analysts'
forecasts because of sluggish soup sales in the United States. The
company also reports first-quarter earnings that match analysts'
expectations.
</P>
<P>
   ICO-BANKRUPTCY (Undated) _ ICO Global Communications emerges
from bankruptcy protection and will now be run by Craig McCaw and
Indian TV network operator Subhash Chandra. By Barnaby J. Feder.
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL-BANKS (Sao Paulo) _ A look at the Brazilian government's
troubled effort to sell Banespa, a state-owned bank and the largest
and most coveted of the state institutions that remain to be sold
under a long-term privatization effort. Many Brazilians, including
bank employees, oppose the sale, which is scheduled to take place
in July.
</P>
<P>
   TOYOTA-EARNINGS (Tokyo) _ Toyota Motor reports surprisingly
strong results for the second half of its fiscal year, helped by
cost-cutting and robust sales in North America that offset the
impact of the expensive yen. By Stephanie Strom.
</P>
<P>
   VODAFONE-CEGETEL (London) _ Vodafone Airtouch says it will sell
its entire stake in French telecommunications operator Cegetel to
Vivendi in a deal that raises questions about Vodafone's strategy
on the Continent. By Andrew Ross Sorkin.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-BANK (Tokyo) _ The Japanese government is expected to
announce as early as Thursday that an investment group run by
Wilbur L. Ross, one of America's leading bankruptcy specialists,
has been chosen to acquire Kofuku Bank, a regional bank in Osaka
that failed last year. By Stephanie Strom.
</P>
