<DOCNO> NYT20000517.0132 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 14:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7725 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-B2B-STOCKS-HNS &LR;      05-17 0838
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-B2B-STOCKS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     ANALYSTS SAY FUTURE OF `B2B' IS BRIGHT DESPITE SKEPTICISM 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ALAN T. SARACEVIC  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Mere months after the business-to-business, or
B2B, sector was anointed as the latest successor to the cyberspace
throne, analysts and investors alike are stepping back and taking a
more tempered view of it.
</P>
<P>
   B2B stocks, much like other technology issues, have been
hammered in recent weeks. The same investment houses that post
outrageous estimates on the potential size of the industry are now
saying that most B2B companies will not survive. In short, the
party's over. The hard work is set to begin.
</P>
<P>
   It is a route similar to that taken by the business-to-consumer,
or B2C, sector of Internet commerce, which was also strongly hyped
before the experts stepped in to spoil the party.
</P>
<P>
   For those unschooled in the intricacies of the Internet
alphabet, here's the deal: B2C companies sell products directly to
consumers over the Internet. B2B companies use the Internet to set
up business transactions between existing, real-world businesses.
</P>
<P>
   While B2C was the first real darling of the e-commerce sector,
punctuated by huge stock run-ups by companies like Amazon.com, eBay
and eToys, Wall Street began questioning the long-term viability of
on-line consumer shopping. Stocks suffered, and venture capital to
fund new B2C firms dried up.
</P>
<P>
   The focus turned to B2B, and it all made so much sense. Over 90
percent of all business in the real-world is B2B, the supporters
argued.
</P>
<P>
   Someone forgot to take into account human nature. Fierce
competitors have been less than eager to cooperate in the name of
B2B e-commerce.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys hate each others guts. Now, they're trying to get
together and work together?'' said an incredulous Tim Clark, senior
analyst at Jupiter Communications. ``We're estimating half of the
announced marketplaces will simply collapse.''
</P>
<P>
   A report from AMR Research, another of the research firms that
follow e-commerce, predicts most of the 600-plus B2B Net markets it
tracks will fail, with only 50 to 100 surviving by 2001.
</P>
<P>
   That kind of thinking has Wall Street scared.
</P>
<P>
   ``In some ways, it's the empire strikes back, with some big
companies striking back against some of the first-generation market
makers, like Ariba and such,'' Rick Villers, an analyst with the
research firm IDC Corp, said in reference to Ariba Inc. of Mountain
View, Calif. ``What's emerging as a problem in these exchanges is
it's not as simple as they thought.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Even the three big auto retailers getting together, they found
their business partners don't want to play,'' said Villers,
referring to a proposed online B2B marketplace headed by General
Motors, Ford and DaimlerChrysler. ``It's too closed. It's too
focused on their supply chain needs. (Vendors) don't believe these
companies can be an impartial decision-maker when it comes these
markets.''
</P>
<P>
   The automakers are not the only big-industry players trying to
get together on the B2B playground. Similar alliances have been
announced in the aerospace, energy, retail, chemical, petroleum and
banking industries. Huge players like Boeing, Lockheed Martin,
Chevron, Sears and Citigroup have put a lot money on the table,
betting the on-line trade can save them money.
</P>
<P>
   For those reasons, B2B stalwarts are not throwing in the towel
by any means. If anything, a shakeout was expected, and the fight
is just beginning.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's huge momentum. Huge pipeline. Huge interest,'' said
Kit Robinson, a spokesman for Commerce One. ``There's no end in
sight because this is a new market.
</P>
<P>
   ``You and I have become accustomed to the fact that we can find
stuff on Yahoo and participate in an auction on eBay. All you need
is a credit card and a modem,'' Robinson said. ``But you have to
remember that there will be $10 spent on B2B for every $1 on B2C.
Regardless of Wall Street's perceptions, there's no let-up.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the potential market estimates are staggering. The same
research firms that are now wavering on the B2B space are
simultaneously playing the other side of the fence with monstrous
predictions on how big B2B will become:
</P>
<P>
   _ Gartner Group Inc. says B2B e-commerce will generate business
valued at $3.95 trillion by 2004.
</P>
<P>
   _ AMR Research Inc. says $5.7 trillion.
</P>
<P>
   _ International Data Corp. says $2.2 trillion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe B2B is not overhyped, but the reality is that we
have to step back and look at the existing business models, looking
for industries where there is inefficiency today and there are some
opportunities,'' Villers said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The industries that can most benefit from on-line marketplaces
are those that haven't been able to improve their supply chains,''
he said, ``either because they're too diverse a community or there
hasn't emerged a dominant company or it's just not an industry
where a supply chain exists, like professional services.''
</P>
</TEXT>
