<DOCNO> NYT20000517.0133 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 14:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7731 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-DYING-HEARTLAND-$ADV2     05-17 1735
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DYING-HEARTLAND-$ADV21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    IN FARM COUNTRY, A WAY OF LIFE SLOWLY WITHERS
 &HT;    1320&AMP;add. For release Sunday, May 21.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LEBANON, Kansas _ As the clock strikes 3, the old ladies of this
depressed farm town shuffle past the boarded-up red brick
storefronts on Main Street and into LaDow's general store for a
daily dose of coffee and gossip.
</P>
<P>
   Every afternoon, Monday through Friday, a dozen of them gather
around two kitchen tables by the window to discuss the world's
problems, and their own.
</P>
<P>
   Their small town is withering away. And these genteel women,
many of them farm widows, are a living testament to this unhappy
trend.
</P>
<P>
   The facts of local life are evident around the table at LaDow's:
Men die earlier than women. The children leave forever, lured away
by city jobs that pay more and demand less toil than growing wheat
on the Great Plains of north-central Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to hang on,'' said Gladys Kennedy, who for half a
century has served as the town's unofficial historian. In 1911, her
father founded a garage that would become the local Ford
dealership. It was boarded up a few years back as the population of
Lebanon plummeted from 1,500 a century ago to just 350 today.
</P>
<P>
   Across Smith County, Kansas, and indeed throughout rural
America, a generational time bomb is ticking.
</P>
<P>
   Older farmers have no one to take over the family property, and
are not sure they'd encourage them even if their children were
inclined to farm. The phenomenon is the same throughout much of the
farm belt in the Midwest and parts of the South. More than 650
non-metropolitan counties in America lost population in the 1990s,
more than at any time in the nation's history.
</P>
<P>
   As the New Economy of the Internet fuels unprecedented national
prosperity, the oldest economy, the family farm, is again facing
hard times. The graying of America's farmers _ average age, 54.3 _
has coincided with low commodity prices to make it difficult, even
with federal subsidies, for some to remain in business.
</P>
<P>
   Life is slowly bleeding from America's heartland, leaving an
increasingly empty landscape full of graceful widows, white-haired
farmers and century-old family homesteads destined for the auction
block.
</P>
<P>
   In Formoso in neighboring Jewell County, Dennis Appleby raises
cattle and crops on a farm founded by his great-grandfather in
1885. He suffered a heart attack in April and, while he remains
robust at 59, has begun to seriously doubt how much longer he'll be
able to work the land.
</P>
<P>
   Formoso was a lively farm town of 500 when Appleby was growing
up. Its Mayberry-like downtown had a general store, a family doctor
and a schoolhouse. Now, it has none of them to serve a population
that has dwindled to 150.
</P>
<P>
   ``My son, an accountant in Wichita, said, 'I'd love to be a
farmer, but I need to make a living,' `` said Appleby. ``Everybody
wishes they could pass their farm along. But my greatest wish is
for my children to be happy. So, I have mixed emotions about
that.''
</P>
<P>
   This is not a new story. Out-migration from counties like Smith
and Jewell began during World War I (reflecting the truth in the
popular song lyric of the time: ``How you gonna keep 'em down of
the farm after they've seen Paris?''). The flow continued through
the Great Depression and Dust Bowl years, right up to the farm
crisis of the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   But the Kansas farmers fear that the last chapter of the family
farm is now being written. The average age of a farmer here is near
60. Across 2,000 square miles of rich acreage in these two
counties, farmers in their 20s and 30s number no more than a dozen.
Jewell and Smith lost more more than two-thirds of their population
between 1930 and 1990. In 1900, the two counties boasted 40,000
residents. Today, the population is only about 8,000.
</P>
<P>
   Most farmers here face the prospects of selling out or leasing
their land when retirement finally comes, usually ending a century
or more of family farming on land homesteaded in the late 19th
century.
</P>
<P>
   The waves ripple through farm society. In some parts of the
Midwest, the one-room schoolhouse has made a return as school
districts consolidate due to declining enrollments. Medical care
has become scarce, with the nearest full-service hospitals hours
away by car. The people of Formoso must drive 20 miles to the
nearest grocery store.
</P>
<P>
   The scale of the economy is reflected in the classified ads of
the Jewell County newspaper. For less than the price of most new
cars, it is possible to buy a three-bedroom house with central heat
and air and a one-car garage. ``Asking price $19,500, but it is
negotiable,'' the ad states.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past two decades in Lebanon, the elementary school and
high school closed, along with most of the retail shops. The only
new building in town is a nursing home.
</P>
<P>
   On a sun-drenched spring day, the rolling farmland is verdant,
with lush green wheat reaching waist-high. But looks are deceiving.
</P>
<P>
   With wheat prices depressed, Dennis Duntz, 60, a Smith County
farmer all his life, made less last year than his wife, Jackie,
earned working part-time cleaning rooms at a local nursing home for
minimum wage. To survive, most small farms now depend on a wage
earner who works off the farm. Nationally, about three of every
four women who live on a farm work away from the farm in a
non-agriculture job.
</P>
<P>
   Had it not been for government subsidies, Duntz would have made
only about a $965 profit in 1999 due to deflated wheat crop prices
and the mounting interest payments on his farm machinery, which
totals about $14,000 a year. He was forced to sell off about half
of his 100-head cattle herd to satisfy his creditors.
</P>
<P>
   He worries now that a drought forecast for this summer will
reduce his wheat yield.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I've got in the world is what you see around you and a
note at the bank,'' Duntz said, surveying the farm founded by his
grandfather. ``All I'm doing now is riding it down. I don't have
anyone to take it over. All I can do in five or six years is call
in the auctioneer.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1900, 50 percent of all Americans lived and worked on a farm.
A century later, it's less than 1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The result is a WalMart-ization of farms. With no one to take
over, small farms consolidate into bigger ones, or are bought out
or leased by large agri-business corporations, whose economies of
scale put a further squeeze on the remaining small family farms.
</P>
<P>
   Will urban and suburban Americans notice a difference at the
supermarket if their food comes from giant corporations instead of
small farms? Probably not. The cost of raw ingredients and animal
feed accounts for a relatively small share of consumer food prices.
</P>
<P>
   But the fiercely independent farmers in north-central Kansas
argue that no corporation will care for the land like a proud,
multi-generational family will. And, they contend, a concentration
of agriculture in the hands of a few major corporations can
suppress competition and place the power of food in the hands of
relatively few.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly, they feel helpless and victimized by factors beyond
their control _ the complex, regulated economy of food prices and
controls, international competition and an American public that
pays little attention to their plight. Wheat farmers earn only
about five cents on the sale of a $1.39 loaf of bread, and ranchers
make about 68 cents from a $4.39 pound of sirloin sold in a retail
store, according to estimates by the U.S. Department of
Agriculture.
</P>
<P>
   ``The farmers don't have a voice. We take our product to market,
but we have no power,'' complained Dale Lyon, 69, who faces
retirement and hopes his daughter and son-in-law may take over the
land to raise horses and cattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, agriculture in the United States is in good
shape,'' Lyon said. ``It's the farmers that are hurting. (Federal
Reserve Chairman Alan) Greenspan is supposed to be some kind of
hero. Well, all he's doing is cutting off the little guy with every
increase he makes in the interest rate.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   The current low price of wheat and other commodities resulted in
part from the Asian financial crisis in 1997, which depressed world
markets and forced Congress to extend billions more dollars in aid
to U.S. farmers _ assistance they need to survive but would rather
do without.
</P>
<P>
   Reliance on government aid is further fueled by the aging
population.
</P>
<P>
   In Smith Center, the county seat with a population of 2,000,
there are two group homes for the elderly and a nursing home. It
has the fifth highest per-capita population over age 80 of any
county in the nation, and one in three residents is over 65. Jewell
County is close behind.
</P>
<P>
   Some farm families dream about the Internet as their economic
salvation, luring telecommuting yuppies to the green, and
inexpensive, pastures of Kansas. Others believe tourism is the
future, with hunters and anglers coming to enjoy
farmland-turned-grasslands under an ongoing federal conservation
program.
</P>
<P>
   But some local rural economies simply cannot be transformed,
said Kenneth Johnson, a demographer and sociologist at Loyola
University in Chicago who studies rural population trends. Counties
close to major cities have benefited from what he has dubbed the
``rural rebound,'' due largely to the influx of people and money as
suburbs expand.
</P>
<P>
   But in counties like Smith and Jewell, at least four hours by
car from from Kansas City, Mo., and Lincoln, Neb., there is only
one economic engine, and revival seems distant, if not impossible.
Kansas state estimates predict that Smith, Jewell and 37 other
counties in the state will continue to lose population at least
through the year 2040.
</P>
<P>
   ``These people are producing the basic sustenance of our lives,
and yet the farms fade,'' Johnson said. ``I don't think there is
any magic. These places live and die by farming.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Web:
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Census Bureau, www.census.gov
</P>
<P>
   Loyola University-Chicago for recent research on rural
populations, www.luc.edu/depts/sociology/research.html
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Department of Agriculture's National Commission on Small
Farms, www.reeusda.gov/agsys/smallfarm/report.htm
</P>
<P>
   Charles W. Holmes's e-mail address is chuckh(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
