<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-QUADRIPLEGIC-GRAD-PHOTO-ADVISORY-NYT </SLUG>
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Editors:
</P>
<P>
   The honors thesis that Brooke Ellison presented earlier this
spring at Harvard University, ``The Element of Hope in Resilient
Adolescents,'' was a scientific analysis steeped in data. But her
own story would have made a good case study.
</P>
<P>
   Struck by a car on her first day in the seventh grade and given
little chance of survival, Ellison awoke after 36 hours in a coma
as a quadriplegic.
</P>
<P>
   Though she would regain no sensation below her neck, Ellison
never missed a grade, and early next month she will cap her
improbable educational odyssey by graduating from Harvard with an
A- average and a bachelor's degree in psychology and biology.
</P>
<P>
   We have moved the following selection of photos by photographer
Evan Richman:
</P>
<P>
   NYT9, Ellison with her mother Jean on campus at Harvard.
</P>
<P>
   Photo slug: QUADRIPLEGIC GRAD 1
</P>
<P>
   NYT10, Ellison and her mother in their dormitory.
</P>
<P>
   Photo slug: QUADRIPLEGIC GRAD 2
</P>
<P>
   NYT11, Ellison and her mother with classmates and workers at the
campus cafeteria.
</P>
<P>
   Photo slug: QUADRIPLEGIC GRAD 3
</P>
<P>
   NYT12, A portrait of Ellison and her mother.
</P>
<P>
   Photo slug: QUADRIPLEGIC GRAD 4
</P>
<P>
   The photos are part of tonight's New York Times Photo Package,
moving Wednesday, 05/17/00. Photo clients will automatically
receive these photos via AP's PhotoExpress or may download them
from either the Wieck Photo Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or
from NYTPhotos on Newscom at 305-448-8411. Non-clients can make
individual purchases by calling (888) 603-1036 or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
