<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOYOTA-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOYOTA PROFITS BOOSTED BY STRONG SALES  
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed.) 
 By STEPHANIE STROM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Toyota Motor Corp., the largest car manufacturer in
Japan and the fourth-largest in the world, on Wednesday reported
surprisingly strong financial results for the second half of its
fiscal year, aided by robust sales in its North American and
Japanese markets and cost-cutting that helped offset the effects of
a strong yen on profits made overseas.
</P>
<P>
   Toyota's earnings climbed 25 percent to 205.1 billion yen, or
$1.9 billion at current exchange rates, in the last six months of
the fiscal year that ended March 31, compared with earnings of
163.5 billion yen in the same period a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   The increase illustrated the effectiveness of the company's
vaunted cost-cutting programs, which contributed a total of $1.4
billion in operating profits to Toyota during the last fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
   The maker of the best-selling Camry sedan and Lexus line of
luxury vehicles also benefited from new models and the redesign of
several old ones in its Japanese market, like the new Estima
minivan and its luxury model, the Crown. Two derivatives of its
popular small car model, Vitz, also sold briskly, and next week the
company plans to unveil a new version of its popular Rav4 sports
utility vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   Profits at several subsidiaries helped, too. Daihatsu Motor Co.,
51.1 percent owned by Toyota, said Tuesday that its net income
quadrupled in the last fiscal year and profits at smaller
affiliates also soared.
</P>
<P>
   ``I must say, the outlook for Toyota is pretty positive,'' said
Koji Endo, an automotive analyst at Credit Suisse First Boston in
Tokyo. ``They have strong volumes in the U.S. and in Japan, and
with significantly more new products, both for Japan and outside,
costs will continue to fall.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite Japan's weak economy, Toyota predicted domestic sales
would climb 6.9 percent to 1.83 million cars in the current fiscal
year. The Japanese auto market is enjoying a small rebound; Goldman
Sachs estimates that domestic car registrations will rise at an
annual rate of 6.4 percent for the next three years.
</P>
<P>
   With its new models and strong brand presence here _ Toyota's
share of the Japanese market climbed above 42 percent in fiscal
1999 _ the company is well positioned for rising demand.
</P>
<P>
   Toyota's sales abroad helped compensate for the strong yen,
which reduced earnings from sales made in foreign currencies. The
yen's strength dealt a vicious blow to Toyota's competitor, Honda
Motor Co., which is heavily reliant on the U.S. market.
</P>
<P>
   Toyota's shares ended 2.6 percent lower at 4,930 yen, or about
$45, on the Tokyo Stock Exchange.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-17-00 1459EDT &QL; 
