<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 15:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7768 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-OLY-SAILING-HNS &LR;      05-17 0845
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-SAILING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     SAILOR KEEPS EYE ON 2004 AS OLYMPIC DREAM FADES AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JERRY BRIGGS  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Last month, the ``Bullet Lasagna'' sailing star
left his heart on San Francisco Bay.
</P>
<P>
   In a grueling eight-day, 16-race regatta, Mattia D'Errico
confronted choppy seas, tricky currents and the best of America's
one-man, small-craft skippers.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, he finished 18th out of 32 in the Laser class of the
U.S. Olympic Trials for sailing.
</P>
<P>
   It was the second time in D'Errico's 11-year career that he has
entered the Trials and fallen short of his Olympic dream.
</P>
<P>
   ``The elements we had to deal with were really hard,'' said
D'Errico, 22, a native of San Antonio. ``I thought I sailed very
well. The chips just didn't fall into place for me. Really, it's a
tough thing for me to handle.''
</P>
<P>
   D'Errico, who earned the ``Bullet Lasagna'' moniker several
years ago on a family sailing expedition, roared into San Francisco
with substantial momentum.
</P>
<P>
   He entered last fall at No. 4 in the North American Grand Prix
rankings, which includes Laser sailors from the United States,
Canada and Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   In October, D'Errico earned his berth in the Trials when he won
the U.S. Single-Handed Nationals at Long Island, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   After moving to the West Coast earlier this year, he added a
grand prix victory in the Mid-Winters West Regatta at San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   But on the first race of the Trials, disaster struck, as
officials disqualified D'Errico for an improper start.
</P>
<P>
   To make matters worse, he made a sharp turn in the third race
and flipped the 14-foot fiberglass craft into the 50-degree water.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just a really hard venue, extremely tough,'' recalled
D'Errico, who rallied for a 10th-place finish in the eighth race.
``Out there, you didn't even have to make a mistake and a boat
would pass you.
</P>
<P>
   ``You make one (mistake), and the whole fleet passes you.''
</P>
<P>
   Undaunted, D'Errico said he intends to try again in the summer
of 2004, and the experts have said he could be a top-five contender
if he can maintain what has become a $55,000 annual budget.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad jokingly told me to go get a job,'' D'Errico said. ``I
do have plans to do this again. I haven't finalized anything, but
the guy who won at the Trials was 29. I think I'm still in this.
I'm so close.''
</P>
<P>
   The winner in the Trials was John Myrdal of Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   Several years ago, D'Errico's campaign for sailing supremacy
became known as team ``Bullet Lasagna'' during a campfire dinner at
Eagle Mountain Lake, near Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   Joking about a wayward racer known as ``Bullet'' Marinelli,
family members tweaked the name, tied it to a favorite food and
bestowed it upon a sailing-crazy teen-age duo _ Mattia D'Errico and
his younger sister, Lacy.
</P>
<P>
   A bullet, in sailing parlance, is a first-place finish. So
``Bullet Lasagna'' seemed fitting for the D'Errico family, which
had started to stack up a few victories.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first time I saw Mattia, he was so small,'' said
Houston-based sailing instructor John Kolius. ``It was at a clinic
I was giving. He really had trouble staying up with the older kids.
I called him `The Worm.'''
</P>
<P>
   Gradually, D'Errico has inched his way toward stardom.
</P>
<P>
   Building himself up physically in the weight room, he also has
honed his skills on the water, and has maintained a top 10 grand
prix ranking in North America for the last three years.
</P>
<P>
   Lacy D'Errico, 18, recalled fond memories of the family's
weekend outings to Galveston, Austin and beyond.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a great way for us to bond,'' said Lacy D'Errico, who
has cut back substantially on her competitions lately. ``Mattia and
I were always pretty close. But with the sailing, we were able to
become best friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Mattia D'Errico made his first major splash in the sport four
years ago when he won the U.S. Open and qualified for the 1996
Trials.
</P>
<P>
   At the age of 18, he emerged as the youngest sailor in the Laser
class at Savannah, Ga. Overmatched, D'Errico placed 46th and
withdrew from the event early.
</P>
<P>
   Kolius said D'Errico's career should be viewed with the
perspective that very few racers qualify for the Trials as a high
school senior.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Kolius said, most prominent sailors grow up on either the
East or West coasts with greater access to open water.
</P>
<P>
   ``Texas is a tough place to come out of and be successful,''
said Kolius, a skipper in three America's Cup races. ``We have some
very beautiful and very good places to race, but it's not a
mecca.''
</P>
<P>
   D'Errico is considering relocating to Rhode Island to race in a
professional circuit, sailing larger craft with nine-or 10-man
crews.
</P>
<P>
   After about 18 months, D'Errico said he likely will return to
his one-man Laser boat in an effort to prepare for 2004.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a contender this time, and I just came up short,''
D'Errico said. ``Next time I'll have all my guns blazing.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Jerry Briggs can be reached by e-mail at
jbriggs(at)express-news.net)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
