<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 15:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7777 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CPT-INTERNET-DETECTIV     05-17 1859
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-INTERNET-DETECTIVES-TRIMS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CYBERSLEUTHS AT WORK IN PURSUIT OF INTERNET CRIMINALS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By MATT RICHTEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Within hours after a destructive computer program began
circulating this month, borne by an e-mail message marked ``I Love
You,'' a handful of high-tech detectives around the globe leaped
into action.
</P>
<P>
   Scrutinizing clues left in the programming code, and pursuing
evidence accumulated in hidden corners of cyberspace, the
detectives homed in on several suspects in the Philippines. And
within days, Onel A. de Guzman, whose name the investigators had
turned up, came forward and said it was possible he had unleashed
the rogue program.
</P>
<P>
   But the detectives are unlikely to testify at trial, or receive
official commendation. That is because they are not police
officers, but ordinary citizens, like a retired software
entrepreneur in Cambridge, Mass., and two Swedish computer security
experts.
</P>
<P>
   They are among a growing number of Net habitues turned
cybersleuths whose work has become vital to the pursuit of Internet
criminals. In the spirit of members of a neighborhood watch
program, they protect their turf on the Internet and point law
enforcement officials to leads. And some have escalated their role
from tipster to sleuth, accumulating evidence to identify actual
suspects, including malicious hackers, virus writers and online
child pornographers.
</P>
<P>
   Armed with home computers and technical expertise, the
cybersleuths themselves say there are only a few hundred of them.
But these amateur detectives have pursued suspects in some of the
most highly publicized cybercrimes, assisting in an area where law
enforcement officials say they lack resources and sometimes
expertise. Police agencies have even deputized cybersleuths and
worked with them in the most critical parts of investigations.
</P>
<P>
   As private citizens, however, the cyberdetectives can also be
hard to control and monitor. And law enforcement officials say that
sometimes they act less like members of a neighborhood watch than
like vigilantes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a computer game,'' said Paul Coggins, U.S. attorney
in Dallas. ``They're playing catch-the-crook.''
</P>
<P>
   The authorities have relied on citizens with technical expertise
for some time. But Coggins said he now sees a higher proportion of
citizens seeking to pitch in on cyberspace-related crime fighting
than he does in the physical world, perhaps because cyberdetectives
never have to leave home. ``Some people who have come to our
attention are spending an inordinate amount of time doing this,
then calling law enforcement,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And even as federal and state law enforcement agencies are
beefing up the personnel and technical resources devoted to
investigating computer crime, many say they still welcome the
outside assistance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Law enforcement is more and more reaching out to the private
sector for knowledge, for training,'' said Michael McCartney,
special investigator for the high-technology crime unit of the New
York State attorney general's office, who said he keeps several
high-tech experts on his informant payroll. ``We all have to work
together in fighting this thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the sleuths say that what drives them is not an urge to
play police officer, but rather a simple desire to protect
cyberspace. ``As computer geeks, we felt the Internet belonged to
us,'' said Kevin Patterson, founder of Ethical Hackers Against
Pedophilia, a group that works with law enforcement to track down
online child pornographers. ``Just like saying, `You're not going
to sell crack on our corner,' we don't want you to distribute child
pornography on our Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   Patterson, a 33-year-old computer network administrator in
Knoxville, Tenn., founded Ethical Hackers in 1997 when he came
across a lurid picture of a 4-year-old girl in an unrelated
discussion forum. ``It reminded me of my niece,'' he said, and he
vowed to hunt down online purveyors of child pornography.
</P>
<P>
   Impassioned foes of child pornography are common in the physical
world too, but what is remarkable in cyberspace is the interaction
between citizens and the police, as Patterson's case illustrates.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, the state of New York started Operation
Sabbatical, an investigation of a group suspected of circulating
child pornography online. Strapped for resources and expertise, the
state turned to Ethical Hackers, a group whose members identified
themselves online with names like Chalk, Sgt. Rock, Merc, Tattoo
Man and Conjure.
</P>
<P>
   McCartney, from New York's high-tech crime unit, said he did
background checks on the men first. ``We traveled to some of their
homes and inspected their computers,'' he said, making sure none of
them were child pornographers.
</P>
<P>
   On Oct. 28, 1998, law enforcement officials obtained 21 search
warrants in 14 states and 4 countries, while the members of Ethical
Hackers played central roles from their home computers. While
warrant-bearing police knocked on doors of suspected members of the
ring, the members of Ethical Hackers effectively barred access to a
discussion area in cyberspace where child pornographers were known
to congregate, flooding it with meaningless data to render it
unusable. The idea was that if the members could not communicate,
they would not be able to warn one another about the raids.
</P>
<P>
   McCartney said the idea of using private citizens in this way
was so unusual that the FBI declined to participate. But he said
his team decided it needed to employ the technical expertise of the
Ethical Hackers. ``I didn't wake up one day and know everything
there is to know about high-tech investigations,'' he said. Still,
he said the situation was unusual. ``We don't want other vigilantes
thinking they can do the same thing,'' he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Often, the arrangements between citizens and the police appear
to be less formal. Richard Smith, a software entrepreneur in
Cambridge, Mass., who made a name for himself as a private citizen
sleuth who helped track down the author of the Melissa virus in
February 1999, said he had periodic discussions with law
enforcement officials about cybercrimes, some discussions started
by the authorities and others by him.
</P>
<P>
   Smith refused to comment on whether he was contacted by the FBI
after the I Love You program began spreading, but he did say he
started working on the case minutes after he learned about it on
May 4. Smith looked at the source code _ the instructions and text
_ buried inside the rogue program and discovered an e-mail address,
ispyder(at)mail.com. He then got in touch with the president of the
company that operates that e-mail service and urged him to contact
the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   In the following days, Smith said he searched Internet news
groups and Web sites for key words that he had found in the source
code of the program and pieced together evidence suggesting that
the program originated in the Philippines. He then publicized his
findings in conversations with reporters. Smith said he had time to
devote to these tasks because he was on sabbatical. ``It's fun,''
he said of his motivation. ``It's a game.''
</P>
<P>
   On May 7, Smith joined forces with two Swedes, Jonathan James,
19, and Fredrik Bjorck, 27, with whom he had collaborated in the
Melissa case. They pursued what Smith said was a crucial discovery
by James, namely that the name of the hacker group GrammerSoft,
which was embedded in the source code, was also embedded in the
source code of a virus called Myckl.
</P>
<P>
   In turn, the Myckl virus included the name of students at Amable
Mendoza Aguiluz Computer College in Manila, including de Guzman.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said he did not know whether he and his cohorts were
responsible for directing the FBI and Philippine authorities to de
Guzman, who surfaced last Thursday. Jim Margolin, a spokesman for
the FBI's New York office, which is leading the bureau's
investigation, said the agency had consulted with the three men and
had done so in the past. ``I can't characterize the value of the
information or how instrumental it's been in this case,'' he said.
``We've found their information to be useful in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   But however grateful law enforcement officials may be, the
cyber-sleuths often leave them uneasy. Some law enforcement
officials worry that amateur detectives may break the law
themselves when hunting down cybercriminals. Police officers say
the concern is particularly acute with child pornography foes, who
have been known to shut down pornographic Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Della-Colli, director of the Cybersmuggling Center, the
online investigative arm of the U.S. Customs Service, said Customs
often receives e-mail messages from people who forward child
pornography they have downloaded from the Internet. It is illegal
to download child pornography.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you observe criminal activity, we instruct you to take down
the license plate,'' Della-Colli said. ``We don't want you crawling
in the back window of the house to give a detailed accounting of
what they're stealing.''
</P>
<P>
   Coggins, the U.S. attorney in Dallas, said private citizens
could also interfere with an actual undercover investigation, or
gather evidence in an illegal way that undermines a conviction.
``Any mistakes they make really come back to haunt us,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The work of Joel de la Garza, a recent Stanford University
graduate who now works for a computer security firm, illustrates
the potential pitfalls for amateur cybersleuths, no matter how well
meaning or skilled. He was working part time in Stanford's computer
security office when he started tracking activities of hackers who
were breaking into university computers.
</P>
<P>
   Among other tactics, de la Garza created programs to record
conversations in chat rooms where hackers were believed to
congregate. Then in February, after a spate of attacks that blocked
or impeded access to major commercial Web sites, de la Garza got a
tip that someone using the name Mafiaboy, thought by some private
sleuths to have been involved in the attacks, was hanging out in a
chat room in a forum called Internet Relay Chat. Once again, de la
Garza logged onto the chat room using an alias, and recorded a
discussion. In this one, Mafiaboy took credit for crippling the CNN
Web site.
</P>
<P>
   De la Garza said he turned the transcript over to the FBI,
though he cannot be sure if it contributed to the arrest last month
of a Montreal teen-ager in the case. But while potentially valuable
evidence, the material that de la Garza gathered is ``arguably
violating your state's two-party consent'' laws that prohibit
recording conversations without the other party's assent, said
McCartney of the New York State attorney general's office.
``There's no clear-cut answer,'' he said. ``There are a lot of laws
you have to watch out for.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, de la Garza says he never set out to be a crime
fighter. ``I don't want to be a cop,'' he said. ``I just want these
guys to stop messing with the Stanford computers.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-05-16-00 2352EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-17-00 1511EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
