<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 15:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7780 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-G8-CYBERCRIME-0518-CO     05-17 1015
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-G8-CYBERCRIME-0518-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FAST PACE OF TECHNOLOGY LEADS G8 NATIONS, INDUSTRY TO WORK
TOGETHER TO FIGHT INTERNET CRIME
 &HT;    (600&AMP;ADD)
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (f) Financial categories.
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON JR. 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ While offering few concrete proposals to deal with the
rising tide of computer crime, law-enforcement officials from the
major industrialized powers pledged Wednesday to forge a campaign
to secure the Internet from fraud and virtual vandalism.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the dizzying speed of technological change
law-enforcement agencies will have to rely on the expertise of the
Internet industry to keep up, delegates to the G8 Cyber-crime
Conference said.
</P>
<P>
   The three-day summit was the first high-level meeting between
industry and government leaders of the world's major economic
powers, the Group of Eight countries _ the seven industrialized
democracies of Britain, Canada, France, Germany, Italy, Japan and
the United States, plus Russia.
</P>
<P>
   While many issues remain to be resolved _ indeed, the conference
helped determine what the important questions are _ both sides said
that cooperation is vital.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Assistant Attorney General James Robinson said governments
are incapable of policing cyberspace alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only way for effective law-enforcement to occur is by
creating dialogue with industry experts that can help law
enforcement to track down cyber-criminals,'' Robinson told
reporters as the summit wrapped up Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Saying that the Internet has rendered borders ``meaningless,''
he also said that governments will also have to find innovative
ways to work together to scale cumbersome legal and logistical
obstacles that can slow the pursuit of computer hackers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to work at 'cyber speed' with regard to investigation
and prosecution of cyber-crime,'' said Robinson, who heads the U.S.
Justice Department's criminal division.
</P>
<P>
   A new ``24-7'' system that provides a virtual hotline among
law-enforcement and technical experts in 15 countries _ the G8,
plus others such as Sweden, Australia and Brazil _ represents a
major advance in assisting police in pursuing cyber-criminals
across borders, Robinson said.
</P>
<P>
   David Aucsmith, the chief scientist at Intel Corp., urged
industry leaders to cooperate with governments, particularly in
training ``cyber-police'' and keeping law-enforcement agencies up
to speed on technological innovations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Governments should not be the last to know about technology,''
said Aucsmith, who emerged as perhaps the top industry spokesman
during the conference. ``It is probably of use to industry to make
sure that the government understands what the technology can be out
there so governments can pursue hackers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think the most important thing that came out of the meeting
is that cyber-crime is a worldwide thing, and it is every country's
problem and every company's problem,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The conference identified six basic principals that should be
taken into account in pursuing anti-cyber-crime policies:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Ensuring the protection of individual freedoms and private
life;
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Preserving governments' ability to fight high-tech crime;
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Facilitating appropriate training for all involved;
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Defining a clear and transparent framework for addressing
cyber-criminality;
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Ensuring free and fair activities, the sound development of
industry and supporting effective industry-initiated voluntary
codes of conduct and standards;
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  And assessing effectiveness and consequences.
</P>
<P>
   If nothing else was accomplished, the conference provided a rare
opportunity for industry and law-enforcement officials to meet _
albeit behind closed doors _ and get acquainted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone at the convention has agreed to exchange E-mail
addressees,'' said Toshinori Kanemoto, a Japanese police agency
official and conference chairman.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Despite the air of cooperation, divisions remain between
governments and the private sector over how to fight cyber-crime.
The world's leading Internet players say they expect to work with
governments, but have expressed concerns that excessive state
intervention could stifle the enormous growth of the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   While U.S. and British officials leaned toward industry
self-regulation, other officials, particularly those in Europe
favored more state intervention.
</P>
<P>
   Vladislav Selivanov, the Russian interior minister, used a
metaphor to explain that individual rights and commercial freedom
may at times have to be tempered to help crimefighters. ``When you
enter a church, you take off your hat, not your head,'' he said
when asked about his country's attitude about keeping a balance
between the rights of the state and individuals.
</P>
<P>
   French President Jacques Chirac left no one in any doubt that
his country wanted a bigger state role. ``To prevent and fight
crime, our democratic societies have only one legitimate actor _
the state _ and a single method _ applying the law.''
</P>
<P>
   Italy also advocated for more state intervention.
</P>
<P>
   All players at the conference excluded, for the moment, creating
an international ``cyber police'' body.
</P>
<P>
   Internet users worldwide are expected to reach more than a
half-billion by 2003, industry representatives said. The value of
Internet retailing is expected to rise from $20 billion to $185
billion by 2004. At the business-to-business level, it is expected
to jump from $100 billion to more than $2.7 trillion over the same
period.
</P>
<P>
   The G8 meeting is the first international gathering of law
enforcers, business representatives and government officials to
address the burgeoning problem of cyber-crime. It will report its
conclusions to the G8 summit in Okinawa in July.
</P>
<P>
   (Bert Roughton Jr.'s E-mail address is: BertR(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   For more information:
</P>
<P>
   www.cybercrime.gov
</P>
<P>
   www.fraud.org,
</P>
<P>
   www.g8parishightech.org
</P>
<P>
   www.ifccfbi.gov
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
