<HEADLINE>
YOUR MISSION: TO ELIMINATE SPY PROGRAM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  By DR. EMILIO BOMBAY  
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: My ex-wife downloaded a spy-type program. I
knew something was wrong when the hard drive ran every time I
pressed a key. Yes, this is my home PC. With a lot of effort, I
eventually found ``KeyLogger.'' I was able to delete it using Safe
Mode. Something is still in there, I think. The hard-drive light
continues to blink every few seconds. Is there any way other than
wiping the hard-drive to find these spy programs?
</P>
<P>
   _ Bugged in California
</P>
<P>
   DEAR BUGGED: Well, I understand why you divorced her. These
weaselly keystroke recorders are abominable evidence of just how
endangered the concept of trust has become.
</P>
<P>
   The same technology that gives us instant access to a world of
information also gives your boss, your spouse, your neighbor and
even your government an easy way to spy on you. And this isn't the
usual paranoid rant: I'm not even going to mention the black
helicopters that have been following my every move.
</P>
<P>
   Just be aware that anything you do on a computer potentially can
be seen by somebody else. It may be a $30 shareware program that
somebody slips onto your hard drive or a multimillion-dollar
radio-frequency sniffer that the CIA uses to track your keystrokes
from a block away, but you should always act as if something is
watching and recording. I don't think I was supposed to mention the
CIA thing.
</P>
<P>
   There are a couple of types of recorders. The one you disabled
was fairly easy to get to and not much of a challenge to kill. When
it runs, it sits between your application programs, like
word-processors or browsers, and the part of the Windows system
that interprets keystrokes. It gathers what you type and saves them
to an encrypted log file. These kinds of loggers generally show up
when you hit Control-Alt-Delete to get the list of everything
running in Windows. You can kill it there temporarily if you know
what it's called, but it'll restart when you reboot.
</P>
<P>
   You were able to permanently delete it while you were in Safe
Mode since most background programs don't load when you start
Windows like that. If your ex-wife is as devious as I imagine,
there's more going on, though.
</P>
<P>
   The other kind of recorder is a stealth logger. It loads at such
an elemental level of the Windows system that it's invisible. It
works in much the same way, though. Generally, it will store around
50 keystrokes, then dump them to a log file. That may be why your
drive light is blinking.
</P>
<P>
   The bad news is that unless you know for sure which file to look
for, you've pretty much got a needle-and-haystack scenario. To find
out if something really is recording, you might try using the Find
utility in the Start menu to look for all recently modified files.
There's a chance you'll spot a continually growing log file to
verify your suspicions.
</P>
<P>
   If it was me, I'd nuke the drive.
</P>
<P>
   I'd also like to emphasize, for my editors', uh, reassurance,
that, in my purely professional opinion, the use of any such
software at the office would negatively affect computer performance
and endanger productivity, and that I was checking those
airline-ticket prices for an upcoming travel story.
</P>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: A little humility would be refreshing!
</P>
<P>
   _ Harrrummmph!
</P>
<P>
   DEAR HAR: You want humility? Go read Ann Landers. She's got a
lot to be humble about.
</P>
<P>
   (Dr. Emilio Bombay was recently selected Man of the Year by the
Bombay Institute of Electrical Shocks and Psychic Surprises. You
could have knocked us over with a feather. Write him at
drbombay(at)star-telegram.com (snail-mail: Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, TX 76101). Fax: (817)
390-7257. In the nonvirtual world, Dr. Bombay is Michael Gerst,
editorial systems manager for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-05-12-00 1328EDT &QL;
</P>
