<HEADER>
A7783 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-DEM-CONVENTION-HNS &LR;      05-17 0826
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEM-CONVENTION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     GOVERNOR SEEKS STATE AID TO PROTECT DEMOCRATIC CONVENTION 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ROBERT SALLADAY  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ As activists around the country secure
lawyers and plan for massive demonstrations at the Democratic
National Convention, Gov. Gray Davis is asking the Legislature for
$4.1 million so the Los Angeles police and the California Highway
Patrol can pay overtime and buy equipment in preparation for
potential riots, vandalism or terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   Davis spokesman Michael Bustamante said the money should not be
taken as a sign the governor is worried about anarchy at the August
convention in downtown Los Angeles. The state, he said, simply
should shoulder a portion of the burden being put on the LAPD and
other law enforcement agencies because of the weeklong convention.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles police, the Secret Service, the FBI and the CHP,
which protects California dignitaries, are preparing for a huge
show of force in Los Angeles, if needed, after the wild
demonstrations in Seattle and Washington, D.C., over global trade.
</P>
<P>
   The LAPD said it has been working for more than a year with
about 30 police agencies planning for the convention. They sent
agents to Seattle and Washington to observe the police and
protesters there. They also plan to send a team to the Republican
National Convention in Philadelphia in late July to get pointers.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, groups of demonstrators have become equally
organized. The National Lawyers Guild hopes to engage up to 60
volunteer attorneys to represent arrested protesters. It has
scheduled two training sessions so its observers can learn how to
monitor the police and get names and badge numbers, and so
volunteer civil attorneys can learn how to represent criminally
accused clients for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   ``What are we preparing for?'' said Cynthia Anderson-Barker, an
attorney with the Lawyers Guild in Los Angeles. ``We're preparing
for large numbers of demonstrators, there is no question about
that. But our goal is to inform people of their legal right to
protest and make sure their rights are respected.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson-Barker said the recruited attorneys will be trained in
dealing with protesters who refuse to give their names and
addresses to police officers. They also should be prepared to
``have many clients who range in charges from petty unlawful
assembly to felonies,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles police said they will set up a public
demonstration area near Staples Center, the convention site, and
will close streets to the public, diverting traffic away from the
convention. The police hope demonstrators will stay in the
so-called ``protest pit,'' but they know that is unrealistic for
some protesters.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect to have a lot of people who are going to want to
slow down traffic and disrupt operations of the convention,'' said
LAPD Lt. Horace Frank. ``Our No. 1 priority is to ensure the
community is not disrupted. Second, that the convention goes as
planned. And third, that people get to exercise their
constitutional right to demonstrate, but do so peacefully.''
</P>
<P>
   Without elaborating on the department's plans, Frank said the
LAPD wants to make sure it has all the tactical resources it needs
to respond to any situation. At the beginning of the convention,
that probably means uniformed officers patrolling the convention
center, not a hugely visible show of force.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to be standing 24 hours a day in front of the
convention in riot gear,'' Frank said. ``Our hope is this is going
to be a peaceful convention.''
</P>
<P>
   Similar plans are being worked out in Philadelphia for the GOP
convention that begins in late July. Demonstrators there have won a
critical legal battle with the police over Philadelphia's planned
protest pit. Protesters were given the right to march down a main
thoroughfare as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just felt that the whole concept of having one spot in the
city where you could express your First Amendment rights was
outrageous,'' said Michael Morrill, an organizer with Unity 2000,
the umbrella group for Philadelphia organizers. ``When we found out
about the police plan, we encouraged people not to participate.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis, a Democrat, announced the $4.1 million for the LAPD this
week in his budget address. The administration wants $730,000 for
the CHP to ``fund dignitary protection for elected state officials
and 21 (Democratic) governors from other states'' attending the
convention.
</P>
<P>
   The remaining $3.4 million will buy equipment that will be
loaned to the LAPD for ``additional security as well as terrorism
preparedness and prevention,'' the governor's Department of Finance
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a lot of overtime. There are a lot of costs that are
going to happen,'' Bustamante said, ``and a lot of economic good
because of the convention. This is just some assistance.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
