<SLUG> BC-CPT-LOVEBUG-FAX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SECRETS OF LOVE REVEALED, WHEN `I LOVE YOU' CAME AS A FAX 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By JOHN MARKOFF   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a direct echo of Neal Stephenson's path-breaking 1992 science
fiction novel ``Snow Crash,'' the recent Love Bug computer worm had
one oddly disturbing behavior: In a few scattered cases the program
faxed itself to its victims.
</P>
<P>
   In the dystopian ``Snow Crash'' vision of the world, viruslike
software leaps across the boundary separating machines from humans.
</P>
<P>
   Here is a sample passage, describing the hacker's means of
invasion: ``He messes with binary code for a living. That ability
is firm-wired into the deep structures of the brain. So he's
susceptible to that form of information. And so are you,
home-boy.''
</P>
<P>
   In a case of life imitating art, when the virus struck the
Thursday before last, a reporter received a copy of one of the ``I
Love You'' notes _ in this case, as a fax accidentally sent by the
Microsoft Corp.'s public relations office. (``It's an interesting
and logical conclusion to everyone's desire for
mega-connectedness,'' a Microsoft spokesman said of the incident.)
</P>
<P>
   Attached to the cover sheet, which stated ``kindly check the
attached LOVELETTER coming from me,'' were two pages of the
program's destructive code. Because the code had been attached to
the e-mail message as a standard word processing text file, the fax
machine simply printed it out.
</P>
<P>
   Because the rogue program was designed to send itself to every
address in a Microsoft Outlook e-mail address book, when it came
across a fax number in the list it simply transmitted itself via
fax.
</P>
<P>
   In Stephenson's novel, the invasive virus also carries
subliminal messages, such as ideologies and other concepts.
</P>
<P>
   The LOVELETTER fax, though, did not seem to carry any subliminal
information. And yet, since it was sent from the embattled
Microsoft Corp. to a technology writer who covers the company, who
really knows?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-05-14-00 1653EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-17-00 1515EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
