<SLUG> BC-CPT-PHILIPPINES-LOVEBUG-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIRUS BRINGS PUBLICITY TO COMPUTER SUBCULTURE IN PHILIPPINES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By WAYNE ARNOLD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANILA, Philippines _ If what local investigators suspect is
true, the virus that brought some of the world's most sophisticated
computer networks to a halt this month was hatched in a noisy
inner-city neighborhood where residents live under corrugated steel
roofs and raise fighting cocks in their front yards.
</P>
<P>
   It was in a two-bedroom apartment on the ground floor of a
grubby concrete apartment building that an unremarkable programming
student named Onel A. de Guzman lived with his sister Irene and her
boyfriend, Reonel Ramones.
</P>
<P>
   There, de Guzman worked on his college thesis: a program
designed to help fellow Filipinos gain free access to the Internet
by harvesting passwords from paying subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   He said last week that he might have inadvertently unleashed the
program that on May 4 spread to computers around the world
disguised as an innocuous e-mail message titled ``I Love You,''
costing by some estimates $10 billion in lost data and
productivity.
</P>
<P>
   That the world's most infectious computer virus to date could
have such origins illustrates how the Internet's global sprawl has
left the network vulnerable to disruption from even its most remote
technological backwaters.
</P>
<P>
   For the Philippines, on the other hand, the ``Love Bug'' and the
hacker subculture that it exposed are an embarrassing advertisement
of the country's programming talent and infant dot-com scene. They
also raised the issue of the cost of Internet access for developing
countries struggling to close a daunting technology gap with richer
countries.
</P>
<P>
   While maintaining that he meant no harm, de Guzman said that
Internet access should be free and that charging for its use was
immoral. In his thesis, which his college rejected, he introduced
his program by saying it would help many people ``spend more time
on the Internet without paying.''
</P>
<P>
   To understand the grudging admiration people here have shown for
de Guzman, Internet executives say it helps to understand the
public's reverence for a more low-tech Filipino innovation, a
vehicle known as the jeepney.
</P>
<P>
   Jeepneys made their first appearance after World War II,
hand-built from liberated Japanese equipment and U.S. Army jeeps of
dubious provenance. The ungainly utility vehicles transformed
four-seat machines of war into gaudily decorated, smog-belching
conveyances for as many as 22 commuters.
</P>
<P>
   Maligned these days as unsafe and environmentally unsound, the
colorful jeepney survives on Philippine roads as cheap public
transport and a symbol of Filipino ingenuity.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like the jeepney,'' Zenisa Perez, an analyst at the
Manila office of the International Data Corp., a computer research
company, said of the de Guzman's program. ``He made do with what he
has.''
</P>
<P>
   In a country where the gap between rich and poor is enormous,
Filipinos say, the jeepney ethos has moved beyond transportation to
inspire a kind of subculture of proletarian larceny. Poor Filipinos
commonly tap into everything from power lines to cable television.
</P>
<P>
   The Business Software Alliance, a U.S. trade group that fights
software piracy, estimates that about 77 percent of the software
used in the Philippines is pirated.
</P>
<P>
   Like commercially written software, the Internet is considered
by many Filipinos to be unjustly expensive. While customers in the
United States and other developed countries can use it at
negligible cost, or even free, Internet services here charge nearly
$1.50 an hour.
</P>
<P>
   Why so expensive? Limited competition for international
telecommunications links keeps Internet access more than four times
as expensive as in the United States. Making matters worse, poor
domestic telephone lines mean that the fastest connections here are
still roughly 50 times slower than the best lines available to
Internet users in the United States. Most Filipinos do not even
have a telephone, much less a personal computer.
</P>
<P>
   At the school that de Guzman attended, Amable Mendoza Aguiluz
Computer College, the situation is even more challenging. The
school has 150 branches around the country, though it has yet to be
accredited. Many of its instructors are recent graduates, and de
Guzman's campus in Manila is in a former warehouse without flush
toilets.
</P>
<P>
   It is no MIT, but to its 15,000 students it holds the promise of
a lucrative career, perhaps even the chance to work in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Myra Deguro, an 18-year-old junior, grew up in a
home without a phone. She hopes to turn her computer science degree
into a secretarial job if she does not land a position in a
high-tech company.
</P>
<P>
   Deguro is fortunate: her father is a driver for a wealthy Manila
family, which is paying her annual tuition and laboratory fees of
about $1,500. Other students, she says, end up taking time off so
they can save enough money to graduate.
</P>
<P>
   Students say Internet access is a precious commodity. College
labs limit them to several prescribed hours among a limited number
of computers, many of which are incapacitated at any given time by
unsuccessful student programs or successful student viruses. That
leaves Internet cafes, which offer a more reliable, though
expensive, alternative.
</P>
<P>
   De Guzman, students say, is just part of a lively Filipino
hacker community that has sprung up to circumvent such obstacles.
In addition to selling homework projects, they say, hackers often
circulate purloined account information among the student body.
</P>
<P>
   One of several local hacker sites, the Pinoy Virus Writers Web
site, declares: ``Information will be free for everyone.
Information will be fed to those in need. Information shall never
again be sealed.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all of the students applaud the hackers' sentiments.
</P>
<P>
   The college administration is also not amused. It said Saturday
that it would seek disciplinary action against de Guzman and the
nine other members of a group of student programmers named
Grammersoft, whose name appeared in the ``I Love You'' virus' code.
Grammersoft's members, two of whom have reportedly already gone off
to work in the United States, deny any involvement in the case. One
group member, Michael Buen, appeared at a news conference on Sunday
to declare his innocence. De Guzman and his lawyer could not be
reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   But the police have not formally named any suspects in the
suspected misdeed, which so far does not appear to be an explicit
crime under Philippine law. Legislators are pushing for a new law
that would make a crime of unauthorized entry of computer networks.
</P>
<P>
   The only charge pending is against de Guzman's roommate,
Ramones, contending that he violated a law against misusing
passwords.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-05-14-00 2054EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-17-00 1516EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000517.0161 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 15:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7793 &Cx1f; ttd-z
u a BC-CPT-GENECOMPUTER-CELE     05-17 1296
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-GENECOMPUTER-CELERA-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPERCOMPUTER HELPING CRACK GENETIC CODE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By TOM ABATE   
 c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROCKVILLE, Md. _ At Celera Genomics' data processing center
stood a supercomputer, 5 feet tall and nearly as wide.
</P>
<P>
   It had no lights, no monitor, no way to display the fact that
all its circuits were straining to solve a giant puzzle _ how to
put the 3 billion chemical letters of human DNA in the proper order
and thus produce the first complete copy of the human genome.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's only one other like it in the world,'' Celera
spokesman Paul Gilman said, patting the silent machine. Its mate
was under wraps in the research laboratories at Compaq Computer,
which plans to unveil the Alpha GA160, or Wildfire, on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   With 64 gigabytes of RAM _ a thousand times as much memory as a
store-bought PC _ Wildfire is one of the most powerful civilian
computers in the world. The fact that Celera got its Wildfire three
weeks before the official release date is testimony to the fact
that DNA discovery has become the hottest challenge in computing,
as high-tech gurus team up with biologists to unravel the software
of life.
</P>
<P>
   ``The genome effort is pushing every aspect of computer science,
from mathematics and database software to hardware and
networking,'' said Peter Karp, who heads a research group at SRI
International in Menlo Park that focuses on bioinformatics _ the
effort to search, study and store biological data.
</P>
<P>
   DoubleTwist Inc. of Oakland, Calif., is a perfect example of how
those who hope to study DNA data must first build the computing
tools to make that possible. Last week, using three supercomputers
and 350 workstations from Sun Microsystems of Palo Alto, Calif.,
DoubleTwist identified 105,000 possible genes by sifting through
the mass of information stored in a public database.
</P>
<P>
   Before DoubleTwist could start its gene hunt, however, a team of
programmers including Honbo Zhou, who worked on IBM's Deep Blue
chess-playing computer, and Kyle Hart, a specialist from the
University of Pennsylvania, had to write software that treated all
those supercomputers and workstations as one giant processor.
</P>
<P>
   Assembling this virtual machine was just their first step.
Finding genes in the DNA posed an equal challenge. DNA is made up
of four chemicals, represented by the letters A, T, G and C. They
are joined in a string more than 3 billion letters long.
</P>
<P>
   But only 3 to 5 percent of those letters encode the genes, and
it is genes that are expected to lead to breakthroughs in promoting
good health or combatting disease.
</P>
<P>
   What the rest of those DNA letters do is still a mystery, but
for the gene hunters, the challenge was to sift through that
unwanted information to find the desired data. Yannick Pouliot,
director of DoubleTwist's bioinformatics group, said DNA does
provide some clues as to where genes begin and end. The letters ATG
signal a start. Stop signs can be expressed as TGA, TAG or TAA.
</P>
<P>
   But out of billions of letters, the programs are bound to
encounter many false starts and stops.
</P>
<P>
   ``Distinguishing the actual starts is one of the greatest
challenges,'' Pouliot said. ``They don't (all) stand out, that's
the problem.''
</P>
<P>
   So the data must be sifted time and again, using a variety of
comparative software. Sylvia Spengler, director of computational
genomics at Lawrence Berkeley Laboratory, said these programs look
to see whether possible genes resemble genes that are already
known.
</P>
<P>
   ``At some level, it's like the children's game of animal,
vegetable or mineral,'' Spengler said. ``You ask questions of the
data by comparing it to what you know.''
</P>
<P>
   The trouble with DNA analysis is that we still know so little
about genes that it's hard to develop software that asks the right
questions. Spengler likened the current computer studies of the
genome to the maps used by early European explorers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'd drawn the continents as big blobs without distinct
coastlines, and when they got to unknown waters, they'd say, `There
be dragons here,''' she said. ``Well, we've got lots of dragons.''
</P>
<P>
   One subtle sign of the cross-fertilization of computing and
biology has been the spirit of playfulness that the bioinformatics
specialists bring to their tasks.
</P>
<P>
   At DoubleTwist, where the 25-person programming team worked
nonstop for nine months, games of foosball and pingpong broke the
tension, while Friday afternoon beer busts provided informal
brainstorming sessions.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, a tour of the computing department at Celera showed
cubicles armed with as much Nerf firepower as an Internet startup.
About two-thirds of the firm's 400 employees are either hardware or
software engineers, with biologists rounding out the mix.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Celera's chief computer scientist, Gene Myers, in many
ways exemplifies the cyber-biologic synergy driving the genome
effort.
</P>
<P>
   For a brief meeting in the Celera cafeteria, Myers showed up
wearing a leather jacket and scarf _ evidence that he had ridden to
work on his hog, a Shadow 1100 motorcycle. His blue sapphire
earring, he explained, is a memento of his many years as a computer
science professor at the University of Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   But behind this Brandoesque exterior, Myers is redefining the
science of computerized puzzle solving. Celera's privately funded
effort to sequence the human genome is predicated on the notion
that the company could break the 3 billion letters of DNA into
blocks 500 letters long, and then put these pieces back together
again with computer software and hardware.
</P>
<P>
   The publicly funded scientists who began the Human Genome
Project never believed a puzzle that huge could be solved, so they
opted to break the genome into several dozen midsize puzzles that
could be solved more easily.
</P>
<P>
   Celera bets that its more daring strategy will succeed first.
Myers has yet to prove the point by producing a 3 billion-letter
sequence of human DNA; that's the problem that has the Wildfire
supercomputer working overtime.
</P>
<P>
   But even skeptics were impressed in March when Celera, in
conjunction with researchers at the University of California at
Berkeley, used Myers' puzzle-solving software to sequence the
genome of the fruit fly, the most ambitious DNA study done to date.
</P>
<P>
   True, the fruit fly project involved only one-30th as many
pieces as the human genome puzzle. But then Celera cracked that nut
using 800 smaller Compaq processors. When asked just how many
pieces of data he is asking the computers to sort this time, Myers
took off his glasses, closed his eyes and rubbed the bridge of his
nose.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a one with 360 zeros after it,'' he said, looking up
again. Indeed, that data set is so huge, even Wildfire's 64
gigabytes of memory can't open the file in one chunk. ``We need
about 600 gigabytes of memory,'' Myers said at a scientific meeting
last week. Because memories that huge don't yet exist, Celera has
had to chop its puzzle up so that Wildfire _ with the help of those
smaller Compaq processors _ can comprehend the task.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, the objective of all this genome research is to put
data in a form that can be easily searched over the Internet so
that it's available, not just to drug and biotech researchers, but
to doctors and patients. That distribution problem poses huge
challenges, said Spengler, the researcher at California's Lawrence
Berkeley Laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   ``How are people going to access it from laptops?'' she asked.
And, one might add, how far over the horizon might that be?
Spengler might love to venture a guess, but right now, on her maps,
there be dragons in the way.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Tom Abate at abate(AT)sfgate.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-05-14-00 2219EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
