<SLUG> BC-CPT-ECOMMERCE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
E-COMMERCE: CATALOG COMPANIES EXPLOIT THE WEB 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By BOB TEDESCHI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In this season of comeuppance for Internet-only retailers,
catalog companies that also sell on the Web may finally be getting
their due.
</P>
<P>
   Even as the stock prices of so-called ``pure play'' electronic
retailers spiked last Christmas season, the e-tailers acknowledged
that they would still need to spend hundreds of millions of dollars
on marketing and warehouses to make their businesses viable _
investments the catalog companies had made long ago.
</P>
<P>
   Internet merchants also acknowledged their need for direct
marketing expertise _ an admission that might have seemed downright
flattering to catalog companies, if they were not too busy trying
to keep the dot-coms from luring away their best executives.
</P>
<P>
   But now that investors have turned their attention to
profitability, the old-line catalog companies that have built the
most extensive Web operations are stepping into more favorable
light. Companies like Lands' End, Hanover Direct and BMG Direct are
already generating profits from their e-commerce sites. And, thanks
to the Web, the prospects for their catalog businesses are
improving.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their numbers are staggering,'' said Barbara Wykoff, an
analyst with the investment firm Buckingham Research. ``It's
frightening how fast they're growing.''
</P>
<P>
   Lands' End, for example, generated 3 percent of sales from its
Web site (www.landsend.com) in 1998, Wykoff said. But last quarter,
that number was 12 percent. BMG Direct, a Bertelsmann unit that
sells CDs, generated 10 percent of its sales from the Web last
year, and could reach 15 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
   Wykoff said that companies with a catalog pedigree _ including
J.C. Penney, Lands' End and L.L. Bean _ not only have some of the
most visited e-commerce sites on the Web, but they have proved to
be the best at converting browsers to buyers. Those three companies
each have conversion rates of 13 to 16 percent online, according to
Nielsen NetRatings, an Internet research firm, compared with an
average of about 1.8 percent among all Web retailers.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps the most important statistic separating catalog
companies from their Web-only competitors is customer acquisition
cost. According to a recent survey by the Boston Consulting Group
on behalf of the industry association Shop.org, catalog retailers
spent $11 on average for each new customer last year. In
comparison, e-tailers spent $82 per customer.
</P>
<P>
   The reason for such a disparity, of course, is that e-tailers
are still burning through tens of millions of dollars in
advertising to attract customers to their sites.
</P>
<P>
   Catalog companies, meanwhile, have a built-in marketing vehicle
that can sit around a consumer's house for weeks before it reaches
the trash. And to make sure customers remember the Internet sites,
catalog companies often print their Web addresses on every page.
</P>
<P>
   Catalog companies also report that instead of the Web
cannibalizing their catalog sales, it is creating new customers.
</P>
<P>
   Hanover Direct, which owns several catalog operations, including
Gump's, International Male and the Company Store, said that 50
percent of its online customers last year had not previously
purchased goods from their catalogs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've found that taking a print catalog and using targeted
marketing principles is the most efficient way to create online
customers,'' said Rakesh K. Kaul, Hanover's chief executive. ``It's
no contest,'' he said, when compared with ``e-tailers who go out
and buy ads on the Super Bowl.''
</P>
<P>
   The Web has also helped build the overall profit the company can
squeeze out of each customer over repeat visits, he said. Rather
than send an existing customer a new catalog each month, Kaul said,
the company complements the catalog mailings with e-mail messages,
thereby reducing marketing costs. ``So the Web now becomes a very
efficient way to maintain customer contact,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Catalog businesses benefit from the Web in other ways as well.
</P>
<P>
   George McMillan, chief executive of BMG Direct, said the company
could use the Web to test and create new catalog ideas that might
not otherwise be viable.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can't identify a market of 400,000 to 500,000 users,
you can't justify the product development costs and research
necessary to test it,'' McMillan said.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the Web, you don't have any paper or printing costs
associated with testing an idea,'' he continued. ``You can try more
things without getting burned, and maybe find niches of the market
that are smaller, but still make sense economically.''
</P>
<P>
   McMillan declined to say if BMG would roll out new catalogs
aimed at BMG customers as a result of this testing. But he said the
company was ``experimenting with some things'' among BMG's 10
million customers _ 2.8 million of whom are online. ``There are a
lot of segments in 10 million people,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Happy as they are with their core businesses, catalog companies
recognize that it is far more economical to close a sale over the
Web than over the phone, so they are pushing to convert more of
their customers to the Web with every passing month. According to
Wykoff of Buckingham Research, catalog companies ``won't save a
significant amount of money'' on overall customer costs ``until the
Internet gets to 20 percent of their business.''
</P>
<P>
   There are exceptions. Bear Creek Corp., which owns Harry and
David, a food catalog and Web site (www.harryanddavid.com),
generates about 9 percent of its sales on the Internet, and saves
about $4.60 for each order placed through the Web, according to
Nancy Tait, the company's executive vice president. Given the
orders the company handled on the Web last year, that amounts to
about $1.1 million saved.
</P>
<P>
   But as Lands' End found out last year, companies cannot rely too
much on the Web to deliver profits. Lands' End mailed about 9
percent fewer catalogs last holiday season, analysts said _ a move
that might help explain its 17 percent dip in holiday sales and a
substantial decline in its stock price.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an inextricable link between the catalog and the
site,'' said Bill Bass, vice president of e-commerce for Lands'
End. ``Our traffic always spikes when the catalogs arrive.''
</P>
<P>
   But that will not stop the company from an Internet-only
approach in other countries. This summer, Bass said, Lands' End
will roll out sites in several European countries where the company
does not mail catalogs. As for marketing in those countries, he
said, ``online, word-of-mouth means a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   For catalog companies, one of the most satisfying aspects of the
recent slide in e-tailing stocks is that their own employees are
now less inclined to jump ship when a dot-com recruiter calls.
``That's been a real drain on our industry,'' said Tait of Bear
Creek. ``I'm hoping those days are over.''
</P>
<P>
   They may be. Kaul of Hanover said that dot-coms were now more
interested in forming partnerships with catalog companies than in
luring away their employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've seen a number of Internet companies approach us recently
saying, `Gee, why don't you create a catalog for us and help us
understand how this works?''' he said. ``So I wouldn't be surprised
if you see more and more combinations in the catalog and Internet
world.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-05-14-00 1749EDT &QL;
</P>
