<HEADLINE>
AOL-TIME WARNER MAY HAVE A `SUPER-EDITOR' 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  (ART ADV: Photo NYT1 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By ALEX KUCZYNSKI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last Thursday night, Norman Pearlstine, the editor in chief of
Time Inc., boogied to the sounds of Barenaked Ladies, the Canadian
pop group, at a party at San Francisco's Pacific Bell Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The occasion was an invitation-only party for 1,000 guests to
introduce Time Inc.'s E-Company Now, an offshoot of Fortune
magazine that will focus on the Internet economy.
</P>
<P>
   The party was supposed to mark the first time that executives
from Time Warner and America Online celebrated the birth of a Time
Inc. magazine together. And the gala took place far from Time
Warner's New York headquarters, in a city more closely linked with
the new-media culture that America Online so embodies.
</P>
<P>
   Gerald Levin, chairman of Time Warner, and Don Logan, chief
executive of Time Inc., joined Pearlstine. Stephen M. Case,
chairman of America Online, was supposed to attend but could not
get away from the East Coast. He sent remarks by videotape.
</P>
<P>
   Which raises the inevitable question: Can the current executives
of Time Warner and America Online all boogie to the same corporate
tune?
</P>
<P>
   That question was addressed, at least for the moment, last week,
when the two companies released an organization chart with a mother
lode of corporate turf under the name of Robert W. Pittman, an
America Online executive and the designated co-chief operating
officer of the new company, to whom Logan and his magazine
division, pushed further down the food chain, will now report.
</P>
<P>
   And within the last six weeks, Pearlstine has seemingly answered
questions about his own immediate future. A year ago, it was widely
believed inside Time Inc. that he would leave the job of editor in
chief at the end of 2000, a belief that led to an internal guessing
game about whether John Huey, managing editor of Fortune, or Walter
Isaacson, managing editor of Time magazine, was more likely to take
his job.
</P>
<P>
   But the 57-year-old Pearlstine has renegotiated his contract and
in an interview last week said he would stay at the company for at
least another three years.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the corporate tinkering may be far from over. Two senior
Time Inc. executives said last week that an editorial job might be
created above Pearlstine's, a sort of AOL Time Warner super-editor
who would oversee _ and try to create synergies between _ the
journalistic activities at Time Warner and America Online. In this
scenario, one person would supervise the journalistic work of CNN,
Time Inc. and America Online.
</P>
<P>
   The notion of an editor in chief for the integrated company
would please both Case and Levin, who have discussed the notion,
the executives said. Both men are determined to show an integrated
company to Wall Street _ and Time Warner has never been perceived
by the business community as particularly well integrated. And
Levin, the Time Inc. executives said, has not been excessively
pleased with the level of synergy within his own company,
particularly between Time Inc. and CNN.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Costiglio, a spokesman for Time Inc., said no plans had
been made for the editorial-czar position. But with Pittman now
overseeing subscription and advertising sales not only at Time Inc.
but for other Time Warner and AOL divisions as well, some believe
it might make sense to have an executive with the same breadth of
editorial responsibility reporting to him. If the position is
created, it will not be happen before the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Or, as another Time Inc. executive put it: ``Until the merger is
done, you never know how things will play out.''
</P>
<P>
   America Online has long argued that the separation of editorial
church and commercial state does not jibe with the new-media
concept that success comes from the integration of commerce and
content.
</P>
<P>
   But does it make sense to alter a magazine division that is
thriving so mightily? Time Inc. _ a division that includes both
magazines and book publishing _ took in $4.6 billion in revenue in
1999, according to the company's annual report, up from $4.4
billion in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The magazines that the division publishes range from the
outrageous puffery of In Style and Teen People to the authoritative
business coverage of Fortune magazine. (Only 6 percent of the
division's revenue was attributable to book publishing, according
to industry estimates.)
</P>
<P>
   Pearlstine, at a conference sponsored by Industry Standard and
New York magazines two weeks ago, said he was less worried about
interference from America Online on the editorial front than about
the internal distribution of corporate resources. How does one
convince Wall Street, he asked, that investing in a new magazine is
better than say, expanding a cable system?
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Of course, there are more pressing concerns for Pearlstine. As
Time Warner is absorbed into America Online, there is a question
within the company about whether Time Inc. magazines will receive
special treatment from America Online and whether America Online
might even get preferential treatment in the pages of Time
magazines _ which have so far in fact gone out of their way to
cover Time Warner and America Online with a brusque and sometimes
biting fairness.
</P>
<P>
   (Time magazine clearly portrayed Time Warner as the loser in the
company's public relations battle with Walt Disney Co. over the
Time Warner cable blackout of ABC two weeks ago.)
</P>
<P>
   And there is some minor turbulence within the magazine division:
Real Simple, the new magazine for women from Time Inc.'s immensely
successful People division, has met with disappointment both on the
newsstand and within the company.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Henry Muller, Time Inc.'s editorial director for
seven years, gave up that position to become an editor at large. At
the same time, Isolde Motley _ the former managing editor of Life,
which was closed last month _ was named corporate editor. But no
replacement was named for the editorial director position that
Muller left.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview last week, Pearlstine addressed the issue of
editorial independence _ which has been assured to him from all
angles, he said _ and whether Time Inc. magazines would receive
preferential treatment on America Online.
</P>
<P>
   ``From a distance you might say, `Why do this merger if you
don't do that?''' Pearlstine asked. ``But I think it winds up being
more an issue of right of first refusal. If it makes sense, you
obviously want to cooperate. But if you try to force everything
through those filters, you will probably get in trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   The situation, Pearlstine said, is not unlike that in which Time
Inc. found itself when Time magazine sought a television network as
a partner in producing a special based on Time magazine's Person of
the Century issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went to CNN first and they said, `We don't have a lot of
money to put into this, and we don't have 50 years of archives,
because we haven't been around that long, and we don't have that
many customers for this kind of appointment viewing,''' he said.
``Meanwhile, CBS was there saying, `We have fifty years of
archives, and lots of eyeballs and money to put into it.' So we
wound up doing the deal with CBS.''
</P>
<P>
   All the instincts within the company, Pearlstine said, ``will be
to _ the old Wall Street cliche _ `unlock shareholder value' by
finding more synergy in the deal.'' But he added, ``Gerry, and
certainly Case, at least to date, have been saying that where it
makes sense, we will do deals, but where it does not, we will
not.''
</P>
<P>
   Pearlstine insisted there were no substantial problems at Real
Simple _ although one senior staff member said the new magazine
might better be described as ``real complicated.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It has some work to do, and it is a hard concept to execute,''
he said. He added that because of the swift success of Teen People
and In Style, both of which also originated in the People division,
the introduction of Real Simple faced higher expectations from the
outset than most magazines. The first issue was also released at
the same time as the first issue of Hearst Magazine's ``O: The
Oprah Magazine,'' which Pearlstine described as ``first-rate.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the larger corporate structure has yet to
affect Pearlstine, or his relationship with Logan. It is known
throughout Time Inc. management that Logan and Pittman get along
well. They share the ideas about using each other's companies to
get more subscriptions and about using the two companies together
as a formidable advertising platform _ and they have similar
Southern backgrounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm from Mississippi, and he's from Alabama,'' Logan said.
``So we both know the difference between hush puppies and
barbecue.''
</P>
<P>
   As for filling the super-editor job, candidates mentioned
include Pearlstine, Isaacson and, to a lesser degree, Huey.
</P>
<P>
   Logan would not comment on whether the new position would be
created. As for any other changes, he said: ``You will see some
movement within the management teams. But it too early to say
what.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-05-14-00 1736EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
