<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 15:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7801 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CPT-ARNAULT-PROFILE-A     05-17 1705
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-ARNAULT-PROFILE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PURVEYOR OF PRESTIGE BETS HIS OWN MONEY ON THE WEB 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  (ART ADV:  Photo NYT2  is being sent to NYT photo clients.
 Graphic  is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can
purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 BY ANDREW ROSS SORKIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Bernard Arnault, the chief executive of the luxury goods
conglomerate LVMH Moet Hennessy Louis Vuitton, wants to get
something straight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see myself at all as a fashion guy,'' he said in
fluent, if heavily accented English, in a conference room adjacent
to his office at LVMH's headquarters here.
</P>
<P>
   Arnault, who controls an A-list of luxury goods companies
including Louis Vuitton, Christian Dior, Tag Heuer and Dom
Perignon, would much prefer to be considered ``a business guy'' _
even if he happens to manage fashionable businesses. And even if he
happens to be garbed in Dior from head to toe, as he gives an
interview.
</P>
<P>
   Lately, Arnault has begun to move beyond tres chic to geek chic,
personally investing hundreds of millions of dollars of his own
money into Internet ventures here in Europe and across the
Atlantic. His American investments have included $115 million in
the American online trading firm the Datek Online Holdings Corp.,
$90 million in the controversial music site MP3.com and about $10
million in the Web auctioneer eBay.
</P>
<P>
   But those are mere side bets compared with his ambitious
investment vehicle, Europ(AT)Web, which he sees as a European
version of CMGI, the U.S.-based Internet incubator and holding
company. He has invested $500 million in Europ(AT)Web (pronounced
Europe-at-Web), which plans to make a public stock offering of its
shares in July.
</P>
<P>
   Arnault's is a decidedly European approach to Internet business
_ a game so far being played by executives older and more
established than the young upstarts so common on the American Web
scene.
</P>
<P>
   ``There'll be no Jerry Yang of Europe,'' said Olivier
Beauvillain, a French Internet analyst with the research firm
Jupiter Communications in London. Yang, of course, is the storied
young Silicon Valley billionaire who co-founded Yahoo while still a
student at Stanford University. ``The big Internet players here are
dominated by traditional businessmen,'' Beauvillain said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, many of Europe's largest Internet operations are
outgrowths of traditional businesses, run by management teams with
decades of experience. Take bol.com, the European equivalent of
Amazon.com. Owned by the German media conglomerate Bertelsmann AG,
bol.com is managed by Heinz B. Wermelinger, who is 53 years old.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, at 51, Arnault, is not merely an investor in the Web.
Beneath his tailored suit, he insists, there beats the heart of
cybernaut. ``I've had broadband at home for the past year,'' he
said proudly, then added a road warrior's lament. ``Sometimes I'm
in hotel room and I use narrow band now and it's so frustrating.''
</P>
<P>
   So far the more than one dozen hatchlings from Europ(AT)Web's
incubator have had mixed results. One success is LibertySurf, a
French Internet service provider, that recently went public and
made Arnault's initial investment of $58 million now worth more
than $2 billion. But Europ(AT)Web's 8 percent stake in a British
clothing retailer, Boo.com, has been a disaster, as the company
bleeds losses and the management is fleeing.
</P>
<P>
   Europ(AT)Web has also invested in a bevy of other Internet
sites. Arnault is excited about the prospects for Flutter.com, a
new British betting site, as well as Ze Project, a European online
bank. The group has also invested in MetaMarkets, a discussion site
for individual investors, and Aucland, a French online auction
company.
</P>
<P>
   Arnault still spends most of his working time managing LVMH's
pedigreed line of luxury products. But he says he devotes about a
quarter of his time to Europ(AT)Web, working with his younger
colleagues, of whom he observes: ``They aren't concerned with
fashion. They wear the Gap.''
</P>
<P>
   Arnault contends that even though he has become a business
tycoon and a staple of the glossy fashion magazines, his younger
colleagues do not treat him like a celebrity. ``People are very
relaxed,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Not too relaxed, though. Chahram Becharat, the 33-year-old
managing director of Europ(AT)Web refers to his boss as Arnault,
not Bernard. And Arnault maintains the constancy of Internet time,
in which any time might be work time. ``He usually calls me every
weekend,'' Becharat said.
</P>
<P>
   Arnault, who started his career as an engineer at a French
construction company before trading in his hardhat for haute
couture, became interested in the Internet in 1997, when he
invested in Cisco Systems Inc. After further investigation, he put
a stake in eBay. When both investments came up winners, ``it became
obvious that something was happening in the world with the
Internet,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While the revolution was in full swing in the United States when
Arnault jumped in, the Internet was still a novelty in Europe.
Still, by the time he began Europ(AT)Web in June 1999, investing in
European Web sites and Internet service providers, some analysts
say he was already too late.
</P>
<P>
   ``Europ(AT)Web would have been a massive force if it came along
three years ago,'' said Beauvillain, the Jupiter analyst. ``A lot
of windows of opportunity have closed,'' he added, explaining that
much of the Internet in Europe has already been carved out by
American imports like Yahoo and Amazon.com and earlier European
start-ups.
</P>
<P>
   But Arnault sees a benefit to his timing, even with the
so-called dot-com bubble in the air.
</P>
<P>
   ``During the exaggeration of this `exuberance,' as the Fed says,
you could find any project funded immediately with crazy amounts of
money,'' he said, laughing. ``Today there is more common sense. Now
we look carefully at the business model.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, some business models stand up to scrutiny better than
others. Arnault's due diligence before paying an undisclosed amount
for a stake in Boo.com last April did not anticipate the losses and
management turmoil at the British e-clothier. After spending a
fortune on advertising, sales have not gone as expected.
</P>
<P>
   Europ(AT)Web is now beginning a second round of financing for
Boo.com in the hope of keeping it afloat. Arnault declined to
discuss the situation.
</P>
<P>
   What he did want to talk about was the future of retailing on
the Internet. ``It will never replace the showroom,'' he said,
noting that with many products customers will continue wanting to
actually touch and view the goods. ``But it will change the way we
buy everything,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``When you want to buy a gift, the Web is very useful,'' he
continued. ``I have my assistant telling me next week it's my
nephew's birthday. So I have to send something. So what should we
do?'' he asked. ``A week before, the site can tell me it's his
birthday and tell me what he likes. And it will work for many other
occasions, like my assistant's birthday, too.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Through his personal investments in the Internet, via
Europ(AT)Web, Arnault is gaining experience that helps him assess
the online strategies for LVMH's brands. In a few weeks the company
is opening eluxury.com, a mini-mall peddling only LVMH's most
``fabulous'' brands, according to Arnault.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, LVMH has also started individual sites for some of
its brands, including Dior.com, moet.com, and Sephora.com among
others.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to test the shops,'' said Arnault, who often Web surfs
to keep tabs on the competition. ``When you go to Amazon it's very
well done. But there are other sites that are not as good.'' He
demurred at naming the homely.
</P>
<P>
   But he had no compunction about declaring a winner. ``The best
site for a fashion brand is Dior.com,'' he said, as if the matter
were beyond debate. ``You should look at it. You compare it to
competition. No comparison. It's fantastic. Really.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The Internet project he seems to be most proud of is the
Internet service provider LibertySurf, which was one of the first
companies created by Europ(AT)Web. According to Jupiter
Communications, LibertySurf grew to become one of the top four
access providers in France early this year, with 374,000
subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Talking like an Internet guru, Arnault argued the benefits of
being local. ``So many U.S. companies have so many problems here,''
he said. ``Take AOL in France for example. It was not very good.
It's very strange. LibertySurf did in one year here what AOL
couldn't do in three years,'' referring to how LibertySurf outpaced
the growth of AOL France.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   LibertySurf is a free Internet access provider, modeled on
Freeserve in Britain, which gets its revenue from advertising,
e-commerce and a share of the local telephone charges that modem
users pay in Europe. But Beauvillain, the analyst, said LibertySurf
would face stiff competition as it tried to enter other European
markets, where Internet service providers are already ensconced.
</P>
<P>
   And not all analysts are keen to jump at shares of Europ(AT)Web
when it goes public.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate Internet investment companies, and Arnault's will be no
different,'' said Miles Saltiel, an analyst at the investment bank
West LB Panmure Gordon in London. ``They attract ludicrous
overvaluations and then collapse. But every stupid French investor
will buy it because it is Arnault.''
</P>
<P>
   That may be the rub: With such a high profile, Arnault's
Internet projects tend to have some of the same cachet associated
with the fashionable brands of LVMH _ but without the history and
proven market of brands that have been around for decades.
</P>
<P>
   It is a quandary that Arnault, smoothing his Dior pleats,
readily acknowledges. ``I can guarantee that in one century people
will drink Dom Perignon _ I am sure of it,'' he said. ``What type
of Internet will they look at in one century? I'm not so sure.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-05-14-00 1622EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
