<SLUG> BC-CPT-NEW-ECON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIVIDED AGAINST EACH OTHER; UNITED AGAINST THE GOVERNMENT
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By ALLEN R. MYERSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   About a year ago, Joel Klein, chief of the Justice Department's
antitrust division and perhaps Bill Gates' least favorite lawyer,
was moving into his new home in Washington. He called for cable
service and was told that the cable guy could come between 8 a.m.
and 5 p.m. on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Could they be more specific, Klein asked.
</P>
<P>
   No, they couldn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought of saying, `Do you know who you're talking to?'''
Klein recalled.
</P>
<P>
   He told the story during a recent panel discussion about
monopolies, a forum whose unstated question for debate seemed to
be: If Bill Gates worries the government, then shouldn't the cable
guy _ in the form of a merged AOL-Time Warner _ drive the antitrust
people absolutely nuts? For Klein, the antitrust czar, at least,
the two situations are not comparable. (More on him later.)
</P>
<P>
   The discussion, part of The New Yorker's 75th anniversary
celebrations, came a few days after Time Warner blocked signals
from Disney's ABC network to millions of cable subscribers, then
restored them a day and half later.
</P>
<P>
   Time Warner executives declined invitations from Ken Auletta,
the New Yorker writer who organized the panel, to take part. So
they weren't on hand to defend themselves from the view put forward
by some panelists that the planned merger of America Online and
Time Warner could turn the Internet from an open prairie into a
collection of fenced and gated estates.
</P>
<P>
   Disney proponents, led by the company's pugnacious Washington
lobbyist, Preston Padden, who urged confrontation with Time Warner,
have used the ABC blackout as evidence of why the merger would be
dangerous. Padden, a panel member whose boss, Michael Eisner, sat
in approving attendance in the audience, portrayed AOL-Time Warner
as ``Microsoft on speed,'' and called the blocking of ABC's signal
``a remarkable display of monopoly power.''
</P>
<P>
   Listening to this proved too much for another panelist, Candace
Carpenter, the founder of iVillage, a Web site for women. Having
already said that Disney was first among the media giants that had
tried to squash her and her Web site _ ``I'm representing the
mice'' in the day's discussion, she explained _ she put her head in
her hands and said, ``Disney as the underdog is such an amazing
concept.''
</P>
<P>
   Although iVillage shares have fallen from a high of more than
$100 after the initial public offering last year to below $8 on
Friday, Carpenter actually remains optimistic that mice like hers
can survive by building strong brands and befriending a corporate
elephant or two. And she opposes government intervention as a means
for preserving competition. But she said, ``I do think distribution
is going to become a narrower funnel.''
</P>
<P>
   Padden's strongest support, on legal and technical grounds, came
from Lawrence Lessig, a Harvard Law School specialist in technology
and antitrust who has managed to vex both Microsoft and Time
Warner. Lessig first drew Microsoft's objections in 1997, when the
judge presiding over the antitrust case appointed him to sort out
some issues related to the government's 1995 agreement with the
company.
</P>
<P>
   Based on his comments as a panelist, Lessig is now poised to
become AOL's and Time Warner's least favorite lawyer. ``I'm deeply,
deeply pessimistic,'' Lessig said of the pending merger. He
explained that as Internet service progressed from narrow to
broadband, it would be easier for those providing the service to
favor some forms of content _ theirs _ over others. The openness
that has made the Web so inviting to new ventures and ideas will
suffer, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lessig reminded his audience that AOL formerly wanted the
government to guarantee neutrality in high-speed Internet
communications via cable TV systems, but changed that position once
it agreed to merge with Time Warner. All the more reason for the
government to step in, he said, adding, ``You don't want the
Internet to turn out like TV.''
</P>
<P>
   Eisner, Disney's chief executive, took in these arguments with a
benign smile. Afterward he declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   But Lessig also needled the Disneyites, saying that a proposed
law to strengthen and extend copyrights would hinder public
discourse and innovation. He said the ``Mickey Mouse Protection
Act,'' as he called it, and similar measures seem to come up
whenever Mickey risks falling into the public domain.
</P>
<P>
   Time Warner took the opportunity to respond to the panelists a
few days after the debate. Ed Adler, a spokesman from Time Warner,
said in an interview that AOL and Time Warner had committed
themselves to offering diverse content. And he said any
discrimination in favor of their own products _ on the Web, on
cable, or anywhere else _ would scare off their other corporate
customers. ``If either company did that, there would not be a
business,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   With the AOL-Time Warner merger now before the Federal Trade
Commission and the Federal Communications Commission, Klein of the
Justice Department doesn't have jurisdiction in the matter. But he
does have an opinion: that the AOL-Time Warner merger is nothing to
fear or prevent. (He said he couldn't recall the cable company that
had refused to give him a specific appointment, but it wasn't Time
Warner.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Who would think in a panel of all these people, I'm the
optimist?'' he said. ``There is a market mechanism that is going to
answer this question. Technology is so powerful that in the next
three to five years there are going to be alternative mechanisms
into the home.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft had proven a much bigger threat, he said, because the
company was able to use its monopoly power to restrict Netscape's
access to personal computers.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft had no representative on the Auletta panel. But the
company points to the pending AOL-Time Warner merger as evidence
that other companies can indeed thrive as Microsoft's rivals. AOL,
in fact, has pounded Microsoft's MSN Web network at every
opportunity. ``AOL, before and after its merger with Time Warner,
is a serious competitor on a wide range of businesses,'' Jim
Cullinan, a Microsoft spokesman, said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   If the panelists' debate had no clear winner, at least one thing
is now clear: In wanting to fend off government, Microsoft, AOL,
Time Warner, Bill Gates and the cable guy are all on the same side.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-05-14-00 1629EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
