<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 15:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7810 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CPT-MICROSOFT-AT&AMP;T-NY     05-17 1086
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-MICROSOFT-AT&AMP;T-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT CITES AT&AMP;T TO FIGHT BREAKUP
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By JOEL BRINKLEY  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Comparing the proposed breakup of Microsoft to the
AT&AMP;T case of the 1980s, Brad Smith, a Microsoft lawyer, said he saw
one big difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``AT&AMP;T was mostly a national company,'' he said, ``but Microsoft
is operating in a global marketplace. If we are replaced as the
technology leader, there's no guarantee that our successor will be
from this country.''
</P>
<P>
   Seventeen years ago, as AT&AMP;T was preparing to spin off its
regional telephone companies to resolve an antitrust case, Charles
Brown, AT&AMP;T's chairman, had a similar thought.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess the competition feels pretty good about it,'' he said.
``The Japanese, primarily.''
</P>
<P>
   As the Microsoft antitrust case hurtles toward its conclusion,
both sides are drawing on the experiences of AT&AMP;T to support their
legal and political arguments, though in some cases the references
are inaccurate or incomplete. And a few of Microsoft's darkest
predictions mirror arguments AT&AMP;T made 20 years ago _ predictions
that never came to pass.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's legal briefs rebutting the government's breakup
proposal, filed with the court on Wednesday, include numerous
references to the AT&AMP;T case, and Joel I. Klein, head of the Justice
Department's antitrust division, devoted considerable attention to
the subject in a speech on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The record shows that in the late 1970s and early 1980s, AT&AMP;T
mounted aggressive legal arguments against the government's
proposed breakup plan. Innovation would be stifled, research
stunted and a precious national resource _ the world's best
telephone system _ would be destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   None of that happened.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there is nothing to demonstrate that if Microsoft is
broken up, its experience, for better or worse, will resemble
AT&AMP;T's. Still, in invoking the AT&AMP;T case to justify some of its
arguments, Microsoft is in some instances misstating the record.
</P>
<P>
   Consider Bell Labs, which was the vaunted research arm of AT&AMP;T,
and its counterpart at Microsoft, the research division. The
government's breakup proposal makes no recommendation for how
Microsoft's research group would be treated; that would be decided
later.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Microsoft's brief said: ``Research and development
organizations are fragile organisms, and the notion that they can
be pulled apart with minimal adverse consequences is dangerously
naive.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The one unit of AT&AMP;T that remained intact during AT&AMP;T's
divestiture of its regional operating companies,'' it adds, ``was
Bell Laboratories, an organization with strong parallels to
Microsoft as a whole.''
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T, like Microsoft, argued during its trial that a breakup
would damage or destroy the company's research capabilities. But in
fact, Bell Labs, formed in 1925, was broken up along with the rest
of the company; 7,500 of the lab's 25,000 employees were taken away
to form the nucleus of the new Bellcore research lab serving
regional telephone companies.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T has since spun off Bell Labs; now it is part of Lucent
Technologies. And the engineers and executives leading the labs
today say they believe they are doing quite well.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sure looks to us like we've been just as prolific in the
last 15 years as were were in the previous 50,'' said Michael
Jacobs, a spokesman for the labs. ``The pace of innovation at Bell
Labs today is faster than it's ever been.'' Bell Labs scientists
have won two Nobel Prizes in the last 15 years, in 1997 and 1998,
compared with four in the previous 50 years. Jacobs said he
believed the prospect of increased competition after the breakup
energized the Bell Labs scientists and ``fired up'' the labs.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere in its brief, Microsoft seeks to draw a fundamental
distinction with AT&AMP;T by arguing that ``Microsoft is a unitary
company,'' not ``an agglomeration of separate operating
companies.''
</P>
<P>
   As it happens, AT&AMP;T made the same argument during its trial.
Central to its lawyers' defense was that ``the Bell system was so
tightly integrated that you could not take it apart without doing
enormous damage to the best telephone system in the world,'' said
Philip Verveer, a Washington lawyer who worked for the government
during the early stages of the AT&AMP;T case.
</P>
<P>
   ``They showed that they had a tremendous number of assets in
common, and the entire industry was structured around integration''
_ down to the long distance toll switches embedded in the local
phone switching stations.
</P>
<P>
   A expert witness who testified on behalf of the Bell system
during that trial, but who asked not to be identified, said the
company's legal team tried to make the case that ``the monopoly was
necessary for rapid technological change.''
</P>
<P>
   Verveer added, ``They said they could not be pulled apart, but
all of these arguments proved to be incorrect.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Microsoft is also arguing that continued innovation will be
threatened if the company is split up. Microsoft's success and
ability to create innovative new products ``would not have been
possible but for Microsoft's unified structure.''
</P>
<P>
   Another AT&AMP;T argument is more complicated, with both Microsoft
and the government falling afoul of history.
</P>
<P>
   Acknowledging that AT&AMP;T did remain a highly innovative company
after it was broken up, Microsoft argues in its brief that it was
not the breakup that freed AT&AMP;T to compete and innovate, but an
accompanying order to deregulate it.
</P>
<P>
   In his speech on Tuesday, Klein countered that by noting that
AT&AMP;T and the Baby Bells were left with significant restrictions
prohibiting them from entering one another's markets. But Microsoft
notes that AT&AMP;T labored under a far more onerous regulation
previously, prohibiting the unified company from branching into new
businesses not related to telephony.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe so, a government official said, but while AT&AMP;T was a
monopoly, smaller companies trying to make telephone equipment
``kept running into AT&AMP;T and got nowhere if AT&AMP;T wasn't interested
_ that's exactly analogous to Microsoft.'' The company disputes
that.
</P>
<P>
   Verveer said the analogies could be taken only so far. ``The
AT&AMP;T case was about physical assets primarily,'' he noted, ``while
with Microsoft we are largely talking about human capital _ very
smart people.''
</P>
<P>
   As Microsoft does, Verveer says that makes the outcome of this
case harder to predict.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-05-14-00 1548EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
