<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 15:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7812 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-CPT-G8-CYBERCRIME-051     05-17 0927
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-G8-CYBERCRIME-0516-COX </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 &HT;    INTERNET CRIMINALS STAYING ONE CLICK AHEAD OF LAW ENFORCEMENT
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON JR.  c.2000 Cox News Service  PARIS _ The
<TEXT>
world's law-enforcement agencies are struggling to keep pace with
Internet criminals who strike without warning and then slip nearly
unseen into cyberspace leaving behind few clues, officials at an
international cyber-crime conference said Monday.
<P>
   The three-day conference, organized by the G8 group of
industrialized nations, is the first international gathering of law
enforcers, business representatives and government officials to
address the burgeoning problem of cyber-crime.
</P>
<P>
   A virtual crimewave is accompanying the surge in worldwide
Internet use that is forcing authorities to develop new sets of
skills to counter rivals who are developing sophisticated new scams
at rate that far outpaces conventional police tactics, industry and
law-enforcement officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, because the Internet has no national borders
authorities are hampered as they pursue cyber-criminals across
jurisdictions where laws and customs often have not been brought up
to date.
</P>
<P>
   David Aucsmith, the chief scientist at Intel Corp., said that
government and industry leaders are beginning to find some
consensus in how to approach the problems of Internet crime but the
gap remains.
</P>
<P>
   ``The technology has outpaced any of our ability to agree on
some of the social ramifications of it,'' said Aucsmith, one of the
industry leaders at the conference. ``The technology is much easier
to evolve than are policies or laws.''
</P>
<P>
   James Robinson, head of the U.S. Justice Department's criminal
division, said law-enforcement officials confront a dizzying array
of issues in combating cyber-crime.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson said cyber-criminals ``can sit at a laptop and commit a
crime across the street and weave it through seven countries and
pretty soon you don't have any idea where it's coming from,''
Robinson told reporters at the conference.
</P>
<P>
   International protocols will have to be changed to allow
investigators to move through various jurisdictions quickly. ``When
things are moving at such a speed, you can't sit there and work for
months and months to wait to have things translated and go through
this process,'' Robinson said.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, the interests of law-enforcement agencies often
are in conflict with the desires of computer users to protect the
secrecy of their transactions and privacy of their communications,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a tension between finding a way to secure the system
to minimize misuses that still allows us to do the job we need to
do,'' he said. ``We all think about coming across encrypted
communications ... that may involve terrorist acts or kidnapping or
other ... criminal activity.''
</P>
<P>
   While officials say that it is very difficult to measure the
scope of Internet crime, there is a consensus that is growing
rapidly. The FBI opened an online fraud complaint center last
Monday and received 3,700 complaints in the first 3 1/2 days. ``We
were frankly kind of surprised because it isn't well-known, yet,''
said Tom Packard, the FBI's delegate at the conference.
</P>
<P>
   Despite heightened concerns about fraud with the explosion of
online financial transactions, many industry officials say they
worry more about viruses, such as the ``Love Bug'' variant that
struck hundreds of thousands of computers a week and a half ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``The threat of serious crime is not that significant at the
moment,'' said Aucsmith of Intel, which produces the ubiquitous
Pentium microprocessors. ``However, the average person using the
Internet is actually subject to a considerable amount of attack.
Those attacks are the equivalent of cyberspace vandalism. They're
not fraud., not someone robbing you.''
</P>
<P>
   Packard said he was concerned by the apparent trust people put
in information on the Internet. ``What's more troubling to me is
the way people view the internet, and if it's on the Internet they
seem to be more trusting of it or more believing in it whether it's
a news article that they read in the Internet or baseball cards,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   One of the thorniest issues facing the conference is defining
the limits of industry self-regulation. Generally, Internet
companies resist government involvement, seeing in it a potential
form of censorship and an invitation to let states meddle with the
sector's organic growth.
</P>
<P>
   They prefer fighting cyber-crime with technical innovation,
educating users and companies about security risks, and making
better use of existing laws.
</P>
<P>
   A conference delegate, Stephanie Perrin, chief privacy officer
at a Canadian company, Zero-Knowledge Systems. Inc., said firms,
while eager to uphold the law, are suspicious of ``extending the
arm of law enforcers into the private sector.''
</P>
<P>
   Delegates hope the conference will develop a consensus on basic
principles in policing cyberspace. However, it is unlikely to
produce any sweeping multi-national policies. It ends Wednesday and
will report its conclusions to the G8 summit in Okinawa in July.
</P>
<P>
   The G8 comprises the G7 group - Britain, Canada, France,
Germany, Italy, Japan and the United States - plus Russia.
</P>
<P>
   (Bert Roughton Jr.'s E-mail address is: BertR(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   For more information:
</P>
<P>
   http://www.cybercrime.gov
</P>
<P>
   ww.g8parishightech.org
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
