 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 &HT;    Use browser to open those downloads
 &HT;    By Sue Cleere and Jacki Rudd
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Dear Sue and Jacki: I can't find a good answer to why
I can't open many downloads, both photos and text files. Often, all
I get is ``gobbledygook'' symbols. Is software available that will
``read'' all these?
</P>
<P>
   _ Jack D.
</P>
<P>
   Sue: These days there are so many graphic and text file types.
You may be able to open one and not another. Take a look at your
browser preferences. In Netscape, go to Navigator/Applications.
You'll see a list of file types and applications. Make sure the
file type you're opening is listed with an application that will
open it. If it is, double-click to make sure the file type
information is correct. In Explorer, refer to the Receiving
files/File Helper preference. Double-click the format to make sure
it's configured properly.
</P>
<P>
   Jacki: Try to open graphics and text documents in a browser
window. Simply download the file and drop it into your browser.
Voila! The file can be viewed. Browsers have format limitations,
though.
</P>
<P>
   Sue: PC users might want to try Pad. It's freeware. It opens
text and graphics. For Mac viewers, look at DoItAllText or
RealView, $25 shareware. Download them from CNet.com. There may be
garble at the top, but scroll down to see the ``real'' text. They
do a nice job on graphics. DoItAllText even lets you view movies.
</P>
<P>
   Dear Sue and Jacki: What can you tell me about the i-opener?
</P>
<P>
   _ William D., Stuart, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Sue: It's a 5-pound gadget that fits anywhere. Billed as an
Internet ``appliance,'' the i-opener could go in your kitchen but
isn't a toaster. It's an out-of-the-box, flip-up-the-screen,
plug-and-play way to hit the Net.
</P>
<P>
   Jacki: Internet service, browser and e-mail are ready to go. It
has e-mail and Web access _ that's all. Its goal is to connect with
the technophobe and appeal to PC households wanting a mini-Web
cruiser in another room.
</P>
<P>
   Sue: It has two components: A 10-inch flat screen and a
keyboard. The i-opener uses a 56k modem (broadband's next). It
shares your phone line but claims it won't hog it. Information
channels bring you news, weather, sports, financial, etc. Get this,
a Pizza button points you to a pizza delivery place.
</P>
<P>
   Jacki: The i-opener costs $99 until Father's Day. After that,
it's $199. You can buy a mouse and printer, too. Internet access is
$21.95 a month. Buy from Netpliance (www.netpliance.com/) or
Circuit City and CompUSA, although it's big-time on back order.
</P>
<P>
   Sue: Want a real eye-opener? You're locked into the i-opener's
Internet service. Also, you must activate the service within 30
days and buy it for at least 90 consecutive days. If you violate
the terms of sale, there's a $499 termination fee.
</P>
<P>
   Sue Cleere and Jacki Rudd write for The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution. E-mail questions to techsavvy(at)ajc.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
