 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 &HT;    Women totally at home on Web
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It's always amusing to read those ``gee whiz''
articles in newspapers and magazines marveling at the fact there
are so many women starting up Internet companies, designing and
producing Web sites and actually using the Web.
</P>
<P>
   Most stories about wired women make it sound as if we had just
won the vote, when nothing could be further from the truth. If you
are a woman and have a computer, you can go online, e-mail your
mom, order books or even play fantasy baseball. And millions of
women do these things every day.
</P>
<P>
   The annual media excitement about women online always seems odd
to me, because I happen to be one of those women who was somehow
able to find my way to a computer and log on to the Internet about
six years ago without any trouble whatsoever.
</P>
<P>
   I'm sure Amazon.com, eBay, Webvan and my close personal friends
at Visa will all tell you their accounting departments just love me
and all the other wired women (and men) who know how to click that
``submit'' button.
</P>
<P>
   With a telephone assist from my best friend Janet, I even
installed a newer, faster modem one night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't be afraid,'' she said as she coached me through the
installation process. ``It's just a piece of metal.'' And she was
right. Going online is not rocket science, and more and more women
are discovering this, which is good news for the Web and all the
people who write and produce content and commerce for it.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the runaway success of Salon's ``Mothers Who Think''
daily columns (www.salon.com) written by ordinary women talking
about ordinary things like parenting and the struggle to balance
work and family. (``Mothers Who Think'' became so popular that
there's now a hardcover collection available from Amazon.com or the
local bookstore.) Sites like iVillage (www.ivillage) and relative
newcomer Oxygen (www.oxygen.com) also cater to an audience of wired
women who want to do more than check stock quotes or read the
paper. Wired women tend to use the Web to communicate and to learn
more about the world around them.
</P>
<P>
   A new study from the Pew Internet and American Life project
released last week shows that women are going online not to isolate
themselves but to stay close to the people and issues that concern
them.
</P>
<P>
   The study (www.pewinternet.org), designed to get an accurate
reading of how the Net impacts the lives of average Americans, was
based on a daily poll of Internet users asking what they did not
just that day only, but the previous day as well, when recent Web
adventures were fresh in their minds.
</P>
<P>
   The findings reveal that more than 9 million women have gone
online for the first time in the last six months and that these
women are far from alienated, isolated computer addicts. For women,
the Internet is an enriching experience that enables them to stay
in touch with family and friends around the corner and around the
world. The new crop of online women has reshaped America's social
landscape, the study says, because women have used e-mail to enrich
their important relationships and enlarge their networks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet has the opposite of an isolating effect on these
users,'' the study said. ``They report that e-mail has helped them
improve their connections to relatives and friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Even without the Pew study, there are millions of women who log
on every day just to chat with faraway friends and relatives.
Several women I know, myself included, have been able to maintain
long-distance relationships with family and friends that never
would have survived if letter writing, birthday cards and phone
calls were the only means of communication.
</P>
<P>
   ``More than men,'' the study says, ``women say they are attached
to e-mail and pleased with how it helps them.''
</P>
<P>
   However, when women are done sending and reading e-mail, they do
go online to search for information. Here, the Pew Study says, the
Web sites women visit most are very different from the sites men
visit. Women are more likely to seek health and religious
information, research new jobs and play games online. Men are more
likely to get news and financial information, trade stocks,
participate in online auctions, shop, access government Web sites
and search for sports news.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't necessarily a situation that needs to be corrected,
and the Pew study does not suggest that it should. Everyone has
different interests, and they go to the Web sites that address
them,interests, whether it's the stock market or online grocery
shopping.
</P>
<P>
   But the study does note that Web veterans who have been online
for three years or longer know their way around the Web and a wider
variety of sites that reflect that experience. The main point that
should be taken away from the study is that women are online,
surfing the Web for communication, utility and fun.
</P>
<P>
   MaybeNow might be time to stop all the ``golly gee'' noise about
women on the Web and just get used to the fact that women are
online right alongside the boys.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
