 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 &HT;    Souping up computer takes just a few touches
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When I was a young man, way too much of my time was
spent trying to get more speed and louder exhaust noises out of a
car that began life as a rather ordinary Chevrolet Chevelle.
</P>
<P>
   After I was done, it had more bolted-on equipment than a space
shuttle built from junkyard parts.
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays cars aren't that big of a deal to me. Instead, I spend
just as much childish zeal and grown-up money hopping up my home
PC. From what I can tell, lots of folks are in that same boat.
Computers have taken the place of hot rods for those of us who
never quite grew up.
</P>
<P>
   That's why a lot of the stuff I do isn't really necessary. It's
just fun. Besides, it does speed up the computer, and as was true
with that red Chevelle, it pleases me in intangible ways. So come
along with me, we'll crawl under the hood of that PC of yours and
make a few minor changes.
</P>
<P>
   Memory: Let's add a lot. Modern versions of Windows seem to
thrive on more memory. At one time, you ran into the law of
diminishing returns at 32 or 64 megabytes. But now, if you have
less than 128 megabytes of RAM, you can really add some life to
that old machine with more memory.
</P>
<P>
   Tweaking: Click on the Control Panel to open it, then open the
System icon. Click on the tab at the top of that window that says
Performance. Now select File System. Then _ under settings _ change
the setting that says ``typical role of this computer'' to Network
Server. Only do that if you have 128 megs or more of memory. This
change will let your PC use the memory you added more efficiently.
</P>
<P>
   Video: Next to adding system memory, the least expensive way to
speed up an existing computer is to add a video card with a lot of
video memory. My own video card has 32 megabytes of RAM (you can
probably pick one up for $120 or so), and there are a lot of
computer enthusiasts who argue that this change offers more
potential for speed than a faster processor. Here's why. Almost
everything about Windows is graphics. Your processor spends a lot
of energy managing all those little dots of light on your screen. A
souped-up video card takes on a lot of that processing work,
freeing your processor and letting it work faster.
</P>
<P>
   Defrag: Hey, this one is free. There's a program that comes free
with Windows called Disk Defragmenter. You'll find it under the
Start button by selecting Accessories, then System Tools. Run this
program at least once a week, and it'll organize your hard disk so
that programs load faster and run faster. The good thing about
Defragmenter is that it also organizes the programs on your disk so
that the ones you use more often load the fastest. So the longer
you run it, the better it learns your own habits and speeds things
up based on them.
</P>
<P>
   Internet: If you have the fastest computer in the world, one of
those 1-gigahertz speed demons, and a slow connection, then when
you are on the Web you have a slow computer. A middle-of-the-road
computer with a fast connection will run circles around it. Since
so many of us camp out on the Web these days, consider getting DSL
service from the telephone company or a cable modem from your cable
TV provider.
</P>
<P>
   Once you've done all this, get some orange paint for the side of
your computer. It'll have earned its racing stripes.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
