 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 &HT;    Go ahead _ work through the storm
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _
</P>
<P>
   I've spent many a long day at the computer and endured a good
many thunderstorms; but it wasn't until recently when the two
events happened to coincide, fiercely, that the importance of
workstation surge protection came to the forefront of my mind. As
it turns out, there are roughly 17 trillion surge protectors on the
market, but I settled on the Recoton Home Office Surge Suppressor
with Phone Line Protection ($25; www.recoton.com) for its
reasonable price and versatility. The unit, which also acts as a
six-outlet power bar, protects one's system from a power surge of
up to 800 joules (bring it on, Zeus!). It works for both the power
supply and the phone/modem jack as well as the suppression of less
cataclysmic and more niggling electrical and radio frequency
transient noise. It's also complete with appropriate blinking
lights telling you just how fine a job it's doing. This particular
model comes with a $15,000 warranty on the product(s) it's
protecting, though only for five years.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
