 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
Combining paintings with digital images, executive creates new kind
of art &HT;    By Robert W. Gee
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Zvi Yaniv isn't the typical artist. He's not the
typical physicist either.
</P>
<P>
   He speaks in staccato bursts and gestures in broad strokes as he
makes bold statements about the future of technology. He envisions
a world with wall-sized video displays and spends his days in a
mostly windowless office perfecting a prototype that he hopes will
make his dream a reality.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's forget about putting a television in the wall. Let's
make the wall a television,'' says Yaniv, president and chief
operating officer of SI Diamond Technology, Inc.
</P>
<P>
   At his home in the hills of West Austin, Yaniv retreats in bare
feet to his screened porch amid a rock garden and reflecting pools,
and he flips on his PC to create a new kind of art. He calls it
two-dimensional kinetic art.
</P>
<P>
   He programs a series of digital images _ either photos, other
artists' work or his own _ onto a flat panel, liquid crystal
display and inserts the panel into a rectangular hole that he has
cut in a painting or lithograph, not his own.
</P>
<P>
   A chip drives the display, flashing a series of images often
with a theme independent from the original work giving new meaning
to the art. The digital panel typically measures about 10 inches by
10 inches and the painting 2 feet by 3 feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I combined art with the digital world,'' Yaniv says. ``It
gives the artist and the computer guy the power to create.''
</P>
<P>
   Yaniv, who is from Israel and moved to the United States in
1983, has created nine works of art, seven of which are on display
at the IC2 Institute in Austin. One is at Gallery Soco and the
other hangs in Yaniv's home.
</P>
<P>
   He holds a patent on the concept. His next work, he says, will
contain 3-D digital images and video display. He also will
collaborate with an Irish sculptor to incorporate the flat panel
displays into sculpture.
</P>
<P>
   He plans to launch a Web site that will allow users to make
virtual art by cutting a hole in a canvas and replacing it with
images of their own. He'd also like to use the concept for a
children's game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came up with an idea and I want people to use it and use
it,'' he says, smiling widely. ``It gives people the freedom of
expression.''
</P>
<P>
   Two of his favorite works hang on the third floor of IC2. One is
called ``Conflict.'' The digital window, inserted in the center of
an abstract artwork by Linda Dumond, flashes a series of 10 images
that connect seamlessly with the lines of the painting, showing one
color growing into another, then retreating. ``I call it 'Conflict'
because it's a conflict between the blue area and the area it
conquers,'' Yaniv says.
</P>
<P>
   Another favorite, ``Oasis,'' displays six frames of the sun
setting from The Oasis restaurant west of Austin. The digital
sunset becomes the focal point of the original work, in which a
pencil hovers near two broken orbs and two strawberries. A woman in
a black formal dress stands to the right of the sunset.
</P>
<P>
   Another Yaniv work, ``Faces of the World,'' on display at IC2,
will be shipped to an art gallery in Vancouver, Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Yaniv has long collected art, and despite his giddiness over his
first foray into creating his own works, he emphasizes that he does
not consider himself an artist _ rather a facilitator of art.
</P>
<P>
   He recently made a special wedding display for some friends by
putting 47 images of the couple in various stages of youth and
adulthood on a flat panel in the corner of a larger picture of the
two at their wedding.
</P>
<P>
   ``You open a new dimension to the two-dimensional picture,''
Yaniv says. ``The idea is very simple . . . to combine art and
technology and make it one.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
