<SLUG> BC-CPT-CYBERSCENE0516-COX </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 &HT;    Modern-day soothsayer: Weather sites predict future
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The weather this time of year can shift as often as a
four-cylinder car with an automatic transmission. And, in the
Midwest and South, there is the added danger of severe
thunderstorms and tornadoes.
</P>
<P>
   No list of weather-related Web sites should be attempted without
putting the Weather Channel right at the top of the list. The site
at www.weather.com gets more traffic than any other site devoted
entirely to the weather.
</P>
<P>
   One of the features of the site is the ability to customize the
start page so you'll immediately get the weather information you
need for the cities you care about most. You can also decide which
maps will appear and add other weather-related items such as travel
and airport information.
</P>
<P>
   But there's another contender that lacks some of the slickness
of the Weather Channel site yet offers some features that make it
unique on the Web. That's the Weather Underground site at
www.weatherunderground.com.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, you can display the information in an incredible
number of languages. Just pick from a list that includes the ones
you'd expect plus some you might not expect _ Bulgarian and Slovak,
for instance.
</P>
<P>
   There's more, including some things that you may not expect to
find on a weather site. For instance, click on the link labeled
astronomy and enter your ZIP code. You'll be able to see where the
stars and the planets will appear in the night sky in your part of
the country.
</P>
<P>
   The online edition of the USA Today newspaper also has an
excellent section devoted to the weather. Just go to
www.usatoday.com/weather/wfront.htm.
</P>
<P>
   While you're there, you may want to indulge in one of mankind's
favorite pastimes, talking about the weather. Just click on the
link called Talk Weather and complain to your heart's content. You
can also ask questions or even make your own predictions.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to the official version of the weather _ and also
the place where most weather gathering organizations get primary
data _ there's only one choice: The National Weather Service.
You'll find that home page at www.nws.noaa.gov.
</P>
<P>
   Once there, you'll find a staggering amount of information. For
instance, you can click on the link called Web sites and find the
National Weather Service office for your area. In my case that's
the Atlanta office, which is really located in Peachtree City.
</P>
<P>
   You'll find that site at www.srh.noaa.gov/FFC.
</P>
<P>
   The site offers weather data rolled almost any way you'd like,
including links for short-term forecasts, long-term outlooks,
agricultural weather, and weather watches and warnings. You'll also
be able to learn the radio frequency for the Weather Service's
weather warning radio broadcasts for this area.
</P>
<P>
   People in my state also will enjoy a visit to the Georgia
Weather _ Automated Environmental Monitoring Network Page at
www.griffin.peachnet.edu/bae.
</P>
<P>
   This service was established in 1991 by the College of
Agriculture and Environmental Sciences of the University of
Georgia. Mostly the weather information seems to be intended for
farmers.
</P>
<P>
   The network has weather stations scattered across the state
where air temperature, relative humidity, rainfall, solar
radiation, wind speed, wind direction and soil temperature at
various depths are monitored literally every second.
</P>
<P>
   Then the information gathered at the stations is dumped into a
master computer every 15 minutes. That compilation is used to
provide information to the Web site and researchers.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-05-15-00 1122EDT &QL;
</P>
