<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-COMPUTER-HELPLINE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH-SPEED HOOKUP COULD LET YOU DOWNLOAD NAPSTER BETTER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By DWIGHT SILVERMAN   
 c.2000 Houston Chronicle   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Question: Your columns about Napster were interesting. In fact,
they introduced me to a new world of songs. My problem is I have
been able to download only one song. All the others resulted in
``corrupt files.'' Do you know what I might be doing wrong? I have
tons of available space, a 56K modem, an almost new computer and a
fabulous CD writer.
</P>
<P>
   Answer: First remember that Napster is beta software _ it's
still in the development stage, and it has bugs. However, that may
or may not be your problem.
</P>
<P>
   When you search for a song and get a list of possible files to
download, Napster presents you with a lot of information about each
file. It shows you the size of the file, the bit rate of the file,
the frequency at which it was recorded, the speed of the file
owner's connection and the ping between your machine and the file
owner's computer. The ping reflects the speed of the Internet
connection.
</P>
<P>
   Pay particular attention to the size of the file. The size is
tied to the bit rate, which is an indication of the song's sound
quality. A higher bit rate means better sound quality, but also a
larger file size.
</P>
<P>
   If you see several copies of the same song listed, the file size
should be the same for all copies of a given bit rate.
</P>
<P>
   Let's say you're looking for a particular song. You find four
copies, and they all have a bit rate of 128. They should all be
roughly the same size. If you see one that is much smaller or
larger, stay away from it _ it likely is corrupt, incomplete or
mislabeled.
</P>
<P>
   Be aware that some Napster users with very fast connections have
a tendency to cut off standard modem users because it takes so long
for the slower users to download a file using Napster. The cutoffs
result in corrupt or incomplete files.
</P>
<P>
   Napster really is a broadband application, much more suited to a
very fast connection. You may want to make the move to a DSL or
cable-modem connection, if either are available in your area.
</P>
<P>
   Q: This may seem like a dumb (newbie) question but inquiring
minds want to know: Can you tell me what WINIPCFG is and what it
does? A: Whenever a computer connects to a network that uses TCP/IP
_ the protocol or ``language'' of the Internet _ it either must
have or be given a numeric address, called an IP address. The
WINIPCFG program that comes with Windows is a way to identify your
address, and manage it.
</P>
<P>
   Most Internet service providers assign you an IP address when
you dial in, and you are likely to get a different address each
time you connect.
</P>
<P>
   Cable-modem and DSL connections for home users also do this,
though the IP address usually stays the same over long periods of
time.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, when your Net connection has come to a standstill,
WINIPCFG may fix your problem. Go to Start, Run, type WINIPCFG and
hit the Enter key. The program will show you a drop-down box with
various connections methods _ your modem's PPP adapter for dialup
and/or your Ethernet card for faster connections. Choose the one
you want to work with.
</P>
<P>
   If your connection seems stuck, try clicking the Release, then
Renew button. This will drop your current IP address and ask your
provider for a new one. Disconnecting and redialing does the same
thing (or rebooting your machine, if you have cable or DSL), but
using WINIPCFG is faster.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-05-16-00 1341EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
