<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 15:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7825 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-CPT-VIDEO-GAMES0515-C     05-17 1232
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-VIDEO-GAMES0515-COX </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 &HT;    High technology, urge to converge melding media
 &HT;    By Lyle V. Harris
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Imagine going online to play a video game spinoff
of your favorite movie that's based on a hit TV series while
listening to the show's soundtrack on a file downloaded to an MP3
player.
</P>
<P>
   No need to just imagine. It's already happening.
</P>
<P>
   This topsy-turvy phenomenon called ``convergence'' is blurring _
even erasing _ the lines that once separated mainstream modes of
entertainment such as television, movies and recorded music from
newer media such as DVDs, video games and the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   For a generation of tech-savvy consumers who grew up with a TV
remote control in one hand and a computer mouse in the other,
convergence could make it easier to seamlessly mix-and-match
different types of entertainment sources to suit their individual
tastes.
</P>
<P>
   Although it's still in its infancy, the urge to converge was in
full swing as 55,000 conventioneers from 60 countries gathered at
the Los Angeles Convention Center for the annual Electronic
Entertainment Expo. Better known as E3, this massive, 6-year-old
trade show left Atlanta in 1998 and has returned to the city
regarded as the world capital of pop culture.
</P>
<P>
   Convergence was the big buzz at this year's show, where industry
observers were predicting that it will revolutionize mass consumer
entertainment. But beyond the high-tech hypebole, what does
convergence look like?
</P>
<P>
   On one side of the sprawling exhibit floor, several Hollywood
movie studios previewed video games that are being tied to
hoped-for holiday blockbusters such as ``The Grinch,'' ``X-Men''
and ``Dinosaur.''
</P>
<P>
   At another booth, an actress dressed like Lara Croft, the
impossibly buxom heroine of the ``Tomb Raider'' video game, was
pointing a pair of authentic-looking guns at a mostly male audience
that seemed to be admiring more than her sidearms.
</P>
<P>
   The Croft clone was pulling double duty by advertising the
newest version of the popular fantasy-adventure game and also
promoting an upcoming movie of the same name that will star Oscar
winner Angelina Jolie.
</P>
<P>
   Convergence also seems to be taking root in book publishing,
albeit more slowly. Two video games based on cloak-and-dagger
novels by noted spy author Tom Clancy were on display. Animorphs, a
popular series of children's books, is already on TV and now has a
companion video game.
</P>
<P>
   Also attending E3 were television's so-cute-it-hurts Olsen
twins, Mary-Kate and Ashley, who signed autographs to promote their
new video game. Nearby, hard-core rapper Ice-T did the same for
fans interested in ``Sanity,'' a soon-to-be released video game
that will feature his voice and music.
</P>
<P>
   ``These games aren't just for kids,'' Ice-T said. ``They're not
even like games anymore. It's like you're making a movie even as
you're playing along with the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Bryan Davies, a spokesman for Eidos Interactive, developer of
the Tomb Raider game, agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's getting to the point where it's harder to tell the
difference between games and TV and other forms of entertainment,''
Davies said. ``Movies have the look and sound of a video game, and
the games are more like little movies, with drawn-out story lines
and good characters.''
</P>
<P>
   Technology has played a key role in making the promise of
convergence a reality. Just a few years ago, watching a DVD movie
or copying a digital music file was an expensive and slow process.
But as the cost of high-tech hardware has fallen, the equipment has
become more powerful and sophisticated. Faster modems and
lightning-quick broadband connections have also made it possible to
send CD-quality sound and high-resolution images over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The convergence craze has also caught the attention of prominent
musical artists David Bowie, Trent Reznor of Nine Inch Nails,
composer Danny Elfman and Grammy-winning hip-hopper Coolio. All
have scored, or are workig on, video game soundtracks.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Luden, president of the Guitammer Company of Ohio, is no
musician. But he's excited about the prospects of creating new
types of sounds for the coming convergence.
</P>
<P>
   Luden's company has developed a device that recreates the
thundering bass that moviegoers are accustomed to at their local
multiplex in the comfort of the average living room. It's called
``The Buttkicker.''
</P>
<P>
   The $700 device is about the size of a football and can be
placed under the foundation or crawl space of a house. A smaller
version, for $149, fits underneath a sofa or easy chair.
</P>
<P>
   When connected to a home theater system, it delivers a powerful
``infrasonic'' rumble that vibrates through the listener's body,
adding another dimension to games, movies, and compact discs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like watching fireworks on the Fourth of July,'' Luden
says. ``You don't just see them; you hear them and you feel them,
right here in your chest. We want to re-create that sense of being
right there.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Luden, most of the E3 exhibitors were looking at ways to
deal with convergence while boosting their company's bottom line.
</P>
<P>
   Disney plans to roll out more than 16 video games this year
based on its vast library of animated movies, including older
releases such as ``101 Dalmatians'' and relatively new ones like
``Toy Story.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're agnostics when it comes to convergence,'' said Leslie
Oren, a spokeswoman for Disney Interactive. ``Whether it's on the
Internet, on video or on a game, we want consumers to be able to
take the product home, or wherever they are, and extend their
entertainment experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox Interactive is also ramping up for the convergence
sweepstakes. It's releasing video games based on ``Planet of the
Apes,'' the long-running TV show ``The Simpsons'' and the upcoming
animated sci-fi flick ``Titan A.E.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Fox has no plans to release an online version of its
disastrous ``Who Wants To Marry a Multimillionaire'' special, the
company unveiled a new video game based on a more successful but
still cheesy Fox reality show, ``World's Scariest Police Chases.''
</P>
<P>
   Angela Edwards Emery, a Fox spokeswoman, explained that these
new games take advantage of built-in familiarity that audiences
have with Fox's branded network broadcasts.
</P>
<P>
   In the ``World's Scariest'' game, players pursue a fleeing
``perp'' as the action is described by an unseen narrator. As the
chase unfolds, the distinctive Fox News logo is displayed on a
corner of the screen _ just like on television.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to re-invent the wheel with consumers,'' Emery
said. ``We don't have to. We have a brand they identify with and
recognize, and we just need to build on that.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone at E3, however, was convinced that convergence is
such a good idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the year of the licensee; everything has to have some
celebrity endorsement or crossover appeal,'' said Rick Mears, an
editor with Gamefan, an online magazine devoted to video games.
``We've found that when content producers depend on some brand
name, it dilutes the product. They're just rehashing old stuff.
After a while they don't care if the game or the movie is any good,
just as long as it makes money.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-05-14-00 2017EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
