<SLUG> BC-CPT-COMPUTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEWARE OF THINGS THAT COME BY MAIL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By DWIGHT SILVERMAN   
 c.2000 Houston Chronicle   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Most of the computing world has recovered from the attack of the
Love Letter virus. Antivirus software has been updated, users have
been warned about its characteristics _ and those of copycat
versions _ and the furor has subsided.
</P>
<P>
   But I have bad news for you, boys and girls. It will happen
again. And again. And then again.
</P>
<P>
   That is, unless, two major changes are made. One involves your
behavior; the other involves Microsoft's.
</P>
<P>
   Viruses that bedevil computers are very much like sexually
transmitted diseases in the 3-D world _ they are spread by
conscious action. If you don't engage in the behavior that spreads
them, you won't get the virus.
</P>
<P>
   It's just that simple.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of VBS.LoveLetter.A and its variants, the behavior
that caused the virus to spread like wildfire last week was the
casual way computer users regard files attached to e-mail. Many
people think nothing of launching an attachment sent to them, even
if they don't know the person who sent it.
</P>
<P>
   With Love Letter, users also were enticed by some clever social
engineering. Like the Melissa virus before it, this nasty bug was
spread by hijacking the address book from Microsoft's popular
Outlook e-mail program. Someone receiving the virus might recognize
the sender's name as someone to be trusted, and would be more
willing to open the attachment.
</P>
<P>
   And here's the problem: Internet and corporate network users too
often send attachments, particularly Microsoft Word documents,
without getting permission. To me, this is like giving someone a
puppy for Christmas without first asking whether the receiver is
ready for the responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   Attached files that can run a program on your computer are
dangerous _ period. Word documents are capable of running macros, a
form of automated routine. In a sense, a Word document is basically
a type of small computer program. As evidenced by Melissa, which
was a Word macro virus, it's a powerful capability that can be
easily misused.
</P>
<P>
   Most people know better than to run program files they receive
as an attachment, so why should a Word document be any different?
</P>
<P>
   In 99 percent of all cases, you don't need a fancy, formatted
word processing document to get your information across. Plain text
is always better for e-mail, anyway, because anyone can read it,
regardless of their computer, word processor or bandwidth.
</P>
<P>
   In the business world, however, Word documents are tossed across
the Net with abandon. For example, I get several a day as press
releases from public relations people _ and yes, I have gotten
viruses from press releases! I simply don't accept Word documents
anymore unless I arrange for them in advance, and I would urge
others in the business world to do the same.
</P>
<P>
   The second problem has to do with how easy it is for automated
programs, such as macros or scripts, to make major and potentially
disastrous changes to Windows' crucial files.
</P>
<P>
   The Love Letter virus uses Microsoft's Visual Basic Script. The
filename of the attachment is LOVE-LETTER-FOR-YOU.TXT.vbs. The VBS
extension indicates it is a script file _ something the average
user doesn't recognize.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft includes this script capability in some versions of
Windows and in its Office productivity suite to automate some
processes. But while powerful, this feature is also pretty dumb; it
lets a program do almost anything.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Love Letter does the following, thanks to Visual
Basic Script:
</P>
<P>
   _ Changes the default start-up page for the Internet Explorer by
making changes in the Windows Registry, the master configuration
database. The new page then downloads an executable that collects
passwords off the hard drive and sends them to an e-mail address.
</P>
<P>
   _ Installs itself as a series of files in the windows and
windowssystem folders, two key repositories for crucial system
files.
</P>
<P>
   _ Makes further changes to the Registry to ensure that the virus
launches each time the computer is booted.
</P>
<P>
   _ Reads the Microsoft Outlook address book and sends a copy of
itself to everyone listed there.
</P>
<P>
   The notion that an operating system allows this much destructive
activity to occur without at least warning that major changes are
being made is outrageous, and Microsoft is to blame here.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the company is responding to a market that wants the
ability to automate routine tasks. And it would be fairly
irritating if users had to approve every change made to the
operating system, such as during a software installation.
</P>
<P>
   But as Love Letter shows, Windows _ particularly the Windows
95/98 family _ is simply too trusting. While I'm not sure that I'd
want Windows to be as locked down as Unix, users should at least
have a choice as part of its security features of being alerted
when these kinds of changes are about to be made.
</P>
<P>
   Until that changes, you can expect more attacks _ and probably
even more vicious ones _ from across the Net.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-05-16-00 1340EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
