<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 15:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7840 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-JUDGE-ROADBLOCK-HNS &LR;      05-17 1031
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JUDGE-ROADBLOCK-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     DEMOCRATS DECRY EFFORT TO BAR HISPANIC LAWYER FROM APPELLATE
BENCH 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By PEGGY FIKAC  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EL PASO, Texas _ It's an American success story on the verge of
getting even better until, some say, it ran into the reality of
American politics.
</P>
<P>
   The story is classic: The Mexico-born son of immigrant parents
graduates from Harvard, goes home to El Paso, forges a successful
legal career and makes this far West Texas border city proud when
the president nominates him to a seat on the 5th U.S. Circuit Court
of Appeals.
</P>
<P>
   There, the story of Enrique Moreno hits a roadblock. Some blame
the twist in the plot on the politics of this presidential election
year, in which Republican Gov. George W. Bush is primed to face
Democratic Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Moreno's nomination to the New Orleans-based appeals court, made
in September 1999 by President Clinton, has been blocked by the
Republican senators from Texas, Phil Gramm and Kay Bailey
Hutchison. Judicial nominations are subject to Senate approval.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas senators said a nonpartisan committee of lawyers that
reviews prospective judges for them found that Moreno, 44, was not
experienced enough ``to be fully engaged and effective on a court
one notch below the United States Supreme Court.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreno, a trial lawyer whose practice includes employment, civil
rights and personal injury cases, has practiced law 19 years. He
has no experience as a judge.
</P>
<P>
   However, Moreno's supporters say the complaint about his
qualifications is patently untrue.
</P>
<P>
   They cited his nearly two decades in private law practice and
support from Republicans as well as Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   They noted his backing from legal, business and law enforcement
entities and high ratings from groups including the American Bar
Association, whose federal judicial committee gave him its top mark
of ``well-qualified.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The implication from Senator Gramm and Senator Hutchison's
letter is that Enrique is not qualified. That's the meanest,
ugliest thing that you could say about Enrique, because it's
clearly not true,'' said El Paso District Attorney Jaime Esparza, a
Democrat. ``It's just pure politics.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreno's supporters generally contend the GOP senators want to
hold open the judicial seat in the hope that Bush will win the
presidency and can choose his own nominee. The court hears cases
from Texas, Louisiana and Mississippi.
</P>
<P>
   ``This decision was clearly a partisan decision without any
regard at all to El Paso as ... a community that needs
representation on the 5th Circuit,'' said El Paso Assistant County
Attorney Annabell Perez, president of the local Mexican-American
Bar Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not important enough to jeopardize any kind of strategy
or plan that the senators may have had for the governor,'' said
Perez, who describes herself as a Democrat ``for the most part.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreno would have been the first judge on the court from El
Paso, his supporters said. That meant a lot to residents of this
city, who can feel geographically isolated, ignored and taken for
granted, they said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This entire episode once again shows El Paso that we do not
have the clout on either a state or national level that other
cities in the state have,'' said 327th District Court Judge Philip
R. Martinez, a Democrat who graduated one year behind Moreno at
Harvard Law School.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez added, however, ``What the senators have done isn't as
much a disservice to El Paso as it is a disservice to the nation.
... He was certainly well-qualified to play a larger role on a
bigger stage.''
</P>
<P>
   Gramm spokesman Larry Neal said the senators' letter speaks for
itself.
</P>
<P>
   While suggesting Moreno lacks sufficient experience, it also
notes his ``enviable personal success story'' and doesn't rule out
a future judicial nomination. In addition, it lists those who have
successfully been through the process, including those with
Hispanic surnames.
</P>
<P>
   ``This (lawyers' committee) process has approved 17 Clinton
judges, while only two have been turned down. But it was late in
the term and the committee was not comfortable with an appellate
court appointment for a person who has no judicial experience and
no written record,'' said Hutchison spokeswoman Lisette Mondello.
</P>
<P>
   Moreno's defenders point out that half of the 14 judges on the
5th Circuit Court are listed as having no judicial experience,
including six nominated by Republican presidents.
</P>
<P>
   There are three vacancies on the 17-slot court, which has a
heavy workload.
</P>
<P>
   The 5th Circuit's chief judge, Carolyn Dineen King, last year
declared a judicial emergency to clear the way for the court to
more extensively use visiting judges.
</P>
<P>
   Noting ``an explosion'' of cases, particularly drug cases, along
the U.S.-Mexico border, Martinez said, ``It escapes me to
understand how ... all those factors have not allowed this process
to move at any faster pace.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Asked recently whether he thought the senators opposed Moreno
because he is Hispanic, Clinton said, ``That, or they just don't
want to confirm any judges unless they are right-wing ideologues.''
</P>
<P>
   The uproar over the block shows no sign of letting up, with
elected officials touting Moreno's credentials and the Mexican
American Legal Defense and Educational Fund describing itself as
``appalled by the continuing efforts by some in Congress to
stonewall Latino nominees from reaching high-ranking judicial
positions.''
</P>
<P>
   The controversy has reached into the presidential race, with
Gore and others saying Bush should use his influence to help
Moreno's case. Bush frequently touts his support from Hispanics and
particularly from El Paso residents.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Constitution gives that authority and responsibility to
the United States Senate,'' said Bush spokesman Scott McClellan.
``Governor Bush has a proven record of appointing judges from all
walks of life in Texas, and he will do the same as president.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Peggy Fikac can be reached by e-mail at
pfikac(at)express-news.net)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
