<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 15:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7891 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-GARDEN-Q&AMP;A-NYT &LR;      05-17 0673
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-Q&AMP;A-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GARDENING QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
   By LESLIE LAND    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Moving Wild Canada Columbine
</P>
<P>
   Q. Each day on the way to work I drive past a hillside that has
many clumps of beautiful bright red and yellow flowers growing
among the rocks. They look like little rocket ships on tall stems.
What are they? Will they survive transplanting? I would like to put
some by the edge of my front walk.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. The wildflowers brightening your commute are Canada
columbines, Aquilegia canadensis. This delicate-looking but very
tough species, ancestor of many garden hybrids, is widely
distributed, growing in open woodlands and along roadsides from
eastern Canada to Florida and New Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, at least, they are not endangered; but that
doesn't mean it's all right to blithely start kidnapping them. Not
only does the removal of plants threaten the parent colony and set
you on the path to sin, it's also a bad idea from the point of view
of pure survival. Plants dug up from the wild often suffer root
damage, and even when roots are preserved intact, the transition to
different soils and different light levels puts a lot of strain on
the plants. Container-grown (or adapted) plants are expressly
created to deal with moving and usually do better at it.
</P>
<P>
   From the columbine's point of view, it would be best if your
front walk were in light shade, but they will tolerate full sun if
it isn't baking hot, and they are adaptable to a wide range of
soils as long as those soils are well-drained.
</P>
<P>
   Canada columbine's flowers bloom only in spring, and the
fernlike blue green foliage is too delicate to attract the casual
browser's eye, so this plant is seldom sold in garden centers, but
it is widely available by mail order. Sources include Prairie
Nursery, P.O. Box 306 Westfield, Wis. 53964, Catalog free at (800)
476-9453. Extensive guide to and discussion of native plants at
www.prairienursery.com.; We-Du Nurseries, Route 5, Box 724, Marion,
N.C. 28752, Catalog, $2 at (828) 738-8300 or www.we-du.com.
</P>
<P>
   If You Want to Save a Yew
</P>
<P>
   Q. I have a yew about five feet wide next to the deck of my
swimming pool. It is blocking part of the deck so we cannot pass
by. Can this be trimmed from the front? It looks as if all I will
have is the inside branches left, a rather ugly sight. But if I can
do it, when is the best time?  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. It sounds as if you may secretly hope there is nothing to be
done, so before we get to the pruning part, let me encourage you to
be brave and get rid of the thing. Though it goes against a
gardener's grain to kill a healthy shrub, why keep one where you
can look forward to two or three years of bare spots followed by a
lifelong commitment to time-consuming maintenance?
</P>
<P>
   If you are determined to keep it, there are two alternatives.
The yew can be trimmed from the front, but it will be ugly, and not
just while the inside branches are putting on new growth. No matter
how green it gets, the shrub will always look like it has been
sliced in half.
</P>
<P>
   A more attractive alternative is to reshape the whole plant. Cut
back a little bit (6 to 9 inches) all around each year, pruning
individual branches to slightly different lengths rather than
shearing along the face. It will take longer to prune than to
shear, but the result will be a tall, narrow shrub that's vaguely
columnar without looking as though it belongs in a cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   No matter what shape you choose, the best time to start cutting
is early spring, before the plant puts out new growth. This gives
you maximum green to cover the exposed bare spots and gives the
plant maximum time to harden up before winter. But it's not too
late; get going right now and you will still have quite a bit of
new yew this year.
</P>
<P>
   Address questions to Garden Q&AMP;A, The New York Times, 229 West
43rd Street, New York 10036, or by e-mail to
gardening(at)nytimes.com. Those of general interest will be
published. Unpublished questions cannot be answered individually.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-17-00 1553EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000517.0184 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 15:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7892 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-NYT &LR;      05-17 0843
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOU HAVE THE CARPET, NOW THE PAD 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can make purchase
one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 &HT;     
 By EDWARD R. LIPINSKI    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A good carpet should never rest directly on the floor but on a
pad. The pad can add extra cushioning to the carpet and provide a
softer walking surface. In addition, the pad insulates the carpet
from the hard floor and thus prevents the carpet fibers from being
crushed whenever someone walks on it. This can add to the life of
the carpet.
</P>
<P>
   Carpet pads can be divided into two broad categories: attached
and unattached. The attached pad is bonded to the back of the
carpet at the factory. It is usually made of an inexpensive foam
material that quickly loses its resiliency. It is cheap and easy to
install, but it deteriorates in a short time.
</P>
<P>
   It is far better to invest in an unattached pad. Unattached pads
are available in a variety of materials, thicknesses and prices, so
you can choose the best product for your carpet. Pads are available
in either natural or artificial (synthetic) materials.
</P>
<P>
   The natural materials include hair, jute, cotton and rubber.
Hair pads are made from horsehair. They are quite durable, but they
are also expensive, so most natural fiber pads are a combination of
hair, jute and possibly cotton. Unfortunately, these amalgams
weaken the pad, causing it to break down over time. In an effort to
prevent deterioration, manufacturers coat both sides of the pad
with a layer of latex.
</P>
<P>
   Natural fiber pads tend to be firm, and they do not create a
cushioned effect the way the more popular artificial sponge pads
do. Sometimes, however, this can be an advantage, especially with
woven carpets. Many woven carpets have stiff backs that cannot be
fully stretched during installation. If these carpets are placed
over a soft pad, they will bend, stretch and wrinkle.
</P>
<P>
   Rubber pads are a good compromise between the firm fiber pads
and soft ones of synthetic materials. They are made in a firm
sponge composition or in a softer ``waffle'' design. Sponge rubber
pads are available in quarter-inch- and three-eighths-inch
thicknesses. Waffle pads are thicker, a half inch or more, but much
of that thickness consists of air pockets.
</P>
<P>
   All rubber pads have some ingredients that affect their quality
and durability. One common element is clay. The clay gives the
rubber more body, but as it dries out over time, the pad will
deteriorate. Unfortunately, there is no way to tell how much clay
is in any pad. The best the consumer can hope for is a warranty
from the dealer stating that the pad will last as long as the
carpet.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, natural pads are rated according to the number of
ounces per cubic yard they weigh. A good quality fiber pad should
weigh about 40 ounces, a sponge rubber pad about 64 ounces and a
rubber waffle pad around 80 ounces.
</P>
<P>
   Artificial pads are made from polyurethane foam and are less
expensive than natural pads. Artificial pads are called either
prime or rebonded, depending on the composition of the polyurethane
in them. Prime pads are made with urethane of one consistency in
varying thicknesses from one-quarter to three-quarters of an inch.
Thickness is not as important, however, as density. Dense pads tend
to be firmer and more durable than an open pad.
</P>
<P>
   Rebonded pads are made of polyurethane chunks that have been
bonded into a single sheet. These pads are heavier, denser and more
durable than prime pads. Rebonded polyurethane pads are the most
common type of residential carpet pad.
</P>
<P>
   While it is tempting to install an extra-thick artificial pad
under a carpet to give it a luxurious feel, this can have some
drawbacks. The carpet may flex too much, and if it is not well
made, the backing and seams may crack. A pad that is too thin, on
the other hand, may not provide enough cushioning and cause the
carpet to wear prematurely. It is best then to choose a pad
three-quarters of an inch a a half-inch thick with a density of six
pounds per cubic foot.
</P>
<P>
   Even the best carpet will bubble or wrinkle if it is not
installed properly. Wall-to-wall carpet should be stretched with
power stretchers. If the carpet is not stretched, it will
eventually expand on its own and create an unsightly surface that
will wear quickly and become a tripping hazard.
</P>
<P>
   The stretched carpet should be secured with tack strips that are
nailed in place one-half inch away from the baseboard around the
perimeter of the room. The gap between the tack strip and the
baseboard allows clearance to tuck the edges of carpet down and
hide any irregularities.
</P>
<P>
   Not all carpets are wide enough to cover a large room. Often,
sections have to be joined with seam tape. All seams should be
positioned in low-traffic areas away from direct sunlight. It is
important that the pile in both sections of the carpet run the same
way or the seam will be obvious. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
