<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 15:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7893 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-COMPUTER-COLUMN-N     05-17 1271
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-COMPUTER-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TO PREPARE FOR WORST, BACK UP 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 By PETER H. LEWIS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Computers are treacherous. Thanks to the wonders of modern
technology, they make it easier than ever before to lose vast
amounts of important information in a hurry. Anyone can misplace a
set of car keys, but only a computer can lose years' worth of
banking and investment records, family photos, music files, a
nearly finished novel and tomorrow's important business
presentation instantly and irretrievably.
</P>
<P>
   But disasters can be minimized, if not avoided entirely, with a
regular backup program. As recounted here last week, a successful
data backup strategy for personal computers has to be reasonably
easy, regular, remote and reliable.
</P>
<P>
   There are three major categories of backup devices: magnetic,
optical and online. I've tried several examples of each, ranging
from the most basic floppy disk system to the newest online storage
services. Each has advantages and disadvantages. There is no single
solution that is perfect for everyone.
</P>
<P>
   If you are shopping for a new PC, adding a magnetic Zip drive or
an optical drive (either CD-R or CD-RW) is highly recommended. If
you are one of the estimated two million lucky people who have a
high-speed Internet connection through a cable modem or DSL, an
online storage service may be the answer.
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, PC owners may choose to use some combination of
techniques, sort of a belt-and-suspenders approach. Others may
simply choose the easiest or cheapest solution.
</P>
<P>
   Personal psychology affects the decision. For example, I avoid
almost any type of backup solution that involves data compression,
even though compression speeds the backup process by squeezing more
files onto fewer disks.
</P>
<P>
   My aversion stems from two very bad experiences in trying to
restore compressed files after a hard disk failure. I know it is
irrational, just like the geezers who go to the bank and demand to
see and count their money because they don't trust the idea of
their life savings existing only as a green glow on a computer
screen. I like to see my backup files displayed as exact copies of
the original files, instead of the hieroglyphics that compressed
files often resemble. I am happiest when I can back up a file,
click on it and test it immediately, just to reassure myself that
it works.
</P>
<P>
   For the same reason, tape drives give me the willies. Yes,
magnetic tape is fast and cheap and reliable, and many corporations
rely on it for their most important archiving. But it does not
offer the instant gratification of other options, and testing a
tape backup is a hassle. For those reasons I avoid it. With my
biases now disclosed, let's look at the remaining options.
</P>
<P>
   Magnetic Backup
</P>
<P>
   Magnetic systems for desktop PCs include the humble floppy disk
and high-capacity disks like Iomega's Zip and Imation's SuperDisk.
There are other variations, but Zips and SuperDisks are the most
common.
</P>
<P>
   In the easy and cheap category, the floppy disk is king. Most
PC's still come with a floppy drive as standard equipment. A floppy
disk formatted for Windows holds 1.44 megabytes of data, good for
impromptu backups of small files but grossly inadequate for today's
multigigabyte hard drives and multimegabyte digital photo and music
files. Although it may seem like the floppy is flopping toward
extinction _ Apple computers did away with the floppy drive some
time ago _ it still serves a limited role for backups and file
transfers.
</P>
<P>
   Several years ago I got a computer with a built-in Iomega Zip
drive. Each Zip disk (about $9) holds about 100 megabytes of data,
the equivalent of 69 floppies, making it handy for backing up
entire folders full of files. An external Zip drive costs about
$100.
</P>
<P>
   Recently I bought an external 250-MB USB Zip drive (about $200;
disks about $18 each), which is backward-compatible with older
100-MB disks. The USB connection allows me to move the drive, and
the data, easily from one USB-equipped computer to another.
</P>
<P>
   On my iMac, however, I use an Imation SuperDisk drive (about
$120). Unlike the Zip drive, the SuperDisk drive can read and write
both conventional 3.5-inch floppy disks and 120-MB SuperDisks
(about $10 each, less if bought in bulk).
</P>
<P>
   The Zip is more common, which is an important consideration if
you need to rush to Kinko's in the middle of the night to retrieve
a file. But the SuperDisk is not exactly rare. Several companies
offer SuperDisks in their laptop computers.
</P>
<P>
   Optical Disks
</P>
<P>
   CD-RW (rewritable) optical drives are increasingly popular,
especially among people who store a lot of music files and digital
photos. The storage capacity of a CD is 650 MB, and blank discs are
cheap, about $2 or less in most computer stores.
</P>
<P>
   CD's have some modest drawbacks, especially in ease of use.
Unlike copying to Zips or SuperDisks, which function a lot like
floppy disks, copying files to a recordable CD typically requires a
bit of study and practice.
</P>
<P>
   A CD-RW drive (around $275) can create both CD-R and CD-RW
discs, while a CD-R drive can make only CD-R discs. Get the CD-RW
for the most flexibility. In general, a CD-R disc is best for
making audio CD's and permanent archives of other types of files.
Almost any CD or DVD drive can read CD-R discs, while CD-RW discs
are more finicky. On the other hand, CD-RW discs are handy for
backing up files that change frequently, because files can be
erased and overwritten.
</P>
<P>
   Online Storage
</P>
<P>
   The new champion of easy and cheap backup is online storage.
There are several free services on the Internet that allow users to
park copies of their important files on secure network server
computers. These personal storage areas, which are password
protected, are accessible from any computer that has a browser and
access to the World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   My favorite is X:drive (www.xdrive.com), which offers new users
25 MB of free space. More space, up to 100 MB, is awarded in 5-MB
or 10-MB increments for enticing friends to sign up for the service
or for visiting the site frequently. Extra space can also be
purchased for a monthly fee ranging from $4.95 a month for 25 MB to
$19.95 a month for a gigabyte of storage.
</P>
<P>
   There are two ways to use the service. One is to log on through
a browser (Netscape or Microsoft) and download or upload files one
at a time. The other, limited to Windows 95 and 98 users, involves
downloading a simple application from the X:drive site.
</P>
<P>
   Once the application is installed, the X:drive shows up on the
desktop and in the Windows Explorer file tree just as if it were a
local drive, like the A or C drive. It is then easy to drag and
drop files and folders between the local hard disk and the remote
X:drive.
</P>
<P>
   Before leaving on a trip, I copy my most important files into a
private folder on the X drive. I can then retrieve them, or simply
use them on line, from any Web-connected computer in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Apple offers a similar service called iDisk, exclusively for
Macintosh computers. But Apple's service is limited to a paltry 20
MB.
</P>
<P>
   There are drawbacks. Working with the X:drive files can be
sluggish, especially over dial-up modem connections, and 25 MB is
not a lot of space.
</P>
<P>
   There are also nagging concerns about the free online storage
services. I'm not sure I'd trust my long-term archiving to a
start-up. I have more trust in the Zips and the CD's that I burn
myself and can hold in my hands. Also, as recent events have shown,
no password-protected system is entirely secure from a clever and
determined hacker.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
