<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 15:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7895 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-ETHICS-WORKPLACE-NYT &LR;      05-17 1044
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ETHICS-WORKPLACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAUGHT BETWEEN PAYDAY AND PRINCIPLE 
</HEADLINE>
   By EVE TAHMINCIOGLU    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   When she was a securities broker in Florida for NationsBank
Corp. in the early 1990s, Catherine Hovis knew that the elderly
clients she was selling mutual funds to did not have the financial
or emotional means to take on risky investments. One couple, both
in their 70s, were living on Social Security and wanted something
as safe as a certificate of deposit but with a better return _
maybe 7 percent to 8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Hovis convinced the couple that the bank's mutual funds were
safe and, at her bosses' urging, reassured them they had made a
smart investment even after the value of the funds declined.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Hovis, 43, acknowledges that she had begun to suspect the
mutual funds were not as solid as bank management had led her to
believe. Yet, she continued to sell them to risk-averse elderly
clients because, she says, she was doing what her bosses told her
to do. She was also motivated by her supervisor's praise, a
six-figure salary, financial bonuses and a free trip to the Cayman
Islands, becoming one of the top 25 sellers of the funds for
NationsBank, now part of Bank of America.
</P>
<P>
   ``Money makes people do very strange things,'' Hovis said. ``As
a single mother, I was willing to do what I had to do.'' Besides,
she added: ``I'm human. I wanted to be a team player.''
</P>
<P>
   The practice of pressuring the elderly to buy mutual funds,
which Hovis said was pervasive throughout the bank, led to a $29
million class-action settlement by NationsBank in 1997 with people
who had been sold the funds. Despite the settlement, the bank
vigorously denied the assertions in the suit. Last week, bank
officials declined to comment on Hovis' assertions.
</P>
<P>
   As she describes it, her moral plight was unusually stark. But
the basic choice she faced between her paycheck and her principles
is one that most workers eventually encounter. And with hordes of
people now fixated on stock market riches and million-dollar game
shows, ethicists warn that ordinary Americans are having an even
harder time holding on to their moral bearings.
</P>
<P>
   The transgressions that tempt them can be as seemingly trivial
as fudging an expense report and as troubling as lying to law
enforcement officials to protect their boss. Sometimes, they make
headlines, as happened this year when Christopher Davidge, a former
chief executive of the Christie's auction house, was said to have
told government investigators that Sir Anthony Tennant, a former
chairman, had ordered him to carry out a price-fixing scheme.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people just go along with what other people do and
respond to the expectations of those around them,'' said David
Vogel, an ethics professor at the Haas School of Business at the
University of California at Berkeley. ``This encourages and permits
ethically dubious behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   Paradoxically, the tight labor market _ which logically ought to
diminish worries about job security _ might actually encourage
ethical lapses, some experts say. ``In a rising economy, you don't
want to be left out,'' said William Lundin, author of ``When Smart
People Work for Dumb Bosses'' (McGraw-Hill, 1998). ``To be at the
big table and play with the big guys, you take chances and risks,
and bend your ethics.''
</P>
<P>
   Many companies have adopted codes of conduct and other ethics
programs in recent years. Yet, a new survey by the consulting and
accounting firm KPMG shows that unethical behavior is still rife in
the workplace. The survey of 2,300 workers in a broad range of
industries was conducted in 1999 and released last week. More than
three-quarters of the respondents had witnessed illegal activities
or breaches of company rules over the previous 12 months, and 38
percent said they believed that senior managers would ``authorize
illegal or unethical conduct to meet business goals.'' Factors that
they said encouraged unethical behavior included the pressure to
meet unrealistic production and earnings goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still seeing fairly significant levels of misconduct,''
said Richard Girgenti, KPMG's national director of investigative
and integrity management services. ``Ethics programs need attention
and nurturing.''
</P>
<P>
   Crossing certain ethical boundaries may be endemic to certain
industries. In a recent survey by the trade journal PR Week of
1,700 public-relations executives, 25 percent acknowledged lying on
the job, 39 percent said they had exaggerated the truth, and 44
percent said they had ethical qualms about tasks they had been
asked to perform.
</P>
<P>
   A common catalyst for wrongful behavior is common to every
industry: blind devotion to a boss. Nan DeMars, an ethics
consultant in Minneapolis, cited an Atlanta secretary who, trusting
her boss, notarized a document for the sale of his wife's car
without witnessing the wife's signature _ a breach of the law _
because he insisted it was hers. It wasn't, the wife said in a
lawsuit, and the secretary ended up with a felony conviction.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Mason, head of the Maguire Center for Ethics and Public
Responsibility at Southern Methodist University in Dallas, said
that people guilty of ethical missteps usually have a ``moment of
truth'' in which they either decide to rationalize their behavior
or try to make amends.
</P>
<P>
   Hovis is trying to make amends. ``I paid for the blood money,''
she said, fighting tears. ``All the calls and cries for help'' from
clients gave her sleepless nights, she said, and led to occasional
heavy drinking.
</P>
<P>
   She decided in 1994 she did not want to sell the funds anymore
and soon left the bank. Since then, she said, she has cooperated
with federal and state regulators, including testifying to the
Securities and Exchange Commission. On top of the $29 million
class-action settlement, in 1998 NationsBank agreed to pay $6.75
million to settle charges by the SEC and other regulators that it
had misled investors about their investment risks. NationsBank
neither admitted nor denied wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the least I can do to repay my part of what I did,'' said
Hovis, who is now trying to make a career out of teaching financial
education. ``When I'm dead and gone, at least my son will say, `My
mom tried.'''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-17-00 1557EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
