<SLUG> BC-YUGOSLAVIA-MEDIA-1000(2TAKES)-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOVERNMENT SEIZES INDEPENDENT MEDIA OUTLETS 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed.) 
 By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Serbian government on Wednesday seized control of the main
opposition television station, accusing it of advocating an
uprising.
</P>
<P>
   Opposition politicians, taken by surprise, talked of the
beginning of a dictatorship in Serbia, under Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic. They called for an immediate protest rally.
</P>
<P>
   The station that was seized, Studio B, belonged to the city of
Belgrade and also provided a frequency for the independent radio
station B2-92, which was effectively silenced.
</P>
<P>
   Studio B was controlled by the Serbian Renewal Movement of Vuk
Draskovic, the ruling party in the city and the single largest
opposition party in the country. Studio B, although lavish in its
coverage of Draskovic, is the most important opposition television
outlet in Serbia, able to reach up to half the population in normal
times, and its seizure is an attack on Draskovic.
</P>
<P>
   Since December, its broadcasts have frequently been jammed, and
it has been one of the main targets of an increasing series of
fines and lawsuits aimed at the independent media and independent
publishing houses.
</P>
<P>
   The station remained on the air Wednesday, showing
pro-government material and the state news. The government named a
presumed loyalist, Ljubisav Aleksic, as the new editor and general
manager. On the frequency given to Radio B2-92 there was music.
</P>
<P>
   The new management of Studio B broadcast pictures of the empty
newsroom, highlighting cabinets full of expensive foreign liquor, a
British flag and signs from the United Nations and SFOR
peacekeepers in Bosnia, underlining official accusations that the
opposition works for the NATO countries that bombed Yugoslavia last
year.
</P>
<P>
   The official charge against the station, in an order signed by
radical nationalist leader Vojislav Seselj, the Serbian deputy
prime minister, was that Studio B had called for a violent
overthrow of the constitutional order and had incited people to
riot. For that, the government said, it seized control and
ownership of the station.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the beginning of dictatorship,'' said Ognjen
Pribicevic, a top aide to Draskovic. ``Now it's up to the people of
Serbia to see how many show up to defend Studio B. The next step
could be a ban on political parties.''
</P>
<P>
   Pribicevic said the opposition is appealing to the United States
and to Russia, an ally of Milosevic, ``to condemn this attack
against the Serbian people, especially when the Yugoslav foreign
minister has just been in Moscow.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Another opposition leader, Vladan Batic, said: ``The government
has imposed an informal state of emergency. This indicates an
introduction of a civil war.''
</P>
<P>
   An opposition politician, Zarko Korac, said: ``The Serbian
regime has opted for an open dictatorship. It is up to the citizens
of Serbia to respond and say whether they want to live in such a
society.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Studio B director and editor-in-chief Dragan Kojadinovic denied
that the station has called for an uprising. ``I can say that this
has no legal or realistic foundations,'' he said. ``Studio B has
not called for any toppling of legally elected authorities. It only
reported on political and other events.''
</P>
<P>
   The head of the Association of Independent Electronic Media,
Veran Matic, said that B2-92 was ``collateral damage'' in the
closings and that it was looking for backup broadcasting options.
He said the move was ``the most serious assault'' yet on
independent media.
</P>
<P>
   Local and federal elections are due in Yugoslavia before the end
of this year.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Draskovic and other members of the opposition have sometimes
been intemperate in their language and have come close to calling
for a popular movement to sweep Milosevic from power without
benefit of elections. They have also called on the army and police
to defect to the opposition and overthrow the government.
</P>
<P>
   Last Friday, at a party rally in Ravna Gora, Draskovic said his
party would more strongly oppose ``the terror'' of the Milosevic
regime. ``From today, we will not only defend ourselves by
meetings, speeches and statements, but by all means possible,'' he
said. And when his supporters shot guns into the air, Draskovic
said, ``Save your ammunition _ you'll need it.'' That rally was
shown on Studio B.
</P>
<P>
   Studio B has regularly broadcast Draskovic's charges that senior
government police and political officials conspired to kill him in
a car accident last October in which his brother-in-law and some
bodyguards died.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The police moved at 2 a.m. to seize the building housing the
offices and newsroom of Studio B. The police also locked the
offices of B2-92 and Radio Indeks, in the same building, as well as
the offices of the largest independent newspaper, Blic.
</P>
<P>
   Blic, which has a circulation of more than 220,000 copies, was
already being harassed by the government, with the state-owned
Borba printing press refusing to print the paper on the grounds
that a press was broken.
</P>
<P>
   Blic, which has been able to print only about half of its normal
circulation using two other printing houses, presumably will
continue to appear, since it has no connection to Studio B.
</P>
<P>
   But the private printing house that prints Glas Javnosti,
another independent newspaper, and has been printing some copies of
Blic as well as the independent weeklies Nin and Vreme is also
under attack by the government for alleged financial
irregularities. The printing house, ABC Grafika, has been ordered
to vacate its premises, although it has appealed.
</P>
<P>
   In recent days, especially after the murders of some senior
officials, including Bosko Perosevic, a senior member of
Milosevic's party, Yugoslav authorities have increased their
attacks on the opposition, labeling them traitors, terrorists and
fascists.
</P>
<P>
   The opposition, often divided, has lately shown signs of more
unity. But after a successful rally in Belgrade last month, when
more than 150,000 people gathered, a second rally on Monday
attracted fewer than 20,000. Government officials gloated and may
have taken the low turnout as a signal to move forward with this
crackdown and challenge to the opposition.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The government also increased its attacks on the student
organization Otpor, which means Resistance, which has attracted
more serious political support in recent months.
</P>
<P>
   In the last week, at least one journalist was accused of
espionage, but was later released. And some 40 Otpor activists and
other opposition figures have been detained in recent days for
``informative talks'' with the police.
</P>
<P>
   The only independent electronic media that could be heard in
Belgrade on Wednesday was Radio Pancevo, based in an
opposition-controlled town nearby. And there were concerns that the
government would try to move against the many small television and
radio stations controlled by the cities where the opposition holds
power.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic has typically been careful to keep to the letter of
the law, but he and his government now are acting more arbitrarily
than in the past. He has also generally allowed a zone of free
speech and independent newspapers and magazines that tend to preach
to the converted. He often did so to please the West, but since the
war over Kosovo and his indictment on war crimes charges,
Milosevic's motivation to satisfy Western requirements has been
considerably diminished.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did not begin as a dictator and has not been one,'' said
one opposition politician, asking for anonymity. ``But he may
become one yet.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
