<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 16:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7902 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-BROOKLYN-BOTANIC-GARD     05-17 1658
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BROOKLYN-BOTANIC-GARDEN-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAPANESE GARDEN IS REBORN, IMPERFECTIONS AND ALL
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: S.C., Japan)   (ART ADV: Photos NYT 7,8 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By ANNE RAVER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Trying to see through the gates, shuddering at the
sound of jackhammers and buzz saws, worrying about 85-year-old
cherry trees dangling their roots in the drained pond: It was like
pacing the halls during a beloved's interminable operation. But now
the vigil is over and worrywarts can relax: The Brooklyn Botanic
Garden is about to reopen its Japanese Hill-and-Pond Garden, and
the patient never looked better.
</P>
<P>
   Like the ducks and herons that showed up as soon as the water
returned in April (who told them?) and the three turtles basking on
a rock (how did they escape the turtle roundup last summer?),
people will flock back to the Japanese Garden on May 24, when the
gates are thrown open on the yearlong $3 million renovation.
</P>
<P>
   There are interesting things to quibble over, like a few
lollipop grafted cherry trees that may never learn to weep, and the
vibrantly orange-red torii gate, but overall, the restoration has
remained true to the spirit of the original garden, designed by
Takeo Shiota in 1915.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very experimental dynamic time, when young designers
were reinventing the Japanese garden,'' said Annie Van Assche, a
art historian at the Japan Society Gallery in Manhattan. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Brooklyn garden, the first public Japanese garden in
America, ``incorporates many of the classical conventions,'' Van
Assche added, like terraced hillsides and a cascading waterfall,
and the borrowed scenery of hills and trees reflected in water.
</P>
<P>
   But it takes liberties too, like the bronze cranes standing in
the pond. ``You would never see a crane sculpture in gardens in
Japan,'' Van Assche said. And that torii gate, she said, modeled
after the great Miyajima gate that stands on its own in the Inland
Sea of Japan, framing the islands in the far distance, is a bit
epic for a little Brooklyn garden. (So maybe Shiota, a young
immigrant himself, was missing home.)
</P>
<P>
   As restorers examined the interpretations of the garden passed
down as truths by ``experts'' over the years, they found them to be
legends that dispelled like mist. Yet like Gilbert &AMP; Sullivan's
``Mikado,'' they tell a story in themselves about what Americans
understood _ or misunderstood _ about this exotic land.
</P>
<P>
   There's a jarring newness to the fresh wooden pilings, the
orange-red paint, the clunky bluestone benches of the amphitheater
dedicated to the garden's first benefactor, Alfred T. White. ``It's
going to take me a little while to accommodate myself to those
pilings that edge the pond,'' said Archie Hobson, a book editor and
garden guide, who married Susan Lacerte, the director of Queens
Botanical Garden, by the Shinto shrine 13 years ago. ``I was used
to a more natural edge. And I'm not happy to see the bird
sculptures come back, or those bright azaleas.''
</P>
<P>
   Those birds are replicas of the original bronze cranes that
stood in the pond, by Turtle Island, when the garden first opened,
so they are just as faithful to Shiota's design as the tall pines
that evoke eternity, the flowering cherries that speak of the
evanescence of life. Or the crisp edges of the dredged pond. But
time, and each person's interpretation of the garden, had blurred
those edges. And why not?
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese waterfall ``is actually an Italian grotto built
with Manhattan schist,'' said Hobson, who learned this from Marc
Keane, a consultant brought over from the University of Kyoto to
advise restorationists on the garden's authenticity. The
five-tiered waterfall, with echo chamber to magnify the sound of
rushing water, is like something you might see in a Long Island
diner. But what do you expect from stone masons longing for the old
country?
</P>
<P>
   As Hobson said: ``We don't have to be deadeye-Dick about it. We
don't have to be defensive. This is an American garden in Brooklyn.
The water drowns out the traffic.'' It's our garden. And grottos
are just fine with us.
</P>
<P>
   Keane is an American landscape architect who fell so in love
with Japan he now lives in Kyoto. When he went back to Japan, he
left quite a few ripples, good and bad, depending on your personal
mythology.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen the Miyajima gate twice and it was not orange, it
was vermilion,'' said Elizabeth Scholtz, who directed the botanic
garden for eight years, and is the vessel of all its arcane
history. ``It was orange originally, but when Dr. George Avery went
to Japan in 1960, he came back with the theory that the Japanese do
not like painted wood. So he caused it to be scraped.''
</P>
<P>
   Avery ran the garden from 1945 to 1969; Scholtz steered it
through the budget crunch of the 1970s. Around that time, a
gardener handed her an article in Scientific American about the
Miyajima shrine, which had a picture of the torii gate in glorious
color _ vermilion, not orange.
</P>
<P>
   So Scholtz decided to paint the gate scarlet. ``So it would
stand out in the landscape,'' she said. ``As if to say, `We may be
suffering financially, but look at us!'''
</P>
<P>
   Then the interloper, Keane, came along and stuck in his two
cents: an authentic torii gate would be more orange.
</P>
<P>
   Forget that cockamamie story that the lake echoes the shape of
the Chinese character for heart _ or is it mind?
</P>
<P>
   ``He just tossed that aside,'' Scholtz, who rather liked that
story, said. ``He said it was an irregular shape because it fit the
contours of the land.''
</P>
<P>
   Sure enough, when they went back to the 1910 plan of the
Brooklyn Botanic Garden, before the Japanese garden was built, why
there was a pond with a squiggly shape.
</P>
<P>
   Keane also debunked the long-told theory, first espoused in a
walking guide written by Bunkio Matsuki, in 1930, that various
parts of the garden represented heaven, man and earth. ``I was so
relieved when he said that,'' Scholtz said. ``Because I could see
that heaven was the top of the hill. But where was man?''
</P>
<P>
   In short, it soon became clear that no one but Shiota, who left
no records of his work, really knew the true meaning of the garden,
nor understood the complexities of centuries of Japanese design,
with its mixture of Shinto and Buddhism, borrowed from the Chinese
(who loved that orange-red paint, as well).
</P>
<P>
   ``In the Shinto religion, the gods, or kami, reside in nature,''
Van Assche said. ``They could be in a tree, a rock, a piece of
moss. They were never represented in human form, until Buddhism
came to Japan.''
</P>
<P>
   The kami are here.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pine grove in front of the Shinto shrine always reminds me
of camping in Maine and New Hampshire,'' said Lacerte, who worked
in the Brooklyn garden for five years. ``It's very evocative for
me. When I go hiking in the mountains, I feel like trees and rocks
speak to me. I feel that comes out in the Japanese garden.''
</P>
<P>
   The wisteria is blooming lustily over the arbor that stands on
sturdy locust posts in the pond. The torii gate has had what sounds
like a root canal job _ the rotting cores of its cypress posts dug
out and replaced with fiberglass _ before its glossy paint job.
</P>
<P>
   The curving pond has been restored to its original shoreline,
which had eroded, along with the surrounding slopes, after 85 years
of rain. ``The erosion had been terrible,'' said Ralph Morgan, the
director of capital projects standing by newly planted kurumi
azaleas on the northern slope of the Japanese garden. Now, stone
retaining walls hold soil and plants in place, and an ingenious
drainage system designed by Vollmer Associates of New York channels
torrential downpours away from the pond.
</P>
<P>
   The dreary stockade fence that kept visitors from glimpsing the
mystery of pine, stone and water has been replaced by a graceful
larch fence with a snow-cap top (to artfully catch the snow) and
eye-level openings with views of every angle of the garden.
</P>
<P>
   A wide crushed gravel path, accessible to wheelchairs and baby
carriages, now circles the pond, whose banks will soon be soft
blankets of ferns, liriope and Japanese lilies. New grass covers
Turtle Island, which, like Atlantis, was about to slide into the
sea, and much-needed new trees _ pines, katsura and cherries, to
name a few _ have been planted among the venerable originals.
</P>
<P>
   Now Judith Zuk, the current president, is putting her own mark
on the garden by bringing the bronze cranes and lotuses back to the
pond. Avery had gotten rid of the exuberant flowers in the 1940s.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lake was absolutely clogged with lotus,'' Scholtz
recalled. ``And I think Avery decided they looked messy.'' He was
also on the ``vanguard of the weed-killer movement,'' which used up
all those postwar chemicals, ``so he got rid of them.''
</P>
<P>
   These new lotuses, germinating in a greenhouse, hark back to
seeds found in a broken piece of canoe more than 3,000 years old.
``They were found in the mud at the bottom of the river Kenmi in
Chiba city,'' near Tokyo, Zuk said.
</P>
<P>
   America's flirtation with Japanese culture cooled during World
War II, of course. The Shinto shrine was razed by an arsonist in
1937. A few years ago, Madoka Yoshida, a grand-niece of Shiota,
came to visit the garden. ``She brought pictures of his birthplace,
Ohtaki Chiba,'' Zuk said. ``It was a village with an Inari shrine
like the one he designed here.'' Inari is the Shinto god of the
harvest.
</P>
<P>
   Yoshida brought a letter her great-uncle had written to her
mother, in which he told her of the ``eye-soothing'' lotus flowers
in the pond. ``This garden is the pride of my life,'' he wrote. ``I
believe it will live long and my soul will be always living in the
garden.''
</P>
<P>
   Takeo Shiota died on Dec. 3, 1943, in a Japanese internment camp
in South Carolina. As his greatest work reopens this week, we think
of him among the pines.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
