<HEADLINE>
HALF AND HALF DO NOT MAKE A WHOLE LOTTA BEER SENSE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAUL BOURGEOIS 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Now anyone paying attention knows that we believe ``beer'' and
``fruit'' have about as much place together as do ``happily'' and
``married.''
</P>
<P>
   And the same goes for beer befouled by ginger ale. Which brings
us to Shandy Carib, a drink made and bottled in Trinidad. (See
www.caribbeer.com.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Shandy'' is a generic term for a drink that is half beer and
half ginger ale, lemon-lime soda or lemonade.
</P>
<P>
   Now to beer drinkers, meaning people who like the taste and
aroma of beer, adding soda pop, or ginger ale or whatever to beer
is a sin akin to mixing single-malt scotch with Dr Pepper.
</P>
<P>
   So what we have here is the Carib Brewery doing it for us. But,
then, how hard can it be?
</P>
<P>
   To answer this question, we mixed a quart of Old Milwaukee with
a quart of ginger ale. It took fewer than 10 seconds and the total
cost for this half-gallon of swill was about $2, compared with the
$7 for the six-pack of 12-ounce Shandy Carib, which has 1.2 percent
alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   Now keeping in mind that I drank this only because I get paid
to, I found the homemade shandy preferable. It was less sweet and
without the limey citrus taste of the Shandy Carib. The homemade
stuff had a better head. It lacked the deep amber color of the
Shandy Carib, but the bottled shandy doesn't come by its color
naturally. They add coloring. It says so on the bottle.
</P>
<P>
   But the color and sweetness of Shandy Carib was a plus for
D'Licious Pink, a Milwaukee exile, friend, confidant and former
member of the Milwaukee Bucks' Energee! Dance Team.
</P>
<P>
   D'Licious went on to say she thought Shandy Carib was a beverage
that also might be appreciated by her sisters, D'Lightful and
D'Lovely.
</P>
<P>
   It may be hard to believe, but growing up in Milwaukee, the town
made famous by Schlitz, D'Licious had never tasted a beer, and
something that was even half-beer was a new drinking experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Shandy's color is pretty,'' she said, ``and this is
something I could get into drinking at the beach or at a sports
party. It's light, and I'm not feeling the least bit woozy, which
happens easy to me.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it might be something the guys could have on hand
while watching a game on the tube with their wives and girlfriends,
but not both at the same time,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   And so it seemed that D'Licious had unwittingly hit upon the
message of the day.
</P>
<P>
   You don't mix wives with girlfriends, and you don't mix beer
with soda pop.
</P>
<P>
   D'Licious gives Shandy Carib a 4 ``because it's pretty and it's
sweet.''
</P>
<P>
   I give it a 1 for the same reasons.
</P>
<P>
   (Paul Bourgeois is beer critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
