   POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-SOCIAL-SECURITY (Washington) _ In laying out his Social
Security plan, George W. Bush talks about federal workers' private
investment accounts and suggests Vice President Al Gore is
hypocritical in denying them to the general public. But federal
workers don't get anything special. They pay comparable payroll
taxes for retirement and like 32 million other American workers,
they have a 401(k)-type investment plan. A Bush spokesman says the
candidate brought up the point only to counter Gore's suggestion
that stock market investing is ``risky.'' A News Analysis. By DAN
FREEDMAN.
</P>
<P>
   GAO-STUDY (Washington) _ A Government Accounting Office study
last year concluded that privatization of the Galveston County
(Texas) employees' retirement plan benefited higher-income
employees but hurt low-paid ones. The camp of Vice President Al
Gore is pointing to the study in its argument against the Social
Security investment accounts proposed by Republican George W. Bush.
By BENNETT ROTH.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-SENATE (Albany, N.Y.) _ President Clinton, a lame duck
in his own right, canceled two speaking engagements before two
major constituencies to attend the Democratic convention in New
York, where First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton became the party's
nominee for Senate. By JAY JOCHNOWITZ.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   HIGH-TECH-WORKERS (Washington) _ Congress is expected to clear a
major hurdle to passing legislation boosting the number of visas
for foreigners with technical skills such as computer programmers
and electrical engineers. The House Judiciary Committee likely will
approve a bill by Rep. Lamar Smith, R-Texas, that would lift limits
on such visas. By MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   SELECTIVE-SERVICE (Washington) _ Texas, Louisiana and Hawaii
have the poorest rates of compliance with the Selective Service
requirement that men born in 1980 must register for the draft, the
agency reports. New Hampshire, Maine and North Dakota have the best
rates. We look at the rates of other states including California,
New York, Michigan and Illinois. By AUSTIN ZALKIN.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   ROCKET-LAUNCH (Undated) _ Inclement weather forces NASA to
cancel the launch of an Atlas III rocket and postpone the lift off
of the shuttle Atlantis on a mission to the international space
station. By MARK CARREAU.
</P>
<P>
   RAILWAY-KILLER (Houston) _ A jury deliberates whether admitted
serial killer Angel Maturino Resendiz is innocent by reason of
insanity in the death of a Houston-area physician. The drifter, 40,
could receive either life in prison or the death penalty if found
guilty for raping and killing the woman. By LISA TEACHY.
</P>
