<SLUG> BC-CIR-ONLINE-SHOPPING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NET PAWNSHOPS SAY THEY'RE JUST THE TICKET 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 By MICHELLE SLATALLA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Snob that I am, I never thought I would consider buying a Norman
Rockwell collector's plate.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, I never thought that I would consider buying
something from a pawnbroker, either. Until last week, in fact, my
knowledge of the profession was limited to the movies. If you ever
want to feel really hopeless for two hours, find a video of ``The
Pawnbroker,'' with Rod Steiger. In the title role, Steiger conducts
business from behind the metal bars of a security cage as
desperate, lonely customers offer him their meager possessions _
cheap candlesticks, an old radio, a wristwatch _ in exchange for
quick cash.
</P>
<P>
   I have to say that none of that misery was evident last week on
Pawnbroker.com, a new site that acts as an online clearinghouse for
the wares of about 600 pawnshops across the country. With its clean
interface, straightforward query box for searches and inventory of
75,000 items organized into 10 categories, the site looks as
sanitized as any other used-goods emporium online. But you can
understand why I shied away from anything resembling candlesticks,
radios or wristwatches as I examined the merchandise.
</P>
<P>
   As in a typical pawnshop, much of the merchandise fell into the
category of Jewelry/Gemstones, with thousands of rings, watches and
necklaces at prices ranging from a few dollars to $125,000 for an
emerald-cut diamond. The category with the smallest selection was
Vehicles, which last week consisted of three motorcycles with
asking prices ranging from $3,500 to $30,000.
</P>
<P>
   One difference: Unlike most offline pawnshops, Pawnbroker.com
sells no firearms.
</P>
<P>
   I found the Norman Rockwell plate under
Antiques/Collectibles/Art. Issued as a limited edition plate titled
``Santa's Golden Gift'' to commemorate Christmas 1987, it was on
sale for $30.95 (negotiable).
</P>
<P>
   What tempted me was not the apple-cheeked Santa. No, I was
thinking more of the investment possibilities. After years of being
scorned by the art establishment, Rockwell's wholesome
freckles-and-pigtails style is suddenly on the verge of becoming
trendy. Last fall, a national exhibition of his paintings and
Saturday Evening Post covers began traveling to art museums in
major cities. I figured that before the exhibition reaches the
Guggenheim Museum next year, it might be wise to snap up a plate at
pre-Manhattan prices.
</P>
<P>
   As I read the item's description (``plate measures about 8
inches across''), it seemed I didn't have much to lose. Where else
was I going to put my money last week, tech stocks? And if I
guessed wrong, I could always serve dinner on the plate and plop
some mashed potatoes on Santa's twinkly eyes.
</P>
<P>
   I was about to click on the button that said Negotiate, which
would prompt a software program to dicker with me within price
limits set by the pawnbroker who owned the plate. But I hesitated,
considering the tragedy of the person who had pawned the plate in
exchange for quick cash, back in the days before it was OK to like
Norman Rockwell.
</P>
<P>
   Would I be profiting from someone else's misfortune? To find
out, I phoned Pawnbroker.com's chief executive, Neil McElwee.
</P>
<P>
   ``You, unfortunately, are suffering from the same
Hollywood-based stereotype as the rest of the 90 percent of the
public that doesn't go into a pawnshop,'' McElwee said. ``In
September, we did focus groups all around the country, where we
tested attitudes and found all of the stereotypes. People said they
were afraid of being ripped off, afraid of what would happen if a
neighbor sees me.''
</P>
<P>
   For 3,000 years, pawnbrokers have had to combat those
prejudices, McElwee said. ``But what is unique about the pawnbroker
model, how it works, is that it provides a service. The pawnbroker
gets merchandise from people who really were looking for short-term
loans because they have to pay the taxes or something. Seventy to
80 percent of those items are reclaimed.''
</P>
<P>
   No money for taxes? The more I heard, the sadder it sounded.
</P>
<P>
   McElwee assured me that focus group participants softened their
attitudes after they heard about the good deals available on
Pawnbroker.com _ he said the site generally sold items for no more
than 40 percent of their retail value.
</P>
<P>
   But I decided to look around for another source of Rockwell
plates. Faster than you could say, ``Is that a real Richard
Diebenkorn painting?'' I found ``Santa's Golden Gift'' for sale on
eBay.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, I found a number of identical listings on eBay: for a
camera, binoculars and a harmonica. Each sold for less than the
asking price on Pawnbroker.com (on eBay, the Rockwell plate sold
for $6.50).
</P>
<P>
   For all I knew, the eBay listings could have been for the same
items as the ones on Pawnbroker.com.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pawnbrokers are selling everything under $50 that they can
possibly post on eBay,'' McElwee said. ``But they have a devil of a
time selling anything over $150 because in a consumer-to-consumer
model like that, you have no idea whether what you are buying is
authentic.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike eBay's ``buyer beware'' policy, which the online auction
company overrode last week in canceling the notorious $135,805 sale
of an abstract painting that may or may not have been the work of
the artist Richard Diebenkorn, Pawnbroker.com offers some
insurance. Buyers can get a refund for up to 10 days after
receiving a purchased item in the mail, no questions asked, McElwee
said. That's plenty of time to seek an appraisal from, say, a
qualified Rockwell plate expert.
</P>
<P>
   So where did I buy the plate? After seeing the lackadaisical
bidding on eBay, I passed it up because I decided, in the end, that
buying tech stocks might be a better investment. However, I am
seriously considering another item on Pawnbroker.com: the Franklin
Mint's medal for the inauguration of President Richard M. Nixon and
Vice President Spiro T. Agnew in 1973. It's $199.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
