<HEADLINE>
`MAMA' PRESERVES HER BUSINESS BY KEEPING IT SMALL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ART CHAPMAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Don't bother to look for Mama's Best jams and jellies on the
Internet. Helen Beauchamp _ the owner, chief cook, marketing
executive and the ``Mama'' referred to on the label _ says she's
thought about it, but decided she doesn't want her enterprise to
get much bigger.
</P>
<P>
   She and her husband, Durant, still work off two gas stoves on
the converted back porch of their modest brick home in Millsap,
Texas. They've been there more than 30 years, the past 10 or so in
the canning business.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first started making the jams and jellies, a man told
me to not let it get too big,'' she said. ``I think he was right.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, she said, it's hard enough just to keep up, let alone
expand.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I could get out of it now if I wanted to,'' she
said with a laugh. ``I've added an apricot-peach jam, and I still
do a lot of jalapeno jelly. I have one man who comes from Dallas to
buy the jalapeno jelly, and he sends it to Germany.''
</P>
<P>
   Beauchamp ships her products to several countries. She has
packed it off to 15 states.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the marketing is simply word of mouth. Beauchamp does
sell her Mama's Best line at Weatherford's First Monday market and
at the Weatherford Public Market.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a lady come to the last First Monday and tell me she had
to try my mesquite bean jelly,'' Beauchamp said. ``She hadn't
tasted it before, but she said she was in an elevator in Fort Worth
with a man who kept looking at his watch and saying he had to get
to the Weatherford market before it closed so he could get some
mesquite bean jelly. The woman said he was in such a hurry, she had
to try some, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Beauchamp does take orders at her home. She'll ship her jams,
jellies, picante sauce and chow-chow anywhere UPS goes. She takes
the order over the phone, calls UPS, and then depends on her
customers to mail in their checks when the products arrive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody has been pretty honest, so far,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Chow-chow is still her biggest seller.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what I started out with,'' she said. ``When we are
making chow-chow, we grind up 100 pounds of cabbage at a time,
sometimes 150 pounds. The next day we put it all up.''
</P>
<P>
   It takes Helen and Durant both to keep up. She makes the
chow-chow, he puts the lids on and screws down the tops.
</P>
<P>
   During their busiest season _ the summer _ she gets away from
the canning process only on Sundays and on Monday mornings, when
``I have my hair done.''
</P>
<P>
   Any other time, the couple can be found in their kitchen,
cooking on the two gas stoves, or straining syrup from fruit, or
filling jars or making preparations for the next day's work.
</P>
<P>
   The Mama's Best label is placed on pint jars of picante sauce,
chow-chow, bread and butter pickles, and pickled beets. There are
also jams and jellies made from blackberries, peaches, pears, wild
plums, apricots, wild mustang grapes, wild hog plums and possum
grapes (winter grapes), and watermelon rind preserves.
</P>
<P>
   They also make apple butter.
</P>
<P>
   Beauchamp says the continuing Texas drought has affected her
business this season. ``We were trying to raise tomatoes and
peppers for chow-chow,'' she said. ``But the drought has been bad.
My son grew some onions that had roots 12 inches long. I guess they
were going down for water, I never saw such roots in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   The annual peach crop is still questionable. Beauchamp's biggest
selling weekend comes during the Parker County Peach Festival in
July. Some customers make the festival their once-a-year trip to
buy Mama's Best, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Mama's Best products can be ordered by calling Beauchamp at
(940) 682-4914.
</P>
<P>
   (Art Chapman writes on food for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Write to him at: Fort Worth Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, TX
76101. E-mail: artc(at)star-telegram.com. Web Site:
www.startext.net/interact/chapman.htm. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
