<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONFEDERATEAIRFORCE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONFEDERATE AIR FORCE MAY DROP `CONFEDERATE' FROM NAME OF VINTAGE
PLANE GROUP
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanied by CONFEDERATE-NAME) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS VAUGHN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lore has it that a practical joker _ no one has ever said who _
in 1957 painted the words ``Confederate Air Force'' on a P-51
Mustang owned by a group of men in South Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Back then, the name got a laugh. But in the America of today,
the joke doesn't go over as well. Just about anything asssociated
with Johnny Reb tends to incite controversy, even though the modern
aviation buffs have nothing to do with the War Between the States.
</P>
<P>
   So the Confederate Air Force, now with 8,500 members who
preserve a shrinking inventory of World War II warbirds, is
considering changing its name to defuse what some contend is a
growing public relations problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the long run, it's going to take corporate support'' to
keep the planes flying, said V. Neils Agather, a Dallas businessman
and one of 11 board members of the CAF. ``But the very first thing
you do when you meet with a CEO is explain why you have that name.
</P>
<P>
   ``From my perspective, it's easier to change the name. It
doesn't describe our mission.''
</P>
<P>
   Changing the name will be hard, mainly because the Midland-based
group wrote its bylaws to make it so. Any alteration in bylaws
requires the votes of nine of the 11 board members and 75 percent
of the voting members. The board is expected to vote in July
whether to send the proposal to the full membership.
</P>
<P>
   Proponents of changing the name acknowledge that they have to
persuade some members who see it as caving in to political
correctness.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, there is clearly a move within the organization to
consider Ghost Squadron, Commemorative Air Force or some less
controversial name. A similar idea was talked about among board
members in the early 1970s, but it never went to a vote. The idea
came up again last year _ this time by rank-and-file members _
during one of the group's annual meetings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hate to lose the name. It has meaning to the membership,''
Marvin Wood, a retiree and member of the Dallas-Fort Worth CAF
unit, said. ``Still, if you want to maintain your membership or get
new members, you're going to have to follow what's happening. And
looking at the atmosphere of the country right now, it's probably a
good idea.''
</P>
<P>
   The Confederate Air Force has about 140 airplanes that flew
during World War II, including the B-24 Liberator, the P-38
Lightning and the only B-29 Superfortress still flying. CAF units
scattered around the country, staffed only by volunteer members,
fly in dozens of air shows, make special appearances and
occasionally get parts in Hollywood films.
</P>
<P>
   The CAF also operates the American Airpower Heritage Museum in
Midland, Texas. The group's motto is ``Lest we forget.''
</P>
<P>
   It can be expensive to fly an airplane that is almost 60 years
old. For example, the B-29, nicknamed Fifi for Agather's mother,
costs $5,000 an hour to fly. At least half the costs to keep the
planes flying is borne by CAF members, with perhaps 30 percent
coming from money made selling T-shirts and caps at air shows.
</P>
<P>
   But the CAF's membership is aging _ the average is now 60. In a
few years, leaders have said, money will have to come from sources
other than just members. And so far, many corporations have shied
from linking their products with the word ``Confederate.''
</P>
<P>
   Agather said even the Pentagon withdrew an offer for the CAF to
appear at an event for fear of a public relations problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``Corporations have been reluctant to provide monetary support
for that very reason,'' said Bob Rice, the CAF's executive
director. ``Anyway, the name is not reflective of the mission of
the organization. We should spend more of our time talking about
what the organization accomplishes, rather than having to explain
why we're called the Confederate Air Force.''
</P>
<P>
   Ron Haddock, president and CEO of Fina, a major sponsor of the
CAF, has told the group's leaders that he would like the name
changed, although he said he doesn't want it to appear that he's
pressuring the CAF.
</P>
<P>
   Haddock said he hasn't had complaints from anyone within Fina,
but he has heard from people outside.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've heard it from people in the community I work with in
other activities,'' Haddock said yesterday from his office in the
Dallas suburb of Plano. ``I've been questioned about our support
for a group called the Confederate Air Force.
</P>
<P>
   ``It creates an impression in the minds of many segments of our
society that is not consistent with the objectives and the mission
of the organization.''
</P>
<P>
   Stephanie Cole, a history professor at the University of Texas
at Arlington, said it's understandable why corporations might be
reluctant to be identified with a group with that name.
</P>
<P>
   ``Choosing the name ``Confederate'' in 1957 clearly reflects a
stance on race relations that I can see people not wanting to
identify themselves with today,'' Cole said.
</P>
<P>
   Agather, whose father rescued the B-29 for the CAF many years
ago, said he doesn't think the group's founders gave much thought
to the name or how it would be viewed generations later.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sensitive'' to concerns about changing, he said. ``But at
the end of the day, you have to ask, `What is reality?'
</P>
<P>
   ``And the reality is, there is a lack of support out there for
the name.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
