<SLUG> BC-RECIPES-BUNDY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAKE IN A JAR? YES, YOU CAN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BEVERLY BUNDY 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Clara Doshier of Fort Worth saw our request for cakes baked in a
jar and sent the spice cake version. Joan Hallford of North
Richland Hills, Texas, sent in the chocolate version.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Strittmatter has made cakes in a jar, and here's her take.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was fascinated by the premise and made a batch. I discovered
it was novel but way too labor-intensive for my taste. It was a lot
of work without a great deal to show for it. Canning is an exacting
practice no matter what you can _ cakes or tomatoes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I discovered something that I liked much better _ `cookie mix
in a jar.' It's simple to do, and it doesn't heat up your kitchen.
They make great gifts, and they're pretty, too.'' She contributed
the recipe for sand art brownies.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   SPICE CAKE IN A JAR
</P>
<P>
   Yields 6-8 cakes (each cake serves 2)
</P>
<P>
   2/3 cup shortening
</P>
<P>
   2 2/3 cups sugar
</P>
<P>
   2/3 cup water
</P>
<P>
   2 cups applesauce
</P>
<P>
   4 eggs
</P>
<P>
   3 1/3 cups flour
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 teaspoons salt
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons baking soda
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon baking powder
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon ground cloves
</P>
<P>
   2/3 cup nuts, optional
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 325 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Cream shortening and sugar. Add water and applesauce. Add egg
and mix well.
</P>
<P>
   Combine dry ingredients in another bowl and add to creamed
mixture. Add nuts, if desired.
</P>
<P>
   Spray clean, wide-mouth pint canning jars with nonstick spray,
and fill jars about half full. This will fill 6-8 jars.
</P>
<P>
   Bake exactly 45 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Remove jars one at a time and quickly screw lid on each jar. Let
sit until cool, and store. When you use canning jar lids, this cake
has a shelf life of at least three months.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving without nuts: 316 calories, 9
grams fat, 55 grams carbohydrates, 4 grams protein, 53 milligrams
cholesterol, 363 milligrams sodium, 27 percent of calories from
fat.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   CHOCOLATE CAKE IN A JAR
</P>
<P>
   Yields 6 (each cake serves 2)
</P>
<P>
   2 1/2 cups sugar
</P>
<P>
   2/3 cup shortening
</P>
<P>
   4 eggs
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup buttermilk
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup cold brewed coffee
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon vanilla
</P>
<P>
   3 1/2 cups flour
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon baking powder
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons baking soda
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   6 (1 ounces) squares unsweetened chocolate, melted
</P>
<P>
   2/3 cup chopped nuts
</P>
<P>
   In large bowl, cream sugar and shortening with electric mixer.
Add eggs and mix well. Add buttermilk, coffee, and vanilla, and mix
well. Place dry ingredients in a separate large bowl and blend with
a whisk. Add creamed ingredients to dry ingredients and mix well
with a spoon. Blend in melted chocolate. Place 1 cup batter in each
of 6 well-greased, 1-pint, wide-mouth canning jars. Wipe batter
from rim. Place jars on a baking sheet. Bake at 325 degrees for 45
minutes or a toothpick inserted in center comes out clean. Wipe
rims. Place hot, sterilized seals and rings on hot jars.
</P>
<P>
   Keep in refrigerator for prolonged storage. Will last several
months without refrigeration.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 518 calories, 24 grams fat, 74
grams carbohydrates, 8 grams protein, 71 milligrams cholesterol,
419 milligrams sodium, 41 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   SAND ART BROWNIES
</P>
<P>
   Yields 9
</P>
<P>
   1 wide-mouth 1-quart jar with lid
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   2 1/2 tablespoon flour
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup cocoa
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup flour
</P>
<P>
   2/3 cup brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   2/3 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup chocolate chips
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup vanilla chips
</P>
<P>
   Nuts to fill jar
</P>
<P>
   Layer all ingredients in the jar in the order given, tamping
down after the brown sugar layer.
</P>
<P>
   To bake:
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   3 eggs
</P>
<P>
   Pour mix into medium bowl; add vanilla, oil and eggs. Stir to
combine. Mix well. Pour into greased 9-by-9-inch pan. Bake 45
minutes at 350 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   I've given sand art brownies as gifts on several occasions. It's
an easy gift for children to help assemble and a very simple treat
to prepare with some supervision.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per brownie: 431 calories, 26 grams fat, 51
grams carbohydrates, 5 grams protein, 71 milligrams cholesterol,
423 milligrams sodium, 54 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   Requests:
</P>
<P>
   A reader e-mails a request for blackberry jam cake.
</P>
<P>
   Another reader would like a recipe that ran years ago in the
Fort Worth Star-Telegram. My predecessor, Joanne Vachule, couldn't
find the recipe in her files but does recall that it ran. The
recipe is for Lucille's chili biscuits.
</P>
<P>
   Lucille B. Smith made the biscuits commercially for years _ a
``bowl of red'' in biscuit form.
</P>
<P>
   Evelyn King of Springtown, Texas, recalls a dish she used to
make called salmon pie. Clipped from the Star-Telegram, probably in
the mid-1960s, the dish had a double pie crust and was filled with
canned salmon, rice and, she thinks, frozen chopped broccoli. A
cheese sauce made from canned Cheddar cheese soup was served over
the pie when it was sliced.
</P>
<P>
   (Beverly Bundy is food editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Send recipes and requests to Beverly Bundy, Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, Texas 76101. Or E-mail to
bbundy(at)star-telegram.com. Include a daytime phone number.
Responses to requests will be made only through this column. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-17-00 1632EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000517.0202 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 16:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7939 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a BC-CONFEDERATE-NAME-TEX     05-17 0383
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONFEDERATE-NAME-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`CONFEDERATE' NAME SLIPPING IN POPULARITY AS VIEWS CHANGE
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanies CONFEDERATE AIR FORCE) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF CLAASSEN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   New businesses and groups rarely use it, but owners of some
older places proudly keep it.
</P>
<P>
   Businesses and civic groups with the word ``Confederate'' in
their names are as rare in Texas today as Civil War artifacts.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1980, for example, eight businesses and other
organizations with ``Confederate'' in their names have registered
with the Tarrant County clerk's office.
</P>
<P>
   The list includes a glass company, home builder and
window-cleaning company. But most of those appear to be defunct,
and none is listed in phone books.
</P>
<P>
   Some long-standing businesses, including a steel company and a
restaurant in Houston, hold on to ``Confederate'' with pride.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be a tough word to use in almost any new business
name,'' said Mike Carr, co-owner of the Name Stormers, a business
consulting company near Austin that helps people find names for
their companies, products and Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so clearly associated with one event in history that it's
hard to overcome that meaning, anywhere in the U.S.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the 20 companies with names including ``Confederate''
that are listed with the Texas secretary of state's office are not
in phone directories or could not be reached Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   For Confederate Steel Corp. in Houston, however, the word is a
source of pride.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't had any problems, and we've had this name for 38
years,'' company President Clayton Underwood said.
</P>
<P>
   New owners of the Confederate House Restaurant, a 52-year-old
landmark on Houston's west side, said they struggled with their
decision to keep the original name.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made a concerted effort to let our customers know that by
no means are we agreeing with the negative aspects of the
Confederate era, but instead are paying homage to the former owner,
Gordon Edge; and his family history,'' general manager Thomas Leman
said.
</P>
<P>
   Edge's ancestors fought for the Confederacy, and the restaurant
has artifacts from the Confederate and Union armies, Leman said.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
