<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 16:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7941 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX     05-17 0735
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH ENEMIES LIKE THESE, DOES THE NRA NEED FRIENDS?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I don't mind saying that I was worried about the Million Mom
March.
</P>
<P>
   As a supporter of the constitutionally guaranteed right to keep
and bear arms, I feared that the anti-gun demonstration on Mothers
Day could ignite a grassroots furor for new gun-control laws _
including some that might be drastic and unwarranted.
</P>
<P>
   As a supporter of George W. Bush's presidential campaign, I
feared that the Texas governor/Republican nominee-to-be might be
perceived as too supportive of gun rights by a massive army of
nonpartisan moms mobilizing in a sincere commitment to making our
country safer.
</P>
<P>
   Now that the march is over, I can see that my concerns were
unfounded. The Million Mom March was not a nonpartisan, grassroots
movement organized to support ``common-sense'' laws that would
promote gun safety. It was an overhyped dog-and-pony show organized
by gun-hating liberals for the purpose of promoting Al Gore's
presidential campaign and putting more Democrats in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   If the march and the ensuing rally had lived up to its billing,
Mother's Day 2000 might have gone down in history as the day that
the long-standing battle over gun rights was removed from the arena
of partisan politics. As it turned out, the march might mark the
day that the anti-gun crowd became as politically and socially
marginalized as its archenemy, the National Rifle Association.
</P>
<P>
   The NRA and some of its goofy spokesmen have often made it
difficult for reasonable people to be on their side. If ever there
was a collection of folks who don't know when to shut up, it's the
pro-gun activists who send the likes of Wayne LaPierre out into the
world to argue their point of view.
</P>
<P>
   Even the once universally admired Charlton Heston has turned
into a babbling idiot, spouting NRA propaganda with the conviction
of Moses handing down the Ten Commandments.
</P>
<P>
   But how lucky can they get? Just as LaPierre and Heston dig a
hole so deep that it looks like the Second Amendment will never
crawl out of it, along comes the Million Mom March with a pair of
spokespeople who make these guys sound like great communicators.
</P>
<P>
   First, there's Donna Dees-Thomases, the New Jersey woman who
conjured up the whole idea of a Million Mom March. Asked Monday if
her Million Mom March ``action committees'' would be endorsing
political candidates, Dees-Thomases said she didn't know and then
proceeded to endorse Gore for president.
</P>
<P>
   She had only scorn for Bush's plan to offer free trigger locks
to gun owners. This common-sense proposal to promote gun safety
must require more common sense than Dees-Thomases can muster.
</P>
<P>
   And then there's Rosie O'Donnell, who presided over the Million
Mom rally and helped lead the crowd in clever chants such as
``Time-out chair for Wayne LaPierre, time-out chair for Wayne
LaPierre ...''
</P>
<P>
   Columnist Ellen Goodman recently described O'Donnell as ``mentor
and emcee, adviser and starshine'' for the Million Mom March.
</P>
<P>
   O'Donnell's frequent pronouncements on the gun issue have made
it clear that she has no interest in common-sense proposals to
promote gun safety. She believes that the federal government should
do whatever it takes to eliminate guns from society.
</P>
<P>
   It seems odd, doesn't it, that an entertainer who makes her
living shooting off her mouth and thus must cherish the First
Amendment to the Constitution of the United States would have no
use whatsoever for the Second Amendment?
</P>
<P>
   It's too bad, actually, that the Million Mom March turned out to
be a sham. Many _ maybe even most _ of the participants were
sincere and were led to believe that they had signed up for
something meaningful, something that would have lasting value.
</P>
<P>
   The truth is that America's legions of concerned, caring moms
really could make a difference if they came together in a
legitimate, nonpartisan movement dedicated to making their families
safer through sensible measures to reduce gun violence.
</P>
<P>
   But the Million Mom March was just politics. We didn't need more
politics.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can reach him at (817) 390-7787 or
billthompson(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
