<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 16:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7953 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-TONYS-THEATER-ART-2ND     05-17 1517
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TONYS-THEATER-ART-2NDTAKE-$ADV21-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: was granted.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Such efforts notwithstanding, Jed Bernstein, president of the
league, said the process generally worked. ``It's easy to take
potshots at individual rules and individual outcomes,'' he said.
``But once you start to understand the ultimate goal _ that there
ought to be a level playing field _ whether it's right or wrong, at
least it's fair.''
</P>
<P>
   Some producers beg to differ. Since 1994, Roy Gabay has
produced, or been general manager for, three Pulitzer Prize-winning
plays _ ``Three Tall Women,'' ``How I Learned to Drive'' and
``Wit'' _ all Off Broadway, none Tony eligible. ``That to me is
wrong,'' Gabay said. ``I don't understand how that can be, that
plays that were honored for excellence in the theater are not
eligible for an excellence award.''
</P>
<P>
   The Off Broadway industry itself has in the past resisted the
idea of becoming Tony-eligible because of logistical and financial
obstacles. Trying to get all the Tony voters into the multitude of
small Off Broadway houses to see every production would be almost
impossible. In addition, it could drive up the costs of producing,
due to the loss of revenue that would result from having to give
away seats to Tony voters, and because the unions might then demand
Broadway rates _ or at least a higher wage scale _ for their
services.
</P>
<P>
   Some theater executives suggested creating a few Off Broadway
Tony Awards and appointing a special Off Broadway Tony committee so
that every voter would not have to see every Off Broadway show. ``I
don't know if it's feasible,'' said Daryl Roth, an Off Broadway
producer who has also produced on Broadway. ``But it feels like the
right thing to do and where we're heading.''
</P>
<P>
   Because Off Broadway productions are excluded from the Tonys,
Roth said they miss out on national exposure during the Tony Awards
show. This is particularly critical to productions that can barely
afford their own marketing. Broadway producers often counter that
Off Broadway has its own prizes. But others say these do not have
the prestige of the Tonys in terms of what they can do for a show's
fortunes and a performer's reputation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Careers change when they get a Tony Award,'' said Virginia P.
Louloudes, the executive director of the Alliance of Resident
Theaters/New York, a service group for nonprofit theaters. ``And
God knows, the actors deserve the recognition. So do the directors
and designers.''
</P>
<P>
   What it comes down to, it seems, is what the Tonys are really
about. ``If the point of the awards is to promote Broadway, then
keeping Off Broadway out of the awards is appropriate,'' said Todd
Haimes, artistic director of the Roundabout Theater Company, an Off
Broadway house that also produces on Broadway. ``If the point is to
award excellence in the theater in the New York metropolitan area,
then to keep Off Broadway out is ridiculous.''
</P>
<P>
   Broadway executives say the Tony is not an equal-opportunity
perk; it is reserved for those foolhardy enough and financially
able to gamble on Broadway. Big risks, this argument goes, deserve
the biggest potential reward.
</P>
<P>
   ``No business is going to give away its franchise for nothing,''
said Landesman, the producer. ``Would Rolls-Royce say, `Here's our
emblem, go put it on a Chevy?' I don't see why we're expected to do
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Gabay said the major flaw of the Tonys was who rules on
eligibility. ``You're looking at people with completely vested
interests,'' he said about the 24 members of the Tony
administration committee. ``It's not a group of people who can make
a fair decision. They are theater owners, they are producers. Why
would I want `Wit' to be eligible when I'm producing `Art' or `The
Beauty Queen of Leenane'?''
</P>
<P>
   Gabay said that when a producer appears before the
administration committee to argue his case, as he has, the deck is
stacked. ``You feel like you're just going through the motions,''
he said, ``because it's completely political in there.''
</P>
<P>
   Producers who serve on the committee defend the selection
process, saying, essentially, welcome to the real world. ``Is it
any different in this industry from the television industry or the
recording industry or the film industry?'' asked Barry Weissler,
who, with his wife, Fran, has produced several of Broadway's
biggest hit revivals. ``It's the same. Everyone has
self-interest.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Azenberg, the producer, said, the Tonys make no
pretense of being about which artist or project is better than
another; it isn't like winning a track meet because you ran the
fastest. ``We have an artificial competition,'' he said. ``Shows
don't compete. It's just a subjective choice between people.''
</P>
<P>
   Bernstein, of the league, pointed out that many of those who
criticize certain rules are not prepared to present viable
alternatives. Some people in the industry, for example, have
objected to considering ``True West'' a new production because,
although it was written in 1980 and produced Off Broadway, the play
has never been produced on Broadway. But then, Bernstein asked,
what does the definition of a new play become? A production that
was never done in New York City but might have been done in
Connecticut or New Jersey? A play that has never been given an
``important production''? And if that is the case, what defines
important?
</P>
<P>
   As to what constitutes a musical, that appears to be up for
grabs these days. With shows like ``Smokey Joe's Cafe,'' ``Fosse,''
``Riverdance,'' ``Swing!,'' ``Contact'' and ``James Joyce's `The
Dead''' stretching the boundaries of a traditional book musical, it
is hard to know what a musical is anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Some theater professionals suggested creating more specific
categories, along the lines of London's Olivier Awards or
Hollywood's Golden Globes _ like Tonys for best solo performance or
best entertainment _ though this would mean more to squeeze into
the already crowded broadcast.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are those who argue that there are not enough voters
with the appropriate expertise in each category, like craftspeople
who can judge design. But critics of this idea caution that the
voting pool is already bloated and adding voters is not the answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there are too many people voting,'' Azenberg said.
``You can't get a lifetime franchise by producing one play. Some of
us still want to be judged by our peers.'' He said he had given
Tony voters $125,000 worth of tickets to ``The Iceman Cometh,''
which he produced last year in a limited run starring Kevin Spacey
(who was also a producer of the play). ``If I'm going to do a play
for 12 to 14 weeks, that's giving away 25 percent of the potential
profit if the play is successful,'' Azenberg said. (``Iceman''
orchestra tickets were $100.)
</P>
<P>
   With increasing numbers of new people dabbling in Broadway, ``it
will get out of hand,'' he warned. ``It IS out of hand.''
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, the league stepped up its enforcement of a policy
mandating that only producers who have produced a show in the
previous four years could remain active members and therefore have
a Tony vote, though they may retain their league membership _ a
decision that angered several voters, about 30 of whom have drafted
a complaint against the league that has been sent out to members of
the group for approval. This reduced the number of Tony voters from
825 to 705, a figure that will jump slightly, because the league
recently lengthened the required time period within which someone
must have produced to six years and decided to create a new
lifetime membership category for inactive theater veterans to honor
their service.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, there are still a lot of voters, each of whom is
entitled to a pair of tickets per show, which amounts to a
potential loss of about $100,000 for each production. Moreover,
many producers complain that some voters give their tickets away
but cast their votes nonetheless _ a violation of rules that
producers nevertheless feel unable to enforce without alienating
voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to be offensive and cost myself a vote,'' Gabay
said. ``Will they get really annoyed and not vote for me if I put
the screws in?''
</P>
<P>
   When the Tonys were created by the American Theater Wing in
1947, the ceremony took place at the Waldorf-Astoria. The award
consisted of a scroll and women got a monogrammed sterling silver
compact; men a cigarette lighter or an engraved gold money clip.
Some people miss the old days.
</P>
<P>
   ``I enjoy the intimacy and the feeling of family in the ballroom
that we had then,'' said Isabelle Stevenson, chairwoman of the
American Theater Wing.
</P>
<P>
   Stevenson makes no secret of her belief that the Tonys have
become too concerned with commercial interests. ``The Tony Award
was created to reward excellence in the theater,'' she said.``There
was no thought of it being of economic value.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't be blind to the fact that it is an important
economic boost to the theater. On the other hand, it cannot become
just that. The commitment to excellence must remain. You cannot use
it only as an economic marketing tool.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
