<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-SENATE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     PRESIDENT SKIPS EVENTS TO BACK FIRST LADY'S CAMPAIGN 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JAY JOCHNOWITZ  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ President Clinton broke two engagements to be by
his wife's side when she officially became the state Democratic
Party's nominee for Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The lame-duck president's decision to attend the New York
Democratic convention Tuesday night came after days of uncertainty
over whether he would join her on what was undoubtedly one of the
most important nights of her life, not to mention her new political
career.
</P>
<P>
   While his wife addressed more than 11,000 delegates in Albany,
Clinton sat quietly on the stage with retiring Sen. Daniel Patrick
Moynihan and other top Democrats. But in a party given by state
Democratic Chairwoman Judith Hope, he explained his last-minute
decision and gave a speech of his own.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said that before they knew when his wife would speak, he
had already committed to attending a dinner for the Mexican
American Legal Defense Fund and a campaign event for the Senate
Democratic Committee.
</P>
<P>
   He said he finally canceled the MALDF event, telling the
organization: ``I've been with you folks a long time, and if you'll
let me go hear my wife give a speech, I'll do any event you want in
America, anytime, wherever in the future. And I told the Senate
Democratic Campaign Committee that the Senate campaign I was most
interested in was otherwise occupied tonight and I was going
there.''
</P>
<P>
   The president took a more serious note in talking about the
race, thanking the crowd for supporting his wife and urging them to
fight for her victory, and for Vice President Al Gore's
presidential campaign, in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big test facing New York and America is what are we going
to do with this magic moment of prosperity we have all worked so
hard for,'' Clinton said. ``A moment like this imposes a test on a
people just as severe as great adversity does.''
</P>
<P>
   Recalling how Americans elected Franklin Roosevelt in the middle
of the Depression, Clinton chided Republicans for promising ``a big
tax cut and all the things you ever dreamed of'' and warned against
squandering the riches brought on by the sustained economic boom
throughout his presidency.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know a little something about American history,'' he said.
``It may be 30, it may be 50, it may be 80 or 100 years before our
country ever has so much prosperity, so much social progress, so
little internal crisis and external strife as we have today. We are
being tested as surely as if we were in the middle of a war or a
depression. And we are being tested when it's easy for us to be
distracted.''
</P>
<P>
   The president gave his wife good marks for her speech and told
party-goers he wasn't alone: At one point, he said, Moynihan
commented, ```Good speech.' Now that would be like the rest of us
comparing it to the Gettysburg address, and I knew that she was on
a roll.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
