<SLUG> BC-RAMSEYS-TALKSHOW-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAMSEYS PLAN TO DISCUSS FAITH, JONBENET'S KILLING IN TEXAS TALK
SHOW
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TARA DOOLEY 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EULESS, Texas _ They may just be the most recognizable parents
in the country.
</P>
<P>
   After the killing of their 6-year-old daughter, JonBenet, more
than three years ago, John and Patsy Ramsey took center stage in a
case that continues to evoke strong emotions from an audience of
American onlookers.
</P>
<P>
   Photographs of the Ramseys, especially JonBenet, are regularly
splashed on the covers of supermarket tabloids, and the killing
remains a popular topic on radio talk shows. Sometimes, the parents
are accused in the child beauty pageant queen's death. Other times,
their innocence is proclaimed.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, the Ramseys added their voices to the chorus by taking
to the interview circuit to promote their new book and to answer
the accusations.
</P>
<P>
   On May 30, the Ramseys can again be heard _ this time in Euless.
</P>
<P>
   The couple will tape a segment of ``Life Today with James
Robison,'' a talk show hosted by the Christian television
evangelist. The show will air in mid-July, producers said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I plan to talk very candidly with them but give them an
opportunity to perhaps share some areas that they have not been
able to share on other programs,'' James Robison said.
</P>
<P>
   In particular, the Ramseys are eager to speak about their
Christian faith, said Rolf Zettersten, publisher of the Ramseys'
book, ``The Death of Innocence.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Their relationship to Christ is an element that hasn't been
explored in any of the other interviews they have done,''
Zettersten said. ``They really would like to talk to someone purely
about their faith experience and how God has sustained them through
this ordeal.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, the Ramseys have appeared on a series of
television programs. An interview with the couple also appeared in
Newsweek.
</P>
<P>
   Robison's show is the first Christian program to host the
Ramseys. But they may speak on other religious television or radio
shows, Zettersten said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until now, the Ramseys have been portrayed to the public by
the tabloids in a negative way,'' he said. ``I don't think the
Christian community understands that these are decent God-fearing
people who have a deep relationship with Christ.''
</P>
<P>
   JonBenet was found bludgeoned and strangled Dec. 26, 1996, in
the basement of the family's Boulder, Colo., home.
</P>
<P>
   A grand jury investigated the case for 13 months before
disbanding in October without indictments.
</P>
<P>
   Although no charges have been filed, the Boulder police have
said that the parents remain under an ``umbrella of suspicion.''
</P>
<P>
   The Ramseys have repeatedly said they were not involved in their
daughter's death. In their book, they present a theory that an
intruder beat and strangled JonBenet.
</P>
<P>
   This spring, the couple said they would undergo polygraph tests
if administered outside the Boulder Police Department.
</P>
<P>
   The department Monday declined an offer by the American
Polygraph Association to conduct the tests.
</P>
<P>
   Robison said he and his wife, who co-hosts the show, will not
shy away from asking the Ramseys difficult questions about
JonBenet's death.
</P>
<P>
   But the show also will offer time for prayer, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If public opinion were raising all sorts of questions about
me, I would want someone to pray for me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
