   NATIONAL GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   ALA-CHURCH-BOMBING (Birmingham, Ala.) _ Two of four suspects in
the 1963 Birmingham church bombing are indicted by state
authorities after a lenghty investigation with federal officials.
The case is the most prominent of a number of unresolved, racially
motivated killings of blacks from the civil rights era that are now
under scrutinty. Thomas Blanton Jr., a onetime member of the Ku
Klux Klan, surrendered Wednesday and Bobby Frank Cherry was
expected to turn himself in. By Kevin Sack.
</P>
<P>
   DOMESTIC-VIOLENCE (Undated) _ Confirming a long-standing trend
in crime and society, a new Justice Department study released
Wednesday shows a dramatic drop in domestic murders, particularly
the killing of black men by black women, which fell 74 percent from
1976 to 1998, as black women gained new legal protections against
domestic violence and more job opportunities outside the home. By
Fox Butterfield.
</P>
<P>
   LOS-ALAMOS-FIRE (Los Alamos, N.M.) _ A National Park Service
plan for igniting what has become the largest fire in New Mexico
history described as ``moderate'' the danger that the blaze would
escape beyond its bounds. It said any damage would likely be
confined to ``timber and private land values,'' not buildings. At
the same time, however, the plan warned that federal officials
might be underestimating the danger that the fire or any other
controlled blaze, of a sort routinely ignited by wilderness
officials, might spill beyond its intended limits. By Douglas Jehl.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-DIET-HYPERTENSION (Undated) _ A controlled study shows that
lowering sodium intake along with a high calcium diet known as DASH
is effective in combatting hypertension. By Denise Grady.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-DIOXIN-CANCER (Undated) _ In a long-awaited draft of a
report on the health effects of the pollutant dioxin, scientists at
the Environmental Protection Agency say that the chemical can cause
cancer and other adverse health effects in humans. By Gina Kolata.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-TRADE (Seattle) _ Calling trade relations with China the
work of ``13 years and three administrations,'' Gov. George W. Bush
Wednesday urged congressional Republicans and Democrats alike to
support President Clinton and vote next week to grant China
permanent trade rights. Although Bush has long supported free
trade, his address on the vast factory floor of a Boeing plant here
marked one of the very few times that he has tried publicly to
affect pending legislation in Congress. By Alison Mitchell.
</P>
