<HEADER>
A7966 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-TECH-VISAS18-1STLD-CO     05-17 0885
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-VISAS18-1STLD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TECH VISAS BILL TAKES ANOTHER STEP ALONG A TWISTING PATH
 &HT;    Eds: Rewords 2nd graf.
 &HT;    520&AMP;add. Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By MARILYN GEEWAX
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ U.S. companies would be able to hire an unlimited
number of highly skilled foreign workers under a bill the House
Judiciary Committee approved Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   But the effort to expand visas, backed by industry, President
Clinton and most members of Congress, is being complicated by
attempts to attach unrelated amendments to the popular legislation.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Clinton wants to use the legislation as a way to
grant ``amnesty'' to as many as 2 million illegal foreigners
already living in this country.
</P>
<P>
   And Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., wants to use it as a vehicle to
carry campaign finance reform.
</P>
<P>
   Such attempts to add freight to the visa locomotive is slowing
it down, much to the frustration of high-tech companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not helpful,'' said Thom Stohler, a lobbyist with the
American Electronics Association, a tech trade group.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Stohler remains hopeful that Congress will expand the
so-called H-1B visas. ``It's not going to be easy, but in the end,
we'll get a bill that increases the H-1B cap,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, it's not clear how that will happen amid all of
the political maneuvering.
</P>
<P>
   Under current law, high-tech employers can hire only 115,000
foreign workers this fiscal year using H-1B visas, which are good
for six years. The H-1B cap falls to 107,500 in 2001 and 65,000 a
year later.
</P>
<P>
   But high-tech employers say the demand is far greater for
skilled workers, such as computer programmers and engineers.
</P>
<P>
   It would seem, then, that they would be thrilled with
Wednesday's vote for a bill that would let employers hire all the
temporary foreign help they wanted.
</P>
<P>
   But the bill, sponsored by Rep. Lamar Smith, R-Texas, also would
impose new rules on businesses. For example, a company would have
to pay an H-1B worker at least $40,000 a year, and would have to
show that it has raised median salaries for all workers in the past
year. Most high-tech executives adamantly oppose such salary
requirements.
</P>
<P>
   Despite industry objections, the Judiciary Committee voted 18-11
to approve Smith's bill.
</P>
<P>
   The approval came only after committee chairman Henry Hyde,
R-Ill., joined Smith in resisting an ``amnesty'' amendment that
Democrats wanted. The amendment would have given anyone who arrived
illegally in this country before 1986 the ability to apply for
legal residency. Under current law, only illegal immigrants who
arrived before 1972 may seek legal status.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Smith bill must go to the House Rules Committee, where
it will face new challenges. There, committee chairman Rep. David
Dreier, R-Calif, has a competing visa bill backed by the high-tech
industry and numerous Democrats, such as Reps. Lloyd Doggett of
Texas and Zoe Lofgren of California.
</P>
<P>
   The Dreier bill would limit high-tech immigration to 200,000
visas a year, but would put fewer restrictions on businesses. The
Rules Committee could end up substituting the Dreier bill for the
Smith bill.
</P>
<P>
   After Wednesday's vote, Lofgren, the primary backer of amnesty,
said her amendment could yet get tacked on to Dreier's visa
legislation.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   She added that Smith's bill has gotten as far as it has only
because the GOP leadership has wanted to show deference to Smith.
But now, she said, those Republican leaders must ask themselves:
``Do they want a bill that everyone hates?''
</P>
<P>
   She predicted GOP leaders would make sure the Dreier-Lofgren
bill reaches the House floor for a vote, not the Smith measure.
</P>
<P>
   No matter how the legislation takes shape, it ultimately would
have to be reconciled with a Senate version.
</P>
<P>
   And things are complicated over on the Senate side as well.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate's version of the visa bill, sponsored by Judiciary
Committee Chairman Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, would increase H-1B visas
to 195,000 through 2002. But that bill is having trouble getting to
the floor for a vote, in part because Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz.,
wants to maintain the right to add his campaign finance bill to the
measure.
</P>
<P>
   Key Republican backers of the Hatch bill want to limit
amendments to five each for Democrats and Republicans. Such a limit
likely would preclude an unrelated measure, such as campaign
finance reform. Democrats have resisted the GOP limits, saying that
while they support consideration of the Hatch bill, they want to
preserve their right to offer any amendment to the measure.
</P>
<P>
   Without an agreement limiting amendments, GOP supporters of
expanded visas may try to get the measure moving by attaching it to
digital signatures legislation or to a bankruptcy bill.
</P>
<P>
   But Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle, D-S.D., has said he
disapproves of such maneuvers, so it's not clear how the Senate
will proceed on H-1B visas.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web:
</P>
<P>
   National Immigration Forum, www.immigrationforum.org
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Lamar Smith, R-Texas: www.house.gov/lamarsmith
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Geewax's e-mail address is marilyng(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
