<HEADER>
A7969 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-WEB-MAPS-2TAKES-N     05-17 1014
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-WEB-MAPS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDY REVEALS WEB AS LOOSELY WOVEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 By IAN AUSTEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Web idealists and online merchants like to think that the World
Wide Web is, like its name suggests, an interconnected global
bazaar of ideas and products, a place where the answers to any
question or want is only a few clicks away.
</P>
<P>
   But a sweeping new study of the Web _ the largest ever
undertaken _ paints a very different picture. The impression that
emerges is less like an elaborately interwoven community and more
like the vast bureaucracy in Kafka's ``Castle'': a mountain of
disconnected information, lost files and frustrating dead ends.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was an assumption when we started that the Web was like
a ball of spaghetti that allowed you to get from one page to
another pretty quickly,'' said Andrew Tomkins, a researcher at
IBM's Almaden Research Center in San Jose, Calif., who worked on
the study. ``This is a real surprise. It's just not what you would
have expected.''
</P>
<P>
   The study, which was presented this week at conferences in
Amsterdam, Netherlands, and Dallas, focused on Web links, the
characteristically underlined pieces of hypertext that allow users
to leap from page to page. The study looked at roughly 200 million
Web pages (about one-fifth of the estimated current Web) and the 5
billion links to and from each page.
</P>
<P>
   What the researchers found was that more often than not, links
are a trip to nowhere. ``Most of the time, it's not the case that
you can get anywhere from anywhere on the Web,'' Tomkins said.
``There's no point at all in even trying. It's a lot tougher than
we thought to get around.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the study's conclusions:
</P>
<P>
   _ Users trying to reach a specific destination using only links
will fail three-quarters of the time.
</P>
<P>
   _ Only about 28 percent of all Web sites are what the study
calls ``strongly connected'' to the rest of the Web _ sites with a
substantial number of links to and from other sites.
</P>
<P>
   _ The theory of six degrees of separation exists on the Web
except that the number is somewhat higher. It takes, on average, 16
mouse clicks to get from one strongly connected page to another.
</P>
<P>
   Links, of course, are only one tool for surfing the Web, but,
the authors argue, they are as integral to the Web _ and as popular
_ as search engines. ``The opportunity to find yourself somewhere
totally unexpected through links is a big part of the Web's
attraction,'' Tomkins said. ``The dogma is that this is what's
really made the Web into the Web instead of a big, distributed
database.''
</P>
<P>
   Raymie Stata, a researcher at Compaq and an author of the study,
agreed that ineffective links weaken the Web's appeal. ``If we
didn't have links, the Web would basically be the Lexis-Nexis
collection,'' he said, referring to a popular commercial database
of corporate news, newspaper and magazine articles and legal
decisions. ``The average person wouldn't find that a compelling
experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the frustrations of a weakly linked Web, the survey's
results are important for another reason. The Web crawlers that
search engines use to explore the Web also use links to determine
the value of a particular page. The large number of elusive or
weakly linked sites will also elude Web crawlers, meaning that
surfers who rely on search engines ``probably won't be able to
reach substantial portions of the Web,'' said Andrei Broder, a vice
president for research at the AltaVista Co. and a member of the
research group.
</P>
<P>
   Until the release of this study, which was conducted by IBM in
cooperation with the Compaq Systems Research Center and AltaVista,
most descriptions of the Web were based on fairly small samples.
Steven H. Strogatz, an applied mathematician who studies
large-scale networks and teaches in Cornell University's department
of theoretical and applied mechanics, said that those studies bring
to mind the old joke about three blind men trying to describe an
elephant. ``This study is the first suggesting what the entire
elephant really looks like,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers began with fairly modest ambitions, hoping to
compile statistical tables about links and possibly answer some
fairly obscure questions of interest only to people building search
engines. But the group had at hand some exceptionally powerful
research tools. The first was a Compaq AlphaServer 4100 computer
that had a staggering 12 gigabytes of random access memory. The
second was access to the usually closely guarded efforts of
Scooter, AltaVista's Web crawler. Normally the results of Scooter's
efforts are analyzed by AltaVista for its content. But for this
study, Tomkins said, ``we threw the words away and only looked at
the links.''
</P>
<P>
   The research group was also able to perform a trick that is
impossible for the lone Web surfer. Not only could they link
forward from a page but they could also link backward. That is,
they could analyze how many links pointed to a particular page and
determine which pages were particularly attractive link targets.
</P>
<P>
   A surprising pattern formed almost immediately. ``About half the
time, we'd follow all the links from a page and the whole thing
would peter out fairly quickly,'' Tomkins said. ``The other half of
the time, the list of links would grow and grow and eventually we'd
find 100 million other pages _ half of the whole universe.''
</P>
<P>
   But not all pages, even the ones with strong connections, were
linked in the same direction. The researchers quickly discovered,
for example, that many pages offering relatively few links to the
outside proved to be popular linked destinations from other pages.
</P>
<P>
   Out of this analysis, the researchers compiled a new map of the
Web, one that looks less like an interconnected web and more like a
bow tie. The most connected pages _ the roughly 56 million in the
center knot _ link to pages on either side as well as to one
another. These include portals like Yahoo, large corporate sites
like Microsoft's and popular news and entertainment destinations.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The pages in the knot link directly to what the study calls
``the introverts'' in the right side of the bow. But those 44
million pages do not have any links back to the center. Broder said
that there were many e-commerce sites in this wallflower group
because they frequently do not include external links on the theory
that the longer they keep shoppers trapped, the more the shoppers
will spend. Similarly, intranets _ corporate sites intended mainly
for employee use _ generally do not link outward.
</P>
<P>
   In the left side of the bow is a far more elusive group of 44
million relatively recent pages _ the newbies. They link to the
powerhouse sites in the middle. But the powerhouses, probably
because they do not know the newbies exist, do not have links back
into the left side the bow.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the bow tie are the least connected Web pages of all.
The study estimates that another 44 million pages _ the tendrils _
have links only to the newbies or the introverts and have no direct
ties to the most popular parts of the Web. Beyond the tendrils,
about 5 percent of all pages sit in total isolation, with no links
whatsoever.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seemed reasonable to assume that a fairly high mass of the
Web was connected,'' Broder said.``But this is a fascinating
picture.''
</P>
<P>
   For Web surfers, a better word might be frustrating. ``From the
point of view of a surfer, links are useful. But there's no way
that just by clicking, you're going to get to all the places you're
going to go,'' Broder said.
</P>
<P>
   So far the research group has run its experiment three times
using data from three crawls the first in May 1999 and the latest
earlier this year. That is not really enough data to predict a
trend, Broder said.
</P>
<P>
   But there has been a slight increase in the relative number of
sites in the connected core. ``Maybe everyone's original concept of
the Web will be borne out,'' Stata speculated. ``It just might be
10 years late.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-17-00 1652EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000517.0216 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 17:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7977 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-HINTERLANDS-INTER     05-17 1217
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-HINTERLANDS-INTERNET-ART-1030(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RURAL AREAS FRUSTRATED BY POOR WEB ACCESS, SCARCITY OF LOCAL DATA
ONLINE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Okla., Va., Colo., Calif., N.C., Utah, Ariz., Miss., Fla.)   (ART ADV: Photo NYT3 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.)  
 By CATHERINE GREENMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Although Debbie Wintz often surfs the Internet in the evenings,
much of that time is actually spent folding a load of clothes,
feeding the cat or tidying up the kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   Wintz, a real estate agent who lives in Pryor, Okla., about 40
miles northeast of Tulsa, uses a standard dial-up modem, connecting
through her local Internet service provider. The connection is
never very fast _ 33 kilobits per second at most, although she has
a 56K modem _ and at night it often slows to a crawl. So Wintz
occupies herself with other tasks until a Web page with a few links
and pop up messages finally reveals itself.
</P>
<P>
   Like millions of other Americans, Wintz craves a faster Internet
connection. But unlike millions of urban and suburban Americans,
Wintz has no alternative to dial-up service in Pryor, population
8,300.
</P>
<P>
   While high-speed options like cable modems and digital
subscriber line service are becoming increasingly available in
populous areas, Wintz and others in more isolated communities are
stuck in low gear, limited by the capabilities of local providers
which in turn rely on the local phone network to transmit data. For
her and other rural Americans, the much-touted promise of a
high-speed Internet seems as far off as the East or West Coast.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand that it's about profits,'' Wintz said, ``but I
feel like we're being discriminated against. How come we always
have to be last?''
</P>
<P>
   Broadband technologies like digital subscriber lines, or DSL,
and cable have been slow to reach rural America. According to a
report issued last month by the Commerce Department, 5 percent of
towns with fewer than 10,000 people have access to DSL service,
compared with more than 56 percent of cities with more than 100,000
residents. Less than 5 percent of towns with fewer than 10,000
people had cable modem service, compared with 65 percent of cities
with more than 250,000 residents. And although some people who have
tried to get high-speed access, particularly DSL, have been
frustrated by poor service and other problems, people in rural
areas would at least like to have the choice.
</P>
<P>
   The lack of high-speed connections is not the only complaint
among rural Internet users. News and information about rural areas
is often difficult to obtain online _ it can be far easier to find
the address of every coffee bar in Seattle, say, than the hours of
the local library in a small town in rural eastern Washington. And
rural residents who use national Internet service providers like
America Online or EarthLink often find themselves paying toll
charges to call their access numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're looking for free local access, you're better off
going with a small, local ISP,'' said Laura Kelso, co-founder of
Ubundle.com, a company that lets consumers customize their Internet
and telecommunications services. ``Even America Online has a lot of
areas where it's going to be a long distance call to dial up.''
Most big providers, she said, do not have the necessary Internet
connection points, known as points of presence, to accommodate
rural residents.
</P>
<P>
   But above all, slow Internet transmissions and crowded phone
networks are the biggest frustrations for many people in rural
areas.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Holton, who lives in Fort Gibson, Okla., and works in nearby
Muskogee, said he could not call his office between 8 p.m. and 10
p.m. because the phone lines in his area are tied up by young
people who are logged on to the Internet. ``The bottom line is that
the infrastructure is old and noisy,'' he said, ``and the issues to
fix it are cost and amortization of the equipment. It leaves me and
everyone else in the area just dying.''
</P>
<P>
   Holton, who uses Azalea.net, a local ISP, also has an America
Online account for e-mail, but he has to dial a number in Tulsa,
which is a long-distance charge, to gain access to the service.
</P>
<P>
   The problems of Internet access in rural areas have begun to
attract the attention of the Federal Communications Commission.
Linda Kinney, assistant chief of the common carrier bureau, said
the agency would conduct a survey this summer to determine whether
rural areas are being properly served.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the larger telephone companies say they are working to
increase local dial-up access. ``It's been a part of our strategy
to continue reaching into smaller calling areas,'' said Rich
Jeffers, a spokesman for Bell South, which covers nine southeastern
states. Jeffers said Bell South's Internet service, BellSouth.net,
is available to more than 80 percent of its customers through a
local call. ``Our goal is to get it to 100 percent,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Trish Primrose, a spokeswoman for America Online, said the
company offers consumers who cannot dial in to the service from a
local number an alternative plan in which they can sign up with a
local ISP, and connect to AOL through their ISP at a reduced rate
of $9.95 per month.
</P>
<P>
   In the last few years, many rural communities have connected to
the Internet through small, local Internet service providers that
sprang up to fill a need. In many rural areas, the local ISP is the
only access available for a toll-free call, because the larger
ISP's have opted not to invest in the installation of network
equipment in that area.
</P>
<P>
   John Nunn, for example, started Twin County Internet Access, an
ISP, in 1996, because he and his neighbors in Galax, Va., in the
southwest corner of the state, were paying long-distance charges
for access to ISP's like America Online and Netcom.
</P>
<P>
   Nunn was also frustrated by a lack of local information
available online. Nunn's ISP provided local users with links to
Virginia newspapers, and even had its own advice column, ``Ask the
Blonde,'' written by a local schoolteacher. (He has since sold the
ISP to NetAccess, a regional ISP.)
</P>
<P>
   But as broadband DSL and cable Internet access spreads to
metropolitan areas and suburbs, rural ISPs that were started to
provide basic dial-up service find that they cannot meet the demand
for faster access. Instead, they have usually been forced to wait
until their local phone network or cable company decides their
market is worth the investment.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Mendocino Community Network, an ISP in Mendocino, Calif.,
with about 5,000 customers, was built in part to foster economic
growth in the community, which is about 125 miles north of San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Mendocino Community Network provides community residents with
150 hours of local dial-up access for $19.95 per month, and it
donates ISP services to local nonprofit organizations. The ISP also
functions as an active community service, featuring local news and
events on its Web page and sending out e-newsletters from movie
theater and storeowners. But without broadband Internet access, the
community is at a disadvantage, said Rennie Innis, manager of the
network.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the biggest complaints is the slow speed of the phone
lines,'' Innis said. ``DSL or cable access would be a real gift,
because how you operate your business depends on what the
technology will allow. It's not just about faster speeds, it's
about people living where they want to live and still maintaining
an urban quality job.''
</P>
<P>
   DSL service is limited to customers who live within about five
miles of a telephone company central office, which is more of a
problem in rural areas than in cities or suburbs. But DSL providers
say new technology will help ease the distance limitations before
the end of the year. ``We'll break through those limitations, which
will justify a further reach into rural areas, from an economic
standpoint,'' said Hank Carabelli, president and chief operating
officer of (AT)Link Networks, based in Louisville, Colo., which
sells broadband services to regional ISPs and businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Some broadband providers, including New Edge Networks and
DSL.net, specialize in bringing DSL service to smaller markets
through line sharing agreements with local telephone companies and
reseller agreements with local, regional and national ISPs. And
although they are still in the testing stages, wireless
technologies like multichannel multipoint distribution services and
satellites are seen by some in the industry as effective ways to
bring high speed Internet access to rural areas without incurring
the high costs of building network infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint Broadband Wireless Group is test marketing Sprint
Broadband Direct in Phoenix, a multichannel multipoint service the
company says is 36 times faster than a regular dial-up connection.
It relies on radio transmission rather than phone or cable lines,
and works with a two-way digital transceiver installed on a rooftop
that is pointed toward a radio tower to send and receive signals.
Although the service is designed to reach people who do not have
DSL or cable access, it has a 35-mile limit, which does not help
many rural residents.
</P>
<P>
   Some people in rural areas are hopeful about satellite
technology, which does not pose the same distance limitations as
other broadband solutions. Hughes Network Systems, which has about
8.5 million subscribers on its DirectTV satellite service, said it
expects to add two-way high-speed Internet access later this year.
``We discovered we could hit a low cost for this two-way terminal,
and offer it to consumers for about the same cost as a dial up
account,'' said Paul Gaske, executive vice president of the
Consumer Division at Hughes. Pricing has not been announced.
</P>
<P>
   The two-way transmission works with an antenna that transmits
data to satellites. Uploading speeds are expected to range between
128 kilobits per second and 256 kilobits per second, but
downloading speeds are expected to average a much slower 40
kilobits per second.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of what speeds are involved, larger ISPs have
generally been slower than local and regional ISPs in building
their networks to provide rural residents with local Internet
access. There are a few larger ISPs, however, that are focusing
specifically on rural markets.
</P>
<P>
   For the past two years, for example, OneMain.com, based in
Reston, Va., has been acquiring small, local ISPs, in addition to
building Internet connection points in rural areas, in an effort
become the leading national ISP for rural communities. ``In 65
percent of the rural markets, you can't access America Online with
a local phone call,'' said Stephen E. Smith, chairman and chief
executive of One Main. ``We think there's a lot of growth potential
because they've been largely ignored.''
</P>
<P>
   OneMain.com also designs its ISP affiliates as local portals and
directs content to customers geographically through agreements with
local newspapers and merchants. ``People don't want to dial up from
Bakersfield, Calif., and read information about Roanoke, Va.,''
Smith said. ``We built our networks around geographical content,
which is what the larger ISPs can't do because they've outsourced
nationwide networks.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith said One Main has 800,000 customers, and the plan is to
provide Internet access to more than 65 markets by the end of this
year. Many of OneMain affiliates will also offer DSL access, Smith
said.
</P>
<P>
   Another ISP, OneWorldOnline.com, based in Provo, Utah, offers
potential users cash incentives to get other people in the area to
fill out forms saying they will sign up once a local connection is
established. When a local ISP affiliate is established, the
original customer will get $25 for each subscriber he signs up for
the service. ``Our rural approach has been to go and identify the
customers first, then go and put a point of presence in,'' said
David Nemelka, chief executive of OneWorldOnline.com.
</P>
<P>
   ISP Channel, a subsidiary of SoftNet Systems, a San Francisco
broadband Internet access company, is entering into partnerships
with smaller cable television operators to provide rural areas with
broadband Internet service via cable networks. Customers who sign
up with ISP Channel buy or lease a cable modem which connects to
their home cable. The customer's modem data travels to the cable
operator, where ISP Channel connects via high speed telephone lines
to the Internet. Download speeds average 500 kilobits per second,
and upload speeds average about 100 kilobits, according to ISP
Channel's president, Jonathan Marx.
</P>
<P>
   ISP Channel also provides Web building services to cable
operators who want to build and host local Web sites. ``A lot of
other ISPs have national content, but we provide local,'' said
Larry Brilliant, chief executive of SoftNet Systems, ISP Channel's
parent company. ``We've found that people really like to do
business locally and to know who they're working with.''
</P>
<P>
   Marx said ISP Channel has agreements to reach 2.4 million homes
in 22 states. It is available in parts of California, Arizona,
Mississippi and Florida. The service will not benefit rural
residents who do not already have cable service, however.
</P>
<P>
   Even if problems of low-speed access are solved, however, there
is still the problem of a lack of content geared to smaller
communities. But several companies, including Streetmail.com and
Koz.com, are working to improve the situation, creating local
content to be provided by smaller ISPs.
</P>
<P>
   Streetmail.com, based in Waltham, Mass., for example, hires
correspondents in small communities around the country and has a
central editing group at its headquarters to produce local
newsletters, which it then co-brands with the local ISP. A recent
newsletter for Cape Lookout, N.C., for example, included an opinion
poll about what the local drawbridge's hours of operation should
be.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many small ISPs have wanted this kind of thing but aren't
organized enough to create editorial content,'' said Barbara
Johnson, chief executive of StreetMail. ``We've used the Internet
to connect in all kinds of ways around the globe. We're only now
turning to connect ourselves to where we live.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
