</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-TRADE-CLINTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON NOTES NEW DANGERS TO NATIONAL SECURITY AT COAST GUARD
CEREMONY 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed. This story is
being considered for page 1.) 
(See also CHINA-TRADE, CHINA-TRADE-LOBBY) 
 By NEIL A. LEWIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW LONDON, Conn. _ Embracing a broad concept of national
security, President Clinton told the graduating class of the U.S.
Coast Guard Academy Wednesday that the world is becoming more
dangerous because of new threats from disease, terrorism and even
global warming.
</P>
<P>
   Presidents have used their annual commencement speeches before
one of the service academies to present grand visions of the
future, and Clinton in his final such address offered a view that,
while promising, encompassed menace on many fronts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The central reality of our time is that the advent of
globalization and the revolution in information technology have
magnified both the creative and destructive potential of every
individual, tribe and nation on our planet,'' he told the audience
of 5,000, which included 189 graduating cadets, a third of them
women.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also sought to link his message about the long-range
future with the imminent political question of extending trade
preferences to China, arguing that Congress should realize that
next week's vote on the issue will have deep implications for
America's security.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the biggest question marks of the 21st century is the
path China will take,'' he said. ``Will China emerge as a partner
or an adversary? Will it be a society that is opening to the world
and liberating to its people or controlling of its people and
lashing out at the world?''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton argued that if Congress votes to provide China with
permanent normal trading relations, ``It will not guarantee that
China will take the right course.'' But, he added, ``I believe a
`No' vote invites a future of dangerous confrontation and constant
insecurity.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said the larger issue for future leaders is to maintain
a balanced security strategy, one with diplomatic and economic
elements in addition to traditional military ones.
</P>
<P>
   ``Globalization is tearing down barriers and building new
networks among nations and peoples,'' he said. ``The very openness
of our borders and technology, however, also makes us vulnerable in
new ways.''
</P>
<P>
   While the internet and developments like the growth of democracy
are heartening, ``We must understand the other side of the coin as
well,'' the president said. ``The same technological advances are
making the tools of destruction deadlier, cheaper and more
available, making us more vulnerable to problems that arise half a
world away, to terror, to ethnic, racial and religious conflicts,
to weapons of mass destruction, drug trafficking and other
organized crime.''
</P>
<P>
   In cataloging some of the issues that he said should become part
of any new discussions of national security, Clinton also touched
on part of the presidential debate.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats, including Vice President Al Gore, the presumed
presidential candidate, have sought to portray Gov. George W. Bush
as mired in a narrow military vision of national security no longer
appropriate in a post-Cold War world.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, Clinton's lengthy remarks about global warming as a
security threat were a gesture of support for Gore, who has been
criticized by Republicans for his warnings about the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also accused Osama bin Laden, the Saudi expatriate
believed to be living in Afghanistan, of plotting to harm Americans
gathered for millennium celebrations. Links between bin Laden
associates and terrorist plots uncovered in Jordan and at the
U.S.-Canadian border have been widely reported, but Wednesday's
comments were the president's most extensive on the subject.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-17-00 1715EDT &QL; 
