u w BC-SELECTIVE-SERVICE-HNS     05-17 0819
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SELECTIVE-SERVICE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     DRAFT REGISTRATION NUMBERS DECLINING 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By AUSTIN ZALKIN  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Texas, Louisiana and Hawaii have the poorest rates
of compliance with the Selective Service requirement that men born
in 1980 must register for the draft, the agency reported Wednesday.
New Hampshire, Maine and North Dakota have the best rates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Men are simply not getting the word'' in many cases that they
must register, Selective Service System Director Gil Coronado said
at an agency news conference in which he released a survey on
compliance.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of last year, when every male born in 1980 was at
least 19 and should have registered with the agency, only 73
percent of those in Hawaii, 74 percent of those in Louisiana and 77
percent of those in Texas had actually done so.
</P>
<P>
   Others states with low compliance were California, Georgia,
Kentucky, Mississippi and South Carolina, all with a 79 percent
rate.
</P>
<P>
   The compliance rate was 95 percent in New Hampshire and 93
percent in Maine and North Dakota. Others with high rates were Iowa
and Nebraska at 91 percent and Minnesota at 90 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Ranking in between were such states as New York and Michigan,
with an 82 percent compliance rate, and Illinois, with 84 percent
of those born in 1980 registering.
</P>
<P>
   The Selective Service System requires that all men aged 18
through 25 residing in the United States register for a possible
draft. The agency asks young men to register within 30 days of
their 18th birthdays but accepts registrations even from
25-year-olds. It gets concerned when eligible men fail to sign up
within two years of their 18th birthday.
</P>
<P>
   Those who don't register face up to five years in jail and up to
$250,000 in fines, but since 1985 no one has been prosecuted for
failing to register.
</P>
<P>
   Non-citizens living in the United States cannot gain citizenship
if they have not registered.
</P>
<P>
   Those failing to comply with the law are also ineligible for
federal student loans and scholarships and cannot hold most federal
jobs. Many states, such as California, also refuse to give loans or
scholarships to eligible students who fail to register.
</P>
<P>
   ``The intent is to have young men understand their obligation''
to the nation, Rep. Steven Kuykendall, R-Calif., said at the news
conference. Kuykendall introduced California's non-registration
legislation when he was a state assemblyman. ``This is a need we
still have for America's defense,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Education Secretary Richard Riley said, ``The consequences of
not registering for whatever reasons, are enormous.'' Riley joined
Coronado at the news conference, where they announced the draft
agency's partnership with educational associations to urge eligible
young men to sign up.
</P>
<P>
   No one has actually been drafted since 1973 near the end of the
Vietnam War, and military service is now completely voluntary. But
Coronado said his agency must continue to register young men
because it ``preserves America's ability to conduct a fair and
equitable draft in an emergency.''
</P>
<P>
   However, he admitted that as the last draft fades into history,
Americans are losing awareness of the Selective Service.
</P>
<P>
   Agency spokesman Lewis Brodsky said it is ``difficult to know
who you're not reaching. But we suspect, based on the demographics
we've seen, that it's high school dropouts and immigrants'' who are
not registering.
</P>
<P>
   Brodsky said the agency is working with the Immigration and
</P>
<P>
   Naturalization Service as well as schools to try to get more
</P>
<P>
   immigrants to register.
</P>
<P>
   Nationwide compliance has declined one percentage point in each
of the last five years. While the compliance rate among 18- to
25-year-old men was 95 percent a decade ago, it now stands at 88
percent. Only 83 percent of men born in 1980 had registered by the
end of last year.
</P>
<P>
   In order to raise compliance, the Selective Service has produced
a video for high schools. It features Riley and actors Sean Astin,
the title character in the football movie ``Rudy,'' and Mario
Lopez, a former leading character in TV's high-school sitcom
``Saved by the Bell.''
</P>
<P>
   The agency, which is forbidden to buy ads, will continue to ask
broadcast outlets to run public service announcements. It will also
mail registration reminders to high school students.
</P>
<P>
   The agency has also introduced a program that allows
17-year-olds to register so that they are automatically added to
the draft list when they turn 18. Eligible men may also now
register online at www.sss.gov.
</P>
<P>
   Brodsky said there are now 13.5 million men aged 18 to 25 in the
Selective Service data base. Men 26 and older are not eligible for
the draft. An estimated 1.6 million men 18 to 25 have not complied
with the law, he said.
</P>
<P>
   (Austin Zalkin can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at
dart(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
