<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 17:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7994 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-POL-TICKER0518-COX     05-17 2307
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER0518-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: At least they can agree on one thing
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Against the backdrop of a gleaming new airplane, George W. Bush
urged Congress today to extend China's normal trade status as a way
to boost U.S. sales overseas and spread liberty in the communist
nation. Bush, speaking at a Boeing Co. airplane factory in Everett,
Wash., noted it was a rare moment of agreement with the Clinton
administration, which is pushing for normalization. He said
political differences should not prevent Congress from voting in
favor of the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   A SUBJECT AT THE AARP'S HEART
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore was using an address today to about 10,000 senior
citizens at the AARP ``Celebrates 2000'' biennial convention in
Orlando, Fla., to attack George W. Bush's plan to partially
privatize Social Security. Gore contrasts his proposal to bolster
the Social Security system by paying down the national debt with
George W. Bush's privatization scheme that Gore calls ``risky.''
</P>
<P>
   RONNIE WOULD HAVE WANTED IT THAT WAY
</P>
<P>
   Former first lady Nancy Reagan endorsed George W. Bush for
president today, calling him ``a candidate Ronnie would be proud
of.'' She said that Bush, whose father was Ronald Reagan's vice
president, ``is doing a fine job carrying on Ronnie's legacy,''
according to an announcement by the Bush campaign. Using one of her
husband's famous phrases, she said the younger Bush ``will help
America once more become a `shining city on a hill.' '' The
89-year-old ex-president, suffering from Alzheimer's disease, no
longer appears in public.
</P>
<P>
   HILLARY CERTAIN CANDIDATE IN UNCERTAIN RACE
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Clinton lavished praise on her husband, the president,
as she accepted the nomination of New York's Democratic state
convention to make a Senate run in her newly adopted state. The
nomination from the 352 delegates of the only first lady to run for
public office was unanimous. Still uncertain is whether Clinton's
opponent still will be Republican Rudy Giuliani, who within recent
weeks announced he has prostate cancer and is separating from his
wife. The New York City mayor's candidacy was expected to make the
Senate race a clash of political titans.
</P>
<P>
   NEW ALLIANCES IN NEW YORK
</P>
<P>
   Two and a half years remain until the 2002 election for governor
in New York, but the jockeying for position between two Democratic
hopefuls, HUD Secretary Andrew Cuomo and state Comptroller H. Carl
McCall, was on full display at the Democratic state convention in
Albany. By the night's end, there was no question that this was
McCall's crowd. He has an early, imposing lead in collecting
supporters among elected officials and party leaders and, as the
sole trustee of the state pension funds, he is a favorite of public
employee unions and retirees. And as the only black person ever
elected to statewide office in New York, he has a devoted following
among his party's minority members.
</P>
<P>
   CORPORATE WELFARE CASELOAD
</P>
<P>
   Consumer advocate Ralph Nader vowed to wage an active campaign
for president as he slammed elected officials in both parties for
subsidizing corporations. In Hartford, Conn., the Green Party
candidate called for a grass-roots movement to enact such reforms
as universal health care, public financing of campaigns and
stronger labor laws. He accused Democrats and Republicans of
catering to corporate interests and cited efforts to lure the New
England Patriots football team to Hartford and the Adriaen's
Landing riverfront development as examples. ``The program of the
Green Party is to get the rich off welfare,'' he said. Nader got 1
percent of the vote as a presidential candidate in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   MCCAIN GOING TO MICHIGAN _ BUT LATER
</P>
<P>
   John McCain will campaign in Michigan later this summer despite
strong disagreements with the state Republican Party. Spokesman
Todd Harris said McCain will visit Michigan in August or September
after the GOP Convention in Philadelphia. Harris said the visit
doesn't mean McCain has patched up his differences with the state
party. McCain canceled two events with Republican candidates in
Michigan this week after accusing the party of ignoring a delegate
selection agreement at its convention last weekend.
</P>
<P>
   THE MARKET GOES UP, THE MARKET GOES DOWN . . .
</P>
<P>
   With a twinkle in his eye, George W. Bush played a videotape of
Al Gore talking about the virtues of investing Social Security
money in the stock market. In response, Gore said he had indeed
explored the idea last year, but found ``the problems were
severe.'' And he lobbed a firecracker of his own, quoting Bush's
chief economic adviser, Lawrence Lindsey, as saying he had pulled
his money out of the market because ``I don't take any risks. I
hate losing money.'' Bush said that Gore's taped comments last year
showed that the investment idea is a good one, and Gore is only
posturing now for political gain. Gore acknowledged saying that
``over any 10-year period in American history, returns on equities
are just significantly higher than these other returns.'' He added:
``I did not support it, but there was a time when I said let's
explore this.''
</P>
<P>
   . . . AND AS USUAL, THE POORER MAKE OUT WORSE
</P>
<P>
   Trying to bolster his case against privatizing Social Security,
Al Gore's campaign is pointing to a Texas experiment that auditors
concluded was a bad deal for low-income workers and a mixed bag for
those in the middle. The experiment, created more than a decade
before George W. Bush became governor of Texas, allows three
counties to invest workers' pension money in private funds. Bush is
advocating that workers be allowed to invest part _ but unlike the
Texas program, not all _ of their Social Security payroll taxes in
the stock market. The General Accounting Office audit of the Texas
program found that workers making the most money benefit from the
experiment, while those of lower means fare worse.
</P>
<P>
   YOU MEAN POLITICIANS DON'T WANT TO GET RICH?
</P>
<P>
   Missing out on maybe millions in Wall Street's bull market ``is
not the greatest thing in the world,'' Al Gore said with a touch of
wistfulness. ``But for me it was the right decision.'' He was
explaining spokesman Chris Lehane's surprising revelation a day
earlier that Gore has no investments in the stock market.
``Twenty-four years ago when I ran for Congress, for good or ill I
made the decision ... to avoid even the appearance of any conflict
of interest on the many subjects that would come up for a vote,''
Gore said. ``Missing the bull market is not the greatest thing in
the world financially, but for me it was the right decision.'' Gore
added that his wife Tipper once owned stock in her father's
plumbing supply company, but no longer does.
</P>
<P>
   GOING INTO THE FAMILY BUSINESS
</P>
<P>
   For years, Tipper Gore teasingly, and privately, called her
``the next senator from Tennessee.'' And her father, Al Gore, said
recently that she has ``perfect pitch, or very nearly perfect
pitch'' for politics. Political daughter and granddaughter,
campaign adviser and fund-raiser Karenna Gore Schiff, heard her
father give the commencement speech, claimed her degree at Columbia
Law School, and took another step toward the family business.
Schiff's late grandfather, Albert Gore Sr., was a senator from
Tennessee. With school finished and no immediate plans for
employment, Schiff, 26, the eldest of the Gores' four children, is
expected to become more active in her father's campaign, where she
heads Gorenet, an effort to attract young voters. The vice
president dropped out of Vanderbilt Law School 24 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   POWELL READY TO BESTOW HIS AURA
</P>
<P>
   Colin Powell, the retired general with political muscle, will
visit Austin, Texas, soon for a meeting and political event with
George W. Bush. Although the meeting is still in the planning
stages, Powell is scheduled to have a private visit on May 25 with
Bush, and Bush is to sign a proclamation in support of Powell's
group, ``America's Promise, the Alliance for Youth.'' Powell, a
Republican, has said repeatedly that he's not interested in the
vice presidency and that ``political life is not for me.'' But John
McCain has said Bush, if elected, should appoint Powell secretary
of state. Powell has not ruled that out. Since retiring from the
Army in 1993, Powell has remained one of the most popular figures
in public life.
</P>
<P>
   THEY'LL NEED A BIGGER CONFERENCE ROOM
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore has assembled a large team of foreign policy advisers
whose members could form the national security nucleus of a Gore
administration. The current role of the advisory group is somewhat
nebulous, however, since Gore has never relied on outsiders for
advice on foreign policy, and the new panel has not yet contributed
much of substance to his campaign. Gore has great faith in his own
experience and instincts, and an intimate, 20-year relationship
with his national security alter ego, Leon Fuerth, through whom all
foreign policy information flows. But Gore's advisory group now
includes 25 people, many of whom are veterans of the early years of
the Clinton administration, and the list of experts is expected to
swell to include as many as 100 names over the next several weeks.
</P>
<P>
   AND NOW AS E-MAIL IS REPLACING THE MAILS . . .
</P>
<P>
   Oregon made history as ballots were counted in the nation's
first regular primary election conducted not at polling places but
by mail _ a move intended to improve turnout. Ballots were mailed
to voters' households on April 28. With the presidential
nominations already wrapped up, and no governor's race, the primary
didn't generate much heat. Oregonians have voted by mail in local
elections and special statewide elections since the early 1980s,
but this was the first all-mail ballot for a regularly scheduled
election. Two years ago, Oregonians voted to abolish the
traditional polling place in all statewide elections in favor of
the mail ballot because it's cheaper and more convenient.
</P>
<P>
   . . . LESS THAN HALF OF THE VOTERS MAIL IN
</P>
<P>
   Oregon used the vote-by-mail occasion to reject a proposition
that would have allowed the Legislature to limit how much money
people could receive in personal-injury lawsuits, and a proposed
nickel-a-gallon gasoline tax increase to pay for road repairs. The
most hotly contested race was between ``the battling Lynns'' _ two
Republicans who vied to run against Secretary of State Bill
Bradbury in November. House Speaker Lynn Snodgrass, a woman,
defeated state Rep. Lynn Lundquist, a man, 48-44 percent, with 8
percent going to a third candidate. Bradbury was unopposed for the
Democratic nomination. The secretary of state's office estimated
voter turnout at 47 percent.
</P>
<P>
   THEIR OWN PRIVATE IDAHO
</P>
<P>
   A millionaire businessman and a scorched-earth conservative
lobbyist are fighting to claim the right-wing mantle of retiring
Rep. Helen Chenoweth-Hage, the darling of the militia movement who
once claimed that black government helicopters were harassing
ranchers. Lt. Gov. Butch Otter, the businessman, says that his
guiding political philosophy is live-and-let-live and that
government should butt out of people's lives. Dennis Mansfield, the
lobbyist, believes in moral absolutes and says even limited
government has a duty to enforce them. Chenoweth-Hage, 62, admitted
before the 1998 election that she had had an affair with a married
business partner years earlier, and that God had forgiven her. The
Republican primary is Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   KENNEDY OPPOSITION COMING FROM WAY OUT THERE
</P>
<P>
   A Libertarian could be the toughest competition Sen. Edward
Kennedy (D-Mass.) faces in November. The challenge would come from
Carla Howell, a 44-year-old health care consultant who wants to
kill the federal income tax, abolish the U.S. Department of
Education, and counts marijuana smokers among her most ardent
supporters. In her 1998 run for auditor, Howell won 6 percent of
the vote, guaranteeing the party official status. By failing to
field their own candidate, the GOP has raised Howell's status from
obscure third-party candidate to Kennedy's most viable opposition.
The sole Republican still in the race, Jack E. Robinson, appears to
be falling short of the 10,000 signatures needed to get on the
ballot.
</P>
<P>
   EARLY BIRDS IN VIRGINIA
</P>
<P>
   It's a year early, but the 2001 gubernatorial race in Virginia
is already taking shape, with one self-made millionaire announcing
this week that he is stepping aside for another in the Democratic
competition. Former Rep. L.F. Payne Jr., a Charlottesville
developer who was defeated for lieutenant governor in 1997, took
himself out of the running and endorsed Mark Warner, who heads a
venture capital firm in Alexandria. The Republican nominee is
expected to be Lt. Gov. John Hager, who defeated Payne in 1997, and
Attorney General Mark Earley.
</P>
<P>
   IN NEW HAMPSHIRE, IT'S TAX-FREE OR DIE
</P>
<P>
   New Hampshire Gov. Jeanne Shaheen announced she will seek a
third two-year term, but she didn't say whether she would renew her
pledge to veto an income tax, which is seen by some state leaders,
albeit reluctantly, as the best way for the state to respond to a
court order to reform school financing. In this year's Democratic
primary, Shaheen will face state Sen. Mark Fernald, who supports a
state income tax to solve the school problem. On the Republican
side, four candidates are competing for the nomination, with mixed
views on the tax question. There is also an independent candidate.
</P>
<P>
   _ Compiled by Ernie Freda from staff and news reports.
