<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 17:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7995 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-TONYS-BLAKEMORE-$ADV2     05-17 0998
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TONYS-BLAKEMORE-$ADV21-950-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DIRECTOR WHO `MAKES IT SEEM EASY' 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Great Britain)  (For release Sun., May 21) 
 By ROBIN POGREBIN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Casually dressed in a crisp royal blue button-down
shirt on a sunny Saturday morning in the newly renovated kitchen of
his Hampstead townhouse, grinding his own coffee beans (around and
around) by hand, Michael Blakemore hardly seemed the high-powered
theater director who presided over two major Broadway hits this
season.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, in talking about the success of his two productions,
which could not be more dissimilar _ Cole Porter's light confection
``Kiss Me, Kate'' and Michael Frayn's weighty new play about
nuclear physics, ``Copenhagen'' _ Blakemore, who turns 72 next
month, sounded merely pleased that the shows managed to find their
way to Broadway within months of each other. ``It's lovely, it's
terrific,'' he said. ``A very unexpected thing to happen to me at
my age, so I'm very grateful.''
</P>
<P>
   He also seemed only mildly hopeful that each would be nominated
for a Tony Award _ which they were just a few days later. (Between
them, the productions have also won Drama Desk, Drama League, Drama
Critics' Circle and Outer Critics Circle awards.) ``It's silly to
take the awards seriously _ they're really just a means of show biz
advertising itself,'' Blakemore said, settling in with his coffee
on a couch in the home he shares with his wife, Tonya McAllin, a
stage designer, and their two teen-age girls (he also has a son,
38, from his first marriage). ``Imagine if dentists gave themselves
a Tony. It would be something like, the Tony for the Best Root
Canal in the Most Hysterical Woman Over 50.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd love to win,'' he continued (he hasn't before). ``But I am
not going to get upset if I don't _ or I shall try not to.''
</P>
<P>
   It is this low-key, unassuming quality that people who have
worked closely with Blakemore believe helps make him such a strong
director. They say he is authoritative without being strident; that
because he doesn't blow his top, other people working on his shows
don't either.
</P>
<P>
   ``He makes it seem easy,'' said Blair Brown, one of the three
actors in ``Copenhagen.'' ``He makes you feel calm and safe.''
</P>
<P>
   Given Blakemore's even keel and elegant bearing, one cannot help
wondering whether there is any mess to the man's otherwise
apparently ordered life.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a reserved man,'' said Marin Mazzie, who stars in ``Kiss
Me, Kate.'' ``He's not loud, he doesn't scream, but he has a great
energy about him. There is an intensity and a fierceness in those
eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   To understand the complexity of Blakemore, Brian Stokes
Mitchell, Mazzie's co-star, said, one need only look at the
director's body of work _ particularly this season's two
productions. ``It's miraculous that both of these came from the
same director,'' Mitchell said. ``That says more about Michael
Blakemore than anything else.''
</P>
<P>
   The British director Sir Trevor Nunn, who has known Blakemore
for years and first produced ``Copenhagen'' at the Royal National
Theater in London in 1998, said Blakemore's unflappable aura was
deliberate. ``Michael likes to disguise his passion,'' Sir Trevor
said. ``He's very passionate but he doesn't like too many people to
know it, so he goes wonderfully impenetrable, he goes sphinxlike
when you know there's a raging passion inside him.''
</P>
<P>
   Actors speak of Blakemore in respectful terms, as a father
figure, an elder statesman, a wise leader with a dry,
self-deprecating sense of humor who inspires loyalty and fondness.
``He comes just before a generation of British directors who are
starry in their own right,'' said Michael Cumpsty, who is in
``Copenhagen.'' ``He doesn't seem to have a compelling need to
exert his own ego. As a result, he commands a tremendous amount of
affection. Nobody questions his ability or authority.''
</P>
<P>
   Cumpsty said Blakemore's paternal quality resonated particularly
well with ``Copenhagen,'' which deals with the father-son
relationship between Niels Bohr, the Danish atomic physicist, and
his German pupil, Werner Heisenberg, the author of the uncertainty
principle. ``It's been a fascinating experience for me because I
don't have a close relationship with my family,'' said Cumpsty, who
plays Heisenberg.
</P>
<P>
   Blakemore had something of a strained relationship with his own
father, an eye surgeon, who was disappointed that his son flunked
out of medical school in his native Australia and became an actor.
</P>
<P>
   Before he became a director, Blakemore worked onstage for 15
years, including a season in 1959 at Stratford-on-Avon, playing
supporting roles to legends like Charles Laughton, Laurence
Olivier, Paul Robeson and Edith Evans. Ultimately, he decided he
preferred being behind the scenes. ``I was very dissatisfied,'' he
said. ``I couldn't stand being at the mercy of other people's
estimates of you.''
</P>
<P>
   What he really wanted to do, he said, was direct, but it was
almost impossible to break in because Oxford-educated directors had
a lock on London theater. When he was 37, a friend who was running
the Glasgow Citizens Theater asked him to direct three plays. He
went on to become associate director of the theater, where he
directed ``A Day in the Death of Joe Egg.'' The acclaimed play by
Peter Nichols, about bringing up a handicapped child, moved to
London and then to Broadway. ``So within 18 months of being a
director,'' Blakemore said, ``I had a show on Broadway.''
</P>
<P>
   He has since directed such Broadway shows as Frayn's
door-slamming farce ``Noises Off'' and the Cy Coleman musicals
``City of Angels'' and ``The Life.'' In Britain, he was an
associate director at the National for five years under Olivier and
then for two years under Sir Peter Hall, with whom he parted ways
over how to run the theater. He has directed 20 successful
productions in London's West End.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   Blakemore said he had a special place in his heart for ``City of
Angels,'' which opened on Broadway in 1989. ``Of all the things
I've done, I have a greater fervor on its behalf,'' he said,
``because we did it against enormous skepticism and pushed it
through.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes you get the script and it's self-evident how it
should be done,'' he added. ``But other scripts come along where
you have a contribution to make, where you know that if you hadn't
done it, it wouldn't be like it is. I had some bright ideas on
`City of Angels.''' Chief among these, Blakemore said, was the
show's screenplay-within-a-play and its scenic shifts between color
and black and white.
</P>
<P>
   Equal to his passion for directing, Blakemore said, is his
interest in writing _ a pursuit he finds more difficult but
ultimately more satisfying, because it is less ephemeral. His
novel, ``Next Season,'' based on his acting experiences, was
published by Simon &AMP; Schuster in 1968 and reissued by Applause
Books in 1995. He has also written several articles _ like the one
published in The New Yorker in 1996, ``Death Defying Director,''
about directing ``Death Defying Acts,'' a program of one-act plays
by David Mamet, Elaine May and Woody Allen, at the Variety Arts
Theater Off Broadway in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   He said he hoped to find time to finish the memoir he started 10
years ago, which describes his arrival in England in 1950. Because
it took him so long to get to it, Blakemore said he paid back his
advance to his publisher, Penguin Books.
</P>
<P>
   While Blakemore comes to a show with a clear idea of what he
wants, his collaborators say he seems to welcome their ideas, even
if they differ from his own. ``I could struggle with him,'' Cumpsty
said. ``He was amazingly generous about allowing me to test him,
allowing me fairly wide boundaries and encouraging my exploration _
even if it became contentious _ rather than forcing me to accept a
predigested solution.''
</P>
<P>
   Kathleen Marshall, who choreographed ``Kiss Me, Kate,'' said
Blakemore had an apologetic way of offering his responses to a
dance number. ``He would always preface everything by saying, `I
don't know anything about musical theater, but you might want to
think about. . . .''' she said. ``And everything he said was
useful.''
</P>
<P>
   Blakemore also seems to savor the substance of what he is
working on. He had seen the original ``Kiss Me, Kate'' and loved
it. And, having already directed six Frayn plays, he speaks of
``Copenhagen'' with the fervor of a true fan. ``The exciting thing,
and why it works with an audience in spite of being forbidding on
the page, is the human story of the rivalry and competition and
jealousy, which any member of the audience can understand,''
Blakemore said.
</P>
<P>
   Because ``Copenhagen'' is packed with intricate language, the
actors said it was the most difficult play they had ever had to
memorize. ``It's two hours and 20 minutes nonstop,'' said Philip
Bosco, the veteran stage actor who plays Bohr. ``If your
concentration falters at all, you pay the price.''
</P>
<P>
   The play depends on clarity, the actors said, and Blakemore
hammered the point home during rehearsals. ``When talking about the
science, you have got to be letter perfect,'' Bosco said. ``The
audience has to believe that you believe it; your credibility as
scientists must be beyond reproach.''
</P>
<P>
   Bosco said he was initially wary of agreeing to do
``Copenhagen,'' but Blakemore's faith in the project turned him
around. ``I realized it was something of importance, but I said, `I
don't think people are going to sit through this,''' Bosco
recalled. ``Michael said: `You must trust me. This works.' He was
absolutely right.''
</P>
<P>
   Blakemore knew that it worked because it had been successful in
London, where he originally directed an eight-month run at the
National, after which it transferred to the West End, where it is
still playing after more than a year. He also mounted a successful
production in Paris that is now touring France.
</P>
<P>
   Brown said that Blakemore only eventually came to accept the
Broadway cast's emotional approach to ``Copenhagen,'' in contrast
to the London cast's more detached delivery. ``Initially, Michael
was urging us to be cooler and more reserved,'' she said. ``And we
couldn't help it. We're a different breed.''
</P>
<P>
   Blakemore said he worried about how Broadway audiences would
receive such a production, and he added that he was surprised the
producers were willing to risk it. ``It's very heartening for
Broadway that a play of this difficulty and seriousness can fill a
Shubert theater,'' he said. ``The heroes of this undertaking are
really these American producers flying in the face of common
sense.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, the gamble looks as if it might pay off. The critics
almost uniformly had high praise for the play, which opened on
April 11 at the Royale Theater. Writing in The New York Times, Ben
Brantley called it ``the most invigorating and ingenious play of
ideas in many a year and a work of art that humanizes physics in a
way no other has done.''
</P>
<P>
   There was some reluctance of a different sort about attempting
``Kiss Me, Kate,'' which opened at the Martin Beck Theater last
fall. Mitchell, the actor, said he was initially not a great fan of
the show, and that its old-fashioned quality was unfamiliar
territory. ``I had reservations,'' he said. ``I thought the script
lacked heart.'' He said he later realized that what he thought was
missing from the text was actually already there, something that
Blakemore pointed out to him in private conversations and had
clearly known all along.
</P>
<P>
   Blakemore said he hesitated before accepting the project also,
for different reasons. ``I was a little reluctant because I'd seen
it and I'd seen it done wonderfully,'' he said. ``I wondered, `What
can I do with this that hasn't already been done?'''
</P>
<P>
   Aside from some subtle tinkering _ most notably starting the
show with the song ``Another Openin', Another Show'' and altering
one of the supporting roles, changes implemented with the help of
the playwright John Guare _ Blakemore honored the original spirit
of the show and was rewarded for it with rave reviews. Brantley
wrote in The Times: ``The director Michael Blakemore and the
choreographer Kathleen Marshall have shaped a show that is broad,
brazen, often shameless and finally irresistible.''
</P>
<P>
   On June 4, the Tony Awards will reveal whether the theater
community at large considered ``Kiss Me, Kate'' the season's best
musical revival. It has stiff competition in Susan Stroman's
staging of Meredith Willson's ``Music Man,'' which opened last
month.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, ``Copenhagen'' is facing tough contenders for best
play, including Sam Shepard's ``True West,'' Claudia Shear's
``Dirty Blonde'' and Arthur Miller's ``Ride Down Mt. Morgan.''
</P>
<P>
   Blakemore has been here before _ in 1990, when ``City of
Angels'' was up for best musical and ``Lettice and Lovage'' for
best play. He cannot help but hope things will turn out differently
this time
</P>
<P>
   Of course he would not confess as much.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm obviously delighted,'' he said when asked in a subsequent
conversation how it felt to learn of the nominations. Then added
with typical self-effacing humor, ``But I contained my excitement
and steeled myself for disappointment.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
