<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FORECAST0518-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tomorrow's technology offers much greater diversity
 &HT;    By Andrew Park
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The anti-Microsoft crowd has been preaching
diversity lately, arguing that the ``Love Bug'' virus did so much
damage because so many of us use Windows-based programs at home and
at work.
</P>
<P>
   Whether diversity in computing is necessary or not, it's
probably on its way.
</P>
<P>
   As computing continues to evolve into smaller and more powerful
forms, devices from mobile phones to kitchen appliances are
increasingly being designed to surf the Web.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think that that's a trend that's about to start to reverse
itself and we're moving toward a world of greater diversity,'' said
Eric Berg, director of strategic technology services for consulting
firm PricewaterhouseCoopers in Menlo Park, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   The rapid proliferation of non-PC computing platforms is one of
the major evolutions predicted in PricewaterhouseCoopers' latest
Technology Forecast, an annual publication that looks ahead at the
innovations that will drive business in the next couple of years.
</P>
<P>
   If you think you've heard this story before, you may be right.
</P>
<P>
   The network computer, WebTV and Internet appliances have all
been marketed as alternatives to the PC, to little impact so far.
</P>
<P>
   But because personal digital assistants and wireless phones are
simpler to use, less expensive and more mobile, it is predicted
that they will eventually surpass everything else in connecting to
the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   According to PricewaterhouseCoopers, some industry observers
believe that three-quarters of the 1 billion people connected to
the Internet by 2002 will be connected via a wireless device.
</P>
<P>
   The front end of the trend has already been seen in Europe and
Asia, where consumers have adopted wireless Internet access in
rapid fashion. At the end of 1999, 4 million people were
subscribing to a wireless Internet service from DoCoMo, Japan's
largest mobile phone carrier.
</P>
<P>
   Berg said he believes that success will eventually be replicated
in Europe and the U.S. Already companies such as Sprint PCS and
VoiceStream offer wireless Web access and other carriers are
readying their services.
</P>
<P>
   One of the crucial factors in consumers actually subscribing to
wireless Internet will be the growth of compelling applications
that work on the wireless platform _ perhaps more compelling than
the games that are popular on Japanese phones. And those
applications will have to overcome the small screens and text-only
formats that limit what can be displayed on a mobile phone,
typically 11 lines of data.
</P>
<P>
   Across Scandinavia, banks are testing a system from Austin's
Tantau Software Inc. that allows secure banking transactions over
wireless devices. Customers in Finland, Sweden and Norway an pay
bills, check balances and transfer money between accounts while
riding on the train or walking to work.
</P>
<P>
   While financial institutions in the United States will be slower
to incorporate such services, it will happen, said John Sims,
Tantau's chief executive. And eventually, Sims said, wireless
commerce will be bigger than PC-based Internet commerce.
</P>
<P>
   ``''If you look at the Internet its limited by PC people. The
numbers of people that will have access to phones and are
phone-literate will be much much bigger,'' Sims said. ``Our view is
that yes, the U.S. is six months or 12 months behind Europe, but we
don't think it's going to stay that way.''
</P>
<P>
   AgentGO.com, another Austin startup, is betting that wireless
phones will be great vehicles for personalized, targeted marketing
messages, though its first foray into that market in Austin was
slow to take hold.
</P>
<P>
   Within a year, phones will be able to handle applications that
provide information, advertising and coupons based on a user's
location.
</P>
<P>
   For example, if a user was driving by the mall and pushed a
button requesting information on nearby bargains, the phone might
respond by displaying a digital coupon for $5 off at the Gap.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ad agencies start salivating and quaking at the knees when you
start talking about this,'' said Ian Gillot, a telecommunications
analyst at International Data Corp. in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   And San Diego, Calif.'s Packet Video believes that the emergence
of broadband wireless networks that can handle video news reports,
music videos and movie previews is not far off. While Berg doesn't
think wireless video will become a reality for some time, he said
that application developers like Packet Video play a critical role
in the growth of wireless in the U.S.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always been the case that one of the most important
factors in the success of a platform has been the availability of
applications for it,'' he said. ``In order to believe that
(Internet-enabled) phones are really going to take off you've got
to believe that there are going to be services available that
people want.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
