<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Thursday, May 18, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The storm over the Plains will weaken considerably as it moves
quickly toward the middle Mississippi Valley. Heavy thunderstorms
will produce flash flooding near and just north of the path of low
pressure from Nebraska and Iowa to the central Great Lakes. Storms,
strong to locally severe, will erupt just south of the path of the
low in the middle Mississippi and northern Ohio Valleys.
</P>
<P>
   A surge of very warm, humid air into the Northeast will produce
clouds and showers, particularly in New England. An advancing cold
front in the St. Lawrence Valley will trigger a line of
thunderstorms, perhaps with large hail from central New York to
Maine.
</P>
<P>
   The South will be sultry with sunshine and isolated thunder.
Residual cold, moist air in the eastern Rockies will keep clouds
and showers over some of Colorado and New Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: THE LID
</P>
<P>
   With regard to severe weather, the atmosphere often attacks
where defenses are the weakest. On Wednesday, a wedge of very warm
air several thousand feet aloft invaded the southern Plains from
Mexico. With readings aloft as high as the upper 80s, the resulting
temperature inversion acted like a heavy lid, preventing moist air
rising from the ground from penetrating into the upper atmosphere
and igniting severe thunderstorms. But farther over the central
Plains, near the cooler and thus weaker edge of the lid,
forecasters focused their attention and prepared for severe
weather.
</P>
</TEXT>
