<HEADLINE>
&HT;     BUSH'S CLAIMS ON FEDERAL PENSIONS ARE NEWS TO U.S. WORKERS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     A News Analysis 
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DAN FREEDMAN  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Claims by Texas Gov. George W. Bush that 1.3
million federal workers have an advantage in retirement income over
private-sector workers is at odds with what federal workers do _
and do not _ get when they retire.
</P>
<P>
   Bush points to the federal retirement plan when he is arguing
that the Social Security program should include individual
investment accounts so that workers could invest in the stock and
bond market and earn a higher rate of return.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every federal worker is offered a personal account to help
improve their retirement _ 1.3 million have these accounts,'' Bush
said Monday when he announced his Social Security privatization
proposal in Rancho Cucamonga, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   If the stock and bond market is good enough for federal workers,
why does Vice President Al Gore ``object to young Americans doing
the same?'' Bush said. Gore, his expected opponent in the
presidential election this November, opposes privatization of
Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, most of the nation's 2.4 million federal civilian
workers pay Social Security payroll taxes and will collect Social
Security when they retire, just like virtually everyone in the U.S.
workforce of 141.2 million. The federal employees also are eligible
for the federal pension plan.
</P>
<P>
   Some 1.3 million _ 86.2 percent of the federal workforce _ also
participate in the government's Thrift Savings Plan, which is
similar to 401(k) plans covering 32 million workers in the private
sector.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's spokesman insists that the governor wasn't claiming that
federal employees have a privatized version of Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   Ari Fleischer, the spokesman, said Bush isn't asserting that
federal workers use private investment accounts in place of Social
Security. Instead, Fleischer said, Bush was referring to the
government's Thrift Savings Plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gov. Bush is talking about what all Americans can enjoy, what
we all can learn from federal workers' success with thrift
savings,'' said Fleischer. ``The point is if it's OK for all these
people to invest in markets, have control over their investments
and watch their nest egg grow, why is it not alright for all young
people to do the same?''
</P>
<P>
   In 401(k) plans, which are designed to supplement Social
Security income, employees and employers chip in to the account.
Employees have a choice of investments and the yields are tax-free
until retirement.
</P>
<P>
   Approximately 14 percent of eligible federal workers have chosen
not to participate in the thrift plans.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of privatized Social Security accounts counter that
they have nothing against stock market investments, as long as it's
not done through Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our major point is not to say that we shouldn't have other
ways to encourage savings and investments,'' said Roger Hickey,
co-chair of liberal Campaign for America's Future. ``Rather, we
should not cannibalize Social Security in order to allow people to
invest in this stock market scheme.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here _ optional material follows.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Some 39 percent of the total federal workforce are in the
government's pre-1984 retirement plan, which, under law, makes them
ineligible to participate in Social Security. Their retirement
package consists of their pensions and their own thrift plan, which
does not draw a matching government contribution.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Freedman can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address dan(at)hearstdc.com).
</P>
</TEXT>
