<SLUG> BC-ARCHBISHOP-GAYS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     ARCHBISHOP SAYS HE WAS MISQUOTED ABOUT GAY PARADE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By CAROL NESS  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ When in Rome, don't do as San Francisco does,
especially when it comes to gay pride events.
</P>
<P>
   That is the drumbeat out of Italy's ancient capital these days,
and among those reportedly pounding it out is the Catholic
Archbishop of San Francisco, William Levada.
</P>
<P>
   Levada's comments, reported May 11 in the popular Roman
newspaper Il Messaggero, added to intense Vatican pressure to
cancel or postpone World Pride Roma 2000, planned for July 1-9,
because it coincides with the Catholic Church's millennial Jubilee
celebration.
</P>
<P>
   The comments, which Levada claimed Tuesday were reported
inaccurately, raised hackles in San Francisco's gay community,
particularly over what were seen as the archbishop's gross
distortions of pride events here.
</P>
<P>
   In particular, the Vatican is targeting plans for a gay march
July 8 through central Rome nowhere near the papal palace. It's the
most visible event during a week of political and cultural events
that have been planned since 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't believe it. It's not possible for this to happen
during the Jubilee. I'm amazed that the government would permit
it,'' Levada is quoted as telling fellow prelates over dinner at a
cardinal's home. ``Obviously the Italian authorities have no idea
what might happen. This kind of demonstration is not
controllable.''
</P>
<P>
   An English translation of the article, widely circulated via
e-mail by World Pride 2000 organizers, including Deborah
Oakley-Melville of San Francisco, says Levada told his peers that
San Francisco's annual gay parade goes right by St. Mary's
Cathedral, a fact that critics point out is untrue. Many marchers
wear costumes caricaturing Catholic nuns and priests, gesture
obscenely toward the church and strip in public, he reportedly
said.
</P>
<P>
   Il Messaggero has been crusading against World Pride 2000 since
the Vatican launched its opposition in January, and has frequently
used distorted depictions of San Francisco's gay community,
Oakley-Melville said.
</P>
<P>
   In San Francisco, Levada said in a statement Tuesday the
comments attributed to him in February contained inaccuracies and
were made at a private dinner in Rome attended by a journalist who
did not take notes.
</P>
<P>
   ``When asked in conversation about the annual Gay Pride Parade
in San Francisco, I said that I personally had not seen it, because
I usually go out of town,'' Levada said in the statement. ``I said
that there were reports of public displays of nudity that were
offensive and displays of costumes that ridicule Catholic leaders
and members of religious orders.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the journalist at the dinner took no notes, but when the
journalist later asked for a formal interview, Levada said he
declined.
</P>
<P>
   Fernando Orlandi, an Italian-born gay San Franciscan, read the
Il Messaggero article over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just didn't like what the archbishop said because he was
lying or at least stretching the truth about gay pride in San
Francisco. I don't think it's right,'' said Orlandi, who is going
to World Pride 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The march does not go near the San Francisco cathedral, he said.
And ``maybe 10 or 20'' people among 500,000 attending dress in the
exaggerated nun garb of the Sisters of Perpetual Indulgence, the
charitable drag troupe who raised Levada's ire last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
