<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POPPIES0518-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Poppies keep perennial beds abloom
 &HT;    By Diana Blowers
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ When tulips and dogwoods are finishing up their
spring show, poppies come along to fill the void.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this time of year, when there're not a lot of perennials
blooming, they just add a lot of color,'' said Aileen Holliday.
</P>
<P>
   There are about 70 species of poppies, but the most common
perennial in area gardens is P. orientale, the Oriental poppy.
</P>
<P>
   The plants are 2 to 3 feet high, and the blooms are maybe 3 or 4
inches across so you can see them from a good distance,'' Holliday
said.
</P>
<P>
   The large blooms, featuring petals like crepe paper, with dark
centers, emerge from coarse, hairy, toothed leaves. The leaves tend
to look prickly, like a thistle, but they are soft. The orange
varieties are the most familiar, but today many cultivars are
available in shades of red, pink and white.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you plant them, they really require hardly any care. . .
. But they are a little hard to get started,'' she said. ``If you
buy them in the pot, you don't want to disturb the roots very much
at all because they don't like to be transplanted or moved, except
after they've started to die down.''
</P>
<P>
   The only bad feature of the poppy, according to Holliday, is
that as soon as it is done blooming it starts to die down, becoming
completely dormant by July.
</P>
<P>
   In late summer the Oriental poppy produces a small amount of new
growth. This basal rosette, a tuft of small leaves, will remain
green throughout the winter and can be divided in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   Oriental poppies can be difficult to get rid of once their roots
are established, but another perennial, the Iceland poppy, is
considered a short-lived perennial and is best treated as a
biennial. This poppy, P. nudicaule, usually grows to 1 to 2 feet
tall with flowers about 3 inches wide.
</P>
<P>
   There are also annual poppies. One of the most familiar is P.
rhoeas, known as field poppy, corn poppy or Shirley poppy. These
have 3- to 4-inch blooms on hairy stems and come in shades ranging
from white, pink and red. The seed pods are often used in dried
floral arrangements.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have some Shirley poppies, and they will reseed every year.
They will bloom for a good part of the summer if you keep them
deadheaded,'' Holliday said.
</P>
<P>
   _ Common name: Poppy.
</P>
<P>
   _ Genus: Papaver (pa-PAVE-er).
</P>
<P>
   _ Family: Papaveraceae (poppy).
</P>
<P>
   _ Plant type: Perennials and annuals.
</P>
<P>
   _ Size: 1 to 2 feet wide, 1 to 3 feet tall.
</P>
<P>
   _ Bloom season: Early summer.
</P>
<P>
   _ Color: Red, pink, orange, salmon and white.
</P>
<P>
   _ Light: Sunny.
</P>
<P>
   _ Soil: Well drained, moist.
</P>
<P>
   _ Fertilizer: 5-10-5.
</P>
<P>
   _ Pests: Aphids.
</P>
<P>
   _ Diseases: Fungal wilts, downy mildew.
</P>
<P>
   _ Some that grow here: P. orientale (Oriental poppy), P.
nudicaule (Iceland poppy), P. rhoeas (Shirley poppy, corn poppy,
field poppy).
</P>
<P>
   _ Propagation: Seed, division.
</P>
<P>
   _ Uses: Beds, borders and cut flowers.
</P>
<P>
   _ Special note: Keep moist during growing period, but perennial
poppies like to be dry when dormant. Poppies don't like to have
their roots disturbed, so transplant with care and plant seeds
where the plants are to grow when possible. Oriental poppies can be
invasive when roots get established.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
