<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 17:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8012 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-ENCRYPTION-ART-2T     05-17 1265
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-ENCRYPTION-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SECRECY FOR EVERYONE, AS ENCRYPTION GOES TO MARKET 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
(EDS: Spelling of Wil in graf 12 is correct. A list of some privacy
services is at end of article.) 
(ART ADV: Photo NYT2 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By LISA GUERNSEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Austin Hill has become skilled at speaking for those hard-core
computer programmers who spend their time making sure that no one _
not hackers nor marketers nor government investigators _ can pull
aside the curtains cloaking their electronic domains. As president
of Zero-Knowledge Systems, which builds privacy software, Hill has
spoken at conferences around North America, espousing the credo
that a person's online movements are no one else's business.
</P>
<P>
   So when he stood up last month at the Computers, Freedom and
Privacy Conference in Toronto to kick off a low-budget ritual known
as the Big Brother Awards, he was relaxed and smiling. Standing on
a makeshift platform in a crowded lobby, he joked that his company
had spent a million dollars to sponsor the event.
</P>
<P>
   Then he covered his mouth with an expression of mock horror and
said, ``I hope our VCs didn't hear that.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a telling moment. The mention of the million dollars was
obviously a joke, but the reference to venture capitalists was not.
Zero-Knowledge does indeed have a band of VCs helping to bankroll
its operations; it has received as much as $37 million in financing
since October.
</P>
<P>
   Just five years ago, it seemed like a programmer's dream to
think of making big money from cryptography, the field in which
programs are developed to hide e-mail, shield online identities and
lock up files. But today, abbreviations like VC and IPO, for
initial public offering, are becoming as much a part of the
language of secrecy as are three-letter federal agencies and
code-locking keys.
</P>
<P>
   Privacy issues are becoming public concerns as Internet privacy
is increasingly turning up on the evening news. More people are
becoming aware of the vulnerability of their computer files because
of things like hard-drive excavations by private and public
investigators, who routinely dig through e-mail and other archives
once thought to be far beyond the reach of any curious eyes.
</P>
<P>
   And entrepreneurs are betting that as soon as mainstream
computer users realize their vulnerability, they will rush to sign
up for privacy products.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's becoming big business,'' said Lance Cottrell, president
of Anonymizer.com, one of the first privacy services to let people
surf the Web anonymously. ``I think that in the next five years,
the majority of Internet users will be using some form of
privacy-enhancing technology.''
</P>
<P>
   Companies are being started by all sorts of people, whether they
have a background in computer code or not. But it is the emergence
of high-profile, high-budget companies like Zero-Knowledge that
signals a shift in the culture of cryptography.
</P>
<P>
   The quintessential encryption expert thrives in a shadowy world,
writing code in obscurity for days on end. Several of these experts
are suspicious of outsiders, including the press. Many of them
champion individualism, deride big companies and dismiss anyone
toeing the corporate line. The more familiar they are with the
hacker underground, the more status they have.
</P>
<P>
   But now their software may just be something the masses will
want. At the same time that the federal government is loosening
restrictions on encryption technologies, building commercial
products and cashing in on them (either through sales or
advertising revenue) has become a viable option. And that means
meshing two seemingly opposed ways of life, one based on
advertising and corporate profits and another that prides itself on
its insider culture and was founded on fervent beliefs in
individual rights.
</P>
<P>
   For example, one of the companies, Hush Communications, got its
start on the Caribbean island of Anguilla to avoid federal
regulations on exporting encryption. Its co-founder, Cliff
Blatzley, has a pierced tongue and has been known to work on
projects for days without sleep. Another company, PrivacyX, was
started by a Canadian named Wil Boucher, who describes himself as
``a bit on the paranoid side.'' He once had a Mohawk haircut that
was dyed green and was 6 inches high.
</P>
<P>
   And Zero-Knowledge's chief scientist is Ian Goldberg, a computer
expert who is well known among early Internet users for finding
security holes in popular software. He goes by the title head
cypherpunk (a label embraced by libertarian computer programmers)
and leads a research group he calls the Evil Geniuses.
</P>
<P>
   Such irreverence may seem odd for people trying to attract
mainstream users to their cause, but it may work to their
advantage, just as a mass audience can be attracted to
alternative-rock bands. The more these privacy companies snub
corporate conventions, the more they may appear to be true
crusaders against intrusive marketing companies.
</P>
<P>
   But can these companies maintain their underground image while
engaging in the promotion that is required of most new tech
companies these days? Can they continue to uphold the values of
straight talk and consumer trust while focusing on profits and
advertisers? Or, like some rock bands, will they be accused of
selling out?
</P>
<P>
   Hill says they can. He equates his privacy company with
start-ups like Netscape that emerged from Silicon Valley before
dot-coms began to rule the Internet. It was a different time, he
said. ``It wasn't about, How do I get my new Porsche?'' Hill said.
``There was a culture about, How do we change the world?''
</P>
<P>
   Changing the world by building privacy software has not always
been a simple business proposition. It used to require years of
legal fights for the right to market the technology at all. Just
ask Philip R. Zimmermann. In 1991, Zimmermann created a system
called Pretty Good Privacy, which was distributed on the Internet
and subsequently drew the ire of the U.S. government.
</P>
<P>
   PGP, as the system is now known, was designed to keep the
contents of e-mail messages secret to everyone except their
intended recipients. The technology is based on public-key
cryptography, a technique that requires two related keys for
messages to be opened. In simple terms, one key is used to lock the
message, and the other is used to unlock it.
</P>
<P>
   In reality, however, the system is much more sophisticated. PGP
was considered so strong an encryption program that the U.S.
government was considering whether to classify it as a munition
that was not allowed outside the country. By 1993, the code behind
PGP had been posted on the Internet. Although Zimmermann maintained
that he was not the person who posted it, he came under
investigation by the U.S. attorney's office in San Jose, Calif.,
for possible prosecution for violating export laws. Federal
officials argued that terrorists and other criminals could use the
system to keep their plans secret, even from intelligence agencies.
</P>
<P>
   After three years, the government decided to drop the
investigation. In the meantime, PGP had become the encryption
program of choice among longtime Internet users and technical
wizards. It had also started to be adopted by people living under
oppressive governments in countries where speaking freely in an
unprotected e-mail message could mean a death sentence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today,'' Zimmermann said, ``PGP is used by every human rights
organization in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
