<P>
   TAIWAN-HITECH _ TAIPEI _ Fred Chiou earned a Ph.D. at Georgia
Tech and spent 15 years working in Atlanta. Twelve days before
Taiwan's March presidential election, he returned to the land of
his birth. But politics wasn't the attraction. Chiou came back to
do what more and more people in Taiwan are doing these days: Make
money by exploiting cutting-edge technology. A hundred miles away,
the communist government of mainland China is threatening war
against what it sees as a renegade province with a new government
that could veer dangerously toward a declaration of independence.
But, despite the elections that are bringing a dramatic shift in
power, most people in Taiwan still hope for business as usual.
Business with a capital B. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
