<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EARLY-FRONTPAGE-NYT </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Thursday, May 18 Page 1. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The NYT News Service Night
Supervisor is Ned Kilkelly (888-346-9867).
</P>
<P>
   SIERRA-LEONE (Freetown, Sierra Leone) _ Sierra Leone's rebel
leader Foday Sankoh, who vanished nine days ago during a violent
confrontation outside his Freetown house, was captured Wednesday by
pro-government soldiers. By Norimitsu Onishi.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-TRADE (Washington) _ China trade legislation received the
endorsement Wednesday of four previously undecided Democrats in
Congress, indicating that the White House and congressional
supporters may be less than 10 votes shy of the number needed for
passage. By Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT14.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-TRADE (Seattle) _ Calling trade relations with China the
work of ``13 years and three administrations,'' Gov. George W. Bush
on Wednesday urged congressional Republicans and Democrats alike to
support President Clinton and vote next week to grant China
permanent trade rights. Although Bush has long supported free
trade, his address on the vast factory floor of a Boeing plant here
marked one of the very few times that he has tried publicly to
affect pending legislation in Congress. By Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   ALA-CHURCH-BOMBING (Birmingham, Ala.) _ Two of four suspects in
the 1963 Birmingham church bombing are indicted by state
authorities after a lenghty investigation with federal officials.
The case is the most prominent of a number of unresolved, racially
motivated killings of blacks from the civil rights era that are now
under scrutinty. Thomas Blanton Jr., a onetime member of the Ku
Klux Klan, surrendered Wednesday and Bobby Frank Cherry was
expected to turn himself in. By Kevin Sack.
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT6.
</P>
<P>
   YUGOSLAVIA-MEDIA (Belgrade, Yugoslavia) _ In a dramatic
challenge to the democratic opposition, the Yugoslav government on
Wednesday seized ownership and control of the main opposition
television station, Belgrade's Studio B, which it accused of
advocating an uprising against the authorities. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   INDIAN-SCHOOLS (Macy, Neb.) _ Even in a nation used to hearing
stories about battered public schools, those in Indian country
stand out. Last year, the average student here at the Omaha Nation
Public School scored in the 15th percentile on national
standardized tests, and almost half scored below the 10th
percentile. Less than half the students in grades 3 through 12 came
to take the test. And while this year's graduating class of nine is
twice as big as those of a few years ago, it represents only a
third of the 27 students enrolled in that class in ninth grade. The
obstacles the Omaha Nation School wrestles with are echoed in
Indian schools around the country. On average, between 36 percent
and 51 percent of Indian students drop out of high school,
according to the American Indian College Fund, the largest dropout
rate of any ethnic group. Only about 17 percent of high school
graduates go to college, and most do not finish. Now, the white
house and others are staring to go after this problem. By Pam
Belluck.
</P>
</TEXT>
