<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL (i) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   LEONE-CAPTURE (Johannesburg) _ Rebel leader is shot, captured,
stripped, and paraded through a cheering Sierra Leone capital
before being taken into British custody. By Kurt Shillinger. 900
words.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-OLIGARCHS (Moscow) _ Putin administration is taking shape
with confirmation of his prime minister and a surprise decision to
keep the prosecutor. Analysts see both as signs that President
Vladimyr Putin has no interest in bringing down the oligarchs or
challenging their power. By Brian Whitmore. 750 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON (w) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-TRADE (Washington) _ In the first tests of congressional
sentiment on the issue, two key committees give advocates of
expanded U.S. trade with China a bigger-than-expected boost heading
into next week's climactic House vote on granting permanent normal
trade relations to Beijing. By Susan Milligan. 1100 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL (a) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-BINLADEN (New London, Conn.) _ In a commencement address
at the US Coast Guard Academy in New London, President Clinton
accuses the terror network of Saudi fugitive Osama bin Laden of
plotting to harm Americans at millennium celebrations. By Ann
Scales. 900 words.
</P>
<P>
   TOBACCO-CHILDREN (Washington) _ The Massachusetts antitobacco
chief releases a study showing that cigarette makers, despite
promises, are targeting kids more than ever in ads. By Bob Hohler.
1200 words.
</P>
<P>
   RESEARCHERS-CONFLICT (Undated) _ The new editor of the New
England Journal of Medicine and the outgoing editor are divided on
one of the most sensitive issues in medicine: Should scientists
personally profit from companies whose products they research? By
Richard A. Knox. 1000 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL (f) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   LYCOS-WETHERELL (Boston) _ No one has more reason to be pleased
with the Terra-Lycos deal than David Wetherell of CMGI. The biggest
investor in Lycos, Wetherell and CMGI helped kill the USA Networks
deal last year because they weren't pleased with the price. With
this deal, CMGI's 16 million shares of Lycos are worth a $1.5
billion. By Peter Howe. 800 words.
</P>
