<HEADLINE>
FOR RELEASE: SUN., JUNE 4, 2000. 
 HOME IMPROVEMENT QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS
</HEADLINE>
  By BERNARD GLADSTONE 
 Includes illustration. 
 Copyright 2000 Bernard Gladstone 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: I want to install a ceiling fan in my kitchen in place of the
ceiling light.
</P>
<P>
   The outlet box for this lighting fixture is simply nailed to the
side of a joist, and I have been told that the mounting of this box
is not strong enough to support a ceiling fan.
</P>
<P>
   Also, I want the fan to be mounted in a different location that
is between the joists, not right against or under the joist.
</P>
<P>
   I can only work from below because there is a second floor above
this room.
</P>
<P>
   How can I install a bracket or box that will support a ceiling
fan without having to tear out much of the ceiling?
</P>
<P>
   A: You can work from below through a hole no bigger than the
existing outlet box by installing a special adjustable metal brace
or bar that is made for this purpose. It is designed to fit between
the joists.
</P>
<P>
   Slide one end of the bar up through the hole, then tip it to a
horizontal position when it is above the ceiling.
</P>
<P>
   Position it so the non-adjustable leg presses against the side
of one joist, then rotate the shaft at the other end to expand the
brace until the spikes at that end dig into the wood and the brace
is wedged firmly between the two joists. The bottom of the box
should be flush with the bottom of the joists.
</P>
<P>
   You can then proceed with installing and hanging the fan from
the metal outlet box according to the directions supplied with the
fan.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Our downstairs shower changes from a normal temperature to
very hot while it is use.
</P>
<P>
   A plumber told us he thought this was because the pipes are old
and need replacing. Yet this problem does not occur in our upstairs
shower where the pipes are just as old.
</P>
<P>
   Do you think the plumber is right?
</P>
<P>
   A: It could be, but doesn't seem likely. Chances are the
temperature changes when someone flushes a toilet or turns on the
dishwasher or clothes washer in another part of the house while the
shower is in use.
</P>
<P>
   This would be a particular problem if the water pressure in the
house is lower than it should be.
</P>
<P>
   It's possible the problem would be solved by installing a
temperature control faucet instead of the existing one, but this
could be an expensive solution.
</P>
<P>
   Q: My patio is covered with flagstones that sit in a bed of sand
and very fine gravel.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the sand and fine gravel comes up between the flagstones
after a very heavy rainstorm.
</P>
<P>
   How can I prevent this?
</P>
<P>
   A: Apparently there was no mortar used under or between the
flagstones so there is nothing to keep the sand from being washed
away where it is not covered.
</P>
<P>
   Unless you are prepared to scrape out the joints between the
flagstones and then apply a mortar or cement of some kind I'm
afraid the only solution is to take up all the flagstones and then
reset them with no spaces in between.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Our house has a fireplace that has one problem. Every time we
light a fire a small amount of smoke comes out into the room. After
a few minutes the fire gets going and the smoking problem
disappears.
</P>
<P>
   Is there any way to avoid this smoke coming into the room at the
beginning?
</P>
<P>
   A: Make sure the damper is fully open before you light the fire.
</P>
<P>
   Then before you light it, roll up a wad of newspaper and light
the end of this while holding it inside the fireplace and up near
the damper.
</P>
<P>
   Allow this to burn until it's almost gone, then drop it on top
of the logs and light the fire as usual.
</P>
<P>
   The burning paper will have warmed the air going up the chimney
and thus start the draft going to prevent that early smoking
problem.
</P>
<P>
   Questions about home-repair problems should be addressed to
Bernard Gladstone, care of The New York Times Syndication Sales
Corp., 122 E. 42nd St., New York, N.Y. 10168. Questions of general
interest will be answered in this column; Mr. Gladstone regrets
that unpublished letters cannot be answered individually.
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: Drawing captioned ``STEEL POINTS GRIP JOISTS'' goes with
this column.
</P>
<P>
   CAPTION: Adjustable metal bar can be wedged between joists to
properly support an outlet box for a ceiling fan.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
