<HEADER>
A8047 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-MESSIAH-GAME-NYT &LR;      05-17 1169
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-MESSIAH-GAME-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE WEIRD SCIENCE OF ANGELIC POSSESSION 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
(Eds.: Game notes at end of review.) 
 By JOE HUTSKO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's a new kid in town, and he's not like the macho,
muscle-bound heros brandishing brazen attitudes and big guns in
games like Quake III and Unreal Tournament. His name is Bob, and
he's the cute little cherub starring in Messiah, a new 3-D action
game from Interplay.
</P>
<P>
   The world that Bob is sent from heaven to save is a distressed
one. The apocalypse has come, and those who have survived it are
none too happy or friendly. Outfitted only in diapers and a cuddly
layer of baby fat, Bob explores a realm that includes gorgeously
rendered burned-out alleys, Byzantine factories and processing
plants where the main ingredient is all too human.
</P>
<P>
   Despite appearances, Bob is one of the mightiest heroes to hit
the gaming scene in a long time. His secret weapon is possession:
He can take over anyone's body, usually the bodies of those who can
get him access to the next level of the game through a special key,
a code or sheer firepower.
</P>
<P>
   The choice of hosts is crucial. Guards, for instance, can open
only some doors, while lab technicians have special skills needed
to operate certain machinery. Maintenance workers _ by far the
funniest of the bunch, they wear baggy jeans and utter niceties
like ``Hey, little fella'' and ``Well, I'll be'' _ wield
blowtorches, used for repairing faulty elevators.
</P>
<P>
   The game player has a third-person point of view, following the
actions of Bob as if floating over his shoulder (or over the
shoulder of whatever body he inhabits). Getting Bob into the body
of any of the characters takes stealth and good aim. In most cases,
Bob's best tactic is to sneak up behind the soon-to-be host, then
make a flying leap to land square between the shoulder blades.
</P>
<P>
   If successful, Bob's possession of the host will take place
without anyone's noticing. That may seem more than a little fishy
since the excruciatingly all-consuming act occurs with a startling
flash of pyrotechnics and gasping sounds that go a long way to
indicate the unpleasant role the host must now play. It's hard to
believe that anyone nearby wouldn't run in horror. Still, in this
game's weird science, stealth begets a kind of invisibility and the
safety it offers.
</P>
<P>
   A translucent halo floats above the host's head _ handy in
heated firepower situations when it is sometimes hard to tell just
which soldier you're playing. Once the shooting starts, both fellow
soldiers and the rebels they're fighting, whose allegiance you'll
switch to and possess in the dank underbellies of the havoc-racked
futurescape, will turn on you and blast away, once they see Bob pop
out of a deceased body. Bob must then quickly fly into another,
playing this form of human-host pinball as many times as necessary
until the last man or woman standing is the one you will continue
with. For a while, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   That's because Bob will sometimes have no more use for his host
and will need to escape it so he can run around barefoot or duck
under stuck doorways. Or, more enthralling, he may rise to a higher
place by using his angelic wings, which he beats with a
whoosh-whoosh sound and which grow more powerful as the game
progresses.
</P>
<P>
   But depossession has its nasty side effects. A few moments after
Bob springs from the host's head with fireworks, the soldiers, and
at times even the gentler inhabitants, will attack Bob. Sometimes
the attacks are with firepower or fists, and sometimes they come
with swift kicks punctuated by curses and taunts like ``take that''
or ``little punk.''
</P>
<P>
   One strategy for depossession involves having Bob stand his host
in a corner and then abandon the body, sneaking to safety before
the host has time to turn around and spot him. An even better
tactic is to abandon the body with a swan dive off a high ledge.
That lets Bob flap backward to safety while the useless host falls
to its death with a bone-smashing thud.
</P>
<P>
   With all its profanity and often graphic violence, Messiah isn't
for the faint-hearted. The explicit religious references (Bob is
supposed to be acting on the orders of God to restore order to the
world) might also offend some players. Bob's selection of unseemly
hosts even lands him in a lustful red-light district known as Sex
City. Once there, he will get into the tormented hearts, burned-out
minds and scantily clad bodies of prostitutes, a transvestite and
eventually a particularly unhygienic pimp.
</P>
<P>
   Think ``Bladerunner'' meets ``Dogma,'' and you will begin to
understand the feeling Messiah is trying to evoke. Players who stay
in the game through the first few levels discover that the voice
that is bellowing orders at Bob with a rising tone of menace
belongs not to God but to an imposter. Hint: Hell won't be freezing
over anytime soon as long as it's under this bad guy's watch. And
it's up to Bob to stop the masquerader in an extremely challenging,
mischievous, apocalyptic showdown ending that comes far too soon.
</P>
<P>
   In its short in-store life, Messiah has had a history of
technical problems, including lockups and quirks and
incompatibilities with certain video and sound cards.
</P>
<P>
   Players and would-be players passionately vent these gripes and
others in news groups and on the official Messiah Web page. My
version didn't play any of the accompanying music tracks by the
rock band Fear Factory, which Interplay made a big deal of
promoting during the game's much-delayed development, which took
more than two years. Other than that, Messiah played fine on my
computer, running under Windows 2000 Professional no less, which
isn't exactly touted as being game-friendly.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the company posted the latest patch to correct many
of the game's errors, I had already reached the open-ended ending,
which finds Bob tired, alone, wandering and wondering where
everyone has gone. He calls out: ``Hello? Dad? I'm ready to come to
heaven.'' It's a poignant moment.
</P>
<P>
   Conflicts aside, Bob is an engaging character, vulnerable and
sympathetic. He even elicits a weird sort of affection as he draws
out his finger and utters an earnest ``bang'' to desperate effect,
finishing with a little blow on his finger as though it were a
smoking gun, his lower lip pushed out in defiance as his attackers
swarm and ultimately overtake him. Thank goodness the Save Game
feature lets you back up to your last safe point to try another
tactic.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, Messiah transcends much of the usual senseless
carnage that describes most first-person shooter games. For gaming
mortals equipped with fast computers and 3-D video cards capable of
running the game with no hang-ups, Bob's role in taking on the
presumed Almighty is mighty entertaining. But for those unlucky
souls whose systems can't accommodate Messiah, heaven will have to
wait.
</P>
<P>
   GAME NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   Messiah, from Interplay; recommended for Windows 95 and 98; $45;
ages 17 and older.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
