u e BC-TV-CBS-SEASON-NYT &LR;      05-17 0609
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-CBS-SEASON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CBS ADDS COMEDIES, AIMING MIDLER AT `MILLIONAIRE' 
</HEADLINE>
   By BILL CARTER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a week in which all the networks are announcing their new
fall television lineups, CBS is the first to take the bold step of
predicting flat out that it has a hit series on its hands.
</P>
<P>
   It's ``The Bette Show,'' a new comedy starring Bette Midler, and
CBS is demonstrating its ultimate faith in it by scheduling it on
Wednesday at 8 p.m., where it will challenge the ABC juggernaut
``Who Wants To Be a Millionaire.''
</P>
<P>
   CBS executives called it the best comedy they have developed in
years. It had better be, because it will lead off CBS' Wednesday
night lineup against ``Millionaire'' and will shelter another new
comedy, ``Welcome to New York,'' under its wing. The executives
said they were trying to expand the store of comedies because CBS
really has only one night, Monday, on which comedies have worked.
So CBS is adding three.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Bette Show'' will get the most attention because it is
Midler's first attempt at a television series. Essentially, she
plays a fictionalized version of herself, an entertainer who keeps
her household in turmoil, including a professor husband and a
13-year-old daughter trying to escape her mother's outsize image.
She also has a manager and an accompanist: Midler is expected to
sing every week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Welcome to New York'' stars Christine Baranski as a producer
of a morning television show in New York. The show hires a green
weatherman from Indiana played by the stand-up comedian Jim
Gaffigan.
</P>
<P>
   The network's third new comedy gets the best spot on the CBS
schedule, Monday nights at 8:30 between ``King of Queens'' and
``Everybody Loves Raymond.'' It is ``Yes, Dear,'' a show about two
couples whose life styles differ widely, especially when it comes
to raising children. The show stars Mike O'Malley, who failed
spectacularly with a comedy for NBC last season.
</P>
<P>
   CBS' four new dramas are headed by a show that few took
seriously when it was first proposed: a remake of the classic
series ``The Fugitive.'' It is basically the same as the one that
set ratings records in the 1960s with David Janssen and then became
a hit film starring Harrison Ford. It now stars Tim Daly as Dr.
Richard Kimble, who escapes execution and hunts for the one-armed
man he believes killed his wife. One switch is that his pursuer,
Lt. Gerard, is an African-American with his own personal baggage.
He is played by Mykelti Williamson.
</P>
<P>
   ``CSI,'' another crime drama, is about a criminal investigation
unit that uses forensic science to solve crimes in Las Vegas. It
stars William Petersen and Marg Helgenberger. A third
crime-oriented drama, ``The District,'' stars Craig T. Nelson as a
police commissioner in Washington. Finally there is ``That's
Life,'' a family drama about a 30-year-old woman who returns to
college. It stars Heather Paige Kent and Ellen Burstyn.
</P>
<P>
   CBS is dropping ``Early Edition,'' ``Ladies Man,'' ``Cosby,''
``Martial Law'' and ``Now and Again.'' It has also juggled the time
periods of its three Thursday night shows.
</P>
<P>
   Here is the new CBS schedule:
</P>
<P>
   MONDAY: `Kings of Queens,'' ``Yes, Dear,'' ``Everybody Loves
Raymond,'' ``Becker,'' ``Family Law.''
</P>
<P>
   TUESDAY: ``JAG,'' ``60 Minutes II,'' ``Judging Amy.''
</P>
<P>
   WEDNESDAY: ``The Bette Show,'' ``Welcome to New York,'' movies.
</P>
<P>
   THURSDAY: ``48 Hours,'' ``City of Angels,'' ``Diagnosis
Murder.''
</P>
<P>
   FRIDAY: ``The Fugitive,'' ``CSI'' ``Nash Bridges.''
</P>
<P>
   SATURDAY: ``That's Life,'' ``Walker, Texas Ranger,'' ``The
District.''
</P>
<P>
   SUNDAY: ``60 Minutes,'' ``Touched By an Angel,'' movies.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
