<HEADER>
A8054 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-JAPAN-POLITICS-NYT &LR;      05-17 0708
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAPAN'S FINANCE MINISTER DENIES BRIBERY CHARGES
</HEADLINE>
  By STEPHANIE STROM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Finance Minister Kiichi Miyazawa on Tuesday denied
charges that when he was prime minister he bribed a politician for
his silence.
</P>
<P>
   The politician, Kishiro Nakamura, who served as construction
minister from 1992 to 1993, said in court on Monday that Miyazawa
handed him a paper bag containing 3 million yen, or roughly $27,000
at current exchange rates, in cash when he visited the prime
minister's residence in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Nakamura said Miyazawa did not say what the money was for, but
he assumed it was to silence his opposition to government efforts
at the time to increase fines for violating Japanese antitrust
laws. At the time, he was serving as the acting chairman of the
ruling party council that was studying reform of the antitrust
laws.
</P>
<P>
   Nakamura also said in court that he believed he was later given
the construction portfolio _ a powerful cabinet position because of
the vast sums of taxpayer money Japan spends on public works
projects _ because the ruling Liberal Democratic Party hoped to
keep the bribe secret. Nakamura, a member of the Lower House of
Parliament since 1976, served in the cabinet during Miyazawa's
tenure as prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   His testimony came during hearings in an appellate court, where
Nakamura is contesting a lower court conviction on charges that he
accepted 10 million yen in another bribery case.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Miyazawa said the accusations were unfounded. ``I
have no memory at all'' of the activities Nakamura described,
Miyazawa said. He characterized the charges as ``wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   By the standards of Japanese political scandals, this one is
minor. But Miyazawa's international stature is such that any hint
that his tenure as finance minister may soon come to an end has the
potential to upset financial markets. Indeed, the yen's fall
against the dollar in early trading Tuesday was attributed in part
to the brewing scandal.
</P>
<P>
   But Miyazawa has already told some ruling party officials that
he wants to leave his post at the Finance Ministry sometime after
the upcoming election, which is widely expected to be called for
June 25, according to party insiders who asked not to be
identified. A finance ministry spokesman said he did not know the
minister's plans for the future.
</P>
<P>
   Miyazawa, 80, relinquished control of the party faction he
controlled in December 1998, and he has asked to run for a
proportionally elected seat in the next election rather than a
directly elected seat, a sign many regard as his desire to take a
more marginal role in government and political affairs.
</P>
<P>
   He has thus far refused to say anything publicly about his
plans, perhaps in deference to the concerns party elders have that
his departure could further complicate Japan's role in the Okinawa
summit meeting of world leaders scheduled for late July. Miyazawa,
who has developed strong ties to U.S. leaders since serving as a
translator during the American occupation of Japan after World War
II, is considered the man in Japan best able to keep the subtly
tense economic relationship between the two countries from erupting
into contentiousness.
</P>
<P>
   He has been the one constant figure of authority in a country
that changes its prime ministers almost as frequently as Italy.
President Clinton, for example, has dealt with seven different
Japanese prime ministers during his presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Miyazawa is also the cabinet minister that has most sought to
call a halt to the vast public spending that underpins Japan's
deficit, which has risen to levels that are unparalleled globally
and historically. And he was pivotal in arranging a bailout package
for the Japanese banks in 1997, when the financial system was
teetering on the brink of disaster.
</P>
<P>
   This is not the first time Miyazawa has found himself embroiled
in a bribery scandal. He resigned as finance minister in 1988 after
being implicated in a scheme by the Recruit Co. to buy political
influence.
</P>
<P>
   And some still remember him as one of the chief architects of
the ``bubble'' economy that defined Japan in the 1980s and became
the root of the problems it has suffered for the last decade.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-17-00 1815EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
