<DOCNO> NYT20000517.0256 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 18:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8056 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-HUNTS-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT     05-17 1070
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HUNTS-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`HUNTS IN DREAMS': PUCKISH RAMBLINGS IN A MIDSUMMER WEEKEND 
</HEADLINE>
   (Editors: Publication notes appear at end of review.)  
 By RICHARD EDER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   How incompetent at reality the characters are in Tom Drury's
beguiling novel _ beguiling and itself not 100 percent
reality-competent. A common enough thing, this, in an age when
reality can seem to float and a brightly attuned young writer may
not feel authorized to assert it.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the only truly competent character in the book is
Micah, a little boy. But then in childhood, where the mind needs
straying room to accommodate growth (an infant's skull bones drift
for the same reason), it is essential sometimes to see things
askew. In that respect, competence at reality lies in being
incompetent at it.
</P>
<P>
   Micah is the youngest member of the Darling family, residents of
a Midwestern farm town. Like Charles, his father; Joan, his mother;
and his stepsister Lyris, he spends a long summer weekend
wandering. Even in the most traditionally settled American
heartland life is an unmoored thing, ``Hunts in Dreams'' suggests.
The title sketches the theme.
</P>
<P>
   The four Darlings amble through something resembling separate
fugue states; so do the other people in the book. Sunny, funny and
lurching into disconcert, the fugues are musical as well as
dismaying, their zigzags the best attempt the characters can make
at straight lines.
</P>
<P>
   Charles, the local plumber, pursues a well-meaning principle of
order without knowing how to go about it. He makes a series of
far-fetched efforts to recover a fine old shotgun his stepfather
once gave to the town minister. The minister's widow hung it over
her fireplace and refused to sell it to Charles, who finds it
demeaning that a thoroughbred weapon should be reduced to an
ornament.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile Joan, convinced that their marriage has gone dead,
packs to attend an animal-rights convention in a nearby city,
hoping to find romance and change her life. A vague suspicion
prompts Charles to the antiromance precaution of emptying her
makeup kit and substituting walnuts. Joan and the lover she
acquires _ a smitten doctor neighbor who has followed her to the
city _ nibble the walnuts to go with the vodka from her hotel
room's minibar.
</P>
<P>
   Lyris, a teen-ager, has only joined the Darlings recently. An
unmarried actress at the time of her daughter's birth, Joan had
left her at an orphanage; later Lyris lived with four successive
sets of foster parents. When explosives were found in the home of
the last set (Lyris scorched her jeans while ironing them and the
smoke alerted the authorities), Joan was traced.
</P>
<P>
   Though welcomed into her family, Lyris is insecure; on the same
night that Joan goes off and Charles is breaking into the
gun-widow's house (the widow smashes him in the nose with a heavy
coat hanger and gives him a cold compress for the blood), she takes
a ride with Follard, an unbalanced young man. When she nervously
asks to go home, his answer is all the creepier for its fashionable
blur of text and reality:
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I would take you, but the car's out of gas. Or it's
thrown a rod, or the key's in the trunk, or there is no car. This
is another story that I'm telling now, and this one is true. He
wanted to take her home but could not, and therefore, with nothing
better to do. . . . You see where I'm going.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Micah, deposited at his grandmother's so Charles can go
burglarizing, he is unable to sleep. He ventures out in his pajamas
and makes a dreamlike peregrination through the town's deserted
streets.
</P>
<P>
   It is one of a number of lovely passages stretched between
lyrical and cockeyed that give a Puck-like air to Drury's midsummer
night's dream-hunt (even to its subliminal ``what fools these
mortals be''). When Lyris manages to get away from Follard by
jumping into the river and taking to the dark woods, she removes
her wet socks under the gaze of an owl in a nearby tree. She
resumes her flight: ``Soon the owl overtook her, flying low beneath
the branches with one of her socks snagged in its talons. Its body
hung like a weight from the yoke of its wings.''
</P>
<P>
   Misdirections abound, though most come out all right. Follard's
later evil efforts, for instance, are frustrated by his pure
incompetence. Drury is tender toward his characters (like many of
his contemporaries, he uses an absurdist black light, but in his
case the result is shade more than darkness). Meaning well, they
occasionally manage to do well.
</P>
<P>
   There is a lovely sequence in which, with some difficulty,
Charles gets Micah the pet goat he longs for. An old farmer advises
about the diet: separate buckets of oats, lamb feed and sunflower
seed. To a child, suddenly, it is the newfound joy of the world's
specifics: ``Many buckets, and one with black sunflower seeds . . .
The future was taking shape before Micah's eyes and it was good.''
</P>
<P>
   Joan's wandering is sensitively handled for a while. Her tryst
with the doctor _ a figure of at least equal zaniness and
misdirection _ is blissful and comically vague. When they stroll
out together in the early morning, the walk seems more real to her
than the love-making. ``Now what do we do?'' she wonders. ``We have
no present.'' She continues her fugue alone; and here, in a series
of incidents I would have to call toylike, Drury falls into some
arch contrivance.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, he avoids it. ``Hunts in Dreams'' is just short of
allegory, but the characters have a comic innocence that persuades
us quite a way into even their more far-fetched ventures. The
Darlings' struggles to find a balance in an unmoored world carry
some real eloquence. ``Sometimes I feel like whatever I'm supposed
to be is tacked to the back wall of the universe and moving away
from me at the speed of light,'' Joan complains, uniting the
contemporary states of physics and feelings.
</P>
<P>
   Carrying on with physics a moment to suggest the problem with
this perceptive and captivating book: the characters are convincing
in the postmodern wooziness with which they feel and think, most of
all about their own lives. These float touchingly, but Drury cannot
or does not choose to get them to tread hard enough for a reality
that is more than conceptual. They do fine as wave; not so well as
particle.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `HUNTS IN DREAMS'
</P>
<P>
   By Tom Drury
</P>
<P>
   200 pages. Houghton Mifflin. $22.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
