<SLUG> BC-CIR-PANTY-RAIDER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CD-ROM GAME `PANTY RAIDER' DRAWS RANGE OF PROTESTS 
</HEADLINE>
   By BONNIE ROTHMAN MORRIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The scheduled release on Saturday of a new CD-ROM game, ``Panty
Raider: From Here to Immaturity,'' has drawn protests from a wide
range of organizations: groups on the Christian right, national
advocacy groups for women and girls, and a group of hard-core
gamers. Many of them are using phone calls, e-mail, letters and
even prayer in an effort to halt the distribution of the game.
</P>
<P>
   The object of the game is for the player to strip cartoon
supermodels down to their underwear, take their photographs and
deliver the photos to three sex-starved aliens before the aliens
blow up the earth in ``hormone-driven anger.''
</P>
<P>
   To accomplish that goal, the player uses pickup lines supplied
by the game, clothes-dissolving goop and bait, like a lunch of tiny
breath mints and credit cards, which a press release says ``no
self-respecting supermodel can resist.'' Created by Hypnotix for
Simon &AMP; Schuster Interactive, the game was rated M by the
Entertainment Software Review board, indicating that the game is
aimed at adults.
</P>
<P>
   But Carlton Kendrick, a family therapist in Boston, said adults
were not the intended audience. ``Anybody who hasn't been
lobotomized knows that this game is not being geared toward mature
teens or grown-ups,'' said Kendrick, a consultant for the
FamilyEducation Network, which operates a group of Web sites and
issued a statement calling for Simon &AMP; Schuster to halt the game's
release. ``This is aimed at pubescent little boys who are trying to
sneak onto Web sites and see porn.''
</P>
<P>
   The protests seem to have been sparked by Dads and Daughters, a
national group based in Duluth, Minn., whose mission is to urge
fathers to help their daughters develop self-esteem without regard
to how they look. The group took up the cause against ``Panty
Raider'' and asked its members to send letters of protest.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Kelly, founder of the group, said the protest had ``gotten
the biggest response on any actions we've done.'' Kelly said the
game treated women as objects and made fun of anorexia. He said it
sent the message that ``I'm a male, I have sex on my mind _ if I
don't get it, I'm going to kill somebody.''
</P>
<P>
   Groups like the National Center for Policy Research for Women
and Families and the Center for Health and Gender Equity have also
denounced the game as offensive. The American Family Association
has asked members to pray that Viacom, the parent company of Simon
&AMP; Schuster, will choose not to release the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``This game is not for kids at all,'' said Peter Binazeski, a
spokesman for Simon &AMP; Schuster Interactive. ``It is for mature
adults only and is being marketed accordingly.'' He described the
problem of the product's getting in the hands of children as ``a
retail issue,'' and added, ``I think a parent is the one who should
be there watching.'' Binazeski said that he had received only five
letters protesting the game's release but that many e-mail messages
had been sent to the company's ``Panty Raider'' Web site.
</P>
<P>
   ``Protest letters outweigh support 60-40,'' he said. ``We've
gotten quite a few e-mails from people saying it's hysterical.''
</P>
<P>
   Some adult male gamers are not thrilled either. ``Please don't
accuse us of not getting the joke of `Panty Raider' or of being
politically correct zealots,'' Chris Kramer wrote in an article for
DailyRadar.com about the game's release. ``We're as PC as `Panty
Raider' is funny: not at all.'' He called the premise of the game
``heinously stupid.''
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Kay, senior editor of MyVideoGames.com, said that even
though the premise of the game was ``unusually dumb,'' calls for
censoring it were even more worrisome.
</P>
<P>
   Kay said the game's list price, $19.99, indicated that even
Simon &AMP; Schuster Interactive did not consider ``Panty Raider'' much
of a game. Most high-profile games sell for $40 and up, he said, so
the low price indicates that ``Panty Raider'' may be headed
``straight for the bargain bins.''
</P>
<P>
   Binazeski explained the price by saying, ``It's considered a
casual game, not a game you'd play for hours and hours, and it's
priced accordingly.''
</P>
</TEXT>
