<HEADER>
A8059 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-BOOK-TALK-NYT &LR;      05-17 1103
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-TALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOOK TALK: `FLAGS OF OUR FATHERS' _ RUN IT UP, SEE WHO SALUTES 
</HEADLINE>
   (Editors: in reference to ``M.A.S.H,'' replace points with
asterisks) 
By MARTIN ARNOLD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``No one wants to read a book about old men weeping
into the telephone.''
</P>
<P>
   This was perhaps the harshest of 27 rejections that a particular
book proposal received when it was offered around in New York in
1997 and 1998. But there were 26 others, representing nearly all of
the most esteemed publishers in the country. They were just as
unyieldingly dense, if not quite as nasty, when it came to
evaluating the project's possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   It was, as it turned out, one of those fantastical enormities in
judgment, as unprophetic as it was ridiculous, that engulfs the
industry periodically, like the coming of the locust. For the book
dismissed with such general brio by publishing's best and brightest
has become the surprise runaway nonfiction best seller of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   It is ``Flags of Our Fathers,'' the story of the six young men
who raised a flag on Iwo Jima and who, by accident, became forever
part of the iconic frieze of what the book's authors call ``The
Photograph.'' Written by James Bradley, son of one of the
flag-raisers, with Ron Powers, the book (from Bantam) will be No. 3
on The New York Times nonfiction best-seller list on Sunday and
will rise to No. 2 the following week. It had an initial printing
of 60,000 when it went on sale May 2. There are now 270,000 in
print.
</P>
<P>
   So why was it so soundly and roundly rejected? The acquisition
of a book is mostly a subjective decision, often involving nothing
more than personal taste, but of course there are other factors.
Was the proposal submitted by the writer and the agent compelling?
Will the finished product deliver on the promise of that proposal?
Will it be too hard to get the manuscript in publishable shape?
Will it be a good book? Will anybody buy it? (Certainly it is true
that most books celebrating the 50th anniversary of the end of
World War II went unread.)
</P>
<P>
   But there is another, maybe even subliminal reason. Most of
today's book editors and publishers were culturally formed by the
1960s and '70s and seem to suffer that Manhattan-West Coast
ambivalence toward, if not aversion to, things military. As one
publisher said: ``There's a snobbishness about book people. They
aren't attracted intellectually to stories about soldiers. They are
seen as Middle America books, which is still a hard sell to
editors. Even editors who come from Middle America like to forget
that.'' (Give a publisher Tom Clancy, and see how he overcomes this
allergy.)
</P>
<P>
   The movie ``Saving Private Ryan'' began to change that
antagonism for soldiering, but ``Flags'' was offered around before
the movie.
</P>
<P>
   Now, ``Flags'' is not the first hugely successful book that was
hideously rejected, although most of them were fiction works.
Twenty-three publishers rejected the first Dr. Seuss book, and John
Grisham had trouble getting sold. Seventeen didn't want Irving
Stone's ``Lust for Life.'' Twenty-two said no to Richard Hooker's
``M.A.S.H,'' and 18 disdained ``Jonathan Livingston Seagull'' by
Richard Bach. Laurence Peter's ``Peter Principle'' failed to entice
16 publishers, and Thor Heyerdahl's true tale of crossing the
Pacific on a raft, ``Kon-Tiki,'' simply wasn't exciting enough for
20 of them.
</P>
<P>
   Little comfort to the authors and agents for ``Flags'' back in
1998. A number of the rejects suggested, in the words of one, that
``nobody saw a particularly big market'' for the work. Indeed, one
prominent editor and one publisher known for his literary smarts
each thought that ``Flags'' would make a dandy magazine article,
but forget it as a book. In a manuscript that was really all about
the personal stories of six individuals, one editor, speaking for
himself and five colleagues, wrote that the biggest problem ``was
trying to figure out how to present the personal stories.''
</P>
<P>
   It isn't my intent to embarrass anyone, so I am leaving the
blameworthy nameless. And to be fair, the book's proposal underwent
changes when Powers was brought in as the writer, and the project
was given to two new agents, Frank Weinmann and Jim Hornfischer,
but nonetheless one would have thought that some smart editor
somewhere would have seen its potential.
</P>
<P>
   Well, one finally did. She was Katie Hall, then 30, an unwarlike
editor at Bantam, who grew up in Indiana and graduated from DePauw
University and who actually didn't think of it as a war book at
all, or even a ``boy'' book. She recalled: ``You had to see beyond
the battle of Iwo Jima. It was the back story that counted, six
boys who grew up in the '30s and who came together from all parts
of small-town America, and did this by accident. We could tell a
story about what it was like to be a kid in the '30s. There's a big
America between the coasts.''
</P>
<P>
   As Hall, now a senior editor, tells it: ``Perhaps it wasn't that
clearly shown in the proposal, but it was so obvious immediately. I
walked into Irwyn's,'' that's Irwyn Applebaum, publisher of the
Bantam Dell Publishing Group, ``and said, `There's a beautiful back
story here.' And he got it immediately and said, `Let's go for
it.''' And they did, for an advance of only $75,000. Hall says that
perhaps her Indiana roots helped her ``see'' the book in the
proposal. On the other hand, Applebaum grew up in Queens.
</P>
<P>
   Quite naturally, Bradley and Powers are thrilled with Hall.
``Before she came along,'' Bradley said, ``I was used to very
literate people sitting down and composing a letter telling me what
an idiot I am. You know the title of the book that was in my mind
was `Mothers and Sons,' so I was glad to have a female editor.''
</P>
<P>
   Powers was equally impressed. ``She understood military history
and was interested in having a salable product,'' he said. ``But
she was also interested in a strong narrative. I give her a lot of
credit for our success.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Flags'' is apparently destined to become one of those great
word-of-mouth best sellers. Everyone I know who has read it, myself
included, has urged it on friends. Will it start a trend, since
publishers, like moviemakers, seem slavish at times to trends? Most
likely.
</P>
<P>
   Probably ``Flags'' has been helped by Tom Brokaw's two best
sellers, ``The Greatest Generation'' and ``The Greatest Generation
Speaks'' (both from Random House), the latter a collection of
letters by people who fought in World War II. But one wonders: If
those books had not been proposed by a celebrity, would anyone have
published them?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
