<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BUSH'S SOCIAL SECURITY PLAN 'STOCK MARKET ROULETTE,' GORE CLAIMS
 &HT;    720&AMP;add. Moving in (w) Washington and (p) politics categories.
 &HT;    By LARRY LIPMAN
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORLANDO, Fla. _ Gov. George W. Bush's plan to partially
privatize the federal retirement system would ``take security out
of Social Security'' and ask people to ``play stock market
roulette,'' Vice President Al Gore warned seniors Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to about 8,000 delegates at the biennial AARP
convention, Gore said the Texas governor's recent statements about
reforming Social Security have raised numerous questions about the
program's future.
</P>
<P>
   He called for a debate on Social Security and Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can we really settle for so many unanswered questions on an
issue as important as Social Security?'' Gore asked. ``He deserves
a chance to fill in the blanks on his plan.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore, who was accompanied here by his 87-year-old mother,
Pauline, called Social Security _ which covers 44 million Americans
with retirement, disability and survivors benefits _ ``the greatest
act of social policy in the entire history of the United States of
America.''
</P>
<P>
   He warned that Bush's proposal could be a first step toward full
privatization of the program.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could see the end of Social Security as we know it,'' Gore
said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush campaign spokesman Ari Fleischer said there were no plans
to replace Social Security with a fully privatized system. Instead,
he said Bush's plan would ``save and strengthen Social Security and
have money available for people in addition to Social Security.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, the presumptive Republican presidential nominee, declined
invitations to appear at the convention either in person or on
video, said AARP Executive Director Horace Deets.
</P>
<P>
   Deets noted that Bush was the only presidential candidate of
either party to fail to appear at AARP-sponsored candidate forums
in Iowa, New Hampshire, South Carolina and Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't say they are snubbing us. ... They just haven't
accepted a number of invitations, and it's kind of hard to
understand why,'' Deets said.
</P>
<P>
   Fleischer said scheduling problems prevented the Texas governor
from attending the convention. Bush was campaigning in Washington
state.
</P>
<P>
   In a written statement, Bush said Gore ``is willing to try and
scare the elderly and frighten people.
</P>
<P>
   ``My job as the president is to assure Congress that I will
spend the capital necessary to get something done and lay out the
framework for reform,'' Bush said. ``This is an issue that shows
the vice president is mired in the past and my campaign is willing
to think about the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Fleischer scoffed at Gore's call for a debate on Social
Security, commenting that Gore has issued 68 challenges for debates
with Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be no shortage of opportunity for debates,''
Fleischer said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore used his speech to question Bush's statements this week on
Social Security. Although Bush has not offered a detailed plan, he
said he wants younger workers to have the option of investing a
portion of the 12.4 percent payroll tax paid by workers and
employers in private accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said such a plan would be unfair because it would not
provide guaranteed benefits to all retirees, ``and you shouldn't
have to foot the bill for those who do play and lose.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore received a warm reception for his Social Security comments,
but received the loudest applause when he said he would work to
ensure that doctors make medical decisions without interference
from health maintenance organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Minna Wilensky, an AARP member from West Palm Beach, Fla., said
Gore ``hit the correct note with me.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe in investing in the stock market. I'm a
Depression kid and I don't forget what happened in 1929 and 1930,''
Wilensky said, adding that Social Security has ``given us a base
for the prosperity of this country.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Holden, another AARP member from West Palm Beach, said he
strongly believes people should be encouraged to invest in the
stock market as part of their retirement income planning, ``but
there should be a portion of our retirement income that is
guaranteed, and that would be from the government.''
</P>
<P>
   George Puca, an AARP member from Atlanta, said, ``I think, for
the most part, he (Gore) was right. Back in 1932 when the New Deal
started, every American working man and woman was made a promise,
and the United States government ought to keep its promise. Gore's
plan is more realistic than the other plan.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   James Dunham, 65, a retired district fire chief from Dayton,
Ohio, said Gore ``kicked butt today.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said the right things for the people here and in the
nation. You don't put all of that money into stocks and bonds,
because there are some people who will make some bad decisions and
some people who will make good decisions,'' Dunham said.
</P>
<P>
   Although AARP, formerly the American Association of Retired
