<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 18:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8065 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-POPE-BIRTHDAY-NYT &LR;      05-17 1272
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POPE-BIRTHDAY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BIRTHDAY PRESENT FROM THE `MAESTRO' TO HIS `HOLINESS' 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn., Poland, France, Spain, Britain and Israel)   By ALESSANDRA STANLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ Popes do not make a big deal of their birthdays. John
Paul II usually celebrates his by holding a private lunch for close
aides.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, however, he turns 80, a milestone that falls in a
Holy Year of the Roman Catholic Church, and the Vatican has
prepared a daylong religious and musical extravaganza.
</P>
<P>
   The archbishop of Paris, Cardinal Jean-Marie Lustiger, who is
well aware of the pope's preference for low-key birthdays, dryly
described the Vatican's fevered party-planning as a ``cardinals'
plot.''
</P>
<P>
   But among the chief conspirators is Gilbert Levine, a Jewish
Brooklyn-born conductor who is so comfortable inside the Vatican
that he refers to audiences with the pope as ``going upstairs.''
</P>
<P>
   Levine said he would ``go upstairs'' with his wife and two sons
for a private, relaxing audience with the pope on Friday. His
younger son plays chess, and Levine said he would take along a
chessboard in case the pope wants to test his skills against his
8-year-old's.
</P>
<P>
   But first, on Thursday evening inside the Vatican's vast Paul VI
concert hall, Levine is planning to conduct the London Philharmonic
Orchestra and Chorus and guest soloists in Haydn's ``Creation'' to
honor the pope.
</P>
<P>
   It will be Levine's third Vatican concert and the first at which
he will wear a small red-and-gold button on his lapel, an insignia
of the Equestrian Order of St. Gregory the Great, a papal
knighthood bestowed on Levine in December 1994, a few months after
he conducted a papal concert in the Vatican in memory of the
Holocaust. The concert was a watershed event that Levine helped
plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was my suggestion that the pope attend a concert for the
Holocaust organized by the Jewish community,'' Levine said in an
interview, recalling another private meeting with the pope
``upstairs.'' He added: ``But the pope said, `No, I want this to be
a papal concert.' That's the way he is: if an idea is compelling,
he makes it his own.''
</P>
<P>
   Few popes in history could have credibly claimed Jewish friends.
But John Paul II, who grew up alongside Jews in Wadowice, Poland,
before World War II, remains close to some survivors of the
Holocaust, including a boyhood friend, Jerzy Kluger, who moved to
Rome after the war and operates as a kind of backdoor emissary
between the pope and Polish and American Jews. Levine is a more
recent acquaintance, but his eagerness to put his music at the
service of the pope has forged a friendship between the two very
different men.
</P>
<P>
   John Paul II has made Jewish-Christian rapprochement a hallmark
of his papacy, an odyssey of reconciliation that began when he
visited Auschwitz in 1979 and culminated in his whispered prayer at
the Western Wall in Jerusalem during his Holy Land pilgrimage in
March.
</P>
<P>
   Levine, whose grandparents were immigrants from Poland, became
the conductor and musical director of the Cracow Philharmonic in
December 1987 when Poland was still under Communist rule. He was a
Jew taking on a prominent artistic position in a city whose Jewish
residents had been all but wiped out by the Holocaust. That unusual
role made him an ideal agent of the pope's larger goal of
Jewish-Christian reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
   The Cracow conductor came to the pope's attention through
Cardinal Franciszek Macharski, who succeeded John Paul II as
archbishop of Cracow, and sent a Newsweek article about Levine to
the pope. ``If you are coming from Cracow,'' Macharski joked in an
interview, ``it is very easy to meet with the Holy Father.''
</P>
<P>
   In February 1988 Levine was summoned to the Vatican. He recalled
that the pope greeted him by saying, ``How are you treating my
orchestra?'' and added, ``More importantly, how are they treating
you?''
</P>
<P>
   Later that year he was invited to bring the Cracow orchestra to
the Vatican for a concert to celebrate the 10th anniversary of John
Paul II's pontificate. On that visit he also brought his
mother-in-law, an Auschwitz survivor, to meet the pope. ``He really
made her understand powerfully, as a nonsurvivor, how much he
understood,'' Levine said.
</P>
<P>
   Levine, 52, who studied at Juilliard and Yale and worked with
Nadia Boulanger in Paris and Sir Georg Solti in London, has never
shed his down-to-earth Brooklyn manner. Blunt and exuberant, he
does not seem like an obvious papal confidante. For one thing, his
eagerness to talk about his relationship with the pope and repeat
papal remarks raises some eyebrows in a milieu where self-promotion
is more expertly veiled. As one Vatican official put it, ``People
who really are his friends never say it.''
</P>
<P>
   But Levine, well versed in Vatican protocol, has learned at
least part of that lesson. ``I call him, `your holiness,' he calls
me `maestro,''' Levine said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The relationship is warm and personable but I would never call
myself a friend of the pope. He has showed me the most incredible
warmth. I think that after our first meeting, he saw something
about me that made it possible for him to think he might want to
know me better.''
</P>
<P>
   Levine also became close to the pope's personal secretary, Msgr.
Stanislaw Dziwisz, the real gatekeeper at the Vatican. ``I would
never bother him unless it is important; he is a very busy man,''
Levine said. But later he recalled with relish a phone conversation
with Dziwisz he had had a few days earlier on his way from Cracow.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our city has really changed,'' he recalled telling the pope's
secretary about Cracow, a city that he last saw in 1991 and that is
the monsignor's hometown. Levine added that Dziwisz ``was stunned
how my Polish came back after only two days.''
</P>
<P>
   Levine, who learned Polish in Cracow, said that he and the pope
converse in Polish and that in one early meeting, when he and the
pope and Lustiger were discussing Levine's plans to hold a memorial
concert for reconciliation at an empty Cracow synagogue, the pope
translated their conversation into French for the cardinal. (
Levine said he and the cardinal usually speak in German, using the
familiar ``du.'')
</P>
<P>
   Lustiger, archbishop of Paris, has known Levine for years and
was the one to invest him as a papal knight in 1994, making him the
fourth Jew so honored. (A fifth was named in 1998.) The cardinal
shares Levine's Polish-Jewish roots; the cardinal was born in
Paris, his mother, who had been born in Poland, died at Auschwitz,
and he was sheltered by Catholics during the war and eventually
converted. The cardinal did not hesitate to describe Levine as a
``friend'' of the pope, saying that John Paul II was fond of the
American conductor.
</P>
<P>
   But he placed the friendship in the context of the pope's larger
vision. ``Gilbert's enthusiasm was helpful to the pope,'' he said.
``Music is a language that can help advance human understanding and
ease conflicts. The concert for the Shoah was quite astonishing,
though in the year 2000 and the pilgrimage to the Holy Land the
pope has in a way surpassed that which music promised.''
</P>
<P>
   Levine said he had sold the pope on the idea of another Vatican
concert by presenting it as a papal concert to commemorate the
millennium; a series of concerts to promote interfaith
understanding in 2000 that Levine plans to take on tour to the
United States, France, Spain and Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Levine said that John Paul II chose the date for the Vatican
concert. ``It was really his idea,'' Levine said. ``When I
described the idea for the concert, the pope told me, `It should be
on my birthday.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-17-00 1826EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000517.0264 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 18:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8067 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CALIF-SCHOOLS-2TAKES-     05-17 0723
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-SCHOOLS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CIVIL RIGHTS GROUPS SUE CALIFORNIA OVER DISPARITIES IN SCHOOLS 
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: Miss., Fla., Ohio, N.C., Ala.)  By TODD S. PURDUM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ On the 46th anniversary of the landmark Brown vs.
Board of Education decision, a coalition of civil rights groups
filed a class action lawsuit saying that the disparities between
California's best and worst public schools are so great as to
violate the state constitution's guarantee of a free and equal
public education for all, and demanding that the state assure that
all schools have the bare necessities of teachers, textbooks,
classrooms and toilets.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the plaintiffs described the state court suit as the
first in the nation to seek a guarantee of education basics, and
say they hope it will open a new front in a three-decade drive that
began with attempts to equalize school financing, then moved on to
address the adequacy of conditions. The suit seeks no monetary
damages, only an order requiring the state to assure certain
essentials like textbooks and safe buildings throughout California.
</P>
<P>
   The suit comes as Gov. Gray Davis and other state politicians
are grappling with how to return the state, which once led the
nation in educational spending, standards and achievement, to
something close to the national average in per pupil spending,
computers per student and the like. In his revised budget this
week, Davis proposed more than $3 billion in new spending for
education, including a controversial plan to exempt public
schoolteachers from state income taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first case that has said what are the bare
essentials that a kid needs to even have a hope of equal
educational opportunities,'' said Mark D. Rosenbaum, legal director
of the American Civil Liberties Union of Southern California, which
filed the suit along with other civil rights organizations,
including the Mexican-American Legal Defense and Education Fund, on
behalf of students and parents in poor and minority districts.
</P>
<P>
   ``California used to be the model which all states would look to
for a public education system that was the institution for
democratizing the citizenry,'' Rosenbaum added, referring to the
era before the late 1970s when Proposition 13 and tax revolt set
off a decline in school funding that the state has struggled to
stem. ``Now it's a measure of the Mississipification of California
that the national average is looked at as a goal to accomplish, and
not necessarily one that will be met anytime soon.''
</P>
<P>
   Doug Stone, a spokesman for the state department of education,
and for Delaine Eastin, the superintendent of public instruction
and the lead named defendant in the suit, said it would have no
immediate comment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The department counsel, which just received the lawsuit, has
not had an opportunity to thoroughly review it,'' Stone said. ``The
next logical step is for our counsel to work with the attorney
general's office and the governor's office to develop a response.''
</P>
<P>
   A somewhat similar suit was filed last year in Florida and is
pending in state court there, accusing the state of violating the
constitutional rights of tens of thousands of school children by
failing to provide them with an adequate education that would
enable them to pass standardized tests, learn basic skills and
compete in the workplace. Similar suits have been filed in Alabama,
North Carolina, Ohio and Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last several decades, various court decisions have
sought to rectify imbalances in financing among districts, or to
end overt racial discrimination. But because equalizing current
financing cannot address disparities built up between rich and poor
districts over time, and because discrimination suits have faded
with the end of legally sanctioned segregation, the latest wave of
cases has begun focusing on conditions and programs, not money.
</P>
<P>
   In California, for example, state chapters of the Civil
Liberties Union, have already filed suits against the state
university and the state's public schools, arguing that a lack of
advanced placement classes in poorer high schools leads to
discrimination in college admissions and advancement, since
students in many schools have no access to the classes that could
gain them extra credit.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The suit filed against the state Department of Education on
Wednesday, based on five months of research in schools around the
state and interviews with students, parents and teachers, found
some textbooks so outdated that they describe the Soviet Union as
still in existence and locked in a Cold War with the United States.
In at least 68 schools, at least half the teachers lack full
credentials. Others require students to pay for basic instructional
materials in core subjects like English and science, while others
lack bathrooms, ventilation or adequate seats in classrooms.
</P>
<P>
   ``The staggering range of disparities in public education in
this state offend the core constitutional principle of equality,''
according to the plaintiffs' 44-page complaint, which catalogs a
range of horror stories. At Jefferson Senior High School in Los
Angeles, for example, students in five different classes must share
one set of 30 Spanish textbooks, students lack desks and teachers
must pay for gas for field trips out of their own pocket, the suit
says.
</P>
<P>
   Theodore M. Shaw, associate director and counsel of the national
office of the NAACP Legal Defense and Educational Fund, which is
not a party to the suit but supports its goals, said it was
``obviously no coincidence that the suit was filed today,'' on the
anniversary of the Supreme Court case that held separate schools
for blacks and whites were inherently unequal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The irony lies that 46 years ago we had the Supreme Court
saying that separate but equal is never equal, and almost half a
century later, the Supreme Court and lower federal courts have been
making it more difficult to achieve racial desegregation,'' Shaw
said. ``And this suit, in a sense, is circling back around to the
pre-Brown days, focusing on conditions in the schools, the
tangibles, and saying you have to make schools equal. The argument
here is not so much that there's invidious segregation and
discrimination, but that the policies and practices and the willful
ignorance of the disparities that characterize our public schools
still have this racially disparate effect.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ultimately, it's a reflection of the kind of retrogression
we've seen,'' Shaw added, ``or to use a term popular in black
churches, the backsliding we've seen.''
</P>
<P>
   Matthew I. Kreeger, a lawyer in San Francisco for the firm of
Morrison &AMP; Foerster, which is helping to argue the case pro bono,
said the timing was apt.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the one hand, there are resources available from the state
now to deal with problems like this, and a commitment from state
officials to try,'' he said. At the same time, he said, the need
for adequate conditions is ``even more acute'' in the face of newly
adopted standards for students, including strict new exit
examinations for high school that will make it harder than ever for
students from disadvantaged schools to pass.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenbaum of the Civil Liberties Union added: ``At a time when
the governor is properly calling for accountability from students
and teachers, it's the state that must be held accountable first.
Right now the buck isn't stopping anywhere.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
