<DOCNO> NYT20000517.0266 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 18:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8069 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-HEDGE-TRIMMING0518-CO     05-17 1067
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEDGE-TRIMMING0518-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Badly trimmed shrubs are `everywhere you look'
 &HT;    By James Cummings
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Most of what people know about trimming hedges is
probably wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first rule you have to follow, no matter what shape you
cut, is that the base of the shrub should always be wider than the
top,'' said Chris Jensen, horticulturist with the Wegerzyn Center
at Stillwater Gardens MetroPark. ``Very few people seem to know
that, and you see bushes cut the wrong way everywhere you look.''
</P>
<P>
   If a bush is wider on top than at the bottom, the top of the
plant keeps light from reaching the lower branches. The lack of
light causes the lower branches to die, creating top-heavy plants
with bare bottoms.
</P>
<P>
   If you haven't trimmed the evergreen hedges or bushes around
your house yet this year, they're probably kind of shaggy with new
growth right now.
</P>
<P>
   Jensen and two other horticulturists _ Reuben Huffman of
Fullmer's Landscaping and Liz Cramer of Siebenthaler Inc. _ say now
is the perfect time to get evergreen bushes into shape.
</P>
<P>
   The first step is deciding whether you want the plants to be
formal, as in sculpted geometric shapes, or informal, as in more
naturally shaped.
</P>
<P>
   Formal shrubs complement formal housing styles while informal
shrubs go well with more relaxed styles such as cottages or
farmhouses. But the final decision between formal and informal is
generally made on the basis of personal taste.
</P>
<P>
   The best tool for maintaining a row of bushes as a formal hedge
is an electric hedge trimmer. In especially large yards where
electric outlets are scarce and rechargeable trimmers can't finish
the job, gas-powered trimmers are available. Hand trimmers, the
ones that look like giant scissors, are OK if you have only a few
bushes to trim.
</P>
<P>
   You'll probably only use the trimmers a few times each year, so
don't go overboard on buying expensive ones. Also remember that
longer electric trimmers _ 2 to 3 feet _ may be harder to control
than more moderate ones of 12 to 18 inches.
</P>
<P>
   For an even cut, run a level string between posts at each end of
the hedge. Use the string as a reference to keep your cuts
straight.
</P>
<P>
   Start trimming near the top of the bush, and remember that
you'll probably trim more plant material high on the bush than near
the bottom. Try to avoid cutting away so much of the growing layer
that you expose bare branches from the interior of the plant.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, try not to make the top of the hedge too flat. Snow
builds up on the top of a flat hedge, weighing down the branches
and causing them to splay out. In fact, it's a good idea to go out
after a heavy snow and knock the snow off bushes to keep them from
being squashed out of shape.
</P>
<P>
   Taxus bushes, also known as yews, are the most common ornamental
shrub in the area, and they can withstand removal of a lot of
needles. However, if you trim the tree so deeply that bare branches
show, the plant will take a lot of time to green up again.
</P>
<P>
   Some other evergreens _ including junipers, hemlocks and white
pines _ only grow from the ends of branches and must be trimmed
very delicately. Cut off the end of a branch, and that branch will
never recover.
</P>
<P>
   If you're not sure what kind of evergreen bush you have, take a
cutting to the Wegerzyn Center or to a nursery and ask one of the
professionals there for an identification and some trimming tips.
</P>
<P>
   Trimming an evergreen to an informal shape is done with hand
pruners, one branch at a time. Nip off the fronds of new growth
that are heading in directions you don't want the plant to go. You
can also remove dead or damaged branches.
</P>
<P>
   Cramer said an important way to beautify any hedge is to get rid
of the weeds and volunteer trees growing from underneath. She
suggests cutting off any unwanted woody plants at the soil line and
painting the stumps with a herbicide such as Round Up.
</P>
<P>
   Evergreens have small, closely placed waxy needles that stay
green year round. Deciduous shrubs, shrubs that lose their leaves
in the fall, tend to have bigger, softer leaves.
</P>
<P>
   A few leaf-shedding shrubs, such as densely growing privets, can
be shaped with hedge trimmers like evergreens. But most deciduous
bushes look ragged after being attacked with hedge trimmers because
the trimmers leave many leaves half shredded.
</P>
<P>
   The horticulturist suggest pruning off unwanted branches to keep
deciduous shrubs in shape. First remove branches that are dead,
dying, diseased or poorly shaped. Get rid of crossing branches that
are growing in such a way that the bark of one branch touches
another branch or the tree trunk.
</P>
<P>
   Cut the branches off but leave their collars intact. Collars are
the rounded knobs that form where a branch meets its parent branch
or the tree trunk.
</P>
<P>
   Make sure your pruning shears or other cutting tools are sharp
and clean. Dip the blades in bleach occasionally to avoid carrying
diseases from one plant to another.
</P>
<P>
   The best time to prune most woody plants is during their dormant
season in late fall or early spring, before the plants are actively
growing. But most deciduous plants still flourish if pruned
judiciously at this time of year.
</P>
<P>
   Avoid pruning or trimming shrubs during hot, dry spells,
however. Plants have a hard enough time dealing with the heat
without the added stress of pruning.
</P>
<P>
   Certain flowering shrubs can be improved by trimming them in the
weeks after their spring blooms die, said Huffman. Lilacs,
forsythia, viburnum and flowering quince all develop new flower
buds in the summer after their spring blooms fall.
</P>
<P>
   If you prune the plants now, the plant will be forced to direct
its energies to producing buds for next year on the branches you
leave behind. If you prune these flowering shrubs in the fall or
spring, you'll be cutting away buds the plant worked all summer to
produce, and next spring's flower production will be small.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes pruning and trimming are not enough. If the species of
plant you have in a particular spot is simply too big for its
location, constant aggressive pruning will lead only to frustration
and an ugly plant.
</P>
<P>
   If a plant refuses to live in the space it has been given,
sometimes the best option is to remove the plant and replace it
with a more appropriate variety.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
