<DOCNO> NYT20000517.0267 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 18:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8071 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TV-HOLMES-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      05-17 1017
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-HOLMES-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MURDER ROOMS': A BLUEPRINT FOR IMAGINING SHERLOCK
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: Broadcast notes are at end of review. Time, channel are for
New York area. Check local listings.) 
 By JULIE SALAMON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nothing explains Sherlock Holmes' ongoing appeal better than his
own analysis of his detective work. ``It saved me from ennui,''
Holmes once said to his sidekick, Dr. Watson. ``Alas! I already
feel it closing upon me. My life is spent in one long effort to
escape from the commonplaces of existence. These little problems
help me to do so.''
</P>
<P>
   When he's figuring out one of his little problems, the universe
has focus and meaning. When he isn't solving mysteries, or fencing
or boxing, he escapes by means of cocaine or his violin music, or
he simply sinks into an existential torpor. His brilliant
deductions are amusing, but it's the languor _ the hints of
personal darkness _ that captivates.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last century, numerous films and then television
adaptations have been based on the Sherlock Holmes stories. Yet a
new British series has found a clever way to capitalize on Holmes'
popularity without trying to reinvent ``The Hound of the
Baskervilles'' yet again. In fact, Holmes doesn't even appear in
``Murder Rooms: The Dark Origins of Sherlock Holmes,'' presented in
two hourlong episodes Thursday night and next Thursday on
``Mystery,'' the PBS anthology.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps taking its cue from ``Shakespeare in Love,'' ``Murder
Rooms'' places the author _ in this case, Sir Arthur Conan Doyle _
at center stage and aims to satisfy our curiosity about the
creative process with a dramatized version of reality.
</P>
<P>
   Conan Doyle might actually have approved of this fictionalized
fact. As Holmes observes to Watson, in ``A Case of Identity'':
</P>
<P>
   ``If we could fly out of that window hand in hand, hover over
this great city, gently remove the roofs, and peep at the queer
things which are going on, the strange coincidences, the plannings,
the cross-purposes, the wonderful chains of events, working through
generations, and leading to the most outre results, it would make
all fiction with its conventionalities and foreseen conclusions
most stale and unprofitable.''
</P>
<P>
   David Pirie's witty and intelligent script for ``Murder Rooms''
begins with the premise, promulgated by Conan Doyle himself, that
Conan Doyle's mysteries were rooted in reality and that Holmes was
modeled after Joseph Bell, a professor at the medical school in
Edinburgh when Conan Doyle enrolled as his student in 1878. Bell
was modestly famous for making extravagant (but often accurate)
diagnoses divined as much from a patient's accent or clothing or
occupation as from specific symptoms _ much the way Holmes would
solve crimes. Apparently Bell also had a night job as a kind of
forensic detective, using his powers of deduction to help the
police unravel difficult cases. Conan Doyle became Bell's helper,
his Dr. Watson.
</P>
<P>
   Buttressing these spare facts with considerable research about
Victorian Edinburgh, and an obvious affinity for the Holmes
stories, Pirie has imagined Conan Doyle's apprenticeship as a
blueprint for his life as an author. Not incidentally, he has
staged these events that could have fed Conan Doyle's imagination
as a satisfying Sherlock Holmes story.
</P>
<P>
   Trailing after his mentor, Bell, the 19-year-old Doyle
encounters the city's bottom-feeders (many of whom hold positions
of prominence). Though young, he isn't innocent _ his own father, a
disappointed artist, has drank himself into madness. But Bell
enlarges Conan Doyle's education further. Their investigations
uncover gruesome examples of cruelty (a corpse whose ears have been
severed) as well as less vivid but even more heartbreaking forms of
loss.
</P>
<P>
   The superb Ian Richardson, who has played Sherlock Holmes (on
HBO's version of ``The Hound of the Baskervilles'' and ``The Sign
of Four''), expertly conveys a plausible prototype with his Bell.
The real doctor may or may not have shared Holmes' quirks. We're
privy only to the intelligence that Richardson uses to make his
character as alluring as a man with steel-wool hair can be.
</P>
<P>
   As Arthur Conan Doyle, the young actor Robin Laing communicates
sweetness and resoluteness in the face of hard sorrow, as well as
offering a touch of self-pity that makes Conan Doyle all the more
human. The actors are generally good and mostly not well known,
except for Charles Dance, playing aristocratic scum, a part he does
well. His character pops up only briefly here and there, but like a
cockroach skittering across a wedding cake, makes an impression.
</P>
<P>
   Shooting on location in Scotland, the filmmakers have made the
streets and laboratories of their 19th-century Edinburgh seem
Gothic and sinister, while the interiors _ where appropriate _ are
warmly lit and elegantly Victorian. Jim Parker's sensitive score is
lovely, especially the violin homages to Holmes.
</P>
<P>
   The director, Paul Seed (whose credits include the classic
``Masterpiece Theater'' miniseries ``House of Cards'') deftly
maneuvers the action through the busy scenario Pirie has concocted.
There are many crimes to contend with, of course, but also poignant
relationships as well as sour ones, and even a dalliance with Big
Issues (feminism, specifically, when Conan Doyle's female
classmates are harassed). That's a lot to cover in two hours, but
everyone manages very well.
</P>
<P>
   BROADCAST NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `Mystery! Murder Rooms: The Dark Origins of Sherlock Holmes'
</P>
<P>
   9 p.m Thursday night on PBS.
</P>
<P>
   Screenplay by David Pirie; Paul Seed, director; Ian Madden,
producer; Tom McCullagh, production designer; Mark Day, editor; Jim
Parker, composer. A co-production of the BBC and WGBH/Boston. David
Thompson, executive producer for the BBC; Rebecca Eaton, executive
producer for WGBH; Diana Rigg, series host.
</P>
<P>
   With: Robin Laing (Arthur Conan Doyle), Ian Richardson (Dr.
Joseph Bell), Dolly Wells (Elspeth), Sean McGinley (Beecher), Alec
Newman (Neill), Andrew John Tate (Eustace Stark), Charles Dance
(Sir Henry Carlyle) and Ruth Platt (Lady Sarah).
</P>
</TEXT>
