<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-POLITICS-550&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUTIN MOVES TO CURB POWER OF REGIONS; DUMA APPROVES PREMIER  
</HEADLINE>
   By MICHAEL WINES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Moving swiftly to gather the reins of power in Kremlin
hands, President Vladimir Putin proposed legislation Wednesday
night that would oust Russia's provincial governors from their
appointed seats in the parliament and, in some instances, permit
him to fire them altogether.
</P>
<P>
   The plan to redraw parliament's upper house, called the
Federation Council, would replace its 178 governors and regional
legislative leaders with lower-level appointees from each of the
nation's 89 regions.
</P>
<P>
   It is the latest in a series of moves by the new Kremlin
administration to reassert central control over its sprawling
territory, which in recent years has sometimes seemed to be
drifting into a collection of autonomous fiefdoms.
</P>
<P>
   Putin went on national television Wednesday evening to reveal
the proposed legislation and several other initiatives that he said
were aimed at ``strengthening and cementing Russian statehood.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A moment has come to separate partisan, regional and personal
ambitions from the strict necessity to strengthen the state system
and reinforce its power,'' he said. ``The citizens of Russia have
been waiting for it for a long time. We have to justify these
expectations.''
</P>
<P>
   He took pains to stress that the proposals, which would require
the parliament's approval, ``are fully within the framework of the
current Russian constitution.''
</P>
<P>
   Some are nevertheless sure to be controversial. But the Kremlin
seemed confident _ and outside experts agreed _ that Putin can
muster enough votes to push the proposals into law. Late Wednesday
night, news services reported that leaders of both the left-wing
Communist Party and the western-oriented Union of Right Forces back
the initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   That impression of support was bolstered by the lopsided 325-155
vote earlier Wednesday in parliament's lower house, the Duma, to
confirm Putin's nominee for prime minister, Mikhail Kasyanov. The
overwhelming vote for approval, the biggest majority received by
any of Russia's seven prime ministers, suggests that Putin is
beginning his term with an unusually strong political base in the
parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Putin said Wednesday night that his latest proposals are driven
not by power politics, but by the need to make the executive and
legislative branches of Russia's government more effective. But one
clear effect would be to shift political power away from regional
leaders and back to Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   Besides rearranging the Federation Council, Putin said he will
seek the authority to remove provincial leaders from office and
dissolve regional legislatures that enact laws in violation of the
federal constitution. Noting that even he can be impeached for such
violations, Putin called it ``an outrageous fact'' that a fifth of
provincial laws are at odds with federal legislation and that many
provincial charters contradict the federal constitution.
</P>
<P>
   ``The consequences of such violations are catastrophic,'' he
said. ``From such seemingly petty issues, drop by drop, separatism
ripens, which sometimes becomes a stronghold for an even more
dangerous evil, international terrorism.''
</P>
<P>
   Putin also proposed that regional leaders get new authority to
remove officials below them, something he said was only fair given
the expanded powers he seeks.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But symbolically, at least, the plan to create a new Federation
Council outshined the Kremlin's other proposals. Russia's
constitution, written in 1993 after President Boris Yeltsin used
tanks to put down a parliamentary revolt, calls only for the
council to be composed of officials from each province's executive
and legislative branches.
</P>
<P>
   It was the Kremlin that allowed legislation specifying that the
governors and legislative chiefs sit on the council, a compromise
that Yeltsin apparently struck to gain political support. The
council's far-flung members assemble only a few days each month and
often use their Moscow posts to trade political influence for
benefits back home. Putin said Wednesday that he is returning to
the constitution's original meaning and freeing the governors and
legislators to tend to their real business back home. In return, he
said, the council will become a more professional, full-time
legislative chamber _ something he suggested would make his life
more difficult but would benefit Russia in the long run.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts agreed Wednesday night that the Russian presidency,
already an immensely powerful institution under Yeltsin's
constitution, would only become stronger should Putin's plans
become law. But they were hard put to say that the proposals were
wrongheaded. Not only has the Federation Council become the
weakling in the Russian legislative system, but some Russian
governors have all but become autocrats in their provinces as the
Kremlin's authority ebbed in the 1990s. A few have erected small
empires based largely on public corruption.
</P>
<P>
   ``Putin is quite sure about the parliament and Moscow for the
time being,'' Lilia Shevtsova, a political scholar at the Carnegie
Endowment for International Peace in Moscow, said Wednesday night.
``He has no enemies, no opponents. So the major activity now is to
curb the power of the feudals, the robber barons of the provinces.
Even liberals and democrats want to curb their activity. The
problem is on what basis. Putin could have done it in creating the
new role of judicial system, or increasing the role of
self-government. But he followed Russian and Soviet tradition, and
did it from the top.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
