<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 18:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8081 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-NJ-CITY-OF-LEARNING-A     05-17 0831
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-CITY-OF-LEARNING-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HELPING PATERSON, N.J., GET BETTER GRADES IN URBAN RENEWAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.)  
 By WILLIAM L. HAMILTON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Trees. I would like to add trees,'' reads the legend on a
simple map of a street in Paterson, N.J., drawn in colored pencil
by a freshman high school student, Leon White, who lives on it.
Green trees have been swirled onto the black and white street like
the rotations of a wand.
</P>
<P>
   Urban solutions can be this simple _ so simple, in fact, that a
child can create them.
</P>
<P>
   Through an ambitious plan called the City of Learning, Paterson,
a city of 170,000, is giving public high school students not only
the tools to understand its urban problems, but also the chance to
solve them.
</P>
<P>
   Leon White is enrolled at the Metro Paterson Academy for
Communications and Technology, or Mpact, a new public school
established in September in an empty downtown mall, where
open-classroom walls are papered with student projects: urban
renewal studies and school construction proposals.
</P>
<P>
   Mpact is a pilot in a program of innovative academies that offer
specialized curricula and smaller classes. Started by Manhattan's
Center for Innovative Education, they are being tested in other
cities. In Paterson, the academies are also being proposed as tools
for urban renewal in an economically distressed city with a school
performance so poor that the district was taken over by the state
in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Anticipating $500 million to $800 million in state money to
build new school facilities, Dr. Edwin Duroy, the state-appointed
superintendent of schools, realized that improving schools was
meaningless if the struggling city was ignored. His budget
represented Paterson's largest potential capital investment. Why
not use it to rescue the schools and try rehabilitating the city at
the same time? And put students at the center of the equation by
teaching them city planning _ at school.
</P>
<P>
   The opportunity demanded vision. Duroy invited urban designers
from the Massachusetts Institute of Technology, with experience in
school districts from Berkeley, Calif., to Washington, D.C., to
develop a master plan for Paterson's schools and its 25,000
students.
</P>
<P>
   The New American School Design Project, a workshop of graduate
students at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology led by Roy
Strickland, an architect, developed a concept called the City of
Learning _ an expanding system of academies throughout Paterson
that would spark investment in neighborhoods, especially a sorely
vacant, turn-of-the-century downtown.
</P>
<P>
   By September, seven academies will be in operation.
</P>
<P>
   In an election year, when the nature of education and the fate
of cities are being debated at a national level, Paterson is
putting the American high school on Main Street. Mpact is at number
175. At the school, which opened last September with a freshman
class of 25, students study college preparatory subjects like
mathematics and history in the morning and technology,
entrepreneurship and urban planning in the afternoon. It is an
extended day, ending at 4 p.m. Visited recently, students were
still working at 6.
</P>
<P>
   Posted in the classroom where urban planning is taught is a list
of ``Existing Conditions'' in Paterson, identified by students.
They include ``railroad tracks,'' ``crackheads,'' ``parking lots,''
``lost treasures'' and ``discarded clothing'': a stream of
consciousness from its younger citizens that runs like the Passaic
River and its treacherous falls, through the heart of the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``We live here; nobody knows it better than us,'' said Kemesha
Pringle, 14.
</P>
<P>
   Her classmate, Maurice Moore, 14, said, ``Now, we've got a
responsibility to give people what they want.''
</P>
<P>
   On June 14, the class will present its first proposal to the
Board of Education: a plan to replace a faculty parking lot between
two schools with an educational park for the community. Their
proposals include a food court (the children complained about the
cafeteria lunch), a swimming pool (the community asked for it), an
arcade for games after school and a tent for reading during the
summer _ improvements to school property that a school budget
theoretically would pay for.
</P>
<P>
   Javier Mendez, 15, said that his work improving Paterson with
planning was important because ``it's my home.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``stepping outside the box,'' as Duroy called
beyond-the-classroom steps like Mpact and the City of Learning,
Paterson hopes to realize not just new facilities with novel
opportunities for urban growth, but to move toward smaller, more
personal learning environments, which are now widely acknowledged
as improving performance. Paterson hopes smaller classes will
combat the dropout rate, which exceeded 15 percent in the 1998-99
school year. The state average was 2.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Many eighth-graders choose not to go to the high schools, but
to vocational schools,'' Duroy said. ``Recognizing this, I felt we
needed to become competitive. We needed to bring alternative
choices to parents.''
</P>
<P>
   The academies are being created to compete. Applications to
Mpact, which is choosing its second freshman class of 25 now, have
doubled because of word-of-mouth between parents.
</P>
<P>
   The anticipated budget is Paterson's share of a 1998 New Jersey
Supreme Court decision requiring the state to dedicate billions of
dollars to school construction in 28 low-income districts.
</P>
<P>
   The New Jersey state Senate will vote Thursday on a proposal to
put the Economic Development Agency in charge of school
construction, a plan that Gov. Christie Whitman supports, said
Gregg Edwards, executive director of the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sponsors of the bill want towns to think creatively about
what school money can be used to do, and that's just what Paterson
is talking about,'' he said. ``Paterson is looking at the money as
part of an economic development strategy. The Economic Development
Agency will be more sympathetic to the sort of things Paterson
wants to do.''
</P>
<P>
   But James W. Hughes, dean of the Edward J. Bloustein School of
Planning and Public Policy at Rutgers University, questioned the
ability of schools to act as economic engines in a city.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to think of what they'll achieve beyond bailing out
property owners,'' he said, explaining that putting schools in
vacant, downtown buildings was not the invitation to commercial
development that placing businesses would be. And, he added,
``there's not that much buying power to support retail
facilities.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Lonreghan, executive director of the Special Improvement
District in Paterson, a coalition of local businesses and property
owners, said of the academies' new downtown: ``We do feel the
schools have had a positive impact _ the added presence of hundreds
of students and teachers. But as for bringing in higher-end
business like Starbucks, I haven't seen that impact.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus far, there has been little criticism of the Paterson
approach. If there are critics, they have been local, though
reluctant to be vocal about what is regarded as an unprecedented
windfall for a city with no substantial money from the private
sector in sight.
</P>
<P>
   Anna-Lisa Dopirak, director of community development in
Paterson, expressed frustration at being out of the loop created by
a state superintendent working with an out-of-state planning
group.? ``There should have been a closer working relationship with
this department on the project,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Will Paterson take its student planners seriously?
</P>
<P>
   Partnerships with institutions like MIT and Lucent Technologies,
which is working with Stephen Cohen, the school district's
technology planner, to wire the City of Learning with
Internet-access cable for every school in Paterson, has gotten the
city's attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``That these are ideas being generated by kids doesn't undermine
the fact that they are bright ideas that have merit,'' said William
McKoy, president of the Board of Education, who was elected to the
Paterson City Council last week on a platform promoting Paterson as
the City of Learning.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're training and thinking with good institutions,'' he
said. ``The collaboration is meaningful to the city _ it's not
Monopoly.''
</P>
<P>
   At Mpact, the students have already developed their own
mass-transit system: rolling desk chairs that speed them from desk
to desk, across the plaza of the classroom, to confer on projects.
The plan for the laboratory is a Socratic circle; there are no rows
or lecterns.
</P>
<P>
   Jean Riesman, an instructor with an MIT master's degree in city
planning, is developing Mpact's first year of programs, which
include working with the class on converting a municipal parking
lot into a civic center and park, with schools, malls and a
transportation hub for a proposed light-rail link to New York.
</P>
<P>
   Like any planning session, the discussion, chaired by Riesman, a
woman in black jeans and wide-heeled boots with a salt-and-pepper
ponytail, came down to what Paterson had, what it didn't have and
what it could have as a place to live.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody wanted stores,'' said LaToya Matthews, 14. ``Old
Navy, Gap. But then we had to stop and think: That's going to take
away business from the stores that are here. We don't want to put
them out of business. So there had to be some sort of
collaboration.''
</P>
<P>
   Sindy Ponte, 14, explained that they took role-playing parts in
the situation to understand it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was the city; other kids were the businesses,'' she said,
referring to local merchants like the pizza parlor down the block,
now a favorite student stop.
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Medina, 15, said that she thought people living downtown
would encourage businesses to open.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see the building across the street?'' she asked, turning
to the classroom window behind her. Above an open store, the
building was empty. ``There's just a bunch of junk in there. We
would like to turn the old buildings into apartments, because there
are a lot of apartments needed in Paterson, with more living
space.''
</P>
<P>
   Ruth Melecio, 15, qualified the idea. ``Not change the outside,
just the inside,'' she said. ``We have some really nice buildings.
We want to keep those in Paterson, so it's not like everywhere
else.''
</P>
<P>
   As a group, the students agreed that there should be
recreational facilities and entertainment at the city-center site,
which are lacking now.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only for us, but for younger kids growing up, too,''
Kemesha Pringle said. ``We're trying to change things so that they
could have a better life or experience different things that aren't
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Ruth Melecio, 15, interviewed her family. ``I asked my mom what
she thinks would go nicely downtown,'' Melecio said. ``She said,
`Oh, a movie theater, a bowling alley.' I brought that in, and
everyone said, `Oh yeah, I didn't think about that.'''
</P>
<P>
   With no theater of its own, Paterson moviegoers travel to
Passaic and Clifton.
</P>
<P>
   More citizen than city official, Leon White, 14, proposed the
obvious.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the movie theaters that aren't being used, that are just
collecting dust,'' he said, speaking of several shuttered theaters
downtown, ``maybe they should try reopening them.''
</P>
<P>
   LaToya Matthews added: ``When a movie comes out, everybody talks
about going that Saturday night. Why can't they go in their own
town?'' She also advocated a skating rink. ``When a DJ from
Paterson wants to throw a party, we have to go all the way to
Wayne,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Maurice Moore, 14, made an observation that could help him in an
election, if he pursues his participation in the city. ``If we had
all this stuff that we want,'' he said, ``it would be stuff that
would attract tourism. People would come in, spend money and
leave.''
</P>
<P>
   The adults led the class in appreciative laughter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
