<SLUG> BC-BAXTER18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Family ties bind Bush, first lady
 &HT;    By Tom Baxter
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   They aren't usually likened to each other, and either of them
would probably be indignant at the comparison. But politically,
George W. Bush and Hillary Clinton have some things in common.
</P>
<P>
   Most obviously, family connections have been crucial for both
the ex-president's son and the president's wife. Neither of them
would likely be in the spotlight this year without those
connections, but the roles they've played in the past have also
affected the way they approach their races, for the presidency and
the U.S. Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Standing behind the shoulder of another candidate has taught
both of them to tone down their rhetoric, even as it has sharpened
their resentment of those they view as having attacked their
families.
</P>
<P>
   Bush tempers his rightward leanings with the theme of
compassionate conservatism. Clinton, traveling New York state on
her ``listening'' campaign, has sublimated her more outspoken
liberal tendencies to what might be called a more consumer-oriented
approach.
</P>
<P>
   The family connections have given both candidates a wealth of
political experience on which to draw, while at the same time
causing them to be underestimated in political circles.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is thought not to have the gravitas his father had, opening
the way for charges that he's a lightweight. (The Oval Office and
the U.S. Senate are the only places left where that old word has
much meaning, incidentally. No one ever worries that Bill Gates
doesn't have enough gravitas.)
</P>
<P>
   Some might describe Clinton's problem as too much gravitas. On
the stump, it is often noted that she lacks the glad-handing
charisma of her husband.
</P>
<P>
   These criticisms are fair enough, but they miss something vital
about the political aptitude of both candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever their deficiencies, both seem to understand a
fundamental campaign principle: When the way has been cleared
before you, the only thing you have to do is plod forward. Now that
both of them have the bit in their mouths, that's exactly what
they're doing.
</P>
<P>
   As his poll numbers have mounted, Bush has put off any talk of
debating Vice President Al Gore or being drawn into an argument
through the media. Clinton, accepting the Democratic Senate
nomination in New York Tuesday night, declared that the Senate race
was not about her or any possible Republican opponent. No need to
refer to any of New York Mayor Rudy Giuliani's problems of the past
week or so: Just keep pulling that wagon in the right direction.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's comment touches on one of the big differences in their
situations right now. Bush can be sure who he's running against.
She can't.
</P>
<P>
   Until Giuliani's situation gets sorted out, it will be
impossible to know how Clinton is likely to do in her first bid as
a candidate. Similarly, while Bush has an impressive lead in the
polls, there's still a long time until November.
</P>
<P>
   If both of them win this year, however, Bush and Clinton are
likely to be linked in another way: as potential opponents in the
2004 presidential race. The comparison game would begin in earnest.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
