<HEADER>
A8084 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-PICK-YOUR-OWN0518-COX     05-17 1122
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PICK-YOUR-OWN0518-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fruits of your labor
 &HT;    By Kitty Crider
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ It's the romance of abandoning your cubicle and
driving down wildflower-lined roads to a place in the country where
you can pluck produce and drop it into a basket (or your mouth).
Then picking again and again as the sun shines brightly overhead,
little kids scamper among the rows of bushes or trees and the Texas
wind blows the hat off your head.
</P>
<P>
   Have another blackberry. Or strawberry. Or peach.
</P>
<P>
   It's springtime in Texas, and the picking is good if you dodge
the less enticing elements of nature.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where are the scorpions and snakes?'' asks a visitor to the
Bella Vista Ranch in Wimberley.
</P>
<P>
   ``No snakes, no scorpions,'' reassures owner Jack Dougherty, who
has planted hundreds of blackberry bushes, with fruit bigger than
your thumb, among a grove of young olive trees.
</P>
<P>
   Just some fire ants and the occasional bee.
</P>
<P>
   John Meyer, a pharmacist picking blackberries at the ranch,
quips, ``I really have enjoyed your fire ants,'' as he settles up
with his Wimberley neighbor. He is going to turn the berries into
cobbler for guests at the Bella Vista Bed and Breakfast (no
connection), which he co-owns.
</P>
<P>
   Cobbler, smoothies, jams, jellies, bowls of ice cream and cereal
_ the lure of farm-fresh fruit is strong. Even in a high-tech,
convenience-minded millennium, pick-your-own farms have a
following. The Texas Department of Agriculture, which compiles a
list of pick-your-own farms, says it continues to be one of the
most frequent consumer requests.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has always been something people have loved,'' observes
TDA's Susan Dunn. And the practice has been sustained by the influx
of people from other states where pick-your-own farms are also big.
It's also a popular family activity because it appeals to so many
generations.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent weekend, John Ivey, a carpenter, was introducing
berry picking to his 2-year-old daughter Melina, who was having as
much fun feeding them to her dad as pulling them from the vines.
</P>
<P>
   For Jim Morrow, a Compaq program manager, and his mom, Veronica
Morrow, peaches are the goal of annual family outings. Last May, in
a short period of time, the Morrows headed over to Fredericksburg
and filled boxes with 100 pounds of peaches (about two bushels)
after a brief tasting and picking lesson from the Marburger Orchard
owners.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a ball with it. That's why we're planning on doing it
again soon,'' said Morrow. There is another reason, too. The
Morrows are down to their last peaches in the freezer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cut them up, tossed them with Fruit Fresh, no sugar,'' says
Veronica Morrow. ``They looked just as pretty as a year ago. The
color stayed the same.''
</P>
<P>
   They still tasted great, too, added Jim. But it's time to
replenish the freezer. And, sure, they could buy peaches at the
market or a roadside stand, but there is something magical about
picking your own.
</P>
<P>
   ``The smell and aroma of the peaches when you are out among
those peach trees _ it is so nice to be out there, `` says
Veronica.
</P>
<P>
   RULES OF THE ROWS
</P>
<P>
   _ Don't wear your favorite white T-shirt to the fields or
orchards. Fruits stain.
</P>
<P>
   _ If given a choice, pick fruit that is close to your car.
Baskets of peaches get heavy.
</P>
<P>
   _ Sun hats are great, but on a windy day, a baseball cap works
better.
</P>
<P>
   _ It's hard to pick in gloves.
</P>
<P>
   _ If you have kneepads, take them with you to the berry fields.
</P>
<P>
   _ Sandals are fine for the lake, but cowboy boots or athletic
shoes work better in the fields.
</P>
<P>
   RECIPES
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry Salsa
</P>
<P>
   1 pint strawberries, hulled and sliced
</P>
<P>
   2 large or 3 small bananas, peeled and sliced
</P>
<P>
   Juice of 1 lime
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon finely chopped or grated fresh ginger
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup flaked coconut
</P>
<P>
   1 kiwi, sliced
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons powdered sugar, may omit if coconut is sweetened
</P>
<P>
   Place strawberries and bananas in a medium bowl and cover with
lime juice. Add remaining ingredients and gently stir to combine.
Chill for no more than 1 hour. Serve over pound cake or ice cream.
Makes about 3 cups salsa.
</P>
<P>
   Best-Ever Peach Crisp
</P>
<P>
   Filling:
</P>
<P>
   5 to 6 peaches, peeled, pitted and cut in 1/4 inch slices.
</P>
<P>
   1/2 to 3/4 cup sugar, about 6 cups
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons all-purpose white flour
</P>
<P>
   Topping:
</P>
<P>
   1 cup all-purpose white flour
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon baking powder
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1 large egg
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup butter (1 stick)
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 375 degrees F.
</P>
<P>
   Put the peaches and 1/2 cup of sugar in a large bowl and stir
until the sugar evenly coats the fruit. The amount of sugar you use
depends on how sweet the peaches are. Taste a peach slice to see if
it seems sweet enough. If not, add the remaining 1/4 cup of sugar
and stir again.
</P>
<P>
   Add 2 tablespoons of flour to the bowl and mix until it is
evenly distributed on the fruit.
</P>
<P>
   Put the peaches in an 8-inch square or a round 1 1/2-quart
baking dish. Don't bother to butter the dish.
</P>
<P>
   Mix together 1 cup flour, 3/4 cup sugar, the baking powder, and
the salt. Crack the egg into a small dish, beat with a fork until
it is all one color, and add to the flour-and-sugar mixture. Using
your hands or a fork, gently mix the egg into the flour-and-sugar
mixture until the egg evenly moistens the dry ingredients. Be sure
not to press the dough into one solid mass. The topping should be
loose and crumbly so that it can be sprinkled over the fruit.
</P>
<P>
   Sprinkle the crisp topping evenly over the top of the peaches.
</P>
<P>
   Melt the butter in a small saucepan over medium-low heat,
stirring regularly. Spoon the melted butter over the top of the
crisp so that it is evenly coated with butter. Put the crisp on the
center rack of the oven and bake for 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   When 30 minutes are up, check to see if it's done. If the top of
the crisp is a deep golden brown, and the fruit is bubbling, it is
done. Remove it from the oven. If not, bake another 5 or 10 minutes
and check again.
</P>
<P>
   Cut the crisp into squares and lift from the pan with a small
spatula onto individual serving plates. Serve warm with whipped
cream or vanilla ice cream. Makes an 8-inch crisp.
</P>
<P>
   Blackberry Smoothie
</P>
<P>
   1 pint vanilla frozen yogurt
</P>
<P>
   1 pint fresh blackberries
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup skim milk
</P>
<P>
   Wash the berries thoroughly in two rinses of cold water. Remove
all sand, leaves and other particles. This can be done in advance
and the berries chilled in the refrigerator.
</P>
<P>
   Place all ingredients a blender. Cover the blender carafe and
blend the mixture at medium speed for 30 to 45 seconds. Serve in
your favorite drinking glasses.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
