<DOCNO> NYT20000517.0280 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 18:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8085 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-EUROPE-THEATER-AWARDS     05-17 1088
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EUROPE-THEATER-AWARDS-$ADV21-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AND THE MOLIERE FOR BEST ACTOR GOES TO ...  
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sun., May 21)  
 By ALAN RIDING    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ ``It is something of a paradox,'' Conor Brady, the
editor of The Irish Times, remarked a few years back, ``that a
director who may have a Tony on his mantelpiece will have no
corresponding award from his Irish peers.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, Brady soon helped fix that. In 1997, The Irish Times
created the Irish Theater Awards in partnership with the country's
Electricity Supply Board. And since then, peer recognition has been
gradually filling mantelpieces from Dublin to Galway.
</P>
<P>
   Not that Ireland's theater is necessarily the better for joining
the awards game. After all, from Oscar Wilde to Sebastian Barry,
the country's playwrights have fared well enough on a diet of
scandal and applause. And surely no Irish actor ever needed more
than an attentive audience for the muse to stir. On the other hand,
since a theater award usually means a splash of publicity and a
good party, no complaints. Free Champagne and a decorated
mantelpiece? Even better.
</P>
<P>
   So is that what theater awards are all about? Sort of, because
the Oscars are everyone's role model. Playwrights, directors and
actors may be at the heart of the show, there to provide glamour,
to excite the paparazzi, perhaps even to add a touch of class, but
they are in fact only bit players. In the more serious business of
selling tickets, it is the party _ the awards ceremony _ that
counts. As with the Oscars, the prize, rather than any individual
winner, is the real star.
</P>
<P>
   Yet on their own, theater awards can do little. Above all, they
are no substitute for good writers, directors, actors, managers,
theaters _ and keen audiences. In fact, for such prizes to be
coveted, for awards ceremonies to be televised, for the competition
to stir interest, a country and, above all, a city must first have
a healthy and active theater life. Conversely, the paucity of
prestigious theater prizes speaks alarmingly of the theater's
losing battle against television and movies in much of the world.
</P>
<P>
   The new Irish Theater Awards have prospered, then, because the
ground was already fertile. With the Gate and Abbey theaters its
traditional pillars, Dublin has been a theater town for well over a
century. And in the last decade, a burst of fine writing and a
fresh generation of directors have injected new blood into theater
there. So even though they have not created it, the theater prizes
are a nice way of celebrating that renaissance. This year's best
new play was ``Howie the Rookie'' by Mark O'Rowe, while the best
director award went to John Breen for his production of his own
play ``Alone It Stands.''
</P>
<P>
   Across the water in London, theater awards are as well
established as the theater business itself, indeed self-confident
enough to honor Irish or American or even French artists who help
keep the lights bright in the West End.
</P>
<P>
   The Evening Standard Theater Awards, created in 1955, eight
years after the Tony Awards, have as good a record as any for
spotting the best. In their first year, they included a bizarre
category, most controversial play. The winner? Samuel Beckett's
``Waiting for Godot.'' And in 1956, the most promising playwright?
John Osborne.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, while acting and directing awards have often gone to
pillars of the London stage like the actors Dame Maggie Smith and
the directors Sir Richard Eyre and Deborah Warner, The Evening
Standard's jury of theater critics continues to seek out new
writing talent.
</P>
<P>
   Recent most promising playwrights include Martin McDonagh (``The
Beauty Queen of Leenane'') in 1996, Conor McPherson (``The Weir'')
in 1997, Mark Ravenhill (``Handbag'') in 1998 and Rebecca Gilman
(``The Glory of Living'') in 1999. The 1999 awards ceremony,
broadcast by Carlton Television, nonetheless had a surprise: no
best play was picked, a decision widely applauded as evidence that
quality matters.
</P>
<P>
   In 1981, the Laurence Olivier Awards were added by the Society
of London Theaters, an organization that, much like the League of
American Theaters and Producers (one of the sponsors of the Tony
Awards), represents the theater business _ producers, proprietors
and managers. While the Evening Standard Awards are given in a
maximum of 10 categories, the Oliviers have 22, including two each
for opera and dance. Unusually, the theater, opera and dance juries
are formed by a mixture of theater professionals and members of the
theatergoing public (theater lovers can apply to become jurors),
which assures that popular appeal remains a key variable.
</P>
<P>
   One measure of this is the emphasis given by the Oliviers to
musical comedies, the West End's main crowd-puller, with awards for
best actor in a musical, best actress in a musical, best theater
choreographer and best supporting performance in a musical, as well
as the Radisson Edwardian Award for Best Musical. This year, when
the ceremony was televised by BBC-2, the Royal National Theater
picked up three musical prizes as well as best director for two
Shakespeare productions by its own artistic director, Sir Trevor
Nunn, accolades that reflect the broad range of the theater's work.
(Sir Trevor also won the less glitzy Critics' Circle Theater Award
for best director.)
</P>
<P>
   France's main theater award, the Moliere, has an even weightier
name and a still stronger commercial lineage. It was created in
1987 by the Union of Theater Managers and the administrator of the
Comedie Francaise, with a Paris publicist, Georges Cravenne, given
the job of founding the Professional and Artistic Theater
Association to promote the Molieres. Since then, winners have
included the actors Jeanne Moreau, Ute Lemper and Sophie Marceau,
the directors Peter Brook and Patrice Chereau and the playwright
Yasmina Reza (``Art'').
</P>
<P>
   From the beginning, however, the award was caught in the
perennial French squabble between government-subsidized theater and
commercial theater, a problem it temporarily resolved by awarding a
best-production Moliere in each of those categories. But some
people in subsidized _ read intellectual and experimental _ theater
felt that commercial theater was favored, and their resentment
surfaced in 1996 when they boycotted the televised Moliere
ceremony. Negotiations followed, and the distinction between
subsidized and commercial theater was eliminated, replaced by
prizes for best repertory play and best new creation.
</P>
<P>
   (MORE) nn
</P>
<P>
   This year's ceremony, held on May 8 in the Opera-Comique and
broadcast in prime time on the government-owned television channel
France 2, went off without controversy, with top prizes spread
around diplomatically. Best playwright, best adaptation of a
foreign play and best comedy went to Dario Fo's ``Accidental Death
of an Anarchist'' at the private Theatre la Bruyere, while best new
creation, best director and best scenic design went to Ariane
Mnouchkine's ``Tambours sur la Digue'' (``Drums Over the Dyke''),
presented at her subsidized Cartoucherie de Vincennes. The prize
for best female newcomer, in turn, went to Brook's daughter, Irina,
for her production of ``Resonances,'' by the young American
playwright Katherine Burger.
</P>
<P>
   In Russia, where theatrical experimentation flourished in the
early 20th century, the end of Communism has spawned intense new
interest in theater despite the economic troubles plaguing most
theaters. As with Ireland, the conditions were ripe for the
creation of a prestigious theater award. The Golden Mask was
established as a Moscow award in 1995 and became the main national
award the following year. In order to embrace work done across
Russia, above all in St. Petersburg, winners in a range of
categories (covering music and dance as well as drama and puppetry)
are chosen from participants in a Golden Mask festival, which now
takes place in Moscow every spring. And while this year's award
ceremony was as long-winded as some Oscar evenings, the Golden Mask
now seems to have established itself as worthy of any mantelpiece.
</P>
<P>
   More of a puzzle is the absence of major theater awards in
Germany and Italy, despite traditions that embrace the likes of
Goethe and Brecht, commedia dell'arte and Pirandello. One
explanation may simply be that both countries were only founded in
the 19th century and, as such, are not dominated by a single city.
Certainly, in Germany, most theater awards are still regional. One
exception is the Bavaria Theater Prize, announced in Munich every
summer, with jurors drawn from across the country and awards given
to opera, drama, dance and new plays performed anywhere in Germany.
With Berlin the new German capital, its two main theater awards _
the Daphne Prize and the German Theater Prize _ are also growing in
stature. No German theater awards ceremony, though, has yet earned
live television coverage.
</P>
<P>
   In Italy, scores of less important theater awards given by towns
and cities across the peninsula go largely unnoticed in the rest of
the country. ``In Italy, every steeple has its own teeny prize,''
Marcantonio Lucidi, a spokesman for the National Academy of
Dramatic Arts, explained. ``It's a cheap form of publicity. It
costs less to invite someone to your town and give them a tin
statue than it does to run an ad campaign.'' Still, one prize, the
Premio Ubu, created in the late 1970s by Ubu Libri, a Milan
publishing house, has won some respect, if only because, unlike
much of Italy's cultural life, it is thought to be above political
manipulation.
</P>
<P>
   All too often, though, theater awards are known to those in the
theater industry and few others. Poland's Schiller Prize, given
annually to an eminent theater figure, does little to boost
contemporary theater. Japan's Education Ministry offers an annual
theater prize, but it barely merits a mention in the press.
Argentina, which offers Latin America's most developed theater, has
no fewer than four theater awards, too many to create a buzz. In
Brazil, the Shell Prize of $1,750, sponsored by the British oil
giant, has existed since 1983, but the state government of Rio de
Janeiro has now stepped in with a much more lucrative theater prize
_ $100,000 for the best production _ to be awarded for the first
time this year.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, money helps _ money for prizes, for publicity, for
glitzy awards ceremonies, for television coverage. And yet for
theater prizes to stir genuine excitement, theater-goers must first
be excited by what they have seen onstage. Or at least that is how
it should be.
</P>
<P>
   The danger arises when awards ceremonies evolve into ends unto
themselves, because once the show becomes the priority, the
temptation is to have television and movie stars handing out and
receiving top prizes. This may be good for the tabloids, good for
the television ratings, even good for the awards, but it probably
does little for theater.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
