<DOCNO> NYT20000517.0283 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 18:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8088 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-BERRIES-LEMONS0518-CO     05-17 1706
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BERRIES-LEMONS0518-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    It's the berries
 &HT;    By Ann Heller
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ And you thought the perfect partner for
strawberries was whipped cream. We're here to tell you about a
different marriage of flavors.
</P>
<P>
   Strawberries and sweet, tart lemon.
</P>
<P>
   Now don't pucker up.
</P>
<P>
   Think of lemon pound cake topped with berries. Or lemon curd,
lightened with _ yes _ whipped cream or sour cream, tucked in a
puff pastry or phyllo cup and topped with a sliced berry. Or maybe
strawberry-cobbler with a lemon butter cookie crust.
</P>
<P>
   In mid-May in Ohio, we straddle the berry seasons. The
California strawberries will soon give way to the cherished local
crop, which, in deference to a past when this was our only
strawberry season, inevitably sparks the annual debate about
strawberry shortcake.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on where you grew up, or whether your mother could
cook, the argument has two antagonists. One insists on
biscuit-style cakes, which may be either individual, sweetened
biscuits or wedges cut from a large, buttered, cake-pan biscuit.
The other uses sturdy store-bought sponge cakes shaped to hold the
berries.
</P>
<P>
   But there are alternatives. To avoid a family split over the
issue, try a lemon cake, which pairs beautifully with the berries.
</P>
<P>
   Or skip the shortcake entirely and try this much easier dessert.
</P>
<P>
   We'll give you our favorite recipe for making lemon curd below.
But that said, a jar of store-bought lemon curd on the shelf is
insurance that you can fix dessert on a busy day. When buying it,
avoid cheap brands that contain artificial ingredients. The shorter
the ingredient list, the better the product. The Thursday Cottage
and Crabtree and Evelyn brands are good.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with lemon curd in the pantry and some puff pastry shells
in the freezer, all you have to bring home is the strawberries.
And, of course, the whipping cream.
</P>
<P>
   STRAWBERRY-LEMON CREAM TARTS
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup chilled whipping cream
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup prepared lemon curd
</P>
<P>
   1 package puff pastry shells (see alternative preparation below
picture)
</P>
<P>
   1 egg mixed with 1 tablespoon water
</P>
<P>
   Sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 pint strawberries, hulled and sliced to fan out
</P>
<P>
   Whip cream to stiff peaks. Place lemon curd in medium bowl. Stir
in half the whipped cream to lighten the mixture, then fold in
remaining cream, leaving some streaks. The recipe can be prepared
ahead to this point. Cover and refrigerate for up to one day.
</P>
<P>
   Bake four puff pastry shells according to package instructions.
When puffed and golden, remove to a rack to cool. While still warm,
use a fork to lift out the pastry lid and remove and discard any
underbaked dough in the bottom. Let cool completely.
</P>
<P>
   Spoon lemon-cream mixture in tart. Arrange strawberries on top.
Serve with additional strawberries around the pastry shell.
</P>
<P>
   Approximate nutritional analysis per serving: 458 calories, 31.9
fat, 171 mg cholesterol, 296 mg sodium.
</P>
<P>
   (Recipe adapted from Bon Appetit).
</P>
<P>
   How to make a single large tart
</P>
<P>
   To make a single rectangular tart as pictured above, use 1 sheet
puff pastry thawed 20 to 30 minutes at room temperature. Preheat
oven to 350 degrees (note: That is a lower temperature than package
instructions). Roll pastry out on lightly floured surface to
14-by-11-inch rectangle. Cut four 1-inch-wide strips off short side
and four 1-inch strips off long side. Transfer pastry rectangle to
an ungreased cookie sheet. Pierce with fork. Brush with egg glaze.
Arrange 1 pastry strip on each edge of rectangle, trimming as
necessary to form straight edges. Brush top of strips with egg
glaze. Repeat with remaining pastry strips. Brush top of strips
with egg and sprinkle with sugar. Bake tart 5 minutes. Pierce with
fork if puffed. Continue baking until golden brown, about 20
minutes. Cool completely. Continue with recipe at right, using
berries sliced in half.
</P>
<P>
   A colleague I met in a French cooking school shared this recipe
for lemon curd years ago. I thought then, and still do, that curd
is an ugly word and renamed the recipe fresh lemon pudding when it
appeared in It's Simple, my 1980 cookbook. But lemon curd it is.
</P>
<P>
   LEMON CURD
</P>
<P>
   Makes 2 1/2 cups
</P>
<P>
   1 stick (8 tablespoons) unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   3 lemons
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups sugar
</P>
<P>
   3 whole eggs
</P>
<P>
   3 egg yolks
</P>
<P>
   Juice the three lemons and grate the rind of one of them (the
best way to do this is to use a lemon zester).
</P>
<P>
   Melt the butter in the top of a double boiler set over simmering
water. Add the lemon rind and strained juice, the salt and sugar
and mix well with a spoon.
</P>
<P>
   Beat the whole eggs and yolks together with a hand beater. Add
to the lemon-sugar mixture and cook over the simmering (not
boiling) water, stirring from time to time. After about 10 minutes
the mixture will begin to bubble. Stir or whisk constantly until
the pudding is thick and shiny. The white froth will disappear.
</P>
<P>
   Cool the pudding.
</P>
<P>
   (This can be made ahead and refrigerated. Use in the tarts
above, or just mix with some freshly whipped cream for a fresh
summer pudding).
</P>
<P>
   Approximate nutritional analysis per 1/4 cup serving: 249
calories, 12.9 gfat, 154 mg cholesterol, 77 mgsodium.
</P>
<P>
   This recipe, from Gourmet magazine, originally called for lemon
verbena but grated lemon zest is an acceptable substitute.
</P>
<P>
   LEMON POUND CAKE WITH STRAWBERRIES
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 to 10 servings
</P>
<P>
   For cake:
</P>
<P>
   Butter and flour for greasing and dusting pan(s)
</P>
<P>
   1 cup cake flour (not self-rising)
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon baking powder
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons freshly grated lemon zest
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup (1 stick) unsalted butter, softened
</P>
<P>
   1 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   3 eggs
</P>
<P>
   3/4 teaspoon vanilla
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons milk
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons fresh lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   For glaze:
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup plus 1 tablespoon powdered sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon fresh lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   For topping:
</P>
<P>
   4 cups sliced strawberries
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 325 degrees. Grease 1-quart kugelhopf or tube
pan with butter and dust with flour. Invert pan and tap out excess
flour.
</P>
<P>
   In medium bowl, whisk flour, baking powder, salt and lemon zest.
</P>
<P>
   In large bowl of electric mixer, beat butter and sugar until
light and fluffy. Beat in eggs, one at a time, beating well after
each addition; add vanilla and beat until blended. Beat in half
flour mixture. Beat in milk and lemon juice. Beat in flour mixture
until just combined.
</P>
<P>
   Spoon batter into pan, smoothing top. Bake in middle of
preheated oven 45-55 minutes or until golden brown on top and a
tester comes out clean. Cool cake in pan on a rack 15 minutes and
invert onto rack to cool completely.
</P>
<P>
   Prepare glaze while cake is cooling: In small bowl, gradually
whisk powdered sugar into lemon juice until smooth and thick.
</P>
<P>
   When cake is completely cooled, drizzle glaze over cake and let
it drip down sides. Cake can be prepared one day ahead and chilled,
covered. Bring to room temperature before serving.
</P>
<P>
   Cut cake into slices. Top each slice with strawberries. If
desired, sweeten strawberries with a little sugar and allow to sit
10 minutes before using.
</P>
<P>
   The colored outside portion of peel is best removed with a
zester so that no bitter white pith is included.
</P>
<P>
   Approximate nutritional analysis per serving: 196 calories, 8.5
g fat, 68 mg cholesterol, 63 mg sodium.
</P>
<P>
   This recipe is from the new Instant Gratification, No -Hassle
Desserts in Just About No Time by Lauren Chattman (see review on
1C). It's nothing more than sweet strawberries baked under a lemon
cookie crust that crumbles into the juicy fruit when you dig a
spoon in. Serve it with vanilla ice cream.
</P>
<P>
   STRAWBERRY COBBLER WITH A LEMON BUTTER COOKIE CRUST
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings
</P>
<P>
   2 pints fresh strawberries
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup sugar, divided use
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon cornstarch
</P>
<P>
   1 stick unsalted butter, softened
</P>
<P>
   1 large egg yolk
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon pure vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon grated lemon zest
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon baking powder
</P>
<P>
   pinch of salt
</P>
<P>
   1 pint vanilla ice cream, softened a bit
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 375 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Wash strawberries and trim off the stems. If large, cut in half.
Combine the berries with 1/4 cup of the sugar and the cornstarch in
a large bowl. Let stand, stirring occasionally, until the sugar
dissolves, 5 to 7 minutes. While the berries are standing, make the
crust.
</P>
<P>
   With an electric mixer cream together the butter and remaining
1/2 cup sugar until smooth. Beat in the egg yolk, vanilla and lemon
zest, beating until smooth, scraping down the sides of the bowl
with a spatula as necessary. Add the flour, baking powder and salt
and stir just until combined.
</P>
<P>
   Spoon the strawberries into an 8-inch square baking dish. Drop
the dough in rounded tablespoonfuls over the fruit. Bake until the
fruit is bubbling and the crust is golden, 50 to 55 minutes. Let
cool slightly and serve warm with the ice cream.
</P>
<P>
   Approximate nutritional analysis per serving, notncluding ice
cream: 323 calories, 17.6 g fat, 79 mg cholesterol, 20 mg sodium.
</P>
<P>
   Again store bought lemon curd shows up in an easy dessert, this
time thinned to a sauce consistency with yogurt or sour cream. It's
flavored with creme de cassis _ a liqueur found at liquor stores.
</P>
<P>
   STRAWBERRIES AND ORANGES WITH CASSIS-SPIKED LEMON CURD SAUCE
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup purchased lemon curd
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons creme de cassis (black currant-flavored liqueur)
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup plain yogurt, creme fraiche or sour cream (not low-fat
or nonfat)
</P>
<P>
   3 oranges, peel and white pith removed, cut into segments
</P>
<P>
   1 1-pint basket strawberries, hulled, halved
</P>
<P>
   Fresh mint sprigs
</P>
<P>
   Whisk lemon curd and creme de cassis in small bowl to blend.
Stir in yogurt or sour cream. (Sauce can be prepared 2 days ahead.
Cover and refrigerate.)
</P>
<P>
   Combine oranges and strawberries in medium bowl. (Can be
prepared 6 hours ahead. Cover fruit and refrigerate.) Spoon fruit
into balloon wine glasses. Spoon lemon curd sauce over. Garnish
with mint sprigs.
</P>
<P>
   Approximate nutritional analysis per serving: calories, fat,
cholesterol, sodium.
</P>
<P>
   (Recipe from Bon Appetit)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
