<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-LEBANON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAELI TROOPS WITHDRAWING FROM LEBANON OUTPOSTS
</HEADLINE>
 By JOEL GREENBERG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Israeli troops in southern Lebanon have begun
evacuating outposts there in preparation for an overall pullout
from the area by July.
</P>
<P>
   Two outposts well inside the 9-mile-wide strip of territory
controlled by the Israelis were turned over this week to the South
Lebanon Army, or SLA, the Israeli-backed militia in the area.
</P>
<P>
   Other Israeli positions are being emptied of heavy equipment so
they can be evacuated quickly.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, a coastal outpost that had included a naval radar
station at Ras Bayada, on the northwestern edge of the Israeli-held
zone, was evacuated. And on Monday, the Israelis left another
outpost near the village of Taibe.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this stage we've handed over forward positions to the
SLA,'' said a senior Israeli officer who spoke on condition of
anonymity. ``These outposts are very close to villages where the
SLA men live, and will enable them to defend themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   The handovers appear to be designed to enable members of the
Israeli-backed militia to continue functioning as locally based
armed groups after the Israeli withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
   But the future of the SLA fighters, who have been condemned as
traitors by the Lebanese government, remains unclear. The United
Nations, which is likely to take on an enhanced peacekeeping role
in the area after the Israelis depart, is said to be pressing for a
disbanding of the militia.
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli officer said this week's handovers did not signal an
acceleration of the timetable for the Israeli withdrawal, which is
supposed to be completed by July. ``This is all according to the
plan,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The army apparently intends to relinquish outlying positions
that are more difficult to reach and defend in preparation for a
quick withdrawal from outposts closer to Israel. The process will
gradually leave fewer soldiers exposed to attacks by guerrillas of
the Party of God, who have been fighting a war of attrition to oust
the Israelis from southern Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   The guerrillas have kept up their assaults this week, shelling
Israeli outposts just over the border with Lebanon. Israeli
officers say they are planning for a possible withdrawal under
fire.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the fighting nearby, preparations for the pullback are
in full swing along Israel's border with Lebanon. Frontier fences
that were built inside Lebanese territory are being moved back to
the boundary, military outposts jutting into Lebanon are being
relocated, and mines that were laid across the border are being
removed.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to improve the morale of jittery residents of Israeli
border settlements who fear that the withdrawal will leave them
exposed to guerrilla attacks, Prime Minister Ehud Barak announced
Wednesday a government aid package for their communities. The $400
million program includes sewage, water and road projects,
assistance to schools and business incentives.
</P>
</TEXT>
