<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 19:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8099 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-HARLEM-DANCE-ART-$ADV     05-17 0657
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HARLEM-DANCE-ART-$ADV21-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-346-9867.)
</HEADLINE>
  
 ANOTHER REUNION OF MR. B's DIVERSE PROGENY  
 (For release Sun., May 21)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or By JENNIFER DUNNING    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Dance Theater of Harlem celebrates its 30th
anniversary this year. The classical ballet company was founded by
Arthur Mitchell, a leading dancer with the New York City Ballet at
the time, in response to the assassination of the Rev. Dr. Martin
Luther King Jr. George Balanchine and Lincoln Kirstein, the
founders of City Ballet, encouraged Mitchell to start the troupe.
</P>
<P>
   City Ballet will salute the company in three shared programs on
May 25, 27 and 28 at the New York State Theater . The two companies
performed together at the State Theater in 1971. This week's event
will include a new ballet, ``Tributary,'' choreographed by Robert
Garland of Dance Theater and Robert La Fosse of City Ballet, as
well as performances of Balanchine's ``Agon'' and ``Slaughter on
Tenth Avenue,'' two works associated with Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   In late March, Mitchell and Peter Martins, a principal dancer at
City Ballet who became artistic director of the company after
Balanchine's death in 1983, talked with Jennifer Dunning of The New
York Times backstage at the State Theater about the joys and perils
of directing ballet troupes. Here are excerpts from a conversation
punctuated by roars of laughter and sympathetic murmurs.
</P>
<P>
   PETER MARTINS. What I often wonder, when I look back, is what it
must have been like for B. when he started. What is the hardest
thing: to establish something, to start from scratch, build
something where there was nothing before? Or to maintain a colossal
institution that requires so much attention in so many areas?
Probably the toughest thing is to start something.
</P>
<P>
   ARTHUR MITCHELL. Well, it's something like six of one and half a
dozen of the other. You have to have a maniacal belief in what
you're doing. In the final analysis, I think the common denominator
is the vision that we're all after. All of us want the best that we
can do in the art form. We are in service, not servants, but in
service to the art form. And once you understand that, everything
else begins to fall in place.
</P>
<P>
   I look back at some of the things that B. and Lincoln were
criticized for. Everyone says they want change, but when you try to
change something they just resist you all the time. I think that
tenacity rubbed off on us.
</P>
<P>
   JENNIFER DUNNING. How did you feel when you realized you were
going to do this? Terror? Excitement?
</P>
<P>
   MARTINS. I never felt terror. Not one moment in my life. I don't
know why. Excitement? No. Neither excitement nor terror. It was
much more like it was the right thing. I had to do it. It was
almost my calling.
</P>
<P>
   MITCHELL. You don't think in terms of terror. There is a sense
of excitement. But you know this is the right thing to do and you
are consumed with it. There are moments when you think, Oh, Lord,
why me? But you are doing what you love to do. How many people ever
get that opportunity?
</P>
<P>
   DUNNING. What were your earliest priorities?
</P>
<P>
   MARTINS. The very first thing that I thought of was stability.
Somebody like George Balanchine passes away and you've got an
organization here where everybody's sobbing and a lot of you
couldn't even get to work. I've never seen such despair, and such
misery, when he died, within these walls. Myself included. But
there was no time to dwell on it. We had to go onstage two hours
later. So life had to go on. My priority was to try to create an
environment in which we could just go on. It was very important to
put calmness on the agenda. To provide leadership that did not
introduce change. I wanted continuation. And I wanted the natural
time to go by. That was very very important to me.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   MITCHELL. With the assassination of Dr. King, I was driving
through the streets of Harlem and I saw all this unrest and
unhappiness. How could we funnel this into something that will be
constructive, not destructive? The arts. And particularly dance,
because it's so physical. And I said, ``Well, let me take the
education I've had downtown with the New York City Ballet,
Balanchine, Lincoln, all my colleagues, and start what could be
like a haven, where young people can come in and get that sense of
discipline and structure in their lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Not every child is going to be an artist or be a dancer. But
they're learning how to live by doing. That sense of loss, of
giving a sense of purpose, is what we're all about. When the
physical entity has been taken away, you've got to put something in
its place. And that is when you have to do what you do well.
</P>
<P>
   DUNNING. What are the priorities today?
</P>
<P>
   MITCHELL. Survival. It was a challenge years ago to prove that a
dancer can be an administrator or fund-raiser. But that's not my
goal. The Arthur Mitchell of 31 years ago and the Arthur Mitchell
of today are totally different persons. I've only gone through high
school. I've never been to college. So I don't know what Harvard
Business School would do. I know what I would do.
</P>
<P>
   MARTINS. I would second Arthur by saying survival is always the
No. 1 priority in the world in which we live. On the other hand,
considering that it's been 17 years since B. died, and considering
the health and the state of affairs of the New York City Ballet,
both artistically and financially, and public attendance and so
forth, I don't think it is premature to say that we sort of did
survive. I look at the dancers and they're as fine as they've ever
been, if not better. I look at the management team. It is
extraordinary. I look at quality of life in this theater that has
improved so vastly.
</P>
<P>
   I would say that the next thing I wish more than anything is new
repertory. I think it is vitally important for the New York City
Ballet to be able to identify _ or help identify _ choreographers
of the future. To be able to create a repertory for the future that
will appeal to today's public, and beyond that, I think is sort of
my mandate.
</P>
<P>
   DUNNING. What are the most enjoyable and troublesome aspects of
running a company today?
</P>
<P>
   MARTINS. Just yesterday or the day before, I taught class. And
Arthur's and my own company kids were there. And there was
something unbelievably enjoyable about being in that studio for an
hour and a half trying to give these kids everything I know, that I
had learned from Balanchine and elsewhere. And see how they soaked
it up, with enthusiasm and hunger. That was a moment of great,
great pleasure. Another moment is just to be in a studio
choreographing with some of the best dancers anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   MITCHELL. Teaching, choreographing, coaching, working. All the
other aspects are very intriguing but not really what you're about.
For myself, I do it because I have to do it. At one time it was a
challenge. But I've proven that, to myself anyway. So consequently
I'd like to get back to what I should be about.
</P>
<P>
   DUNNING. Troubles?
</P>
<P>
   MARTINS. I never look at things as trouble. There are things I
don't enjoy as much. I don't particularly love staying behind my
desk and I basically don't ever do that. I sort of run around with
papers in my hand. Running this company is like a puzzle. Every
little piece works together. I love to deal with marketing. It
fascinates me. But if I only did marketing, I'd go crazy. The fact
is I can do that for an hour, and then go in and choreograph, and
then run in and teach, and then go to a board meeting, and then
have a fund-raising event. So I don't know if there's anything _
yes, the only thing I cannot bear is 8:30 morning meetings!
Especially now that I am a suburbanite.
</P>
<P>
   MITCHELL. Yes, yes! I understand! Basically, we're night people.
</P>
<P>
   DUNNING. Is this a somewhat lonely job?
</P>
<P>
   MITCHELL. It's the aloneness of the long distance runner. If you
are leading the pack, everyone is running behind you and looking at
the back of your head. Occasionally, you'd like to look to the side
and see somebody there.
</P>
<P>
   MARTINS. I don't feel lonely. But there are very, very tough
decisions to be made. You have obviously a few people whom you
trust and you ask advice and so forth. There have been two or three
times in my life here when I thought: ``What would B. have done?
What would Lincoln have advised?'' Those are the tough moments, I
think. You go in and you close your door.
</P>
<P>
   DUNNING. Have there been things Balanchine or Kirstein said that
proved particularly helpful?
</P>
<P>
   MITCHELL. B. used to say to me all the time: ``No, dear, don't
listen to anybody. Don't take anybody's advice.'' Just do what you
think is right. You will make mistakes. But at least you did what
you believed.
</P>
<P>
   DUNNING. What might Balanchine say looking down on you and your
two companies today?
</P>
<P>
   MITCHELL. ``Very good, my son.''
</P>
<P>
   MARTINS. Who knows? But I'd like to think that B. might say,
``You know, my dear, I can't tell you.'' And then he would probably
say, ``No, not perfect, but still, amazing.'' That's what I think
he would say. And you know what? He should be saying that.
</P>
<P>
   DUNNING. Should the Balanchine repertory be preserved in part by
having dancers coach the roles they created?
</P>
<P>
   MARTINS. It depends. Can you remove yourself enough from when
you danced the role? Once there was a very famous dancer here,
coming and coaching another very famous dancer, in a very famous
role. And I can tell you, B. had a fit. He said: ``He did it that
way, and that was great for him. This one should do it his way.''
</P>
<P>
   MITCHELL. And the thing is, when you're dancing B.'s
choreography, it's all in the music.
</P>
<P>
   MARTINS. There is a very famous ballet in this company,
originated by a very famous ballerina, that has very famous images.
And you know what? Those images were mannerisms. If you were not
present when these things occurred, you automatically assume that
that is the choreography. And I remember B.'s saying, ``I didn't
choreograph that.'' I could go on and on and on about these famous
or, if you want to call them infamous, stories. Don't forget, we
were here. And the people who are writing about it, they don't know
these things.
</P>
<P>
   MITCHELL. These are the moments that you asked about earlier.
It's not loneliness, it's making decisions.
</P>
<P>
   DUNNING. Are you preparing successors?
</P>
<P>
   MARTINS. I'm not looking for a successor at all. I find myself
very useful and vigorous. On the other hand, from the day I started
I looked for people who might have the inclination to devote their
life to what I have been doing in my life. But no one has emerged.
</P>
<P>
   MITCHELL. There's a hunger. There's something inside people. You
can't stop it. And all you can say is: ``Pick my brain. Learn from
me. I'll give you all the opportunities. But then are you willing
to devote your life to this?'' Everything else is going to take
second place. B. and Lincoln said I would never sleep again. Not
that I think I'm going any place, because I asked the powers above
to please take me away and they said: ``Not yet, my son. You've got
much more to do.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
