<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PERSONALS: Packing Well Is the Best Revenge
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file.) &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By LEAH GARCHIK &QC;  &LR; 
 &UR; c.2000, San Francisco Chronicle &LR;  &QC; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Moving way past the notion that good things come in small packages,
 &UR; George Leonard &LR;  gripes about growing numbers of tantalizing
packages that are almost impossible to open. Leonard suggests an
annual Packy Award Ceremony, honoring the living proofs of the
principle: ``The Package, Not the Product.'' Packies should be
decided, he suggests, on the following point system based on
whether the package meets the following criteria:
</P>
<P>
   _ Costs at least as much as the product it contains, 2 points.
</P>
<P>
   _ Costs twice as much as the product, 5 points.
</P>
<P>
   _ Requires simple tools (kitchen knives, nail files) to open, 5
points.
</P>
<P>
   _ Damages the product while being opened, 10 points.
</P>
<P>
   _ Destroys the product, 25 points.
</P>
<P>
   _ Slightly injures the consumer attempting to open it, 25
points.
</P>
<P>
   _ Seriously injures the consumer, 50 points.
</P>
<P>
   _ Kills the consumer, 100 points.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; POLANSKI'S PAST &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Roman Polanski &LR; , who emigrated from Europe to America, then
moved back to avoid prosecution for having sex with a minor, talked
with the Telegraph of London about his childhood experiences, which
included hiding with Polish peasants during World War II. His
mother was killed at Auschwitz.
</P>
<P>
   He said that  &UR; Steven Spielberg &LR;  offered him ``Schindler's List''
to direct. ``I said, `No, I have lived with those people. I have
walked those sidewalks. I cannot turn it into a film, I cannot make
it entertainment.' '' (In addition to ``Schindler,'' Spielberg will
be executive producer of a three-hour TV film about  &UR; Anne Frank &LR; ,
based on  &UR; Melissa Muller &LR; 's biography.)
</P>
<P>
   After the war, said Polanski, he joined the Boy Scouts. ``I
remember running through the woods with the other boys, playing
games. It was a good organization. I took it very seriously. It
gave me my identity. I learned its virtues, its values.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Woody Allen &LR;  has included a piece by his father-in-law,
 &UR; Andre &LR; 
 &UR; Previn &LR; , in the soundtrack album for his new movie, ``Small Time
Crooks,'' says Fox 411.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Betsy Nolan &LR; , just back from Australia, clipped a story from
the Australian Financial Review about an Action on Smoking and
Health protest: ``Mr. Butts, the giant cigarette, will be there, as
will the Laryngectomy Choir (men and women without voice boxes),
which will perform its version of `Smoke Gets in Your Eyes.' ''
</P>
<P>
   _ You thought the Webbys were cutting edge? Visiting the recent
Electronic Entertainment Expo in Los Angeles,  &UR; Sir Real &LR;  peeked at
Conker's Bad Fur Day, a video game that features a randy squirrel
capable of a range of bodily functions including optibazoomation,
when ``its eyes pop out of his head at the sight of a dimbo's (a
digitally generated bimbo) 64DDD digitally enhanced swelling bikini
breasts. The game is rated M for Mature.''
</P>
<P>
   _ That Kiss event at Butterfields is only a preview, and it
lasts all weekend. The auction itself is in late June in Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Jennifer Schooley &LR; , who lives in the Napa Valley, writes to
say she has won first and second places in the international
contest to design a logo for  &UR; Guy Williams &LR;  2000. Williams, who
played Zorro on TV, is to be honored on Sunday, May 21, as the
first-ever posthumous inductee into the Bronx Walk of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   _ For a low-cost vacation, Family Money suggests ``the no-frills
house swap'' in which you trade for two weeks ``with the next-door
neighbors. Enjoy a change of scenery without the crippling outlay.
And no annoying currency conversions, either.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; BOBBY BROWN IS &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; ONE LIBERAL GUY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Whitney Houston &LR;  was in the middle of an interview with a
reporter from the gay magazine Out when her husband,  &UR; Bobby &LR; 
 &UR; Brown &LR; , dropped by for a bit of banter. The husband and wife teased
each other, then she bellowed at him, ``Get outta here! Crazy
man!''
</P>
<P>
   Brown left and Houston, jolly and open-minded, gasped to the
interviewer, ``He is so sick. I love him. He don't give a s_ that
you're gay.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``As Gen Xers become more economically dominant, they become &LR; 
 &UR; more comfortable in using their private gestures in the &LR; 
 &UR; workplace.'' &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Margot Magowan &LR;  in a Vanity Fair story about the hipness of
hugging. Magowan, a San Franciscan, is founder of the feminist
Woodhull Institute.
</P>
