A8108 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-EDITORIAL-CRABS-BOS &LR;      05-17 0382
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-CRABS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNREASONABLE BAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The horseshoe crab is a textbook case of an ancient inhabitant
of planet Earth providing a substance of critical importance to a
much later arrival _ human beings. Thirty years ago, a researcher
at the Woods Hole Oceanographic Institute discovered that something
in the horseshoe crab's blood had an uncanny ability to detect
bacterial remains that can be left on medical equipment or in
intravenous solutions, even after sterilization.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the great majority of medical-supply companies worldwide
do their testing for bacterial contamination with the Limulus
Amebocyte Lysate made from the blood of the horseshoe crab, which
sells for $1,000 a liter. The animal, whose pedigree goes back to
the dinosaurs and the primitive coelacanth fish, is clearly earning
its keep and deserves close protection. That said, the US Interior
Department should rethink its recent ban on the use for bleeding of
crabs off the Cape Cod National Seashore and the Monomoy National
Wildlife Refuge.
</P>
<P>
   The real threat is from fishermen who use the crabs for bait,
not from lysate-producing companies like Associates of Cape Cod.
The Falmouth firm, one of four in the field in the United States,
draws about 30 percent of the crabs' blood and then returns them
alive to the waters whence they came. About 60 percent of its crabs
come from the now off-limits areas.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1980s, the Food and Drug Administration did a study
indicating that the mortality rate for crabs that have been bled is
about 10 percent higher than normal. Since then, an official of
Associates of Cape Cod says, the conditions for bleeding crabs have
improved, and the mortality rate could well be lower.
</P>
<P>
   The practice of bleeding and returning crabs has been going on
for 25 years, but the Cape Cod National Seashore now says it must
be stopped because the seashore's enabling legislation prohibits
the removal of wildlife for private commercial gain. That is an
eminently sound rule, but in a case like this, with a clear social
benefit and in which the wildlife are not intentionally killed, it
should be possible for the Interior secretary to justify a special,
limited permit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
