u a BC-SCI-DIET-HYPERTENSION     05-17 0587
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-DIET-HYPERTENSION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOW-SALT DIET FOUND TO BE AS EFFECTIVE AS DRUGS AGAINST HIGH BLOOD
PRESSURE 
</HEADLINE>
   By DENISE GRADY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A diet low in salt and high in fruits, vegetables and low-fat
dairy products can lower blood pressure as much as medication can,
researchers reported Wednesday, confirming earlier work showing
that diet can help to treat high blood pressure.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers urged that people with hypertension adopt the
diet, and, in a more controversial recommendation, said that
healthy people should follow it, too, to prevent hypertension. The
diet lowered blood pressure in both groups, though the benefit was
greater in those with high blood pressure, who achieved reductions
averaging 11.5/5.7 millimeters of mercury.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 50 million Americans have high blood pressure, defined as
readings consistently higher than 140/90 millimeters of mercury, or
130/85 in diabetics. Readings below 120/80 are considered optimal,
and those between 120/80 and 140/90 are called ``high normal.''
Untreated, the condition increases the risk of stroke, heart attack
and kidney failure.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the availability of drugs to lower blood pressure,
hypertension is often ignored or poorly controlled.
</P>
<P>
   The diet in the study contained less than half as much salt as
most Americans eat, and subjects had all their meals prepared for
them by dietitians. The researchers said they did not know whether
most people, cooking for themselves and eating in restaurants,
would be able to stick to such a diet. The scientists called on the
food industry to lower the amount of salt in processed foods to
make it easier for people to comply.
</P>
<P>
   Previous calls to limit salt in healthy people have provoked
heated debate, with some scientists arguing that the resulting
blood pressure reductions, if any, were too small to be worth the
trouble.
</P>
<P>
   But the authors of the study said their findings proved that
restricting salt was beneficial. The scientists, led by Dr. Frank
Sacks of the Harvard Medical School, announced their findings on
Wednesday in New York at a meeting of the American Society of
Hypertension.
</P>
<P>
   The National Heart, Lung, and Blood Institute, which supported
the $11.8 million study, issued a statement from its director, Dr.
Claude Lenfant, saying that the study had proved once and for all
that reducing salt in the diet helps everyone, even people who do
not have hypertension.
</P>
<P>
   ``The finding suggests than an intake below that now recommended
could help many Americans prevent the blood pressure rises that now
occur with advancing age,'' Dr. Lenfant said.
</P>
<P>
   The study, called DASH-Sodium, for Dietary Approaches to Stop
Hypertension, included 412 people, aged 22 and older. About 57
percent were female, and 57 percent were black; blacks have a
higher risk of hypertension than whites. About 41 percent had
hypertension, and the rest were ``high-normal,'' above 120/80.
</P>
<P>
   They ate either their normal diet, but with varying amounts of
salt, or a special DASH diet, also with varying amounts of salt and
including five cups of fruits and vegetables and three cups of
low-fat dairy products per day. The sodium levels from the salt
were 1.5 grams, 2.4 grams or 3.3 grams a day. Most Americans eat
3.5 grams a day, the amount in about 1.5 teaspoons of table salt.
</P>
<P>
   The DASH diet alone and sodium restriction alone both lowered
blood pressure, but the greatest reduction came when the special
diet was combined with the lowest level of sodium.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
