<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-BANK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. INVESTMENT FIRM EXPECTED TO TAKE OVER A FAILED JAPANESE BANK 
</HEADLINE>
   By STEPHANIE STROM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ The Japanese government is expected to announce as early
as Thursday that W.L. Ross &AMP; Co., an investment concern run by the
American bankruptcy specialist Wilbur L. Ross _ together with a
unit of Daiwa Securities _ has been chosen to take over Kofuku
Bank, a regional bank in Osaka that failed in May 1999, people
close to the deal said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The sale signals that contrary to recent speculation, Japan has
not closed the door to potential acquisitions of banks by
foreigners.
</P>
<P>
   Ross has been one of the most committed investors in Asia since
financial crisis shook the region in 1997 and 1998, promoting his
vision of the opportunities that lay in ``vulture investing'' there
_ the purchase of distressed assets.
</P>
<P>
   As senior managing director at Rothschild Ltd., a position he
held before starting his own firm earlier this year, he pledged $1
billion to revive the bankrupt Halla group in South Korea, and
together with Daiwa, he invested in a bankrupt auto parts supplier
in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Banking industry analysts say that Japanese regional banks badly
need to consolidate and lower costs, but progress has been slow. A
string of smaller banks _ Tokyo Sowa Bank, Kokumin Bank, Niigata
Chuo Bank and Kofuku _ went under last year, in spite of the
availability of public funds dedicated to help faltering financial
institutions. Kofuku failed with 52.3 billion yen _ $428 million at
then-exchange rates _ in excess liabilities.
</P>
<P>
   The emergence of foreign-backed buyers in the marketplace may
accelerate the pace of change by intensifying competition. There
have been rumors that Ripplewood Holdings LLC of New York, a buyout
firm that was the lead investor in a group that purchased the
insolvent Long-Term Credit Bank last year, is interested in buying
Tokyo Sowa.
</P>
<P>
   Ross has said previously that he saw merit in cobbling together
a stable of small regional Japanese banks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-17-00 1925EDT &QL; 
