u a BC-CLINTON-BINLADEN-BOS &LR;      05-17 0969
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-BINLADEN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON PAINTS GRIM WORLD SCENARIO FOR COAST GUARD GRADS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANN SCALES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW LONDON, Conn. _ President Clinton Wednesday presented his
most sweeping argument for how the explosion of technology and the
openness of America's borders pose new challenges and dangers for
the nation, and said it was time for the country to be prepared for
the prospect of biological and chemical warfare.
</P>
<P>
   In a somber and foreboding 34-minute commencement address at the
US Coast Guard Academy, Clinton accused Osama bin Laden, the
Afghanistan-based Islamic militant, of plotting terrorist attacks
against the United States on New Year's Eve and called the ``Love
Bug'' computer virus no accident. He also warned of the dangers of
global warming, noting that nine out of the 10 warmest years since
the 15th century were recorded in the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   US officials previously have linked bin Laden to New Year's Eve
bomb plots. Clinton, having largely avoided public statements about
the threat, Wednesday offered his most extensive comments on the
subject.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last December, working with Jordan, we shut down a plot to
place large bombs at locations where Americans might gather on New
Year's Eve,'' he said. ``We learned this plot was linked to
terrorist camps in Afghanistan, and the organization created by
Osama bin Laden, the man responsible for the 1998 bombings of our
embassies in Tanzania and Kenya, which cost the lives of Americans
and hundreds of Africans.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said a US Customs agent in Seattle discovered bomb
materials being smuggled into this country from Canada, the same
material he said was used by bin Laden in other places.
``Thankfully, and thanks to Jordan, New Year's passed without an
attack. But the threat was real, and we had to cooperate with them,
with the Canadians, with others throughout the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton called his address to the 190 graduating cadets, their
families, faculty, and friends gathered at Memorial Field on the
sunny west bank of the Thames River ``nostalgic'' because it is the
last one he will deliver as president to a graduating class of a
military service academy.
</P>
<P>
   During his speech, Clinton announced that he is adding $300
million on top of the $9 billion in funding for counterterrorism
that is contained in his 2001 budget. ``It sounds like a lot of
money,'' he said. ``When you see the evidence of what we're up
against, I think you will support it.''
</P>
<P>
   The extra $300 million would be used for such measures as
tighter surveillance along the US-Canada border, including the
installation of high-resolution cameras and other advanced
monitoring equipment, the White House said. Among the other steps
are stronger efforts to track the financing of terrorist
organizations and increasing the number of Joint Terrorism Task
Forces, which combine the efforts of federal and local agencies, to
37 from 26.
</P>
<P>
   He said that the same technology that gave this country ``the
marvelous possibilities of the Internet also apparently empowered a
student sitting in the Philippines to launch a computer virus that
in just a few hours spread through more than 10 million computers
and caused billions of dollars in damage.''
</P>
<P>
   Recalling a satellite malfunction two years ago that disabled
pagers, ATMs, credit-card systems, and TV and radio networks around
the world, he said: ``That was an accident. The Love Bug was not an
accident.
</P>
<P>
   ``The central reality of our time is that the advent of
globalization and the revolution in information technology have
magnified both the creative and the destructive potential of every
individual, tribe, and nation on our planet,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While international terrorism is not new, Clinton said it has
become more sophisticated. ``Terrorist networks communicate on the
World Wide Web, too. Available weapons are becoming more
destructive and more miniaturized, just as the size of cellular
phones and computers is shrinking _ shrinking to the point where a
lot of you with large hands like mine wonder if you'll be able to
work the things before long.
</P>
<P>
   ``You should understand that the same process of miniaturization
will find its way into the development of biological and chemical,
and maybe, even nuclear weapons. And it is something we have to be
ready for,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also said climate change could become ``a national
security challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless we change course and reverse global greenhouse gas
emissions, most scientists are convinced that storms and droughts
will intensify as the globe continues to warm, crop patterns will
be disrupted, food supplies will be affected, the seas will rise so
high they will swallow islands and coastal area,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The president also said the world is threatened by infections
from malaraia, tuberculosis, and AIDS, as well as narco-trafficking
and drugs. And he included his push for permanent trade relations
with China into his warning about global threats, as Congress
prepares to vote next week on whether to give such status to the
world's most-populous nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a national security issue for stability in Asia, peace
in the Taiwan Straits, possible cooperation with China to advance
freedom and human rights within the country, and to retard the
proliferation of dangerous weapons,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he disagreed with the notion that the United States
doesn't need to play such an active role in the world since the end
of the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
   He said: ``America has been called a shining city on a hill;
that doesn't mean our oceans are moats; it doesn't mean our country
is a fortress. If we wait to act until problems come home to
America, problems are far more likely to come to America.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
