<SLUG> BC-WAFFLE-BIAS0518-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Waffle House motion to move racial bias case denied by judge
 &HT;    By Shelia M. Poole
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A U.S. District Court judge has denied a motion by
Norcross, Ga. -based Waffle House Inc. to move a racial
discrimination case to South Carolina from Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys for the 24-hour restaurant chain argued that plaintiff
Jesse E. Gantt Jr. lives in South Carolina and that many of the key
witnesses live there and outside the area served by the court in
the Northern District of Georgia. Additionally, the company lawyers
argued that the case should be moved to South Carolina because the
alleged discrimination occurred there.
</P>
<P>
   In denying the request, Judge Willis B. Hunt Jr. said that
regardless of where Gantt lives, he ``clearly maintains at least
some significant ties to this district.''
</P>
<P>
   Hunt cited the number of witnesses who work at the company's
Norcross office and documents housed there that might be relevant
to the case.
</P>
<P>
   Gantt claims he was fired for refusing to comply with a
directive from his supervisors to change the racial makeup of his
restaurant staff by firing black employees and replacing them with
whites. ``There are two sides to every story,'' said Waffle House
spokesman Chris Jacobsen.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe the evidence presented will speak for itself and
will not support Mr. Gantt's allegations.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
