<SLUG> BC-CHINA-TRADE-LOBBY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINA TRADE VOTE A TEST OF HIGH-TECH LOBBYING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Mass.)  (Eds: See also CHINA-TRADE, CHINA-TRADE-CLINTON) 
 By LIZETTE ALVAREZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Next week's congressional vote on whether to expand
trade and economic ties with Beijing has high stakes for China and
the Clinton administration, but it is also a test of the political
clout of the technology industry.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, technology companies are playing a leading
role in Washington lobbying over a geopolitical issue. For several
months, executives from Silicon Valley and other technology-rich
areas have been combing the halls of Congress, lobbying for what
they say will be billions of dollars of expanded exports to China
as well as new jobs for Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Whether to grant China permanent normal trade relations is going
to be ``the most important vote of this decade,'' said David
McCurdy, a former Democratic congressman who is the president of
Electronic Industries Alliance, a trade association. ``The industry
will support people who support high-tech.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearly a dozen chief executives made the rounds again on
Wednesday. And a few companies have gone a step further: They have
run radio and television advertisements and conducted grass-roots
campaigns, nudging thousands of their employees to write letters
and send electronic messages to lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   Although they are relative novices in the political arena,
technology concerns are using big business and organized labor as
models for how to press undecided members of Congress to vote for
the China bill. Their deep involvement is in stark contrast to the
detachment they showed three years ago, during the debate on
granting the United States greater trading power.
</P>
<P>
   Previously, high-tech companies lobbied most visibly on narrower
issues, including Internet privacy, data scrambling and
immigration. Microsoft has become a player in Washington's arena of
money and politics, but mostly to protect its interests in the
antitrust battle. In the past, few high-tech companies had large
lobbying presences in the capital. This time around, the industry
has unleashed scores of lobbyists and has banded together in
powerful coalitions.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, their trade associations are employing the
kind of hardball tactics, including advertising, that have served
other industries well in other lobbying wars, working closely with
the U.S. Chamber of Commerce, the agriculture sector and companies
like Boeing, all experienced in past fights involving trade with
China.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Coleman, a spokesman for the Chamber of Commerce, welcomed
the help from high-tech companies. ``They've thrown themselves into
this battle in a strong and aggressive way, and I think they are
picking up the game very quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert A. Kapp, president of the U.S.-China Business Council, an
umbrella group of 300 companies from diverse sectors, said the
China issue has led to ``a massive energizing of the technology
field.'' Their effort, he said, has been especially helpful in the
campaign to sway Democrats, a party with close ties to labor.
</P>
<P>
   These new lobbyists have been effective, lawmakers and others
say. By emphasizing the power of the Internet, lobbyists have been
selling a message that goes beyond their bottom line, stressing
that the products they would export would spread democracy in
China.
</P>
<P>
   And unlike organized labor and big corporations, technology
companies have no firm loyalties and are considered up-for-grabs by
both parties. Their popularity on Capitol Hill has translated into
easy access.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the lobbying of high-tech executives pales next to
organized labor's whirlwind approach and its grass-roots army. And
they lag behind their more experienced big business allies. ``They
are catching up,'' said Rep. David Dreier, R-Calif., a technology
booster. ``But anyone juxtaposed to the organization that labor has
put together, it's tough.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Martin Meehan, D-Mass., said many of the technology
companies in his district are still not politically engaged.
</P>
<P>
   ``They do have a way to go,'' said Meehan, who is undecided on
the bill, referring to the technology industry. ``Labor certainly
knows how to do it more effectively.''
</P>
<P>
   Intel Corp. has dispatched its chairman, Andy Grove, and Craig
R. Barrett, chief executive, to Capitol Hill. The company has also
run radio and newspaper ads and set up a grass-roots campaign
through the company Web site. Within 48 hours, 5,000 of its
employees sent letters to their lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   Motorola has also plunged money into the battle, running
television advertisements.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Rush Holt, D-N.J., who is facing a tough re-election
battle, has a host of high-tech companies in his district and has
been courted by the industry, in part because he is a scientist. He
spent one evening taking a technology tour of a New Jersey plant,
where he met with executives from Sony, Intel and Hewlett-Packard.
</P>
<P>
   Holt remains unconvinced that more trade with China is the
cure-all proponents make it out to be. ``It's as if trade is the
most important thing,'' Holt said. ``And I don't think Americans
necessarily think so.''  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
