<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LYCOS-WETHERELL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CMGI'S WETHERELL LOVES LYCOS DEAL, EVEN IF WALL STREET DOESN'T 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER J. HOWE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Initial investor giddiness over the planned $12.5 billion
takeover of Waltham-based Web portal Lycos Inc. by Spain's leading
phone company gave way to a punishing selloff on Wall Street
Wednesday, with Lycos shares plunging over 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   A day after the stock-swap deal was announced, Wall Street
betrayed concerns about the risks of owning a foreign stock and
fears that shares of acquirer Terra S.A. may be wildly overvalued.
Lycos sunk by just over $15 a share to $57.609 in Nasdaq trading.
Some 32.8 million Lycos shares changed hands, making it the second
most heavily traded US stock Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   But CMGI Inc., an Internet venture capital company in Andover,
Mass. that has seen the $3.8 million it invested in Lycos beginning
in 1995 swell on paper to over $700 million, indicated support for
the deal. CMGI's Lycos stake would be worth nearly $1.2 billion if
the deal goes through at its announced price.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, CMGI and its chairman, David Wetherell, helped
torpedo a planned takeover of Lycos by home shopping concern USA
Networks, charging that the proposed $17 billion combination
undervalued Lycos.
</P>
<P>
   This time, however, Wetherell ``thought it was a very well
architected deal (with Terra), and he has voiced his broad support
for it,'' Wetherell's spokeswoman, Deidre Moore, said Wednesday.
``His general feeling on the deal was it was very positive for both
parties, but he did not say how he was going to vote his shares.''
</P>
<P>
   Moore said CMGI owns just under 12 million shares of Lycos, down
from a reported 16 million last October, and has invested $3.8
million since June 1995. As of Wednesday evening, that stake was
worth about $700 million.
</P>
<P>
   Lycos is the fourth most popular portal site for Web surfing,
with over 32 million individual visitors in March. By most
accounts, it is the best known Internet company in Massachusetts,
employing more than 600 people at its Waltham headquarters and
Williamstown subsidiaries that are being moved to Waltham.
</P>
<P>
   Its planned combination with Terra, a majority-owned unit of
Spanish-based telephone giant Telefonica SA, would create a global
Internet company with over $2 billion in cash and access to the
huge book, music and film content of Bertelesmann AG, Lycos's
German-based Web partner.
</P>
<P>
   Terra Lycos Inc. would have a presence in 37 countries, an
expected 50 million daily visitors and yearly revenues of over $500
million. But analysts noted the combination would be far from
dominant on any continent.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street's fear Wednesday appeared to be that the Terra stock
Lycos owners would get may plunge in value by the time the deal
closes this fall. That uncertainty lowers the value of owning Lycos
stock now.
</P>
<P>
   The deal was valued initially to give Lycos owners stock in
Terra worth $97.55 per share of Lycos stock, subject to a so-called
collar, capping the maximum Terra stock to be swapped at 2.15
shares for each Lycos share.
</P>
<P>
   Fears that by fall, when the deal is scheduled to close, 2.15
shares of Terra could be worth well under the $97.55 fueled the
Lycos selloff, investors said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get shares instead of cash, you have to have a
discount because of that,'' said Brian Grove, a principal with
Vaughan, Nelson, Scarborough McCullough LP of Houston, which owns
55,000 Lycos shares.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Wallace, a UBS Warburg LLC analyst who cut Lycos from a
buy to a hold rating, said, ``You have people who don't want to own
foreign equities, who won't stick around for the deal.'' Wallace
added that Warburg is advising Lycos owners ``to move on.''
</P>
<P>
   Merrill Lynch also downgraded its rating on Terra shares, with
analyst Peter Bradshaw stating that ``we expect the premium paid
for Lycos way outweighs the synergies gained'' by combining the
companies. Terra's bid values Lycos at over twice what Lycos was
trading at before takeover talk surfaced last week.
</P>
<P>
   In Madrid trading Wednesday, Terra shares fell 6.2 euros to
55.80, down 60 percent from its record close on Feb. 25. Terra's
US-traded shares fell $6.5625 to $47.
</P>
<P>
   Anxiety over Terra's value comes amid an ongoing Internet
meltdown. The Bloomberg index of 300 Internet companies has plunged
45 percent since its record high on March 9.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, Lycos reported better-than-expected profits for its
most recent fiscal quarter, with revenues up 120 percent and
adjusted profits up to $7.9 million from a $1 million loss a year
ago. The 7 cents a share in earnings beat a Wall Street consensus
projection for Lycos of 5 cents, according to First Call/Thomson.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Wire service material was used to prepare this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
