<HEADER>
A8129 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-REAL-SIMPLE-RESIGN-NY     05-17 0390
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REAL-SIMPLE-RESIGN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANAGING EDITOR OF REAL SIMPLE, WOMEN'S MAGAZINE FROM TIME INC.,
QUITS 
</HEADLINE>
   By ALEX KUCZYNSKI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In a management shake-up that shows that even the
most promising publishing team does not always guarantee a smooth
start-up, the managing editor of Real Simple _ a new magazine from
Time Inc. for women who want to simplify their lives _ resigned
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The departure of the editor, Susan Wyland, comes after only two
issues of the magazine, both of which have been criticized by some
advertisers as overly spare and unwelcoming. Wyland, a former
editor of Martha Stewart Living, was encouraged to leave by a group
of senior Time Inc. executives headed by Ann S. Moore, the
president of the People division of Time Inc., said Time Inc.
executives. The People group publishes People, People en Espanol,
Teen People and In Style.
</P>
<P>
   Wyland was considered especially ardent as an editor, in part
because she had first brought the idea to Time Inc. Clearly, there
was tension. At one point before publication of the first issue,
she and the magazine's publisher, Alexander Sareyan, were not even
on speaking terms, the executives said. Wyland declined to comment
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Carrie Tuhy, an assistant managing editor at In Style magazine,
will take over as managing editor; it has not yet been decided if
Tuhy will remain on the job permanently. Isolde Motley, the former
managing editor of Life magazine who was named corporate editor of
Time Inc. last week, will oversee the magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Personnel issues aside, the failure of the magazine to become an
instant critical hit may reveal more about the success of the
People division than about Real Simple. The last two new magazines
out of the division, In Style and Teen People, have raised
expectations for the division. In Style, which was introduced in
1994, has a circulation of 1.4 million, according to the Audit
Bureau of Circulations; Teen People, introduced in 1998, has a
circulation of 1.6 million, and People en Espanol, introduced in
1996, has a circulation of 300,000.
</P>
<P>
   The Time Inc. executives said that advertisers were shying away
from committing to the fall issues of the magazine because the
magazine lacked warmth and was too self-consciously plain to
attract readers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
