<HEADLINE>
PUTIN APPOINTMENTS TOE THE POWER LINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN WHITMORE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Parliament overwhelmingly approved Vladimir V. Putin's
choices Wednesday for prime minister and prosecutor, handing the
newly inaugurated president a political victory less than two weeks
into his term.
</P>
<P>
   But observers said Mikhail Kasyanov, the new prime minister, and
Vladimir Ustinov, who was confirmed as federal prosecutor, have
close ties to a group of powerful tycoons who have for years
wielded strong influence on Kremlin policy. This, the observers
said, raises serious doubts about Putin's ability to deliver on his
campaign promises to stamp out corruption and pursue economic
reforms.
</P>
<P>
   By a 325-55 vote, the State Duma, the lower house of Russia's
parliament, confirmed Kasyanov as Russia's seventh prime minister
in eight years. Kasyanov's quick approval contrasted sharply with
the drawn-out confirmation fights that marked former president
Boris Yeltsin's relations with the Duma.
</P>
<P>
   Kasyanov, 42, urged the lowering of taxes to reinvigorate the
economy, and said the state must sell off its poorly performing
companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot ease the pace of reforms, or else we will end up
standing in one place and eventually get mired,'' he said.
``Reforms must be energetic, consistent and balanced.''
</P>
<P>
   Kasyanov, a former finance minister, met later with Putin,
reportedly to discuss Cabinet appointments, which are expected to
be announced in the next several days.
</P>
<P>
   Since Putin's appointment as acting president in January,
Kasyanov has run the Cabinet's daily affairs. Putin named Kasyanov
acting prime minister after his inauguration as elected president
on May 7.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1993, Kasyanov had been Russia's chief foreign debt
negotiator and won a reputation as a tough defender of Russia's
interests. After Russia's financial crisis in August 1998, it was
Kasyanov who told foreign investors that Moscow would not repay
billions of dollars in frozen debt. Earlier this year, he clinched
a deal with creditor nations partially to write off Russia's
Soviet-era debt.
</P>
<P>
   Western investors have praised Kasyanov, who speaks fluent
English, as an intelligent and capable economist.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is smart, competent and understands Western economics. He
knows how to speak the language of foreign investors,'' said Roland
Nash, chief economist for Renaissance Capital, a Moscow-based
brokerage.
</P>
<P>
   But Kasyanov is also widely believed to have close ties to
oil-and-media tycoon Boris Berezovsky, a politically connected
businessman who wielded enormous influence in Yeltsin's Kremlin.
When companies linked to Berezovsky seized most of Russia's
aluminum industry earlier this year in a deal many here said
violated anti-monopoly laws, Kasyanov defended the move.
</P>
<P>
   Kasyanov has repeatedly denied close links to Berezovsky. ``I
know a lot of businessmen and well-known entrepreneurs. But I don't
have any concrete ties to any particular financial-industrial
group,'' he said at a news conference last month.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, analysts say that Berezovsky and a group of
moguls, known as ``The Family,'' are fighting to establish similar
sway over Putin's administration, and appear to be succeeding.
</P>
<P>
   Vladimir Ustinov, another Berezovsky ally, was approved
Wednesday as Russia's top federal prosecutor. As an acting
prosecutor, Ustinov has halted several corruption investigations
initiated by his predecessors against Berezovsky and other Kremlin
insiders.
</P>
<P>
   Ustinov's nomination was a surprise to much of Russia's
political establishment. On Tuesday, Moscow was awash with rumors
that Putin would nominate Dmitry Kozak, an attorney from St.
Petersburg and a longtime protege of the president's.
</P>
<P>
   ``All recent appointments point to the fact that the Family is
still very influential and Putin has to play by their rules,'' said
Yevgeny Volk, a Moscow-based political analyst with the Heritage
Foundation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
