<SLUG> BC-CREDIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TREASURY PRICES EASE AS IMPLICATIONS OF RATE HIKE ARE FELT 
</HEADLINE>
   By ROBERT HURTADO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Prices of Treasury securities fell Wednesday as the
full scope of the Federal Reserve's half-point interest rate
increase and hawkish statement on inflation risks began to sink in
for many investors.
</P>
<P>
   The price of the 30-year Treasury bond fell 1 1/32, to 100
31/32. The bond's yield, which moves in the opposite direction from
the price, increased to 6.18 percent from 6.10 percent on Tuesday.
The price of the 10-year Treasury note fell 15/32, to 100 4/32. Its
yield rose to 6.48 percent from 6.42 percent the day before.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the trading session, the expected announcement of a
government buyback of up to $2 billion in old bonds Thursday failed
to lift the prices of securities as investors fixated on a tighter
credit environment and the prospect of higher rates to come. The
Federal Open Market Committee's raising of short-term rates had
been fully anticipated by the financial markets, despite the benign
Consumer Price Index report for April.
</P>
<P>
   ``Indeed,'' said Donald J. Fine, chief market analyst for Chase
Asset Management, ``torrid economic growth in the midst of an
incredibly tight labor market provides the ideal breeding ground
for a pickup in inflation, and with evidence of rising prices and
wages beginning to mount, the Fed clearly felt that a stepped up
pre-emptive strike was necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   Noting that the risks are still weighted toward heightened
inflation pressures in the near future, Fine said that the Fed
stated in stronger-than-usual fashion that increases in demand had
remained in excess of even the rapid pace of productivity-driven
gains in potential supply, exerting continued pressure on
resources. The concern is, he said, that this disparity will
continue, which could foster inflationary imbalances that would
undermine the economy's performance.
</P>
<P>
   Sherry Cooper, chief economist at Nesbitt Burns, said down the
road, ``Fed uncertainty over how soon consumer spending might slow
might cause the Fed to return to smaller rate hikes at the
remaining FOMC meetings this summer _ June 28 and August 22.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will, of course, depend on incoming data,'' Cooper said,
adding that the following meeting on Oct. 3 will be seen as too
close to the election to interfere in the marketplace. The Fed will
make an effort to get all of the rate increases out of the way
before then, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, the Treasury announced that it was selling $10
billion of two-year notes next Wednesday to pay down $15.94 billion
on the federal debt. In when-issued trading ahead of auction the
note was offered at a price to yield 6.87 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
