<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 19:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8132 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-SAINT-TROPEZ-NYT     05-17 1080
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAINT-TROPEZ-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FABLED BEACH BECOMES ENVIRONMENTAL BATTLEGROUND
</HEADLINE>
 By SUZANNE DALEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST.-TROPEZ, France _ Even on a cold, rainy spring day, the
tourists find their way to the beach that made this resort so
famous. Some of the restaurants perched on the dunes are full,
their tables set below canvas roofs that flap in the blustery
winds. Bleached-blond hunks hustle to park the Jaguar, Mercedes and
Porsche convertibles that roll in.
</P>
<P>
   But behind the familiar scenes of this major French tourist
attraction, a fierce battle is going on for control of Pamplona
beach, which introduced Europe to topless sunbathing in the 1950s
and where Roger Vadim set ``And God Created Woman,'' starring
Brigitte Bardot.
</P>
<P>
   The crazy quilt of beach restaurants and loud clubs that sprang
up illegally decades ago and that, some say, give St.-Tropez its
aura of wild mischief and endless partying may be in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists, fed up with what they see as greed so out of
hand that beach strollers are forced to walk in the surf, have gone
to court to clean things up.
</P>
<P>
   They have so far won two rulings proclaiming that Pamplona _
which on a sunny day in July is a writhing sea of greased bodies _
is a ``remarkable natural preserve.'' If the designation sticks,
virtually all construction here will become illegal. A ruling on a
final appeal is expected in the next year.
</P>
<P>
   Even local officials who want some decorum returned to the beach
do not want things to go that far. Pamplona, which officially
belongs to St.-Tropez's inland neighbor, the village of Ramatuelle,
produces much of the village's budget, provides 5,000 jobs and
draws thousands of tourists to the area each year.
</P>
<P>
   Bruno Quivy, a spokesman for Ramatuelle, said the local councils
would fight the suit.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can you say to 30,000 visitors a year, `This goes back to
nature?' '' Quivy asked. `` `No toilets. No parking. No food.' The
case is deeply troubling. The environmentalists went too far. ''
</P>
<P>
   The restaurant and club owners are equally unhappy. Removing
them from the beach, said one restaurant owner, Patrice de Colmont,
would do no less than destroy ``the image of France.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that sounds pretentious,'' said de Colmont, the owner
of Le Club 55. ``But St.-Tropez is a part of the French image.
St.-Tropez is life _ men and women and all the weaknesses that make
life. It is a strong symbol and one of youth and vitality.''
</P>
<P>
   The 36 businesses on the 3-mile stretch of fine white sand run
the gamut from a thatched Vietnamese restaurant to de Colmont's
sprawling yacht-club style dining room to the raucous and
outrageous La Voile Rouge, owned by a former beach attendant, Paul
Tomasselli, who readily admits he is dedicated to ``having fun,
doing what you please.''
</P>
<P>
   Almost everyone involved in the tug of war over the beach agrees
that the free-spirit feeling so long associated with Pamplona beach
should be preserved. Valerie Tronche, leader of the environmental
federation that filed suit, acknowledges there is something magic
about the activity there. She does not want it completely
obliterated.
</P>
<P>
   But, she argues, the merchants have never been reigned in. ``A
few bamboo cabins have gotten bigger and bigger,'' she said, ``and
they have sold off to each other, making a fortune. There has been
an anarchy that the local officials have closed their eyes to. No
one asked whether it was legal or not because they were making
money.''
</P>
<P>
   When, in the early 1990s, the village started drawing up plans
with the merchants for even bigger beach projects perched on
concrete platforms along the beach, the environmentalists sprang
into action. Under laws that govern the use of the French
coastline, they challenged the construction of anything permanent
on the beach.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent ruling in their favor, by a Marseille court last
December, was immediately appealed. Ramatuelle has continued
leasing out lots on Pamplona, and business has been pretty much as
usual. This year, however, an effort by Ramateulle to do some
self-policing and to close down La Voile Rouge drew the attention
of the director of a federal department that oversees the region,
Daniel Canepa.
</P>
<P>
   He announced that he was annulling all the local annual
contracts for beachfront establishments, saying they were illegal.
But even this has not stopped beach operators from opening.
</P>
<P>
   In deciding not to renew its contract with La Voile Rouge,
Ramateulle called it a nuisance to the community. The possible
demise of this 32-year-old hangout has made headlines all over
France.
</P>
<P>
   The club brings in celebrities like Sylvester Stallone, Prince
Albert of Monaco and Michael Douglas. But its noisy improvised
shows, which have included slathering topless women with food and
having a famous customer take over the mike, are not always deemed
in good taste. Quivy said that the village had been flooded with
complaints about noise and that it had concerns about many other
allegations, including drug use and a cash-only policy that many
find suspicious.
</P>
<P>
   These days, Tomasselli seems a bit subdued. His lawyer has told
reporters that ``removing restaurants from Pamplona would be like
banning waltzes in Vienna or beer in Munich.'' Tomasselli says the
town wants him out so that a casino soon to be built can get a
piece of the beach. That theory is getting a lot of ink here,
though Quivy says there is no truth to it.
</P>
<P>
   Southern France has such a history of corrupt officials and
quirky deals that no one has much trouble believing there is more
than meets the eye on any municipal decision.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, Tomasselli hopes to have Ramatuelle's decision put
aside by the courts so he can join in fighting the environmental
suit.
</P>
<P>
   Canepa wants all parties to negotiate a compromise. With
millions of dollars at stake, he believes that returning the beach
to the wild would be foolish.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, he said, the beach restaurants have branched
out aggressively and leave battered buildings and other unsightly
debris around during the off-season.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps, he said, the environmentalists will be satisfied if the
restaurants back away from the sea a bit and promise to put up only
temporary structures that can be taken off the beach at season's
end, leaving it ``natural'' in the winter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will have to find a solution that is lawful,'' Canepa said,
``but takes into account the reality of the thing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-17-00 1948EDT &QL; 
