<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MATTEL-APPOINT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KRAFT FOODS EXECUTIVE NAMED HEAD OF MATTEL 
</HEADLINE>
   By CONSTANCE L. HAYS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Invading the world of Jell-O and Miracle Whip to revive its
battered toy business, Mattel Inc. announced Wednesday that it had
named Robert A. Eckert, the chief executive of Kraft Foods, as its
new chairman and chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Eckert, 45, replaces Jill E. Barad, who resigned in February
after failing to turn around a troubled software company that
Mattel bought for $3.8 billion a year ago. Losses from the software
company, the Learning Co., were $183 million in the fourth quarter
of last year and erased earnings for Mattel, which makes toys under
the Barbie, Hot Wheels and Fisher-Price brand names. As Barad
stepped down, the company, based in El Segundo, Calif., reported a
loss of $82 million, or 21 cents a share, for the year.
</P>
<P>
   Barad's repeated promises of improvement for the Learning Co.
hurt Mattel's credibility with investors. The stock price has lost
nearly three-quarters of its value over the last two years, trading
at $11 a share in recent weeks, compared with a high of $45.625 in
March 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street applauded the choice of Eckert, under whose watch
Kraft has grown faster than the rest of the food industry, which
has been in the doldrums. Investors sent Mattel's share price up
$1.50, to $12.75.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mandate from the board is to build value for the
shareholder,'' Eckert said Wednesday in a telephone interview,
adding that he plans to do that by cutting costs, building brands
and developing managers. ``I learned how to do that at Philip
Morris and Kraft,'' he said, ``and it is challenging to do those
three things simultaneously. But when we do that, the company will
be back on track with the investment community.''
</P>
<P>
   Eckert said a close look at Mattel's profit margins and
operating expenses showed room for improvement. ``We will take a
hard look at manufacturing costs,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said he left Kraft for Mattel to run what he called ``one of
the greatest consumer brand names in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Philip Morris, the parent company of Kraft, said Eckert, who had
been at Kraft for 23 years, would be replaced by Betsy D. Holden,
44, the executive vice president of Kraft Foods. Both she and
Eckert rose through the ranks at Kraft, with stints in the cheese
division and other packaged-food divisions. A Philip Morris
spokesman, Christopher Kircher, said the company wished Eckert
well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Losing your CEO is not a positive,'' said Marc Cohen, an
analyst at Goldman, Sachs. ``But this is a company that I think has
pretty deep management and, more importantly, doesn't change
strategy. It's not a stand-alone company without any oversight.''
</P>
<P>
   Philip Morris is widely considered to be among the companies
interested in acquiring Nabisco Group Holdings, which owns 80.4
percent of Nabisco Holdings, the maker of Oreo cookies, Wheat Thins
and other food products. Combining the two companies would create a
monolith with unprecedented power in the marketplace, which many
food manufacturers say is essential to working with supermarket
chains, which have gone through their own wave of consolidation
over the last few years.
</P>
<P>
   While many executives have announced plans to depart Mattel in
recent months, including Pleasant Rowland, the founder of the
``American Girl'' doll line that Mattel bought in 1998, Eckert said
he was pleased with the management team he would be inheriting.
``They are doing a wonderful job,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what his management style was, Eckert said: ``I try to be
just another person.'' His decision to leave Kraft, he said, came
because ``it was a time in my life and my career to make a change,
and this came along.'' The prospect of further consolidation in the
food business did not affect his decision, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, after meeting informally with Mattel employees, he
made it his business to quickly read his way through the Harry
Potter books, a highly successful series by J.K. Rowling that sold
licensing rights for toys to Mattel earlier this year. Hasbro,
Mattel's chief competitor, got the rights for trading cards and
other novelties.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
