<HEADER>
A8140 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-FOOD-NEWKITCHEN18-COX     05-17 1088
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-NEWKITCHEN18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    What a new cook needs
 &HT;    By Marcia Langhenry
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Congratulations!
</P>
<P>
   Your education's complete, finals are fini, a promising job and
new digs await. The world truly is your oyster.
</P>
<P>
   Not so fast. Unless you're willing to eat that oyster raw every
morning, noon and night, you may have to equip a now-empty kitchen
and _ gasp! _ learn how to cook.
</P>
<P>
   Do not panic.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing easier than cooking, really. Nothing
mysterious about it,'' claims Julia Child, who's been at it for 55
years. Her advice? ``Just start in and do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Easy for her to say _ she's got some of the world's
best-equipped kitchens on both coasts and both sides of the
Atlantic. Knowing there's more to it than a Nike slogan, we asked
Child and other experts for their best advice on how to learn to
cook, choose essential equipment, stock the pantry, shop wisely
and, inevitably, clean up the mess.
</P>
<P>
   Where to begin?
</P>
<P>
   ``I would tell people to start with the family _ any small
recipe from the family mother,'' advises Jacques Pepin. ``... not
only are they familiar with the recipe but with the taste. They
feel comfortable with it.''
</P>
<P>
   What if Mom didn't cook?
</P>
<P>
   ``You always have a friend who knows how to cook better than
you,'' Pepin said. ``Go cook with the friend. Tell them, `Look,
I'll do the dishes and all that. Can I come a bit earlier? I want
to cook with you.'''
</P>
<P>
   Those same friends can advise you on which pieces of equipment
you'll really need, added Child, Pepin's kitchen partner on their
television show and in the companion cookbook, ``Julia &AMP; Jacques:
Cooking at Home.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't depend on store people _ they want to sell you a
whole set of things and you don't want a set,'' Child said.
</P>
<P>
   She and Pepin also say to get a few good cookbooks.
</P>
<P>
   Pepin, who has written all kinds, suggests a variety ranging
from those on fine points of technique to those on whipping up
foods you like in a hurry.
</P>
<P>
   ``One doesn't necessarily preclude the other,'' Pepin said,
noting that lots of people who are rushed through the week find
they enjoy cooking in a leisurely way on the weekends.
</P>
<P>
   No matter where you get the recipe, read it through completely
before beginning to cook. Then read it again.
</P>
<P>
   Erin Chandler, a 1999 Georgia Tech graduate who's been cooking
one year, learned that lesson the hard way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was pounding out chicken breasts with the flat end of a meat
mallet. I forgot to reread the recipe before I began, so I failed
to cover the breast in Saran Wrap before pounding. I had tiny bits
of raw chicken all over my kitchen,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Now she also recommends plastic wrap as a must-have, along with
her grandmother's telephone number and the red-check covers of
Better Homes &AMP; Gardens cookbooks.
</P>
<P>
   For those who can't call Grandma with every question, there's no
shortage of cookbooks and Internet sites aimed at a generation of
eaters raised by a generation of noncooks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think you can overestimate how we've become dumbed
down,'' says Marie Rama, co-author of ``Cooking for Dummies'' (IDG
Books, $19.95), which sold more than 300,000 copies and was
followed by an expanded second edition last month.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's become a badge of honor today to say `I don't cook,'''
Rama said.
</P>
<P>
   There's no excuse for that kind of thinking or believing that
singles needn't bother to cook, according to Amanda Hesser,
28-year-old New York Times style writer who recently won an
International Association of Culinary Professionals award for her
book ``The Cook and the Gardener'' (W.W. Norton, $32.50).
</P>
<P>
   ``Most college students gravitate toward things like pasta. They
need to move on,'' said Hesser, who lives alone and cooks a lot.
</P>
<P>
   Start with a roast chicken, she said. The next day it becomes
chicken salad, ``and then you can call your mom and ask her how to
make chicken soup.''
</P>
<P>
   Once you've mastered the chicken, the same principles will apply
to other poultry.
</P>
<P>
   That's the ``Dummies'' message, too. Rama said it helps new
cooks master basic techniques so they can branch out to suit their
own tastes. ``That is the goal _ to fly by the seat of their
pants.''
</P>
<P>
   Mistakes are anticipated here, as they are in some decidedly
more highbrow books.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more I cook, the less and less I demand perfection from
myself. It's really good for beginners to understand that,'' Rama
said.
</P>
<P>
   Wisdom like that should make even newcomers feel like creative
people in control of what they eat.
</P>
<P>
   Joan Cirillo, author of the just published ``The Complete
Idiot's Guide to Cooking With Kids'' (MacMillan USA, $16.95),
encourages fearless experimentation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember one night coming home from my first job and making
dinner for myself,'' she said. ``I sauteed some onions and added
chicken breasts to the skillet. I saw some plain yogurt in the
fridge and, spontaneously, I just put some in the pan with some
curry powder. I had a great-tasting dish and without even realizing
it was on my way to discovering Indian food.''
</P>
<P>
   Experts agree, generally on the most important advice of all:
Relax.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always tell people to trust themselves and go with their
instincts,'' says Susie Heller, who helped develop ``The French
Laundry Cookbook'' with chef Thomas Keller, winner of this year's
IACP award for book of the year.
</P>
<P>
   It should be a comfort to know that even though Jacques Pepin
has been in professional kitchens for 51 years, he's still
learning. In an interview last month, he said that as he and Julia
Child were working on a show about stuffed cabbage, they were
preparing to blanch the cabbage in boiling water, the traditional
way of making the leaves limp and easy to roll. A producer on the
show told them they could get the same wilted effect by freezing
the whole cabbage.
</P>
<P>
   ``So people have to get into it and they'll be surprised at how
fast they can learn,'' Pepin says. ``They should start with simple
recipes _ just roast chicken, boil a potato. It could be
extraordinarily good if it's done properly, you know.
</P>
<P>
   ``Relax and start cooking,'' he says. ``I mean, you're not going
to go to jail or anything like this even if you burn the chicken a
little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   No matter what the outcome, never apologize, Brody adds. ``If it
tastes good, that's good enough. If it looks good, that's a
bonus.''
</P>
<P>
   Marcia Langhenry writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
