A8142 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-KITCHEN-COLUMN18-COX     05-17 0590
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KITCHEN-COLUMN18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Nothing says family like Sunday dinner
 &HT;    By Reagan Walker
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Every Sunday afternoon, as many as 20 family members
from Alpharetta, Ga., to Stone Mountain, Ga., descend on Betty
Greene's house in Toco Hills for Sunday dinner.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes Greene, 87, will fix soup or stew for the four
generations. Other times a roast with gravy. There will be a salad
of raw vegetables or fruit, and a dessert of pie or ice cream and
cookies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I no longer set the table and wash all the dishes. We eat on
paper plates,'' said Greene. ``But it's still Sunday dinner.''
</P>
<P>
   As far as her family is concerned, casual is just fine. For the
joy in the meal comes from the company and the cuisine, not the
china. ``It's good food and good visiting,'' said granddaughter
Dell Schenck, 42, of Stone Mountain. ``And I feel out of kilter if
we miss a Sunday. It's the way I stay in touch with my family.''
</P>
<P>
   Staying in touch has always been the offering of Sunday dinner,
no matter what's served on the plate. When I was a child, it was
the only meal of the week guaranteed to bring everyone to the table
at the same time. We gathered an hour after church, and Mammaw
almost always made fried chicken. I came to believe it was a
biblical command to eat fried chicken after a worship service.
</P>
<P>
   Recently I returned to church after several years of sitting
out. After my first Sunday service, I was so overcome by desire for
fried chicken, I drove directly to the nearest fast food joint for
a two-piece snack box.
</P>
<P>
   The next Sunday, I invited friends over and made fried chicken
to share. It was good, but what really made the meal was pausing to
visit with friends before another busy week began.
</P>
<P>
   So I began to invite neighbors and friends every Sunday I could,
and soon it became my favorite way to ``entertain.'' Unlike a
Saturday-night dinner party, there's no pressure to have a
beautifully set table, a spotless house or a ``gourmet'' menu.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more relaxed, and I feel like I have more time to
prepare, '' said Ann Addison of Dunwoody, Ga. She and her husband
often invite their grown daughters or close friends over on
Sundays. ``People can come over earlier and they don't stay as
late.''
</P>
<P>
   Next Sunday, make a date with your family or invite a friend or
neighbor over. And though the nutrition police won't allow it every
week, why not serve fried chicken this time? My friend John
Millsaps offered me this delicious version for Sunday dinner once.
Add something green, something sweet and some comforting
conversation, and the Sunday dinner tradition will be revived
again.
</P>
<P>
   Fried Chicken
</P>
<P>
   Wash and pat dry the chicken parts; salt and pepper and toss in
a large bowl. Pour enough milk over the chicken to cover. Halve 2-3
lemons and squeeze the juice over the chicken; then toss the lemon
halves into the bowl. Cover and chill for several hours or
overnight.
</P>
<P>
   Dredge the chicken parts in flour seasoned with salt and pepper.
Heat up some shortening and bacon drippings in a large, heavy
skillet _ cast iron works best. Put the chicken in the hot grease,
skin side down. Cover and cook for 12-15 minutes. Then turn the
pieces and leave uncovered for several more minutes, until juices
run clear. The milk makes a delicious gravy (be sure it comes to a
bubbly boil).
</P>
<P>
   Kitchen Conversation appears every other week in the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-17-00 1954EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000517.0328 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 19:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8143 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-NEWKITCHEN-RECIPES18-     05-17 2130
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWKITCHEN-RECIPES18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Armed with good advice, conquer kitchen in the kitchen
 &HT;    By Marcia Langhenry
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Relax, it's easy. If the experts have convinced you to get in
the kitchen, they've followed up by recommending some good starter
recipes. A couple don't even require cooking. And all, from
breakfast casserole to brownies, are good enough to serve to family
and friends.
</P>
<P>
   _ Marcia Langhenry
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Bacon and Cheese
</P>
<P>
   Strata
</P>
<P>
   Why not start with a weekend breakfast? This substantial dish
also makes a fine dinner, and it's one ``Cooking for Dummies''
co-author Marie Rama readily recommends for beginners.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: about 25 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Standing time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: about 35 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Butter for baking dish
</P>
<P>
   1 (8-ounce) loaf seedless Italian bread
</P>
<P>
   5 slices bacon
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups grated Gouda, Gruyere or Italian fontina cheese
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup rinsed, chopped, packed spinach or sorrel leaves
</P>
<P>
   5 eggs
</P>
<P>
   2 cups milk
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons tomato-based salsa
</P>
<P>
   Salt and black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Butter the bottom and sides of a shallow, 2 1/2- to 3-quart
baking dish. (Use a rectangular dish that allows the bread slices
to fit snugly in one layer.) Trim and discard about 1 inch off each
end of the loaf of bread and cut the rest into about 16 slices. If
the bread is fresh, dry the slices in a 175-degree oven for about
15 minutes. Arrange the slices in the baking dish, overlapping
edges so the slices fit in the dish. Saute bacon in a large skillet
over medium-high heat, about 5 minutes, or until crisp, turning
occasionally. Drain on paper towels. When it's cool enough to
handle, crumble bacon and sprinkle over bread. Top with cheese and
spinach or sorrel. In a medium bowl, beat together eggs, milk,
salsa, salt and pepper. Pour over the layers of bread, bacon,
cheese and spinach. Using a fork, press the bread slices down to
soak them in the egg mixture. Let stand for about 15 minutes.
Preheat oven to 350 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Bake the strata about 35 minutes or just until the custard
mixture is firm and lightly browned. Do not overbake, or the
custard will be dry. Remove from the oven and serve immediately,
cutting into squares. _ From: ``Cooking for Dummies''
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 359 calories, 20 grams protein, 20 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 49), 25 grams carbohydrates, 225
milligrams cholesterol, 650 milligrams sodium, 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   SOUP
</P>
<P>
   Great-Tasting Gazpacho
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 35 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Chilling time: 1 hour
</P>
<P>
   What could be easier than uncooked, cold soup based on canned
tomatoes? It's a good chance to hone your chopping skills with a
new chef's knife, too.
</P>
<P>
   1 (28-ounce) can whole tomatoes, undrained
</P>
<P>
   1 medium bell pepper, finely chopped, divided
</P>
<P>
   1 cup finely chopped cucumber, divided
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup chopped onion, divided
</P>
<P>
   1 cup croutons, divided
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons chicken broth
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons olive or vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon ground cumin
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon white vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon pepper
</P>
<P>
   In the bowl of a food processor or blender, place tomatoes, 1/2
cup bell peppers, 1/2 cup cucumber, 1/4 cup onion, 1/2 cup
croutons, the broth, oil, cumin, vinegar, salt and pepper. Cover
and blend on medium speed until smooth.
</P>
<P>
   Pour into medium bowl and refrigerate at least 1 hour. Serve
remaining vegetables and croutons as accompaniments. Other good
additions are yogurt or sour cream and chopped hard-cooked egg. _
From: ``Betty Crocker's Best-Loved Recipes'' (MacMillan, 1998)
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 153 calories, 4 grams protein, 8 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 49), 18 grams carbohydrates, trace cholesterol,
692 milligrams sodium, 3 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   VEGETABLE
</P>
<P>
   SIDE DISH
</P>
<P>
   Roasted
</P>
<P>
   Summer Vegetables
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: about 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: about 35 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Once you learn to roast vegetables, you'll find lots of ways to
use them _ tucked into wraps or tossed with pasta, for starters.
</P>
<P>
   3 medium carrots, peeled and cut into 1/4-inch slices
</P>
<P>
   2 to 3 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 red or yellow bell pepper, cored, seeded and cut into 1/2-inch
dice
</P>
<P>
   1 small zucchini, halved lengthwise and cut into 1/2-inch slices
</P>
<P>
   1 small yellow squash, halved lengthwise and cut into 1/2-inch
semi-round slices
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound asparagus, trimmed of thick stems, cut diagonally into
1-inch pieces
</P>
<P>
   1 small red onion, chopped into 1/8-inch dice
</P>
<P>
   1 large clove garlic, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1/2 to 1 jalapeno pepper or small red chile pepper (according to
taste), seeded and minced
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon chopped fresh (or 1 teaspoon dried) basil, marjoram
or thyme
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons peeled and minced fresh ginger
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon brown sugar (optional)
</P>
<P>
   Salt and black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 425 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Scatter carrots over a large roasting pan. Drizzle with 1
tablespoon olive oil; toss to coat. Place uncovered pan on oven
rack closest to heating element; roast for 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Remove from oven and add bell pepper, zucchini, squash,
asparagus, onion, garlic and jalapeno. Sprinkle with herb, ginger,
brown sugar (if desired), salt and pepper; drizzle the remaining 1
to 2 tablespoons olive oil over the vegetables, using only enough
to lightly coat them. Toss well, spreading out vegetables in a
single layer.
</P>
<P>
   Return roasting pan to the oven and roast 20 to 25 minutes, or
until tender, turning once with a spatula or wooden spoon after 15
minutes so the vegetables brown evenly. If after 25 minutes the
vegetables are tender but not browned, place them under the broiler
for a minute or two, but watch them carefully so they don't burn. _
From: ``Cooking for Dummies''
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 123 calories, 3 grams protein, 7 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 53), 14 grams carbohydrates, no cholesterol, 25
milligrams sodium, 5 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   SIDE DISH
</P>
<P>
   Stovetop Anna
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 45 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Julia Child includes this skillet variation of the impressive
oven-baked Potatoes Anna in ``The Way to Cook'' (Knopf, 1989). You
need a cast-iron or nonstick frying pan and a lid or flat baking
pan to cover it to achieve the desired crustiness. Add the optional
cheese to turn the dish into a meal.
</P>
<P>
   2 1/2 pounds potatoes
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup clarified (melted, with white solids removed) butter, or
olive oil
</P>
<P>
   4 ounces Swiss cheese, cut into slices 1/8 inch thick and about
1 by 1 1/2 inches across (to make 1 cup), optional
</P>
<P>
   Salt, to taste
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground pepper, to taste
</P>
<P>
   Freshly grated nutmeg, to taste
</P>
<P>
   Peel potatoes and cut into round slices 1 1/4 inches in diameter
and 1/4 inch thick. Drop them into a bowl of cold water. Drain
slices and dry in a towel.
</P>
<P>
   Pour 1/4 inch clarified butter or olive oil into cast-iron
skillet or nonstick frying pan, set over moderate heat and rapidly
arrange an overlapping layer of potato slices in the pan, shaking
gently from time to time to prevent sticking. Baste with a
sprinkling of butter, then arrange a second layer over the first
and top with cheese, if using. Season third layer of potatoes with
salt, pepper and a speck of nutmeg. Continue filling with potatoes,
optional cheese, salt, black pepper and nutmeg, ending with potato
layer. Shake pan gently and let cook 3 to 5 minutes over
medium-high heat to be sure the bottom is crusting.
</P>
<P>
   Cover the pan and set over low heat for 45 minutes, or until the
potatoes are tender when pierced with a small knife. Make certain
the heat is regulated so the potatoes do not burn. Run a spatula
all around the edge of the pan and underneath the potatoes to
loosen them. Unmold onto a hot serving dish.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving (without cheese): 242 calories, 3 grams protein, 11
grams fat (percent calories from fat, 41), 34 grams carbohydrates,
no cholesterol, 9 milligrams sodium, 3 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Maple Chicken
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Although there are endless variations for broiled chicken
breasts, some, like this one, are easily committed to memory. It's
terrific with mashed potatoes, but you could also serve the chicken
sliced over a salad or alongside rice and steamed vegetables.
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon vegetable oil, plus additional for the pan
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 pounds boneless, skinless chicken breasts
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup maple syrup, at room temperature
</P>
<P>
   Preheat broiler. Line broiler pan with aluminum foil and lightly
coat the foil with oil.
</P>
<P>
   Lightly rub oil on both sides of the chicken. Press black pepper
into both sides of the chicken.
</P>
<P>
   Broil chicken 5 minutes. Carefully remove the pan from the
broiler and brush the chicken generously with some of the maple
syrup. Return to broiler, turning chicken often and basting with
the remaining maple syrup, until the chicken is cooked through,
about 5 more minutes. Serve immediately. _ From: ``The 15-Minute
Chef'' by Patricia Mack (HP Books, $15.95); tested by The
Washington Post
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 335 calories, 42 grams protein, 8 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 22), 21 grams carbohydrates, 116
milligrams cholesterol, 104 milligrams sodium, no fiber.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Lime Ice Cream
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 5-10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Freezing time: about 4 hours
</P>
<P>
   ``No muss, no fuss,'' our tester said of this ice cream so easy
you'll be tempted to keep some in the freezer all summer. You don't
need any special equipment, and it truly takes no more than 5
minutes to mix. It packs a strong lime flavor and ultra-creamy
texture, and is good served with fresh berries or shortbread
cookies.
</P>
<P>
   2 cups heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   1 cup granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons grated lime zest
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup fresh lime juice
</P>
<P>
   Fresh fruit
</P>
<P>
   In a large bowl, combine cream and sugar; stir until sugar is
dissolved. Stir in lime zest and juice. The mixture will start to
thicken slightly.
</P>
<P>
   Pour into freezer-safe metal or plastic container. Cover with
foil and freeze until firm, about 4 hours. Scoop or spoon into
individual serving bowls along with sliced fruit, such as mango,
blueberries, kiwi or strawberries. _ From: ``Cooking for Dummies''
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 409 calories, 1 gram protein, 22 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 49), 54 grams carbohydrates, 83 milligrams
cholesterol, 23 milligrams sodium, trace of fiber.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Germaine's Fudgy Brownies
</P>
<P>
   Makes 10 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooling time: at least 1 1/2 hours, divided
</P>
<P>
   Some people like their brownies cakey; others like them fudgy.
Lora Brody's easy-to-make version, with its rich, chocolatey
frosting, satisfies both camps and would be perfect to tote to a
potluck.
</P>
<P>
   For the brownies:
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup (1 stick) (plus more for the pan) unsalted butter, at
room temperature
</P>
<P>
   1 cup granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   4 extra-large eggs
</P>
<P>
   1 (16-ounce) can (2 cups) chocolate syrup
</P>
<P>
   1 1/4 cups unbleached all-purpose flour, measured after sifting
</P>
<P>
   1 cup chopped pecans (optional)
</P>
<P>
   For the Quick Glaze:
</P>
<P>
   2/3 cup granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons whole milk
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons unsalted butter, cut into small pieces
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup semisweet chocolate chips
</P>
<P>
   For the brownies: Preheat oven to 350 degrees and put rack in
center position. Generously butter or grease 13-by-9-by-2-inch
baking pan. In a medium mixing bowl, using either a spoon or an
electric mixer, cream together the butter and sugar until light and
fluffy. Beat in the eggs, one at a time, mixing until completely
blended. Stir in the chocolate syrup and flour, mixing until just
blended; don't overbeat, as it will make the brownies tough. Stir
in pecans, if using. Bake 30 minutes. Remove from oven and cool in
the pan on a wire rack for 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   For the Quick Glaze: While the brownies are cooling, place
sugar, milk and butter in a small saucepan. Cook over medium heat,
stirring constantly, until the mixture starts to boil. Boil for 30
seconds without stirring, then remove from the heat and add
chocolate chips. Stir until chocolate melts; the mixture will be
very thin. Pour glaze over the brownies, spreading evenly. Cool at
least 1 hour, then cut into 2-inch squares. Store in airtight
container. _ From: ``The Entertaining Survival Guide''
</P>
<P>
   Per serving (without pecans): 502 calories, 8 grams protein, 24
grams fat (percent calories from fat, 44), 68 grams carbohydrates,
204 milligrams cholesterol, 88 milligrams sodium, trace fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Marcia Langhenry writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
