<HEADER>
A8144 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-NEWKITCHEN-TIPS18-COX     05-17 0367
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWKITCHEN-TIPS18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cleanup tips
 &HT;    By Marcia Langhenry
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   1. Plastic (polyethelene) cutting boards are more sanitary
because they are more impervious and you can put them in the
dishwasher.
</P>
<P>
   _ Marie Rama, co-author, ``Cooking for Dummies''
</P>
<P>
   2. Sanitize hardwood cutting boards from time to time by heating
in the microwave 60 seconds on high.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``What Great Chefs Know That You Don't''
</P>
<P>
   3. When wrapping leftovers, the hardest part is getting the
plastic wrap off the roll in a flat, smooth piece. It helps to
store the box of plastic wrap in the refrigerator.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``What Great Chefs Know That You Don't''
</P>
<P>
   4. Keep a box of facial tissues near the stove to wipe up small
spills. They are quicker and cheaper than paper towels.
</P>
<P>
   _ Diana Sturgis, quoted in ``1,001 Secrets of Great Cooks''
</P>
<P>
   5. If your lasagna spills over onto the oven floor, sprinkle
with salt, lift out what you can with a metal spatula and wipe the
rest with a sponge.
</P>
<P>
   _ James Beard, quoted in ``1,001 Secrets of Great Cooks''
</P>
<P>
   6. Small self-closing plastic bags help with cleanup and
storage. Use them to melt butter or chocolate in the microwave.
Remove, knead until mixed, then remove from the bag by snipping a
small opening in one corner and squeezing out. They are also
indispensable for storage of small amounts of leftover tomato paste
or chopped onions or peppers.
</P>
<P>
   7. Clean as you go _ keep sink full of warm, soapy water and
pause once in a while to wash up.
</P>
<P>
   8. If you don't want to keep the sink tied up with soapy water,
wash items individually with one of the detergent-filled brushes.
</P>
<P>
   9. Line roasting pans with aluminum foil for easier cleanup.
</P>
<P>
   10. If your oven is not self-cleaning, try this: Preheat oven to
200 degrees, then turn oven off. Pour 1/2 cup ammonia into a small
bowl and place on the center shelf of the oven. Close door and
allow to remain overnight. Open a window, then open oven door and
air out for 30 minutes. Wipe up the mess with warm, damp paper
towels. _ ``10,001 Food Facts, Chefs' Secrets &AMP; Household Hints''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
