r e BC-AUDIO-MINIS18-COX     05-17 0652
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-MINIS18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CD mini-reviews
 &HT;    By Doug Hamilton, Nick Tate, Howard Pousner and Miriam Longino
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  SOUNDTRACK
</P>
<P>
   ``The Virgin Suicides''
</P>
<P>
   Air. Astralwerks. 13 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   Airheads holding their breath for the French ambient-pop duo's
follow-up to the brilliant 1998 debut ``Moon Safari'' (last year's
``Premiers Symptomes'' was a collection of early singles) will want
to inhale this score for the new Kirsten Dunst drama. Though most
of the tracks sound like moody sketches rather than fully
fleshed-out songs, numbers such as ``Playground Love'' and ``Dark
Messages'' come close to achieving the beautiful mystery of the
first album. Think of it as Air lite. If you just can't get enough
of the movie's tunes, check out a separate ``Music From the Motion
Picture'' soundtrack, on Emperor Norton Records. A collection of
classic rock relics by Heart, Todd Rundgren and others (plus two
Air compositions not included in the score), it plays like a
particularly kickin' super-set on Z93. (B+)
</P>
<P>
   _Doug Hamilton
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  O N T H E W E B : More on Air: www.astralwerks.com
</P>
<P>
   More on ``Music From the Motion Picture'' soundtrack:
www.emperornorton.com
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  POP-ROCK
</P>
<P>
   ``Pioneers Who Got Scalped
</P>
<P>
   (The Anthology)''
</P>
<P>
   Devo.Warner/Rhino.50 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   The spudboys are back. Devo, the Akron, Ohio, weird-wavers who
made flowerpot hats fashionable, have returned _ 10 years after the
``de-evolutionary'' theorists' last album _ with an inspired
anthology of near-hits and rarities. The yuk-yuk factor is high,
with tracks ranging from the ridiculous (``Whip it,''
``Peek-a-boo'') to the more ridiculous (``Satis-faction,'' ``Secret
Agent Man''). There's even a new tune, ``Words Get Stuck in My
Throat'' (suggested subtitle: ``Tongue Gets Stuck in My Cheek'').
But what's most hilarious here are the dead-serious liner notes
deeming Devo's influence ``firmly embedded in our cultural/social
vocabulary.'' Yeah, right. Just like the Flintstones.
www.mutato.com/lowband/mmwww5.html
</P>
<P>
   _Nick Tate
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  O N T H E W E B : More on Devo:
www-unix.oit.umass.edu/(tilde)vndibere/devo.html
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  COUNTRY
</P>
<P>
   ``So Like Joy''
</P>
<P>
   Jonell Mosser. Siren Songs. 12 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   If Jonell Mosser's first album of original material was a movie,
it'd be a chick flick. There's a song asking a lover for
reassurance, a been-done-wrong tune, one about a heartbreaking
breakup, even a lovely tribute to her departed Mom that includes
the lyric ``And though you were like no one else/ I see you
sometimes when I look at myself.'' Mosser, a popular Nashville
session singer and club performer, delivers them in a husky voice
that recalls, at different times, Mary Chapin Carpenter and Aretha
Franklin. The album verifies Don Was' assessment that Mosser has
``a direct link from heart to larynx.'' The songs, co-written with
Johanna and John Hall (Orleans) are well crafted, even if the
lyrics and his production lack the spunk of Mosser's vocals. But
she's a talent to watch _ especially one to hear.
</P>
<P>
   Howard Pousner
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  O N T H E W E B : More on Jonell Mosser: www.sirensongs.com
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  COUNTRY
</P>
<P>
   ``I Hope You Dance''
</P>
<P>
   Lee Ann Womack. MCA. 12 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   Womack is country's sweet heir to Dolly Parton. Her soprano is
twangy enough to belt out ``Muleskinner Blues,'' but she uses it
here to smack life into contemporary tunes about raising kids,
being lonely and falling in love in aisle four at the grocery. The
inspirational single, ``I Hope You Dance,'' is getting all the
attention, but the rest of the CD shows that there's room for a
pedal steel and a mandolin in country's mainstream future.
</P>
<P>
   _Miriam Longino
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ON THE WEB: More on Lee Ann Womack:
www.country.com/gen/music/artist/lee-ann-womack.html
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
