 &HT;    (backslash)bobl -- 5430; home: 404-264-1404
 &HT;    
 &HT;    PLEASE USE ELEANOR RINGEL GILLESPIE PHOTO SIG
 &HT;    KRISS WILL CUT OUT DINO WHEN IMAGE DESK HAS IT READY, KRIS
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Dinosaur flicks keep stomping
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The movies' love affair with dinosaurs began in what could be
called prehistoric times for the cinema. In 1914, venerated
cartoonist Windsor McKay gave us a one-reeler called ``Gertie the
Dinosaur,'' starring a cuddly brontosaurus. Since then, things have
gotten, well, more sophisticated. Consider the $200 million-plus
reportedly spent on this week's new Disney release, ``Dinosaur.''
``Jurassic Park'' _ the original, not the sequel _ remains the best
of the bunch, but everybody knows that one. Here are some more
obscure titles to consider for an evening at home with something
big and scaly (fill in your own spouse joke).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Valley of Gwangi'' (1969): Ray Harryhausen, the master
monster maker who did by hand and by himself what entire computer
departments do these days, created the wonders in this fantasy film
pitting cowboys _ I'm not kidding _ against prehistoric creatures.
A turn-of-the-century circus boss (Richard Carlson) ventures into
Mexico's Forbidden Valley with a cadre of cowboys (led by James
Franciscus). Their mission: to fetch some beasties for his Wild
West show. Roping a little eohippus (the orginal blueprint for the
horse) isn't so hard, but rounding up a flesh-eating allosaurus _
the titular Gwangi _ is something else again. The battle between
Gwangi and an elephant is really quite remarkable and Harryhausen
at his best.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Beast From 20,000 Fathoms'' (1953): Harryhausen again,
but this time he pits a fictional rhedosaur against the residents
of 1950s New York. After taking Manhattan, the creature proceeds to
Coney Island for an amazing sequence in which it's trapped inside
the amusement park's giant roller coaster. Based on a short story
by Harryhausen's old pal Ray Bradbury, the movie kicked off the
sci-fi cycle of nuclear-generated thingies _ from giant octopuses
to giant grasshoppers _ that inundated the '50s. Look for Lee Van
Cleef, later Clint Eastwood's nemesis in all those spaghetti
westerns, in a small role.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Giant Behemoth'' (1959): Sort of the same story as
``Beast.'' Sort of exactly the same story, since both films were
directed by Eugene Lourie. Only this monster, after being blasted
back to consciousness by atomic tests, heads for the Thames instead
of the Hudson. Bye-bye, Big Ben. The special effects, which don't
really kick in until the movie's second half, were done by Willis
O'Brien, Harryhausen's mentor and the creator of, among other
classics, ``King Kong'' and the original silent version of ``The
Lost World.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Baby ... Secret of the Lost Legend'' (1985) and ``The Land
BeforeTime'' (1988): If the lines for ``Dinosaur'' are too long and
you've got a little one clamoring for big lizards, both these films
are good bets. Especially since, like ``Dinosaur,'' they're really
more for tiny tots who think dinosaurs are all colored purple. The
former, a live-action film, is about a family of brontosauruses
discovered in darkest Africa. Sean Young and William Katt are the
good guys trying to protect Baby and her gargantuan folks. Patrick
McGoohan (``Secret Agent'') is the bad-guy archaeologist who wants
Baby for himself. The second title is a pleasant animated tale from
Don Bluth about a quartet of baby dinosaurs on a quest to find the
Great Valley where they'll be safe from the Ice Age or comets or
cigarettes (Gary Larsen's theory) or whatever did the big guys in.
Hmmm ... check this against the plot of ``Dinosaur.'' Sounds
veeeery similar.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  O N T H E W E B : For a comprehensive history of dinosaurs and
movies: www.dinosaur.org
</P>
<P>
   /MovieHistory.htm
</P>
<P>
   To download ``Dinosaur'' trailers:
www.movie-list.com/d/dinosaur.shtml.
</P>
<P>
   Eleanor Ringel Gillespie writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
