r l BC-BUYER'SEDGE18-COX     05-17 0806
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUYER'SEDGE18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Exhibit showcases Lauder perfume compacts
 &HT;    By Marylin Johnson
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The English wag who said ``good things come in small packages''
must have had solid perfume compacts in mind.
</P>
<P>
   These little works of art, which hold concentrated perfume oil
in a wax base, have been made for years by well-known cosmetic and
fashion design houses, including Avon, Revlon, Max Factor, Donna
Karan and St. John.
</P>
<P>
   But the present-day leader, hands down, is Estee Lauder. Since
1968, the cosmetic company has produced 400 of these whimsical
treasures _ filled with such classic Lauder fragrances as
Youth-Dew, Pleasures, Cinnabar, White Linen, Beautiful, Dazzling
Gold and Dazzling Silver.
</P>
<P>
   The first Lauder perfume compact was a golden rope nugget with
faux turquoise and filled with Youth-Dew. Over the years, these
compacts _ hand-crafted by a team of jewelry makers _ have ranged
from traditional cameos to sparkling cats and dogs set with
Austrian crystals to a juicy-looking peach and jewel-encrusted peas
in a pod.
</P>
<P>
   To show the creativity of the designs, the Lauder company has
assembled a traveling exhibit of about 100 of its perfume compacts.
It spans three decades and includes rare pieces from Estee Lauder's
personal collection. You can view the free exhibit through June 5
at Neiman Marcus Lenox Square in Atlanta. ``My mother-in-law
strongly believed that every woman should carry a beautiful compact
in her purse,'' said Evelyn Lauder, senior corporate vice president
of the company during a phone interview. ``She got the idea to put
solid perfume in compacts after learning the Egyptians encased
fragrances in wax as a way of preserving them. `Why don't we do the
same thing?' she asked.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, the company releases about 50 designs each year, usually
in October for Christmas giving. All are limited editions. This
means, they are available for one year or until the supply runs
out, then the molds are retired. Many compacts are made exclusively
for such stores as Neiman Marcus, Saks Fifth Avenue and Nordstrom
with prices ranging from $50-$100. A few go for $150 (enchanted
butterfly) and even $250 (the carousel).
</P>
<P>
   And the really pricey Golden Millennium 2000 round compact in 14
karat gold _ filled with Beautiful and set with diamonds _ is a
Neiman's exclusive for $2,500. Atlanta received four of the 60 that
were made. But don't expect to buy one. All are sold.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, the compacts, both contemporary and vintage,
have become hot collectibles. Gigi Martschinsky of Norcross, Ga.,
has been a collector since 1995, when she bought a Scottie dog for
$65. Now she has 48 compacts displayed in wall cases. Her
collection includes an Easter bonnet, a wagon with toys, a panda, a
teapot and teddy bear.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually I splurge and buy one a season,'' said Martschinsky,
the owner of Baby Warehouse. ``But this year, I went crazy and
bought 12, including the 2000 Millennium compact.'' The oldest
compact in her collection is an early '70s concha pendant on a
chain with squash blossom beads. Her favorite is the carousel. And
she has a Ferris wheel ($475) on order.
</P>
<P>
   ``I go for the beauty and the intricacy of the design,'' said
Martschinsky. ``I love carrying a different one in my purse. People
are always intrigued and telling me I smell pretty!''
</P>
<P>
   Solid perfume compacts have become big business. Collectors
wanting to buy or trade compacts look for them at estate sales, in
antique shops and on Internet auction sites including ebay.com.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women love these compacts because the perfume doesn't leak and
the designs are so ornamental,'' said New Yorker Roselyn Gerson,
the founder of the Compact Collectors Club. ``They decorate their
homes with them. Also, the compacts are affordable and make good
investment pieces.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the most highly sought compacts are the look-like-ivory
and wood series of fish, dog, rabbit, duck and cat issued in the
'80s. They originally sold for around $30. Today, the compacts
command prices of $300-$400 in their original boxes.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the elusive, 1981 Imperial Princess filled with the
Cinnabar scent that originally sold for $27.50. ``I know someone
who has offered to pay $8,000 for this compact, in its original
box,'' said Evelyn Lauder, ``if she can ever find it.''
</P>
<P>
   Gerson, who owns about 530 Lauder solid perfume compacts, says
it's never too late to start collecting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Think of it as a visually, enjoyable addiction,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The exhibit: 10 a.m.-9 p.m. Mondays-Fridays; 10 a.m.-6 p.m.
Saturdays; 12:30-5:30 p.m. Sundays. Through June 5. Neiman Marcus,
Lenox Square. 404-266-8200, Ext. 2270.
</P>
<P>
   Marylin Johnson writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
