<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FURNITURE-MARKET18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    At North Carolina furniture mecca, tradition rules and
large-scale pieces are in demand
 &HT;    By Danny C. Flanders
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HIGH POINT, N.C. _ Furniture shoppers look to North Carolina for
setting the tone in new designs much like the fashion forward turn
to Paris and Milan.
</P>
<P>
   And while trends emerging at the world's largest wholesale
furniture market, held twice a year, don't change as quickly as
Versace's hemlines, new collections do make headlines.
</P>
<P>
   Well, most of the time. This spring's International Home
Furnishings Market was about as quiet as an upholstery shop on
Christmas morning.
</P>
<P>
   The reason? The nation's booming economy. Furniture sales have
never been better, and when times are good, manufacturers play it
safe. They introduce few new lines, trumpet few innovations.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the dull show, retailers and interior designers shopping
High Point's 8.5 million-square-feet of trade-only showrooms
couldn't ignore a few new directions and introductions, which
should begin appearing in stores by fall:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Traditional reigns: New contemporary designs have made inroads
the past few years as interiors become more eclectic. But the April
market brought an influx of 18th-century reproductions, including
new collections by Hickory Chair (William E. Poole), Craftique
(Biltmore Estate) and Stickley (Williamsburg Reserve).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Bigger is better: As living rooms get larger and ceilings
higher, the demand for large-scale pieces is great. And if your
taste is traditional, that means bigger reproductions, sporting
pediments and other architectural elements, large legs and feet,
sculptural trim.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Branding a name. Licensing, in which a manufacturer is
permitted to produce furniture under the name of a celebrity or
famous place, accounted for $4.7 billion in retail sales last year.
This market saw an expansion of Thomasville's Ernest Hemingway
Collection highlighting the famed author's Paris connections, while
new collections were unveiled by Home &AMP; Garden Television gurus
Chris Madden (for Bassett) and Joe Ruggiero (for Norwalk
Furniture).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  O N T H E W E B :
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  High Point, N.C.: ncnet.com/ncnw/hp-intr.html
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  www.thomasville.com
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  www.craftiquefurn.com/product
</P>
<P>
   /product.html
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  www.norwalkfurnitureidea.com
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  www.hickorychair.com
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  www.stickley.com
</P>
<P>
   Danny C. Flanders writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
