A8151 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-SHOPPING-DESTINATION1     05-17 1315
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOPPING-DESTINATION18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Faulkner's hometown offers books, more
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   OXFORD, Miss. _ The stone Confederate soldier still stands on
the square as a silent memorial to Lafayette County's Civil War
dead, but that's about all that hasn't changed in William
Faulkner's hometown.
</P>
<P>
   Once a sleepy community famous only for its literary heritage
and Ole Miss football games, Oxford is rapidly becoming a trendy
urban center for music, art, restaurants and shops.
</P>
<P>
   You can still get collards and chicken-fried steak at the Ajax
Diner or Smitty's, but you also can get capuccino, shrimp and grits
and gourmet meals at the City Grocery.
</P>
<P>
   Shoppers can load up on Ole Miss football souvenirs at
University Sporting Goods on the square, but they also can find
fine art and hand-crafted pottery at the Southside Gallery and
Mississippi Madness.
</P>
<P>
   Named one of the ``100 Best Small Towns'' by USA Today, Oxford
is a walker's _ and shopper's _ paradise. A shady town square built
around the 150-year-old courthouse offers a variety of shops and
restaurants as well as wrought iron-enclosed second-floor balconies
where restaurant patrons can take their drinks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oxford is seen as a quaint Southern town,'' says Richard
Howorth, owner of Square Books, ``but it's more than that.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the town's population is around 10,000, the University
of Mississippi adds 11,000. The result is an eclectic mix of
locals, students and tourists who come to shop, soak up the
literary atmosphere at Faulkner's Rowan Oak plantation, or attend
the numerous live music events.
</P>
<P>
   All the extra traffic and influx of new residents have been
great for business, but there's a downside, says Na-Ann Watts,
owner of Na-Ann's New Look, a frame and accessory shop just off the
square.
</P>
<P>
   ``Property values have shot up astronomically,'' says Watts, a
former insurance agent who turned her interior decorating hobby
into a profession. ``You have the parents of students coming to
Oxford and liking the town so much they move here. A lot of folks
are retiring here, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Watts, who took over an existing picture frame shop, has
upgraded her stock to include a wide assortment of mouldings,
frames, mirrors, lamps and accessories, many of them in a safari
motif.
</P>
<P>
   Around the square, shoppers can find everything: the best
assortment of blues CDs in the South at Uncle Bucks Records; folk
art, antiques and weather vanes at, of course, the Weather Vane;
and hand-thrown pottery, gourmet cookware and kudzu jelly at
Mississippi Madness.
</P>
<P>
   Other shops, such as the Kaleidoscope, sell ``I Love Lucy'' tin
totes, jewelry and exquisitely detailed stuffed animals, while
Occasions offers a selection of Vera Bradley bags and Thomas
Kincaid tapestrys.
</P>
<P>
   Depite the changes and the gentrification of the town, Oxford
hasn't forgotten the man that put it on the map. Situated on a
bench in front of City Hall is a bronze sculpture of Faulkner
wearing a hat with a pipe in his hand. But even in death,
controversy surrounds the author of ``Absalom, Absalom!'' and other
classic novels. Environmentalists were upset over the displacement
of a magnolia tree to make room for the statue. Faulkner fans
complain that the likeness is all wrong. And the writer's relatives
say he would have hated everything about it.
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU GO
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Getting there: Oxford, Miss., is 332 miles west of Atlanta. If
you're driving, take I-20 west for 148 miles to Birmingham, then
U.S. 78 west for 134 miles to the Natchez Trace Parkway. Go south
four miles to Route 6. Turn west on Route 6 for 46 miles to Oxford.
Visitors going by air can fly to Memphis and take U.S. 78 southeast
to Route 7 to Oxford. It's about a 75-mile drive.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Hours: Most shops are open 9 a.m.-6 p.m. Mondays-Saturdays.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Parking: Free and plentiful.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Handicapped access: Most shops are accessible.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Information: 1-800-758-9177, Oxford Tourism Council.
</P>
<P>
   Where to stay
</P>
<P>
   The Oliver-Britt House is a restored manor house a short walk
from the University of Mississippi campus and minutes from Oxford
Square. The house features four guest rooms, all located on the
second floor, with private baths, cable television and central heat
and cooling. $44-$65. 512 Van Buren Ave., 601-234-8043.
</P>
<P>
   The Barksdale-Isom Place near the square originally was built as
a log cabin in 1835. Remodeled in the Greek Revival style, it has
been expanded to include five guest rooms with private baths.
$150-$190. No smoking, no pets. 1003 Jefferson Ave., 800-236-5696.
</P>
<P>
   Where to eat
</P>
<P>
   The City Grocery is the unlikely name for one of the most
elegant restaurants in Oxford. Located in an old storefront
building on the square, the white-tablecloth restaurant serves New
South cuisine at reasonable prices. Lunch specials include penne
pasta with shrimp for $9, an enormous helping of shrimp and grits
for $12, and smoked beef skirt steak sandwiches for $8. Evening
meals are a little pricier. 152 Courthouse Square, 601-232-8080.
</P>
<P>
   The Downtown Grill is another good choice for a quiet, candlelit
meal. Dinner specials include rainbow trout with lump crab meat for
$20.95 or Mississippi Catfish Lafitte topped with ham and shrimp
for $16.95. Lunch specials include chicken Caesar salad for $5.95
or old-fashioned chicken salad for $6.95. 110 Courthouse Square.
601-234-2659.
</P>
<P>
   For down-home Southern meals, locals go to the Ajax Diner for
meatloaf, chicken-fried steak and daily specials for around $6. 118
Courthouse Square, 601-232-8880.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond shopping
</P>
<P>
   A must-see attraction in Oxford is Rowan Oak, the house that
William Faulkner bought in 1930. He christened the house after the
Celtic legend of the rowan tree, which was thought to have magical
powers of protection. While living at Rowan Oak, Faulkner wrote
``Absalom, Absalom!'' and ``The Sound and the Fury.'' The stately
old house is now owned by the University of Mississippi. 10
a.m.-noon Tuesdays-Saturdays; 2-4 p.m. Sundays. Free. Old Taylor
Road, 601-234-3284.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The Blues Archives, located on the campus of the University of
Mississippi, houses the world's most extensive collection of blues
recordings and other material. The B.B. King collection alone
contains more than 7,000 recordings of blues, big band and jazz.
The Kenneth S. Goldstein Folklore Collection includes books and
records that focus on African-American folklore and music. The
Living Blues Archive Collection features books, photographs and
tapes covering all aspects of the blues. 8 a.m.-5 p.m.
Mondays-Fridays. Free. 601-915-7753.
</P>
<P>
