<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Locate hard to find items
 &HT;    By Marylin Johnson
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Having trouble finding a particular item? We'll try to help you
locate it. But because of the volume of mail, we cannot track down
every request. Readers whose queries are answered in the column
will receive a blue-and-cream canvas Buyer's Edge tote bag. Write
us at Buyer's Edge Find It,The Atlanta Journal-Constitution, P.O.
Box 4689, Atlanta, GA 30302; e-mail us at buyersedge(at)ajc.com
(please include your name, the city you live in and daytime phone
number); or call 404-582-7642.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am looking for Marmite, a spicy spread that can be used on
crackers or bread. I know it can be found in England, and in
Florida, but here it is nowhere to be found. Please help.
</P>
<P>
   _ Amanda M. Courchene, Decatur, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   A: Spread this around: Marmite is an extract made from brewer's
yeast and 100 percent vegetarian. We found it at Harry's Farmers
Market, 70 Powers Ferry Road, Marietta (770-578-4400), where a
4.4-ounce bottle is $2.99 and a 2-ounce bottle is $2.19. We also
spotted it at Taste of Britain, 73 S. Peachtree St., Norcross
(770-242-8585). A 4.4-ounce bottle is $4.39, an 8.8-ounce bottle
$8.29. The manufacturer, Britain's CPC, says it's ``delicious when
spread thinly on toast; for a treat, try Marmite on crisp bread
with cottage cheese.'' In addition to yeast, the spread contains
salt, carrot, spice and onion extracts and is enriched with niacin,
riboflavin, folic acid and vitamin B12.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am looking for Mink hair spray and shampoo. I bought it
years ago. Are they still being made?
</P>
<P>
   _ Kimberly Will, Duluth, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   A: It's good news, bad news. Mink shampoo, said a Gillette
spokesman, has been discontinued due to low sales. However, the
hair spray is sold at Eckerd drugstores. We found Mink Difference
Extra Hold Hair Spray ($3.69) and Mink Difference Anti-Humidity
Formula Hair Spray ($3.69) at the 45 W. Paces Ferry Road N.W.
location (404-261-5538).
</P>
<P>
   According to the bottle, you can have hair that feels as ``soft
and silky as a mink.'' And it can be used on wet hair for styling
or dry hair for finishing.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Malt-O-Meal has always been my favorite hot breakfast cereal,
but I have been unable to find it for the past year or two (Kroger
used to carry it). Can you tell me if it is made anymore? Thank
you!
</P>
<P>
   _ Steve Jones, Atlanta
</P>
<P>
   And another cereal query: We have not been able to find a
grocery store that stocks Malt-O-Meal since we moved here in 1998
from New Mexico. In fact, it was easier to find grits in the desert
than Malt-O-Meal in the South!
</P>
<P>
   _ Kiernan Cantergiani, Atlanta
</P>
<P>
   A: Like the Malt-O-Meal slogan says, ``It's good stuff,
Maynard.'' The creamy hot cereal is a blend of wheat farina (the
middle portion of the wheat kernel) and toasted barley. It's
available in original, maple and brown sugar, chocolate, and apple
cinnamon flavors. A spokeswoman for the company says the cereal is
``generally not available in Atlanta.'' However, you can order it
over the Internet at www.malt-o-meal.com Or call 1-800-743-3029.
Three 28-ounce boxes are $6.50, including shipping; six boxes are
$21, including shipping. Company will custom-pack flavors.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Some time ago, I saw a Pond's product that was a cucumber eye
treatment. It was supposed to clear up bags under the eyes. I have
not been able to find it lately.
</P>
<P>
   _ Michelle Ferrera, Jonesboro, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   A: When you open up a jar of Pond's Soothing Cucumber Eye
Treatments pads, you'd swear they were actual slices of cucumbers.
We found our jar (24 eye pads, $8.99) at CVS Pharmacy, 2929 N.
Druid Hills Road N.E. (404-325-1487). The manufacturer says the
pads are ``pre-moistened with real cucumber and other natural
extracts _ green tea, chamomile, aloe _ to soothe tired eyes and
help to reduce eye puffiness.'' After a long day, remove your eye
makeup and contact lenses, if you wear them. Place one pad over
each eye, lie back and relax. Leave on for 5-15 minutes. For
maximum refreshment, store jar in fridge.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am looking for Toilet Duck, a thick liquid bowl cleaner.
It's nontoxic and noncorrosive, and you don't have to wear gloves
to use it. But I heard it was discontinued.
</P>
<P>
   _ Damien Cuen, Atlanta
</P>
<P>
   A: Quack, quack. Yes, this old cleaning favorite has been
discontinued by manufacturer SC Johnson. However, the Toilet Duck
tank tablets are still available. We found our package (1.7-ounce
blue tablet, $1.49) at Kroger, 2205 LaVista Road N.E.
(404-633-8694). To use, you simply remove the tank cover and, when
water level is low, drop tablet into right side of the tank. The
tablet should be on its side, not sitting up. Then wait 10 minutes
before flushing. When color disappears, you need to replace the
tablet.
</P>
<P>
   _Contributing: Michelle C. Brooks
</P>
