<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Igniting physical and spiritual passions
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Neil Jordan's somber, velvety and often sensual adaptation of
Graham Greene's novel explores love both physical and spiritual.
</P>
<P>
   Considering the difficulty of conveying religious faith in film,
he's surprisingly successful in depicting both kinds of passion.
The movie, starring Ralph Fiennes and Oscar nominee Julianne Moore,
doesn't skimp on humid clinches and bared skin, but it also summons
up the intangible mysteries of sacrifice and devotion to a higher
power.
</P>
<P>
   `The End of the Affair'
</P>
<P>
   Rated R / Our critic's grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   _Steve Murray
</P>
<P>
   OTHER RELEASES
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The World Is Not Enough'' (PG-13) _ Alas, even a game Pierce
Brosnan and a classy director (Michael Apted) aren't enough to save
the 19th 007 movie from being more of the same old same old. Bond
is assigned by M (Judi Dench) to protect an heiress (Sophie
Marceau) and her oil pipeline from a nut-case terrorist (Robert
Carlyle). There's the usual eye-popping opening stunt sequence and
Denise Richards is pout-perfect as a nuclear scientist in short
shorts. But it's as if everyone involved knew how to make a Bond
movie, but they were thinking about something else at the time.
(Priced to buy: $19.98 VHS, $34.98 DVD.) Grade: C-
</P>
<P>
   _Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Cradle Will Rock'' (R) _ It doesn't. Tim Robbins' ambitious
and energetic ensemble movie is, on the whole, overdone,
over-cluttered and overly didactic. The movie presents the
collision of art and politics in '30s New York, especially as it
applied to a famous to-hell-with-the-censors staging of Marc
Blitzstein's pro-labor musical, ``The Cradle Will Rock.'' For all
its ambition and good intentions, this is more a rant than a movie.
Grade: C+
</P>
<P>
   _Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Felicia's Journey'' (PG-13) _ Bob Hoskins will creep you out
in this unsettling little movie about a lonely eccentric with
serious mommy issues. Elaine Cassidy, a forlorn, unwed, pregnant
Irish teen, comes under his ``protection.'' The film is elliptical,
intellectual and emotionally distant. But Cassidy is very good _
she's a natural survivor for all her naivete. And Hoskins is
amazing. He gives his performance a twisted delicacy worthy of
Peter Lorre in ``M.'' Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   _Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Dreaming of Joseph Lees'' (unrated) _ Star Samantha Morton
(``Sweet and Lowdown'') is the sole reason to see this brooding
romance, set in small-town 1950s England. She plays a mill worker
torn between a needy guy who loves her, and her dreamy cousin
Joseph (Rupert Graves). At times the plot is part Harlequin
romance, part gothic psychodrama. But Morton, with the intensity
and translucence of her acting, keeps you watching. Grade: C+
</P>
<P>
   _Steve Murray
</P>
