<P>
   ELEPHANTS-ECONSCENE (Undated) _ Last month, delegates met to
consider revisions to the treaty governing trade in endangered
species. Four southern African nations wanted permission to sell
their stockpiles of ivory, amassed mostly from culling herds of
elephants in their national parks. They promised to plow the
revenue back into conservation programs. The southern African
effort, which was vehemently opposed by Kenya, failed. Economists
take two distinct approaches to the problem of preserving
elephants. By Virginia Postrel.
