<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 19:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8156 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-CHINA-TRADE-BOS &LR;      05-17 1055
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-TRADE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINA TRADE BILL PASSES TWO MAJOR HURDLES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN MILLIGAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Two powerful congressional committees voted
overwhelmingly Wednesday to back landmark legislation on trade with
China, giving President Clinton momentum before the sharply divided
House takes up the issue next week.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the most important vote that will be cast in this
Congress, and perhaps, in this generation,'' said House Ways and
Means Committee Chairman Bill Archer, Republican of Texas, said
before the panel voted 34-4 in favor of the legislation. The Senate
Finance Committee approved the bill, 19-1.
</P>
<P>
   Passage of the package, which would grant permanent normal
trading relations with China, would be a major legislative victory
for Clinton, who has been unable to get much of his legislative
agenda approved by a Republican-controlled Congress hostile to the
White House.
</P>
<P>
   A win on China _ following the 1993 passage of the North
American Free Trade Agreement and Thursday's signing of a law
expanding trade ties with Africa and the Caribbean _ would give
Clinton a solid legacy on free trade.
</P>
<P>
   Politically, the China measure defines the ``New Democrat''
principles Clinton has been pushing during his nearly eight years
in office. And as in the battle over NAFTA, which dropped US trade
barriers with Canada and Mexico, victory in the China trade bill
will require the cooperation of a large block of Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Critical of China's poor human rights record, Clinton had argued
for a tough-on-China stance when he campaigned against President
George Bush in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   But after he was elected president, Clinton altered his
position, contending that the globalization of the economy made it
impossible not to trade freely with China, a growing Asian economic
power with 1.2 billion people.
</P>
<P>
   Further, engaging China is more likely to encourage democratic
change there than isolating it would, Clinton insists.
</P>
<P>
   The view is at odds with two longtime Democratic Party
constituencies, organized labor and human rights activists. John J.
Sweeney, president of the AFL-CIO, was lobbying relentlessly on
Capitol Hill Wednesday, pleading with members of Congress to vote
no.
</P>
<P>
   Labor union leaders warn that opening markets further with China
would depress the American job market, since US businesses would be
tempted to hire low-wage workers abroad.
</P>
<P>
   US employers ``are going to lay off people because the jobs will
be picked up in China for 13 cents an hour,'' said Representative
Gerald D. Kleczka, Democrat of Wisconsin, unsuccessfully appealing
to his colleagues on the Ways and Means Committee to defeat the
measure.
</P>
<P>
   ``My friends, we cannot compete with that,'' added Kleczka, who
represents industrial Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   But Republicans, joined by many Democrats, said the United
States had nothing to lose by granting permanent normal trade
status with China. The bill would end the yearly review of China's
access to US markets, and give Chinese products the same tariff
treatment given to nearly all US trading partners. It would also
ease China's accession into the World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
   Proponents argue that freezing out the Asian power would only
deny American firms trading opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   Denying China permanent normal trading relations ``would make
for chaos _ perhaps cataclysm _ in our relations,'' said
Representative Sander M. Levin, Democrat of Michigam. ``It is
playing with fire.''
</P>
<P>
   Republican congressional leaders also agreed Wednesday to
establish a commission that would monitor human rights in China, as
well as strengthen safeguards against surges in imports that could
hurt the US market. Human rights activists complain that the
commission is meaningless, since the US State Department already
does a comprehensive human rights report on China every year.
</P>
<P>
   The establishment of the commission, however, would give
political cover to some undecided members so they could vote for
the bill.
</P>
<P>
   With a House vote scheduled for next week, Clinton is still more
than 40 votes short of the 218 needed for passage. But the
president, who has been personally involved in the White House's
aggressive lobbying effort, appears to be gaining momentum.
</P>
<P>
   ``My hunch is that the president is probably feeling pretty
confident, given the numbers today,'' said Representative Richard
E. Neal, Democrat of Massachusetets, who was officially undecided
until he cast his ``yea'' vote Wednesday in the Ways and Means
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``The situation still remains fluid, but we do beleive we will
be successful next week,'' US Trade Representative Charlene
Barshefsky said.
</P>
<P>
   The bill is gathering an unlikely set of supporters who could
well push it through the House. Previously undecided,
Representative Jose Serrano, Democrat of New York and a longtime
advocate of organized labor, said in an interview Wednesday that he
will vote for the package.
</P>
<P>
   Echoing the views of some other Democrats, Serrano said he
thought his vote would give him more ammunition in his fight to
loosen trade restrictions with Cuba, where human rights violations
have been used to justify the US trade embargo.
</P>
<P>
   Other undecided Democrats are likely to vote for the bill
because they want to help the president score a legacy-building
victory in his waning months in office, Serrano said.
</P>
<P>
   Also notable is the absence of a Republican movement to deny
Clinton a victory for its own sake. The president was embarrassed
last year, for example, when the Senate refused to approve a ban on
nuclear testing.
</P>
<P>
   But on the issue of trade with China, pro-business Republicans
are jumping on board with their New Democratic foes. Partisan
politics have not even entered the debate, unusual in this
post-impeachment Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is one of those marvelous moments when we are working
together, hand in hand, for something that is positive for the
world,'' Archer said.
</P>
<P>
   And while that may not represent a permanent rapprochement
between Capitol Hill and the White House, the Republicans are
softening a bit in the last months of the Clinton era, said Neal.
``It's the seven-years, six-months factor that is driving the
psychology of their position,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-17-00 1957EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000517.0341 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 19:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8157 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-ELEPHANTS-ECONSCENE-N     05-17 1156
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELEPHANTS-ECONSCENE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ECONOMIC SCENE: THE ECONOMICS OF PROTECTING ELEPHANTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: Virginia Postrel is editor-at-large of Reason magazine and
the author of ``The Future and Its Enemies: The Growing Conflict
Over Creativity, Enterprise, and Progress.'') 
 By VIRGINIA POSTREL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The recent film title, ``I Dreamed of Africa,'' captures a
common Western attitude. We tend to see the continent as a mythic
place of romantic dreams _ of exotic adventures, lost ancestors and
awesome creatures.
</P>
<P>
   In the real world, of course, Africans face the same issues of
scarcity and incentives that affect everyone else. The continent's
natural abundance and human poverty simply raise the stakes.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, delegates from around the world met to consider
revisions to the Convention on International Trade in Endangered
Species, or CITES, the treaty governing trade in endangered
species. One of the hottest issues was what to do about ivory. Four
southern African nations _ Botswana, Namibia, South Africa and
Zimbabwe _ wanted permission to sell their stockpiles of ivory,
amassed mostly from culling herds of elephants in their national
parks. They would plow the revenue back into conservation programs.
Vehemently opposed by Kenya, the southern African effort failed.
CITES will take up the issue again in two or three years.
</P>
<P>
   Economists take two distinct approaches to the problem of
preserving elephants.
</P>
<P>
   Neoclassical analysis starts from the assumption that elephants
are ``open-access resources'' like fish in the ocean _ available to
anyone for the taking. Governments regulate access by locking up
the elephants and forbidding poaching. Neoclassical models take the
legal regime and the incentives of poachers (to make as much money
as possible) more or less for granted.
</P>
<P>
   Institutional approaches, by contrast, emphasize the social and
legal context. They explore how the structure of property rights
might be changed to encourage people to protect elephants. While
institutional economists realize that elephants can't be treated
like cows, they look for ways to make them similarly valuable.
</P>
<P>
   In the March issue of The American Economic Review, Michael
Kremer and Charles Morcom offer an ingenious neoclassical model for
elephant conservation. They start by noting that the ivory from
elephants (or the horn from rhinos) isn't like fish. It can be
stored indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
   That means that it is possible to speculate in ivory _ to
stockpile it if you think the price will go up. The result can be a
death spiral for the species. ``If some people go out and poach a
lot of elephants, and everyone thinks that the elephants are going
to be extinct and there's not going to be any more ivory, that can
induce speculation on ivory prices,'' explains Kremer, of Harvard
University and the Brookings Institution. ``And that speculation on
ivory prices can induce more people to go poach. So you get the
possibility of self-reinforcing expectations.''
</P>
<P>
   The economic review's paper offers two policy prescriptions that
might counter the problem. Both use the size of the elephant
population as a trigger. A government can say that if the number of
elephants drops below a certain level, it will crack down on
poachers, presumably with Draconian penalties. Then, says Kremer,
everybody knows that elephants will not become extinct ``and
therefore you don't get into this bad, self-fulfilling trap.''
</P>
<P>
   But if people do not believe the government can stop poachers,
the authorities can block speculation a different way. A government
can build up a large stockpile of ivory and threaten to dump it on
the market if the elephant population drops too low, or if the
price rises too high. That would in theory depress the price and
stop the death spiral. This approach could also be taken by a
nongovernmental organization.
</P>
<P>
   For all its cleverness, this neoclassical scheme does not
consider why people poach or whether elephants must be open-access
resources. Institutional approaches do. They start from two facts:
Elephants are a natural resource, attracting tourists and providing
meat, hides and ivory, and, they are also pests, trampling villages
and destroying crops.
</P>
<P>
   ``This philosophy recognizes that poor rural people living with
wild animals have no incentive to conserve them without having
clear user rights and receiving tangible benefits from them,''
write Urs P. Kreuter and Randy T. Simmons in a paper published in
``Elephants and Whales: Resources for Whom?,'' a 1994 collection
edited by Kreuter and Milton M.R. Freeman. Poaching rates, they
observe, ``seem to be a function of the proportion of local
residents receiving benefits from wildlife management.''
</P>
<P>
   Institutional experiments that give local people a financial
stake in wildlife have had some striking successes, particularly in
Zimbabwe. There, the government in the mid-1980s began the Communal
Areas Program for Indigenous Resources, better known as Campfire.
The program gave local districts wildlife-management authority in
communal areas outside the national parks. In some cases, the local
districts devolved control further, down to groups as small as 200
villagers.
</P>
<P>
   The purpose ``was to get away from the idea of having these
island preserves, and to try and expand the geographic area over
which we could implement wildlife conservation,'' says Kreuter, a
Zimbabwean now teaching at Texas A&AMP;M University. To do that, he
said, the rural people who faced ruin if elephants wrecked their
grain bins, houses, or crops ``had to have economic income
associated with the wildlife; otherwise they just considered it to
be a liability.''
</P>
<P>
   Villagers who reap benefits from wildlife will be less likely to
shoot elephants that threaten their crops and more likely to police
poachers.
</P>
<P>
   Under Campfire, the local authorities worked with outside
experts to determine, for instance, that the area could maintain a
sustainable elephant population by hunting two elephants a year.
Residents would then contract with a safari operator and split the
fee of around $25,000 an elephant paid by the hunter. In most
cases, the villagers also got the meat from the elephant.
</P>
<P>
   But even such innovative economic thinking has its limits. Both
neoclassical and institutional conservation models share an
underlying assumption: that the government respects the rule of law
and the goal of conservation. In Zimbabwe, however, that assumption
has become shaky. Robert Mugabe's increasingly authoritarian rule
is destroying the nation's wildlife programs.
</P>
<P>
   The national government is recentralizing wildlife management,
and the Campfire programs are breaking down. ``They're taking that
authority away from the local community,'' Kreuter said. ``So the
local communities feel, `We're not getting anything out of this, so
why should we tolerate this species? We need to get rid of it.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
