<HEADLINE>
CELLUCCI PICK FOR STATE ETHICS PANEL QUITS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL REZENDES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ A member of the Massachusetts Ethics Commission
resigned Wednesday, after the Globe revealed that the commission's
decisions were vulnerable to legal challenge because Governor Paul
Cellucci had appointed too many Republicans to the panel.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci acknowledged his staff did not check the party
affiliation of his most recent appointment to the panel, Boston
attorney J. Owen Todd. Todd resigned by the end of the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Judge Todd has offered to solve the dilemma and we're going to
reluctantly accept because the statute is pretty clear that we
cannot have a third Republican as one of our appointees to the
commission,'' said a source close to Cellucci.
</P>
<P>
   The questions about the legal status of the commission caught
the Cellucci administration off guard and surfaced at a delicate
time for the panel, which has several cases to decide, including a
recently expanded investigation of Lieutenant Governor Jane Swift.
</P>
<P>
   State law says only two of the three gubernatorial appointees to
the five-member commission can be from the same party.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci named Todd to the five-member commission in March, and
said his staff assumed Todd was a Democrat, because he was named to
the Superior Court bench in the 1980s by former Democratic Governor
Michael S. Dukakis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anyone thought he was a Republican but they
should have checked,'' Cellucci said. ``It's a mistake and we've
got to straighten it out.''
</P>
<P>
   Birtwell also said Cellucci regretted having Todd singled out
because of a mistake committed by the gubernatorial staff. ``Judge
Todd has done absolutely nothing wrong and yet this error has
brought attention to him,'' Birtwell said.
</P>
<P>
   After the Globe checked registration records for Cellucci's
appointees, and found that all three were from the GOP, legal
scholars and former commission members said any decisions made by
the commission were open to challenge based on the violation of the
law regarding appointees.
</P>
<P>
   Carol Carlson, spokeswoman for the Ethics Commission, said Todd
took part in a commission meeting April 19. She said
confidentiality requirements did not allow her to say whether Todd
voted on any matters before the commission but conceded that any
votes in which Todd took part may be invalid.
</P>
<P>
   The commission, in place since the late 1970s, enforces the
state's conflict of interest law for state and local officials
across Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   The Ethics Commission generally meets behind closed doors. But
sources have said that the agency decided to widen a probe of Swift
at about the same time of the April commission meeting in which
Todd took part.
</P>
<P>
   In January, Swift asked the commission to review her use of a
State Police helicopter for personal use. But the Globe reported
last month that the commission had broadened its investigation in
order to scrutinize Swift's use of State House staff to move her
personal residence and perform baby-sitting duties and other
personal chores.
</P>
<P>
   The attorney general and the secretary of state, who are
Democrats, are also given appointees to the commission. Secretary
of State William F. Galvin has yet to make an appointment; with
Owen's resignation, the panel now has three members.
</P>
<P>
   The members include chairman Augustus F. Wagner Jr. and Stephen
E. Moore, Cellucci's other two Republican appointees, and Edward D.
Rapacki, a Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   The embarrassment Cellucci faces over the Todd appointment comes
close on the heels of a successful legal malpractice claim against
Wagner.
</P>
<P>
   Last week a Cape Cod jury awarded $1.3 million in penalties and
interest to Judith Meyer, a Centerville woman who convinced a jury
that Wagner was negligent in making sure that her former husband
fulfilled the terms of her 1989 divorce settlment.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci defended Wagner Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Malpractice doesn't mean you're not ethical, it means a
mistake might have been made,'' Cellucci said. ``Justice Wagner is
a highly repsected former Superiour Court judge. Nothing I've seen
in this malpractice case that I've seen has any impact on his
credentials as a fair, ethical jurist who's now heading up the
Ethics Commission.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
