<P>
   BUSH-SOCIAL-SECURITY (Washington) _ In laying out his Social
Security plan, George W. Bush talks about federal workers' private
investment accounts and suggests Vice President Al Gore is
hypocritical in denying them to the general public. But federal
workers don't get anything special. They pay comparable payroll
taxes for retirement and like 32 million other American workers,
they have a 401(k)-type investment plan. A Bush spokesman says the
candidate brought up the point only to counter Gore's suggestion
that stock market investing is ``risky.'' A News Analysis. By DAN
FREEDMAN. (Already filed.)
