<SLUG> BC-CUBA-ELIAN0518-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Atlanta Cuban-Americans plan to outline stance on Elian Gonzalez
 &HT;    By Mark Bixler
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ If Reemberto Rodriguez is right, a lot of people think
he's a right-wing nut.
</P>
<P>
   He said he and other Cuban-Americans have been unfairly
stereotyped because of their opposition to the government's
handling of the Elian Gonzalez case. He said the rap on Cubans is
that they're extremist with a blind hatred of Fidel Castro who have
created a ``Banana Republic'' in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   He and a dozen other metro Atlanta Cuban-Americans want to
dispel the stereotypes and inject what they say is logic into the
debate about Elian. They've formed a group called Concerned
Americans of Cuban Heritage. On Sunday, they plan to outline the
legal reasons they say support the idea that Elian should live
here.
</P>
<P>
   Rafael Andino, a founder of the group, said he hopes to persuade
native-born Americans that the Elian Gonzalez case does not _ or
should not _ revolve around parental rights. He invited the public
to a meeting this coming Sunday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to put up specific facts,'' he said. ``It's not
that we're nuts. It's not that we're Castro haters. It's not that
we're intolerant.'' Andino, who lives in the Atlanta suburb of
Lawrenceville, left Cuba when he was 3. He said his group has about
a dozen members. Most are middle-aged businessmen, managers and
executives. They left Cuba when they were children or were born in
the United States to Cuban parents. Atlanta's major Cuban
organization, the Cuban Club, is made up mainly of older immigrants
who left Cuba after Castro took power in 1959, said Isabel Frank,
president of the Cuban Club, a social and cultural group that has
not taken a stand on Elian. She said about 7,000 Cubans live in
metro Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Andino, an engineering manager for an Atlanta pharmaceutical
company, said native-born Americans who say Elian's father should
take him home do not realize how dire life is in Cuba even though
the Cold War focused the national consciousness on the perils of
communism for decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're like `We won the Cold War. Great. Let's move on.' ''
Sara J. Gonzalez, Cuban immigrant who is president of the Atlanta
Hispanic Chamber of Commerce, said the gulf worries her. So do
finger-wagging Cuban protesters shouting ``Communist!'' to those
who disagree with them. ``There`s no gray areas in their
politics,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
