<HEADLINE>
STUDY SHOWS INCREASE IN TOBACCO ADS AIMED AT CHILDREN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Cigarette makers, reneging on a landmark pledge to
stop targeting children, have drastically increased spending on
magazine ads aimed at youths, according to a study released
Wednesday by the Massachusetts Department of Public Health.
</P>
<P>
   Prompting new cries for Congress to crack down on the tobacco
industry and state prosecutors to reopen their historic case
against the cigarette makers, the study indicates the industry has
shifted much of its marketing budget into youth-oriented magazines
after agreeing to no longer promote cigarettes on billboards.
</P>
<P>
   The Massachusetts study compared cigarette advertising
expenditures in magazines before and after the industry's historic
settlement with 46 states, focusing on 19 popular magazines with
more than 15 percent of their readership between the ages of 12 and
17. Fifteen percent was the level used by the Food and Drug
Administration in its efforts to regulate tobacco. Magazines in
that category include Rolling Stone, Glamour, Sports Illustrated
and Motor Trend.
</P>
<P>
   Examples included a Rolling Stone issue with teenage singing
star Brittney Spears on the front cover and a full-page Marlboro ad
on the back.
</P>
<P>
   In the first nine months of 1999, cigarette makers spent $119.9
million on advertising, much of it on brands most popular with
young smokers, in magazines with a significant percentage of teen
readers, the study found. That is almost $30 million more than was
spent in the same magazines in the corresponding period before the
settlement, the study said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you see multimillion-dollar increases in magazines with
youth readership, it's disturbing,'' said Timothy J. Shea, chief of
the public protection bureau for state Attorney General Tom Reilly.
``We're going to look at it closely and see how it comports with
the Master Settlement Agreement'' between the states and cigarette
makers.
</P>
<P>
   The state's public health commissioner, Dr. Howard Koh, cited
the study Wednesday in issuing a written request to the major
tobacco companies to adopt ``childproof'' cigarette advertising.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have childproof caps on Tylenol and aspirin,'' Connolly
said. ``We should have childproof advertising from the tobacco
industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Cigarette makers insisted the study's findings were misleading.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing that a tobacco company can do that won't
receive criticism from the special interest groups that have their
own political agenda,'' said Mark Smith, a spokesman for the
Kentucky-based Brown and Williamson Tobacco Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Brown and Williamson has pulled all advertising from magazines
with a significant percentage of readers under 21, Smith said,
basing its decisions on demographic data provided by magazine
publishers.
</P>
<P>
   Philip Morris USA, another tobacco company, carefully researches
publications before choosing to place advertisements where they
reach adult smokers but don't bombard youth, said company spokesman
Tom Ryan. The company, which makes Marlboro, will no longer
advertise on the back cover of any magazine, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, antitobacco activists said the Massachusetts
findings show that cigarette makers are undermining a crucial
provision of the $246 billion settlement they reached with 46
states in 1998. In the pact, the tobacco companies agreed they
would not appeal to minors.
</P>
<P>
   State prosecutors, in response to the findings, said they were
considering taking the industry back to court.
</P>
<P>
   ``This type of advertising destroys our efforts to protect our
children,'' said Greg Connolly, director of the Massachusetts
Tobacco Control Program, at a news conference in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   He said the surge of magazine advertising appears to be geared
increasingly toward black and Hispanic girls.
</P>
<P>
   ``Targeting those groups raises very, very serious concerns,''
Connolly said. ``It's almost like a bomb being planted in many
urban communities, where advertising like this will result in
increased smoking rates among ethnic females 10 to 15 years from
now.''
</P>
<P>
   The study's release coincided with a new push by Senator Edward
M. Kennedy for a law permitting the Food and Drug Administration to
regulate cigarettes as drug-delivery devices. He faces fierce
opposition from Republican leaders, who last year engineered the
defeat of a similar effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``This new evidence is further proof of how essential it is for
Congress to grant the FDA broad authority to regulate the marketing
of tobacco products,'' Kennedy said. ``If the FDA's rule on tobacco
were in effect today, this behavior by the tobacco companies would
be illegal.''
</P>
<P>
   A separate study released Wednesday by the American Legacy
Foundation found more than 70 percent of teenagers in 1999 had seen
cigarette advertisements often enough to notice them and understand
their content.
</P>
<P>
   Advertisements for Marlboro, the favorite brand of young
smokers, reached 89 percent of teenagers, the study found.
</P>
<P>
   The studies used commercial marketing surveys to assess the
popularity of various magazines among young readers. Cigarette
makers say those numbers don't represent who really reads the
publications.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton used the studies to call on Congress to pass
strict tobacco laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``The FDA's hands should not remain tied by Congressional
inaction,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Wire service material was used to prepare this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
