<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 20:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8165 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-BUFFALO-ADCOLUMN-NYT &LR;      05-17 0878
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUFFALO-ADCOLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: PROMOTING BUFFALO'S CLIMATE AS JUST RIGHT FOR
BUSINESS 
</HEADLINE>
   By BERNARD STAMLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   With its shrinking population, declining industrial base and
notoriously cold winters, Buffalo has had its share of image
problems. But local officials and civic boosters insist that the
city and its environs do not deserve their unfortunate reputation.
Thursday, they are announcing a major promotional campaign aimed at
proving that the climate upstate is just fine, for people and for
businesses, too.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign is sponsored by the Buffalo Niagara Enterprise, a
not-for-profit economic development marketing consortium founded
last year to encourage businesses to invest in an area comprising
the eight westernmost counties of New York and the Niagara
peninsula of southern Ontario. Nearly 70 participants, including
local municipalities and private businesses like Key Bank, HSBC
Bank, the Buffalo Bills and Moog Inc., an upstate manufacturer of
motion-control components, have joined, as has one Canadian
participant, the Ontario-based Canadian Niagara Power Co. Ltd.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of their contributions, the money needed for the
first year _ about $5 million _ is already in hand, according to
Tom Kucharski, the president and chief executive of Buffalo
Niagara. That is part of $27 million committed by Buffalo Niagara's
members, three-quarters of it from private companies, according to
Ted M. Levine, chairman of Development Counsellors International,
the public relations firm representing Buffalo Niagara.
</P>
<P>
   That is a large amount to spend on marketing by a community
development organization seeking to create jobs. ``I cannot think
of another community _ especially a moderately sized one _ that has
even come close to raising that kind of sum,'' said Mark
Waterhouse, an economic development consultant who was formerly
chairman of the American Economic Development Council, an
organization for economic development professionals.
</P>
<P>
   With a goal of 50,000 new jobs and $1 billion in new investment
over the next five years, it is also one of the most ambitious
development plans put forward in recent years, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The challenge is to put forward in a focused way all that we
have to offer,'' said Kucharski, who came to Buffalo Niagara from
the Lehigh Valley Economic Development Corp. in eastern
Pennsylvania, where his efforts as president helped attract 18,000
jobs over four years. But the job is bigger in Buffalo-Niagara, he
said, not only because of the greater size of the region _ 2.2
million residents as opposed to Lehigh Valley's 600,000 _ but also
because of the highly negative feelings about the area held by
strangers and natives alike.
</P>
<P>
   Not only do people in general have a ``terrible image of the
Buffalo-Niagara region,'' so do people living in and around the
city, many of whom have ``incredibly low self-esteem,'' said Doug
Bean, a managing partner at Eric Mower &AMP; Associates, the agency
based in Syracuse whose Buffalo team is handling the Buffalo
Niagara account. In addition to aiming at businesses outside the
region, he has made ``internal'' marketing a priority.
</P>
<P>
   ``If people who live here are down on the area, especially
service and hospitality workers, that can have a big impact on
visitors who interact with them,'' he said. ``So we're going to use
this campaign to re-educate our own constituency as well as
anything else we do.''
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of the recipient, the message Buffalo Niagara will be
delivering will be the same, a simple one that tracks the
campaign's three-word slogan: ``available. productive. people.''
</P>
<P>
   Print ads and broadcast spots will feature residents of the area
extolling local advantages, like the high concentration of college
students, affordable housing, low office rents, and the fact that
the work force in the area is ranked ninth in the country in
production output per wage dollar spent. Not to mention, ``summers
that are just beautiful'' and winters that are ``not nearly as
snowy as people think,'' according to Kucharski (``More sun than
Atlanta, less rain than Raleigh,'' say some of the ads).
</P>
<P>
   The campaign will also be aimed at specific industries. Those
include information technology, for which there is already
considerable infrastructure, according to Kucharski; advanced
medical technology, which is already strong in the region, and call
centers and other support services for financial institutions or
insurance companies.
</P>
<P>
   Media buying is to begin later this month, Bean said, with the
rollout of the campaign set for the fall. He anticipates devoting
approximately 85 percent of the $5 million or so first-year budget
to national advertising on cable television aimed at business
viewers on outlets like CNN and CNBC, as well as print ads in The
Wall Street Journal and sponsorship announcements on National
Public Radio. The remaining 15 percent will go to local television
and radio commercials and to billboard, newspaper and transit
advertising in metropolitan Buffalo. There is also a Web site:
www.buffaloniagara.org.
</P>
<P>
   The mix sounds right to Waterhouse, the consultant.
</P>
<P>
   ``With this plan, Buffalo has a chance to become another
renaissance city,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
