<HEADER>
A8168 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-COKE0518-COX     05-17 0422
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE0518-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Deal lets cell phones call up a Coke
 &HT;    By Kathy Brister
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Coca-Cola is betting consumer pockets are as likely to
carry cell phones as coins.
</P>
<P>
   That's why the Atlanta-based beverage maker Wednesday signed a
$100 million deal to fit vending machines with modems allowing a
wireless phone user to dial a Coke. The agreement is with Marconi
PLC, a London information-technology firm that employs 30 in
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The technology already is in vending machines on some university
campuses and in Hong Kong, but it could be another 18 months before
Atlantans see it.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how it works. A thirsty consumer walks up to a Coke
machine. It looks like any other vending machine, although it may
have a screen flashing a Coke ad or the latest sports scores. Using
a number posted on the machine, the consumer dials in, enters a
code and a soda drops out.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the scenes, that order goes into a database managed by
Marconi, which sends the information to a bottler that processes
the order and likely sends it on to the consumer's cell phone
carrier. The transaction shows up on next month's bill.
</P>
<P>
   The technology also works with smart cards, but conventional
wisdom is that U.S. consumers will ``leapfrog'' the debit-card-like
technology now popular in Europe and reach right for cell phones,
said Tim Garnett, Coca-Cola's director of engineering development.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to offering consumers a cashless option, the
technology makes inventory easier for bottlers, Garnett said.
Bottlers can connect to a machine remotely to check its stock, its
sales and whether it's working properly, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Such efficiencies are important to the soft drink business,
which sells about 13 percent of its products through vending
machines, said John Sicher, editor of trade publication Beverage
Digest. But luring consumers is the key, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Coke spokesman Trey Paris said the novelty and usefulness of the
machines is designed to draw in consumers and said the company
won't use them to remotely raise soft-drink prices.
</P>
<P>
   In October, the company came under fire from consumers angered
by reports that Coca-Cola was studying ways to remotely change
vending machine prices according to weather conditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The technology has virtually limitless applications, but
Coca-Cola would never apply it in a way that would take advantage
of consumers,'' Paris said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-17-00 2008EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
