<DOCNO> NYT20000517.0352 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 20:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8169 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-SIERRA-LEONE-U.N.-NYT     05-17 0746
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIERRA-LEONE-U.N.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.N. DISCUSSES HOW TO TRY SIERRA LEONE'S REBEL LEADER
</HEADLINE>
   (With SIERRA-LEONE) 
 By BARBARA CROSSETTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ Discussions began here Wednesday on whether
legal options exist to bring Foday Sankoh, the Sierra Leone rebel
leader, to justice, because no international tribunal has automatic
jurisdiction over him.
</P>
<P>
   Sankoh, whose Revolutionary United Front established itself as
one of the most savage guerrilla movements _ chopping off citizens'
limbs and destroying villages _ won a place in the Freetown
government last year in return for an end to his violent campaign
against President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah. Thus, diplomats said, the
responsibility is on Sierra Leone, which holds the rebel leader
prisoner, to make the first decisions on his future.
</P>
<P>
   Will it try another reconciliation with the warlord, whose
troops control diamond-mining areas, or will Sankoh be declared an
outlaw and turned over to a criminal court?
</P>
<P>
   Key to Sankoh's future may be President Charles Taylor of
Liberia, a beneficiary of diamonds supplied by the Sierra Leone
rebels. Some officials in Sierra Leone say Taylor appears to have
found an alternative to lead the rebels, Sankoh's former field
commander, Sam Bockarie, and could jettison Sankoh.
</P>
<P>
   While awaiting a decision by Kabbah and fearful that threats of
a war crimes trial could endanger more than 200 U.N. hostages held
by rebels, many U.N. officials and human rights groups say Sankoh
should not be absolved in any way.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations, which was not involved in the peace
agreement signed last year in Lome, Togo, took the unusual step of
distancing itself publicly from the amnesty for Sankoh that was
part of that accord. Secretary- General Kofi Annan has said
repeatedly throughout the current hostage crisis _ in which
Sankoh's forces have held as many as 500 U.N. forces _ that the
rebel leader would have to be held accountable.
</P>
<P>
   Reed Brody, advocacy director of Human Rights Watch, said
governments were obliged to see Sankoh prosecuted. ``Once he is in
international custody,'' Brody said, ``there is a duty under the
Geneva Conventions to bring him to trial.''
</P>
<P>
   Brody, who has been active in efforts to try other leaders
outside their countries, including Gen. Augusto Pinochet of Chile
and Hissen Habre of Chad, said there were four possibilities in
Sankoh's case.
</P>
<P>
   ``One, probably the best, would be to create an international
tribunal on the order of the tribunals for the former Yugoslavia
and Rwanda,'' he said. The other possibilities are creating a
regional tribunal to handle the case, sending Sankoh to another
country for trial or trying him in Sierra Leone, Brody said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Normally it is better to try people in the country where their
crimes were committed, where the victims are located, where justice
would ultimately be more meaningful,'' Brody said. ``But given the
unsettled conditions in Sierra Leone and the passions that are
manifesting themselves in the calls by some for mob justice or
lynch justice, it might be better to have him tried by a tribunal
that is perceived to be neutral.''
</P>
<P>
   At the International Peace Academy, a research organization with
close ties to the United Nations, the president, David Malone, said
this is the kind of case for which an International Criminal Court
has been created. But the court, which an international treaty
established two years ago, is bogged down in negotiations over how
it will function, with the United States demanding immunity for its
citizens.
</P>
<P>
   Leading nations, Malone said, have not made the case against
Sankoh clear enough to be heard in Freetown and among those U.N.
officials, some working in Africa, who are inclined to patch up
relations with the rebel leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Security Council has consistently failed telegraph clearly
what its approach to Sankoh on criminal responsibility is going to
be,'' said Malone, a Canadian diplomat. ``The real dilemma is that
there seems to be a split of opinion in United Nations circles on
the Sankoh case. On the one hand, you have people who believe that
somehow the Lome agreement needs to be put back together again and
that in order to do so Foday Sankoh remains a necessary and
legitimate partner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I disagree. Foday Sankoh and his senior lieutenants need to be
on notice that their personal responsibility for war crimes isn't
abstract, that there will be practical consequences.''  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
