<HEADLINE>
DO CARDINAL RULES APPLY?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LEE BARNATHAN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MALIBU, Calif. _ Stanford is the overwhelming favorite to repeat
as the NCAA women's tennis champion. Yet last year, the Cardinal
traveled to Gainesville, Fla., to face overwhelming favorite
Florida for the national title.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinal won, even with an injured player.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA expected to reach Florida last year, but the Bruins lost at
home. Pepperdine is this year's host, but the Waves aren't
participating because LSU defeated them last week.
</P>
<P>
   As the championships begin today, everyone wonders if this
year's tournament will offer any new surprises.
</P>
<P>
   ``To win, you have to be good and lucky,'' Stanford coach Frank
Brennan said.
</P>
<P>
   Make no mistake, the Cardinal (27-0) is good. Top singles player
Marissa Irvin, from Harvard-Westlake High School in Los Angeles,
has lost once all season _ in her last match against Fresno State.
Brennan said Irvin's consistency has instilled confidence in her
teammates, so much so that her defeat didn't cause anyone else to
falter.
</P>
<P>
   ``The girls respect her and look up to her and think she walks
on water,'' Brennan said without jest. ``It's interesting how they
revere her.''
</P>
<P>
   Players such as Laura Granville and Lauren Kalvaria could play
No. 1 singles almost anywhere else. Here, they're depth.
</P>
<P>
   Stanford challenges the rest of the field to pull off something
wild. Northwestern has the first shot , but no one's giving the
Wildcats much of a chance because they upset Tulsa to get here.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves UCLA on Friday, provided the Bruins beat Texas today
at 5 p.m. That's a story in itself. The Bruins were ousted by the
Longhorns in a regional last year at UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   You can bet UCLA, which defeated Texas 5-4 earlier this season
at Austin, wants to avenge last year's loss !ital!and get another
shot at Stanford, which defeated the Bruins 7-2 this season.
Stanford faces Northwestern today at 5 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every match is tough, and some teams can really get up for
playing the NCAAs when they don't have anything to lose,'' UCLA
coach Stella Sampras said.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's USC, which almost didn't make it after the Trojans
freshmen struggled to adjust to the pressures of the NCAAs. The
Trojans open at 8 a.m. today against the same LSU team that shocked
Pepperdine.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will play a lot more relaxed out there Thursday than we did
(Sunday),'' USC coach Richard Gallien said.
</P>
<P>
   The matches begin at 8 a.m. and continue at three-hour intervals
at the Ralphs-Straus Tennis Center and on lower courts around the
campus. The quarterfinals are Friday, the semifinals Saturday, and
the championship match is Sunday at 1 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the five-day individual championships begin. The draw
will be held Saturday. Irvin will be favored to win the title
before she embarks on a pro career.
</P>
<P>
   But strange things can happen. Irvin lost in the final last
year. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
NCAA TOURNAMENT &QL; 
What: Final four rounds of NCAA championships &QL; 
__ When: Today-Sunday. Individual tournament begins Monday &QL; 
__ Where: Pepperdine &QL; 
__ Today's schedule: USC vs. LSU, 8 a.m.; South Alabama vs.
Georgia, 8 a.m.; Arizona State vs. Duke, 11 a.m.; Notre Dame vs.
Florida, 11 a.m.; Wake Forest vs. Tennessee, 2 p.m.; Cal vs.
Vanderbilt, 2 p.m.; UCLA vs. Texas, 5 p.m.; Stanford vs.
Northwestern, 5 p.m.
</P>
</TEXT>
