<HEADLINE>
HAITIANS AND JOURNALISTS COVERING THEM ARE RESCUED BY COAST GUARD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla . )   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The crew of a U.S. Coast Guard cutter has rescued 44 Haitians
and two freelance journalists working for The New York Times from a
sailboat en route to Florida, officials said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Petty Officer Silvia Olvera, a Coast Guard spokeswoman, said the
cutter Forward intercepted the boat on Sunday night about 18 miles
northwest of Tortuga, Haiti. It was trying to sail from Haiti to
the United States, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Coast Guard officers boarded the boat in international waters
and followed it into Bahamian territory. There, officers from the
cutter determined that the 35-foot boat had to be evacuated because
it was slowly sinking, Petty Officer Olvera said.
</P>
<P>
   The 39 Haitian men, five Haitian women and the two American
journalists were offered food, water and medical attention and then
were turned over to Bahamian officials on Tuesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Finkel, a reporter, and Chris Anderson, a photographer,
were on assignment for The New York Times Magazine to chronicle the
kind of journey a growing number of Haitians are making to America,
said Adam Moss, editor of the magazine.
</P>
</TEXT>
