u a BC-GRADESCHOOL-HARASSMEN     05-17 0622
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRADESCHOOL-HARASSMENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWYER DESCRIBES ASSAULT ON GIRL BY THIRD GRADERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MACQUARRIE AND MEADOW RUE MERRILL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST BATH, Maine _ The School Committee Wednesday refused to
disclose specifics about the suspension of five third-grade boys
accused of sexual harassment, but an attorney for the parents of
one alleged victim said the girl complained that two boys twice
pinned her to the ground while another boy simulated intercourse.
</P>
<P>
   The 9-year-old girl complained to an adult playground supervisor
on each occasion, May 2 and 4, and was told simply to ``stay away
from the boys,'' said the lawyer, Richard Regan of Bath, who
represents the girl's parents.
</P>
<P>
   Regan said the child did not tell her parents of the recess
attacks because the boys had threatened her with ``physical
repercussions.'' He says he believes the parents learned of the
incidents only after West Bath School principal Catherine M. Folan
wrote a letter to third-grade parents May 5 about complaints of
harassment including lewd comments and physical abuse.
</P>
<P>
   The case raised eyebrows across the region because of the ages
of the children involved and because of the absence of details of
the alleged offenses.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Chet Garrison, chairman of the School Committee, told
about two dozen parents and school staff gathered at a board
meeting that confidentiality laws prevent public release of
specific information about the children in this case.
</P>
<P>
   Folan suspended the boys last week for four to eight days. The
School Committee met privately with a lawyer Monday and is
reportedly considering whether to expel the boys.
</P>
<P>
   The alleged female victim has spoken twice with Sagadahoc County
sheriff's detectives, who are investigating whether the alleged
harassment warrants criminal charges. The girl also is receiving
counseling because of the alleged attacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can tell you that the girl was afraid to tell the parents;
she was threatened in some way,'' Regan said. ``The thing that
compounded it is that she did what she was told: Report anything to
an adult.
</P>
<P>
   ``And then it happened again.''
</P>
<P>
   Superintendent Bob Young has said the school's investigation
into complaints of harassment found incidents of pinching,
inappropriate touching, and sexual comments. He did not mention the
simulated intercourse.
</P>
<P>
   However, the girl's account of serious harassment on the school
playground appears to have been corroborated by others. One of the
suspended boys, his mother said Wednesday, has admitted seeing a
girl pinned to the ground by four boys while another jumped on her.
The mother said the boy alerted a teacher but was told to ``mind
your own business.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The information (released to date) has suggested that what
we're talking about is poking . . . and saying a few naughty
words,'' Regan said Wednesday. ``Up until now, (the parents) were
very reluctant to say anything publicly about what happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Regan said he does not know exactly what the school found in its
investigation, what the daughter of his clients specifically told
the playground supervisor, and what might occur next.
</P>
<P>
   Folan declined to comment Wednesday. ``This deals with children,
and it is confidential. The whole situation is confidential.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Feldman, an attorney for one of the suspended boys, said
the situation has been sensationalized by the news media.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have any knowledge that anything terrible has
happened,'' Feldman said. ``If there are problems, address them and
get these boys back in school. The worst thing that could happen is
to leave them at home sitting in front of a television.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
