<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 20:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8177 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-CAPTAIN-MURDER-2TA     05-17 1318
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CAPTAIN-MURDER-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CAPTAIN, A COUPLE, A LAND DEAL, MURDER MOST FOUL
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Italy, Fla, Pa.) By KEVIN FLYNN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   NEW YORK _ Capt. John Lau of the
U.S. Army, an officer with the South European Task Force stationed
in Italy, left behind his wife, three young children and the busy
affairs of his foreign posting to make a brisk two-day trip home to
New York four years ago.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Among his reasons for the trip, Lau later told investigators,
were that he hoped to discuss a transfer with a general, deliver an
anniversary gift to some friends and pick up Chinese foods not
available in Vicenza, where he was stationed.
</P>
<P>
   But, investigators say, the most pressing matter that put Lau on
Delta Flight 73 to New York on May 22, 1996, was murder.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors say that during his 50-hour visit, Lau met with a
young couple he had defrauded in a land deal, beat them to death
and dumped their bodies into Newtown Creek, a brackish body of
water that divides Brooklyn and Queens. Then, say investigators for
the Brooklyn district attorney's office, he drove to the airport
the next day, boarded a flight to Italy and resumed his work for
the task force that responds to military emergencies in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Lau, whose discharge from the Army is pending,
returned to New York, this time to face charges in the murder of
the couple, Alexander Barone, 32, and Liane Barone, 29. He is being
held without bail.
</P>
<P>
   In Brooklyn, where many killings stem from drug dealing and
domestic disputes, investigators said that murders that arise from
white-collar crime are uncommon. A suspect who is a decorated Army
officer accused of committing the crime during a short furlough
from foreign soil is unheard of.
</P>
<P>
   ``The combination of the defendant and his background, and the
crime and the motive underlying it, makes it more unusual than
most,'' said Barry M. Schreiber, chief of the district attorney
office's homicide bureau.
</P>
<P>
   Lau, 37, whose family lives in Brooklyn, has denied any murder
role. His lawyers have said that after an exhaustive four-year
inquiry, investigators have yet to uncover any eyewitnesses or
physical evidence, like fingerprints, that link Lau to the crime.
</P>
<P>
   His lawyer, Gary Villanueva, said the defense would have no
comment until the case goes to trial.
</P>
<P>
   The bodies of the Barones were discovered in the creek at 9 a.m.
on May 24, 1996, the Friday of a Memorial Day weekend. Initially,
the police thought they were robbery victims. Their wallets were
missing, as was any form of identification. They had been beaten
with a blunt instrument and their skulls were fractured.
</P>
<P>
   The bodies were not identified for four days. But within a week,
investigators sought to interview Lau, the last person known to
have seen the couple alive. Robbery had become an unlikely motive,
investigators said. Someone had found the victims' wallets and had
mailed them to their address, with credit cards undisturbed.
</P>
<P>
   Local investigators and the Army's Criminal Investigation
Division began to pursue a new theory: that Lau had killed the
Barones to cover up his role in a Florida real estate deal in which
the Barones and others had been cheated.
</P>
<P>
   The deal dated from 1987, when Lau was in the Reserves and was
making his living as an independent real estate agent. He had
offered to help Barone, a friend from their days in the Reserve
Officers Training Corps at Polytechnic University in Brooklyn, buy
a lot in a development known as Deep Creek, near Port Charlotte,
Fla. To help finance the deal, according to court records, Lau told
Barone he would lend him $13,000.
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, Lau never bought the land for the Barones, nor
did he lay out any money on their behalf. Several months later,
when he arranged for the Barones to resell the property to a family
in Queens, that too was a fictional transaction, papered over with
bogus documents that concealed that neither family had ever seen a
deed.
</P>
<P>
   But the Queens family, the Leongs, dutifully sent the Barones a
check for $224 every month as outlined in their installment plan.
Every month, to pay down their debt, the Barones sent a $200 check
of their own to Lau, even after he went on active duty in 1992 and
later was posted to Italy.
</P>
<P>
   For nine years, the monthly payments continued. But in 1996,
when the Leongs tried to pay off their balance and secure the deed,
they discovered during a title search that the Barones had never
owned the property. They complained to the Barones, who in turn
called Lau in Italy. He promised, investigators say, to come to New
York in a few days to clear things up.
</P>
<P>
   Lau arrived at Kennedy Airport at 3:30 p.m. on May 22. The
following night he met the Barones for dinner and, he said, to drop
off some papers related to the sale. While they were upset at their
real estate problem, the couple were happy. Two days earlier,
Barone had graduated from the University of Pennsylvania with a
master's degree in architecture.
</P>
<P>
   Lau told investigators that instead of going to dinner, they
went to his mother's house for a short time, and then the couple
asked him to accompany them to Shea Stadium to meet a friend in the
parking lot. The friend, whom the captain called Gene, was
preparing to visit Italy and wanted advice from someone who lived
there, recounted, and so they waited for him outside the stadium in
parked cars. But when Gene did not show up after several hours, Lau
said, at 1 a.m. he excused himself and returned to his mother's
house in the borough of Queens.
</P>
<P>
   Lau, who had no previous criminal record or history of violence,
has said someone else must have attacked the Barones after he left.
``Murder is outside of my scope of realm,'' he said at a 1999
hearing.
</P>
<P>
   The police version is different. Gene does not exist, they say,
and was invented to explain the missing hours when the murders
occurred. They say that during those hours Lau, possibly acting
with someone else, killed the couple, put their bodies into their
red 1984 Trans Am and drove the car to the Metropolitan Avenue
bridge over Newtown Creek, where he dumped the bodies.
</P>
<P>
   The car was found in Manhattan three weeks later, stained with
blood. Inside it was found a 15-inch-long metal ratchet that
investigators say may have been used in the murders. They say the
killings were premeditated, because the person who drove the car
after the crime appears to have been wearing gloves, according to a
forensic analysis of the steering wheel.
</P>
<P>
   In charging Lau, the office of Charles J. Hynes, the Brooklyn
district attorney, has cited injuries the captain had when he was
interviewed 12 days after the killings. They included a large
scratch across his back and a scab on his left shoulder that
investigators say are evidence he had been in a struggle. But the
captain said he had scratched his back in the shower and been hit
by falling plaster while making home repairs.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the evidence consists of what prosecutors have
characterized as multiple inconsistencies in Lau's statements. He
initially denied that there was fraud in the land deal, for
example.
</P>
<P>
   In a conversation Lau recounted for investigators, he said he
and Mrs. Barone had discussed the Trans Am while waiting for Gene
outside Shea Stadium. The captain recalled complimenting Mrs.
Barone on the car's mint condition, and she had said of her
husband, ``He doesn't ever let me drive this car.'' Investigators
said Mrs. Barone would never have said such a thing, because she
had no driver's license and did not drive.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Lau was charged in federal court in Brooklyn in
connection with the land fraud, and during that case, Paul
Schoeman, an assistant U.S. attorney, put forward some of the
murder evidence. The captain ultimately pleaded guilty to mail
fraud, but steadfastly denied any role in the murder of the
Barones. (MORE)
</P>
<P>
   As part of the captain's defense at a sentencing hearing, his
lawyer, Steven Brounstein, said any inconsistencies were an
insufficient foundation on which to build a murder case. Brounstein
said the lead investigator in the case, Bob Burton of the Brooklyn
district attorney's office, had sent out nearly 400 subpoenas for
evidence, but still there were no fingerprints, fiber evidence or
eyewitnesses to tie his client to the crime.
</P>
<P>
   He said Lau, at 5 feet 4 inches, was too small to have killed
both Barones at the same time. He argued that Lau had been caught
cutting corners in real estate deals before, but that when he had
disagreements with people he had merely paid back what he owed. The
$20,000 involved in this case, he said, was not enough to motivate
a murder.
</P>
<P>
   But Judge Reena Raggi, who presided over the federal case, said
she did not believe Lau's account and sentenced him to 10 years in
prison, far above the 16 months suggested for mail fraud under
sentencing guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   In explaining her sentence, she said in court that she had been
persuaded that the captain had probably committed the murders. ``He
had more to lose than money,'' Raggi concluded. ``He had his
career.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
