<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 20:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8180 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-MUTFUNDS-MARKETPLACE-     05-17 1014
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUTFUNDS-MARKETPLACE-ART-2TAKES(TRIM)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: INTRODUCING THE UNMUTUAL FUND 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Please note that the company name Folio(fn) parentheses has
been used instead of brackets, which are non-transmittable to some
newspaper systems.) 
(ART ADV: Photo NYT13 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By PATRICK McGEEHAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bombarded with pitches for new and different ways to invest
their savings, most people might conclude that the last thing the
world needs is another twist on owning stocks. Steven Wallman is
not one of those people.
</P>
<P>
   This week, while the leaders of the mutual fund industry munch
shrimp and sip chardonnay at their annual gathering in Washington,
Wallman will be 15 miles away in Vienna, Va., plotting to take the
finger food out of their mouths. Wallman, a headstrong former
securities regulator with an appetite for reform, is increasingly
irritated by what he sees as the burdens the typical mutual fund
puts on shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   Most funds are not worth owning, Wallman says, because they cost
too much, repeatedly fail to beat the market and frequently stick
shareholders with big tax bills.
</P>
<P>
   Funds set up to track market indexes solve some problems, but
they do not offer investors much choice or control of risk, he
says.
</P>
<P>
   Wallman says he has found a better and, in many cases, cheaper
way for investors to create their own, customized baskets of
stocks, which he calls folios, and two months ago he started
selling them over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   He is not alone in trying to harness Internet technology to
provide investors an alternative to mutual funds and brokerage
accounts. In San Francisco, a fledgling outfit called eInvesting
plans to introduce ``build your own'' funds by September. ``There
is an enormous opportunity, leveraging the Web, to combine the
convenience and instant diversification of a mutual fund with the
control and direct stock ownership of a brokerage account,'' said
Ben Phillipps, vice president for marketing at eInvesting.
</P>
<P>
   The various fees that funds charge add up to, on average, 1.35
percent of assets. On the median mutual fund investment, about
$32,000, that translates to annual fees of $432, Wallman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If people realized it's costing them $500 a year, that's
something they would be really shocked about,'' he said. ``Why
don't funds have to disclose the monthly cost?''
</P>
<P>
   It is bad news for the fund industry that that question is being
raised by Wallman, a man so persistent that he is still pushing for
stocks to be traded in decimals instead of fractions 2{ years after
he left his appointed position on the Securities and Exchange
Commission. Wallman, 46, is an iconoclast who often butted heads
with Arthur Levitt, the commission chairman, and members of the
commission staff. He does not abandon a cause lightly, but he
contends that his latest venture is no quixotic mission.
</P>
<P>
   For a fee of $295 a year, Wallman's company, Folio(fn), will let
investors create three do-it-yourself stock funds containing as
many as 50 stocks each and as much money as they choose. For no
additional charge, they can make changes in their holdings as often
as twice a day through what Wallman hopes will become an efficient
internal trading system.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the world will beat a path to Wallman's home page at
www.foliofn.com is far from certain. He is not the first to try to
tap into investors' growing discomfort with traditional funds, a
restlessness that has spawned several variations.
</P>
<P>
   Some fund companies have begun listing fund shares on the major
exchanges where they can be priced and traded all day. The Vanguard
Group, the leading purveyor of the index funds so popular with
buy-and-hold investors, announced plans last week to list shares of
several of its most popular funds, including the flagship Vanguard
500 Index fund.
</P>
<P>
   Other companies have created funds that let small investors take
high-risk chances on companies that have not yet been cleared to
sell shares to the public. Merrill Lynch and other brokerage firms
have created baskets of stocks in a given industry that can be
bought at relatively low cost.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of new ideas out there, and some, like
exchange-traded funds, are starting to catch on,'' said John
Rekenthaler, research director for the fund tracking firm
Morningstar Inc. in Chicago. The folio concept ``is a pretty big
idea that's going to stick in some form,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it will be a while before this new breed of investment
product takes a measurable bite out of mutual funds, which have
been the individual's investment of choice for more than a decade.
The Investment Co. Institute, which is holding its annual trade
show this week in Washington, estimates that Americans have more
than $4.4 trillion invested in 4,432 all-stock funds, a tenfold
increase since 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Burton Greenwald, a mutual fund consultant in Philadelphia, is
dubious about the staying power of individuals' interest in
managing dozens of stocks. ``Will these products be a threat to
funds?'' he said. ``I don't think so. I suspect their popularity
would fade quickly if you had a prolonged bear market.''
</P>
<P>
   Folio(fn), whose quirky name, Wallman said, stands for financial
innovation, is taking aim at the bulk of that money, which sits in
funds whose managers are paid to try for a higher return than, say,
the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index. Wallman and his colleagues
say that type of investing is pure folly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every study has shown that stock picking by mutual funds has
not been overly successful,'' Wallman said last Friday. ``Unless
you think you can pick the manager who will outperform, why pay
money to throw the dice?''
</P>
<P>
   The standard disclaimer in fund marketing materials that past
performance is no guarantee of future returns should be replaced,
Wallman said, with a warning label that reads: ``Past performance
has absolutely nothing to do with future performance.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Point out that he sounds a lot like John C. Bogle, the founder
of Vanguard, who has long been an outspoken proponent of low-cost
index funds, and Wallman grins. Bogle is ``one of my heroes,'' he
said. ``I would love to get Bogle working with us.''
</P>
<P>
   Wallman acknowledges that his folios are not for everybody. ``If
you've only got $10,000 or $20,000, then you ought to be in
Vanguard 500,'' he said. ``It's a very good buy.''
</P>
<P>
   But investors with $30,000 or more in folios would pay less than
1 percent of their assets annually and gain the flexibility to
choose the stocks they own and to adjust their holdings frequently
to match their tolerance for risk. To help them get started,
Folio(fn) offers sample folios, like one that contains the 30
stocks in the Dow Jones industrial average.
</P>
<P>
   With a few clicks of a mouse, an investor can order, say, $6,000
worth of the Dow 30, and get $200 worth of each stock _ fractional
shares in many cases _ in one swoop. A week or two later, that
investor could sell 10 stocks and replace them with 10 others, then
ask Folio(fn) to rebalance the folio to keep the investment spread
evenly.
</P>
<P>
   Using a discount brokerage firm, those moves would count as 50
to 100 trades or more. Even at commissions as low as $8 a trade,
that would cost $400 to $900.
</P>
<P>
   Folio(fn)'s pricing structure puzzles some people who have taken
a look at its Web site. ``How are they going to make any money
doing that?'' wondered one broker at Merrill Lynch, which last year
started allowing customers to make unlimited trades for a minimum
annual fee of $1,500.
</P>
<P>
   Wallman and his financial backers say that Folio(fn) can be
profitable because it is building a computerized trading system
that will keep most trades in-house, matching customer purchases
and sales of popular stocks without incurring the costs of a
middleman.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Allen Morgan, general partner of Mayfield Fund, a venture
capital firm in Menlo Park, Calif., that has invested about $20
million in the company, says the proprietary trade-matching and
processing system is the key. Once Folio(fn) builds a base of
thousands of customers, he said, its technology-based system could
become very profitable.
</P>
<P>
   Until it gets to that point, Folio(fn) is compiling the orders
customers place and sending them to market-making firms in two
daily batches, at 10:15 a.m. and at 2:45 p.m. On those trades it
can match among its customers, Folio(fn) says it will split the
difference, or spread, between the prevailing prices offered to buy
and sell that stock. On trades it sends to other firms, Folio(fn)
will receive payments from them of up to $2 a trade, a form of
kickback that is common in the brokerage industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``You either leave that money with the market maker or you take
it,'' Wallman said. ``That's an easy decision.''
</P>
<P>
   One paradox of Wallman's involvement is that his firm stands to
gain in a couple of ways from Wall Street's foot-dragging on the
switch to trading stocks in increments of pennies, instead of
fractions of a dollar. More than three years after agreeing to make
the change, the managers of the Nasdaq market have asked to put it
off until next year.
</P>
<P>
   Wallman estimates the delay is costing investors hundreds of
millions of dollars a year, and despite his financial interest, he
is still calling for the SEC, where he was a commissioner from 1994
to 1997, to insist that the New York Stock Exchange switch to
decimals without waiting for the Nasdaq. Meantime, the higher costs
of trading elsewhere could serve as a marketing tool for Folio(fn)
while the company takes in payments for sending orders to other
firms.
</P>
<P>
   Nell Minow, a prominent shareholder activist, says she is a
convert to folios. Minow has known Wallman since he was a partner
in the Washington law firm of Covington &AMP; Burling lobbying for
state laws to stifle corporate raiders.
</P>
<P>
   As a friend she tested Folio(fn)'s service and came away
impressed. ``I have never in my life invested in a share of stock
on my own,'' said Minow, who was a driving force behind Lens
Investment Management, an activist money management firm. ``I
personally can't stand working with money managers at the retail
level because I feel their interests are contrary to mine. I feel
I've had a lot of bad advice over the years.''
</P>
<P>
   She said she would move some of her family's savings from mutual
funds to folios to take advantage of the greater flexibility. She
also likes the simple way Folio(fn) has set up to allow investors
to vote their shares for company directors and proxy proposals
electronically. Minow, who considers herself a crusader and Wallman
more of an idealist, said she hoped folio investors would use the
Web site as a forum for sharing views on issues of corporate
governance.
</P>
<P>
   Wallman's idea of using the Internet to help individual
investors communicate and marshal their collective power is a bold
stroke, Minow said. ``Talking to him,'' she said, ``is like driving
on the autobahn: You can go as fast as you want and he'll always
keep up with you and respond to what you're saying. It's delicious
to bat around ideas with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Barry Barbash, a former chief regulator of mutual funds at the
SEC, had a different taste after tangling with Wallman over some
mandatory disclosures that Wallman thought would benefit small
investors. ``When you were done with Steve, you oftentimes felt you
had just completed a prizefight that went the maximum number of
rounds,'' said Barbash, now a partner with the law firm of Shearman
&AMP; Sterling in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``This product he's developed is absolutely consistent with the
views he articulated when he was on the commission about the lack
of transparency and high fees,'' Barbash said. ``It is intended to
be something that's anti-establishment. Whatever you think of it,
it's absolutely Steve Wallman.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
