<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 20:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8187 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-VIENNA-ORCHESTRA-MUSI     05-17 1244
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIENNA-ORCHESTRA-MUSIC-$ADV21-1200(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WADING INTO DEPTHS OF MEMORY AND REPRESSION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sun., May 21)  
 By JAMES R. OESTREICH    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   VIENNA, Austria _ City of Mozart, Beethoven, Schubert, Brahms,
sundry Strausses, Mahler, Schoenberg, Berg and Webern. City of
Freud, Adler and Reich. A burnished nostalgia crosses paths with a
studied forgetfulness, and myth lurks at every turn.
</P>
<P>
   When the Vienna Philharmonic performed Beethoven's Ninth
Symphony recently in the quarry of a former Nazi concentration camp
in Mauthausen, Austria, 120 miles to the west, it knowingly waded
into deep waters of memory and repression, meaning and association,
hope and delusion. And all of that is to reckon without the
late-breaking international fracas over Joerg Haider and the
Freedom Party, as the orchestra did through most of its four years
of planning.
</P>
<P>
   Seizing on the symbolism of the year 2000, the event was
intended as a Janus-headed look backward, with remorse and a hope
for healing, and forward, with resolve and a hope for renewal.
Crucial to each point was a frank acknowledgment of a shameful
past, the orchestra's and the nation's as a whole, something that
has been slower to emerge here than in Germany. Austria likes to
portray itself as the first victim of Nazi Germany, pointing to the
Anschluss of 1938, despite its widespread embrace of annexation to
the Third Reich. As has often been noted, Austrians figured among
SS forces in concentration camps all out of proportion to their
percentage of the Reich's Germanic population.
</P>
<P>
   Inevitably, the concert raised questions about the uses and
abuses of music. Although some saw the orchestra's venture as
misguided, many considered it a tool for good. Still, any confusion
of aesthetics with morality, the cherished notion that at least the
loftiest music is invariably a force for human edification and
communication, must fall before even the most cursory reflection on
the place of music in the Third Reich.
</P>
<P>
   Some of these themes have, coincidentally, taken on added
resonance with publication of Richard Newman's new book, ``Alma
Rose: Vienna to Auschwitz,'' the story of a noted violinist who
went on to direct a women's orchestra at Auschwitz-Birkenau. To a
lesser extent, it also tells the story of her father, Arnold Rose,
the leader of the celebrated Rose Quartet through several
transformations, a revered concertmaster of the Vienna Philharmonic
and of its parent Vienna State Opera Orchestra for 57 years, and a
brother-in-law of Mahler. The book encapsulates the plunge from
dizzying heights of Viennese culture to fathomless depths of Nazi
depredation. And through it all, there is every reason to believe,
the Vienna players performed Beethoven brilliantly.
</P>
<P>
   ``My Beethoven,'' Arnold Rose, a thoroughly assimilated
Romanian-born Jew who identified himself completely with Austrian
culture, liked to call the composer. ``To go to a better world,
take the Beethoven piano sonatas and play them through,'' he
advised his son, Alfred, who had fled to Cincinnati, from his own
exile in London. The elder Rose's unstinting service to Beethoven,
to the orchestra and to society availed him nothing. He was
summarily dismissed from the orchestra at the time of the
Anschluss. A dozen or so other Jewish members quickly followed.
</P>
<P>
   Alma Rose saw her father safely to London, then, against advice
from friends, traveled to the Netherlands, where she worked to
support herself and her father, never to return. Arnold Rose sank
into loneliness and despair. The Vienna Philharmonic offered to
reinstate him as concertmaster in January 1946, but he was no
longer in any position to accept. He died in that year, at 82.
</P>
<P>
   With this context in mind, it is eerie to return to a familiar
EMI recording of Beethoven's Ninth Symphony by the Vienna
Philharmonic and the Vienna Singverein, which also performed at
Mauthausen, from 1947. The conductor, Herbert von Karajan, and the
soprano soloist, Elisabeth Schwarzkopf, it later emerged, had both
been members of the Nazi party. So had half the members of the
orchestra, in the estimate of Werner Resel, a cellist now in the
Philharmonic who, as its president in 1996, set the Mauthausen
project in motion.
</P>
<P>
   In early 1946, Newman writes in a similar vein, Arnold Rose
reported ``an unsubstantiated claim from Vienna that 56 Nazis
remained in the Vienna Philharmonic, as opposed to six in the
Berlin Philharmonic.'' During that year the Vienna Philharmonic
sought permission from American military authorities to tour France
and was turned down. The Americans branded it a ``Nazi orchestra,''
a term that continues to haunt it.
</P>
<P>
   Karajan's recorded Ninth of the next year is rousing, to say the
least. (Does a listener hear or only imagine an almost militaristic
aggression at times?) The orchestra, of course, plays brilliantly,
though the amateur Singverein in no sense rivals it, as that
chorus' latter-day counterpart did in a recent performance of the
work here in the Vienna Musikverein. In the years that followed,
the classical-music world, which had retreated into an ivory tower
of its own by midcentury, proved as adept as Austria in
overlooking, excusing and ultimately forgetting unpleasant historic
facts.
</P>
<P>
   Alma Rose, meanwhile, trapped in the occupied Netherlands,
failed in an attempt to escape to Switzerland. Arrested and
imprisoned in France, she was eventually sent to Auschwitz, where
she took over a scrappy little women's band and, by all accounts,
turned it into a crack orchestra, the pride of Maria Mandel, the SS
commandant of the women's camp at Birkenau. The Nazi murderers,
there is every reason to believe, appreciated the orchestra's
playing just as much as their victims did.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to presenting concerts, the orchestra played marches
for forced-labor contingents leaving the camp in the morning and
returning at night. Newman casts doubt on reports that the
orchestra entertained as trainloads of new prisoners arrived, with
many being immediately ``selected'' for death in the gas chambers.
</P>
<P>
   Alma Rose was a stern taskmaster, believing that only by
maintaining the highest musical standards could the orchestra
insure its survival and that of its members. Yet she appears to
have acquitted herself with whatever dignity and humanity the
circumstances allowed: more so than depicted in Fania Fenelon's
1977 book about the orchestra, ``Playing for Time,'' and the CBS
film of the same name. The orchestra members, in any case, received
preferential treatment and did buy time. Most, like Fenelon,
survived. Alma Rose herself died in the camp in 1944, at 37,
apparently from botulism.
</P>
<P>
   What role, then, can music, so obviously ambiguous and amoral in
its meanings and so debased by some of its makers and users, or the
Vienna Philharmonic, so compromised in its integrity, play in the
quest for a brighter future? A crucial one, in the view of Leon
Zelman, who first presented the idea for the Mauthausen event to
Resel and the Philharmonic: that of remembrance.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't understand that the tragedy in Europe did not
begin with Mauthausen and Auschwitz,'' Zelman said. ``It began with
words, with hatred, with annihilation. The young generation in
Austria after us must be reminded, and music has a power to
translate. It helps us to remember.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Zelman, 73, directs the Jewish Welcome Service of Vienna, which
invites refugees to revisit the city they once fled. Born in
Poland, he himself passed through Auschwitz and other camps on his
way to Mauthausen: actually one of its many satellite camps in
Austria, Ebensee, from which he was liberated 55 years ago this
month. He remained in Vienna after the war and eventually developed
friendships with members of the Philharmonic, including Resel and
Clemens Hellsberg, a violinist and the orchestra's current
president and archivist, who himself did much to lay bare the
orchestra's Nazi past in his 1992 history, ``Demokratie der
Koenige'' (``Democracy of Kings''), not yet available in English.
</P>
<P>
   Zelman has no particular connection to music. The references to
music in his touching memoir of 1998, ``After Survival,'' are
mainly to the melancholy songs his mother sang before her
disappearance from the Lodz ghetto in Poland to an unknown but
certain death. He chose Beethoven's Ninth Symphony, with its
concluding chorus based on Schiller's ``Ode to Joy,'' he said,
``because it represents the idea of Mauthausen, the vision we had
that when we survived, it would be in a world of freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   Around 105,000 prisoners died at Mauthausen in unspeakably
brutal conditions: not only Jews but also non-Jews from Eastern
Europe and elsewhere, homosexuals, Communists and ``antisocials.''
Many others besides Zelman survived, and opposition to the
Mauthausen event arose primarily from them, not from Haider's
Freedom Party. (But Zelman is hardly sanguine on that score; he is
obviously still shaken by the shouts of ``Heil Haider!'' and the
Nazi salutes he encountered at a rally in St. Stephen's Square last
December, before the election.)
</P>
<P>
   Some survivors opposed the very idea of presenting a musical
event on what, they insisted, should be preserved as holy ground.
Some protested the nature of the music: the triumphal ``Ode to
Joy'' in a place of such sorrows. Some objected to the
participation of the Vienna Philharmonic, with its tainted past.
</P>
<P>
   B UT Zelman finds nothing of that past in the current orchestra.
He said he was gratified at its unanimous acceptance of his
proposal and its readiness to waive fees.
</P>
<P>
   For Beethoven, said Simon Rattle, who conducted the Mauthausen
performance, joy was always hard-won and thus aptly symbolic of
this occasion. In the case of the Ninth Symphony, the music
historian Richard Taruskin suggested in a 1989 essay, ``Resisting
the Ninth,'' the joy of the finale has to be pried from the
sublimity that characterizes the first three movements.
</P>
<P>
   Edmund Burke ``contrasted the smallness, the lightness and the
pleasurableness of the Beautiful with the vastness, the obscurity,
the painfulness of the Sublime,'' Taruskin writes. ``All the
adjectives Burke applies to the `great' _ vast, rugged, negligent,
dark, gloomy, solid, massive _ suit its first three movements to
perfection, even as the adjectives applied to `beauty' _ small,
smooth, polished, light, delicate _ seem altogether alien to it.''
In the same senses the occasion and the place, in the quarry of
Mauthausen, were truly sublime.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having music here is a very good thing,'' said Thomas
Quasthoff, the baritone soloist in the Beethoven Ninth, who pointed
to a personal meaning in the occasion, since, physically deformed
by his mother's use of Thalidomide during pregnancy, he would have
been among the first slain in Nazi times. ``But is it necessary to
have so many speakers? The music is important. Speakers don't
change anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Zelman is surely right that remembrance can no longer be
entrusted merely to survivors, most of whom will soon be gone.
There must be a way for future generations to connect to the events
of the Holocaust on a visceral level, and this is indeed a function
music can serve.
</P>
<P>
   ``It helps open our hearts,'' Zelman said. And it brings to bear
its tremendous power of association, through which the memories of
musical experiences fuse viscerally with extramusical
circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   ``This sort of thing is important, because it gives people
something to attach to,'' said Wolfgang K. Aulitzky, the director
of the medical program of the American Austrian Foundation. ``The
Vienna Philharmonic is accomplishing something the Austrian
government should have done long ago, making Austrians aware of
their history. They should do this concert every year.''
</P>
<P>
   Back to that notion of joy: to judge from one visit, the
Mauthausen quarry is steadily filled with joyous sounds, the songs
of birds. They must have seemed a cruel mockery to prisoners at the
time, but from this vantage point they seem to speak of natural
renewal. Having learned to destroy more efficiently than nature,
can humans settle for less when it comes to repairing the damage?
Hope and resolve, if not joy, may be the only appropriate
responses.
</P>
<P>
   Beethoven's Ninth Symphony ``still awakens in us longings for
what we can no longer believe in, but wish we could,'' Taruskin
writes, going on to elaborate on a phrase coined by the
musicologist Joseph Kerman. ``We are still in the valley of the
Ninth. And so there's hope.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
