A8191 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-GLF-UGA-EASTREG0518-C     05-17 0470
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-UGA-EASTREG0518-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia well positioned at start of NCAA title defense
 &HT;    By Chip Towers
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. _ Georgia shocked the nation when they came home
with the NCAA Golf Championship last May. But the Bulldogs won't
sneak up on anybody when they begin defense of that title today in
the NCAA East Regional at Glenmaura National Golf Course in Moosic,
Pa.
</P>
<P>
   Despite losing three players from that team, including NCAA
runner-up Ryudi Imada, the fourth-ranked Bulldogs have barely
missed a step in making their fifth consecutive appearance in the
regionals.
</P>
<P>
   With three first-year players in the lineup, they were able to
capture their league-record 23rd SEC Championship _ something they
were unable to do last season _ last month in Florence, Ala., and
won three tournaments, the same number as last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel good about these guys,'' coach Chris Haack said.
``Every time we go into a tournament, I feel like we have a chance
to win. They've definitely exceeded my expectations. To be ranked
No. 4 going into the NCAAs, I would have taken that walking off the
course after (last year's championship). No matter what happens
from here on, it's been a great year.''
</P>
<P>
   Senior Michael Morrison and junior Nick Cassini have assumed the
leadership roles vacated by Imada, Mark Northey and Jeremy Parrott.
Erik Compton and Bryant Odom have proved to be explosive players,
although somewhat inconsistent.
</P>
<P>
   Compton, a freshman who was one of the top junior players in the
nation in Miami, carded a school-record 13-under-par 203 to win the
Golf World Invitational in Hilton Head in November. Then
junior-college transfer Bubba Watson, a big left-hander from
Bagdad, Fla., matched that score at the Schenkel in March.
</P>
<P>
   Cassini, a junior from Atlanta who started his career at Georgia
Tech, has led the Bulldogs all year in stroke average (71.33),
top-10 finishes (five) and rounds of par or better (17).
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a very competitive team,'' Cassini said. ``When we
play bad, we finish fourth or fifth; when we play well, we usually
win.''
</P>
<P>
   However, in the East Regional, the Bulldogs will be looking just
to survive and advance. Twenty-seven teams, including No. 1 Georgia
Tech and eight other top 20 squads, will be competing for 11 spots
in the NCAA Championships, which will be held May 31-June 3 at The
Lake Course at Grand National Golf Club in Opelika, Ala.
</P>
<P>
   Not advancing ``is always a concern,'' Haack said. ``We sat
there last year and watched (top-ranked) Clemson go into a playoff
for the right to go. We'll be a little more conservative and try
not to do anything stupid. Hopefully, we can play well and carry
some momentum into nationals.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
