<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 20:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8197 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-ICO-BANKRUPTCY-NYT     05-17 0749
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ICO-BANKRUPTCY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS ICO GLOBAL RESCUE IS COMPLETE, MERGER IS ANNOUNCED
</HEADLINE>
 By BARNABY J. FEDER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Craig O. McCaw, the cellular telephone pioneer, announced the
completion Wednesday of his investment group's $1.2 billion rescue
of ICO Global Communications Inc., which went bankrupt last summer
developing a satellite telecommunications network.
</P>
<P>
   And, as expected, he also announced his intention to merge the
``New ICO'' he brought out of bankruptcy with Teledesic LLC, the
more ambitious satellite network partnership he founded with Bill
Gates, the chairman of Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   The merged venture, ICO-Teledesic Global Limited, will be
temporarily run by Russell Daggatt, who is chief executive of
Teledesic, based in Bellevue, Wash. But McCaw, who will be
chairman, is seeking a permanent chief executive, according to a
person briefed on his plans. Richard Greco, ICO's chief executive,
resigned Wednesday to pursue other telecommunications work.
</P>
<P>
   The reorganization plan for New ICO requires McCaw, who controls
54 percent of New ICO, to files plans with the Securities and
Exchange Commission to allow the minority stockholders to trade
their shares, either publicly or privately, no later than March 31,
2001, said Roger Nyhus, a Teledesic spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   The value of both New ICO and Teledesic depends on whether
McCaw's consolidation strategy can restore faith in the satellite
communications market. That faith has been badly shaken by the
collapse of Motorola's Iridium network, ICO's fund-raising problems
and weak demand for the satellite phone service that Globalstar
Communications began offering in October.
</P>
<P>
   ``It helps that someone with a demonstrated business sense in
communications is in a position to run things,'' said Roger Rusch,
an industry consultant, referring to McCaw's stellar track record
of building McCaw Cellular into an enterprise that he sold to AT&AMP;T
for $11.5 billion in 1994 and his more recent role in turning
around Nextel Communications, the wireless carrier based in Reston,
Va.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's no guarantee for success,'' added Rusch, whose
company, Telastra, based in Palos Verdes Estates, Calif., advised
ICO Global bondholders during the bankruptcy reorganization.
</P>
<P>
   McCaw disclosed his effort to keep ICO afloat last November. The
investment group he organized included both domestic and foreign
investors, including Subhash Chandra, an entrepreneur from India
who initially announced a competing bid for control of ICO Global.
</P>
<P>
   As McCaw's executives examined the troubled company, they
concluded that its technology and marketing connections could be
built into a business that would function as a steppingstone toward
their vision of Teledesic.
</P>
<P>
   In a written statement issued Wednesday, McCaw characterized the
enterprises signed up to market ICO's service as an ``unrivaled
global network of leading telecommunications companies'' and Nyhus
said there had been discussions of possible ``synergies'' between
ICO and Teledesic.
</P>
<P>
   Under the direction of McCaw executives, ICO has already begun
revamping its ground stations to deliver limited Internet and data
services over its planned 12-satellite network in addition to the
voice traffic it originally envisioned. The work also involves
minor alterations to the satellites under construction by Hughes
Space and Communications and a preliminary agreement for Hughes to
build four spare satellites, according to an executive close to the
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   But McCaw denied a report in The Wall Street Journal on
Wednesday that he would expand ICO's network to 20 satellites. The
report said that the consolidation could bring $1 billion in new
business to Hughes, which is being acquired by Boeing.
</P>
<P>
   ICO Global's first satellite exploded during its launching in
March, but New ICO said it still planned to begin service in 2003.
That would be well in advance of Teledesic, which wants to put a
far greater number of satellites in lower orbits, allowing it to
handle Internet and data services that require hundreds of times
more bandwidth than ICO could handle.
</P>
<P>
   But Teledesic, which was originally envisioned as an
840-satellite network, has been bogged down by design complications
and shifting economic projections. Its latest plan calls for 288
satellites beginning operations in late 2004 at the earliest.
Unlike ICO, its intended market has been stationary users who would
need a satellite dish to send and receive signals.  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
