u f BC-BRAZIL-BANKS-NYT &LR;      05-17 0733
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAZIL-BANKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAZIL ENCOUNTERS RESISTANCE TO PRIVATIZATION OF BANESPA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Spain, Brazil, Germany, Mass.)   (Editors: dOliveira is cq.)  
 By JENNIFER L. RICH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAO PAULO, Brazil _ Over the past six years Brazil has reduced
state ownership of telecommunications, power and mining companies
in what is widely regarded as a highly successful privatization.
But the government is facing unexpectedly tough domestic resistance
to selling one of the biggest state assets, a bank known as
Banespa.
</P>
<P>
   With two months remaining until a scheduled auction of Banespa,
a Sao Paulo court has prohibited potential buyers from looking at
the financial records in Banespa's data room, acting on a lawsuit
from unionized bank employees.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of financial analysts representing potential buyers
have been encamped in Sao Paulo hotels, hoping the order, the
latest in a series of delays, will be reversed. Even if it is, more
court-ordered delays are expected in the sale of a prize with 600
branches, 3 million customers and 6 percent of the nation's bank
deposits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've stopped predicting the frequency of the delays,'' said
Brent Erensel, director of Latin Bank Equity Research at Deutsche
Bank. ``From the time when the data room opens, the soonest we can
expect an auction is ten weeks later. Until the room opens, you
cannot start the clock ticking.''
</P>
<P>
   The battle over the potential sale of Banespa, formally known as
Banco do Estado de Sao Paulo illustrates an underlying ambivalence
in Brazil about the benefits of privatization, which began in 1994.
The change has created an investment boom in Brazil and many
foreign companies now do business here. But the job security of
many Brazilians has been threatened as their employers changed from
the government to private owners who want to cut costs.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of the Banespa privatization say more than job
security is at stake. The Sao Paulo Bank Employees Union, which is
leading the fight, argues that Banespa is an important driver of
growth in the state of Sao Paulo, providing credit to small farms
and businesses and investing in social and educational projects.
Union officials say Banespa's priorities could change completely
under new ownership.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government came out with a study recently that said that
infant mortality in the State of Sao Paulo has tripled,'' said Joao
dOliveira, the union director. ``Why is that? Lack of basic
sanitation. And who invests in those projects? Banespa does.''
</P>
<P>
   Most experts agree, though, that Banespa's sale is inevitable.
``The sale could maybe drag out another two months, but to reverse
the privatization process is practically impossible,'' Eduardo
Guimaraes, the president of Banespa, said in an interview today.
``Once the data room opens, it will be even more complicated.''
</P>
<P>
   Seeking to rebut critics, the government has warned that any
further delay in the sale of Banespa could bring grave economic
consequences to a country still recovering from the currency crisis
of early 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Since the government plans to use the proceeds of the sale,
estimated to be as much as $2.3 billion, to pay down public debt,
the Central Bank estimates that a six-month delay would cause the
government to lose more than $100 million in interest payments.
Many economists say the government is exaggerating the economic
dangers. dOliveira, at the union, agrees. ``Their claim of grave
economic consequences is totally ridiculous,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Banespa's sale would be an important political achievement
for President Fernando Henrique Cardoso. Banespa represents the
last of what critics call the bad old days, when government-run
banks were used to finance questionable government projects.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sale of Banespa is a benchmark in terms of the fiscal
reforms that the government has been undertaking over the last few
years,'' said Andre Loes, chief economist at Santander Investment
in Sao Paulo. ``If the bank isn't sold this year, the government
will lose much more in political terms than in revenue.''
</P>
<P>
   Nine banks have expressed interest in buying Banespa, including
Brazil's three largest private banks _ Bradesco, Itau, and
Unibanco. The others include Brazil's Banco Safra as well as
Citibank, a unit of Citigroup, BankBoston, Britain's HSBC, and BSCH
and Banco Bilbao Vizcaya Argentaria of Spain.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
