u a BC-SCI-DIOXIN-CANCER-NYT     05-17 0982
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-DIOXIN-CANCER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EPA REPORT ON DIOXIN'S CANCER RISKS DRAWS PRAISE AND CRITICISM
</HEADLINE>
 
 (ATTN: Kan.) By GINA KOLATA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a draft of a long-awaited report on the health effects of the
pollutant dioxin, scientists at the Environmental Protection Agency
say that the chemical is 10 times more likely to cause cancer than
previously estimated. Some environmental groups hailed the draft,
but some scientists questioned its assertions.
</P>
<P>
   People with the highest exposures to the chemical _ those who
are older and eat fatty foods _ may have a one in 100 chance of
getting cancer from the dioxin in their bodies, the report says.
Moreover, it says, dioxin can cause other adverse health effects,
like developmental delays in children and disruptions in hormone
secretions.
</P>
<P>
   The agency said the report was still being written, and its
conclusions had not been distributed to an EPA Scientific Advisory
Board _ in fact, a board to evaluate the report was only now being
put together. Some scientists said they doubted the report's
conclusions would stand up to a board's scrutiny, and a few were
scathing in their assessment, with one expert in clinical
toxicology calling the report ``an embarrassment.''
</P>
<P>
   The conclusions of the draft report, but not the need for the
advisory board review, were described on Wednesday in The
Washington Post, sending industry groups and environmentalists
scrambling to respond to a document few had seen.
</P>
<P>
   The report is a revision of one the agency submitted for
assessment by its advisory board in 1994. The board questioned the
conclusions about dioxin's health effects and asked the agency to
repeat its work. The draft is the result of that work.
</P>
<P>
   Staff at the EPA said the report's conclusions were based on
scientific evidence that had emerged in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   A scientist for the agency, who spoke on condition of anonymity
because, he said, the agency was not responding to most calls from
reporters on the draft report, said the data came from the agency's
interpretation of studies in Dutch children showing that dioxin
might alter development and that it might affect thyroid hormone
secretions; studies of a group of men called the Ranch Hands, who
flew planes for the Air Force in Vietnam and were exposed to dioxin
while spraying the herbicide Agent Orange; and studies of
industrial workers.
</P>
<P>
   But, the scientist said, while the cancer risk of dioxin might
be much greater than previously estimated, Americans were exposed
to less of the pollutant than they once were.
</P>
<P>
   Dioxin is formed, for example, when chlorine-containing
chemicals, like plastics or industrial wastes, are burned, or when
pulp and paper are bleached. The chemical can waft through the air
or be carried in dust, settling on plants that are eaten by
animals. Once ingested, dioxin accumulates in the fat. When humans
eat the animals, or when they consume fat-containing dairy products
like milk, dioxin enters their bodies, where it remains, stored in
fat.
</P>
<P>
   Since the 1970s, however, strict pollution controls have caused
dioxin levels in the environment to drop. As a result, individuals
have less dioxin in their bodies than they once did.
</P>
<P>
   The EPA scientist said that even though many foods contained
dioxin, the food supply itself was safe. Though dioxin gets into
breast milk, he said, the benefits of breast feeding far exceed the
risks from dioxin.
</P>
<P>
   The EPA's conclusions on dioxin are being met with vigorous
responses from industry and from environmentalists.
</P>
<P>
   ``The EPA has a real dilemma,'' said Dr. Marcie Francis, senior
director of science policy at the Chorine Chemistry Council, an
industry group. ``If the food supply is safe and yet at the same
time dioxin is causing cancer, it's a real contradiction.''
</P>
<P>
   Rick Hind, legislative director of the Greenpeace Toxics
Campaign, said environmental groups like Greenpeace think the
agency did not go far enough. A pesticide would be banned if its
cancer risk was one in a million, he said. So, he asked, why did
the agency tolerate dioxin, with a cancer risk of one in 100?
</P>
<P>
   ``They prefer to look largely at the endpoints _ what some call
`blame the victim,' '' Hind said. ``Don't burn trash in your
backyard. Eat a low-fat diet. That's not enough.'' His group wants
a ban on chlorine-containing compounds, like polyvinyl chloride
used in plastics, for example.
</P>
<P>
   Some scientists who had reviewed the EPA's previous dioxin
report were skeptical about the new analysis.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Morton Lippmann, a professor of environmental medicine at
New York University School of Medicine, was head of the agency's
advisory board in 1994 and has agreed to head the board being put
together now. He said that while he had not seen the new draft
report, scientific research on dioxin since 1994 ``has been less
than definitive.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Michael Gough, a retired biologist who was on the agency's
scientific advisory board in 1994 and who was chairman of a
committee that evaluated the Ranch Hands data for the Department of
Health and Human Services, said there was no reason to believe the
cancer risk from dioxin is 10 times higher than had been thought.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been no epidemiological study in the last five
years, since their last assessment, that makes that claim any more
credible,'' Gough said.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. John Doull, a clinical toxicologist at the University of
Kansas in Kansas City, also was a member of the EPA's advisory
board that reviewed the previous dioxin report. He said the agency
seemed to have disregarded his group's advice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their review of the critical dioxin literature is inadequate
and their recommendations appear to me to be unsupported and
arrogant,'' Doull said. ``This action appears to be ill-timed,
political rather than scientific and is an embarrassment to science
and certainly to toxicology.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
