<HEADLINE>
AVALANCHE SEEKS BOOST FROM BOURQUE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF CAPLAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Ray Bourque slightly eased Colorado's pain of losing
physical defenseman Adam Foote by announcing his return for
tomorrow's Game 3.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went through practice and it went very well,'' said Bourque,
who last played May 1. ``I'm where I need to be. It's good to go
for Friday.''
</P>
<P>
   The veteran defenseman's return comes at a good time for the
Avalanche, who will be without Foote. A high-energy, aggressive
player, Foote almost single-handedly made life miserable for Stars
center] Mike Modano in Game 1.
</P>
<P>
   Bourque, 39, won't match Foote's physical presence, but his
leadership, as well as his return to the power play, will be a
plus. He said he expects to resume playing his usual 30 minutes a
game immediately. He refuted claims that Foote's eye injury is
rushing his return from a sprained left knee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've kind of turned a corner and that's what I was waiting for
over the last week or so, just getting over that hump,'' said
Bourque, who scored seven of his eight regular-season goals with
the Avs on the power play. ``I feel good about my situation and
feel good about playing on Friday. Regardless if Adam was there or
not, you've got to be good enough to go, and that's why I'm
playing.''
</P>
<P>
   Defenseman Aaron Miller, who is playing with a fractured jaw,
teamed with Bourque yesterday in place of Foote. That duo looks to
be the Avs' new top defensive pair. They will likely match up
against the Stars' top line of Mike Modano, Brett Hull and Jere
Lehtinen.
</P>
<P>
   ``To get Ray back and going is really big for this club,''
Miller said. ``He's kind of been the symbol for the way we've been
playing, kind of Ray Bourque-style hockey. I think we need to get
back to that. Him coming back will certainly help.''
</P>
<P>
   Foote did not attend the team's practice yesterday. He suffered
blunt trauma to his right eye when the blade of Lehtinen's stick
inadvertently struck him 2] minutes, 42 seconds into Game 2. Blood
flowed into the eye, complicating his return.
</P>
<P>
   In 12 playoff games, Foote _ who played 30 minutes against the
Stars in Game 1 _ had five assists, 18 penalty minutes and a
plus-five rating. It is not known if he will play in Game 4 on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to pick it up as a team,'' Bourque said. ``We have to
go play physical and play hard and be tenacious and really
desperate. Adam is a big, physical guy that plays with a lot of
emotion, and he'll certainly be missed, but, we've had guys step
up.''
</P>
<P>
   The Avs will pair Sandis Ozolinsh, who will play with what the
team terms a ``bruised foot,'' with Jon Klemm. Martin Skoula will
play with Greg de Vries, who stepped into the lineup when Bourque
was injured in Game 3 against Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   The loss of Foote also puts more pressure on the Avs' forwards
to take care of their defensive responsibilities, as well as to
create enough offense in the Stars' zone to take pressure off the
defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``It adds more responsibility to everybody,'' Avs winger Dave
Reid said. ``It puts much more emphasis on the forwards to pick up
their games in all parts.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
