<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-GOLFERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRO GOLFERS HAVE IDEAS ON HOW TO IMPROVE JOBS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHARLES CLINES 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ It seems to be such a perfect job.
</P>
<P>
   The work is on the best golf courses in the world. A workday is
about five to six hours. The workers are catered to. They have
someone carrying their golf bag. If they play well, they are paid
handsomely. They get their golf balls, clothes and clubs free.
They're basically their own boss.
</P>
<P>
   Who wouldn't want this job?
</P>
<P>
   It all sounds great. Yet, can any job be perfect, including the
PGA Tour, where anyone who swings a golf club aspires to work? If
the workers could change something to make it better, what could it
possibly be?
</P>
<P>
   Many of the pros who are in the Fort Worth-Dallas area for the
two PGA Tour stops _ the GTE Byron Nelson Classic and the
MasterCard Colonial _ were asked what they'd change, if anything,
if they could be tour commissioner Tim Finchem for a day and have
all-encompassing powers.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't take long for a smiling Nick Faldo to come up with an
answer that probably would get no arguments: ``I'd give everyone
$10 million. We'd all be happy. Equal pay.''
</P>
<P>
   But seriously.
</P>
<P>
   Many others said they couldn't think of a thing they'd change. A
perfect job is a perfect job, after all.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Pernice Jr. echoed the sentiments of several pros when he
said, ``I can't think of a thing. As a group, we may not be paying
Tim enough ... I can't say enough about the job he has done.''
</P>
<P>
   Brian Watts also couldn't think of anything he would change and
praised Finchem. He said that previous commissioner Deane Beman
should also be praised for the job he did for 20 years before
Finchem succeeded him in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tim Finchem and Deane Beman have done tremendous jobs from A
to Z ... A job that's unbelievable. Tim deserves a lot of credit,
and Deane should get a lot of credit for what he did.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, there were others who would take advantage of a wish to
tweak their perfect world.
</P>
<P>
   Some are taking exception to the trend to lengthen courses in an
attempt to ``Tiger-proof'' them. Others suggested tweaking the
world rankings, altering the pro-ams, reducing the number of
tournaments played, increasing the minimum events a player must
play in and taming the galleries.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Brooks of Fort Worth is one who believes a reduction in the
number of tournaments would help the remaining tournaments draw ``a
so-called more quality field,'' making more sponsors happy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd reduce the schedule by about 10 tournaments,'' he said.
``The problem would be finding 10 that would agree \Rto be
discontinued.\S.''
</P>
<P>
   Brooks extended that wish by also saying: ``I would raise the
minimum number of tournaments we have to play from 15 to 20 for the
players 40 years old and younger,'' he said. That would assure that
more tournaments would get more of the tour's top names, he said.
He said that after the top names play the four majors, the
Mercedes, The Players Championship, the World Cup of Golf and the
Tour Championship, they need only seven more tournaments to fulfill
their obligation to maintain an exempt status.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Lietzke, a former Nelson and Colonial winner who has been
on the tour since 1975, said he'd do something to control galleries
that ``are scaring me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm worried about the gallery etiquette and golf knowledge.
The game is so big and popular now and so many people are coming
out who are more rowdy and are more aggressive seeking
autographs,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the heckling at some tournaments is getting out of hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was embarrassing what happened to Colin Montgomerie at the
Ryder Cup,'' Lietzke said of the name-calling and heckling that
Montgomerie had to endure last year when the Europeans played the
Americans at The Country Club in Brookline, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   ``That wouldn't have happened 20 years ago,'' Lietzke said.
``We're getting more college-age kids, and there is more drinking
at the events. It's really scary and I think it's separating the
players from the fans more.''
</P>
<P>
   Lietzke suggested that instead of a tournament being shown every
week on TV, that a few shows could be aired about the history of
the game and about the kind of people the game has created.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to educate the people about the game,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Olin Browne, the defending champion at Colonial, is among those
who believes courses are becoming too long. He said lengthening
courses is playing into the hands of the long hitters such as Tiger
Woods. It's only making it more difficult for the shorter hitters.
He believes there are other, more fair ways to toughen golf
courses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm an average hitter,'' Browne said. ``If I'm hitting a
7-iron, Tiger's hitting a sand wedge. Instead of adding 30 to 40
yards to a hole, there are other ways to make it tougher _ such as
bringing the fairways in and raising the rough.''
</P>
<P>
   Brian Henninger said if he had power to make a change, he'd try
improving the world rankings.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I don't know how I'd do it,'' he said. ``I think Tim
Finchem is trying. The way the world rankings work is not a totally
fair way to judge performance. If you can get into the top 60, it's
hard to get out.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott Verplank said he would reducing the pro-ams to three
amateurs and one pro, instead of four amateurs and one pro as many
are.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would make it more fun for everyone,'' he said. ``We'd go
from 5- to 6-hour rounds to 41/2-hour rounds. It would make
everyone happier.''
</P>
<P>
   And that's something even the fans could wish for, even in a
perfect world.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-17-00 2045EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000517.0379 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 20:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8210 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-BBO-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX     05-17 0846
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLAME THE UMPIRES FOR ALL THIS HITTING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ This, the Rangers told us this spring, would
be the year of pitching and defense. Thankfully, we didn't ask
their advice on the stock market, too.
</P>
<P>
   Remember just a few weeks ago when Baltimore pitcher Mike
Mussina said ``they don't even look like the same Rangers
anymore?'' That was at the end of April. Since then, a
transformation has taken place. Mussina can rest assured, he'd
recognize them now.
</P>
<P>
   The old bop-'til-you-drop Rangers are back and their offensive
surge has helped fuel an 11-5 record for the first 17 days in May,
including yesterday's 11-6 victory over Tampa Bay in the wind
tunnel known as The Ballpark in Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   Six weeks into the season, the Rangers have basically dumped the
pitching and defense approach _ they've had no choice actually _
and resorted to bashing opponents' brains out to the tune of a
league-leading .304 batting average.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's one of the biggest reasons for optimism I have,''
manager Johnny Oates said, ``because we are scoring runs and I know
our pitching is going to pitch better.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't be too sure. What if the Rangers _ and every other team in
baseball _ are already pitching as well as they can? What if this
is as good as it gets?
</P>
<P>
   There's ample evidence that the delicate balance between offense
and pitching in baseball has been dramatically and drastically
tipped toward the hitters for a variety of reasons, from juiced
baseballs, to new technology in bat manufacturing, to bulked-up,
iron-pumping hitters, to bandbox ballparks, like Houston's new
Enron Field.
</P>
<P>
   Bad pitching? Sure. But it's not just bad pitchers who are
getting pounded these days. Rangers closer John Wetteland contends
he's throwing the ball every bit as well as last season, but his
earned-run average is a disturbing 5.71 and he has surrendered six
home runs in 17 1/3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   He's hardly alone. Dodgers closer Jeff Shaw has a 6.75 ERA.
Yankees stopper Mariano Rivera, who normally sets the standard for
all closers, was at 4.12 with two blown saves entering yesterday's
play.
</P>
<P>
   The collective team ERA in the American League is a whopping
5.12. The Rangers' 5.30 team ERA may provoke a sick feeling at the
pit of your stomach, but it ranks seventh in the league. Seven AL
teams are worse.
</P>
<P>
   The point is, what has been happening to Rangers pitchers is
happening all over baseball, sometimes worse.
</P>
<P>
   ``When good pitches are being made and the ball is still jumping
off the bat, it makes you wonder,'' Oates said. ``Good pitches
should get hitters out.''
</P>
<P>
   Too many good pitches, however, simply aren't being called
strikes.
</P>
<P>
   At some point in the distant past umpires woke up and screeched
to commissioner Bud Selig, ``Honey, we've shrunk the strike zone.''
It's now about the size of John Rocker's brain.
</P>
<P>
   ``If \Rthe umps\S called the strike zone like it's supposed to
be called, that would take care of 98 percent of it,'' contended
Rangers reliever Tim Crabtree, he of the handsome 8.66 ERA before
giving the Rangers 4 2/3 innings of relief yesterday without
allowing an earned run. ``If they would call a strike a strike, we
would be fine.''
</P>
<P>
   That, apparently, is not going to happen, at least not in our
lifetimes.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday, with a 35-mile-per-hour wind whistling into The
Ballpark and right back out again, Chad Curtis became the first
right-handed hitter to ever hit a ball into the Home Run Porch
upper deck.
</P>
<P>
   Chad Curtis.
</P>
<P>
   Think about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been hard for me to think \Rthe ball is juiced\S,''
Oates said. ``I just don't know. Then I saw our pitchers hit six
out the first time they took batting practice this year and I have
to wonder what's going on.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see so many good pitches just jumping off the bat. I'm
talking about a pitcher throwing a nasty 1-2 slider down and away
and the hitter just barely getting the head of the bat to it and
lining it through the infield.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's not the ball, though. Maybe it's stronger, bigger
hitters, who lift weights and train year-round. Maybe it's the
ultra-hard bats manufacturers are now supplying. ``Some of them
don't even look like wood,'' Oates said. Maybe it's the new, tiny
ballparks with 370-foot power alleys.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's all of the above.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what the point is where you become saturated with
so much scoring, so many home runs, that people become bored with
it,'' Oates said. ``The offensive explosion we're seeing now is
kind of like this wind: I keep thinking it'll die down
eventually.''
</P>
<P>
   If not, Oates said, baseball will know when it's time to act to
restore balance to the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe the batter will start out with one strike,'' Oates
suggested. ``Or just have two outs an inning. Bring the mound in
six feet. Widen the plate.''
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe get really radical and actually call the strike zone.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the old rock-'em, sock-'em Rangers are back,
and maybe just in time.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
