<SLUG> BC-BOX-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AYALA SEEMS TO HAVE HIS LIFE TURNED AROUND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRAND PRAIRIE, Texas _ Just another typical weekend coming up in
the local jock kingdom. It's a busy combo platter of Rangers in
Arlington against the Orioles, Stars in Denver for Game 3 against
the Avalanche, and, of course, the annual margarita marathon at
Colonial Country Club, where the less-adventurous can also watch
PGA guys play golf for big money.
</P>
<P>
   From the standpoint of an intriguing story line, however, all of
the above pales dramatically when compared to what's going on at
Will Rogers Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Ayala Jr. fights in Fort Worth tomorrow night.
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood has made preliminary inquiries about buying the rights
to the life and times of a former bad guy trying to go good, but
...
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing has come along we're comfortable with,'' said Ayala
yesterday. ``I think for the most part, people are waiting to see
how this story turns out. Do I win a world title, or do I go back
to prison? That seems to be the only two things that matter to
everyone except me.''
</P>
<P>
   And what does matter to maybe the greatest boxing talent ever to
come out of Texas?
</P>
<P>
   Ayala: ``Family. Friends. Money in the bank. Owning a home
that's paid for. And then being able to someday fade into the
sunset and always live happily ever after. I need boxing for some
of that, but I don't need boxing to live a happy life.''
</P>
<P>
   On a wind-blown afternoon at Lone Star Park in Grand Prairie,
Ayala was advancing his Friday night fight with a media conference
and public workout.
</P>
<P>
   Obvious question:
</P>
<P>
   Is this just another ex-con skillfully working a master con?
</P>
<P>
   Obvious answer:
</P>
<P>
   Spend 20 minutes or so with Ayala, listen to what he has to say,
and then tell me you don't come away impressed. And a believer.
</P>
<P>
   Some haven't. His parole officer in New Jersey said if Ayala
returned to the boxing world, he would end up back in prison. The
head of the parole board in New Jersey said two years ago that
Ayala was still every bit the danger to society, if not more so,
that he was when he was sentenced to prison in 1983. Parole was
rejected at that time.
</P>
<P>
   No research was needed to dig up what the parole officer or the
prison board chairman had to say about Ayala. Tony tells that
himself, matter-of-factly.
</P>
<P>
   Ayala is 37 years old now. Go back 20 years, at age 17, and Tony
Jr. was already a world championship waiting to happen in the
boxing world. Ayala hails from a famous San Antonio family of
fighters. He was the special one, however. Even so, the word was
also on the street that Tony Jr. would never make it. Here was a
bad kid, getting worse all the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``If none of this had happened in my life, I'd have gone ahead
and won the world title, defended it successfully once, and then
been dead within 12 months,'' Ayala said yesterday. ``I was totally
out of control. Suicidal, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Ayala had a problem, among other things, with booze, heroin and
women. ``But mainly my problem was a lack of self-esteem,'' he
said. Having moved from Texas to New Jersey, Ayala was charged with
raping a 19-year-old neighbor on New Year's Day 1983. The sentence
was 35 years in prison, with a minimum of 15 years before being
eligible for parole. Ayala served 16 hard years.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, his was a shocking crime for such a high-profile
member of the jock kingdom. But Ayala was a boxer. Only boxers
seemed capable of such behavior. Only boxers seemed to end up in
prison.
</P>
<P>
   Today's sports page headlines tell a much different story, of
course. Two NFL players currently charged with murder. Another with
raping a 17-year-old. ``Athletes aren't exempt from making bad
mistakes,'' said Ayala. ``We have our problems like anyone else.
The exposure factor in the media is what has changed. But that also
goes all the way to the presidency, doesn't it? No one is protected
anymore when it comes to the media looking the other way.''
</P>
<P>
   Once released from prison (on April 20, 1999), Ayala was back in
the gym the next day, resuming a boxing career on hold for 17
years. Friday night will be his fifth fight in the comeback
attempt. Eventually, he hopes it leads him to Felix Trinidad.
</P>
<P>
   ``Prison was a lifesaver for me,'' said Ayala. ``I deeply regret
what I did to people. I regret victimizing my victim. I got what I
deserved when I went to prison. I'm thankful, however, for this
second chance. I'm thankful I'm sitting here with a six-figure
income, talking to reporters. How many ex-cons get that kind of
opportunity? I want to talk to anyone who will listen, just to tell
them about how I went wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``After what I've done to myself, being able to box again is
like being in an amusement park. Boxing is important. Winning is
important. Making money is important. But the rest of my life
doesn't depend on it.''
</P>
<P>
   This busy weekend in the local jock kingdom has many different
story angles. But nothing else comes close to where Tony Ayala Jr.
has been, and where he hopes to go.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
