<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-ROY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROY, STARS IN A CHESS MATCH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Stars winger Kirk Muller learned a little
something in his almost four seasons in Montreal with Colorado
goalie Patrick Roy.
</P>
<P>
   ``You got to be careful with Patty,'' Muller said. ``He's pretty
good at making it look like there are some infractions going on
when maybe it's him doing the bumping.''
</P>
<P>
   Somebody is definitely bumping, and referees are definitely
noticing.
</P>
<P>
   In the first two games of the Western Conference Finals,
one-fourth of the penalties called on the Stars came against Roy.
In Game 1, four of the 10 penalties on Colorado and the Stars were
for bumping or interfering with the goalies.
</P>
<P>
   All the face time prompted the referees to warn players from
both teams before Game 2 that it was OK to look at the goalies,
they just can't touch them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before Game 2, we were told it was going to be called on both
teams,'' Stars winger Mike Keane said. ``We know they're calling
it, and that doesn't work on Patrick, anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Which hasn't stopped them from trying.
</P>
<P>
   Or Roy from taking advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they purposely go in front of people and get in guys'
ways,'' Stars captain and defenseman Derian Hatcher said. ``If the
guy even touches them, they call it. ... You shake your head, yeah.
That's all you can do. You can argue with the refs all you want,
but it doesn't do you a lot of good.''
</P>
<P>
   So do the Stars leave Roy free to roam?
</P>
<P>
   Only if they want to get beat. Badly.
</P>
<P>
   Nervous isn't an emotion Roy feels even if he gets caught behind
the net with a Stars player swooping in on him. Roy, much like
Stars goalie Ed Belfour, relishes venturing from his net, playing
the puck and starting the rush.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's like a defenseman,'' Stars center Mike Modano said. ``If
you rush him, and you force him to make a play he's not comfortable
making, then we're able to feed off that and pick them off along
the boards or along the glass.''
</P>
<P>
   So how does one rush him without bumping him?
</P>
<P>
   ``Very carefully,'' Stars defenseman Sylvain Cote said.
</P>
<P>
   This is the invisible line the Stars walk every game. They can't
get too close to Roy. They can't stay too far away.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we get a chance to whack his stick or get body position on
him, that's what we're going to do,'' Stars defenseman Richard
Matvichuk said. ``What we're not going to do is go out there and
intentionally bump him.''
</P>
<P>
   Which doesn't mean Roy can't make it look as if] they have.
</P>
<P>
   Just ask Muller.
</P>
<P>
   ``Remember during the regular season that goal called back for
interference? They said I got Roy,'' Muller said. ``But Patty, he's
pretty good. I was there, and well, you know ... ''
</P>
<P>
   He didn't finish the sentence.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't exactly know how to say Roy was a good flopper without
saying the word flop, which isn't a compliment in the hockey world.
</P>
<P>
   ``In other words, you mean he's a good actor?'' Stars coach Ken
Hitchcock said. ``So is Eddie. They are both very good. They both
have careers post playing.''
</P>
<P>
   All the ice is a stage, and they're just players.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
