<SLUG> BC-BBA-CATALANOTTO-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CATALANOTTO HAS QUITE A DAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CARLOS MENDEZ 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON _ Frank Catalanotto had the kind of game yesterday
that you laugh about later.
</P>
<P>
   Not because it's funny _ five hits in a game is serious stuff.
It's just that some days, it seems as if you can't do anything
wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday was one of those days for Catalanotto, who used a
fill-in day at first base to collect a career-high five hits in an
11-6 victory against Tampa Bay at The Ballpark in Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   The quick-to-smile Catalanotto, three days removed from the
disabled list, didn't escape some kidding.
</P>
<P>
   ``I teased him about it the last time he got to first,''
first-base coach Bucky Dent said. ``I said, `Cat, you trying?' He
said, `Yeah, I'm trying.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Catalanotto hita run-scoring single and scored in the first
inning, singled to shortstop in the third inning, singled to center
in the fourth, singled to right-center in the sixth and singled to
right in the eighth. He was flawless in the field, too, receiving
the first two putouts of the game and making the last out with a
backhanded grab and toss to first off a grounder by Fred McGriff.
</P>
<P>
   Just another 1.000 hitting and fielding day for the 26-year-old,
a regular second baseman who in 41 career games at first base is
error-free.
</P>
<P>
   ``At second base you're involved, but at first base, you really
have to concentrate,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The concentration began in earnest for Catalanotto about an hour
before yesterday's game, when he learned David Segui would miss his
start at first base because of a virus. Catalanotto moved into
Segui's No. 5 position in the batting order, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really didn't feel like I was going to get beat,'' he said.
``Even when I had two strikes, I thought I'd be able to hit the
ball and put it in play.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the first start of the season at first base for
Catalanotto, who came off the disabled list Monday and appeared as
a pinch hitter on Tuesday. He walked in that plate appearance, and
his five hits yesterday gave him eight consecutive _ tying a club
record last accomplished by Ivan Rodriguez in July 1993.
Catalanotto has also reached base 10 consecutive times, moving
within one of the club record.
</P>
<P>
   His batting average, .500 when he was placed on the DL, is now
.586 (17-for-29). Maybe the DL isn't such a bad place.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's funny. Some guys come off the DL and they just start off
hot,'' Catalanotto said. ``Maybe the time off helped mentally. The
last three weeks, I've been able to go home and study tapes of
myself hitting and the pitchers I'm going to be facing.''
</P>
<P>
   Away from the crowd of reporters that buzzed around his locker,
Catalanotto leaned back in his chair, folded his hands across his
stomach, and thought about his day. But one more question: ``Did
you do anything different today?''
</P>
<P>
   Another smile leaked out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I could tell you what it was, but I can't,'' he said.
``It was just one of those things.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
