<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-PREAKNESS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAINER LIKES RED BULLET'S NUMBERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TIM PRICE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ Because of the way Fusaichi Pegasus dominated the
Kentucky Derby, the numbers have dwindled at the Preakness Stakes _
19 horses raced in the Derby, and eight are entered in the
Preakness.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Orseno, trainer of Preakness entrant Red Bullet, said the
numbers better keep dwindling or Fusaichi Pegasus is in trouble in
Saturday's race at Pimlico Race Course.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers Orseno is talking about are the nationally
distributed performance figures formulated by a group of East
Coast-based handicappers. Also known as the ``sheets,'' they assign
a numerical value to a horse's performance. The numbers factor in
considerations such as the running time of the race and how it
compares to other times at similar races. Wind speed, wind
direction and the position a horse raced on the track also are
considered.
</P>
<P>
   The lower the number, the stronger the performance.
</P>
<P>
   Orseno said Fusaichi Pegasus was assigned a 21/2 when he won the
Wood Memorial by four lengths over Red Bullet, who was assigned a
5. Red Bullet skipped the Derby, where Fusaichi Pegasus recorded
another 21/2, according to Orseno, who has read the sheets long
enough to know the amount of times a horse can repeat a superior
number such as 21/2.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not too often,'' he said. ``And to come back and do it two
weeks later will be very hard to do.''
</P>
<P>
   And Orseno said that Fusaichi Pegasus won't be able to get by
with an inferior number to win the Preakness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Knowing my horse and where we're at, yeah, he'll have to run a
21/2 or 3 to win,'' Orseno said of Fusaichi Pegasus.
</P>
<P>
   There are two reasons Orseno is so confident in Red Bullet. He
said the colt can run better than he did in the Wood, and the five
weeks between the Wood and the Preakness gives him a better chance
at improving.
</P>
<P>
   ``That wasn't his peak race,'' Orseno said.
</P>
<P>
   Orseno said Red Bullet got tired in the stretch because jockey
Alex Solis made a quick decision to send him after the pacesetter
rather than hold him back in reserve and risk traffic problems
later in the race. But he still had enough to finish 11/2 lengths
ahead of Aptitude, and that should grab some attention. Aptitude,
after all, ran second by 11/2 lengths to Fusaichi Pegasus in the
Derby.
</P>
<P>
   That makes Red Bullet's challenge against Fusaichi Pegasus look
intriguing. But there's enough history to work against him. A horse
that skipped the Derby hasn't won the Preakness since Deputed
Testimony did it 17 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Orseno said he and owner Frank Stronach let Red Bullet skip the
Derby because the Wood took a lot out of him. He's at the Preakness
because Orseno and Stronach want him to be selected champion
3-year-old at the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if anybody has skipped the Derby with a horse
that has this kind of talent,'' Orseno said.
</P>
<P>
   Before it's over, Orseno said the numbers will bear that out.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-17-00 2046EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000517.0384 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 20:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8215 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-HKN-WEST-BOURQUE0518-     05-17 0943
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-WEST-BOURQUE0518-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Avs' Bourque thankful for run at Cup
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ The telephone call followed nearly two months of
agonizing. It came after two months of wondering whether the Boston
Bruins were a hopeless cause and whether the idea that he could
awaken his 39-year-old legs was equally hopeless.
</P>
<P>
   Ray Bourque didn't necessarily want to leave Boston after nearly
21 seasons as much as he wondered if there was a life away from the
Charles River. So he made the call.
</P>
<P>
   On Feb. 28, the Hall-of-Famer-in-waiting called Bruins general
manager Harry Sinden at the meeting of NHL general managers in
California and uttered the two words few thought possible: Trade
me.
</P>
<P>
   A week later, he got his wish.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact of the matter is,'' Bourque said Wednesday, ``if I
finished the year in Boston, I probably would've called it quits.
But I wanted to be traded for two reasons. I wanted to find out if
I could play at a certain level again, and I wanted to make a good
run at the Cup. Because of the way I've played and the way things
have gone this year, there's a very good possibility I'll be
playing again next year.''
</P>
<P>
   Bourque only hopes that when he does retire, he will do so with
a ring on his finger and his name engraved on the Stanley Cup. He
hasn't been this close in awhile. Colorado general manager Pierre
Lacroix acquired Bourque and forward Dave Andreychuk, two well-aged
veterans in search of a title, for a significant portion of the
Avalanche's future: Brian Rolston, two top prospects and a
first-round draft choice. Lacroix's mind-set was the same as
Bourque's: Win now.
</P>
<P>
   The Avs mostly have won since the March 6 trade. A skilled but
erratic club before the deal, Colorado went 12-2-1 to close the
season and is 9-3 in the playoffs, including a split of the first
two games against Dallas in the Western Conference finals, which
resume Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Bourque has missed the past four games _ the final two of the
Detroit series and the two against the Stars _ because of a knee
injury; the details have been kept quiet. But Wednesday, after
going through a full practice, including he confirmed that he will
be back in the lineup for Game 3.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a go,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For any other player, it might mean a spot shift. For Bourque,
it will mean playing on Colorado's No. 1 defensive pair, anchoring
the power play and killing penalties _ probably 30 minutes of
action. At this point, his return is not merely welcomed but is
almost mandated.
</P>
<P>
   The Avs have lost defenseman Adam Foote with an eye injury for
at least one game. Another defenseman, Sandis Ozolinsh, practiced
despite a ``bruised foot,'' but team officials have followed the
NHL tradition of being misleading about injuries so often that many
people think that he, too, has a knee injury and might not play.
</P>
<P>
   Bourque's injury initially was identified as a foot problem and
then changed to a knee. ``I just banged up my knee,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Most important is that he will be back.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't replace him,'' Colorado forward Dave Reid said.
``He's such a calming influence back there because of the
experience he brings.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bourque trade ``was like a wake-up call for everybody,''
Reid said. ``We weren't playing that great, but when he came,
everybody knew it was time to get serious.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Bob Hartley said: ``He changed our team totally. I've
never seen a trade where a guy has fit in so quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   Aaron Miller might be paired with Bourque on defense. ``It's not
like he had to carry the team on his shoulders,'' Miller said. ``We
already had a lot of talent here. But he solidified things.
</P>
<P>
   The absolute answer is the Cup. Bourque reached the finals twice
with Boston, in 1988 and 1990. Both times, the Bruins lost to
Edmonton. Because of recent personnel decisions, he knew they
weren't going back any time soon.
</P>
<P>
   Playing for a contender again rejuvenated Bourque, who had 14
points, including eight goals, in 14 games with Colorado to close
the regular season. He also turned the team's power play into the
league's best.
</P>
<P>
   But being this close to the finals and sitting out hasn't been
easy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was tough, but I knew the injury was minor, in terms of not
being out for the rest of the playoffs,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bourque reached icon status in Boston, so it follows that there
are a number of converted Colorado fans along the Charles River.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know there a lot of fans cheering for me in Boston,'' he
said. ``Whenever I call back to Boston and talk to some of my
buddies, they tell me about all of the interest people have.''
</P>
<P>
   The most popular jersey in Boston now is a half-Bruins,
half-Avalanche stitch job with Bourque's name and No. 77 on the
back.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy who made them is from New Hampshire, and he's a Bruins
season-ticket holder,'' Bourque said. ``I met him and signed two
jerseys for him. I thought it was pretty neat.''
</P>
<P>
   Like the mixed jersey, Bourque had mixed emotions about the
trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm the one who asked for it,'' he said. ``But when it
happens, you deal with a lot of different emotions. I've never been
through it before.
</P>
<P>
   Being apart from his wife and children has been difficult. But
the journey, Bourque said, has been worth it. After this season, he
will be an unrestricted free agent, but thoughts of the Stanley Cup
take priority. Everybody else seems to know it, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's people you'd like to see have a Cup, he's one of
them,'' Dallas' Brett Hull said. ``But we're not going to lay down
for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
