<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 20:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8225 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w BC-CHINA-TRADE-ART-2TAKE     05-17 0919
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-TRADE-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE AND SENATE COMMITTEES PASS CHINA TRADE BILL 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(Eds: Also being filed in `i' news category.) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT with DAVID E. SANGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Committees in the House and the Senate
overwhelmingly endorsed the administration's China trade bill on
Wednesday, contributing to a growing sense that the ardently
contested measure was headed for passage.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, which would permanently grant China normal trading
privileges, also got a plug from Gov. George W. Bush, the
presumptive Republican presidential nominee, who renewed his call
on lawmakers to set aside their partisan differences and back the
measure.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, speaking at the U.S. Coast Guard Academy,
warned lawmakers that rejecting the China bill ``invites a future
of dangerous confrontation and constant insecurity.''
</P>
<P>
   In Congress, half a dozen previously uncommitted House
Republicans and Democrats announced they would support the
legislation, a necessary step for American companies to benefit
fully from a market-opening accord that paves the way for China to
enter the World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials and congressional backers of the
measure said they believe they might be close to the 218 votes
needed for passage in the House when the bill comes to a vote next
week, though they continued their heated campaign for votes.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point we're looking for insurance votes,'' said one
administration official. But the U.S. Trade Representative,
Charlene Barshefsky, said, ``the situation is still fluid.''
</P>
<P>
   In Wednesday's House Ways and Means Committee vote, four
previously undeclared Democrats joined an overwhelming vote, 34-4,
in favor of the measure. Earlier in the day, the Senate Finance
Committee approved the legislation, 18-1. Both committees have
jurisdiction over trade bills, and supporters of the China bill
hailed the lopsided results for building momentum toward next
week's House vote.
</P>
<P>
   Barshefsky, Commerce Secretary William M. Daley and other
administration officials continued to buttonhole wavering members
of Congress on Capitol Hill on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials also said they plan to seek air time from
the major television networks to allow Clinton to address the
nation on Sunday night about the China bill's importance, not only
to American farmers, high-tech companies and manufacturers, but
also for the country's long-term national security. Officials at
CBS, ABC and NBC said Wednesday night that they had not yet been
contacted by the White House with the request.
</P>
<P>
   On Capitol Hill, critics of the measure downplayed the committee
votes as preordained, and insisted that their campaign to focus on
Beijing's poor record on human rights, religious freedom,
environmental standards and earlier trade accords, was working.
</P>
<P>
   ``As Americans, we value trade, but we will never trade in our
values,'' said Rep. David E. Bonior of Michigan, the measure's
chief Democratic opponent.
</P>
<P>
   Labor leaders said they would intensify their lobbying of
fence-sitters during the last weekend before the vote. Opponents
cited reports from an official Chinese newspaper Wednesday that
threatened war with Taiwan if the island's president-elect, Chen
Shui-bian, does not commit to a ``one-China'' policy in his
inaugural speech this weekend. One senior Clinton administration
official said this week that ``we're very worried about the
weekend'' because the Chinese ``have a long record of saying just
the wrong thing, or doing something stupid, at the last moment.''
</P>
<P>
   But Wednesday was a day for the China measure's supporters to
cheer.
</P>
<P>
   To attract Democrats with heavy union constituencies, the Ways
and Means Committee amended its bill by including a provision of
the final trade accord negotiated last November to protect American
industries from a surge in imports from China.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation would allow the International Trade Commission,
and then the president, to halt the import of Chinese goods _ from
steel to computers to a range of other products _ if they are being
shipped into the United States ``in such increased quantities or
under such conditions as to cause or threaten to cause market
disruption to the domestic producers of like or directly
competitive products.''
</P>
<P>
   That provision, coupled with the endorsement by the committee's
ranking Democrat, Charles B. Rangel of New York, seemed to provide
the final push for four committee Democrats who had been undecided
to vote for the bill: Richard E. Neal of Massachusetts, Karen L.
Thurman of Florida, Lloyd Doggett of Texas and Benjamin L. Cardin
of Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   But the new provision may also plant the seeds of new American
tensions with China. The definition of what constitutes a ``surge''
of imports is always a matter of dispute, and China would almost
certainly take any American efforts to limit its imports to the
court of the World Trade Organization for adjudication. Because it
is not a WTO member now, it has not been able to challenge such
rulings, including a recent one blocking imports of Chinese steel.
</P>
<P>
   Barshefsky said Wednesday that she was not worried about such
challenges. ``The Chinese know what they agreed to in November,''
she said, ``and they understood we had to have the ability to stop
import surges.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   If the bill is approved, it will end the need for annual renewal
of China's trading status by Congress, an event that prompted
heated debate over the country's human rights record and its
threats against Taiwan. Every year Congress approved the trade
status, even after the 1989 killings in Tiananmen Square. But
opponents of the measure say that by dropping the linkage between
how China treats dissidents and its ability to trade with the
United States, Congress will be giving up leverage over the
government in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   To appease some of the opponents, Democrats and Republicans are
finalizing plans for a permanent commission that will review
China's human rights record annually. But labor unions and other
opponents say the commission would be toothless because it only has
the power to make public its findings, something the State
Department does anyway in its annual human rights report.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to winning over some wavering Democrats, the White
House picked up the support of three uncommitted Republicans: Rick
Hill of Montana, Tillie Fowler of Florida and Henry Hyde of
Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   Some vote-counters had already included Hill and Fowler in their
tallies, but Hyde was a coup because he has consistently voted
against upgrading China's trade status in Congress' annual review.
All the Democrats from Illinois are voting against the pact,
despite heavy lobbying from Barshefsky and Daley, both Chicago
natives.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials and their congressional allies said
they now may be less than 10 votes shy of the 218 needed for
passage in the House. Republicans are expected to provide at least
150 of the votes needed for passage, although two administration
officials predicted that they will get more.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic supporters, while sounding upbeat that they could win
70 votes from their ranks, still voiced caution, especially after a
few unexpected defections this week, such as Rep. Bob Clement of
Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not there yet,'' said Rep. Robert T. Matsui, D-Calif., a
chief vote-counter for the bill. ``It's getting harder and
harder.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, two-thirds of 211 House Democrats are likely to vote
against the measure, but Democratic critics of China's record on
human rights, worker standards and environmental protections were
vastly outnumbered Wednesday in the pro-trade Ways and Means
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Only four of the panel's 16 Democrats voted against the measure:
Pete Stark of California, William J. Coyne of Pennsylvania, John
Lewis of Georgia and Gerald D. Kleczka of Wisconsin. A fifth
Democratic foe, Michael R. McNulty of New York, was absent for the
vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not that I don't want to trade with China,'' Kleczka
said, ``but I don't want to fling open the doors of this country
and never have a review again.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, all members of the Senate Finance Committee,
except Sen. James Jeffords, R-Vt., voted for the measure. Jeffords
said he was protesting the continued imprisonment of Ngawang
Choepel, a Tibetan musicologist and former Fulbright scholar at
Middlebury College in Vermont.
</P>
<P>
   Another critic of China, Sen. Fred Thompson, R-Tenn., voted for
the trade bill, but also introduced a separate bill to monitor
Beijing's proliferation of missile technology and other advanced
weaponry.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
