u f BC-MARKET-NYT &LR;      05-17 0813
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WIDESPREAD SELL-OFF CAUSES MARKET GUAGES TO DIP 
</HEADLINE>
   By KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Stocks fell for the first time in five sessions
Wednesday as investors took some profits from the recent run-up in
prices and re-examined the potential effect of the Federal
Reserve's half-point increase in interest rates on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The sell-off was widespread, with each of the three main market
gauges falling more than 1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But traders and analysts said the drop was understandable in
light of the market's recent gains and a clear signal from the Fed
that the rate increase _ the sixth since last June _ would probably
not be the last.
</P>
<P>
   The central bank signaled its resolve in a tough statement that
accompanied its move to raise the federal funds rate on overnight
loans between banks by 50 basis points, to 6.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you read that statement in a couple of years, you would
have no clue that the Fed had already done five tightenings,'' said
Thomas M. McManus, chief equity strategist at the Bank of America.
``So far, there is little evidence that the tightening they have
done to date has slowed the economy appreciably.''
</P>
<P>
   Market gauges opened lower and stayed that way for the entire
session. An announcement by Intel that it again intends to split
its stock and to raise its dividend at the end of July helped lift
the indexes off their lows during the afternoon, but the relief was
temporary.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average fell 164.83 points, or 1.51
percent, to 10,769.74. Hewlett-Packard, which dropped more than 9
points; General Motors, and Minnesota Mining and Manufacturing led
the blue-chip index down. Only four of the 30 stocks in the Dow
managed to move higher for the day. Market breadth was
distinctively negative, with declining stocks outnumbering those
advancing, 1,906 to 1,017.
</P>
<P>
   Cisco Systems, which fell 2 9/16, to 58, led the Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500-stock index lower. It dropped 18.24 points, or 1.24
percent, to 1,447.80.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index shed 72.61 points, or 1.95 percent,
to 3,644.96, pulled down by stocks like Cisco, Microsoft, Qualcomm
and Nextel. Over the previous four sessions, the Nasdaq had gained
9.8 percent. So far this year, it is down 10.43 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Lycos, a big winner on Tuesday, was a big loser Wednesday,
perhaps reflecting reluctance by some U.S. investors to own
foreign-controlled companies. Its stock fell 15 1/64 to 57 39/64 in
very heavy trading, after having risen 18 percent on Tuesday, when
the portal agreed to be bought in a stock swap by Terra Networks,
the Internet unit of the Spanish phone giant Telefonica. Terra's
American depository receipts fell 6 9/16, to 47.
</P>
<P>
   Small stocks also took a beating. The Russell 2000 index fell
6.32 points, or 1.25 percent, to 499.66.
</P>
<P>
   With the Fed remaining on the offensive, ``we will see a
trendless market for a while,'' said Kenneth M. Sheinberg, head of
listed stock trading at SG Cowen.
</P>
<P>
   ``People will continue to take some money out of stocks with
high price-to-earnings multiples and put money into stocks with
reasonable prices,'' he said. ``That will create some stability in
the market, which is what Alan Greenspan really wants.''
</P>
<P>
   While broad sections of the market moved lower, financial
services stocks, widely seen as vulnerable to rising interest
rates, were little changed.
</P>
<P>
   J.P. Morgan, a Dow component, rose 11/16, to 132 5/8. Citigroup
fell 5/8, to 61 1/16. Merrill Lynch gained 1/8, to 108. And Morgan
Stanley Dean Witter closed at 76, up 3/4.
</P>
<P>
   Hewlett-Packard was the Dow's big loser, falling 9 5/16, to 130
11/16. The stock had surged nearly 10 percent over the previous
four trading days.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T fell 13/16, to 38 1/16, after Jack Grubman, an analyst at
Salomon Smith Barney, lowered his earnings forecast for 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Cisco fell 2 9/16, to 58, its first decline in three sessions.
Microsoft dipped 1 13/16, to 67 11/16, after a four-day rally. And
Oracle fell 1, to 78 3/16.
</P>
<P>
   Intel was one of a very few big technology stocks to rise. It
closed at 123 3/16, up 1 5/16. The company announced a 2-for-1
stock split, and said it would raise its quarterly dividend by 33
percent, effective July 31.
</P>
<P>
   McManus, the Bank of America strategist, said he remained
positive about the stock market, but expected the Fed to increase
interest rates again at its next meeting, on June 27-28.
</P>
<P>
   ``We told people this morning that it was pretty likely the Fed
would bump rates another 50 basis points in June,'' he said. ``But
I am still encouraged that the market is broadening, and that the
S&AMP;P is going up. I expect the market to remain in a trading range,
for technology stocks to continue to correct, and for some of the
other sectors that have underperformed sharply over the last year
to continue to work their way higher.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
