u f BC-NIEMAN0518-COX     05-17 0795
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIEMAN0518-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Online shoe boutique work of Atlanta firm
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The unique and mystical relationship between women and
shoes has been pondered by artists for centuries.
</P>
<P>
   Now an Atlanta company, RichFX, and Dallas-based luxury
department store Neiman Marcus have joined to give women one of the
most unusual virtual shoe-shopping experiences on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   Neiman Marcus and RichFX have announced a long-term strategic
partnership centered on the couture shoe collection of designer
Manolo Blahnik.
</P>
<P>
   The Blahnik shoe salon will debut this fall as a section of the
Neiman Marcus Web site (www.neimanmarcus.com). The companies will
officially premiere the Web site at the RealNetworks conference in
San Jose, Calif., next week. Financial terms were not disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   Shoppers who visit the Blahnik shoe salon _ the Italian
shoemaker's only online presence _ will see the trademark Nieman
Marcus butterfly taking users into a virtual environment resembling
a scene from the computer game ``Myst,'' complete with search
functions and a shopping cart.
</P>
<P>
   The user can walk through the store and select shoes to look at,
then turn them around and put them back on the shelves, just as he
or she would in real life. Shoppers in a hurry, with no time for
icons or virtual worlds, can just search for an item, then purchase
it.
</P>
<P>
   To develop the prototype for Neiman Marcus, RichFX Chief
Executive Tal Kerret and his team used the Lenox Square store as
the model for the first virtual store. But Kerret says the stores
can be customized to represent any city in the world, shown at any
time of day or night, depending on when users log on.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're doing is bringing a whole new way of shopping to
the Net,'' says Kerret. ``Most e-commerce Web sites have millions
of pages, but most people only go about three pages deep. Using the
virtual-store technology from RichFX, customers can browse an
entire store using streaming technology and even click on an item
to see closeups of fabric swatches or product labels.''
</P>
<P>
   The deal with Neiman Marcus could expand into other areas beyond
the Blahnik shoe salon, according to Kerret and Neiman Marcus.
</P>
<P>
   Gayle Tremblay, vice president of Neiman Marcus online, says the
upscale department store first heard of RichFX from its consulting
group. After a presentation, the company started to look for a way
to use the RichFX applications on its site.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our philosophy is that we've always been on the leading edge
of fashion, and we want to be on the leading edge of technology,''
she says. ``That's what we always think about _ what we can offer
that's new and exciting and different for the customer. This is
just another opportunity to share the Neimans experience with our
customers.''
</P>
<P>
   Tremblay says a number of factors led Neiman Marcus to launch
the Blahnik shoe salon.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted a very high-profile fashion designer because it was
important to us, and that's what we are all about. If we are going
to something wild and unusual and exciting, we wanted it to be with
one of our great partners, and Manolo Blahnik is a great partner.''
</P>
<P>
   She said the store has had great success selling accessories
online and that the notion of enhancing an already successful area
of the Web site seemed like a natural.
</P>
<P>
   RichFX is a new company formed by the merger of the Tel Aviv,
Israel-based WebGlide and Atlanta start-up Blue Rock Inc., which
grew out of the Georgia Tech Advanced Technology Development
Center.
</P>
<P>
   Blue Rock developed a proprietary gift delivery and
personalization technology through its gift mail service, the
Giftmail.com Web site slated to launch this summer. Founded in
January 1999, Blue Rock is working with a number of leading
national retailers to implement the gift mail service on e-commerce
sites.
</P>
<P>
   Kerret says it was the combination of the people and the
technology that made the companies decide to team up. Says Vice
President Katherine Kelley, ``We have a common base of customers
and products.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the elegant presence for Manolo Blahnik on the
Neiman Marcus site, the company has developed other applications
that could work for sporting goods stores and even online grocery
stores. Consumers could browse virtual supermarket aisles, select a
box of cereal and even read the nutritional information on the box.
</P>
<P>
   Tremblay says the choice of designer shoes is an excellent way
to use this new technology. ``This is shoes as art and art on the
Web,'' she says. ``We wanted to do something that was unusual and
different that would appeal to a Web audience and the Neiman's
shopper as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
