r e BC-THEATER-REVIEW-LADN &LR;      05-17 0732
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THEATER-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLOOD, SWEAT AND GUFFAWS
</HEADLINE>
  All that gore _ and there's a band as well 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
Our rating: 3 1/2 stars 
By REED JOHNSON 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Once asked if he liked children, W.C. Fields retorted, ``Yes,
provided they're properly cooked.''
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who has spent time with a cantankerous 2-year-old
probably can relate to Fields' infanticidal musings. If you can't,
you may need a massive jolt of ``Shockheaded Peter,'' the
invigoratingly malicious Grand Guignol musical that's continuing
its run this week at UCLA's Freud Playhouse.
</P>
<P>
   Little tykes have seldom been treated with more comic cruelty or
exultant theatricality than in this sly British export by way of
Manhattan. A darkly tuneful parody of those grim children's
cautionary tales that so charmed the Victorian mindset, the show
might well be subtitled, ``When Bad but Laughable Things Happen to
Disobedient Offspring.''
</P>
<P>
   The genius of ``Shockheaded Peter'' lies in its ability to make
you squirm and even flinch at its parade of brilliantly conceived
serial slayings, while giggling over its macabre excesses. In the
course of 90 ghoulishly inventive minutes, fidgety Phil's
predilection for cutlery ends in grisly demise, thumb-sucking
Conrad loses his digits to the scarifying Scissors Man, and young
Harriet the pyromaniac gets summarily flambeed.
</P>
<P>
   It says much for the splendidly primal showmanship of
``Shockheaded Peter's'' five-member creative team, and co-directors
Phelim McDermott and Julian Crouch, that each of these macabre coup
de theatres is accomplished with such nuts-and-bolts storytelling
hardware as puppets, trick optical perspectives, ghastly makeup and
cleverly customized costumes (courtesy of Kevin Pollard) that can
sprout spiky hair and hideous talons, or metamorphose into
imaginary infernos of red and yellow fabric.
</P>
<P>
   The equally simple but effective props and backdrops (designed
by Crouch and Graeme Gilmour) slither across the pop-out main set
with the enigmatic creepiness of Terry Gilliam's animated ``Monty
Python'' figures. ``Shockheaded Peter'' simultaneously leaves
nothing and everything to the imagination.
</P>
<P>
   Structured as three stories in one, the show (which is based on
Heinrich Hoffman's classic 1844 children's book ``Struwwelpeter,''
or ``Slovenly Peter'') is narrated by a bug-eyed, corpselike master
of ceremonies played by Julian Bleach. Bleach gives an expertly
hammy turn as an incompetent, egotistically deluded Victorian
actor-manager presiding over a third-rate traveling theater company
and fighting throughout the evening to hold disaster at bay.
</P>
<P>
   Slinking, strutting, trilling his R's and shamelessly soliciting
applause, he specializes in ludicrously cryptic pronouncements
about the terrors awaiting bad children. His dissonant homilies are
backed by the Tiger Lillies, a spooky trio of squeezebox (Martyn
Jacques), percussionist (Adrian Huge) and bassist (Adrian Stout).
</P>
<P>
   Sporting a bowler hat and cadaverous makeup, singer-songwriter
Jacques delivers the show's dozen minor-key tunes in a squeeky,
officious falsetto that brings to mind a hyper-adrenal Margaret
Thatcher, most Dickensian of modern British prime ministers. His
mock-sympathetic tone builds to a hysterical, reproving bark of
``Dead! Dead! Dead!'' as he recounts the untimely fate of each
aberrant infant.
</P>
<P>
   This spirit of vengeful puritanism is echoed in the show's third
storyline, a melodrama about a morally upstanding couple who bury
their beastly baby, Shockheaded Peter, beneath the floorboards _
only to learn that it's not so easy to disavow one's own flesh and
blood, however flawed.
</P>
<P>
   As the three stories converge, the show sheds its initial
stiffness and becomes something rare and marvelous: a surprisingly
poignant burlesque with the door-slamming energy of a great sex
farce. Like Alice stepping back through the looking glass, you
emerge from ``Shockheaded Peter'' as if from a strange, slightly
terrifying dream, one not easily or willingly forgotten. &QL; 
_____ &QL; 
What: ``Shockheaded Peter.'' &QL; 
Where: Freud Playhouse, UCLA campus, Westwood. &QL; 
When: 8 p.m. Tuesdays through Fridays, 5 and 10 p.m. Saturdays, 8
p.m. Sundays; through May 28. &QL; 
Tickets: $35; $15 for UCLA students with valid full-time ID. Call
(310) 825-2101. &QL; 
Our rating: 3 1/2 stars &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-17-00 2055EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
