<SLUG> BC-BOMB-PLOT-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON LINKS BIN LADEN TO MILLENNIUM BOMB PLOT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SCOTT SUNDE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   President Clinton said Wednesday that the plot to set off bombs
at millennium celebrations in the United States, which caused
nervous Seattle officials to cancel a public event at the Space
Needle, has been tied to Osama bin Laden.
</P>
<P>
   In a graduation speech at the U.S. Coast Guard Academy, Clinton
made his most elaborate statement to date about bin Laden, a Saudi
exile facing a U.S. charge of conspiracy to kill Americans in
embassy bombings in Africa.
</P>
<P>
   The president cited Seattle's own case of alleged terrorism,
which occurred a couple of weeks before New Year's Eve. But he
stopped short of specifically linking Ahmed Ressam, who was
arrested with explosives in his car in Port Angeles, with bin Laden
or the millenium plot.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the National Security Council said the president
did not intend to tie bin Laden to Ressam. Clinton did, however,
say the suspected explosives Ressam carried and those used by bin
Laden's organization are the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last December, we shut down a plot to place large bombs at
locations where Americans might gather on New Year's Eve,'' Clinton
said in his address in New London, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   ``We learned this plot was linked to terrorist camps in
Afghanistan and the organization created by Osama bin Laden, the
man responsible for the 1998 bombings of our embassies in Tanzania
and Kenya, which cost the lives of Americans and hundreds of
Africans.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton immediately added: ``A short time later, a customs agent
in Seattle discovered bomb materials being smuggled into the U.S. _
the same materials used by bin Laden in other places.''
</P>
<P>
   During his speech, Clinton stressed the threats to national and
global security, ranging from bombing plots and computer viruses to
drug trafficking. He proposed spending an additional $300 million
to bolster counterterrorism efforts, including those in Washington
state.
</P>
<P>
   Among other improvements, Clinton is proposing that the U.S.
border with Canada get better monitoring. That would include secure
communications equipment and high-resolution day-and-night cameras.
</P>
<P>
   Security along the Canadian border has long been a sore point,
especially with members of Congress from northern border states. In
Washington state, a transfer of Border Patrol agents to the
Southwest has created even more concern.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's reference to bin Laden wasn't extemporaneous. He
brought the Jordanian ambassador to the United States with him to
New London and introduced him. The reason was to underscore the
importance of cooperation between nations to battle terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   Customs inspectors in Port Angeles, Wash., arrested Ressam, an
Algerian national, on Dec. 14, after he drove his rental car off a
ferry from Victoria, B.C.
</P>
<P>
   Ressam, 32, faces nine federal charges, including possessing and
transporting explosives and intending to use them to cause damage
or injury. A co-defendant is at large, and the U.S. government has
placed a $5 million bounty on his head.
</P>
<P>
   Other arrests have been made in the case, including in New York
and Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   In Seattle, U.S. Attorney Kate Pflaumer would not discuss
Clinton's remarks. ``We can't comment and don't comment on ongoing
criminal cases,'' said her spokesman, Harold Malkin.
</P>
<P>
   Ressam's attorneys couldn't be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   But an attorney for another of the alleged bombing conspirators,
Mokhtar Haouari, said Clinton's remarks turns up the pressure on
the defendants to cooperate or plead guilty.
</P>
<P>
   ``It might make Ressam nervous,'' said Montreal lawyer Joseph
Elfassy. ``When a president talks, he doesn't talk for nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Federal authorities have accused Haouari of forging travel
documents and ordering another conspirator, Abdel Ghani Meskini, to
travel to Seattle in December to meet Ressam. American prosecutors
are attempting to extradite Haouari from Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Elfassy said he is skeptical of Clinton's motives behind the
remarks. ``I understand that the Americans need to justify the
major, major, major money they have put forward to investigate
these charges,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton didn't mention Ressam by name. Nor did he mean to
connect Ressam with bin Laden and the millennium plot, said David
Stockwell, a spokesman for the National Security Council.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no intent in the speech to link the two together,''
Stockwell said.
</P>
<P>
   Court documents have alleged that Ressam and others were in a
cell of a violent terrorist group based in Algeria. There has also
been speculation of ties to bin Laden.
</P>
<P>
   However, U.S. intelligence agencies haven't solidly linked
Ressam and bin Laden, said one government source involved in the
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The same source also noted that intelligence and law enforcement
experts disagree about whether the alleged explosives Ressam had
are the same as those that bin Laden's organization uses.
</P>
<P>
   Stockwell said Clinton didn't intend to mean that Seattle was a
confirmed millennium bombing target.
</P>
<P>
   A worried Seattle Mayor Paul Schell canceled a public gathering
at the Space Needle on Dec. 31, 1999. Ressam had made motel
reservations close to that spot.
</P>
<P>
   A fireworks display at the Space Needle went off, but with the
public kept well away.
</P>
<P>
   Dick Lilly, Schell's spokesman, said Wednesday that the mayor
did not have contact with the White House before canceling the
event. Schell was also never told that Seattle was a bombing
target, Lilly said.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor's office kept in contact with local FBI investigators
and federal prosecutors here.
</P>
<P>
   ``They couldn't tell us if Seattle, in fact, was the target or
wasn't the target. They didn't know,'' Lilly said. ``The mayor
erred on the side of caution.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
