<SLUG> BC-SIERRA-LEONE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REBEL LEADER CAPTURED IN SIERRA LEONE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: Subs throughout to update; note byline and dateline
change.)  
 By NORIMITSU ONISHI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FREETOWN, Sierra Leone _ Foday Sankoh, the rebel leader who
vanished nine days ago after dealing humiliating blows to the U.N.
peacekeeping force in this West African country, was captured here
on Wednesday in a bizarre incident outside his abandoned house.
</P>
<P>
   Sankoh, who was last seen at his house shortly after his
bodyguards killed 19 demonstrators outside the compound last week,
returned on Wednesday morning in the apparent hope of retrieving
some possessions before turning himself in to the Nigerian Embassy,
witnesses said.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, a local man reported Sankoh's presence to an armed
supporter of the government, who shot the rebel leader in the leg
and arrested him, witnesses said. Stripped naked, Sankoh was taken
to a pro-government militia, which quickly turned him over to the
government.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday night, Sankoh, whose forces took 500 U.N.
peacekeepers hostage early this month, was in custody of Sierra
Leone's government and was being protected by British paratroopers,
U.N. and British officials said.
</P>
<P>
   While Sankoh's capture ended days of intense speculation about
his whereabouts, it immediately raised the issue of what to do with
him. Sankoh's forces are responsible for a wave of terror in 1998
and 1999 when they killed, raped and hacked off the limbs of
thousands of citizens, but in recent days, the government had said
that the rebel leader could take his place in the country's
power-sharing government.
</P>
<P>
   A peace accord signed in July 1999 had said he would be
permitted to be part of the government in exchange for ending his
violent campaign against President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah. The accord
also gave him amnesty for any violent acts committed before the
signing.
</P>
<P>
   Officials did not say on Wednesday what they planned to do with
him. Because the amnesty does not apply to his most recent acts,
many people inside and outside Sierra Leone want Sankoh, who
repeatedly blocked the peace process, to face prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations, which is trying to negotiate the release of
270 peacekeepers still held hostage by Sankoh's group, the
Revolutionary United Front, reacted cautiously to the news.
President Charles Taylor of Liberia, a longtime ally of Sankoh's,
helped obtain the release of 139 peacekeepers early this week.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations announced on Wednesday night that an
additional 80 had been freed through Taylor's mediation. But it was
not clear whether the release occurred before or after the news of
Sankoh's capture, said David Wimhurst, the spokesman for the U.N.
force here.
</P>
<P>
   (START OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   British paratroopers engaged in combat for the first time since
they arrived last week, initially to secure the evacuation of
British citizens. British officials said the paratroopers killed at
least two rebels who launched an overnight attack near the
international airport in Lungi. The British, not part of the U.N.
force, are officially here only to offer technical assistance to
the peacekeepers, but their mission has been interpreted broadly on
the ground.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, in the town of Port Loko, about 65 miles from here,
Nigerian peacekeepers and pro-government soldiers fought for two
hours against rebels, Wimhurst said. One Nigerian and six
pro-government soldiers were killed in a firefight after rebels
attacked with mortars and rocket-propelled grenades, Wimhurst said.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Because of the delicate nature of Sankoh's status, neither
government nor U.N. officials gave details on Sankoh's condition or
where he might have been hiding in the last nine days. In late
1998, after the current government sentenced Sankoh to death for
treason, rebels advanced desperately onto the capital, where they
eventually killed and maimed thousands.
</P>
<P>
   According to witnesses who were interviewed a couple of hours
after Sankoh's capture and corroborated one another's accounts, the
rebel leader showed up before dawn in a shantytown built on a hill
behind Sankoh's house. The house, on a hill in a neighborhood with
other large homes, was looted after Sankoh's disappearance.
</P>
<P>
   Kabbah Sesay, a 36-year-old mason, said he had risen around 5:30
a.m. and gotten out of his house to attend morning prayers, when he
was approached by Sankoh and a bodyguard.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   `` `Do you recognize me?''' Sankoh asked Sesay, the mason said.
</P>
<P>
   Sesay, who recalled the events just after he had finished
washing himself in an outdoor spring that local men use as a
communal shower, said: ``They asked me if I could lead them to his
house and find a taxi for him to take him to the Nigerian Embassy.
So I told him, yes, I could do that for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Sesay said he then accompanied Sankoh and his bodyguard to the
abandoned house and told them to wait under the stairs while he
called a taxi. Instead, Sesay said he walked back to his shantytown
and awakened a neighbor, Mustafa Kamara, who is a former soldier
loyal to Lt. Col. Johnny Paul Koroma, the leader of a junta that
briefly held power in 1997 and is still the real power behind
Sierra Leone's army.
</P>
<P>
   The two men returned to Sankoh's house. ``I went inside the
compound and I told Foday Sankoh I've brought a taxi,'' Sesay said.
</P>
<P>
   When Sankoh and his bodyguard stepped outside, Kamara, known as
Black Scorpion, confronted them. When the bodyguard raised a gun,
Kamara fired a single bullet that went through the bodyguard and
tore into Sankoh's left calf, Sesay said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a hero,'' said Kamara, who was greeted with cheers from
his neighbors when he returned to the shantytown around 9 a.m.
``I'm happy, because I've suffered for 10 years,'' he said,
alluding to the length of Sierra Leone's civil war, which began in
1991.
</P>
<P>
   Puddles of blood lay near the house on Wednesday morning.
Inside, members of another militia, the Kamajors, were searching
the house.
</P>
<P>
   Like most people in the area, two militiamen, Elisha Sheaka, 28,
and Julius Mbayo, 29, said they believed that Sankoh had hidden
diamonds in the house and wanted to retrieve them before turning
himself in at the Nigerian Embassy.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why were are here on the ground,'' Sheaka said.
``Otherwise, I see no reason why Pa Sankoh left the bush and came
here.'' After his capture, the locals pounced on him and stripped
him of all his clothes, witnesses said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We take everything,'' said Foday Sesay, who said he was a
member of Koroma's force. ``We even took his hair dress.''
</P>
<P>
   Sesay then produced a green-and-white hat in the style that
Sankoh usually wore. Others showed a towel and a letter that they
said Sankoh was carrying.
</P>
<P>
   By all accounts, Sankoh was then put into a white Land Rover by
Koroma's men and taken to the former junta leader, who had been
allied with Sankoh from 1997 until last year.
</P>
<P>
   A picture taken by a local photographer shows Sankoh, naked from
the waist up, jammed in the Land Rover with several young men. One
man is grabbing Sankoh, whose face is dirtied, by the skin of his
neck. ``He was brought into this compound, naked, because the
public wanted his neck,' said Prince Nicol, Koroma's spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   After about half an hour at Koroma's, Sankoh was taken to the
Sierra Leonean army's headquarters. From there, the British took
him in a helicopter to what they described as a secure location.
</P>
</TEXT>
