<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 21:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8249 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-MICROSOFT18-COX     05-17 0749
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GOVERNMENT TO JUDGE: TWO MICROSOFTS BETTER THAN ONE
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The government fired an answering salvo Wednesday
night in its legal artillery duel with Microsoft Corp., dismissing
the view that the software giant could comply with the antitrust
laws merely by changing the way it does business.
</P>
<P>
   In asking a federal judge to spurn Microsoft's proposed remedies
and split up the company, the Justice Department and 17 states
reinforced their earlier assertion that a breakup is the only sure
way to bar further illegal behavior by a company already found
guilty of breaking the antitrust laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``What remedy does Microsoft propose to undo the damage to
</P>
<P>
   competition caused by its past illegal conduct?'' the 70-page
government brief asked. ``Nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's own proposals, the government held, ``offered a
cosmetic remedy that would have virtually no competitive
significance.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the company told the court it was willing to stop
displaying the Internet Explorer browser icon on the Windows
desktop and to let computer makers prominently feature any other
software, including products from Microsoft rivals.
</P>
<P>
   But the government insisted that only by splitting the company
into two parts _ one to market the Windows operating system and the
other applications such as Word and Internet Explorer _ could the
judicial system ``undo the harm to competition caused by
Microsoft's illegal conduct.''
</P>
<P>
   In meeting a court-imposed deadline, Justice Department
attorneys worked on their concluding briefs deep into the evening
hours and well past the major market closings.
</P>
<P>
   At end of the day, with all the scheduled remedy briefs in the
historic antitrust case against the world's largest software firm
in the hands of the court, the focus once more returned to U.S.
District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson, who must weigh the two
starkly different plans.
</P>
<P>
   Having decided on April 3 that Microsoft had willfully and
repeatedly violated the nation's antitrust laws, the judge has
still given no hint on when and how he will rule in the final
punishment phase of the trial.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft claims it has done no wrong. So, whatever set of
remedies Jackson decides to favor, the company is sure to appeal
the antitrust case all the way up to the U.S. Supreme Court, a
legal process that could consume several years.
</P>
<P>
   Nor has either side has ruled out the option of an eventual
out-of-court settlement, the course that Jackson clearly has
favored, so far to no avail.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's after-hours government filing also set the stage for
a potentially dramatic hearing on remedies hearing on May 24, when
both sides will argue in open court once more over Microsoft's
future. Jackson is expected to question both sides closely on the
potential impact of their proposals both on Microsoft and its
high-tech rivals.
</P>
<P>
   At some point, Jackson must also decide whether to give
Microsoft's legal team up to six more months to defend itself
against what the company regards as a draconian and unwarranted
government breakup plan.
</P>
<P>
   If Jackson blocks efforts by the company's attorneys to win
extra time to prepare their defense for the remedy phase of the
trial, then they are sure to cite the denial as another ground for
their appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson ruled April 3 that Microsoft had broken the 110-year-old
Sherman Antitrust Act by using its monopoly illegally to harm
customers and thwart competition.
</P>
<P>
   That ruling prompted the government team to call on Jackson to
cleave Microsoft in half. In their initial April 28 submission, the
plaintiffs also said Microsoft should be required to share its
programming secrets and digital interfaces with competitors.
</P>
<P>
   Following the judge's orders to come up with its own proposed
punishment, the company on May 10 proposed a set of internal
controls on its business behavior. But it said even those limited
proposals should be set aside while it appeals Jackson's guilty
verdict.
</P>
<P>
   On Wall Street, Microsoft traded near its 52-week low, closing
on the major financial markets at $67.69, down $1.81 for the day on
volume of 26,498,100 shares.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web: www.usdoj.gov/atr/cases/msremediespapers.htm
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass's e-mail address is andyg(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
