<HEADLINE>
BUSH URGES CONGRESS TO BACK CLINTON ON CHINA TRADE 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo NYT22 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.)  
 (Eds: Also being sent in ` i ' code)  
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   EVERETT, Wash. _ Calling trade relations with China the work of
``13 years and three administrations,'' Gov. George W. Bush on
Wednesday urged congressional Republicans and Democrats alike to
support President Clinton and vote to grant China permanent trade
rights. The House is scheduled to vote next week.
</P>
<P>
   Although Bush has long supported free trade, his address here
Wednesday on the vast factory floor of a Boeing plant marked one of
the few times that he has tried publicly to affect pending
legislation in Congress. He called the question of whether to
extend normal trading privileges to China ``among the most serious
