<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 21:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8264 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-BANKROB-AMIN0518-COX     05-17 0480
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BANKROB-AMIN0518-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pair held in Atlanta bank heists
 &HT;    By Joshua B. Good and Ernie Suggs
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ ``Free Al-Amin!''
</P>
<P>
   The shout came from one of two robbers during the April 25
holdup of a SouthTrust Bank in Smyrna, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, federal authorities said they arrested the two men
after another robbery, this time of a Wachovia Bank in north Fulton
County. The men were caught after they tried to hit officers with a
red Chevy Blazer, authorities said. Police fired at them and chased
them onto I-285, boxing them in.
</P>
<P>
   FBI agents say it was the third time in 22 days the pair had
robbed a bank.
</P>
<P>
   Agents say they have no evidence that any bank robbery money was
going to help Jamil Abdullah Al-Amin, who is accused of killing one
Fulton County deputy and seriously injuring another.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't been able to show a tie between these people and
Al-Amin,'' said Mark Giuliano, the FBI supervisory agent in charge
of the bureau's Atlanta bank robbery squad. ``However, we will
continue to investigate it.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta residents Adrian Grove, aka Ishmael Adbullah, 25; and
Michael Angel Soto Jr., aka Miguel, 33; were charged with
aggravated assault and armed robbery in Wednesday's holdup.
</P>
<P>
   The two men told police they were homeless, but had stayed at
the Community Mosque in Atlanta's West End neighborhood. Al-Amin is
the imam, or prayer leader, of the mosque.
</P>
<P>
   Grove's father, Donnie Grove, said his son called him recently
to talk about Al-Amin, the black militant formerly called H. Rap
Brown.
</P>
<P>
   ``He asked me, 'Dad, did you know of H. Rap Brown?' ``
</P>
<P>
   ``He got framed,'' Donnie Grove remembered his son saying.
</P>
<P>
   Donnie Grove, 55, who lives in Denver, said his son had never
been arrested before. ``He wasn't raised that way for sure.''
</P>
<P>
   Mosque member Ibrahim Abdul Salaam said he does not know the
bank robbery suspects. He said Al-Amin's supporters recently
stopped collecting money for Al-Amin's defense fund. He said they
had not raised enough to pay for the printing of fliers. Taxpayers
are paying for Al-Amin's court-appointed lawyers, Jack Martin and
Bruce Harvey. Martin had no comment about the bank robbery
suspects.
</P>
<P>
   No one was injured in Wednesday's holdup. Police found all the
money. It was stained by an exploding dye package. Fulton County
police Maj. Wenda Phifer would not say how much money had been
taken.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliano said the men are suspects in the Smyrna holdup and the
May 5 robbery of a Bank of America branch in Marietta, Ga. A red
Blazer was connected to both holdups, he said. After the first
robbery, the FBI received reports of paint-stained money being fed
into change machines at metro car washes. A red Blazer showed up on
a videotape from a car wash, Giuliano said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
