u w BC-MENTAL-INSURE-NYT &LR;      05-17 0832
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MENTAL-INSURE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANY EMPLOYERS FOUND TO VIOLATE LAW ON PARITY FOR MENTAL HEALTH
COVERAGE
</HEADLINE>
  By ROBERT PEAR    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Congressional investigators say thousands of
employers are violating a federal law that requires similar levels
of insurance coverage for mental and physical illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   The 1996 law has produced few of the benefits intended for
people who need mental health care and does not appear to have
increased access to such care, the investigators said.
</P>
<P>
   The investigators, from the General Accounting Office, will
present their findings on Thursday at a Senate hearing requested by
lawmakers hoping to expand the law.
</P>
<P>
   Under the law, the Mental Health Parity Act, group health plans
may not set annual or lifetime dollar limits on a person's mental
health care that are lower than the limits for general medical and
surgical services.
</P>
<P>
   The General Accounting Office surveyed employers in 26 states
and found that 14 percent were not complying with the federal
standards. Most of these companies, by their own account, had
lifetime limits on mental health benefits of $100,000 or less, but
set higher ceilings for medical and surgical benefits.
</P>
<P>
   The GAO estimated that 9,000 to 13,000 employers in the 26
states were violating the federal standards, but it did not name
the companies.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers in these states ``have often seen only minor changes
in their health benefits, resulting in little or no increase in
their access to mental health services,'' the report said.
</P>
<P>
   Even employers that complied with the law found ways to restrict
access to mental health care, by setting limits on the number of
office visits or days of hospital care for which they would pay. By
such techniques, the report said, most health plans that comply
with the law _ 87 percent _ ``restrict mental health benefits to a
greater extent than medical and surgical benefits.''
</P>
<P>
   The accounting office said it ``did not find significant
differences in the rate of employer noncompliance based on
characteristics such as employer size, industry or geographic
region.'' In other words, investigators found compliance problems
among employers of all types.
</P>
<P>
   The 1996 law does not apply to health plans sponsored by an
employer with 50 or fewer employees. It applies to employers that
serve as their own insurers, paying claims from company assets, as
well as to companies that buy health insurance on the open market.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. James M. Jeffords, R-Vt., said: ``Some employers seem to be
living up to the letter of the law, but not its spirit. I believe
these practices will have to be examined in more detail as we
proceed with reauthorization of the Mental Health Parity Act.'' The
law expires on Sept. 30, 2001.
</P>
<P>
   The hearing is being held by the Committee on Health, Education,
Labor and Pensions, of which Jeffords is chairman.
</P>
<P>
   The authors of the 1996 law, Sen. Pete Domenici, R-N.M., and
Sen. Paul Wellstone, D-Minn., cited the findings to support their
contention that Congress should broaden the law to prohibit
disparities in coverage for mental and physical ailments.
</P>
<P>
   Such a ban would be ``a major step toward ending the persistent
discrimination against people who suffer from mental illness,''
Wellstone said.
</P>
<P>
   Tipper Gore, the wife of Vice President Al Gore, has advocated
``full parity'' in insurance coverage, and Gore sometimes promotes
the idea in presidential campaign speeches.
</P>
<P>
   At the hearing on Thursday, the Clinton administration will
officially embrace the concept for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   In testimony prepared for the hearing, Dr. Steven E. Hyman,
director of the National Institute of Mental Health, says there is
``no reason based on biomedical or behavioral science why mental
disorders should be treated differently from any other medical
disorder.''
</P>
<P>
   There is, Hyman said, no scientific reason that a health plan
should cover Parkinson's disease but not schizophrenia, for both
are ``chronic and not yet curable diseases that affect dopamine
systems in the brain.''
</P>
<P>
   The General Accounting Office said the 1996 law had had ``a
negligible effect'' on health insurance costs and premiums. A more
comprehensive law requiring full parity could lead to ``cost
increases of about 2 percent to 4 percent,'' it said.
</P>
<P>
   E. Neil Trautwein, director of employment policy at the National
Association of Manufacturers, said, ``To the extent that an
employer is not in compliance, it may be because of confusion over
the application of the law or perhaps a continued struggle to hold
health cost increases in check.''
</P>
<P>
   James A. Klein, president of the Association of Private Pension
and Welfare Plans, a trade group composed mainly of Fortune 500
companies, said he was surprised to hear that some companies were
not complying. ``I don't have any evidence to dispute that,'' Klein
said, ``but our members tend to have very high compliance because
they track these requirements closely.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
