<SLUG> BC-HEDGE-FUND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANOTHER HEDGE FUND MANAGER WILL LEAVE HIS JOB 
</HEADLINE>
   By DANNY HAKIM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Stanley Shopkorn said Wednesday that he would leave his job as
chief stock picker at Moore Capital, a $10 billion investment
management business.
</P>
<P>
   But Shopkorn, 57, added that he was not permanently retiring.
```My son's graduating from college and my daughter from graduate
school,'' he said. ``I'm going to take some time off. I've done
this for 32 years.''
</P>
<P>
   As prominent managers of hedge funds leave the business in a
wave, Shopkorn joins Julian H. Robertson Jr., who said he was
shuttering his Tiger Management hedge fund empire in late March,
and George Soros' top money managers, Stanley F. Druckenmiller and
S. Nicholas Roditi, who said they would retire in April.
</P>
<P>
   Soros and Robertson have suffered steep losses this year because
of stock market volatility, but Moore has held up better. The
firm's flagship funds, Moore Global Investment and Remington, have
declined 4 percent to 5 percent this year, and their combined
assets have shrunk from $9 billion at the beginning of the year to
$8.3 billion last week. About half that shrinkage stemmed from
investors asking for redemptions, with the firm choosing to return
the remainder.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Soros' Quantum Fund has dropped 20 percent this
year, while its assets have shrunk from $10.4 billion at the
beginning of the year to $7.1 billion last week, both from market
performance and shareholder redemptions. When announcing his
management changes, Soros said he would remodel Quantum on a more
conservative frame. The fund now has 80 percent to 90 percent in
cash, according to someone close to the operation.
</P>
<P>
   Shopkorn, too, has apparently steered a more conservative course
of late. He said he has trimmed his technology holdings in
particular and equities overall, though he declined to provide
specifics.
</P>
<P>
   A well-known figure on Wall Street, Shopkorn was once vice
chairman and chief of equities trading at the brokerage firm
Salomon Brothers. In the early '90s, he left Salomon to start a
hedge fund. After some publicized struggles, he closed that fund
and, in 1996, was hired by Louis Moore Bacon, Moore's chief
executive, to run its equity operations.
</P>
<P>
   The firm's top stock holdings, at the end of March, included
Minnesota Mining &AMP; Manufacturing, the Internet security company
Verisign and News Corp, according to regulatory filings. Shopkorn
said he had sharply reduced his funds' technology positions in late
March and April, mitigating the damage from April's correction in
technology stocks.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to shareholders this week, Bacon said that Shopkorn
had signed on for five years and was now ready to leave ``with the
goal of simplifying his life.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-17-00 2138EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000517.0414 </DOCNO>
