<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 21:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8271 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-SWIM-AUSTRALIA-NYT &LR;      05-17 0571
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWIM-AUSTRALIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUSTRALIAN BREAKS WOMEN'S BUTTERFLY   RECORD SET IN '81 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Wis., Ga.)  By JOHN SHAW   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ The oldest record in swimming, in the
women's 200-meter butterfly, was broken here Wednesday night at the
Australian national championships after 19 years.
</P>
<P>
   Susie O'Neill, a 26-year-old who has been pursuing the record
for several years, clocked a time of 2 minutes 5.81 seconds,
breaking the mark of 2:05.96 set by Mary T. Meagher of the United
States in 1981.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the one I am after,'' O'Neill said before the race
here at the Sydney Aquatic Center, which will be the venue for the
Summer Olympic Games swimming. She won the event at the Atlanta
Games in 1996, and on several occasions had come tantalizing close
to Meagher's mark. Wednesday night, cheered by a crowd of 10,000,
she accomplished the goal and surpassed the swimmer she had
idolized since getting Meagher's autograph as a teen-ager.
</P>
<P>
   ``Finally, I did it,'' O'Neill gasped in a poolside TV interview
after hugging her coach, Scott Volkers. ``Over the last few yards I
felt strong. The crowd helped me get to the wall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to go faster, and with record pressure gone, I'll be
more relaxed.''
</P>
<P>
   In the 1990s, swimming records rarely lasted more than a year or
two, so Meagher's mark, set almost two decades ago, had become a
unique target. It had held up against the best efforts of strong
East German and Chinese swimming teams the past two decades, and in
the swimming world it was viewed with the same reverence as Bob
Beamon's long jump record, which stood for 23 years, was in track
and field.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill's achievement, reaching across two generations of
champions, won her a matching share of the world swimming spotlight
currently focused on her compatriot Ian Thorpe, who set world
records three times this week. Wednesday night's mark was set in a
race at the midpoint of a week of national qualifiers for the
Olympic events, which are scheduled here in September.
</P>
<P>
   Last August, O'Neill, holder of 34 Australian free and fly
titles and records, launched a long-planned challenge to Meagher's
elusive mark at the Pan Pacific championships here but failed then
by 64-hundredths of a second.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night, O'Neill, a veteran among her many teen-age
teammates, was almost one second ahead of the world pace at 100
meters and 150 meters. Over the last few strokes, with the crowd
and commentators shouting her on, she slowed slightly but just
managed to reach the finish line in record time.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill's rewriting of part of a long-closed page of the record
book came more than a decade after her first title, in the 50-meter
butterfly in the 1989 nationals when she was a 15-year-old still in
junior high school.
</P>
<P>
   Meagher was 16 years old when she set the previous record on
Aug. 13, 1981, at Brown Deer, Wis. She now uses her married name,
Mary Plant, and lives in Peachtree City, Ga., with her husband and
two children. She praised O'Neill's perseverance.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``She missed it a few times but kept her head down and kept
working and finally did it, so all the credit goes to her,'' she
told The Associated Press. ``I couldn't ask for a better way to
have that door in my life closed.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a sadness, a sentimentality that my name is no longer
in the record books.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-17-00 2138EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000517.0415 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 21:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8272 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-INS-IRAN0518-COX     05-17 0928
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INS-IRAN0518-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Woman jailed in Iran, U.S. for opposition to regime
 &HT;    By Don Melvin
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Mahnaz Samadi spent four years in Tehran's notorious
Evin Prison for her efforts to liberate her native Iran from what
she regards as the repressive rule of the mullahs.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Samadi sits in the Etowah County Jail in Gadsden, Ala.,
accused by the U.S. Immigration and Naturalization Service of the
same offense _ trying to ``liberate Iran.''
</P>
<P>
   The case has incensed metro Iranians, who say Samadi, a human
rights activist, has fallen victim to politics. They claim she has
been imprisoned as part of the U.S. administration's decision to
seek closer relations with the current government of Iran.
</P>
<P>
   If Samadi is deported, said Javad Mirzai, an Iranian who lives
in suburban Atlanta, she would face certain death.
</P>
<P>
   ``They will kill her,'' Mirzai said. ``They won't even give her
a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Willie Anderson, the acting deputy district director of the INS,
said Samadi is in no way a victim of politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's being held solely on the grounds that she's a
terrorist,'' Anderson said. ``And we have evidence to support
that.'' He declined to be more specific.
</P>
<P>
   A hearing is scheduled Friday in Atlanta on Samadi's request for
a change of venue to Arlington, Va., near Washington, where her
friends and lawyers are.
</P>
<P>
   But one of her lawyers, Michael Maggio, said the venue will
affect the ability of her lawyers to see her, and of witnesses,
some of whom are congressional aides, to appear on her behalf.
</P>
<P>
   ``Really the issue on Friday is whether this lady is going to
get a fair hearing,'' Maggio said.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson said the INS wants the case heard here because it has
adequate detention facilities in this area and it has no evidence
that Samadi lives in Virginia. Samadi, 35, said in a telephone
interview from jail that she was tortured in prison in Iran from
1982 to 1986.
</P>
<P>
   Her younger brother, Amir, had already been executed at age 18,
she said. Samadi said she was forced to witness the torture of her
older brother, Manouchehr, who was in his early 20s.
</P>
<P>
   ``They hung him from the ceiling and started flogging him on the
back with a very thick cable. . . .'' she said. ``They put a needle
under his fingernails. And they would pick up the needle to put
more pressure on him. He was shouting, and they forced me to open
my eyes and look at this horrible thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, she said, prison guards bound her hand and foot and beat
the soles of her feet while forcing her brother to watch.
</P>
<P>
   They wanted to force her to abandon her opposition to the
Iranian government, she said. Manouchehr was later executed; Samadi
was eventually released.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, she made her way to the United States. The next year,
she was granted asylum. She lived in the United States for six
years without incident, meeting U.N. officials and lobbying members
of Congress about human rights abuses in Iran.
</P>
<P>
   Her immigration troubles began last November, when she visited
friends and relatives in Ottawa. She was arrested in Canada for not
having a valid visa.
</P>
<P>
   On April 3, on her return from Canada, Samadi was arrested by
INS agents. She was notified that she was subject to deportation
because she had failed to acknowledge in her application for asylum
that she had been a member of an organization called the National
Liberation Army.
</P>
<P>
   She was a commander, wrote Michael J. McLaughlin, the INS acting
district director in Buffalo, N.Y., ``and in that capacity you . .
. prepared units under your command for coordinated attacks to
liberate Iran.''
</P>
<P>
   Maggio, Samadi's lawyer, said the asylum questionnaire asks
applicants to what organizations they belonged in their ``home
country'' _ and Samadi was in the NLA in Iraq, not Iran. She is no
longer a member, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1987, the NLA was declared a ``foreign terrorist
organization'' by the secretary of state.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, Maggio said, Samadi cannot legally be deported
because of the likelihood she would be tortured. Thus, he said, the
INS action could lead to Samadi's indefinite imprisonment.
</P>
<P>
   Samadi was jailed first in Decatur and then in Union City before
being transferred _ chained hand and foot, she said _ to Alabama.
</P>
<P>
   Being in jail is difficult, Samadi said, partly because of what
she endured in jail in Iran.
</P>
<P>
   ``My condition is not good at all,'' she said. She is one of
three women in a cell with two beds, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``My view is that I have become a victim in a political game,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Her lawyer agrees. ``It certainly does look like that she's a
victim of politics,'' Maggio said. ``Because at the moment the
United States is, quite incredibly, cuddling up to the Iranian
regime because so-called moderates are emerging.''
</P>
<P>
   The case has drawn the attention of international human rights
organizations and several congressmen, including U.S. Rep. Bob Barr
(R-Ga.). Barr has written to Attorney General Janet Reno praising
Samadi as ``a prominent human rights activist'' and saying ``her
release would be justified.''
</P>
<P>
   And local Iranians, who number in the thousands, said simple
fairness demands it. They're circulating a petition and contacting
local churches and congressmen on her behalf.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Iranian people see freedom and democracy as their basic
right,'' said Mike Dolati, an Atlanta businessman. They want to
resist the Iranian regime, he said, ``the same way as the U.S.
Revolution.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
