<HEADLINE>
PLAYERS RAVE ABOUT CHANGES TO COLONIAL COURSE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH, CHARLES CLINES AND TROY PHILLIPS 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Tom Kite, a Senior Tour participant playing
in his 28th Colonial, said off-season course tweaks represent
``probably the best redesign of a classic golf course that I've
ever seen.'' Kite praised several new bunker placements and said
the new greens, while rolling true, tend to dry out more quickly
than their predecessors.
</P>
<P>
   That, said Kite, might prevent the event from turning into a
putting showdown envisioned by some members and participants. In
addition, Kite said: ``Some of us with long-term memories of the
course are going to be fooled, because the greens do break a little
different than they did in the past. We're probably going to
misread a few.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart Cink said the Colonial greens ranks as ``some of the
best we've seen this year.'' Stuart Appleby, the player in the
field with the best career scoring average at Colonial (69.0), said
the rebuilt greens ``are good, but I think they're really young and
need to settle down a bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Brooks, who has been critical of how firm the Colonial
fairways had become in past tournaments, liked conditions yesterday
during the pro-am.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's in great shape,'' he said of the course. ``It's
softer _ the fairways _ and the new greens are putting much better.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see how they \RColonial officials\S can't be happy
with what they've done to the course.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Davis Love III and Phil Mickelson agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything I've heard is positive,'' Love said. ``Those who
are thinking about redesigning their courses should come and look
at this one. It just needed a new coat of paint and some new
plumbing \Rand not a major renovation\S,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pretty impressed,'' Mickelson said of the changes. He
especially believes the par-5 No. 11 hole has been improved by
moving the bunkers closer to the fairway and making the driving
area smaller.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bunkers were up the hill before and really weren't in
play,'' he said.  &QL; 
Another tree lost
</P>
<P>
   One of Colonial's old pecan trees near the No. 7 green cracked
during play yesterday and was pulled down.
</P>
<P>
   The tree probably was more noticeable to players than to
spectators because part of the tree hung over the right side of the
green, protecting a right pin placement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm guessing it was a 100- to 125-year-old pecan tree,'' said
course superintendent Scott Johnson, who decided to pull the tree
down after it cracked in the high wind that buffeted the course
during yesterday's pro-am.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a Y-shaped tree, and one side of it had been cut off at
least six years ago,'' he said. ``It was very one-sided.''
</P>
<P>
   After it cracked, Johnson said it was wavering like a flag in
the wind.
</P>
<P>
   He said to prevent it from falling on the green and causing
damage, or falling and injuring someone, he decided to have it
yanked down.
</P>
<P>
   With ropes tied to a front-end loader, the tree was pulled down
and fell into the right-front bunker and slightly on the green.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to put just six plugs of grass \Rin the green\S where
the tree landed,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The tree was then chopped up and removed. With the tree gone,
Johnson said it opens the possibility for a pin placement farther
right on the green that was previously possible.
</P>
<P>
   With the tree falling, it marks the loss of another significant
tree at Colonial. The large pecan tree that once spread partially
over the 18th fairway, fell in 1998 after heavy rains, and the big
tree on 17, nicknamed Big Annie, was felled by lightning in 1986.  &QL; 
Allergies hamper Duval
</P>
<P>
   David Duval, the No. 2 player in the world golf rankings,
scratched himself from yesterday's pro-am because of allergies.
Duval remains in the tournament and is scheduled to tee off at 1
p.m. in today's opening round.
</P>
<P>
   Rocco Mediate also skipped the pro-am but remains in the
tournament. Mediate has a 12:50 p.m. tee time today. Replacements
for Duval and Mediate in yesterday's pro-am were Billy Mayfair and
Chris DiMarco, respectively. Brian Watts replaced Dudley Hart, who
withdrew Tuesday from the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Barring last-minute withdrawals, 111 competitors are scheduled
for today's opening round.
</P>
<P>
   The final field shows Colonial with 38 of the top 50 players on
the season money list, the same as at last week's GTE Byron Nelson
Classic. The difference: Nelson officials landed the top three
players on the list _ Tiger Woods, Hal Sutton and Jesper Parnevik.
The season's biggest money winner competing at Colonial is Phil
Mickelson (No. 4, $1,761,264).  &QL; 
Errant Emmitt
</P>
<P>
   During yesterday's pro-am, players on the practice range were
interrupted when a drive from the second tee box smacked the roof
of a golf cart and ricocheted toward them. Moments later, Cowboys
running back Emmitt Smith sheepishly approached the range and said,
``Sorry, guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Sluman retrieved Smith's ball and tossed it back in play.
Smith chipped but landed nowhere near the flagstick.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sorry, Emmitt. I gave you a bad drop,'' Sluman said.  &QL; 
Ace for Brooks' team
</P>
<P>
   Ron Baldwin, a Columbus, Ohio, resident, and one of the amateurs
in Mark Brooks' group, aced the 16th hole in yesterday's pro-am
with a wedge from 129 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was my second hole-in-one,'' Baldwin said. ``And it was a
good swing.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not the first time Brooks has had an amateur score an ace.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, it's happened at least a couple of times,'' said Brooks,
whose team finished at 9 under par.  &QL; 
Greats had fun
</P>
<P>
   Two of sport's greatest players in their respective games, Hank
Aaron and Bobby Orr, helped Justin Leonard's team to a 14-under 56
in yesterday's pro-am. Both agreed that hitting a stationary white
ball is a lot harder than blasting a baseball over fences or hockey
puck into a net.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the toughest game I've played,'' said Orr, a hockey
Hall of Fame member who said he has lowered his handicap to a 6 in
the past 15 years. ``Hitting a hockey puck, for me, was a lot
easier.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My game's not that good,'' said Aaron, a Baseball Hall of Fame
member, who was sporting a 21 handicap. ``But I just enjoy playing.
I'm never going to be invited to play in the Masters, so it's just
fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Aaron said he never played golf during his career, because ``I
had to worry about the big white ball instead of the little white
ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Orr didn't play much during his career, either, but said he has
been hooked and playing steadily for the past 12 to 14 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to tell how much I play now,'' he said with a
laugh. ``Too much.''  &QL; 
Disappointments spur them on
</P>
<P>
   Phil Mickelson and Davis Love III said they're ready to play
this week after losing in a playoff to Jesper Parnevik at the GTE
Byron Nelson Classic.
</P>
<P>
   Both Love and Mickelson believe they let the victory slip out of
their grasps. Love had a two-shot lead after 10 holes on the final
day, and Mickelson had a shot lead before bogeying the final hole.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it makes me more intent on playing well the next week
because I didn't get the result I wanted,'' said Mickelson after
his pro-am round yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm excited,'' Love said. ``I would rather be playing when I'm
playing good than when I'm not. And I'm confident with the way I'm
hitting the ball. If I can get my short game working for four days
like I had it for 21/2 \Rin Irving\S, then I should play well.''  &QL; 
Texas Exes honor Leonard
</P>
<P>
   Justin Leonard was one of four recipients Tuesday night at the
Fort Worth Club of the Outstanding Young Texas Ex Award, first
given in 1980 by the Texas Ex-Students Association.
</P>
<P>
   Given in conjunction with the UT Distinguished Alumnus Award,
the Young Texas Ex Award each year goes to four distinguished
alumni 45 or younger.
</P>
<P>
   Leonard joined fellow PGA pro Ben Crenshaw (1980), former NFL
running back Earl Campbell (1984), New York Yankees pitcher Roger
Clemens (1988), Dallas mayor Ron Kirk (1996), Dell Computers
founder Michael Dell (1991) and actor Matthew McConaughey (1997)
and CNN reporter Catherine J. Crier (1990) as one of the
75,000-member association's more notable honorees.
</P>
<P>
   Normally, the award is presented at UT's commencement, but the
Texas Exes held a special dinner for Leonard in Fort Worth because
of his commitment to Colonial.
nn
</P>
