<SLUG> BC-CAR-MOTORSPORTS-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Reigning CART champion Juan Montoya topped
the speed chart at the conclusion of a rain-shortened practice at
the Indianapolis Motor Speedway yesterday, Day 5 of hot-lapping
leading to Pole Day on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Montoya, an Indy 500 rookie, toured the 2.5-mile oval in 221.566
mph in the No. 9 G Force/Oldsmobile entered by Target/Chip Ganassi
Racing.
</P>
<P>
   Plano's Greg Ray, the reigning Indy Racing League champion, was
sixth-fastest yesterday at 219.674 mph in the No. 1 Conseco
Dallara/Aurora entered by Team Menard.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Sharp still owns the top speed of the week at 223.936 mph
in his backup No. 8 Delphi Dallara/Olds. Sharp ran that lap
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to put four of those laps together,'' Sharp said,
referring to qualifying. ``The pole run might have a couple of 223s
in it, but it's going to have a couple of 222s, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Teams typically crank out their fastest practice laps late on
Friday afternoon. But more rain is forecast for today and tomorrow,
leading into the annual draw for qualifying position.  &QL; 
Speculating on Petty wreck
</P>
<P>
   Speculation as to the cause of the crash that killed teen-ager
Adam Petty at New Hampshire International Speedway on Friday
centers around a possible hung throttle.
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR Winston Cup star Mark Martin says a driver's first
reaction to a hung throttle is to flip off the ignition switch.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you just can't reach over and shut the switch off at every
racetrack every time,'' Martin said, ``based on how much time you
have between where you've figured out the throttle was hung and
your wall impact.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he gets right down to the turn-in point of a corner of a
place like New Hampshire _ he lets off the gas and it stays going _
all you really do and all you'll ever really do is grab two hands
full of steering wheel and hold on tight before you hit.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin said the most common cause of a hung throttle is the
accelerator linkage catching onto the air-cleaner base that lays
over the top of the carburetor.  &QL; 
NHRA readies `Expo'
</P>
<P>
   Scheduled appearances by reigning NHRA Funny Car champion John
Force and Top Fuel title-holder Tony Schumacher, and a Top Fuel
engine demonstration, will highlight activities of the eighth
annual Dallas Motorsports Expo on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   A prelude to the Castrol Nationals at the Texas Motorplex in
Ennis on May 25-28, the Expo will run from 9 a.m. to 9 p.m. in the
historic West End district downtown. Admission is free.
</P>
<P>
   Top Fuel engine demonstrations, courtesy of Team Kalitta, are
scheduled for noon and 7 p.m. A Jr. Dragster demonstration is set
for the same time slots.
</P>
<P>
   Approximately 50 race cars and motorcycles will be on display.
For driver appearance updates and ticket information, check the
track's Web site (www.texasmotorplex.com).  &QL; 
Andretti ties Big Al
</P>
<P>
   Michael Andretti's victory in CART's rain-delayed Firehawk 500
in Japan on Sunday was his 39th, extending his career Championship
Auto Racing Teams record and allowing him to tie Al Unser for
third-place on the all-time list.
</P>
<P>
   Only Michael's father, Mario, with 52 victories, and Texan A.J.
Foyt with 69, stand ahead of Mikey and the elder Unser in all-time
Champ Car victories. Andretti now has won at least one race for a
record 13 seasons, breaking a tie with three-time series champion
Rick Mears.
nn
</P>
