<HEADLINE>
FORCE'S IMPENDING RECORD TAKES BACK SEAT TO TRAGEDY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Nine-time NHRA Funny Car champion John Force
could reach one of drag racing's milestones in Englishtown, N.J.,
on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   But if Force does match Bob Glidden's 85 career national-event
victories by winning the Matco Tools Spring SuperNationals, expect
a scaled-down celebration. The father of four daughters _ including
two teen-agers and a pre-teen _ Force said he was blindsided by the
death of fourth-generation NASCAR driver Adam Petty in a crash at
Loudon, N.H., last Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a heartbreaker,'' Force said]. ``Puts a downer on
everything and makes you realize the value of just being here every
day.''
</P>
<P>
   Force said he met Petty, 19, somewhere during his whirlwind
travels.
</P>
<P>
   ``You read that this young kid was chasing his dreams,'' a
subdued Force said Tuesday. ``I know that's a great bunch of racers
over there, people that have dedicated their whole lives to the
sport. And to have this happen, it makes you want to go home and
grab your children and hide 'em and not let 'em go out into the
world. I don't think it's fair. My heart cries out to that family
because they had a lot of dreams in that kid. And I'm really sad.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I win, I wish I could trade it for that kid, you know
what I'm saying? To give him time to chase his dream. I've had a
lot of my dreams. It's just a bummer.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Force never has made a huge deal of catching and
passing Glidden. The retired Pro Stock champion and Ford loyalist,
Glidden won a record 10 Winston Drag Racing Series championships,
another number also within Force's grasp this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``You strive in life to get somewhere and when you get there you
jump to the next goal,'' said Force, driver of the Castrol GTX Ford
Mustang. ``The bottom line is I'd like to get it over with and get
focused on the championship. Even though I never raced Bob Glidden,
he was a great athlete in the sport and I'd like to be a part of
history.''
</P>
<P>
   Force, 51, has notched back-to-back victories in Richmond, Va.,
and Commerce, Ga., to pull into second place in National Hot Rod
Association Funny Car points, 30 behind surprise leader Jerry
Tolliver of the WWF Racing stable.
</P>
<P>
   If ``Brute'' Force prevails this weekend, he could pass Glidden
with a victory in the fourth annual Castrol Nationals at the Texas
Motorplex in Ennis on May 25-28.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a real love for Texas,'' Force said. ``You can attack
the Motorplex, because it'll take everything you throw at it. Texas
is kinda my deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Force, who began his Funny Car career in 1978, lost nine
consecutive finals before earning his first career victory, at
Montreal in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a time I thought I never would win. Now going on 85,
it's something,'' Force said. ``I never looked at 85 wins or 10
championships. I'd like the 85 wins to say I did something in
history that's big. I want it. It's just a hard time to jump up and
down and say, `Look at me'... after an individual has lost his
life, and the people around him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
