<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-STURBIN-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEWART'S STYLE A PERFECT FIT FOR THE WINSTON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Promoter extraordinaire H.A. ``Humpy''
Wheeler has tapped Dale Earnhardt Jr. to win the 16th edition of
The Winston, the all-star race of NASCAR's Winston Cup Series, at
Lowe's Motor Speedway on Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   It's a solid selection, despite Little E's status as Winston Cup
rookie. Earnhardt Jr. is the series' only repeat winner through 11
starts, including the recent night race at Richmond, Va., on May 6.
Earnhardt Jr. also posted the fastest speed among 14 teams testing
at the 1.5-mile LMS trioval in Concord, N.C., last week.
</P>
<P>
   Little E's breakthrough Cup victory, of course, was scored last
month at Texas Motor Speedway, a sister 1.5-mile facility to the
former Charlotte Motor Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   Humpy annually studies all this stuff, and then makes up the
rest, which is his prerogative as racetrack president/promoter
extraordinaire. For the record, Humpy is batting eight-for-12 as
chief prognosticator for this made-for-TV drama covering 70 laps in
three segments.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a no-holds-barred, stand-on-the-gas race that fits
perfectly with his mentality and his driving style,'' Wheeler said
of Earnhardt Jr.
</P>
<P>
   But Humpy could just as easily have been sizing up Tony Stewart,
whose motivation for victory in Saturday's nonpoints race goes
beyond the record $500,000 winner's purse. For all its hype, the
Winston is out-of-the-ordinary emotional. Traditionally, tempers
flare, sparks fly and shiny special paint schemes are wadded-up
during the macho final 10-lap segment.
</P>
<P>
   Enter Stewart, who is mad at himself _ and mad at the world _
after a stumbling start to his sophomore Cup season. The series'
runaway Rookie of the Year in 1999 after winning a record three
races and finishing fourth in points, Stewart stands 11th in the
driver's standings, 27 lousy points behind Terry Labonte. You could
make a case that Stewart hasn't had any fun since he and Robby
Gordon got into their celebrated shoving match in the garage area
at the Daytona International Speedway in February.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, Stewart visibly was upset as he exited the pits
after that night race at Richmond International Raceway. Recall
that a pit-road incident involving Little E slashed Stewart's left
rear tire as he returned to the track, knocking him out of the lead
of a race he was in position to win.
</P>
<P>
   Tony was ticked, and did nothing to sugarcoat it.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I got out of the car and I wasn't upset about what
happened, I wouldn't be driving in Winston Cup,'' said Stewart,
driver of the No. 20 Home Depot Pontiac Grand Prix owned by Joe
Gibbs. ``Nobody would want me in their race car. Whether it's
politically correct or not _ it's probably not. But at the same
time, I think people deserve to see true emotion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a firm believer that you don't have to like me. I've never
asked anybody or told anybody that they have to like me, but just
respect what I do and respect the fact that I have an opinion.''
</P>
<P>
   Gibbs knows that Stewart's short fuse has made him a ready
target for criticism from some fans and media members. But Gibbs
has found working with Stewart absolutely exhilarating.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, he'll blow up,'' said Gibbs, who dealt with all manner of
temperaments as head coach of the NFL's Washington Redskins. ``Yes,
he'll get in your face. I walked up to him after a race, and I'm
going to congratulate him on finishing in the top 10. And when he
saw me, he turned around and vented for about five minutes. He
said, `I'm sick and tired ...' and he went off and chewed me out,
half the people in our program out and everybody else.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I didn't get excited about that. I got excited because I
know finishing 10th to him stunk. You don't want to finish 10th. He
wants to win a race.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, who will turn 29 on Saturday, said he and crew chief
Greg Zipadelli realistically began the season expecting to at least
match the stats from their ``dream'' rookie season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had unbelievable fortune last year,'' Gibbs said. ``But I
go to the racetrack each week _ and I honestly mean this _ I go
expecting the 20 car to win every single race.''
</P>
<P>
   Including The Winston, a no-holds-barred, stand-on-the-gas race
that despite Humpy's hype, has Tony Stewart's style written all
over it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
