<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-KITE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KITE OUT TO CONTEND WITH YOUNGER SET
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TROY PHILLIPS 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Where his golf game was concerned, turning
50 wasn't a raw deal for Tom Kite.
</P>
<P>
   Approaching 50 was a different story.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was kind of miserable on the golf course,'' said Kite, who
tees up tomorrow at his 28th consecutive MasterCard Colonial. ``I
had a ratty attitude. I was just an unhappy person.''
</P>
<P>
   It showed one year ago, when in the twilight of his days as a
regular PGA Tour member, Kite referred to making his
tournament-record 27th Colonial cut as ``just another check.'' He
tied for 47th and was uncharacteristically surly afterward.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998 and 1999, Kite had no top-10 finishes on the PGA Tour,
his first years without top-10 finishes since his rookie season of
1972. The subject most often broached during his 21 tour
appearances in 1999 was his 50th birthday, Dec. 9.
</P>
<P>
   Heading to the Senior PGA Tour with a game that appeared shot
wasn't how Kite envisioned going out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a real sense of urgency to get my game back,'' Kite
said. ``I got in shape by working out in the off-season, got a new
teacher \RDave Phillips of Baltimore\S and started enjoying the
game again.''
</P>
<P>
   Kite said being among the Senior Tour's latest class of freshmen
that included Tom Watson and Lanny Wadkins has energized him. He
has survived cuts at both regular PGA Tour events he has played in
this season, The Players Championship (tied for 66th) and the Bob
Hope Chrysler Classic (tied for 61st).
</P>
<P>
   This week, he will again put his perfect earnings record at
Colonial on the line.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw a clip from the Senior Tour about Ray Floyd being the
first to win on both tours in the same year \R1992\S,'' tour member
Davis Love III said. ``I thought, `Well, Tom's going to do that,
too.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Senior Tour, Kite is 11th in total earnings ($468,920).
One week after making the cut at The Players Championship, Kite
notched his first Senior Tour victory at The Countrywide Tradition
in Scottsdale, Ariz.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Players Championship gave me a confidence boost,'' Kite
said. ``I'm hitting significantly better than a year ago. If I can
come out here and make cuts and add something to the tournaments
where I've had success and good followings, I'll come out. But I
don't plan to come out and just take someone's spot.''
</P>
<P>
   Kite's 10-year exempt status on the PGA Tour as the 1992 U.S.
Open winner expires after 2002. This week, Kite said Colonial
serves as strategic preparation for the June 15-18 U.S. Open at
Pebble Beach, because he'll miss next week's Senior Tour event due
to his daughter Stephanie's high school graduation. That leaves two
weeks of preparation on the Senior circuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only difference out here is the courses are a little
longer,'' Love III said. ``It's the same thing. I think Tom and
some of those other Senior guys can still win out here. They shoot
low scores over there, get the putter working and come back here
more confident. I'd come back if I was them.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
