<SLUG> BC-ROCKET-LAUNCH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHUTTLE ATLANTIS, CREW GETTING READY FOR FRIDAY LAUNCH  
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MARK CARREAU 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. _ Ground teams relaxed the pace of their
work on Wednesday as they readied the shuttle Atlantis for its
weather-delayed mission to the international space station.
</P>
<P>
   Atlantis, with a crew of seven astronauts, is scheduled to blast
off from NASA's Kennedy Space Center on Friday at 5:12 a.m. CDT, a
day later than planned.
</P>
<P>
   The shuttle's liftoff was bumped to Friday when the inaugural
launching of a commercial Atlas III rocket from the neighboring
Cape Canaveral Air Force Station was postponed Tuesday because of
high winds.
</P>
<P>
   The shuttle and the Atlas III rely on the same ground-based Air
Force radar tracking equipment. The commercial rocket lost its
priority for use of the equipment on Wednesday when a third launch
attempt was unsuccessful.
</P>
<P>
   A combination of electronic and sensor problems halted the
countdown and could not be resolved before Wednesday's launch
period ended. The Atlas III will not be scheduled again for launch
until after Atlantis lifts off.
</P>
<P>
   Postponements are nothing new to Atlantis commander Jim Halsell,
pilot Scott Horowitz and the remainder of the crew, Jeff Williams,
Jim Voss, Susan Helms, Mary Ellen Weber and Russian cosmonaut Yuri
Usachev.
</P>
<P>
   Their flight was postponed three times last month by winds at
the shuttle's emergency runways in Florida, Spain and Morocco.
</P>
<P>
   This time, near ideal weather conditions are forecast.
</P>
<P>
   Once aloft, the shuttle crew will dock late Saturday with the
uninhabited first components of the international space station.
Williams and Voss will begin a lengthy spacewalk late Sunday to
re-secure a wobbly cargo crane on the station's exterior.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the shuttle crew will enter the station to begin
replacement of failing power storage batteries, repairs to a
communications system and other maintenance chores.
</P>
<P>
   The activities will prepare the orbital outpost for the arrival
of the Russian crew module in July and the first resident crew of
astronauts and cosmonauts late this year.
</P>
<P>
   Russian financial ills and problems with the country's Proton
rocket stalled the start of station assembly. The crew module
itself is more than two years tardy.
</P>
<P>
   Before the shuttle crew members depart the station next week,
they will use the shuttle's steering thrusters to gently raise the
altitude of the orbital outpost by more than 20 miles. The boost
will position the station for its automated rendezvous with the
crew module in July.
</P>
<P>
   The 16-nation partnership involved in the development of the new
station envisions a state-of-the-art, orbiting laboratory for
physics, biology and medical research as well as a testbed for the
development of hardware for human deep space exploration.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
