<HEADER>
A8289 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-AIG-MEETING-NYT &LR;      05-17 0862
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIG-MEETING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHIEF EXECUTIVE OF AIG SAYS HE WILL CONSIDER CHANGING MAKE-UP OF
BOARD 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOSEPH B. TREASTER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Fending off questions from shareholders at the annual
meeting of the American International Group on Wednesday, Maurice
R. Greenberg, its chief executive, said he would consider reversing
the insider dominance of his board. But he would not budge on his
designation of his son, Evan, as his eventual successor.
</P>
<P>
   ``The board has approved Evan Greenberg as the CEO of the
company, period,'' Greenberg, 75, said. ``That's been decided.''
</P>
<P>
   Greenberg announced the succession plan for AIG, one of the
world's largest insurance companies, earlier this year while on a
trip to China with his son, but he has said he has no plans to
retire.
</P>
<P>
   In the more than two-hour-long meeting, Greenberg said that
until last year, when two insiders were added to the board as the
result of an acquisition, independents had been in the majority and
that that balance might well be restored ``at an appropriate
time.''
</P>
<P>
   But when Brandon J. Rees, a researcher for the AFL-CIO, asked
Greenberg why the company did not simply endorse the AFL-CIO's
proxy proposal seeking an independent majority on the board,
Greenberg replied:
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, the board will decide at the appropriate time. We're not
going to act on your proposal. We'll act when the board believes it
should act.''
</P>
<P>
   Referring to the proxy proposal, Greenberg added: ``This is a
democratic vote. If you get a majority vote, something will happen.
If you don't, that's what won't happen.''
</P>
<P>
   There are now 10 AIG employees, including Greenberg and his son
on the board. Two other board members are AIG consultants and six
are independent. In 1998, AIG had 17 board members; nine of those
were not employees, but two of them were consultants.
</P>
<P>
   During the meeting, Greenberg said it was ``an insult'' to
suggest that directors who had consulting contracts with AIG might
vote along with management on issues that they did not personally
endorse.
</P>
<P>
   Other shareholders raised questions about executive
compensation, AIG's policies on employment opportunities and
investments in projects in impoverished communities. But most of
the several hundred shareholders _ many of them employees _ who
crowded into AIG's Wall Street cafeteria for the meeting, clearly
sided with Greenberg, who reported an 18.1 percent increase in
earnings for last year and announced a 3-for-1 stock split as well
as an 11 percent increase in the annual stock dividend.
</P>
<P>
   ``There isn't another insurance company that has outperformed
us,'' Greenberg said.
</P>
<P>
   On the question of executive pay, Greenberg, who received $6
million in salary and bonuses last year plus stock options that
compensation experts say are now worth about $4.5 million, said
that of the 800 best-paid chief executives, he ranked 176th, while
AIG ranked 17th among the companies in profits.
</P>
<P>
   Without directly engaging on investments in poor communities,
Greenberg said that the Starr Foundation, named for AIG's founder,
C.V. Starr, and headed by Greenberg, had made significant
contributions ``in areas you discussed.'' As for employment
practices, Greenberg said: ``We hire people on the basis of the
best qualifications.''
</P>
<P>
   Toward the end of the meeting, Greenberg announced that the
AFL-CIO proposal had received the support of 27 percent of the
shareholders. A proposal by the Presbyterian Church (USA) to
establish an independent nominating committee for the board
received a little more than 26 percent of the vote, up about 2
percentage points from the vote on the same question at last year's
meeting.
</P>
<P>
   American International, which was founded in Shanghai, has
pioneered the reopening of the insurance and financial services
businesses in China. And Greenberg has been campaigning for
congressional approval of permanent normal trading relations with
China. He bristled when a shareholder raised the question of human
rights in China.
</P>
<P>
   ``How many times have you been to China, my friend?'' Greenberg
asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Zero,'' his questioner replied.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been going to China since 1975, several times a year,''
Greenberg said. ``The changes taking place in that country that
affect human rights and rights in general are nothing short of
astounding. It is like going to a new planet. People are living
better today in China than at anytime in their 5,000-year
history.''
</P>
<P>
   One shareholder, who characterized Greenberg as ``a super guy,''
and said he would ``make you a five-star general'' if he had the
authority, called for a salute to both father and son and the
audience rose in a standing ovation.
</P>
<P>
   Elaborating on the choice of Evan Greenberg, 45, as his
successor, Greenberg said that while he had recommended his son,
the board had made the final decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``Evan Greenberg is a 25-year veteran in AIG and I can tell you
that that decision was the right decision,'' the elder Greenberg
said. ``My best interest is what's best for the company. And if I
thought that it was Evan or Timbuktu or somebody from Buck Rogers,
that's the person I would recommend.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
