   (NYT13) VIENNA, Virg. -- May 17, 2000 -- DO-IT-YOURSELF-FUND --
Most mutual funds are not worth owning, says Steven Wallman, a
former federal securities regulator, because they cost too much,
repeatedly fail to beat the market and frequently produce big tax
bills. He contends that he has found a better and cheaper way for
investors to create their own, customized baskets of stocks. For a
fee of $295 a year, his company, Folio, will let investors buy
three of these do-it-yourself mutual funds and fill each one with
as much money as they choose spread among as many as 50 stocks.
(Jana Curcio/The New York Times)
