<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTEL-REPORT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTELLIGENCE AGENCIES ARE NOT UP TO THE JOB, CONGRESSIONAL REPORT
SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Also being filed in `w' category.) 
 By JAMES RISEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Poor organization, inadequate funding and a lack of
aggressive leadership have eroded the ability of the U.S.
intelligence community to face new threats, according to a
congressional report released Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   It also found that the effects made the intelligence community
more prone to serious errors like the bombing of the Chinese
embassy in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   In a scathing survey of the Central Intelligence Agency, the
National Security Agency and the other elements of the intelligence
community, the report by the House Permanent Select Committee on
Intelligence found that ``the United States is placing undue risks
on its armed forces and its national security interests by not
redressing the many crucial problems facing the intelligence
community.''
</P>
<P>
   The report, issued in conjunction with the committee's proposed
intelligence budget for fiscal 2001, argued that broad, systemic
problems are behind a series of costly mistakes, from the CIA's
failure to predict that India would test a nuclear bomb to the
mistaken embassy bombing in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   Resources are increasingly being drawn off to meet day-to-day
tactical requirements, meaning that broader, strategic intelligence
has suffered, the report found.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the CIA had no comment on the House report.
</P>
<P>
   The report charged that ``human intelligence'' _ espionage by
spies operating overseas _ is now stretched too thin by demands
from policy-makers to provide support for military operations and
other emergencies in the Third World.
</P>
<P>
   ``Contingency operations'' have taken money from CIA espionage,
``limiting our efforts to rebuild our eyes and ears around the
globe,'' the report concluded.
</P>
<P>
   Technical intelligence programs, from spy satellites to
eavesdropping and code-breaking operations, also came in for tough
criticism.
</P>
<P>
   The report warned that the government has failed to develop
advanced computer systems to adequately process and analyze photos
produced by the nation's latest spy satellites.
</P>
<P>
   The report said that imagery intelligence still suffers from
``totally inadequate systems planning and investment,'' and that
``unanticipated technical problems'' with some new satellite
programs will ``likely cause scheduling delays and cost
increases.''
</P>
<P>
   The National Security Agency, the super-secret eavesdropping and
code-breaking arm of the U.S. intelligence community, was also
cited for its inability to keep up with the rapid advances in
communications technology.
</P>
<P>
   A highly-publicized crash of the NSA's computer systems in
January was not caused by hackers or foreign spies, the report
said, but resulted from the NSA's ``lack of resources for new
infrastructure needs, the mismanagement of outdated information
technology resources, and the lack of sufficient acquisition
processes and expertise.''
</P>
<P>
   The NSA, the report concluded, ``is seemingly incapable of
responding in an integrated fashion'' to the challenges posed by
the spread of new global networks that tie together radio,
satellite microwave, cellular and cable traffic.
</P>
<P>
   It is becoming increasingly difficult for NSA to penetrate and
then sift through the flood of e-mail, cell phone calls and other
new forms of communications to find the few bits of secret
information from other countries that the U.S. government might
need.
</P>
<P>
   ``NSA's modernization must result in a highly integrated system,
and will require a very sophisticated systems engineering and
program management capability, the like of which NSA has not
experienced in a very long time, if ever,'' the report said.
</P>
<P>
   The House panel also expressed anger at the handling of a series
of security breaches at the State Department.
</P>
<P>
   Among other matters, the report noted that the State Department
delayed notifying the FBI of the recent disappearance of a laptop
computer containing classified material for up to two months,
hindering the bureau's ability to conduct an effective
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The report also said that the congressional oversight committees
were not notified of the potential loss of classified material
until after the laptop's disappearance was reported in the press.
</P>
<P>
   The House panel had concerns about the scope and enforcement of
a new State Department policy restricting unescorted visitors to
the department's headquarters building, the report added. The FBI
has reported that foreign spies have frequently taken advantage of
the State Department's lax policy on visitors, and that some spies
obtained access to the department by posing as reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Lax security at the State Department has infuriated Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright, prompting her to transfer responsibility
for the handling of highly classified material from the State
Department's Bureau of Intelligence and Research to the Diplomatic
Security service.
</P>
<P>
   ``Were intelligence information not so important for the State
Department for the conduct of informed foreign policy, the
Committee would likely be advocating drastic measures cutting off
access to highly classified materials,'' the report said. The
report added that the House intelligence committee is launching its
own in-depth investigation of security at the State Department.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-17-00 2154EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
