u w BC-GUNS-CONGRESS-NYT &LR;      05-17 0588
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUNS-CONGRESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARTISAN ACIDITY FILLS SENATE AMID A SYMBOLIC GUN VOTE
</HEADLINE>
  By LIZETTE ALVAREZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Hoping to prod Republicans on gun control,
Democrats forced a symbolic vote Wednesday on a stalled bill to
combat juvenile crime after tangling up the Senate with arcane
parliamentary devices for two days and unleashing deep acrimony
between the parties.
</P>
<P>
   The resolution, which does not carry the weight of law, passed
by a hair-thin margin of 50-49. It urged Republicans to immediately
pass the crime bill and an accompanying amendment that would
require all sellers at gun shows to conduct background checks on
buyers. Both have been stuck in the congressional pipeline for
eight months.
</P>
<P>
   Unwilling to stay silent on the issue, Republicans offered their
own resolution, which accused the Clinton administration of failing
to enforce existing gun laws and defended the rights of a ``citizen
to own a firearm for any legitimate purpose.'' That passed by a
vote of 69-30.
</P>
<P>
   Although the resolutions were pure symbolism, nothing more than
for-the-record suggestions, the action Wednesday comes at a
politically opportune time for Democrats, who are pushing for
stricter gun control measures.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, hundreds of thousands of people rallied on the Mall
to voice support for gun control and, in a sign that the issue
remains potent on the campaign trail, Gov. George W. Bush tried to
fend off criticism that he is soft on guns by announcing a plan to
provide trigger locks to gun owners in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Sensing vulnerability, Republicans are reluctant to face another
vote, no matter how symbolic, on gun control.
</P>
<P>
   But the real war of words today took place immediately after the
votes, when a fuming Sen. Trent Lott of Mississippi, the majority
leader, attacked Democrats for accusing him of trying to stifle
debate and for what he said was deliberately trying to thwart his
efforts to move important appropriations bills.
</P>
<P>
   Lott said that Democrats clogged up the Senate with countless
unrelated measures, then ``they criticize us for not getting the
work done.'' He added, sputtering with anger, ``That's smart, real
smart.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Thomas Daschle of South Dakota, the Democratic leader, was
able to force the gun issue on to the Senate floor by using a
loophole in new Senate rules. Republicans voted to close that
loophole Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   After Lott spoke, Daschle asserted that Democrats were relegated
to using parliamentary maneuvers to talk about gun control and
other issues because they had no choice.
</P>
<P>
   Then, arms flailing, he accused Lott of carrying out ``a version
of dictatorship on the Senate floor'' and running the Senate, where
debate is deliberately long and loosely structured, as if it were
the House. Lott's real motive, he said, was keeping politically
difficult issues from coming to the floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way the Senate is being run is wrong,'' Daschle said. ``No
majority leader in history has attempted to constrain Senate debate
as aggressively as Senator Lott has attempted to do. He is trying
to protect his members so they don't have to vote on tough
issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Daschle also threatened to make future trouble for Lott by
further slowing down Senate proceedings if the majority leader did
not permit Democrats more leeway.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate passed the crime bill last May, with Vice President
Al Gore casting a tiebreaking vote on the gun show amendment. But
the the House passed a crime bill that left out the gun show
measure.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-17-00 2155EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000517.0435 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 21:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8303 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-GORE-SOCSEC-1STLD-WRI     05-17 0800
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-SOCSEC-1STLD-WRITEHRU-425&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE SAYS BUSH'S SOCIAL SECURITY PLAN COULD HURT CURRENT
RECIPIENTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Subs 5th graf to fix typo in `market'; subs 7th graf to
recast.) 
 By JAMES DAO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORLANDO, Fla. _ Stepping up his criticism of Gov. George W.
Bush's proposal to let taxpayers invest some of their Social
Security taxes, Vice President Al Gore told a convention of older
Americans on Wednesday that the plan could jeopardize the
retirement benefits even of current recipients.
</P>
<P>
   Injecting a sense of urgency into his dire warnings about Bush's
plan, Gore argued that the proposal could have an almost immediate
impact by destabilizing the Social Security system, weakening the
economy and reducing government resources for other programs,
including Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   ``You shouldn't be asked to play stock market roulette with your
retirement savings in the Social Security program,'' Gore told
several thousand people at a convention of AARP, formerly known as
the American Association of Retired People. ``You shouldn't be left
without retirement security if you do. And you should not have to
foot the bill for others who do play and happen to lose, because
some people would lose. The Bush plan raises all of these
possibilities.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore also seized on remarks Bush made Tuesday, when the
Republican governor of Texas suggested that his proposal might be
just a first step toward allowing workers to invest most or all of
their payroll taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``What if people make poor choices?'' asked Gore, the Democratic
Party's presumptive presidential nominee. ``What if the stock
market dips right before an individual retires? Are individuals
stuck with nothing?''
</P>
<P>
   Saying that Bush has not ruled out the possibility of future
benefit cuts, Gore added, ``I don't think your Social Security
should be up for grabs, and under my plan, it won't be.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Bush has not filled in many details of his proposal, its
broad outline calls for allowing workers to invest in the markets a
portion of the 12.5 percent payroll tax that finances Social
Security benefits.
</P>
<P>
   The governor argues that allowing people to take advantage of
Wall Street's strong returns could reduce the cost of retirement
benefits and help extend the solvency of the system. Under current
projections, Social Security will become insolvent by 2037, as more
baby boomers retire.
</P>
<P>
   Gore contends that the best way to strengthen the system is to
use the Social Security surplus to pay down the national debt, and
then devote the interest savings to the system. The plan, he
claims, would not only prolong Social Security's solvency until
2054, but also keep interest rates down and sustain the economic
boom.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Bush argues that the Gore proposal, by failing to address Social
Security's underlying problems, would inevitably lead to tax
increases or benefit cuts to close future shortfalls in the system.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has sought to turn the Social Security debate into a
broader issue of leadership style, asserting that Bush's
``irresponsible'' plan demonstrates that he would be an incompetent
steward of the economy.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has also tried to make the debate as much about character
as about policy, arguing that Gore has shown himself to lack
credibility, consistency and vision on this and other issues.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign hammered at that theme again Wednesday,
releasing material from a White House Web site in which Gore is
said to have supported a proposal last year by the Clinton
administration to invest some Social Security money ``to achieve
higher returns.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Al Gore proposed allowing the federal government to invest in
the stock market to save Social Security and now he's denying it,''
said Ari Fleischer, a spokesman for the Bush campaign. ``Whether
the issue is abortion, gun control, medical marijuana and now
Social Security, Al Gore has a history of changing his position for
political gain. That's why he has a problem with credibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's aides contend that the administration's proposal involved
less risk than Bush's. And Gore himself says he grew wary of the
plan after hearing debate on it.
</P>
<P>
   John Rother, director of legislation and public policy for AARP,
said the organization, which represents 34 million people, has not
taken a position on either candidate's plan. But he said AARP would
almost certainly oppose any proposal that called for allowing
workers to invest all of their payroll taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``What privatization means to me is that the risk is shifted
entirely on to the individual instead of being shared broadly,''
Rother said. ``The whole point of Social Security is that it be
something you can count on, where you are not at risk.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
