<SLUG> BC-CUBA-SPY-TRIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRIAL OPENS FOR IMMIGRATION OFFICIAL CAUGHT IN STING OPERATION 
</HEADLINE>
   By RICK BRAGG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ A trusted veteran U.S. Immigration official betrayed his
country when he passed on a government secret to a wealthy friend
who plans to do business in Cuba after President Fidel Castro's
death, a federal prosecutor said Wednesday in his opening statement
in the official's espionage trial.
</P>
<P>
   Mariano Faget, a Cuban-American who has worked for immigration
since 1970, is charged with violating the Espionage Act by leaking
classified information during an FBI sting operation, and by lying
about meeting with agents of the Cuban Interest Section.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're going to have to decide which side Faget is on,''
Assistant U.S. Attorney Dick Gregorie told the 12 members of the
federal jury here Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   But Edward O'Donnell, a lawyer for Faget, said his client did
nothing to warrant charges under the Espionage Act, and did nothing
to betray his country or jeopardize national security.
</P>
<P>
   Faget, 54, who rose steadily up the ranks to become acting
district deputy director of immigration's office in Miami, has been
held without bond since his arrest in February.
</P>
<P>
   Gregorie said that federal agents suspicious of Faget, who has a
high security clearance and has access to classified information,
showed him a phony document about the impending defection of a
Cuban official.
</P>
<P>
   Just 12 minutes later, he used his private cellular telephone to
call Pedro Font, his boyhood friend and business associate, and
told him about it.
</P>
<P>
   He has said he did not intend for the information to be used by
Cuban spies.
</P>
<P>
   Both Faget and Font are on the board of directors of a company
called America-Cuba, formed to do business in post-Castro Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   But Gregorie said Faget and others established a Panamanian
company as a way to get around the U.S. embargo of Cuba. The
company would buy land for cemeteries in Cuba, and ultimately
transport the bodies of Cuban exiles in the United States back to
Cuba for burial, for a price.
</P>
<P>
   Faget used his government connections and information to help
his business associates, said Gregorie. He said that Faget met in a
Miami bar with Jose Imperatori, a Cuban diplomat, even though under
the guidelines of his own agency, he is not supposed to meet with
agents of a foreign country.
</P>
<P>
   O'Donnell in his opening statement described Faget as a longtime
public servant with an unblemished record.
</P>
<P>
   Faget faces as much as five years in prison if convicted.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
