<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORLD-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIDDLE EAST
</P>
<P>
   PALESTINIANS: CLASHES CONTINUE
</P>
<P>
   Sporadic clashes between young Palestinians and Israeli troops
continued in the West Bank and near Jewish settlements in the Gaza
Strip. Israeli soldiers fired tear gas and rubber bullets at
protesters who threw stones and firebombs; they also reported
shooting at Israeli posts and responded with live fire to the
sources of fire.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL: TYING UP BARAK
</P>
<P>
   Two opposition bills that could tie Prime Minister Ehud Barak's
hand in negotiations with the Palestinians passed preliminary
votes, although both require three more readings to become law.
They would require absolute majority approval of the Parliament to
change the municipal boundaries of Jerualem and to allow the right
of return of Palestinian refugees to Israel.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL: UNCERTAIN WELCOME
</P>
<P>
   A Palestinian legislator said eggs were thrown at President
Costas Stephanopoulos of Greece as he toured the walled Old City,
to protest his position on Jerusalem. Greek and Israeli officials,
however, adamantly denied the claim. ``Not a single egg was thrown
at the Greek president,'' said an indignant Israeli police
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   AUSTRIA: FORCED-LABOR ACCORD
</P>
<P>
   After a two-day conference attended by delegates from the United
States, Austria and six eastern European countries, Austria agreed
in principle to a $390 million compensation fund for Nazi-era
forced laborers. The fund is to be distributed among 150,000
survivors, most in eastern Europe. A meeting on the ``legal
closure'' of the accord will be held in Washington on May 30.
</P>
<P>
   YUGOSLAVIA: CLEARING THE DANUBE
</P>
<P>
   A plan to clear bomb wreckage that has blocked the Danube for
more than a year has finally been agreed upon. The president of the
Danube Commission in Budapest told Reuters that work on a $21
million plan is scheduled to begin in about five months. Three
bridges in Novi Sad, Yugoslavia, were bombed by NATO as part of the
campaign to end the expulsion of Albanians from Kosovo. The
wreckage of one bridge, the Varazdin, has blocked barge traffic
ever since.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA: NUCLEAR PACT APPROVED
</P>
<P>
   The upper house of Parliament voted after a secret debate to
ratify the Comprehensive Nuclear Test Ban treaty, which the lower
house ratified last month. While Russia has not conducted a nuclear
test since 1990, it will officially forswear the tests only after
the United States and a handful of other nuclear powers, including
China, Pakistan and India, also approve it. The U.S. Senate
rejected the treaty last year.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   CANADA: ALBERTA WARNED
</P>
<P>
   Health Minister Alan Rock has threatened to withhold health
funding from Alberta after it approved a law to allow overnight
stays in private clinics, which Canadians fear might undercut the
national health service monopoly. Rock also said he would double
the budget for inspectors to check for violations of the Canada
Health Act, which created the state monopoly for much health care.
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   SRI LANKA: BLAST KILLS 23
</P>
<P>
   At least 23 people were killed by a bomb blast near a Buddhist
temple in the eastern town of Batticola. The government blamed the
Tamil Tigers for the attack, which occurred as the birth of the
Buddha was being celebrated.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN: PREMIER'S APOLOGY
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Yoshiro Mori made a ``heartfelt apology'' for
calling Japan a ``divine country with an emperor at its core.''
Mori's comments, to a Shinto religious group, drew widespread
criticism for violating the spirit of the postwar constitution
guaranteeing a secular state. Shinto was the official religion of
wartime Japan, and the emperor was regarded as a deity.
</P>
</TEXT>
