<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAO-STUDY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE USES STUDY TO PAN BUSH'S PLAN FOR SOCIAL SECURITY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Al Gore's presidential campaign has seized on a
study of private retirement programs run by three Texas counties to
illustrate risks Gore says are inherent in Gov. George W. Bush's
proposal to add private investment options to Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   Bush would allow workers to put a portion of their Social
Security payroll taxes into individual investment accounts that
could include stock market participation.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's campaign says the study of the Texas counties shows that
such a system might leave some seniors with lower retirement income
than they would get under the present Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the Government Accounting Office analyzed the
benefits of county workers in Galveston, Brazoria and Matagorda
counties who have opted out of Social Security and invested all of
their retirement funds in selected stocks and bonds.
</P>
<P>
   The study concluded that low- and moderate-income employees who
worked for 35 years and retired in 1998 would have qualified for
higher benefits had they remained in the Social Security system.
However, higher-income workers fared better under the private
market system, according to the analysis of the privatization
program begun in the early 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   The lower-income workers would have done better by remaining in
the federal system, the study found, because Social Security is
``tilted to provide relatively higher benefits to low-wage workers
and the benefits are fully indexed to protect against inflation.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the study noted that under Social Security the
workers' spouses would have been eligible for additional benefits
that were not included in the private investment system.
</P>
<P>
   Aides to Gore, who has opposed privatization efforts, are
pointing to the study to bolster their claims that private
retirement accounts would produce vast inequities.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is empirical evidence in the governor's home state that
taking away a guaranteed benefit that Social Security represents
and replacing with investments in the market is inherently risky,''
said Gore spokesman Chris Lehane.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and Gore have spent much of this week promoting dueling
plans for keeping Social Security solvent after 2037, when the
retirement system will not have enough income to pay out benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has proposed keeping the Social Security system fiscally
sound by adding funds from the projected federal budget surplus and
savings from paying down the debt.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking Wednesday to members of the influential senior citizens
group AARP in Orlando, Fla., Gore said, ``You shouldn't have to
play stock market roulette with your retirement savings.''
</P>
<P>
   Plans already proposed in Congress, which Bush aides have said
might serve as models for his proposal, allow but do not require
stock market investments.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, campaigning in Washington state, issued a statement
accusing Gore of employing ``the same old tired rhetoric on Social
Security _ this vice president is willing to try and scare the
elderly and frighten people.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokesman Ari Fleischer defended the private Social
Security accounts. ``The broader point is people want to have more
control over their retirement nest eggs,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Fleischer said that it was not fair to compare the Texas
experience with what the governor is proposing, in part because the
counties require conservative ``fixed rate investments'' of
retirement funds.
</P>
<P>
   He also noted that county workers must pay taxes on the income
on their investments when they retire, which is not the case with
Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   Even the GAO report warns that ``it is important to note that
the Alternate Plans' performance is not necessarily indicative of
how well a proposed system of individual accounts within Social
Security might perform.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush has only provided a vague outline of his privatization plan
and it is far from clear that it would resemble the Galveston,
Brazoria, Matagorda retirement programs.
</P>
<P>
   The programs were launched two decades ago by officials of the
three Texas counties who withdrew from Social Security because they
believed that the federal system faced probable tax increases.
County workers voted heavily in favor of withdrawing from the
federal system, and now about 3,000 employees participate in the
new programs.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, state and local governments were allowed to opt out
of Social Security, an exemption that was eliminated in 1983.
</P>
<P>
   Under the ``Alternative Plan,'' the counties still collect the
payroll tax but now turn the money over to professional managers
who are only allowed to invest in conservative funds such as
government bonds, corporate bonds and preferred stock.
</P>
<P>
   Upon retirement, employees can receive their money in one lump
sum or can purchase annuities that allow them to stretch out
payments for the rest of their lives.
</P>
<P>
   The GAO study found that low-wage workers who retired in 1998
received monthly benefits of about $617. Under Social Security
those workers would qualify for $750. High-income workers, however,
who received $1,848 a month under the privatization plan, would
have qualified for $1,283 under Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   The analysis also said that county workers who will retire in
the future may do better under the privatization plan because the
stock market has performed better in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
