<HEADER>
A8308 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-NOMINATIONS-POLL-365&AMP;     05-17 0993
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOMINATIONS-POLL-365&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLL FINDS AMERICANS FEEL THEY HAVE LITTLE SAY IN PRESIDENTIAL
NOMINATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   By ADAM CLYMER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Americans have little sense of power over the presidential
nominating process, with only a fifth of them saying that voters in
the primaries chose Gov. George W. Bush of Texas and Vice President
Al Gore as the presidential nominees, the latest New York Times/CBS
News Poll shows.
</P>
<P>
   A vast majority of the 947 adults interviewed last week said
they would prefer a single national primary to the present system,
where they feel early states have too much influence. Seventy-five
percent favored a national primary, while 20 percent said the
present system was preferable.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly three-fifths of the public called the campaign dull,
rather than interesting. Republicans, perhaps because three-fourths
of them expect to win the White House in November, were less
critical. They divided evenly on the question.
</P>
<P>
   But overall interest in the campaign has dropped sharply in the
two months since the nominations were decided. Only 15 percent said
they had discussed the campaign in the past day. In mid-March, 49
percent told pollsters for Harvard's Joan Shorenstein Center on the
Press, Politics and Public Policy that they had talked about the
campaign that day.
</P>
<P>
   While respondents agreed that voters had little influence over
either party's choice, they had different explanations of who made
the Republican and Democratic decisions. For Bush, the public
thought campaign money was most important, while for Gore, they
said it was the backing of party leaders. Both judgments reflected
the attention those strengths drew during the nomination contests.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-one percent said the voters had the most influence in
picking Bush, while 26 percent said party leaders were decisive,
and 44 percent credited his success to ``people who contributed
money.''
</P>
<P>
   Twenty percent said the voters were decisive for Gore, while 48
percent said party leaders had the most say and 24 percent said
contributors called the tune. The telephone poll had a margin of
sampling error of plus or minus 3 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   The public support for a national primary in the poll, which was
conducted May 10-13, was not unusual. The Gallup Poll has found
comparable majorities for the idea since the 1950s.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Respondents who were asked to amplify their reasons for
supporting a national primary generally argued that it would make
the process shorter, neater and, surprisingly, cleaner.
</P>
<P>
   Annette Scott, a nurse's assistant from Miami who is a Democrat,
said, ``A single primary day would eliminate the money spent
digging up dirt on each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Glenda Tager, a homemaker in Lexington, S.C., who is a
Republican, said, ``With one day, they would spend less money, and
people wouldn't have to listen to so much negative campaigning.''
</P>
<P>
   But the depth of the support for the concept was not tested
because the poll did not pose the arguments against such a plan
that would be raised if the political parties or Congress seriously
considered a national primary.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Mann, a senior fellow at the Brookings Institution, said
Wednesday that politicians and academics are generally hostile to a
one-day national primary because they feel it would require
tremendous resources available only to someone already perceived as
a front-runner. And he said, ``It removes any real opportunity for
a sequential testing for the candidates and a learning process for
the voters.''
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders are considering a third option, with small
states voting first and the biggest states holding their primaries
last. They argue that this is the only way to forestall the
national primary they see developing as states seek political
influence by seizing the earliest possible dates. But this plan,
which was also presented without arguments pro or con, did not
impress the respondents. Thirty-six percent said it would be better
than the present system, but 49 percent said it would be worse.
</P>
<P>
   About half of the public said it was satisfied with the
candidates who emerged, while half said they wanted more choices.
People who said they would vote for Bush were slightly more
content; 58 percent of them said they were satisfied with the
choices now, compared to 52 percent of Gore's backers.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the questions tapped, quite deeply, into traditional
reservoirs of hostility or at least skepticism about the system.
For example, 33 percent agreed with the statement: ``It makes no
real difference who is elected president _ things go on as they did
before.'' Findings at about that level were typical in 1996. But 20
years earlier, in 1976, only 19 percent agreed.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, 64 percent of the public said people like themselves
had ``not much'' to say about what government does. Since the
Times/CBS News Poll first asked the question in 1990, only once was
a higher number recorded. And this February, at the peak of the
primary season, just 48 percent expressed that sort of
powerlessness.
</P>
<P>
   The dismay came through in some of the follow-up interviews.
Jane Marawar, a homemaker in Austin, Texas, said, ``I think it's
important to vote, but money seems to be running the election
process.'' Marawar, a Democrat, said she did not vote in the Texas
primary on March 14, a week after Gore was credited with wrapping
up the nomination. By then, she said, ``The die was cast.'' She
said, ``people think `the nomination is already decided, why should
I bother, why should I get involved.'''
</P>
<P>
   Scott, the Miami Democrat, said ``I didn't feel I had much of a
say. It just seems whomever the party sent out, we were expected to
accept. It wasn't as if there were a variety of people to choose
from. It just seems like the candidate was prepackaged, endorsed by
the party and that's the way it is, take it or leave it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-17-00 2202EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
