<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FORD-PRODUCTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEAK DEMAND PROMPTS FORD TO PRODUCE FEWER EXCURSIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ The Ford Motor Co. said Wednesday that it would
produce fewer Ford Excursion sport utility vehicles during the 2001
model year, but attributed the cutback to weak consumer demand for
the vehicle rather than the company's concerns about its safety and
environmental problems.
</P>
<P>
   George Pipas, a Ford spokesman, said that the automaker would
cut its production rate for the Excursion to 52,000 a year this
summer, from 69,000 a year now. By building 17,000 fewer
Excursions, Ford will be able to build 35,000 more Ford Super Duty
pickup trucks, which are produced on the same assembly line in
Louisville, Ky., he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ford had only a 45-day supply of Super Duty pickups at the end
of April, compared with a 100-day backlog of Excursions. Automakers
like to have a 60-day supply of vehicles on dealership lots and in
transit to dealerships at any given time, so that each dealer can
offer a selection of vehicles in different colors and with
different equipment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not a company that our No. 1 goal is to shove sport
utilities down the throats of consumers'' by offering deep
discounts, Pipas said. Because the $40,000 Excursion and $30,000
Super Duty share the same engines and transmissions and have
similar fuel economy, the shift in production will have little if
any effect on the environment, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Taller than Michael Jordan and weighing as much as three Honda
Civics, the Excursion gets only 10 miles to the gallon in the city
and 13 on the highway, making it the target of heavy criticism from
environmentalists. In a ``corporate citizenship report'' released
last Thursday in Atlanta at Ford's annual shareholders' meeting,
the automaker acknowledged the criticism and quoted the Sierra
Club's condemnation of the vehicle as ``a rolling monument to
environmental destruction.''
</P>
<P>
   William C. Ford Jr., Ford Motor's chairman, said in an interview
at the meeting that the company planned to continue making the
vehicle because a halt in production would prompt the introduction
of similar vehicles by rival automakers with less commitment to
safety and the environment. Ford voluntarily builds the Excursion
to emit less pollution than regulations allow for sport utilities.
The Excursion is also equipped with impact-absorbing steel bars
below the bumpers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-17-00 2203EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000517.0441 </DOCNO>
