<HEADLINE>
TEXAS PANEL DELAYS VOTE ON VEHICLE EMISSIONS STANDARD 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BILL DAWSON 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ State environmental commissioners put off a
scheduled vote Wednesday on whether new vehicles sold in the state
must meet California's emissions standard.
</P>
<P>
   The surprise two-week delay was prompted by a last-minute sales
pitch from automakers and U.S. officials, who argued in favor of an
alternate federal standard.
</P>
<P>
   It was the second time in two months the Texas Natural Resource
Conservation Commission has postponed deciding on the issue, which
it has studied for months.
</P>
<P>
   If the three commissioners do not adopt the California rules,
new cars and trucks sold in Texas after 2003 would have to meet the
federal standard.
</P>
<P>
   State officials are relying on major cuts in automotive
pollution _ regardless of which standard accomplishes them _ to
meet a federal smog-reduction deadline in 2007 for the Houston and
Dallas regions.
</P>
<P>
   Both the California and federal standards would require new
vehicles to emit much less pollution than current models. Officials
estimate roughly equivalent price increases in each case _ about
$200 on average.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists argue that the California approach would yield
more sweeping cuts in automotive emissions.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush hinted last year that he preferred the
California option, as he urged the commissioners to study it
closely. Another Republican governor, New York's George Pataki,
recently chose the California standard for his state.
</P>
<P>
   But in letters sent Tuesday, major car companies and the U.S.
Environmental Protection Agency sought to allay concerns raised by
two commissioners _ Chairman Robert Huston and Ralph Marquez _
about whether the federal standard is tough enough.
</P>
<P>
   In moving to postpone the vote, Huston said the letters from
Ford, General Motors and DaimlerChrysler were ``a very important
development'' that could produce a decision to stick with the
federal standard.
</P>
<P>
   He had wanted a pledge that models sold in Texas, even though
built to the U.S. standard, will meet a stricter California limit
for smog-forming chemical gases.
</P>
<P>
   In virtually identical language, the three companies' letters
offered that promise. Huston said if legal details can be worked
out in the next two weeks, he will favor the federal approach
because it would then offer virtually as much pollution reduction.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists continued to argue, however, that only the
California standard will require large numbers of extremely clean
``alternative vehicles'' _ electric-gasoline hybrid models and
fuel-cell designs _ to be readily available in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Some hybrids are already being advertised nationally, but cannot
be found in Texas showrooms.
</P>
<P>
   In letters to the commissioners Tuesday, the EPA and the
Alliance of Automobile Manufacturers said the federal standard also
will result in ready availability of such vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Marquez said these messages still did not offer as much
assurance as he wants that alternative models will be marketed
widely in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The commissioners originally planned to choose a vehicle
standard for the entire state last month when they adopted a
smog-reduction plan for the Dallas-Fort Worth region.
</P>
<P>
   Marquez said that even if they decide in two weeks against the
California standard, they may change that stance later this year
when they adopt a plan for the Houston area, which has a far worse
smog problem than Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   It ``will take everything we can muster'' to achieve enough
pollution cuts in Houston in order to meet the federal cleanup
deadline in 2007, he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
