<SLUG> BC-TEN-USCTEN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE ROYAL RIDE FOR USC'S SAFAROVA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ USC senior Veronika Safarova might not ever be
labeled queen of the tennis court, but she is literally a princess
off it.
</P>
<P>
   While her teammates played in the Pacific-10 singles
championships two weeks ago in Ojai, Safarova was receiving a far
different honor. She was selected to represent her native Czech
Republic as its ``princess'' at the International Azalea Festival
in Norfolk, Va., which honors the 19 member nations of NATO and is
annually attended by more than 250,000.
</P>
<P>
   Safarova was chosen by her country's ambassador to the United
States, and the festivities were a far cry from her usual routine
of spending hours on the tennis court.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was interesting to do something completely different than
tennis. I had never done anything like it,'' Safarova said.
</P>
<P>
   Among the first-time experiences was riding a parade float
through Norfolk and walking down a runway in a formal dress.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first I said, `No way. I'm not a model.' The worst thing
was I had to wear a bridesmaid dress,'' Safarova said.
</P>
<P>
   She also had to walk in public in high heels.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought, `Oh no.' These are the shoes I usually wear,''
Safarova said, pointing to her comfortable tennis sneakers.
</P>
<P>
   These were all minor complaints, however, for the 22-year-old,
who came to USC four years ago after growing up in Brno, a large
city about 2 hours from Prague.
</P>
<P>
   ``All things being equal, I'd like to have her at Ojai, but it's
a long year and a little rest is not a bad idea. This is an amazing
memory she's going to keep,'' USC coach Richard Gallien said. ``I
would have been more hesitant if I thought she would be on the
bubble for NCAAs, but she already qualified. Down the road, she'll
tell her daughter she was a princess.''
</P>
<P>
   There has been a whirlwind of memories lately for Safarova.
Besides the Azalea Festival, she participated in graduation
ceremonies at USC last Friday, then helped the Trojans win
opening-round NCAA matches Saturday and Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Today, she leads the 12th-ranked Trojans in an NCAA round of 16
match against Louisiana State at Pepperdine. Following the team
competition, she will take part in the singles competition as one
of only two Trojans to make the cut.
</P>
<P>
   ``A senior in women's collegiate tennis has so much more miles
on her than a volleyball or basketball player. She's been playing
in tournaments since she was 9,'' Gallien said. ``So it takes a lot
of character in your last semester of your senior year, knowing you
won't go on, to give it your all.''
</P>
<P>
   It might be excusable for Safarova to suffer from burnout, since
she honed her tennis skills when the communist government was in
control of what was then Czechoslovakia.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first 12 years of her life, being in a communist
environment, tennis almost wasn't able to be fun,'' Gallien said.
</P>
<P>
   But Safarova has flourished her senior season, moving from USC's
No. 4 singles player to No. 2. She credits a new outlook toward
tennis as the reason for her success.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason I've played so well is because I decided to
appreciate it and I've been relaxed,'' Safarova said. ``I knew it
was the last season of my career. I see things differently on the
court now. I'm not stressed out.''
</P>
<P>
   This year she is 26-8 in match play and has even surprised her
teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, toward the end, she didn't play as well as she
wanted,'' said fellow senior Jacqui Boyd. ``It's made a big
difference for us because she's won a lot of good matches.''
</P>
<P>
   What inspires Gallien is Safarova's demeanor. He can rarely tell
if she's winning or losing a match just by looking at her, because
her emotions are always the same on the court.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her background was so much more serious in a way than some of
the American kids. She's above the pettiness you typically see,''
Gallien said. ``The world is not full of people like Veronika. It's
full of people who are lazy and make excuses and underachieve.''
</P>
<P>
   That description would probably embarrass Safarova, who winces
when she gives presentations in her business classes because she
thinks her English could improve, although she speaks the language
fluently.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been with her in classes and she's very nervous,'' Boyd
said. ``That's understandable. I couldn't give a presentation in
another language.''
</P>
<P>
   But Safarova is also enjoying life in Los Angeles. When she left
the Czech Republic four years ago, she was certain she would return
immediately after graduating. Now, she would like to stay a few
years and see what happens as she tries to get a job in sports
management.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never thought that by the time I would graduate I would
adapt to the American culture the way I did,'' she wrote in a
recent essay. ``I am no longer the shy naive girl that barely
speaks English and doesn't know what she wants to do with her
life.''
</P>
<P>
   And for a few days, she even got to be a princess.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm never going to get a chance to be a princess of the Czech
Republic again,'' Safarova said. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
VERONIKA SAFAROVA FILE &QL; 
Class: Senior &QL; 
Age: 22 &QL; 
Hometown: Brno, Czech Republic &QL; 
Notable: Two-time member of the Pac-10 Conference All-Academic
team &QL; 
Personal: Won the Czech Republic junior national championship in
1993. . . . Sister Lucie is the top 13-year-old tennis player in
Czech Republic.!dlim!!end!
</P>
</TEXT>
