<SLUG> BC-HKN-DEVILS-FLYERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON HOCKEY: ROUGH STUFF EQUALS GOOD STUFF
</HEADLINE>
  By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Late in Game 1 of the Eastern Conference finals on Sunday, a fan
wearing a Philadelphia Flyers jersey began pummeling a fan wearing
a New Jersey Devils jersey in the seats of the First Union Center
in Philadelphia. Although the Devils were on their way to a 4-1
victory, the Philadelphia spectators cheered. It was the wildest of
several fights among fans.
</P>
<P>
   The people who run the arena issued stern warnings for the next
two days that such things are forbidden and would result in swift
punishment. They said so in news releases, on the scoreboard and on
cards passed out to ticket holders entering the arena for Game 2 on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   But the nonverbal message had already been delivered. In Game 2,
a 4-3 Flyers victory, the rough stuff increased, but it stayed on
the icy side of the glass, among the athletes. There were lots of
cheap shots, a couple of bloody cuts, a few exchanges of nasty
words, one double-spearing incident, a fist fight between two big
forwards and a concussion from a thundering body check.
</P>
<P>
   Remarkably, two referees called a total of only 26 penalty
minutes. Although the Devils dished out as much as they absorbed,
the style favored the Flyers, who evened the best-of-7 series at
one victory apiece.
</P>
<P>
   With Game 3 in the Meadowlands Thursday night, it is hoped by
most that there will be no retaliation from spectators representing
the northern end of the road in this Battle of the Turnpike. As for
players, the Flyers hope things continue just as they are.
</P>
<P>
   ``If that's what it's going to take for us to win, we're going
to have to bear down and stick together,'' said Dan McGillis, a
Flyers' defenseman. ``I definitely think the refs were letting us
play it out there. It's good to see. It's good to watch. It's good,
clean hockey. That's what the game's all about. It's nice to play
it like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Late in the game on Tuesday, McGillis hit Sergei Brylin not once
but twice from behind in succession and rapped his head into the
boards. This knocked off Brylin's helmet and opened a cut above
Brylin's right eye. He showed it to the officials, who shrugged it
off. Afterward, McGillis suggested that Brylin might have cut
himself on his own helmet visor. When this was relayed to Brylin,
he wrinkled his nose as if a sudden, sour odor had entered the
room.
</P>
<P>
   This is not to suggest that the Devils are all passive victims.
Randy McKay, the veteran right wing, got the best of Keith Primeau
when the Flyers' recent concussion victim challenged McKay to
fight. This was before Scott Stevens, the Devils' captain, put
Philadelphia's Daymond Langkow out of the game with a hard shoulder
check that left Langkow with a cut and a concussion.
</P>
<P>
   Primeau got even later by putting New Jersey's John Madden out
of the game with a knee-to-knee hit that left Madden writhing in
pain and limping out of the building. And Stevens responded to that
by upending Primeau with a low check in the knee area and glowering
down at him.
</P>
<P>
   While some of this is inevitable in the playoffs, Stevens
expressed concern about his teammates being drawn into too many
post-whistle scrums, with pushing and pulling and gloves rubbing
across faces.
</P>
<P>
   ``Philly's a dump-and-grind team, let's not kid ourselves,''
Stevens said. ``At times, we lost our focus, getting into scuffles
and stuff like that, which is uncharacteristic of our team.'' This
hurts the deeper Devils, Stevens said, who ``use more people'' than
the Flyers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is to their advantage if there's a scrum and a delay of
game,'' Stevens said, referring to the Flyers. ``We want to keep
the game rolling. It's more beneficial to us.''
</P>
<P>
   Stevens' counterpart, the Philadelphia captain Eric Desjardins,
is also a veteran defenseman. He agreed. ``We're that kind of
team,'' Desjardins said. ``We like to play physical. It's our
style.''
</P>
<P>
   Larry Robinson, the coach of the Devils, said: ``You get tired
of getting elbowed in the head and punched in the face. We just
have to get away from it and let the officials do their job.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the Flyers best scrummers is Rick Tocchet, who scored
twice and speared Claude Lemieux. ``We've got to stay in their
face,'' Tocchet said.
</P>
<P>
   Referring specifically to Lemieux, Tocchet said: ``Lemieux's
going to be yapping. I just yap back at him.''
</P>
<P>
   Of Game 3, Tocchet predicted: ``They're not going to come out
and try to hammer us. They're going to play disciplined.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Devils do not, that would please Keith Jones, another
agitator among the Philly forwards. ``Good, clean hockey,'' Jones
said of Game 2, echoing McGillis. ``It was a big win for us. Where
it takes us, we'll find out. When you win those games, it can
really carry over. It was a fantastic win for us, the type of
victory that can carry you through a series.''
</P>
<P>
   Like many Flyers, he praised Primeau for picking a fight despite
a recent concussion, calling him a ``warrior.'' Primeau, who
assisted on one of Tocchet's goals, said, ``We kind of settled more
into our style. I didn't want to come off the ice. I wanted to stay
out there. These games are so much fun. That's old-time playoff
hockey. It doesn't get any better than that.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
