<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 22:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8322 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-NY-GIULIANI-DONORS-(T     05-17 1110
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-GIULIANI-DONORS-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR GIULIANI, OUT-OF-STATE DONATIONS ARE BALANCING ACT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mo., Mich.)   By ERIC LIPTON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Weighing in the balance of Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's
decision on whether to stay in the Senate race are the millions of
dollars he has raised in his effort to defeat Hillary Rodham
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly half of the $19 million has been donated by out-of-state
voters, many of whom answered solicitations because they despise
his opponent. Yet under federal law, Giuliani may squirrel away
every cent of the more than $9 million he has not spent _ even if
he drops out.
</P>
<P>
   That prospect irritates Michael Ross, a St. Louis banker, who
contributed as much as federal law allows to Giuliani's Senate
race. Sure, he admires Giuliani and wishes him well. But the $2,000
in checks he wrote to the Friends of Giuliani account were for one
purpose, he said: keeping Clinton out of the U.S. Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could put Mickey Mouse in there and I would give him
money,'' Ross said. ``If he drops out, the money should go to his
successor. Any other course would look bad and it would ultimately
help Hillary out.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's most likely substitute, Rep. Rick Lazio of Long
Island, could certainly use the assistance, said state Republican
leaders. Lazio has little name recognition outside the New York
City region and no statewide campaign infrastructure in place. He
has about $3.5 million in the bank, for his re-election bid. But if
he stepped into the most expensive and high profile Senate race in
the nation, he would need to raise $10 million to $15 million more,
political consultants said.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor, who announced in the last three weeks that he has
prostate cancer, is separating from his wife and is having a
relationship with another woman, again Wednesday offered no
concrete hints on what was in his political future or what he would
do with his campaign war chest if he dropped out.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   His campaign staff continued its work unabated, with two aides
dispatched to Buffalo to help select the music, lighting and stage
design for the Republican nominating convention on May 30. The
mayor had no public appearances, but he indicated Wednesday that he
was still struggling to decide on a treatment regimen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to think about it,'' Giuliani said, on his way out
of 17 Murray Street, a restaurant near City Hall, where he had
walked to lunch after a morning of meetings with some of his
closest advisers, including his campaign manager, Bruce J.
Teitelbaum, and a friend, Elliot Cuker. ``The decision-making
process is fine. I am not going to comment on it today.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   But it has become clear in recent days that if Giuliani does
back out, he risks alienating some of his approximately 200,000
campaign donors. As of the end of March, Giuliani had spent $10.1
million starting up his campaign against Clinton, leaving $9.2
million in the bank.
</P>
<P>
   Federal law does not allow Giuliani to give his money directly
to Lazio or another replacement candidate, but the mayor could
transfer it to a state or national Republican Party committee that
could spend it on Lazio's behalf.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani could also donate some or all of the money to charity,
said Kenneth A. Gross, a Washington-based election law expert and
former head of enforcement at the Federal Election Commission.
Finally, he could follow the lead of Gov. Christie Whitman of New
Jersey. As of earlier this year, she had returned about half of the
$2.2 million she had raised, after she bowed out of a New Jersey
race for the U.S. Senate.
</P>
<P>
   But several political consultants and campaign finance experts
said that Giuliani, if he pulled out, would most likely not rely on
any of those options for the majority of his remaining cash.
Instead, he would save it for a future run for governor or some
other office, they said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would surprise me if he does not hang on to the lion's
share of it,'' said Jay Severin, a New York-based Republican
consultant who has worked on 100 campaigns since 1980.
</P>
<P>
   Kieran Mahoney, a Republican consultant who has worked on more
than 160 races, said, ``He has no incentive to give most of the
money away.''
</P>
<P>
   Severin and Mahoney, as well as several Democratic political
consultants, agreed that the mayor would most likely give at least
a share of his $9 million to a Republican Party committee that
would assist his successor in the Senate race. To keep every cent
would offend the party, they said.
</P>
<P>
   Some donors said that Giuliani should give up all of the
out-of-state contributions, given that so many were motivated by an
anti-Clinton sentiment.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``Yes, the money was for Rudy, but the investment I made was in
the Senate race,'' said Andrew J. Futey, a government relations
consultant from Cleveland who contributed $1,000 to Giuliani's
campaign. ``The main goal here is making sure there is somebody
else besides Hillary. I would like to see my money stay in the
race.''
</P>
<P>
   For a replacement to make up the difference in the next several
months would be very difficult, many said. By the end of March,
Clinton had $6.6 million in the bank of the $12.8 million she had
raised.
</P>
<P>
   By following the advice of Ross and Futey, the mayor would risk
alienating other Republicans who said in interviews that they were
not so sure they wanted to see their money go to Lazio. Giuliani,
though a Republican, has stands on several issues traditionally
associated with Democrats, such as his support of abortion rights
and gun control. Lazio's record is not as consistently moderate.
</P>
<P>
   Wendell A. Peterson of Ida, Mich., said he considered himself a
liberal Republican, and that though he could not control what
Giuliani did with his $500 donation, he would be disappointed if it
ended up being spent to elect Lazio.
</P>
<P>
   ``I grew up in politics with Republicans like Rockefeller of New
York,'' he said, referring to Nelson A. Rockefeller, the New York
governor from 1959 to 1973. ``I view Mr. Giuliani as a Republican
in that tradition, and that was the primary reason I gave money to
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Lazio caused a rustle of attention Wednesday night when he
arrived at a Conservative Party dinner, wearing a tuxedo. He said
repeatedly that he was waiting for Giuliani to make a decision and
did not want to interfere during the mayor's difficult time. ``I
think right now it would probably be unseemly for me to make any
overt gestures that could be exploiting this time he's choosing to
make his decision,'' Lazio said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
