<SLUG> BC-GLF-GOLFCOL-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORTH THE WAIT AT COLLEGE OF THE CANYONS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE SHELBURNE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If the game plan counts as much as the game, maybe so.
</P>
<P>
   College of the Canyons golf coach Gary Peterson produced his
second state team titlist in seven seasons last week, when his
Cougars capped a 59-1 campaign with a 19-stroke victory in the
eight-team California Community College Championship at Glendora
Country Club.
</P>
<P>
   Peterson prevailed with a team that began the season with
redshirts filling three of six starting spots.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three of our top five waited a year to play,'' he said. ``I
think that's been one of the strengths of the program.''
</P>
<P>
   The waiting period, Peterson said, helps with maturity and
improvement, giving incoming players _ many of whom have been stars
in high school _ a more realistic idea of what it takes to succeed
at the college level. Peterson's competitive qualifying process
increases the focus. Each spring, all Cougars play 15 rounds, with
the top six scoring averages earning starting berths.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the COC qualifying produced four rounds of 68 and a
school record of 7-under-par 353 by the top five in a match at
Buena Ventura GC.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids come in with high expectations, then realize there's only
six spots,'' Peterson said. ``A lot of them want to spend that year
wisely.''
</P>
<P>
   That combined decision made this year's Cougars practice
sessions impressive for more than the ability of starters Mike
Applegate (a team-leading 73.25 average), Travis Matye (74.25),
Matias Gil (74.50), Pat Kelly (74.75), Mike Scott (75) and UCLA
transfer Charlie Smith.
</P>
<P>
   While they were honing the skills that would produce the most
wins in school history, 20 other players were working through their
own redshirt seasons, aware that Applegate was one of them just a
season earlier.
</P>
<P>
   The waiters could have plenty of positions to shoot for next
year, when Peterson expects five and maybe all six of this year's
starters could be playing at four-year colleges.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Peterson continues to enjoy the glow of an
almost perfect season.
</P>
<P>
   ``You knew early that this was a deep team and that they were
extremely focused,'' he said. ``They set goals. I don't think it
was winning state, but it was hammering conference and going far.''
</P>
<P>
   Peterson and assistant Mark Savage contributed their contrasting
coaching input to the mix _ Savage as tactician, Peterson as
motivator _ and the Cougars wound up dominating the Western State
Conference as intended, and as past COC teams have done often in
winning eight WSC titles.
</P>
<P>
   But Peterson knew the best of plans and best of talent don't
always work out: The Cougars took a 50-0 team into the postseason
two years ago and were eliminated in the first round. Six previous
COC squads had reached the 36-hole state tournament with only one
champion coming out of it.
</P>
<P>
   This time, however, the meld of talent and focus was perfect.
The Cougars led by 13 strokes after the first 18 holes at state and
Peterson was actually able to enjoy the stretch run without
anxiety.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we won in '93, it was with calculator in hand,'' he said.
``We didn't know until the end. With this team, it was relax, sit
back and watch and appreciate the moment. Travis (COC leader at
state and second overall at 2-over-par 142) told me he played the
last three holes with goosebumps.''
</P>
<P>
   Peterson thinks the success of this redshirt-led team was an
endorsement of patience.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really think when you stick around awhile, you become a
better golfer. With our qualifying system, you've got to suck up
that bad round and focus. You've got to learn how to score when
you're not striking the ball well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good competition breeds good golf. You know you've got to
bring your best game every day.''
</P>
<P>
   __ What's happening: Scholl Canyon in Glendale is one of several
area courses conducting special programs Saturday for American
Golf's fifth annual Women in Golf Day. The event, celebrating the
growth of women's participation in the game, takes place at more
than 250 American Golf-owned or operated courses this weekend. Last
year more than 18,000 women participated. At School Canyon, head
professional Ted Eleftheriou and staff will conduct morning clinics
on full swing, short game and putting before a complimentary lunch
and afternoon scramble tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Also this weekend, Scholl Canyon will conduct its first Junior
Golf Day, from 1 to 3 p.m. Sunday. There is no charge for the
clinics on Saturday or Sunday, but registration is advised.
Information: 818/243-4100. . . .
</P>
<P>
   Body Balance for Professionals, a La Crescenta-based national
golf health and fitness program, will conduct a golf seminar for
health care professionals May 28-30 in Westchester. The Body
Balance program was designed with the help of Paul Callaway, former
PGA Tour Director of Physical Therapy, to help golfers achieve
greater accuracy and consistency through golf-specific fitness.
Information: 800/473-6211 or 818/236-2410.
</P>
<P>
   __ Names in the game: Mark Singer of Moorpark shot 1-over-par 73
at La Purisima on Tuesday to earn one of six berths for next
month's U.S. Open sectional qualifier at Lake Merced Golf and
Country Club in Daly City, Calif. Five other area players earned
section berths Monday at par-72 Saticoy Country Club, where Steve
Holmes of Van Nuys was medalist at 68. Others advancing out of
Saticoy included Brandon Ditullio of Thousand Oaks (70), Tommy
Stankowski of Oxnard (70), Mitch Voges of Simi Valley (71) and Jon
Fiedler of Camarillo (72). . . .
</P>
<P>
   Former Occidental College golfer Olin Browne defends his title
this week in the Colonial Invitational at Fort Worth, Texas. . . .
Sylmar's David Berganio ranks fourth in Buy.Com Tour (formerly Nike
Tour) scoring with a 70.08 average. . . . Tommy Barber of Notre
Dame leads a contingent of 13 area high school golfers into
Monday's Southern Section championship at Palm Springs' Canyon CC
after shooting 3-under-par 68 in a qualifier at Montecito CC this
week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
