<HEADLINE>
VENUS WILLIAMS IS BACK, AND SHE INTENDS TO STAY
</HEADLINE>
  By CHRISTOPHER CLAREY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ Sporting less muscle and hardly any beads, Venus Williams
returned to the scene of one of her most important victories
Wednesday and made it clear that, despite her father Richard's
suggestions to the contrary, she always intended to return to the
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, no,'' she said about retirement. ``I would have been back
a lot sooner if it wasn't for the tendinitis in my wrists. It just
took a long time to heal. I used to have tendinitis in my knee. I
could play with that. It was different. But you can't do it without
your hands.''
</P>
<P>
   Citing sore wrists, Williams missed the first four months of
this season, withdrawing from five tournaments, including the
year's first Grand Slam event, the Australian Open. During her
layoff, she said she followed the game on television and the
Internet and took a course in fashion illustration.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like playing tennis more,'' she said. ``Studying is a real
job.''
</P>
<P>
   She returned to competition two weeks ago in Hamburg, Germany,
beating Irina Spirlea in three often unsightly sets and then losing
in straight sets to Amanda Coetzer, a player she once dominated
consistently. But Wednesday, on the same court where she won the
last Italian Open title, she bore a closer resemblance to the power
player her opponents remember.
</P>
<P>
   Against Coetzer in Hamburg, she had made unforced errors in
bunches and often looked off balance. In Wednesday's 6-1, 6-2
victory over Chanda Rubin, she covered court very well, kept her
aggressive groundstrokes more consistently in play and finished off
the inconsistent Rubin with her fifth ace of the match, five more
than she hit against Coetzer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really starting to play better now,'' said Williams, who
spent the last nine days training in Rome. ``Starting last week in
Hamburg, I was a little iffy. It was just tough. I was not
practicing very much, and I just had to learn a tough lesson.''
</P>
<P>
   This has been the most trying period yet in the 19-year-old
Williams' short but compelling career. In an interview after the
match, conducted with her tiny Yorkshire terrier Pete sitting
comfortably on her lap, Williams said she had first felt a twinge
in her left wrist here while warming up on center court for a match
in Rome last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't pay much attention to it,'' she said. ``You use your
whole body. Sometimes you feel different things, but they go away.
But I can tell you that I sure didn't know it was going to come out
like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams, a right-hander with a two-handed backhand, taped her
wrist for matches occasionally throughout the summer: reaching the
quarterfinals at Wimbledon and the semifinals at the U.S. Open,
where her younger sister, Serena, won the singles title.
</P>
<P>
   ``The wrist just got steadily worse over the season,'' said
their mother and co-coach, Oracene. ``Venus was playing hurt and
not telling anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   But Venus said that it was only after reaching the Chase
semifinals in November that the pain became too intense for her to
practice or play.
</P>
<P>
   ``In December, I was home really training and trying hard to get
ready for the Australian Open, and I just couldn't do it,'' she
said. ``Between January and April, I would say I had a total of
maybe three weeks of practice at the most.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could have gone to tournaments, but I just don't know how
good it would have been to take the risk of losing matches because
I was a little bit injured or having to retire from matches. I just
thought it would be wiser to stay home until it was healed.''
</P>
<P>
   Venus, whose two-handed backhand is her best shot, even
experimented with switching to a one-handed backhand in an attempt
to accelerate her comeback.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was hitting one-handed with slice,'' Oracene said. `And we
just told her, `Venus that's not your game.'''
</P>
<P>
   Venus said, ``All it did was end up hurting my right wrist.''
But I'm better now.''
</P>
<P>
   Venus said she tried a variety of treatments, including
acupuncture, but the only remedy that really helped was time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I missed tennis, but I had a lot to do,'' she said. ``Every
day was packed, and it was like I was the one at home, so I did
everything. I became the businesswomen. I did things for Serena,
things for my mom, things for my dad, things for myself. Everyone's
affairs, I handled.''
</P>
<P>
   In March during the Ericsson Open, her father said that he
believed it was very likely that Venus would retire.
</P>
<P>
   ``Venus was shocked when she heard it,'' Oracene said of her
husband's comments.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``So what can I say?'' Venus said Wednesday. ``I was just an
innocent bystander. I was just watching the story, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Venus declared herself ``pain free,'' she played
Wednesday with her left wrist taped, which she had not done in
Hamburg.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fine,'' she said. ``I'm feeling real good. If it wasn't
good, I would just be shipped home. It's not holding me back from
my regular shots.''
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, she is not hitting her first serve as
consistently hard as before her layoff. She has clearly lost muscle
definition, if not weight, in her legs and arms.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad, he wanted me to do a lot of fitness work,'' she said,
``but I usually found a way to get out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether she might not feel she had maximized her talent
until she, too, had won a Grand Slam singles title, she said:
``There's no one out here who doesn't want to win a Slam. I know I
have the capability. We'll see if I can.''
</P>
<P>
   Barring a relapse, she will get her next opportunity at the
French Open, which begins on May 29. Serena, who has struggled with
her game of late, is currently in Florida because of a sore knee
and is spending her time moving into her and Venus' recently
completed new home.
</P>
<P>
   But Oracene and Venus both expect Serena to play at Roland
Garros. The other contenders are well aware that, unlike most of
them, the sisters do not necessarily need many matches to reach
cruising speed. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
