<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-TANNER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOUISE TANNER, AUTHOR OF `BANNISTER'S GIRLS,' DIES AT 78 
 
</HEADLINE>
  c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Louise Tanner, a writer whose work often mirrored her Social
Register upbringing, died on Monday at her home in Manhattan. She
was 78.
</P>
<P>
   The widow of Edward Everett Tanner III, who, as Patrick Dennis,
wrote ``Auntie Mame,'' Tanner was herself the author of five books,
including the novel ``Bannister's Girls,'' inspired by her
experiences as a student at Chapin's, a New York finishing school.
</P>
<P>
   Born Louise Frith Stickney, Tanner grew up in what she called
``Edwardian opulence'' on the Upper East Side of Manhattan. She
demonstrated her writing talent at an early age by winning Vogue
magazine's Prix de Paris. After graduating from Vassar in 1944 she
met Tanner; they were married four years later, preventing her, she
once remarked, from having ``wound up a very embittered
ex-debutante.''
</P>
<P>
   Her wry, wisecracking persona made her the perfect counterpart
to her husband, who based one of the main characters in his 1962
best seller, ``Genius,'' on his wife. He also cast her in the role
of Pixie Portnoy in his 1961 novel, ``Little Me,'' which was made
into a Broadway musical.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to two social histories, ``Here Today'' (1959) and
``All the Things We Were'' (1968), Tanner wrote two novels for
young adults, ``Reggie and Nilma'' and ``Dr. IRT.'' She is survived
by a son, Michael; a daughter, Betsy; and a grandchild, all of New
York.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-17-00 2231EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
