<HEADLINE>
WEB SITE WITH INSPECTIONS OF RESTAURANT KITCHENS IS OVERWHELMED
</HEADLINE>
  By THOMAS J. LUECK and NEIL MacFARQUHAR    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The city's Department of Health created an instant
sensation among food-crazed New Yorkers on Wednesday by
inaugurating a Web site listing every blemish noted by inspectors
at all licensed restaurants in the five boroughs.
</P>
<P>
   Given the number of city residents who treat jockeying for
restaurant reservations like a blood sport, the site quickly
clogged, unable to sustain the average 23,000 hits an hour it was
getting by late afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   With a few clicks of the mouse, users could call up the latest
inspections of the most expensive, most coveted tables in the city
_ places like Le Bernardin or La Caravelle where a dinner for one
is in the $70 range _ and read that they were cited for ``vermin or
other live animal'' in their food storage, preparation or service
areas.
</P>
<P>
   In general, restaurateurs supported the idea that the public had
a right to know such details, but the one-size-fits-all categories
prompted Gallic cries of dismay from numerous kitchens. Some chefs
and owners at the city's elite restaurants expressed horror at the
idea that what they called picayune infractions would be lumped
together with problems at the corner greasy spoon.
</P>
<P>
   Inspectors found ``mice droppings in a single bag of flour,''
said Eric Ripert, the chef at Le Bernardin, which has been
consistently rated by food bibles like Zagat as the best restaurant
in New York. ``When we got that inspection we acknowledged it and
we talked to our purveyor right away and they changed all the
flour. I don't believe we have a mouse in the house.''
</P>
<P>
   Ripert said that the restaurant's regular customers were
unlikely to be deterred by the December 1999 inspection report,
especially since the kitchens are open for visits by any customer
who so desires. But he and other restaurateurs are concerned that
the listings are not thorough or specific enough.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Neal L. Cohen, the city's health commissioner, said that the
information on the site would provide a snapshot of health
conditions in each of the city's more than 18,000 restaurants. But
he also acknowledged that the information was limited and
potentially misleading.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be wrong to interpret any inspection report as a
final grade for a restaurant,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, on the Health Department Web site, if a restaurant
is cited for vermin or some other infraction, the word is
highlighted so that clicking on it produces a glossary of the
misdeeds. Vermin, for one, is defined as ``insect or small animal
that is destructive, annoying, or harmful to health. Includes
cockroaches, flies, and rats.''
</P>
<P>
   Rita Jammet, who with her husband, Andre, owns La Caravelle,
says she was shocked by the word vermin from their July 1999
inspection.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very scary word; you see the word vermin and you think
of all sorts of nasty animals crawling,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The inspector found a fly!'' Jammet added, noting that her
restaurant is scrupulous about cleanliness. ``It was July. It was
New York. It's the summer. Our food preparation areas are in the
basement which we share with a hotel. There was construction. I am
not trying to make excuses, but this is the reality of living in
New York.''
</P>
<P>
   Jammet, like many others, suggested that the Health Department
might want to adjust the wording so it would not seem quite so
alarming.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not my idea of a glamorous description, but in general I
think it is a good thing they are doing,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen of the Health Department said the Web site would provide
better consumer safeguards and a new incentive for restaurants to
improve health standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``With this ease of access to information by the public,
restaurant owners will no doubt aspire to even higher standards of
public health safety and cleanliness,'' Cohen said.
</P>
<P>
   City rules require an unannounced inspection once each year,
with more frequent visits where serious problems are found and not
immediately corrected. The Web site lists only the latest
inspection.
</P>
<P>
   The Web site (http://207.127.96.244/webfood/search.htm) allows
users to search for restaurants either by name or location,
clicking on a map of each of the five boroughs.  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
