<SLUG> BC-CAMPBELL-OUTLOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAMPBELL SOUP POSTS DROP OF 14% IN QUARTERLY PROFIT
</HEADLINE>
  By CONSTANCE L. HAYS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ With sales of its signature soups on the wane, the
Campbell Soup Co. said Wednesday that its third-quarter earnings
fell 14 percent, and warned that the rest of its fiscal year, which
ends in July, was unlikely to be much better.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking at a meeting with analysts in New York, Campbell's
president and chief executive, David Johnson, acknowledged the
company's dismal performance, but insisted that it could fix the
problems. ``We are not paralyzed; we are moving forward,'' Johnson
said.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson came out of retirement to replace Dale F. Morrison, who
resigned in March after less than three years in Campbell's top
job. Under Morrison, Campbell struggled to improve its soup
business, which accounts for half of the company's earnings. At the
same time, sales of its Pepperidge Farm cookies and crackers
boomed, and a new product, V8 Splash, enjoyed brisk sales.
</P>
<P>
   In the most recent quarter, however, soup was not the only
culprit. The company said on Wednesday that Pepperidge Farm's
earnings declined in the quarter, mainly because of marketing for
its Goldfish crackers. V8 Splash also declined, pulling down
earnings in the company's beverage division. Sales of Pace salsa
also fell, the company said. For the quarter, earnings fell to $139
million, or 32 cents a diluted share, from $162 million, or 37
cents, a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   One of the few bright spots came from one of the company's
smallest divisions _ Godiva Chocolatier, which had solid sales
because of Valentine's Day and Easter.
</P>
<P>
   Some industry experts have said that soup sales are down because
people these days do not have the time or inclination to prepare
it, a theory Campbell's executives have gone to great lengths to
counter. At the meeting, Johnson announced plans to build up
Campbell's soup business by bringing out new products and
repackaging some old ones. These include putting pull-off lids on
soups that are marketed as ``ready to serve'' to make the cans
easier to open, and making some additional flavors in the
ready-to-serve package, including minestrone.
</P>
<P>
   One analyst voiced concern about how the new products would
affect the company's profits. ``It will make the packaging more
expensive, and they said they are not going to raise prices,'' said
Nomi Ghez, a Goldman, Sachs analyst, who estimated the additional
cost at 2 cents to 3 cents a can. She added that putting more kinds
of Campbell's soup on the grocery shelf might draw business away
from existing Campbell's products. ``It is likely to be
cannibalistic,'' she said, ``and the ready-to-serve soups are
lower-margin than the condensed soups.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson also said the company would pursue strategic
initiatives, including acquisitions, to improve sales. ``He said he
won't just combine with someone to get synergies,'' Ghez said.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson gave no details about which companies Campbell might be
considering. But one possibility is H.J. Heinz, which makes
private-label soup that competes with Campbell's brands.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking strength in scale, many large food companies are
considering partnerships of various kinds, with Nabisco Group
Holdings on the block and Unilever actively courting Bestfoods.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have a lot going on in the back room, but when they get to
the front room, they can't talk about it,'' said John R. McMillin,
a Prudential Securities analyst.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson is respected by Wall Street for his record at Campbell,
where he was president for seven years before turning the reins
over to Morrison. In the old days, Johnson would don a cape and
call himself Souperman to inspire his employees. On Wednesday, he
appeared subdued and serious, but insisted that Campbell could
resolve its issues and improve performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the meeting, it became clear that next year is going to be
a transition year and not great, either,'' said Ghez, who reduced
her earnings expectations for 2001 by 5 cents, to $1.75, which is
scant improvement on the $1.65 expected this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are addressing the big brands with some innovation, and
with good management, at least the precipitous decline of the
business can be stemmed,'' she added. ``The question is, can they
get it to grow?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
