<SLUG> BC-CHINA-TRADE-BUSH-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH URGES CONGRESS TO BACK CLINTON ON CHINA TRADE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Subs 8th graf for Bush remark that he would be willing to call
congressmen) 
(ART ADV: Photo NYT22 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.)  
 (Eds: Also being sent in `p' code)  
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   EVERETT, Wash. _ Calling trade relations with China the work of
``13 years and three administrations,'' Gov. George W. Bush on
Wednesday urged congressional Republicans and Democrats alike to
support President Clinton and vote to grant China permanent trade
rights. The House is scheduled to vote next week.
</P>
<P>
   Although Bush has long supported free trade, his address here
Wednesday on the vast factory floor of a Boeing plant marked one of
the few times that he has tried publicly to affect pending
legislation in Congress. He called the question of whether to
extend normal trading privileges to China ``among the most serious
decisions our government will make this year.'' And he said ``no
one serious about shouldering the responsibilities of the
presidency'' should remain silent.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the start of this campaign, I have defined some sharp
differences with the Clinton-Gore administration,'' Bush said, a
sleek Boeing 777 behind him. ``But today I want to address an
important area of agreement. A pressing question now confronts the
Congress and it will not wait until the next president takes
office.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a Republican or Democratic concern,'' Bush said.
``It is an American concern. This trade agreement is the work of 13
years and three administrations. We cannot let that work be
undone.'' He did not mention his father by name, although he was
one of those presidents. But he quoted Ronald Reagan, who called
free trade ``a forward strategy for freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   With his remarks, Bush put himself in a tradition of bipartisan
cooperation on foreign policy that has increasingly been eroded in
recent years. And the speech was just the latest example of his
efforts to portray himself as leader willing to reach across party
lines.
</P>
<P>
   Only a day earlier, he parted company with Senate Republicans,
criticizing a bill that would set a deadline for withdrawing U.S.
ground troops from Kosovo. A spokesman for Bush said he considered
the measure ``legislative overreach on powers of the presidency.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush made his speech in a region of the country that has been at
the epicenter of the debate over trade. While Washington is
oriented toward exports and the Pacific rim, nearby Seattle was
also the site of last year's violent protests against the World
Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
   The vast Boeing plant itself showcased those divisions. The
company is the nation's largest exporter, but a number its workers
said they feared China's entry into the World Trade Organization
would ultimately cost Americans jobs. Indeed the local congressman,
Rep. Jack Metcalf, is one of the few undecided Republicans on the
issue. Bush, on his campaign plane this afternoon, said that he had
made no telephone calls to wavering house members, but would do so
if Rep. Tom DeLay, the majority whip, asked for his help.
</P>
<P>
   Washington state has voted Democratic in the past three
presidential elections, but Bush's aides say they are contesting
the state. The employees at the Boeing plant gave Bush a generally
polite reception. He drew applause and a few boos. A long line of
workers waited to meet him and shake his hand after the speech.
</P>
<P>
   The measure cleared the House Ways and Means Committee on
Wednesday by a larger-than-expected margin of 34-4 as several
undecided members sided with Clinton. The full House, which is
bitterly divided on the issue, is to vote next week on whether to
grant China permanent normal trading privileges.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Clinton, who has made this one of his foreign policy priorities
for the year, has argued for months that Congress must grant China
permanent trading rights or risk damaging the competitiveness of
U.S. companies and relations with the world's most populous
country.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the vote is too close to call. And if the measure passes,
it will do so largely with the support of Republicans. Many
Democrats have sided with organized labor, which is fighting hard
against the measure, arguing that permanent support for China trade
would leave Congress few ways to pressure China to improve its
record on human rights, labor and the environment.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has supported the bill, but been less fervent than the
president, trying to avoid the wrath of organized labor, a critical
Democratic constituency.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Bush has seemed a more enthusiastic ally to Clinton on
the China bill than Gore. He argued Wednesday that ``the stakes are
high'' in how the debate is decided and made an impassioned
argument for the House to ratify China's entry into the WTO.
</P>
<P>
   ``For businesses and workers and farmers, it will mean lower
trade barriers and important opportunities for U.S. exports and
more work and jobs for United States workers,'' he said. ``For the
people of East Asia, it will affect their relations with the
region's major superpower. For the people of China it holds out the
hope of more open contact with the world of freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   He did however use the occasion to draw distinctions between the
administration's approach to China and trade and his own. He said
Clinton and Gore view China as a `'strategic partner'' and said,
``I view China as a competitor.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush also accused the administration of being inconsistent in
its approach to Taiwan. And he charged that it had bungled various
high profile battles over trade. ``They failed to obtain `fast
track' trade negotiating authority,'' Bush said, ``I will fight for
it. They mishandled the global trade negotiations here in Seattle.
I will make expanding trade and therefore expanding jobs at home a
consistent priority of my administration.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush argued that while China is not a ``strategic partner,'' it
is not an enemy. ``When I am the president, China will have no
doubts about our power and purpose in the region _ about our strong
commitment to democratic allies throughout Asia,'' he said. ``But
this is accomplished through confident diplomacy, strong alliances,
and a military to back us. It is not accomplished by hindering free
trade or seeking to isolate China.''
</P>
<P>
   The Boeing workers were divided on the issue. Before Bush spoke,
Jon J. Walker, 46, a tool maker, said he opposed normal trade with
China because it would result in the loss of U.S. manufacturing
jobs. ``We know that labor is cheaper elsewhere,'' he said. ``We
can't compete with somebody who's living in a cardboard box.'' He
said he was a Democrat who would vote for Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Afterwards, Charles Webb, 42, a mechanic, said he was a
unionized worker who does not ``follow the union line. But he said
he was uncertain about China trade because ``I'm not confident with
China's human rights record.''
</P>
<P>
   He took a dim view of both candidates. ``I'm not going to vote
for Gore _ that's a definite,'' Webb said. ``Vote for Bush? I'd
prefer not to. But that may be my only choice.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
