<SLUG> BC-NY-LEVY-SCHOOLS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEVY IS CHANCELLOR ON 7-0 VOTE; 2-YEAR CONTRACT EXPECTED 
</HEADLINE>
   By EDWARD WYATT    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After voting unanimously to make Harold O. Levy the
first businessman and noneducator to be named chancellor of the New
York City school system in its 102-year history, Board of Education
officials said Wednesday that they expected to award Levy a
two-year contract to manage the country's largest school system.
</P>
<P>
   That means that Levy is likely to remain chancellor until at
least the summer of 2002, well after Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani
leaves office, whether or not the mayor runs for or wins a seat in
the U.S. Senate. Giuliani, who opposed Levy's appointment to the
interim post in January, reversed course on Tuesday and endorsed
him.
</P>
<P>
   Levy said that among his first priorities as permanent
chancellor would be to deliver a plan to overhaul the Board of
Education's sprawling bureaucracy and to create partnerships in the
community among school employees, parents, businesses, other
educational institutions and political leaders, aimed at improving
the schools. He also announced that Judith A. Rizzo _ the deputy
chancellor of instruction under Rudy Crew when he was chancellor,
who had been recently thinking about leaving the board _ would
remain as his chief education deputy.
</P>
<P>
   In an address to the board after his election, Levy said: ``I
come to the job as a business person but also as somebody who loves
education and is very pleased to have an opportunity to contribute
to what I believe is the most important function in our society
today. The system that I begin to lead now is a system that has had
enormous successes and has proven beyond any possible doubt that it
is capable of creating greatness. That is a greatness that I want
to achieve again.''
</P>
<P>
   After the meeting, Levy received lukewarm support from Ninfa
Segarra, one of Giuliani's two representatives on the board, who
said her vote reflected a show of support for a chancellor who
already had the promised votes of a majority of the board. In that,
she echoed the mayor, saying that many areas of disagreement remain
between the Board of Education and City Hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would not be a positive thing for the system if he walked
in with a split vote,'' Segarra said, referring to Levy. ``We
wanted to show that the mayor is willing to work with the new
chancellor. That's an important indicator for the city.''
</P>
<P>
   The Board of Education conducted a nationwide search for a
chancellor, producing scores of applicants but no one who was
willing to compete directly against Levy, who took over as interim
chancellor in January. One speaker at Wednesday's session, Michael
Meyers of the New York Civil Rights Coalition, sharply criticized
the board for failing to find any qualified minority candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Levy's selection is, in my considered judgment, the
triumph of cronyism,'' Meyers said.
</P>
<P>
   But other speakers, including Cynthia Cummins, a member of a
South Bronx parents group, supported Levy. Cummins said she
believed that he could help to change ``the persistent educational
failure'' in many Bronx schools.
</P>
<P>
   Levy will receive a salary of $245,000 a year, plus other
benefits that remain to be determined. Among them are likely to be
a housing allowance as the board prepares to study the sale of the
Brooklyn brownstone bought several years ago to serve as the
chancellor's residence.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
