<HEADLINE>
PEGASUS RECEIVING KID-GLOVE TREATMENT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TIM PRICE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ The conservative and protective nature of trainer
Neil Drysdale was evident when Fusaichi Pegasus arrived yesterday
in Baltimore after a flight from Louisville, Ky. Drysdale has him
stabled on the backstretch in Barn 7 at Pimlico, the opposite side
of the track from the stakes barn, where most of the horses for the
Preakness are stabled.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's quieter over here,'' Drysdale said.
</P>
<P>
   Drysdale also decided to unload him at the back of the barn away
from the racetrack where horses were ready to start the next race
on yesterday's card. He unloaded the colt directly into the barn so
he didn't have to step on the concrete surrounding the barn.
</P>
<P>
   Drysdale said Fusaichi Pegasus probably will be saddled in the
inside paddock at Pimlico that's used on a daily basis, rather than
on the infield turf course where the horses for the Preakness are
saddled every year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sun is beating down. Why not go someplace where it's
cool?'' Drysdale asked.  &QL; 
Briefly
</P>
<P>
   Pimilico oddsmaker Clem Florio said the morning-line odds of 3-5
on Fusaichi Pegasus is the lowest he has set for the favorite at
the Preakness in his 36 years.
</P>
<P>
   Citing his allegiance to longtime friend and Indiana basketball
coach Bobby Knight, trainer D. Wayne Lukas said he won't grant
interviews to CNN//SI or any of the network's affiliates for an
unspecified period because the cable network aired a videotape of
Knight choking former Hoosiers player Neil Reed. ``I thought CNN
started the whole damn thing,'' Lukas said.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
