<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS GET EVEN AFTER WOBBLY START
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ A quarter of a season has passed and the
Rangers find themselves no better than a .500 team.
</P>
<P>
   Considering where they've been, they'll gladly take that for
now.
</P>
<P>
   The usual flogging of the Tampa Bay Devil Rays' pitching staff
and a gritty relief performance by Tim Crabtree allowed the Rangers
to reach that mark with an 11-6 victory yesterday afternoon at The
Ballpark in Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers, led by Frank Catalanotto's five-hit performance,
pounded out an 8-1 lead after three innings. But, after Fred
McGriff's grand slam made it 8-5, Crabtree had to rescue struggling
starter Doug Davis in the fifth and pitch 4 2/3 innings to preserve
the victory.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers, after an 8-15 start, have now won 12 of 17, putting
them at the .500 mark (20-20) for the first time since they were
6-6 on April 16.
</P>
<P>
   ``From where we started, going through that bad streak, to be
able to come back from that is good,'' designated hitter Rafael
Palmeiro said. ``Our team is going to get better. We made a lot of
changes and when you do that, it's hard to expect that you're not
going to miss a beat. Nobody likes to struggle, but sometimes you
have to struggle to get better. I think we've done that.''
</P>
<P>
   The offense has done much to get the Rangers back. They had 16
hits yesterday, raising the club average to .304, the highest it
has ever been after 40 games in a season. Catalanotto led the way,
but Ivan Rodriguez added to his latest tear by going 3-for-4 and
Luis Alicea, Chad Curtis and Mike Lamb had two hits each.
</P>
<P>
   ``This team can hit,'' Crabtree said. ``They can flat-out hit.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers had hoped the bullpen would be just as good as their
offense. It hasn't been. But yesterday it was and it was all
Crabtree.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Johnny Oates went with him much earlier than usual
because of the Devil Rays' predominantly right-handed hitting.
Oates was hoping Crabtree could at least get the Rangers through
the seventh. He got much more, all at Crabtree's request.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first brought him in, I told him I needed eight or nine
outs,'' Oates said. ``When he came in after the seventh, he said,
`I've got at least another inning in me.' After the eighth, he
said, `I'd really like to finish this thing.' I asked him if he'd
ever thrown 50 pitches in a game before. He said `It doesn't really
matter. I feel really good. I think I've got one more in me.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Crabtree threw a season-high 61 pitches, and the 4 2/3 innings
made it the longest outing of his professional career.
</P>
<P>
   ``We maintain ourselves each and every day,'' Crabtree said.''Me
and \RJeff Zimmerman\S, we throw 40-45 pitches every day in batting
practice. I felt strong in the ninth inning. It's almost like a
starting pitcher when you get into a rhythm. It's just a matter of
maintaining your stamina.''
</P>
<P>
   Crabtree finished strong. Five of the first 10 hitters he faced
reached base on three singles, a walk and an error, which led to an
unearned run in the sixth. But he retired the final eight hitters
and gave much credit to the strong wind that was blowing toward the
outfield.
</P>
<P>
   ``The wind was awesome,'' Crabtree said. ``It gave my fastball
some major sinkage. I couldn't have thrown a better sinker. I had
the perfect arm slot. I just need to build on that and stay with
it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers know about sinking. They almost sank themselves out
of a division race in April. Now that they're back at .500, their
division title hopes seem afloat again.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're back where we can see out of the foxhole,'' Oates said.
``Hopefully now we can get out of the foxhole.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
