A8343 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-BBA-RANGERS-NOTES-TEX     05-17 0630
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ The Rangers are bringing Triple-A pitcher Dan
Kolb to Arlington today and are expected to send pitcher Doug Davis
back to the minor leagues. The Rangers are concerned about running
short of pitching after Tim Crabtree pitched 4 2/3 innings
yesterday and Kenny Rogers still being doubtful for Sunday's start
because of a sore shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll wait until \Rtoday\S and then visit,'' general manager
Doug Melvin said. ``We want to make sure everybody is healthy
before we make a determination.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis continues to impress the Rangers and frustrate them. He
took a 8-1 lead into the fifth yesterday but had to come out after
Fred McGriff's grand slam. In the fourth, Davis walked the first
three batters he faced, then left the bases loaded by striking out
the side.
</P>
<P>
   ``He needs to pitch regularly,'' manager Johnny Oates said.
``There's no doubt in my mind he can get major-league hitters out.
But there are times when he's all over the place.''
</P>
<P>
   Kolb was 4-1 with an 0.98 earned-run average and four saves with
the Oklahoma RedHawks.  &QL; 
Greer's return delayed
</P>
<P>
   Outfielder Rusty Greer has recovered from ankle surgery and his
pulled hamstring muscle is no longer a problem. But his return from
the disabled list, planned for today, has been delayed by a sore
left shoulder, the result of having to make an excessive number of
throws while playing for the Tulsa Drillers on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been throwing every other day, but throwing in a game is
different,'' Greer said. ``Last night I had to make quite a number
of throws and I felt some pain and discomfort.''
</P>
<P>
   Greer has been found to have inflammation, and the Rangers are
still hoping he can return to the lineup before the end of the
homestand.
</P>
<P>
   Other injury news:
</P>
<P>
   First baseman David Segui was scratched from yesterday's lineup
with a viral infection.
</P>
<P>
   Outfielder Gabe Kapler said he's hoping to test his strained hip
flexor by running the bases today. If that goes well, he could go
out on medical rehabilitation assignment on Saturday and be
activated next week in Kansas City.  &QL; 
Curtis hits second deck
</P>
<P>
   Chad Curtis' first-inning home run landed in the first row of
the upper deck in right field. That blast gave him the honor being
the first right-handed hitter to ever hit one into the upper deck
of the Home Run Porch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm kind of surprised nobody else has done it,'' Curtis said.
``Guys like Juan Gonzalez and Dean Palmer, they've had some guys
here with power and opposite-field power. I'm sure the wind had
something to do with it, and I hit it solid. I'll take it.''  &QL; 
Orioles watch
</P>
<P>
   News flashes from the Baltimore Orioles, who open a four-game
series with the Rangers tonight at The Ballpark in Arlington:
</P>
<P>
   First baseman Will Clark, on the disabled list with a strained
hamstring, is expected to be activated for tonight's game and
return to the lineup. If so, it will be his first appearance at The
Ballpark since leaving the Rangers as a free agent after the 1998
season. He was on the disabled list last season when the Orioles
came to town.
</P>
<P>
   The Orioles, taking advantage of an off-day, are giving
struggling pitcher Mike Mussina an extra day of rest. Mussina, who
pitched Sunday, is being pushed back to Saturday instead of
pitching Friday on his normal four days of rest. Jason Johnson, the
Orioles' fifth starter who was skipped in his last start, is being
reinserted into the rotation on Friday.  &QL; 
Briefly
</P>
<P>
   John Wetteland will be honored before tonight's game for his
300th save, which he earned on Friday at Anaheim. Former Rangers
closer Tom Henke, who has 311 career saves, will take part in the
ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
