<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-AUSTRALIANS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUSTRALIANS THRIVING ON TEXAS TOUR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By J. DOUGLAS FOSTER 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ The koala population in Tarrant County is
limited to the confines of the Fort Worth Zoo.
</P>
<P>
   Crocodiles don't run rampant around the banks of the Trinity
River, and there's no barrier reef in Lake Worth.
</P>
<P>
   But Texas, to some Australians playing on the PGA Tour, feels
like home.
</P>
<P>
   For some reason, Australians thrive in the Texas heat, wind and
course conditions. Six Australians _ Stuart Appleby, Steve
Elkington, Robert Allenby, Greg Chalmers, Bradley Hughes and Craig
Parry _ will compete in the MasterCard Colonial starting today,
each hoping to become the fourth player from their country to win
the event and the second to win in Texas this year.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the Aussies' game just seems to fit Texas perfectly.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the wind,'' Parry said last week during a day of 38-mph
gusts at the GTE Byron Nelson Classic. ``This is a pretty normal
day for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Wind does seem to be a friend of Australians. Allenby won this
year's Shell Houston Open less than a month ago. Appleby won the
event last year.
</P>
<P>
   Appleby's success is not confined to South Texas though. He has
played the Colonial three times and owns the lowest career stroke
average at Hogan's Alley, tied with Peter Jordan at 69.00.
</P>
<P>
   ``It resembles Australia,'' Appleby said. ``The firmness of the
place, the wind, the style of the course. Obviously I feel
comfortable here.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's mainly the firmness of the fairways and the wind.
Ninety-nine percent of our tournaments are played on really soft
fairways and greens. The U.S. Open gets dry and firm, the Western
Open gets firm, and here it's always firm. But that's about it. In
Australia it plays firm every week.''
</P>
<P>
   Allenby and Appleby aren't the first Aussies to succeed in
Texas. Ian Baker-Finch won the Colonial in 1989, while countrymen
Bruce Crampton and Bruce Devlin won in 1965 and '66, respectively.
Crampton and Devlin also combined for three victories in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   The next trick, Australian players hope, is getting at least one
member of the group into the band of PGA Tour superstars. Elkington
was once there and has twice finished a season in the top 10 of the
money list _ including a No. 5 finish in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   But only one Australian has sat atop the PGA Tour, that being
Greg Norman when he won Vardon Trophy (lowest tour scoring average)
in 1988, '89 and '94.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know when I was coming up through the junior ranks I really
looked up to him,'' Allenby said. ``Greg Norman is such a big part
of Australian golf. We owe him a lot because we all wanted to turn
out being like Greg Norman.''
</P>
<P>
   Norman hopes to see another Australian reach that level as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to see that for Australia,'' Norman said during the
week of the Masters. ``We always need a Tiger Woods; we always need
a Jack Nicklaus or Seve Ballesteros. We always need somebody with
that type of charisma to keep the game going.''
</P>
<P>
   Australia, for its depth of golfing talent, doesn't have a
player at that level, but it might be close. Allenby and Appleby
are ranked Nos. 6 and 27, respectively, on the tour's all-around
rankings. Both are in the top 25 of the money list (Allenby No. 14,
Appleby No. 24) with more than $1.6 million combined.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a lot of very good young players,'' Parry said.
``We're getting back to the stage we were eight or nine years ago
when we had a dozen or so players around the world winning
everything.''
</P>
<P>
   While Allenby and Appleby are thriving now, people all around
the PGA Tour can't stop talking about 19-year-old amateur Aaron
Baddeley.
</P>
<P>
   Baddeley won the 1999 Australian Open and played in this year's
Masters. He's playing throughout the United States and Canada this
year on sponsor's exemptions to determine if he's ready to turn
professional.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a very good player,'' Chalmers said. ``For his age, he's
a fantastic player. Everyone is expecting big things of him.''
</P>
<P>
   But rest assured, Baddeley is not the last one. Appleby said
golf in Australia _ thanks to year-round playing conditions and the
inexpensive nature of the game compared with the cost in the United
States _ will just continue to grow. He also said the group of
young stars goes far beyond Baddeley, and that within the decade,
his country's tour success could stretch far outside the Texas
borders.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm beginning already to feel old,'' Appleby, 29, said. ``Only
a few years ago I was the young guy on tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're going to keep punching them out. By the end of
2010, you're going to see a bunch of world-class players.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
