<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   House and Senate Panels Endorse China Trade Bill
</P>
<P>
   Congress took its first step toward approving a trade bill
designed to change the United States' relationship with China, as a
House and a Senate committee each resoundingly endorsed the measure
in important test votes.
</P>
<P>
   Half a dozen previously uncommitted House Republicans and
Democrats said they would support the legislation granting China
permanent normal trading privileges. Administration officials and
congressional backers said they now think they are close to having
collected the 218 votes needed for passage in the House, but they
are still locked in a battle to put the measure over the top.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AIG Head May Reconsider Board
</P>
<P>
   Fending off questions from shareholders at the annual meeting of
the American International Group, Maurice R. Greenberg, its chief
executive, said he would consider reversing the insider dominance
of his board. But he would not budge on his designation of his son,
Evan, as his eventual successor. Shares of the company fell
$4.5625, to $118.125.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell Soup Profit Drops 14 percent
</P>
<P>
   With sales of its soups on the wane, Campbell Soup said that its
third-quarter earnings fell 14 percent and warned that the rest of
its fiscal year was unlikely to be much better.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rescue of ICO Global Is Completed
</P>
<P>
   Craig O. McCaw, the cellular telephone pioneer, announced the
completion of his investment group's $1.2 billion rescue of ICO
Global Communications, which went bankrupt developing a satellite
telecommunications network. And he announced his intention to merge
the company with Teledesic.
</P>
<P>
   Ford to Produce Fewer Excursions
</P>
<P>
   Ford said that it would produce fewer Excursion sport utility
vehicles during the 2001 model year, but attributed the cutback to
weak consumer demand for the vehicle rather than the company's
recent concerns about its safety and environmental problems.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Toyota Posts 25% Gain in Earnings
</P>
<P>
   Toyota Motor posted a 25 percent gain in profit for the second
half of its fiscal year, helped by robust sales in North America
and Japan and cost-cutting that partly offset the effects of a
strong yen on profits made overseas.
</P>
<P>
   Editor Steps Down at Real Simple
</P>
<P>
   In a management shake-up that shows that even the most promising
publishing team does not always guarantee a smooth start-up, the
managing editor of Real Simple _ a new magazine from Time for women
who want to simplify their lives _ resigned. The departure of the
editor, Susan Wyland, comes after only two issues of the magazine,
both of which have been criticized by some advertisers as overly
spare and unwelcoming.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sale of Bank Is Opposed in Brazil
</P>
<P>
   Brazil has reduced state ownership of telecommunications, power
and mining companies in what is regarded as a highly successful
privatization. But the government is facing unexpectedly tough
resistance to selling one of the biggest state assets, the bank
Banespa.
</P>
<P>
   Vodafone to Sell Stake in Cegetel
</P>
<P>
   Vodafone AirTouch, the wireless telephone operator, will sell
its 15 percent stake in the French telecommunications operator
Cegetel to Vivendi of France.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Takeover of Japanese Bank Is Seen
</P>
<P>
   Japan is expected to announce as early as Thursday that W.L.
Ross &AMP; Co., an investment concern run by the bankruptcy specialist
Wilbur L. Ross _ together with a unit of Daiwa Securities _ has
been chosen to take over Kofuku Bank, a regional bank in Osaka.
</P>
</TEXT>
