<SLUG> BC-NY-ASSEMBLY-DEMS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATS' UNITY ENDS IN ASSEMBLY OVERTHROW ATTEMPT
</HEADLINE>
 By RICHARD PEREZ-PENA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ The State Assembly suddenly dissolved into open
warfare Wednesday, as the second-ranking member, Michael J.
Bragman, announced he would try to overthrow Speaker Sheldon Silver
in a showdown vote Monday. The speaker retaliated by stripping
Bragman of his title of majority leader.
</P>
<P>
   The extraordinary turn of events _ the last overt attempt to
topple a speaker was in the 1960s _ left Democrats agog. Coming the
day after the party displayed a united front at its state
convention in nominating Hillary Rodham Clinton for the Senate,
this fight extends far beyond the walls of the Assembly chamber to
gubernatorial and regional politics.
</P>
<P>
   Silver may have hurt himself by trying to undermine State
Comptroller H. Carl McCall's undeclared candidacy for governor in
2002 and promoting Andrew Cuomo, the secretary of housing and urban
development. McCall has wide support among elected officials, and
he demonstrated his popularity Tuesday with a speech at the
Democratic convention that brought down the house.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, the election of Bragman, whose district is
near Syracuse, would be a seismic shift in tradition that has
dictated for generations that when the Democrats control the
Assembly, the speaker must be from New York City. Silver's defeat
would leave the Capitol's ruling troika, the governor and the
leaders of the Assembly and Senate, without a member from New York
City for the first time since 1974.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats frantically conducted head counts Wednesday, with many
acknowledging that their tallies were barely more accurate than a
reading of tea leaves, as fence sitters nervously tried to decide
which side to embrace. Most Democrats interviewed predicted that
Silver would survive, but few ruled out Bragman's chances,
especially if he won the support of the Republican minority in the
Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   Many Democrats said Bragman had hurt his chances by reaching out
to Republicans, an alliance many Democrats, including those with no
love for Silver, recoil from. At an impromptu news conference,
Bragman denied conspiring with Republicans or making them any
promises.
</P>
<P>
   Bragman said he had the support of most Democrats, who have a
98-to-52 advantage in the Assembly. ``We will call for a vote to
replace the speaker and to elect a new speaker,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Silver loyalists insisted that the speaker held control.
``The notion that the Democrats are dissatisfied with Shelly Silver
is hallucinatory,'' said Assemblyman Richard L. Brodsky, a
Westchester County Democrat. ``There's no rationale for the
candidacy, and no votes for it.''
</P>
<P>
   If Bragman can force a leadership vote _ a question in some
doubt _ it will be partly a referendum on Silver's ruling style,
which has been criticized as secretive and inclined to hoarding
power.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have felt for a long time that I am not as productive as I
could be, that whatever intelligence I may have, whatever talent I
may have, whatever energy I may have, is not being used
appropriately,'' said Assemblyman Martin A. Luster, a Democrat from
Ithaca who was one of the few to speak openly in favor of Bragman.
``More often than not, I feel more like an ornament standing around
at the speaker's press conferences.''
</P>
<P>
   Silver does not socialize much with the Assembly members, a fact
that produces some grumbling, while Bragman does. But Bragman is
not well liked either, having gained a reputation for hardball
tactics bordering on meanness.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are wary of Bragman, but he's perceived to be someone
you go to when you have a problem, you need a favor, you need
something to get fixed,'' said an Assembly member from New York
City who described himself as a fence sitter, leaning toward
Silver.
</P>
<P>
   ``But this is not just about being liked. This is also about
promises that are being made, about committee chairmanships, about
young careers getting fast-tracked, about pork spending in
individual districts.''
</P>
<P>
   Several officials said Bragman set the coup attempt in motion on
Tuesday, at the convention, perhaps emboldened by McCall's showing
and by Silver's being so wrapped up in organizing the event.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the timing was odd, and it perplexed many Assembly
members. Speakers are elected at the start of each two-year term,
and in some respects it is more difficult to replace one midterm.
</P>
<P>
   Usually, a speaker is chosen by the majority party's conference
in an informal closed session. When a candidate emerges with a
majority _ in this case, 50 of the 98 Democratic votes _ the
Assembly is convened and the entire party conference unites behind
that candidate in a formal vote.
</P>
<P>
   Bragman introduced a motion Wednesday to change the Assembly
rules to allow the removal of a speaker at any time. He said that
if the motion passed, he would then make a motion to remove Silver.
Silver's allies insisted he might be able to prevent a vote on the
rules change.
</P>
<P>
   Each motion requires 76 votes, a simple majority of the State
Assembly. Many Republicans, whose distaste for Silver is intense,
would surely go along. But relying heavily on Republican votes
could leave Bragman ruling through a rump Democratic faction, and
beholden to the Republicans.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
