<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-CHISOX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILLIAMS EXPLODES FOR TWO HOMERS AS YANKEES DOWN WHITE SOX
</HEADLINE>
  By JACK CURRY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Bernie Williams was still in his T-shirt and long
underwear when Chuck Knoblauch shouted across the clubhouse to tell
the cleanup hitter that he was batting second Wednesday night.
Williams did a double take, skipped a few steps to peek at the
lineup card posted on the clubhouse door and softly said, ``Cool.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams was happy to be hitting second for the first time this
season after Joe Torre juggled the lineup to try to spark a
moribund offense and find a suitable replacement for the injured
Derek Jeter. Torre decided that Williams could mimic Jeter and
moved him up in the batting order. The manager might consider
leaving Williams in that cozy spot for a while.
</P>
<P>
   The switch-hitting Williams hammered two homers, including a
grand slam, hitting one homer from each side of the plate, to help
the Yankees cruise to a 9-4 victory over the White Sox and end a
five-game losing streak. After managing 11 runs in their last five
games and not winning since Jeter left last Thursday's game with a
strained abdominal muscle, the Yankees erupted for almost as many
runs in one night, possibly pacifying the ever-antsy George
Steinbrenner.
</P>
<P>
   ``If things don't work one way, you got to try another way,''
Williams said before the game.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees did try another way and they could exhale after
finally ending their longest losing streak since last May. Roger
Clemens pitched like a stopper on a night on which he did not have
to be so dominating, holding the White Sox to two runs and four
hits in seven innings, while striking out nine, walking none and
tossing a tidy 87 pitches. But even if Clemens had pitched a
shutout, the focus was on the disappointing offense cranking for
one fun night.
</P>
<P>
   Torre said he was ``playing with things'' by moving Williams up
in the order, inserting Shane Spencer into the cleanup spot,
batting Jorge Posada fifth and using Tino Martinez in the sixth
position. Torre had toyed with moving Williams behind Chuck
Knoblauch and liked how Spencer had been swinging, so he tinkered
with the lineup against the left-handed Jim Parque and, presto, the
Yankees responded.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, who now has eight career grand slams, homered from
both sides of the plate for the sixth time in his career. Spencer
stroked three singles and Posada reached base three times.
Knoblauch and Paul O'Neill, who remained in their usual spots, also
played key roles. Knoblauch had two hits, scored twice and studied
plenty of pitches, and O'Neill had two doubles and also scored two
runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``All we need is one big inning,'' Knoblauch said before the
game. ``A few bloop hits. Something has to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, something did happen for the Yankees in the first
inning, and Knoblauch started it. He lashed a liner off first
baseman Paul Konerko's glove and raced to third with a tainted
triple as the ball rattled around right fielder Magglio Ordonez. It
was New York's first extra-base hit in 28 innings.
</P>
<P>
   Williams lined out to shortstop, but O'Neill slapped a double
past first base and into the seats along the right-field line.
Spencer, the cleanup man for the second time this season, punched a
single to right and Posada knocked in the second run with a
sacrifice fly to center. O'Neill doubled in the third, Posada
walked and they both scored when Chris Singleton misplayed Jim
Leyritz's liner to center field, putting the Yankees ahead, 4-0.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens was firing fastballs, getting ahead of hitters and doing
what the Yankees want and need him to do. Even after plunking Jose
Valentin in the first, which might have been payback for Clay
Bellinger getting hit on Monday, Clemens stranded him at second by
retiring Frank Thomas on a groundout and striking out Ordonez with
a split-finger fastball. He did not face more than four batters in
any inning and was bruised only by homers from Ordonez and Greg
Norton.
</P>
<P>
   Williams belted his first homer to left field off Parque in the
fourth to give Clemens a 5-0 edge and he followed that with a
towering grand slam to right field off Tanyon Sturtze in the fifth.
The Yankees had a 9-1 cushion, there were smiles in every corner of
the Stadium and Williams even jumped out of the dugout for a
curtain call. For Williams, that was cool. Just like batting
second.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
