r f BC-TOURISM-NUMBERS-SFCHR     05-17 0642
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOURISM-NUMBERS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 SAN FRANCISCO TOURISTS SPENDING HAPPILY  &HT;     By PETER SINTON 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ San Francisco likes to call itself ``everybody's
favorite city,'' and the latest tourist numbers seem to bear this
out.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors to San Francisco spent a record $6.55 billion in the
city last year, according to a new report from the San Francisco
Convention and Visitors Bureau, which sliced and diced the city's
biggest industry into an impressive statistical salad:
</P>
<P>
   Among the highlights:
</P>
<P>
   -- 16.8 million visitors came to San Francisco last year, 1.6
percent more than 1998.
</P>
<P>
   -- An average of 146,000 visitors spent $17.9 million a day in
the city.
</P>
<P>
   -- 35.1 percent of visitors stay at local hotels and spend an
average of $233 a day.
</P>
<P>
   -- Hotel occupancy was 80.7 percent in San Francisco last year,
13 percent ahead of the national average, according to PKF
Consulting. (Only Las Vegas and New York have higher occupancy
rates.)
</P>
<P>
   -- In the first quarter 2000, hotel occupancy was 7.6 percent
ahead of the same period last year, and average daily room rates
are up 12.2 percent to more than $155 a night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tourism in San Francisco is at an all-time high,'' said John
Marks, president of the convention and visitors bureau.
</P>
<P>
   Not only that, but the city has an enviable well-balanced mix of
visitors: 37.6 percent are leisure travelers, 32.4 percent attend
convention or group meetings and 30 percent come for other
business.
</P>
<P>
   The best news, said Marks, is that 81 percent of 2,745 recently
surveyed guests to the city are repeat visitors, and 94 percent
said they would definitely come back. Five percent of respondents
said they didn't know if they would come back, and only 1 percent
said they would not return.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the ideal customer profile,'' added convention and
visitors bureau research manager David Bratton. ``Our average guest
is affluent, likes to spend, is satisfied and plans to return.''
</P>
<P>
   International travel to San Francisco increased 8 percent, to
2.9 million visitors, last year and accounted for 24 percent of all
San Francisco hotel guests. Only New York; Los Angeles; Miami; and
Orlando, Fla., receive more foreign travelers.
</P>
<P>
   In its recent survey, the bureau asked visitors what they liked
and didn't like about San Francisco. Marks said the remarks were
not tabulated because they were similar to responses in previous
surveys.
</P>
<P>
   ``To no one's surprise, everyone liked the ambience, the scenic
beauty, the dining, the cultural diversity,'' he said. ``What they
didn't like was street people, panhandlers, traffic and parking.''
</P>
<P>
   Tourists contacted at random by The Chronicle at the Cable Car
turnaround at Powell and Market streets Wednesday confirmed the
bureau's findings.
</P>
<P>
   Most visitors said they were having a good time but 13 of 20 (or
65 percent) said they were bothered by panhandlers and homeless
people.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Cuskley, who works for American Express Travel Services in
New York, complained that panhandlers are even more aggressive here
than in Manhattan. He said he offered $1 to one Tuesday night and
``the guy negotiated me up to $3.''
</P>
<P>
   Sue Tobler, who is visiting with her family from near Zurich,
Switzerland, said the homeless scene was ``a shock.'' And Steyn
Arild from Bergen, Norway, said he was appalled by the huge gap in
American society between ``the lowest of the low and all the people
at the top.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the few tourists who took the street people in stride was
Reg Smith, a psychiatrist who works at a hospital for the
criminally insane in Adelaide, Australia. Although Smith said his
wife and elderly parents were intimidated by local panhandlers, he
said philosophically, ``There are schizophrenics everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Peter Sinton at  &LR; psinton(AT)sfgate.com. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
