 BRONX SLAYING OF CABDRIVER IS NYC'S 10th FOR THIS YEAR  
 By C.J. CHIVERS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A young Cambodian immigrant who had just begun using
his car as a taxi was fatally shot early Wednesday morning in the
Bronx, becoming the 10th cabby to be slain while on duty in the
city this year.
</P>
<P>
   Police said the latest victim, Kim Hong Tim, 20, was driving his
black Acura Legend for the Preferred Luxury Car Service shortly
after midnight when the car crashed into a parked car at East 215th
Street and Barnes Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   A woman who called 911 at first said that Tim, who was found
lying on the pavement near the car, had been struck by the vehicle
and was having trouble breathing. Emergency workers later found
that he had been shot in the back and robbed, apparently before
stumbling from the driver's seat. He was pronounced dead at 12:35
a.m. at Montefiore Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   Tim, of the Bedford Park section of the Bronx, immigrated with
his parents and five siblings to the United States in 1982 from the
Cambodian city of Battambang, and grew up in the Bronx. He dropped
out of high school two years ago to marry.
</P>
<P>
   Tim's family said Wednesday that he had been laid off as a
security guard within the last week and had converted the family
car to a taxi to support his 2-year-old daughter, Aleena, and his
wife, Gia Lee Tim, who is six months pregnant. His car did not have
a bulletproof partition.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   His father, Sovann Tim, 56, said he did not know his son had
begun working as a cabby until he learned of his death.
</P>
<P>
   ``He never told me he was driving,'' he said. ``I feel like I
want to die. I want to die with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Tim's wife was inconsolable Wednesday when news of his death
reached her. ``She almost fainted,'' said Jenny Tim, 27, her
sister-in-law. ``She was crying uncontrollably until this
morning.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The killing of Tim was the latest in a series of attacks against
cabdrivers in the city. The deaths have prompted the city to
underwrite the purchase of bulletproof partitions for all livery
cabs, and the Police Department to deploy hundreds of extra
officers each night on cabby-protection assignments.
</P>
<P>
   While the authorities said Wednesday that Tim was not licensed
as a cabdriver, and his Acura was not registered with the city's
Taxi and Limousine Commission, he clearly was working as a cabby.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Nestor Rodriguez, a dispatcher at the Preferred Luxury Car
Service at 1067 White Plains Road, said Tim started a shift Tuesday
evening and spent the night ferrying passengers in the
neighborhood. His last call, which came about 11:30 p.m., was to
pick up a man on East 167th Street.
</P>
<P>
   Tim was not heard from again until 12:02 a.m., when the 911
caller reported the accident at East 215th Street.
</P>
<P>
   Police said the investigation was continuing, and declined to
discuss a report that a gang member had been involved. Sgt. Brian
Burke, a police spokesman, said detectives were looking for the
passenger Tim picked up at East 167th Street, and hoped to question
him.
</P>
<P>
   Police said Tim had been robbed of cash, his jewelry and a
two-way radio. Detectives also found a shell casing from a .380
semiautomatic pistol at the crime scene.
</P>
<P>
   Fernando A. Mateo, president of the New York State Federation of
Taxi Drivers, said he spent part of the morning with Tim's family.
He said that Tim was working in the taxi industry illegally and out
of desperation, trying to support his family, and fell victim to
the same sort of crime that had spread fear through the ranks of
livery cabbies this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly the person who did this meant to kill a livery cab
driver,'' Mateo said. ``There is no doubt about it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
