<SLUG> BC-MOM-ONLINE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 ONLINE SALES BLOOMED FOR MOTHER'S DAY  &HT;     By CAROLYN SAID 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Beset by admonitions that it's time to pull up
their socks, clean up their act and make something of themselves,
e-tailers this month found support and solace from the one person
who really cares: Mom.
</P>
<P>
   Online sales for Mother's Day soared to $190 million, up from
$14 million last year, according to BizRate.com. That's more than
double the $80 million that BizRate had predicted.
</P>
<P>
   The rating service, which tracks about 60 percent of e-commerce
sites, uses a methodology similar to political exit polls. It
surveys shoppers right after they've completed an online purchase,
then extrapolates results from that data.
</P>
<P>
   From May 1 to May 12, shoppers placed 2.9 million online orders,
up from 250,000 last year, with an average purchase price of $66,
BizRate said.
</P>
<P>
   The news gives the e-commerce segment validation after weeks of
battering in Wall Street and the press, and appears to show that
many consumers who first shopped on the Internet over Christmas
were satisfied enough to return.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a wake-up call for a lot of people, especially people
in the press, who've been bad-mouthing e-commerce,'' said Barry
Parr, director of consumer e-commerce research at IDC in Mountain
View, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a lot of hype and market overcrowding, online sales to
consumers are a huge market, Parr said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year consumers will spend $42 billion on the Internet
versus $26 billion last year,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Flowers, chocolates, jewelry, gifts and online greeting cards
were the most popular Mother's Day categories online.
</P>
<P>
   Visits to five top flower sites (1800flowers.com, Ftd.com,
Proflowers.com, PCFlowers.com and Virtualflowers.com) hit almost a
quarter of a million on Thursday, May 11, close to double from a
week before, according to Nielsen/NetRatings in Milpitas, Calif.
The firm measures Web-site traffic, not actual purchases.
</P>
<P>
   Flower-site traffic was significantly higher than for
Valentine's Day, even adjusting for a growth in Internet usage
between the two holidays.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your mom is more likely to live far away'' than your spouse or
sweetheart, said Lisa Strand, an Internet analyst with
Nielsen/NetRatings. While you might buy a bouquet from the local
flower shop for Valentine's Day, ``if you're not going to see the
actual bouquet for mom, you might as well buy it online because at
least you'll see a picture.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Ken Young, a spokesman for 1800flowers.com in Westbury,
N.Y., said, ``this is the busiest two-week period in the year.''
The company averaged 120,000 orders a day for the three days before
Mother's Day weekend, more than half of them online. That's almost
triple the online percentage from last year.
</P>
<P>
   Web sites had few problems handling the deluge of visitors,
according to San Mateo, Calif.'s Keynote Systems, which measures
Web site performance and availability.
</P>
<P>
   Keynote measured a dozen chocolate, flower and greeting card
sites and found that all had good performance, loading a page in
4.1 seconds or less, except for Proflowers.com (6.26 seconds) and
Chocoholic.com (43.85 seconds). The sites were available at least
96 percent of the time, except for Hallmark (91.1 percent),
Proflowers (91.7 percent) and Chocoholic (83.1 percent).
</P>
<P>
   Greeting card site traffic spiked on Mother's Day, when it was
too late to order anything else in time. ``If you're so lazy you
can't even go out and send a real card, you can cop out and go
online for an electronic card,'' said Gene Shklar, vice president
of public services at Keynote.
</P>
<P>
   Of course that only works if your mom is wired.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Carolyn Said at  &LR; csaid(AT)sfgate.com. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
