<HEADLINE>
CAMPAIGN NEWS AND NOTES FROM AROUND THE NATION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Colo, Ga., Ore., Conn., Ariz., Mont.)  c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUCHANAN RESIGNATION SOUGHT
</P>
<P>
   Reform Party leaders in Colorado and Georgia have called on Pat
Buchanan, the leading contender for the Reform presidential
nomination, to resign from the party on the ground that he has been
spreading hate and intolerance and ignoring the party procedures.
At a meeting last Saturday, the executive committee of the party in
Colorado passed a resolution saying that Buchanan was ``promoting
discrimination, intolerance and hatred against various groups of
law-abiding American citizens.'' In addition, it condemned remarks
attributed to Buchanan in which homosexuality was called a
disorder. ``We just don't have any room for intolerance,'' Victor
Good, the party chairman, said. The Reform Party in Georgia called
for Buchanan's resignation after he invited state residents to a
May 21 state convention that party leaders said was scheduled
illegally. Jim Mangia, secretary of the national Reform Party,
predicted that more states would move against Buchanan. Bay
Buchanan, Buchanan's sister and chief strategist, called the
Colorado and Georgia moves ``much ado about nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   BUSH ENDORSED AS REAGAN'S HEIR
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Reagan endorsed Gov. George W. Bush of Texas for president
Wednesday, claiming him as an heir to the conservative political
tradition of her husband, former President Ronald Reagan. ``His
agenda of tax cuts, smaller government and a strong national
defense will build pride in America just as it did when my husband
was president,'' Reagan said. ``This is a candidate Ronnie would be
proud of.'' Reagan, 89, has Alzheimer's disease and no longer makes
public appearances or statements. Nancy Reagan has offered her
endorsement of every Republican presidential candidate since her
husband left office in 1988. Bush proudly embraced the Reagan
mantle. ``I thank her for her endorsement and pledge an optimistic,
positive campaign, in the Reagan tradition, to renew America's
spirit and encourage a new era of personal responsibility and
freedom,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   THE VOTE IS IN THE MAIL
</P>
<P>
   Unable to affect the presidential nominating contests at this
late point, Oregon voters used Tuesday's vote-by-mail primary, the
nation's first, to reject ballot proposals calling for a new
gasoline tax and limits on damages in personal-injury lawsuits.
Oregon residents have voted by mail in local elections and special
statewide elections since the early 1980s, but they had never
before voted entirely by mail in a regularly scheduled election. A
footnote: Vice President Al Gore and Bush won going away, as
expected, not that it made any difference in the nominating
contests. And the turnout? The secretary of state's office put it
at 47 percent, the highest since the 1992 primary, when turnout hit
49.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN FINANCING LOOPHOLE
</P>
<P>
   A bipartisan group of senators introduced legislation Wednesday
to close a loophole in federal tax and election law that allows
nonprofit groups to raise and spend unlimited amounts of money on
political campaigns with virtually no disclosure. Organizations
like the Sierra Club and the Republicans for Clean Air have taken
advantage of the provision, Section 527 of the Internal Revenue
Code, to raise and spend millions of dollars on behalf of
candidates. They can run television advertisements and conduct
telephone campaigns as long as they do not explicitly advocate the
election or defeat of a candidate. The proposed legislation,
similar to a bill already before the House, would require that such
groups register with the Federal Election Commission and comply
with federal election laws. It also would require that they
disclose their existence to the Internal Revenue Service and that
they reveal their large contributors and expenditures. One of the
sponsors of the Senate bill, Sen. Joseph Lieberman, D-Conn., said
that passage of the measure would ``remove 527s from the shadows
and expose their activities to the light of public scrutiny.'' Sen.
John McCain, R-Ariz., another sponsor and longtime advocate of
campaign finance reform, called the proliferation of 527
organizations ``a pernicious evil'' that has helped bring U.S.
politics to an all-time low.
</P>
<P>
   LIBYAN INNUENDO
</P>
<P>
   With an uphill battle to keep Sen. Conrad Burns, R-Mont., from
winning a third term, Brian Schweitzer, a Democratic challenger,
has found another obstacle to overcome. Schweitzer said this week
that the same phone bank company that made negative calls against
McCain before the Republican presidential primary in South Carolina
was making calls to Montana on behalf of Burns. Schweitzer said a
Houston firm, Voter Consumer Research, asked Montana voters if they
had been aware that Schweitzer had once worked in Libya, ``a known
terrorist state.'' Yes, he did once work in Libya, Schweitzer said,
in 1980, as an importer of U.S.-made farm equipment for farms being
worked by Americans. And if there was something wrong with that, he
went on, ``whoever is paying for this dirty trick push poll needs a
civics lesson.'' Well, it was not the Burns campaign, said Tricia
Pearson, the campaign coordinator. ``We're not doing it,'' she
said. ``We don't know anything about it.''THURSDAY'S SCHEDULES
</P>
<P>
   GEORGE W. BUSH: Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   AL GORE: Washington
</P>
</TEXT>
