r f BC-STAFFORD-COLUMN-KAN &LR;      05-17 0536
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAFFORD-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OF MONEY SAVED AND LESSONS LEARNED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE STAFFORD  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Undated) Expect change. Don't be afraid of it. Adapt to it.
Enjoy it. And, sometimes, seek it out.
</P>
<P>
   Astute readers of Who Moved My Cheese? will recognize the plot
line. That's it. That's all there is to it.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, you'd expect more from one of the best-selling
motivational books of the past 12 months.
</P>
<P>
   The little _ and I mean little _ book by Spencer Johnson is
subtitled An A-Mazing Way to Deal With Change in Your Work and in
Your Life. In it, four characters _ two mice and two inexplicably
mouse-size ``littlepeople'' _ react to the loss of their
longstanding storehouse of cheese in different ways.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, one mostly fails to react except to grouse about it.
The three others (in one case after an agonizingly prolonged and
self-reflective effort) manage to find new cheese somewhere else in
their maze.
</P>
<P>
   The book's blurbs and foreword helpfully emphasize that
``cheese'' is a metaphor for whatever you want to have in life. No
doubt the metaphor has clubbed you till it hurts already.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the tiny story's hammering simplicity has made the $19.95,
94-page hardback fly off the bookshelves. Why?
</P>
<P>
   Not even a gracious and heartfelt introduction by business
motivational speaker Ken Blanchard, who previously co-wrote The One
Minute Manager with Johnson, convinces me that Who Moved My Cheese
deserves its moment of fame.
</P>
<P>
   The slim volume is slim pickings. It's a lot like the equally
best-selling bit of nonfiction Tuesdays With Morrie, which to my
mind is a crass exploitation of a good man's final days by someone
who came late to the human decency party.
</P>
<P>
   Are they popular because they're short and people are desperate
for quick fixes to whatever ails them?
</P>
<P>
   Are they popular because they give permission to be responsible
for yourself and your own attitude in a ``woe is me, the poor and
powerless victim'' world?
</P>
<P>
   I don't know.
</P>
<P>
   Cheese's book jacket and flyleaves are padded with testimonials
from business titans. A few say it helped them accept and deal with
change. Most of them, though, say they're giving the book to others
_ family, friends, work teams, management teams, subordinates and
so forth _ to help them cope. Funny how that works.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past five years on the workplace beat, I've attended a
lot of motivational and training seminars. I've heard the big names
in the American success industry _ Covey, Peters, Nelson,
Blanchard, Ziglar and more _ share their ``secrets'' for
prospering.
</P>
<P>
   No matter what their particular shtick, there are two common
themes at their presentations.
</P>
<P>
   One: An attendee always stands up and says, ``I get it, but how
do I get my boss (or my company) to get it?'' To which the speaker
always responds something like: ``You can't change your boss (or
your company). You can only change your reactions to
him//her//them//it.''
</P>
<P>
   And two: The speaker always, always, always says something to
the effect of, ``Expect change. Don't be afraid of it. Adapt to it.
Enjoy it. And, sometimes, seek it out.''
</P>
<P>
   There. You just saved $19.95.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
