<SLUG> BC-RAILWAY-KILLER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JURY BEGINS DELIBERATIONS IN MATURINO RESENDIZ CASE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By LISA TEACHEY 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ A jury deliberated eight hours before being
sequestered Wednesday in the capital murder trial of Angel Maturino
Resendiz, who has admitted to killing nine people in three states.
</P>
<P>
   The jury will resume deliberations Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Maturino Resendiz, 40, charged with killing Dr. Claudia Benton
on Dec. 17, 1998, has pleaded not guilty by reason of insanity,
claiming ``evil forces'' had drawn him to her West University home
near Houston and told him it was God's will that he kill her.
</P>
<P>
   While deliberating, the panel asked to review all the physical
evidence, including letters Maturino Resendiz wrote after he was
arrested. They were given the evidence.
</P>
<P>
   They also asked to review all the testimony from an FBI
profiler, but Harmon said they could be given only the specific
part that is in dispute.
</P>
<P>
   The punishment phase will begin after the verdict is reached,
with at least two days of testimony expected. Maturino Resendiz
could be sentenced to death by injection or get life in prison with
no parole for 40 years.
</P>
<P>
   As proceedings began Wednesday, Maturino Resendiz, who has shown
no emotion through most of the trial, turned to his mother in the
audience and smiled thinly.
</P>
<P>
   The defense conceded the drifter from Mexico had killed all nine
people, but argued that he had been driven by paranoid
schizophrenia and a delusion that he is ``half angel, half man.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The defendant's mind is twisted,'' defense attorney Allen
Tanner told jurors. ``He is a sick, sick man.''
</P>
<P>
   Two defense experts, a psychiatrist and a psychologist,
diagnosed schizophrenia after Maturino Resendiz surrendered to a
Texas Ranger at the Mexican border in July.
</P>
<P>
   Virginia Maturino Resendiz testified that her newborn son landed
on his head when she stood up during delivery. As a child, she
said, his head was also damaged in a fight and in a fall.
</P>
<P>
   He grew up without a father, the defense said. He also suffered
brain damage from years of drug abuse, mostly sniffing
industrial-strength glue.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know what happened to Angel Resendiz that made him
turn out what he became,'' Tanner said. ``We don't know where the
hatred comes from.''
</P>
<P>
   Tanner said it was during a prison stay in 1979 _ after Maturino
Resendiz was convicted of breaking into a man's home and beating
him _ that he began reading the Bible, came to believe he had a
special relationship with God and developed an intense hatred for
abortionists and homosexuals.
</P>
<P>
   Becoming more delusional, he began thinking of himself as an
``angel of wrath,'' able to cause floods, earthquakes and evade
police by becoming invisible, his lawyer said.
</P>
<P>
   Then he developed a sense for detecting evil and that drew him
to his victims, Tanner said. In Benton's case, he imagined he saw
pictures of fetuses on her computer and inferred that she was
experimenting on babies.
</P>
<P>
   In the crime scene photos, the computer screen displays only a
report that Benton, a pediatric geneticist, was working on.
</P>
<P>
   Maturino Resendiz said he used a statue he found in the house to
bludgeon her because he thought she worshipped idols.
</P>
<P>
   A pathologist testified that Benton fought for her life while
being beaten and stabbed. She was raped as she lay dying.
</P>
<P>
   Before surrendering last summer, Tanner said, Maturino Resendiz
told his brother to turn him in because he ``couldn't be
responsible.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He knew he was sick,'' Tanner said. ``He knew what he was
doing was illegal ... but he was answering to a higher power. In
his mind he thought what he was doing was the right thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   But two prosecution experts said Maturino Resendiz suffers only
from depression, though he has personality disorders and some weird
religious beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   One expert, a jail psychiatrist, found Maturino Resendiz showed
no signs of delusions until he was moved into the general jail
population. There, he was given anti-psychotic drugs, which he
still takes. The doctor said a paranoid schizophrenic's symptoms
would take much longer to control with drug therapy.
</P>
<P>
   In his closing, prosecutor Lyn McClellan countered that Tanner
was simply playing on words with the argument ``that illegal is not
wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   In Texas, jurors can only find someone insane if they believe
that at the time of the crime the person suffered a severe mental
disease or defect that prevented him from knowing the actions were
wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``Use your common sense,'' McClellan said. ``Anti-social
behavior is not a mental disease. ... He was motivated by anger, by
power, by a desire for sex. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``The defendant does suffer from one delusion, and the delusion
he has is that he will be able to convince one of you he's
insane.''
</P>
<P>
   McClellan also reminded jurors that while imprisoned in Florida
in 1990, Maturino Resendiz wrote insanity arguments for other
inmates to use in trying to overturn their convictions.
</P>
<P>
   And, McClellan stressed, Maturino Resendiz didn't start killing
until after he had been sent to jail by the testimony of two
victims.
</P>
<P>
   ``He learned don't ever leave them alive because they can come
back and identify you,'' McClellan said.
</P>
<P>
   District Attorney John B. Holmes Jr. was the last to speak to
jurors. ``Please don't let this man deceive again,'' he implored
them. ``He's a cold-blooded killer.''
</P>
<P>
   Holmes told the jury that many people have mental diseases but
don't turn to crime, and that insanity is a legal term, not a
medical condition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, Virginia,'' he said, ``there are mean people in this
world who aren't crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
