r f BC-SCOUR-NAPSTER-SFCHRON     05-17 1107
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOUR-NAPSTER-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 SCOUR EXPANDS NAPSTER'S CONCEPT BEYOND SWAPPING MUSIC  &HT;     By BENNY EVANGELISTA 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Napster's huge underground success has unleashed
the maverick concept of creating a shared online library of free
songs.
</P>
<P>
   Now, a new program called Scour Exchange takes the Napster
concept and extends it to photos, videos and feature-length films.
</P>
<P>
   So in addition to downloading hits by Metallica and Dr. Dre,
both of whom have sued Napster, Scour Exchange will give users
access to bootlegged versions of recent movies like ``American
Beauty'' and ``Romeo Must Die.''
</P>
<P>
   But Scour ( &LR; www.scour.com &LR; ), the Beverly Hills, Calif., company
that produced Scour Exchange, is trying to steer clear of digital
pirates and does offer a large array of legally licensed
downloadable music, music videos, movie trailers and photos.
</P>
<P>
   The company is instead hoping to gain long-term commercial
success by landing legitimate licensing and syndication deals with
the same entertainment industry giants that consider San Mateo,
Calif.,'s Napster public enemy No. 1.
</P>
<P>
   And unlike Napster, Scour already has the backing of one of the
biggest names in the world of entertainment _ Hollywood super agent
and onetime top Disney executive Michael Ovitz.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't intend to take an antagonistic approach with the
industry,'' said Dan Rodrigues, Scour's 24-year-old president and
co-founder. ``In the long term, we have to make it work for the
industry.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're working really closely with the record labels, using
licensed content to showcase a lot of legitimate uses of this
technology,'' he said. ``What we're going to do is try to find a
model that makes all sides happy.''
</P>
<P>
   In just four weeks since its beta version was released in April,
the free Scour Exchange search program has been downloaded by about
500,000 people who are sharing about 1 million files, Rodrigues
said.
</P>
<P>
   At one point Tuesday night, there were 7,150 Scour users logged
on sharing 2.77 terabytes worth of files. That's comparable to the
number of files Napster users have at their disposal at any one
time. While there are far more Napster users, Napster routes its
members through different servers, while Scour users have access to
the files of all Scour members who are logged on at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   Napster and Scour Exchange are similar because the programs
allow members to quickly search for downloadable files stored on
the hard drives of other members. The files can then be transferred
directly from computer to computer.
</P>
<P>
   Scour Exchange, though, can also search for other multimedia
files. During a test, a Chronicle reporter was able download and
watch the Jet Li flick ``Romeo Must Die'' converted into the
Windows Media Technologies format. The video was jumpy but
watchable, although the movie took about three hours to download
using a high-speed cable modem and ate up about 500 MB of hard disk
space.
</P>
<P>
   But Rodrigues said Scour is trying to discourage piracy, saying
the company is being ``more diligent'' about giving the boot to
Scour users who are offering files that infringe on copyright laws.
Scour has a ``three strikes'' policy designed to permanently ban
repeat offenders, although only a handful have been banned.
</P>
<P>
   And Rodrigues said Scour has rounded up partnerships with other
online music companies, such as MP3.com and EMusic.com, and
expanded its offerings to include Internet radio broadcasts ``so we
can be the one-stop aggregator of content.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the company is courting record and film industry
executives to use Scour's search program and Web site as a
promotional tool and, eventually, a new method to distribute
licensed entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   Scour recently scored a deal with Dimension Films, a division of
Miramax Films, to become the exclusive Internet distributor for the
promotional trailer to the upcoming thriller movie spoof ``Scary
Movie.'' More than 30,000 copies of the ``Scary Movie'' trailer
have been downloaded since late April.
</P>
<P>
   By Hollywood standards, the Dimension Films deal was small
potatoes, but it was a big deal for the small company once called
Scour.Net, which was founded in December 1997 by Rodrigues and four
other University of California at Los Angeles computer science
students.
</P>
<P>
   With the MP3 search engine they designed, the students moved
from the dorms to a small two-bedroom apartment near the campus. By
the end of 1998, the Scour.Net Web site was getting 1 million
unique visitors per month, and that traffic doubled in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   In early 1999, the founders met Ovitz, the onetime president of
the Walt Disney Co., who was looking to make investments in
Internet companies through his venture capital firm the Yucaipa
Cos., which invested $4 million to gain a 51 percent stake in
Scour.
</P>
<P>
   Besides allowing Scour to move out of the apartment and into a
real office, Rodrigues said Ovitz is helping open doors in the
entertainment industry. ``He's talking to a lot of people for us,''
Rodrigues said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to get entertainment companies to test the water,''
Rodrigues said. ``Napster has shown the viral power of sharing
entertainment. The next step is to transition to a model where
everybody has the incentive to participate.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether Scour is able to find that model is unclear. But a new
study by online research firm Webnoize showed 42 percent of college
students who use Napster would be willing to pay a $15 per month
subscription to use a fully sanctioned version of the program.
</P>
<P>
   And the survey showed students who spent $50 a month on music
were just as likely to use Napster as students who spent $10 a
month, said Ric Dube, an analyst for Webnoize.
</P>
<P>
   The data points to a potentially ripe market of music fans who
would pay for legal, downloadable music or other entertainment
through subscriptions or other means that have yet to be tried,
Dube said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe Scour is the sleeper company, the one that comes from
behind to lead the charge for file swapping,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Analyst Malcolm Maclachlan of International Data Corp. was less
optimistic that the traditional record companies will embrace a
so-called ``legal Napster.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't fit neatly into the traditional record industry way
of doing things,'' Maclachlan said.
</P>
<P>
   Rodrigues isn't expecting an immediate sea change.
</P>
<P>
   ``This revolution that's going on in entertainment is a very
empowering thing,'' Rodrigues said. But, he added, ``It's going to
be a long process. I don't think it's going to happen overnight.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Benny Evangelista at  &LR; bennye(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
