<HEADLINE>
LEITER, PLAYING THE ROLE OF ACE, MOVES TO 5-0 AS METS TOP ROCKIES
</HEADLINE>
  By TYLER KEPNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Al Leiter never quite fit as the New York Mets' ace
last season, and he seemed to know it. He had moments _ beating the
Yankees in a critical game in June, shutting out the Reds in
October to clinch a playoff berth _ but when the Mets acquired Mike
Hampton last winter, it relieved Leiter of a burden.
</P>
<P>
   It turns out this is the season in which the ace tag fits.
Hampton is pitching better lately, and he is unquestioned as the
Mets' No. 1 starter. But whenever Leiter has pitched, the Mets have
won, and they did it again Wednesday night by beating the Colorado
Rockies, 4-2, at Shea Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Leiter's confidence is soaring now. Through eight starts, he is
5-0 with a 3.24 earned run average. He was overpowering at times
Wednesday night, recording at least one strikeout in seven of his
eight innings. He allowed five hits and two runs, walking two with
nine strikeouts. John Franco pitched a scoreless ninth for his
second save.
</P>
<P>
   Leiter's first eight starts were much different last season: he
had an 0-4 record and a 6.12 ERA. He had just been rewarded with a
four-year, $32 million contract, and he pressed, letting one bad
start affect his next outing and his confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless there's something wrong with you physically, it's
between the ears,'' Leiter said last week, referring to last
season. ``Even though we get paid for what we do, players lose
confidence, your self-esteem drops, and before you know it, you're
playing accordingly.''
</P>
<P>
   Manager Bobby Valentine said he could not remember much about
Leiter's struggles early last season, and he would not make a
comparison to his performance this year. But he did refer to
Leiter's mind-set in explaining his recent success.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's going out with confidence and throwing all of his
pitches,'' Valentine said before Wednesday night's game. ``He's
very relaxed out of the stretch as well as out of the windup.''
</P>
<P>
   Leiter has been especially effective this year pitching out of
the stretch. Coming into the game, he had allowed opponents only
seven hits in 47 at-bats with runners in scoring position, a .149
average.
</P>
<P>
   Leiter squelched a two-out rally in the second by getting Neifi
Perez to pop out with runners on first and second. But in the
third, the Rockies put together consecutive hits with men in
scoring position to take a 2-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Leiter swiped at the dirt on the mound after issuing a walk to
Brian Hunter with one out in that inning. Hunter does not walk
often but is dangerous when he gets on base. But it was the next
hitter, Mike Lansing, who stole second after reaching on a
fielder's choice.
</P>
<P>
   Lansing reached by grounding to first baseman Todd Zeile, who
fired wide of second base in an attempt to force Hunter. Shortstop
Rey Ordonez stretched to his right for the catch, falling to the
ground and bobbling it before securing it for the force. But there
was no time for a double play, and the next hitter, Jeff Cirillo,
looped a cutter into the left-field corner for a run-scoring
double.
</P>
<P>
   That gave the Rockies a 1-0 lead. They increased it to 2-0 one
batter later, when Jeffrey Hammonds lined a single to left. Lansing
scored from first when Benny Agbayani's throw bounced twice before
reaching catcher Mike Piazza.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets, meanwhile, were having trouble converting scoring
chances off Colorado's Rolando Arrojo. In the third inning,
Agbayani, Ordonez and Joe McEwing all singled off Arrojo the
opposite way, to right field, producing the Mets' first run. Derek
Bell walked to load the bases.
</P>
<P>
   That brought up the middle of the Mets' order, with a chance to
overcome the 2-1 deficit. But Edgardo Alfonzo struck, and after
getting ahead 3-0, Piazza popped to right to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets left runners in scoring position in each of the next
four innings, but one big hit gave them the lead in the fifth. With
two out, Alfonzo walked and Piazza singled, bringing up Robin
Ventura, who had lined out to first two times.
</P>
<P>
   Ventura pulled it again this time, but he lifted the ball,
knocking it into the right-field corner. Two runs scored _
including Piazza from first, standing _ and the Mets had a 3-2 lead
and all the runs Leiter needed. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
