<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOTHEBYS-AUCTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOTHEBY'S CONTEMPORARY ART AUCTION TOPS EXPECTATIONS
</HEADLINE>
 By CAROL VOGEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the elevator at Sotheby's after Wednesday night's sale of
contemporary art, two collectors were bemoaning all the things they
didn't buy last year. While prices just six months ago may have
seemed too expensive, compared to Wednesday's prices they were a
veritable bargain.
</P>
<P>
   Bidding on contemporary art of all periods, tastes and styles
was fast and furious, often exceeding the heady prices of the 1980s
art boom. The sale totaled $46 million, above its high estimate of
$41 million. Of the 70 works offered, only three failed to sell.
</P>
<P>
   How long until the bubble bursts?
</P>
<P>
   ``We keep asking ourselves that,'' said Diane Upright, a former
head of contemporary art at Christie's who is now a private dealer
in Manhattan. ``This sale showed both sides of the contemporary-art
market: it's not just young blood going after young art, but what
Alan Greenspan calls irrational exuberance.''
</P>
<P>
   The sale set records for 17 artists, including modern masters
like Mark Rothko, Clyfford Still and Bruce Nauman.
</P>
<P>
   By far the star of the evening, however, was Rothko's ``Yellow
Over Purple'' (1956), one of the artist's abstract canvases. It was
being sold from the Morton G. Neumann Family Collection, having
been on exhibition at the National Gallery of Art in Washington in
1980 and 1981. Sotheby's had offered the Neumann family a
guarantee, an undisclosed minimum price that an auction house
promises the seller regardless of the sale's outcome. After three
telephone bidders vied for it, the painting sold to an unidentified
collector for $14.3 million, sailing above its high estimate of $9
million.
</P>
<P>
   The sale featured eight Warhols, of which three were in the top
10 selling works. Two of the eight were being sold by S. I.
Newhouse Jr., the publishing magnate.
</P>
<P>
   Among the best was Mr. Newhouse's ``Natalie Wood,'' a 1963
overlapping grid of images of the movie star. Three bidders tried
for it, and the painting finally sold for $2.7 million, nearly
twice its high estimate of $1.5 million, to an unidentified German
bidder standing in the back of the salesroom. A Warhol watercolor
also sold by Mr. Newhouse, ``One Dollar'' (1961), also nearly
doubled its high estimate, selling to an unidentified telephone
bidder for $489,750.
</P>
<P>
   Far more expensive were ``Mona Lisa-Four Times,'' a 1978
silkscreen that brought $830,700, just over its high estimate of
$800,000, and one of the artist's classic ``Flowers'' silkscreens.
This one, from 1964, was being sold by Senator Frank R. Lautenberg
of New Jersey. It went to an unidentified telephone bidder for
$830,750, far above its high estimate of $600,000.
</P>
<P>
   (Final prices include Sotheby's commission: 20 percent of the
first $15,000, 15 percent of the next $85,000, and 10 percent of
any amount over $100,000. Estimates do not reflect commissions.)
</P>
<P>
   Fashionable artists like the 1980s art star Jeff Koons were also
represented. Mr. Koons' ``Yorkshire Terriers,'' a 1991 wood
sculpture, was expected to sell for $120,000 to $180,000; an
unidentified bidder bought it for $258,750. But the other work by
Mr. Koons offered did not fare so well. ``Wall Relief With Bird''
(1991), a sculpture of candy-colored flowers from the artist's
``Made in Heaven'' series, was expected to fetch $500,000 to
$700,000; Anthony d'Offay, the London dealer, bought it for
$610,750.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
