<SLUG> BC-RESEARCH-PARTNERS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOSPITAL, INSTITUTE JOIN TOGETHER FOR RESEARCH ON CHILDREN'S
HEALTH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALAN BAVLEY  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Children's Mercy Hospital and the Midwest
Research Institute on Wednesday announced sweeping plans to
collaborate on children's health research.
</P>
<P>
   Under the new partnership, called the Research Alliance for
Children's Health, or REACH, the institutions will share
facilities, bid jointly for government grants and private industry
contracts and provide new training opportunities for students and
researchers.
</P>
<P>
   They also will work together on commercial development of drugs
and other medical products they discover.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have technology we'll never develop here, and we can
provide clinical experience they don't have,'' said Ralph Kauffman,
director of medical research at Children's Mercy.
</P>
<P>
   The collaboration is the most recent step taken by Kansas City
area research institutions and civic leaders to make the region a
center for life-sciences research.
</P>
<P>
   The endeavor has been spurred by development of the richly
endowed Stowers Institute for Medical Research next to the
University of Missouri-Kansas City campus.
</P>
<P>
   Founded in 1944, Midwest Research conducts a broad range of
applied research on agriculture, energy and health for government
and industry.
</P>
<P>
   Children's Mercy has bolstered its research capabilities for the
past decade in such areas as genetics, immunology and pharmacology.
</P>
<P>
   The hospital and the institute have collaborated in the past,
but on an ad hoc basis, said James Spigarelli, Midwest Research
president.
</P>
<P>
   For example, institute computer experts have been working with
nursing researchers at Children's Mercy to develop a computer
program to monitor quality of care at the hospital. And Children's
Mercy allergy researchers have used air-sampling equipment
developed by the institute to test air quality.
</P>
<P>
   The new partnership will expand these efforts, Spigarelli said.
</P>
<P>
   Among the most likely collaborations by the institute and
hospital will be projects to develop new drugs for children. The
institute would conduct the laboratory analysis of drugs and test
them on animals, while Children's Mercy would test them on
patients.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pharmaceutical industry can look to Kansas City and say,
`Here's a one-stop shop,' &UR; '' said Children's Mercy President
Randall O'Donnell.
</P>
<P>
   Children's Mercy and Midwest Research also plan joint training
programs, including post-doctoral fellowships for scientists and
internships for Children's Mercy residents and faculty seeking
technical training at the institute.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
