<SLUG> BC-BBN-FITEFOLO-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASEBALL LOOKING INTO WRIGLEY FRAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Several members of the Los Angeles Dodgers could be
suspended and/or fined when Major League Baseball concludes its
investigation into the team's Tuesday-night melee with Wrigley
Field fans.
</P>
<P>
   The fight began when catcher Chad Kreuter was allegedly struck
in the back of the head by a fan and had his hat taken. Kreuter and
other Dodgers then went into the stands, breaking the imaginary
barrier between the field and seating area.
</P>
<P>
   The harshest penalty could come to Kreuter since he was the
first to enter the stands.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's black and white in one respect, in people are on the
right side of the fence or the wrong side of the fence,'' said
Sandy Alderson, executive vice president of baseball operations for
the office of the commissioner. ``If a uniformed person is in the
stands, there's a presumption of being on the wrong side.''
</P>
<P>
   When Alderson was asked if he agreed with the presumption, he
said, ``Yes.''
</P>
<P>
   The on-field investigation is being handled by Frank Robinson,
vice president of on-field operations for baseball. Sources said
Kreuter told Robinson via telephone Wednesday he didn't plan on
going into the stands, but the fan who allegedly hit him and
grabbed his hat, tripped and fell after a few steps.
</P>
<P>
   Kreuter also told Robinson he thought he would be able to detain
the fan until security arrived, but when he entered the stands
several other fans began hitting him.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson also spoke with Dodgers manager Davey Johnson and Cubs
manager Don Baylor.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Robinson) wanted to know about the incident, what I saw, what
happened, how many players were involved,'' Baylor said. ``I just
told him I saw a lot of gray shirts in the stands. It got ugly.''
</P>
<P>
   Alderson said a decision could be reached by the end of the
week, but the review of the incident will take time. Robinson spent
his day working on the case.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Major League Baseball Commissioner Bud Selig nor
Robinson returned repeated phone calls to the Daily News.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't encourage what happened, we're not happy it
happened,'' Dodgers general manager Kevin Malone said. ``I'm glad
the players rallied around each other. Even though it's
self-protection, I don't encourage it and we don't condone it. The
Dodgers don't condone what happened. You shouldn't go into the
stands, but I think for security purposes, Chad was going to go in
the stands to prevent the fan from running off after he got hit.''
</P>
<P>
   Kreuter, at the urging of the Dodgers, declined comment because
of possible litigation and suspensions stemming from the incident.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody attacks you from behind, a lot of times you don't
think about it, you react,'' Johnson said. ``I don't condone
players going into the stands, or fans making contact with players
in general.''
</P>
<P>
   The incident occurred with one out in the bottom of the ninth of
the Dodgers' 6-5 win against the Cubs on Tuesday. Many members of
the Dodgers, including manager Davey Johnson, said the mayhem began
when a fan allegedly hit Kreuter in the back of his head and
grabbed his hat.
</P>
<P>
   While Kreuter was in the stands, several members of the bullpen,
including coach Rick Dempsey, went in to try and bring Kreuter back
onto the field. At that point, the players on the field and
everyone in the dugout ran down to the bullpen, situated along the
right-field line.
</P>
<P>
   The melee lasted nine minutes. Malone expressed concern over how
long it took security personnel to reach the scene. Malone added
that the problem, he believed, came about because of intoxicated
fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's get to the real issue, it's public intoxication. If they
weren't drunk, this wouldn't have happened,'' Malone said. ``It's
not the Cubs, it's not Wrigley Field, it's an industry-wide
problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark McGuire, Cubs executive vice president of business
operations, said the person who allegedly hit Kreuter and took his
hat was not caught. However, three fans residing in Illinois were
arrested for disorderly conduct. They are each scheduled to appear
in City Court June 19 and are subject to a $750 fine, police said.
</P>
<P>
   The Chicago Police Department said the arrests were misdemeanor
violations and no counter complaints were made against Dodgers
players.
</P>
<P>
   Wrigley Field security was intensified in the area near the
Dodgers' bullpen for Wednesday's game, including uniformed and
nonuniformed personnel, according to McGuire.
</P>
<P>
   McGuire said the Cubs did their own investigation of the
incident but couldn't determine if Kreuter was hit before his hat
was taken.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel we had quite a bit of personnel in the area, and had
we not had players in the stands, it certainly would have been
easier to gain control,'' McGuire said. ``If players go into the
stands, it gets raised to a different level. Then, anyone in the
crowd management business will tell you that it's a much, much more
difficult undertaking.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
