<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NY-SCHOOLS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: FRESH LEADERSHIP FOR NEW YORK SCHOOLS
</HEADLINE>
  c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Thursday, May 18:
</P>
<P>
   The New York City Board of Education made the only sensible call
Wednesday when it promoted Harold Levy from interim chancellor to
permanent chancellor. Mayor Rudolph Giuliani had little choice but
to go along with the decision. With a majority of the board
supporting the interim chancellor, City Hall's appointees could not
have blocked the appointment. The mayor would have risked voter
disapproval and political embarrassment had they tried. Even so,
Wednesday's unanimous vote brings a welcome end to the uncertainty
and political infighting that have dominated the school system
since the former chancellor, Rudy Crew, was forced out by the mayor
in January.
</P>
<P>
   During his four months on the job, Levy has shown impressive
management and personnel skills, as well as imagination and energy.
Now he must apply those skills to the more difficult challenges
ahead. He must, for starters, ensure that the critical summer
session runs smoothly and upgrades the performance of thousands of
children in danger of failing. Even more important, he must make
certain that the schools they return to in the fall have
better-prepared teachers and smaller classes.
</P>
<P>
   The need for more-qualified teachers is particularly pressing in
low-performing schools, where the least experienced teachers are
being required to do the most difficult jobs of all. Levy will need
to negotiate a more flexible teachers' contract so that capable
teachers can be shifted where needed, and he should develop a bold
new certification program that will allow the system to recruit and
train talented teachers from the business and professional world.
</P>
<P>
   Other key tasks include holding principals and superintendents
accountable for their schools' performance, streamlining the
bloated bureaucracy at the Board of Education headquarters and
repairing the city's crumbling and sometimes dangerous school
buildings. Levy has gotten a jump on this last problem by sitting
as a trustee on the board of the School Construction Authority
instead of appointing a surrogate, as previous chancellors have
done. As the system gets better at building and repair, the case
for more money will be easier to make in Albany.
</P>
<P>
   If all these tasks are carried out expeditiously, the chancellor
will have a fighting chance to reach the most important goal of all
_ upgrading the performance of the system's students.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-17-00 2321EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
