<HEADER>
A8524 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-ALA-CHURCH-NYT &LR;      05-17 0637
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-ALA-CHURCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: ALABAMA'S LONG SEARCH FOR JUSTICE 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Thursday, May 18:
</P>
<P>
   A new generation of Southern prosecutors has shown laudable
persistence in reopening the investigations of Ku Klux Klansmen and
other white racists suspected of civil rights killings in the
1960s. In the past decade, Mississippi authorities secured
convictions in the murders of two of that state's black civil
rights pioneers, Medgar Evers and Vernon Dahmer. Wednesday, Doug
Jones, the U.S. attorney in Birmingham, Ala., and David Barber, the
local district attorney, revealed the murder indictments of two
former Klansmen in one of the era's most heinous crimes, the
Birmingham church bombing that killed four black girls on Sept. 15,
1963.
</P>
<P>
   Without prejudging the cases, it seems clear that authorities
are armed with both determination and new information. As early as
1964, the indicted men, Bobby Frank Cherry and Thomas Blanton Jr.,
were identified in FBI files as having helped a well-known
Birmingham racist, the late Robert ``Dynamite Bob'' Chambliss,
place the bomb at 16th Street Baptist Church in the predawn
darkness of a Sunday morning. Chambliss was finally convicted of
murder in 1977, but Alabama authorities felt their cases against
Cherry, Blanton and a third Klansman, now deceased, were not as
strong.
</P>
<P>
   According to The Jackson Clarion-Ledger, which has followed the
new prosecutions in Alabama and Mississippi, Cherry's former wife
and a granddaughter have now come forward to say they heard him
admit participation in the bombing. Testimony at the Chambliss
trial placed Blanton's car at the scene of the crime, but it is not
clear what additional grand jury testimony may have led to his
indictment. Both men have professed their innocence and attribute
their prominence in FBI files and other investigative records to
conspiracies, betrayals or overzealous prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, zeal in such investigations is warranted and was too
long in coming. In the 1960s, Gov. George Wallace of Alabama and
FBI Director J. Edgar Hoover, both motivated by hostility to the
civil rights movement, hampered efforts by state and federal
investigators to prosecute the 16th Street bombing.
</P>
<P>
   In securing the conviction of Chambliss 14 years after the
bombing, Alabama's attorney general at that time, Bill Baxley, set
the precedent for the reopening of dormant civil rights crimes by
Southern officials. In neighboring Mississippi, according to The
Clarion-Ledger, state authorities have reopened nine cases,
securing five murder convictions and one guilty plea.
</P>
<P>
   The latest round of prosecutions in Alabama represents an
example of state-federal cooperation that was often missing in the
1960s. Jones, the U.S. attorney, has been designated a special
assistant attorney general by the state of Alabama so he can
present the cases against Cherry, now 69, and Blanton, 61.
</P>
<P>
   Such prosecutions give vitality to the legal principle that
there is no statute of limitations on murder. As a matter of simple
justice, that principle is valuable in every case. But it is
especially important when killing is used as an instrument of
political or racial oppression or is aimed at innocents like Denise
McNair, Cynthia Wesley, Addie Mae Collins and Carole Robertson, the
children who died in the rubble of 16th Street Baptist Church.
</P>
<P>
   In numbers of people killed at a single stroke, the 16th Street
bombing was the most heinous crime of the civil rights era. It was
a crime that helped bring white Alabama to what Dr. Martin Luther
King Jr. called an accord with its conscience. Now, the fact that a
legal resolution is still being pursued after so many years holds
the promise of a new definition for Southern justice.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-17-00 2326EDT &QL; 
