<HEADER>
A8526 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f BC-CHINA-BUSINESS-KAN &LR;      05-17 0919
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-BUSINESS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONFERENCE DISCUSSES PROS AND CONS OF IMPROVING CHINA'S TRADE
STATUS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ERIC PALMER  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OVERLAND PARK, Kan. _ With 1.3 billion consumers who have a
growing appetite for more and better things, China makes any
capitalistic trader weak in the knees.
</P>
<P>
   But as the world's largest communist country and one that is
known for putting dissidents in jail, China is an unsavory customer
to many in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   With the U.S. House of Representatives set to vote next week on
granting China permanent normal trading relations, the subject of
free trade with that country was at the center of Wednesday's World
Trade Week conference, sponsored by the International Trade Club of
Greater Kansas City. The event was at the Ritz Charles conference
center in Overland Park.
</P>
<P>
   Granting normal trade relations to China would help American
businesses make money there, said Michael Copps, assistant
secretary of commerce for trade development. Copps was the
conference's keynote speaker.
</P>
<P>
   ``On its merits, it isn't even a close call,'' Copps said.
``Basically, we give up nothing, since our market has long been the
most open in the world for China, and in return, we get access to
theirs.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether to grant China permanent normal trade relations is among
the most important economic issues facing Congress this year. But
the outcome is uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   Labor, environmentalists and human rights activists say China is
a country without environmental scruples that treats many of its
citizens cruelly and pays its factory workers about 20 cents an
hour.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are numerous instances of environmental activists being
put in jail there,'' said Craig Volland, who also spoke Wednesday.
Volland is with the Kansas chapter of the Sierra Club, which
opposes granting China permanent normal trade relations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is an article of faith among environmentalists that if you
can't speak out, you can't protect the environment of any
country,'' Volland said.
</P>
<P>
   Congress has been deciding each year whether to treat China as
it treats Japan, Great Britain and other trading partners. That
annual debate is seen by some as an important public relations
hammer on China to do better about human rights.
</P>
<P>
   But China is expected to be accepted into the World Trade
Organization later this year whether or not the United States
grants it permanent normal trading relations. As a member of that
trade organization, it must agree to open its markets to countries
that do the same. If the United States doesn't give China permanent
normal trading status, some argue, other countries will get to
China's markets ahead of the United States and get better deals.
</P>
<P>
   ``The potential here to access the world's most populous nation
is incredible,'' said Harry Cleberg, president and chief executive
of Farmland Industries Inc., the country's largest farmer-owned
cooperative. The Kansas City cooperative estimates that the United
States could sell by the year 2005 an additional $1.6 billion worth
of grain to China under the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our choice is if we want to enjoy these favorable terms or if
we want to hand this market over to our competitors,'' Cleberg said
recently.
</P>
<P>
   According to the White House, tariffs that Beijing places on
farm products would decline from an average of 31 percent to 14
percent under a permanent trade agreement. Average tariffs on
industrial goods would fall from 24.6 percent to 9.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Judy Ancel, with the Institute for Labor Studies at the
University of Missouri-Kansas City, disagrees with the argument
that the China market might slip through U.S. fingers. Ancel, who
spoke Wednesday, said that is an argument made by big business,
whose main motivation is to open factories in China and exploit its
cheap labor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, big business is trying to harness the power of the
U.S. government to help it edge out other countries and get in on
the ground floor of privatization in China,'' Ancel said.
</P>
<P>
   Proponents also act as if this will be a one-way street, that
the United States will be only selling things to the Chinese, Ancel
said. But America currently buys a lot more products from China
than it sells.
</P>
<P>
   The United States bought $4.6 billion more in goods from China
than it sold to it in the first two months of this year, the
Commerce Department's most recent figures show.
</P>
<P>
   The department's statistics show that exports to China from
companies in the Kansas City area and throughout Kansas and
Missouri haven't amounted to much in recent years, making up less
than 2 percent of total exports for each of those areas in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   That is part of the point, proponents say. If China is a member
of the World Trade Organization and has normal trading status,
companies and farmers from this area could sell a lot more to
China, whose middle class is growing at a phenomenal rate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a huge potential market, and if the tariffs get reduced,
it makes us more competitive,'' said Christopher Pirotte, China
sales director for Kansas City-based BHA Group, makers of pollution
control equipment. BHA, which had sales last year of $155.7
million, manufacturers one product in China but imports its other
products for sale there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Working with China and not against it, a lot more can be
accomplished,'' said Pirotte, who lived in China for two years.
``You can't tell China what to do; you just can't. It has a lot of
pride.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-17-00 2328EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000517.0489 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 23:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8527 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-KNICKS-HEAT-ART-4     05-17 1194
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-HEAT-ART-460&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAJERLE LEADS HEAT PAST KNICKS
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT25 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ A deflated Latrell Sprewell slowly left the floor like a
wind-up toy on its last tick. He was out of energy, out of time.
For most of the night, Sprewell propped up his team as his co-star
on the court, Allan Houston, continually gave in to the junkyard
defense of Dan Majerle.
</P>
<P>
   Then, with just under three minutes left in Wednesday night's
Game 5, Houston and the New York Knicks gave into Majerle's
offense. Drifting out on the perimeter, Majerle hit two 3-pointers
in 15 seconds. Then Bruce Bowen added another with 35 seconds left
to give the Miami Heat a pivotal 87-81 victory Thursday night at
American Airlines Arena.
</P>
<P>
   The stunned Knicks are now one game from elimination, trailing
in this best-of-7 Eastern Conference semifinal series by 3-2.
Sprewell led the Knicks with 24 points, while Patrick Ewing added
16 and Houston came up with 12 on a 4-for-10 shooting effort. The
Heat were led by Jamal Mashburn's 21 points, while Alonzo Mourning
scored 18 and Majerle added 16. Once again, the Knicks were
outrebounded by the Heat (42-32).
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks will have a chance to even the series when Game 6 is
played at Madison Square Garden on Friday night. Thursday night,
the Knicks dug their hole early and never came back. The Knicks
were down, 64-55, with 1 minute 54 seconds left in the third
quarter. After scraping up a few points, they got a reprieve from
their nuisance in the paint when Mourning picked up his fifth foul
with 7:36 left. The Heat was ahead, 66-62, but vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   With Mourning on the sideline, the Knicks took an opportunity to
go inside without his intimidating presence to stop them. Quickly,
Camby scored on a layin. Then, when Camby lost the ball on another
drive, Johnson recovered the ball and scored on a layin to tie the
score, 66-66, with 6:44 left in the game.
</P>
<P>
   But the Heat leaned on the courage of the rookie Anthony Carter.
He hit a key jumper in the panicked moments before the shot-clock
expired. Off a turnover by Sprewell, Carter then led a fast break
that ended up with Majerle scoring on a layup and drawing a foul
with 5:16 left. Majerle converted the 3-point play to put the Heat
up, 73-68. Majerle then answered Houston's first field goal of the
second half by drifting free of him for a 3-pointer with 2:27 on
the clock to give his team a 77-70 lead.
</P>
<P>
   But the cool-headed Ward came right back with another three
before Majerle trumped that with his own three. After a layup by
Ewing, after Mourning picked his sixth foul, Houston went to the
free-throw line. He hit both with 56.2 seconds on the clock. And
the Knicks trailed, 80-77. But off the penetration of Majerle,
Bowen ended up open for a 3-pointer with 35.2 seconds left _ a shot
that put the Knicks away.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The nervous two days leading up to Game 5 were filled with
daunting numbers for any team that dared let Thursday night's game
slip away. In a seven-game series, the winner of Game 5 has gone on
to eliminate its opponent 84 percent of the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a high number,'' coach Jeff Van Gundy said before the
game. ``But you know what? Whoever wins tonight, they're in great
position, but, obviously it's not over. Usually, Game 5s are at the
home of the team that has the better record. If we win, I don't
think they will worry about the other 16 percent. I remember in
1995 we had Indiana on our floor for a Game 7. And the home team
had won 20-something straight Game 7s at home.'' The Knicks lost. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Van Gundy was mainly concerned with another statistic. Above the
Knicks' shooting problems against the Heat, beyond their execution
issues down the stretch, Van Gundy was worried about rebounding.
That fear was justified in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   As the aggressors, the Knicks took a 14-4 lead on Sprewell's
energy. But before long, the awkward play of Camby, the team's
inability to grab a loose ball and discord between teammates on the
court caught up to them. After scoring just 13 points in the second
quarter, while allowing the Heat to shoot 52.9 percent, the Knicks
found themselves down, 41-35, at the half.
</P>
<P>
   The third quarter didn't unfold much better. Tim Hardaway shook
off his 1-for-3 start, ignored the pain in his foot and began to
drive on the Knicks for points and hit the open man for easy
scores. With five minutes left in the third quarter, Hardaway
caught Sprewell napping as he snapped a bullet pass to an open
Majerle in the paint for a layup to give the Heat a 59-53 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell, locked in a furious one-on-one battle with Mashburn
all night, recovered with an audacious play three minutes later.
Mashburn was dribbling at the top of the arc when Sprewell flicked
the ball away and darted in for a menacing two-handed dunk. But
that didn't deter the Heat as Miami took its biggest lead of the
game, 64-55, as Hardaway blew by Houston with a crossover for a
layin with 1:55 left in the third. But the unflustered Knicks
managed a 5-0 run to close the third quarter and cut the Heat lead
to 64-60.
</P>
<P>
   Entering the fourth quarter, Sprewell had 22 points, while Ewing
added 13. But no other Knick was in double figures. Majerle had a
clamp on Houston (nine points), and Ward (nine points) was kept
under wraps by a much more attentive Heat defense. But even with
the Knicks' scoring problems, they were still in the game, still
within reach of a victory.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, the Knicks' first-half spiral was related to
Camby's start. He entered the game with four minutes left in the
first quarter, and his team ahead, 19-10, when the bottom began to
fall out. Camby was eaten alive by Mourning every time he drove to
the basket, and he was beaten to rebounds by Clarence Weatherspoon.
He was driven around by Weatherspoon and also picked up two quick
fouls. At the end of his miserable 11 first-half minutes on the
floor, Camby was 0 for 5 and had three rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't all Camby's fault, though. The calm that Ward brought
to the floor in the first quarter was lost once Childs came into
the game two minutes into the second quarter. The Knicks were
clinging to a 26-23 lead but were quickly overtaken with 6:15 left
in the half when Carter broke free of Childs for a jumper to give
the Heat a 29-28 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Then, Ewing and Childs started to quarrel on the court. With
three minutes left in the first half, Childs called for Ewing to
set a pick for him. With his hands ready to receive a pass in the
post, Ewing refused. Childs drove inside anyway and missed a
runner.
</P>
<P>
   That wasn't the first sign of chemistry problems. Sprewell was
visibly upset when he was taken out of the game with 9:30 left in
the second quarter. At that point, he was 6 for 10 with 13 points.
He was in a groove. When he returned three minutes later, he wasn't
the same. He was flustered by a shot block from Mourning and missed
his last three shots of the half.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
