</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEITER DETERMINED TO USE HIS FAME FOR GOOD WHILE HE CAN
</HEADLINE>
 By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Al Leiter felt homesick Sunday night. Missed his
wife, missed his daughters, missed his 1-month-old son, so he
jumped on the last flight to Fort Lauderdale.
</P>
<P>
   It's nice to be a major league ballplayer who essentially does
not have to worry about the staggering inequities of last-minute
airline fares. Blessed with unimagined income, Leiter is also
setting a high standard for athletes with his hands-on involvement
in charity work, while trying to keep a perspective at home. He
arrived in time for a major milepost in the life of his 5-year-old
daughter, Lindsay, who had lost her first tooth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got to be the Tooth Fairy,'' Leiter reported. ``I was
stunned to learn that the going rate is $5 these days. We persuaded
her this is only for the first one, then it goes down.''
</P>
<P>
   Good luck with that theory. With three young children, Leiter
figures to be working out a reasonable scale for Tooth Fairy
activities, but he has vowed that he will be there for much of it.
A 34-year-old left-hander, Leiter has a perfect 5-0 won-lost record
for the New York Mets after pitching eight innings in Wednesday
night's 4-2 victory over Colorado. He is coping with pitching in
New York while his family is living in Florida for much of the
year, but he does not want this to go on forever.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got two years left on my contract after this year,''
Leiter said the other day. ``I still love the competition, and this
is not about money, but I'm not going to miss the early years of my
kids' lives. I'm just not going to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   He is tired of getting messages on his answering machine up
North from his daughters, saying they miss him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see guys playing as long as they can, while their kids are
teenagers,'' he said. ``I want my kids to know me.''
</P>
<P>
   Not only his own children will feel the impact of Al Leiter,
however. He and his wife, Lori, are actively working to help other
children through the Leiters Landing Foundation, which they began
in 1996, when he pitched for the Marlins.
</P>
<P>
   The most noticeable figures are the $1 million they pledged over
his four-year contract beginning in 1998, and the 2,500 children
who have watched Mets games. But Leiter is not a passive spectator
of the charity, like many public figures who write a check. He is
an activist.
</P>
<P>
   ``We ask organizations to write grant proposals and we look them
over,'' Leiter said. ``It is such a good feeling when you do it
yourself. It seems things run much more smoothly. We had one
employee, but we found we could do it ourselves, with my wife and a
friend of ours, Val Chevalier, taking care of the smallest
details.''
</P>
<P>
   Leiter recently organized and financed a project at City Meals
on Wheels that got 15 high school students doing volunteer work
delivering meals to homebound elderly people. There is a mentoring
program in Harlem, a ball field in New Jersey, a computer project
in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   He uses his celebrity status to bring in other benefactors,
including Knight Securities, Ultimate Software, Twin Labs, Coverall
America and Park Avenue Country Club.
</P>
<P>
   His efforts have not gone unnoticed. Recently the Dime Savings
Bank of New York organized a program called Hometown Heroes, giving
six grants of $50,000 each to be donated in the name of six New
York athletes personally involved in community work _ Adam Graves
of the Rangers, Marcus Camby of the Knicks, Kenny Jonsson of the
Islanders, Michael Strahan of the Giants, Jayson Williams of the
Nets and Leiter.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is fun,'' Leiter said. ``We can have tremendous impact.
Charles Barkley said we are not role models, that parents and other
adults are role models, and I understand what he means, but I would
tell Charles: `You know, people are looking at you. While you're
here, do something. When we're back home, people are not going to
care about us. We're going to be regular people again.'''
</P>
<P>
   Leiter looks forward to being a regular person. ``It was so
great being home,'' he said. ``My 3-year-old was afraid of the
Tooth Fairy, so she had to sleep in our room. My 5-year-old was so
excited with the money. We went out on a date Monday; she bought
headbands with the money.''
</P>
<P>
   He knows full well that regular people don't excite
corporations, don't attract galleries at charity golf events, don't
make public-service announcements. Al Leiter is doing all that,
rather than merely brood over his homesickness, which can only
occasionally be alleviated by a quick dash to the departure gate.  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
