<SLUG> BC-VODAFONE-CEGESTEL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VODAFONE TO SELL CEGETEL STAKE 
</HEADLINE>
   By ANDREW ROSS SORKIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Vodafone AirTouch PLC, the world's largest wireless
telephone operator, will sell its 15 percent stake in the French
telecommunications operator Cegetel to its French partner, Vivendi,
the companies announced Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Vodafone's sale of the stake, which Vodafone saw as having
little strategic value, gives Vivendi majority control of Cegetel,
which controls the French wireless operator SFR.
</P>
<P>
   The sale does not mean Vodafone and Vivendi are reducing their
friendly relationship. The closeness of that relationship became a
critical reason for Vodafone's success in buying Mannesmann AG, the
German telecommunications conglomerate, in a record hostile
takeover earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   On the contrary, Vodafone and Vivendi Wednesday unveiled a new
joint venture called Vizzavi, a European Internet portal accessible
by mobile telephones, desktop computers and handheld devices. They
hope to sell Vizzavi shares to the public within two years.
</P>
<P>
   Vodafone and Vivendi became bedfellows in late January during
Vodafone's bid for Mannesmann. &UR;  &LR; The German company had been
negotiating with Vivendi in hopes of thwarting Vodafone's bid, but
at the last minute, Vivendi agreed to a surprise alliance with
Vodafone, effectively guaranteeing Vodafone's successful takeover
of Mannesmann.
</P>
<P>
   As part of Vodafone's alliance with Vivendi announced then,
Vodafone had said it would sell Vivendi half of Mannesmann's 15
percent stake in Cegetel if Vodafone acquired the German
conglomerate. On Wednesday, Vodafone said it would sell the entire
Cegetel stake to Vivendi.
</P>
<P>
   Vivendi already owns a 44 percent stake in Cegetel; Wednesday's
deal would bring that stake to 59 percent. Cegetel is also partly
owned by British Telecommunications, which holds a 26 percent stake
and SBC Communications, which has 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Jeane-Marie Messier, chairman of Vivendi, said said he would
consider reselling the 15 percent stake purchased from Vodafone to
the other partners or outside suitors.
</P>
<P>
   Even without its stake in Cegetel, Vodafone still has a direct
investment stake in SFR.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference in Paris, Chris Gent, Vodafone's chief
executive and Messier said they would launch the Vizzavi site this
summer across Europe in multiple languages. In a separate,
unrelated announcement, Vivendi said it would drop out of the
auction for the next generation cellular license in Germany.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
