<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RALLY IN NINTH WINS FOR DODGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ It was a mind-numbing, dizzying 19 or so hours for the
Los Angeles Dodgers, but a few clutch hits and a pitiful display by
the wretched Chicago Cubs bullpen certainly made for smiles in the
visiting clubhouse at Wrigley Field.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to put distance between themselves and the wild events of
Tuesday night, when players went into the stands and fought with
fans, the Dodgers kept Wednesday's excitement contained to the
field.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Hansen's leadoff pinch-hit homer triggered a three-run
ninth inning as the Dodgers rallied to beat the Cubs 8-6 before a
docile crowd of 30,235, sending Chicago to its third straight loss.
</P>
<P>
   And given the circus-like atmosphere that surrounded the Dodgers
since the fight, Gary Sheffield had no problem placing the
importance of their fourth win in five games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew when we came in today we were going to see a lot of
chaos,'' Sheffield said. ``We all talked about it. With everything
that went on out there, we just had to deal with it. We couldn't
let anything distract from doing what we came to do, play baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``We kind of felt like our hands would be full today and we
still got the job done. It was an important win; probably the
biggest game of the year for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Eric Karros had the game-winning hit, a two-out single to center
to score Shawn Green. Adrian Beltre added an RBI single to left to
score Sheffield and give the Dodgers a two-run lead.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Mills (2-1) threw one pitch for his second victory in as
many days, and Dodgers closer Jeff Shaw, apparently past his shaky
outings of last week, recorded his 10th save with a perfect ninth
inning, which is something the Cubs long for.
</P>
<P>
   Cubs closer Rick Aguilera continued his horrid stretch by
blowing his fourth save in 10 opportunities. He's allowed 10 runs
in his last 5 innings for a bullpen whose ERA actually dropped to
7.45 thanks to solid pitching in relief of Scott Downs. Or, at
least until Aguilera entered the game.
</P>
<P>
   Hansen worked the count full before driving a pitch into the
right-field bleachers. It was his second pinch-hit homer of the
season and eighth of his career. But more important, it brought
life back to a Dodgers lineup that hadn't sniffed a scoring chance
since getting five runs in the fourth, and it tied the game at 6.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was 3-2 and I was just trying to relax, and I got out there
a little bit and tried to put the ball in play,'' Hansen said.
``This team is really close. We've moved on (from the fight). We've
already forgot about it. It was a little harder, but we moved on.''
</P>
<P>
   Aguilera retired Todd Hollandsworth and Mark Grudzielanek, but
Cubs manager Don Baylor opted to match Felix Heredia (1-1) against
Shawn Green, who walked. Sheffield also walked before Karros, and
Beltre followed with a hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a good ballclub, which is evident (Sunday) when we're
down a touchdown with five outs recorded and come back and make a
game of it,'' Karros said. ``Hansen, he's been awesome for us. He's
one of the most valuable players.''
</P>
<P>
   However, the one downer for the Dodgers was right-hander Darren
Dreifort's breakdown after the third inning.
</P>
<P>
   The right-hander had allowed one run in the first three innings
and he looked much like the pitcher who shut out St. Louis on two
hits in his last start. But Dreifort did himself in on the bases,
though the reason for it can vary.
</P>
<P>
   With three runs already in and runners on first and third,
Dreifort doubled to right-center field to score Karros. When Sammy
Sosa bobbled the ball, Todd Hundley scored to give the Dodgers a
5-0 lead. Dreifort continued to third, sliding and jamming his
right knee.
</P>
<P>
   Dreifort said he wasn't hurt, but he allowed six runs on six
hits in the next 1 innings before getting pulled.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all coincidence,'' Dreifort said. ``I would rate (the
slide) a negative-4 on a scale of 1 to 10. It was horrible. It was
stupid even going to third. Three words for that: Stupid, stupid,
stupid.''
</P>
</TEXT>
