<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-PREAKNESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`PEGASUS' 3-5 CHOICE AT PIMLICO 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOSEPH DURSO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ Fusaichi Pegasus arrived at Pimlico Race Course with
royal fanfare Wednesday after a flight from Louisville, where he
won the Kentucky Derby a week and a half ago and put himself in
position to become the 12th horse in racing history to win the
Triple Crown.
</P>
<P>
   Fusaichi Pegasus, the star of the 3-year-old class, was made the
3-5 favorite to win the Preakness Stakes on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The final test in the Triple Crown, the Belmont Stakes, is June
10. His chances were not particularly affected, for better or for
worse, at the draw for post positions Wednesday. He received slot
No. 7 in the field of eight starters.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the draw gave none of the starters much cause for
either joy or anxiety. Hugh Hefner, a long shot at 20-1, drew the
rail.
</P>
<P>
   The speed horse Hal's Hope drew the outside and was also listed
at 20-1. Red Bullet, who did not run in the Derby, drew the No. 4
gate and was made the second choice at 9-2.
</P>
<P>
   Captain Steve, eighth in the 19-horse Derby, drew the No. 6 slot
and was made the third choice at 8-1. High Yield, 15th in the Derby
but still carrying the flag for D. Wayne Lukas, will start from the
fifth slot at 10-1.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is very straightforward,'' said Neil Drysdale, the
English trainer of Fusaichi Pegasus. ``It's a quarter of a mile to
the first turn. Eight horses. I don't think the draw is that
important.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Baffert, who trains Captain Steve, quipped: ``I'd feel
better if Fusaichi Pegasus were to break from behind the gate.''
</P>
<P>
   Lukas, who has won the Preakness five times, said he was still
mystified by High Yield's flat performance in the Derby.
</P>
<P>
   The horse had won the Fountain of Youth Stakes and the Blue
Grass Stakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we went over for the Derby, I was convinced he was the
best horse,'' Lukas said. ``I don't know what happened. But he's
been training beautifully at Pimlico, he likes the track, and we're
expecting him to run a big race.''
</P>
<P>
   Fusaichi Pegasus was unloaded from his horse van by Drysdale,
who bedded him down in Stall 20 of Barn 7 near the five-eighths
pole.
</P>
<P>
   Drysdale elected to stable him across the track from the
Preakness Barn, where the rest of the eight colts will be housed
for the 125th running of the Preakness.
</P>
<P>
   The trainer decided that his star, who has a balky disposition,
would find more privacy on the backstretch than at the Preakness
Barn with its clamor of news media.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very good flight,'' Drysdale said. ``He handled it
very well. We expect to gallop him each morning up to the
Preakness.''
</P>
<P>
   Fusaichi Pegasus led the midweek migration with a two-hour
flight to Pimlico from Churchill Downs, and was promptly surrounded
by the type of tumult that his trainer had been trying to avoid. He
was met by about 80 people from the news media.
</P>
<P>
   He arrived on a flight of 14 horses, but only two others,
Captain Steve and Snuck In, were headed for the Preakness.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Hugh Hefner arrived from the West Coast at 9
o'clock Wednesday morning after an overnight cargo flight from Los
Angeles. He was greeted by an entourage of two: his owner, Ed
Nahem, and his trainer, Marty Jones.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cargo plane stopped in Dayton and had a layover for about
an hour,'' Jones said, ``but that's pretty good when you hear
stories of planes sitting on the ground for 10 hours. I'm tired,
but he seems fine. Better the trainer is tired than the horse.''
</P>
<P>
   Red Bullet, who ran second to Fusaichi Pegasus in the Wood
Memorial last month, took life easy Wednesday while awaiting his
old nemesis. He galloped two miles, then drew praise from his
trainer, Joe Orseno, who said he had handled the Pimlico track
well.
</P>
<P>
   He won a reward of sorts by getting the first choice in the
selection process, a two-tiered gimmick for adding suspense to the
television program on which the draw was broadcast.
</P>
<P>
   Red Bullet will also gain the services of Jerry Bailey, the
country's premier jockey, who replaced Alex Solis.
</P>
<P>
   As for post position, Orseno said: ``I'm not too concerned with
only an eight-horse field and the long run to the first turn. It's
different than when there was 12 in the Wood and a short run to the
turn. He drew the 2-hole, and the horses outside were dropping down
in there. Solis gunned him, and he was up there dueling for the
lead. That was the last thing I wanted to see, but he still ran a
game race.''
</P>
<P>
   The eighth and last Preakness horse to arrive at Pimlico will be
Impeachment, third in the Kentucky Derby and third in the Arkansas
Derby.
</P>
<P>
   His trainer, Todd Pletcher, said the colt would board a van at
Belmont Park at 4:30 in the morning and should join the Preakness
parade about 9 o'clock. He will start the race from the No. 3 gate
and will share third place in the betting with Captain Steve at
8-1.
</P>
</TEXT>
