<HEADLINE>
HERNANDEZ TO PLAY SATURDAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JOSE _ With new Galaxy standout Luis Hernandez arriving
Friday in Los Angeles, Galaxy coach Sigi Schmid said Hernandez will
play in Saturday's match against MLS champion D.C. United at the
Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez, the biggest foreign acquisition in MLS history,
agreed Tuesday to a three-year contract. As long as he passes his
physical, he will debut in his No. 15 jersey.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll play,'' Schmid said. ``I don't know for how many
minutes, it depends on how he feels. He's just come off a season,
so he's fit, but we've got to make sure he doesn't have an injury
or anything like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Galaxy equipment manager Raul Vargas teased former Galaxy coach
Lothar Osiander, now coach of the Earthquakes. Vargas hung
Hernandez's jersey in the Galaxy's dressing room in San Jose,
explaining to Osiander that Hernandez surprised everyone by showing
up Wednesday morning for his physical and that he was ready to
play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he believed me for a second,'' Vargas said. ``I was
just having fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Osiander was happy Hernandez delayed his debut until Saturday.
He also said the Galaxy shouldn't complain for losing three players
to acquire Hernandez. L.A. parted with Clint Mathis, Joey Franchino
and Roy Myers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They feel sorry because they want it all and sometimes you
can't have it all,'' Osiander said. ``I'd trade those players they
traded for Hernandez anytime.''
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez will be introduced Friday at a Rose Bowl press
conference. The Galaxy has averaged an MLS-best 18,987 at the Rose
Bowl this season, but Galaxy officials expect 40,000 to 50,000 for
Saturday's game.
</P>
<P>
   __ Slow start: San Jose striker Khodadad Azizi has been a huge
disappointment since being allocated to San Jose in March. The
Iranian forward, who looked wonderful during the 1998 World Cup in
France, has only one assist and no goals in six appearances for the
Earthquakes.
</P>
<P>
   He has already been suspended three games and fined $7,500 for
shoving an MLS referee. Azizi has looked like a statue at times,
rarely showing consistent effort. The Galaxy had a chance to pursue
Azizi in March, but Schmid opted to pass to wait for a Mexican
player. Of course, it paid off when the Galaxy acquired Hernandez.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's probably good he didn't come here,'' said Schmid, who
took some heat for passing on Azizi at the time. ``There is a huge
Iranian community in Southern and Northern California, so he helps
with attendance up here,'' Schmid said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I think our Mexican-American community is still the
biggest community we have. If we would have taken a player like
Azizi, it would have prevented us from getting Hernandez. Hernandez
is a much bigger bang in our community, so in the end we made the
right decision.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-17-00 2341EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000517.0495 </DOCNO>
