<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000517.0497 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 23:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8555 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR &LR;      05-17 0576
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SURPASSING THE LEGAL LIMIT OF RETRIBUTION  
 (FOR USE BY N.Y. TIMES NEWS SERVICE CLIENTS) 
</HEADLINE>
   By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
(PHOENIX) - There were five vic tims, so prosecutors charged
Phillip Woods with five counts of endanger ment. He'd been driving
the vehicle when it rolled over, and one of the passengers broke
her neck and nearly died. Woods' blood-alcohol level was 0.114,
over the legal limit. He was told a guilty verdict at trial could
put him in prison for years.
<TEXT>
<P>
   At his arraignment, Woods was ordered to avoid all contact with
the victims of his alleged crime.
</P>
<P>
   This might be difficult, the defendant claimed, since the judge
was talking about his wife, mother, sister and two best friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``And none of them wanted him prosecuted,'' says Woods' grandfa
ther, Ernest Apostle, ``particularly the one who got hurt the most,
his mother.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods and his family had gone to a haunted house near Bartlett
Lake one evening last October. Woods had some beers at the house,
his grandfa ther says, but no one thought he was drunk when he got
behind the wheel.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tricky road, and he made a mistake and the thing rolled
onto its roof,'' Apostle says. ``It wasn't assault. It was an
accident.''
</P>
<P>
   Not according to the Maricopa County Attorney's Office. A plea
bargain was offered. It would send Woods to jail for six months,
revoke his driver's license and label him a felon. Fearing prison,
Woods decided to take it.
</P>
<P>
   ``If someone were to ask any of us if Phillip should be
punished, we would tell them, `Yes,'' says Apostle, who spent 22
years in the U.S. Army. He believes in rules and taking responsi
bility. He's always thought of himself as a tough, law-and-order
kind of guy.
</P>
<P>
   ``But,'' Apostle adds, ``anyone who believes in discipline also
under stands you must temper it with common sense and proportion. I
don't feel that happened here.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods' family says the 33-year-old doesn't have a criminal
record. After high school, he spent four years in the Marines. He's
married with two children. He works.
</P>
<P>
   ``And the only people harmed have already forgiven him,''
Apostle says. ``If he had been out with a bunch of hooligans, I'd
understand getting harsh. If he had a history of this, yes. But
that isn't the case. . . . Why ruin his life and further harm his
fam ily?''
</P>
<P>
   When Woods' plea bargain was presented to Maricopa County Supe
rior Court Judge Peter Reinstein, he refused to sign off on it. The
judge won't comment, but others involved say he felt the punishment
was too severe. Rather than modify the deal, prosecutors asked to
have the case reassigned to a new judge.
</P>
<P>
   The Maricopa County Attorney's Office also won't comment, since
the final outcome is pending. A spokes man would say only that the
policy is to enforce drunken-driving laws strictly.
</P>
<P>
   After all, what if Phillip Woods had hurt someone to whom he
wasn't related? And what if Woods were let off with probation, then
was in volved in another DUI in the future? Should the wishes of
the victims in this case win out, or is the system's job to
dispense justice with the entire community in mind?
</P>
<P>
   They're fair questions, but maybe not as important as the one
prosecu tors should be asking themselves:
</P>
<P>
   How is justice served when the people harmed most by your deci
sions are the victims themselves? &QL; 
 &QL; 
Reach Montini at &QL; 
Ed.Montini &LR; ArizonaRepublic.com or (602) 444-8978. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
